A2452 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-OZ-DEVELOPERS-KAN &LR;      08-19 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZ-DEVELOPERS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACE HOBSON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When developers ask for approval to build their Wonderful World
of Oz theme park in Johnson County, Kan., they might have to agree
to 47 pages of requirements proposed by county planners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The requirements say ``no'' to gambling and adult entertainment,
``yes'' to marinas and ``maybe'' to fireworks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson County Commission will vote on the proposed
requirements next Thursday (8-26). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   County planners drafted regulations for resort and entertainment
developments with the Wonderful World of Oz in mind and got
comments from the developers. But the requirements would apply to
any similar project, said Dean Palos, a county planner handling the
Oz matter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Oz Entertainment Co., based in Los Angeles, proposes
building a $771 million theme park and resort at what is now the
Sunflower Army Ammunition Plant. The company is negotiating with
federal and state officials to buy the plant's 9,065 acres in
exchange for ridding the land of its environmental hazards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In drafting the requirements, planners wanted to strengthen the
county's current theme-park zoning regulations in anticipation of
the Oz project. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before building, a developer would have to obtain a conditional
use permit that would come with 30 pages of new stipulations and
restrictions _ in addition to 17 pages of existing requirements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the requirements would allow the county to be
proactive in zoning the land and allow the Oz company to know what
is expected, Palos said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The County Planning Commission approved the requirements July
27. Since then, the requirements were changed slightly to
incorporate suggestions from the Oz company, a county resident,
some Planning Commission members, a zoning board member and county
staff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations would lay out what steps Oz would have to
take to win approval, including presenting a plan to the county and
agreeing to the land-use requirements. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the proposed provisions: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The theme park could have special lighting effects _ such as
sky beacons, laser lights, searchlights and fireworks _ with
approval of the fire marshal. The developer would have to submit a
plan for special lighting. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The development could not include adult entertainment; bingo
or any other gaming establishment; a car wash; pawnshops; or gun
sales. Oz developers have not proposed those businesses. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Buildings could not stand more than 150 feet tall, or as
recommended by the county's zoning administrator and approved by
the commission. Oz said the building requirements were too
restrictive. The proposed requirement was not changed, however. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --A quarter of the development would have to be open space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --]Lighting at the development ``should present an inviting
atmosphere'' but not be visible to residential areas. The
regulations spell out 11 provisions to ensure the lighting is
``festive'' and to buffer surrounding areas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The park must have a 25-foot landscape buffer between it and
public right-of-way. Oz has said it plans a generous buffer between
the development and surrounding areas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The permit would last for 10 years. Oz asked that it last for
up to 30 years, but that is a provision the commission would have
to approve, Palos said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --All environmental contamination would have to be cleaned up
before building permits would be issued. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The permit would apply to the 1,750 acres on which the Oz
company plans to build its resort, Palos said. Plans call for
building the 55-acre theme park, a hotel with conference center
space, a golf course and an RV park on that acreage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
