<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-PATIENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG CANCER PATIENT MAKES TRIUMPHANT RETURN TO SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MHARI DOYLE  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year ago, Michael Scherzer didn't have the strength to write
his own name. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 8-year-old can write just about anything in flowing
cursive _ and he's really good at it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing is my favorite thing,'' Michael said quietly Wednesday
as he answered questions on a sheet titled ``To Know Me Is to Love
Me'' at Briarwood Elementary School in Olathe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1998, Michael was diagnosed with a rare form of
leukemia that doesn't respond well to chemotherapy. Because the
transplants severely weakened his immune system, Michael wasn't
allowed in large groups of people _ and that included most of his
first-grade year and all of second grade. Even his parents, Jeff
and Susan Scherzer, had to avoid contact with crowds. They couldn't
go to church, malls or social events. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, after a year and a half filled with hospital stays and four
bone marrow transplants, Michael's cancer is in remission, and he's
finally back in school. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, third-grade teacher Kathy Sanders
introduced him to his classmates, some of whom remembered him from
kindergarten and first grade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When she asked the class questions, Michael's hand shot up
almost every time. At recess, he played with friends he hadn't seen
for months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I treat him like everyone else,'' Sanders said. But, she
added, ``I want to...be sensitive to the fact that he's not been in
this environment for a while.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said that despite having missed nearly two full grades
of classroom instruction, Michael is ``right where he needs to
be.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it was a long road for Michael, who has survived painful
surgeries, sickening medication and prolonged detachment from
schoolmates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The journey started shortly before May 28, 1998, when Michael
and his family, including his younger brother, Austin, went to
Cardinal Glennon Children's Hospital in St. Louis for his first
bone marrow transplant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of more than 3 million donors on file with the Heart of America
Bone Marrow Donor Registry, Susan Scherzer had the best match for
Michael's blood. But, as Michael said, ``it was too good,'' and his
body rejected the transplant, throwing him into a tailspin of
sickness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the next month, the family searched for acceptable donors,
but found none. Briarwood staff and area parents raised about
$70,000 to offset the costs of bone marrow donor screening, which
costs $45 per person. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At school, his friends wrote letters of encouragement and hoped
for his early return. Blair Ryan, one of Michael's classmates, said
several children shaved their heads in support: ``I did it because
he didn't have much hair and he would be the only one.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the illness, Susan Scherzer said, her son never lost
hope. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The neat thing about Michael is that he could be easily
distracted from everything that was going on,'' she said Tuesday.
``He could be throwing up for hours and then stop and play video
games for a long time. You knew he had that life in him.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael said he doesn't remember much about his extended stays
in the hospital, but he said one of the worst parts was hospital
food. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``My favorite thing was tricking nurses,'' he said. He tried to
scare them by wrapping fake snakes around IV poles and surprise
them with noises from a whoopee cushion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In late September 1998, doctors finally found that bone marrow
from Michael's aunt might work. He received his fourth transplant
from a bone-marrow bag with a note that read, ``Love, Aunt Jill.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It took,'' Susan Scherzer said as she hugged Michael closer to
her. ``The leukemia and the transplant are doing good, but
nothing's normal yet. We're still fighting infection.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael is battling a lung disease that attacks some transplant
patients, Scherzer said. To treat his lung problem, Michael had to
add steroids, which make his face puffy, to his lengthy list of
medicines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And while Michael was learning how to pronounce the names of his
medications, his former classmates were learning basic reading and
math skills. Michael was falling behind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In January, Olathe teacher Carol Sieber started tutoring him in
reading, writing and math. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had anyone who wanted to learn so badly,'' Sieber
said. ``You could see the eagerness and this bright shine in his
face that would glow when all of a sudden, he's got it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By July, Michael was reading at the fourth-grade level, writing
in cursive and mastering addition and subtraction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``His handwriting started out very shaky,'' Sieber said. ``Now
he's got some of the most beautiful cursive I've seen.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, Michael even wrote a book, /{Michael's Favorite
Foods./} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, he said, he's content playing video games, going to
school and staying away from hospitals. But, he added, he is
thinking about writing another book, /{How to Trick Your Nurse./} &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scherzer said she's happy to see her son start school again, but
she knows it will be hard to be away from him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do,'' she said. ``I've had him
next to me this whole time. He's been my right foot!'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
