<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POWS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHETHER U.S. POWS WERE TRANSFERRED TO FORMER SOVIET UNION FOR
QUESTIONING IS UNANSWERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Right now the idea is more Cold War fiction than fact. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is the suspicion that American prisoners of war were taken
to the former Soviet Union for questioning during the Korean War. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the fall of communism in the former Soviet Union in 1989,
American officials could only speculate about what may have
happened. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But since 1992, both American and Russian officials have been
working together to solve such mysteries, Major Gen. Vladimir A.
Zolotarev, member of the U.S.-Russia Joint Commission on POW//MIA
Affairs, said Wednesday during the Veterans of Foreign Wars
national convention in Bartle Hall in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The commission formed to exchange documents and information
about the fate of missing soldiers representing both Cold War
antagonists.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The task of our commission is to see that there are no unknown
soldiers, that their names should be known not only to God, but to
their fellow human beings,'' Zolotarev told the assembled
delegates. VFW veterans gave Zolotarev a standing ovation for his
statement. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a scene that would have been hard to imagine just 10
years ago. But there was no objection to Zolotarev's presence, said
Bruce Harder, VFW director of national security and foreign
affairs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It might seem odd that the VFW would invite a Russian officer
to speak, but because of the particular subject and the position he
holds, there has been no opposition,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, according to Zolotarev, since 1992 have passed
along more than 12,000 pages of documents, many of them formerly
classified. Such disclosures have helped shed light on the
circumstances of about 80 American servicemen who died during the
Korean War, he said, as well as more than 20 American soldiers who
died in Cold War incidents. About 8,000 U.S. service members are
listed as missing from the Korean War. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   American sources have confirmed the deaths of 14 Soviet pilots
in Cold War incidents, Zolotarev said, and supplied videotapes
containing evidence in other cases. Russian officials continue to
seek information about the more than 1,000 Russian servicemen
reported missing during Cold War service, including about 300
sailors and pilots who disappeared at sea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The idea of American servicemen taken to the former Soviet Union
for questioning during the Korean War has endured. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Malcolm Toon, a former U.S. ambassador to Moscow and a
former commission co-chairman, said the questioning was possible,
given the close relationship between the Soviet Union and North
Korea in the early 1950s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Toon acknowledged then that no evidence of that questioning
had been found in Russian archives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aleksandr Orlov, a Russian historian who accompanied Zolotarev
to Kansas City, and who is co-chairman of the joint commission's
Korean War Working Group, said research on the questioning
continues. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``However, to date, there has been no evidence to show that
there was a transfer of U.S. personnel to the Soviet Union,'' Orlov
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
