A2459 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-McCAIN-SPEECH-KAN &LR;      08-19 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-McCAIN-SPEECH-KAN </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN TALKS OF WHITE HOUSE FLAWS, HIS CANDIDACY IN SPEECH TO VFW  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ The Clinton administration's approach to
foreign and military affairs suffers from wild inconsistency that
puts the world in peril, Sen. John McCain told about 4,000 fellow
veterans Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Congress makes things worse, the former Navy fighter pilot said,
by siphoning off money for pork-barrel projects that could be
better spent boosting military pay and buying better equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, Congress could free $4 billion for
defense spending if it only had the courage to close redundant
military bases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people must recognize the gravity of the problem
before their employees in Washington will fear to do the wrong
thing more than they currently fear to do the necessary things,''
McCain said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republican, among a field of GOP presidential
hopefuls trailing Texas Gov. George W. Bush in early polls,
delivered the keynote address to the Veterans of Foreign Wars
convention in Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was among comrades. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His jet was shot down during a bombing mission early in the U.S.
involvement in the Vietnam War. His subsequent capture led to more
than five years in captivity in communist North Vietnam, where he
endured injury and torture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The son and grandson of Navy admirals, McCain left the Navy in
1980 and was elected to the U.S. House in 1982. He was elected to
his first Senate term in 1986. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His political career has been marked by successes in supporting
Indian gaming and brokering a deal that led television networks to
begin rating the sex and violence in their programming. He failed
in efforts to win Senate approval of a tobacco settlement or more
tightly restrict the financing of political campaigns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain is also a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee,
and he appealed to the veterans group Wednesday on the issues of
their benefits and the treatment of men and women still in the
military. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A paucity of veterans among top administration officials, the
senator said, makes an ``inattention to our military and
veterans...not surprising.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain described a military stretched ``perilously close to the
breaking point'' around the globe in peacekeeping and humanitarian
missions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are,'' he said, ``on the razor's edge of hollowing out.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On foreign policy, McCain said the Clinton administration bounds
from crisis to crisis with ad hoc policies that reveal an
indecisiveness the world could read as weakness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Clinton's credibility on Sino-American relations was
destroyed when his campaign took money from a subsidiary of the
Chinese People's Liberation Army and by the subsequent discovery of
stolen nuclear secrets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, the administration risks lives by delivering mixed
signals about renewed hostility between the governments of mainland
China and Taiwan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The reunification of China must only occur peacefully, in
other words, voluntarily,'' McCain said. ``China must be made to
understand that the use of force would be a very serious mistake in
judgment, a serious mistake with grave consequences.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, who spoke to the VFW Monday, McCain got a standing
ovation at the opening and close of his speech. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, a Tennessee Republican sometimes mentioned
as a presidential prospect, came to Kansas City with McCain to
endorse his candidacy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``On so many of the issues that are important to our country,''
Thompson said, ``Senator McCain has been a leader.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander's withdrawal
from the presidential race freed him to endorse his fellow maverick
GOP senator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference after his speech, McCain continued to hint
that he will not compete in the Iowa caucuses in February and
instead skip ahead to primaries in conservative New Hampshire,
heavily military South Carolina and delegate-rich California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCain sat out the fund-raising straw poll conducted by the Iowa
Republican Party on Saturday that Bush won. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to compete in Iowa,'' McCain said. ``But I've got to
make a decision based on time and assets and viability.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting with supporters after his speech, he said veterans
``are the base of this campaign'' for the presidency. He was
flanked by two fellow former prisoners of war. Everett Alvarez was
held captive in North Vietnam longer than any other American POW.
Bud Day was McCain's senior ranking officer in his Hanoi prison. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also said that even though B-2 stealth bombers flew dozens of
missions over Yugoslavia from their west-central Missouri base, he
would rather spend defense funds on other weapons systems. The
long-range bombers cost $2 billion a copy, and the senator said
that each mission costs $350,000. (Estimates provided by Whiteman
Air Force Base for per-hour flying costs and munitions put the
total closer to $444,000 for the missions to Yugoslavia.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as enamored with its capabilities as many are,'' he
said. ``I think the investment in tactical fighter aircraft is
probably more valuable.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
