<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2460 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-19 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SHOCKED. Amazed. Dismayed. Angry. Hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley was every one of those things last week when he
saw on television that Scottie Pippen had requested a trade to the
Lakers. Barkley was in Kona, Hawaii, for what he called ``a Nike
vacation.'' Just that afternoon, he had played a round of golf with
one of his best friends, a Rockets teammate.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie hadn't told me a thing about it,'' Barkley said. ``Not
one word. Nothing. Man, it threw me for a loop. I almost fell out
of my chair. I felt very frustrated very betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found Scottie the next morning and told him how disappointed
I was in him. It really rubs me wrong that he'd try to bail out on
the team after one season. It's unbelievable to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley is in Houston, at least for a couple of days, talking to
the Rockets about returning to a team Pippen wants to escape. A
team that paid Charles a piddling $1 million last season _ at
Barkley's behest _ in order to make possible Scottie's five-year,
$67.5 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day before he signed,'' Barkley said, ``Scottie was
calling me and asking me if I was going to be (in Houston). He said
he wasn't coming if I wasn't staying. I gave him my word, and
that's why I signed for what I did when I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, you may recall, the Chuckster went out and gave Houston
twice the season Pippen did, for less than one-thirteenth the
compensation. Still, he never complained. He didn't even complain
when Pippen's turnover cost the Rockets that playoff game in LA and
Scottie later suggested to the press it was Barkley who had messed
up.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Barkley has a suggestion for Pippen. No, it's not about
shoving anything anywhere the sun doesn't shine. It is about
maturity, leadership, responsibility and, above all, owning up to
one's mistakes. That's what Charles calls Pippen's trade request _
a dumb, insensitive, regrettable mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, Scottie owes the Rockets' fans an apology,'' Barkley
said. ``They've been terrific to him. Second, he owes the Rockets
an apology. And third, he owes me an apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie needs to stand up and be a man. If he does, we can
move on. Everything will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will,'' Barkley said, brushing off the question.
``But this is a real challenge for him. This will tell you a lot
about who Scottie Pippen really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of us have already jumped to conclusions regarding same.
Pippen's debut season for the Rockets, if not an out-and-out
failure, left a bad taste in lots of mouths. On a dollar-for-dollar
basis, he might have been the Least Valuable Player in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But Barkley hasn't given up on the notion that Pippen has a
viable future in Houston. The story can have a happy ending,
because at least in Houston, Pippen has an opportunity to escape
the stigma of being merely an overhyped, artificially enhanced
accessory to Michael Jordan's mythic skills.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers, he would be back in the same cushy place he was
in Chicago, letting someone else carry the brunt of the
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Scottie played hard,'' Barkley said, ``he played good.
Y'all saw it. I don't want Scottie traded to LA. I want him here,
playing like I know he can play. I believe in Scottie. He needs to
come in, apologize, then kick some butt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about him taking charge and being a leader. With the
Lakers, it would be like Chicago all over again _ a no-lose
situation. If they win, it will be because of the `leadership'
Scottie brought to the team. If they lose, then it's going to be
Shaq's (Shaquille O'Neal's) fault or Kobe's (Bryant's) fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, who would the Lakers give us that I'd want _ Kobe?
And from what I'm told, the Lakers don't want Scottie. They haven'd
BX1d us about him; he's calling them.''
</P>
<P>
   n &UR; S
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
