A2466 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG)     08-19 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINEMEN FIND CAMP TOUGHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The most distinctive voice at Spaulding Field
these days belongs to first-year assistant Jethro Franklin, who
coaches the defensive tackles. It is loud and relentless,
unforgiving yet motivating _ like a drill sergeant's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely feels like boot camp out here,'' senior tackle
Pete Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   That's by design.
</P>
<P>
   When defensive-line coach Terry Tumey joined the Denver Broncos'
staff last spring, UCLA coach Bob Toledo hired Franklin to oversee
the tackles and John Pearce to direct the ends. His instructions
were explicit: Make the linemen meaner, make them tougher and make
them better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys come off the field now and they're wet, and I don't
know if they've ever done that,'' Toledo said. ``In the Miami game,
the players were holding their hands on their heads to come out of
the game and that didn't sit well with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Practice respites were plentiful last season as the young
linemen struggled to grasp the system. Time and again, they'd take
a knee and listen to Tumey explain assignments and alignments.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Bruins know where to go and what to do,
permitting Franklin and Pearce to focus on techniques and
fundamentals. No detail is overlooked. Few breaks are granted and
water requests are often rejected. The results are palpable: The
defensive line appears to be UCLA's most improved unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The individual drills are so intense, and I think we got away
from that a little last year,'' said Holland, the defensive
captain. ``The coaches are good at relating how the drills improve
our play. We know they aren't something to keep us busy. They're to
stop the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   __ How they stand: Holland and sophomore Ken Kocher have emerged
as the top tackles in UCLA's four-man defensive front. Sophomore
Anthony Fletcher and redshirt freshman Steve Morgan comprise the
second unit, giving the Bruins four big tackles for the first time
in years. Fletcher, with his cinder-block shoulders, is the most
difficult player to block.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've all made jumps since the spring,'' Franklin said.
</P>
<P>
   Massive junior Kenyon Coleman mans one defensive-end spot, with
redshirt freshman Rusty Williams at the other. The top reserves are
senior Travor Turner, a pass-rush specialist, and redshirt freshman
Sean Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ends pride themselves on being great pass rushers, but the key
for us is stopping the run,'' Pearce said. ``That's what we're
focusing on.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Pearce must make do without one of his most experienced
players. Junior Santi Hall, an expected starter, is playing outside
linebacker until Ali Abdul Azziz and Ryan Nece return from their
disabled-parking-scandal suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   __ Saving a year? With their depth at receiver, the Bruins might
redshirt sophomore Jon Dubravac, who played sparingly as a freshman
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a real possibility if our receivers stay healthy,''
Toledo said. ``We've talked to the parents. He'll go to the Ohio
State game and then we'll make a decision. We want to try to save
his year.''
</P>
<P>
   College athletes have five years to play four seasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
