<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYPE DOESN'T MAKE RIVALRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; For all of you dizzy with anticipation about the next great
rivalry in golf, and of course we're talking Sergio Garcia and
Tiger Woods, close your eyes, take a deep breath and get a grip.
</P>
<P>
   The back nine of the PGA Championship Sunday afternoon at
Medinah Country Club outside Chicago was absolutely Jordanesque as
sports theater. It was the best finish to a major championship
since 1986, when Jack Nicklaus' improbable win at the Masters gave
golf a nostalgia transfusion.
</P>
<P>
   That was a glimpse of golf's past. Sunday afternoon, we saw its
future.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brent Musburger could not have overhyped Sunday, let's
get real.
</P>
<P>
   One round of golf _ even a stellar one _ does not a rivalry
make. Even a highly rated television special cannot get the rival
juices flowing.
</P>
<P>
   Rivalries are a lot like dancing, excluding tap and break. It
takes two to rival.
</P>
<P>
   It does no good to declare a rivalry, then get to the first tee
only to discover you haven't got anyone to rival. Which seems to be
where golf finds itself now in the lingering shadow of the
Garcia-Woods Sunday afternoon shootout.
</P>
<P>
   The two principals offered disparate views on this rival stuff
after the last putt fell.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, flush with the exuberance of youth and a golf game that
seems skilled beyond its years, seems ready to accept or issue the
challenge, which ever the case might be.
</P>
<P>
   After Garcia posted a birdie on the 13th hole Sunday he cast a
glance toward Woods that made it clear Tiger was the only one on
the course being stalked. This is a comfortable mindset for Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I said when I turned pro that I wanted to be the No. &UR;  &LR; 1
golfer in the world. And so I knew I was going to be a rival for
Tiger. But I said that I want to be a rival but always friends like
we did today,'' he said in the post match news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Woods, who is No. &UR;  &LR; 1, a position he could hold
for years, does not have such a narrow focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as competing against Sergio as a rivalry, well I hate
to say this. &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . I don't think there is,'' Woods said.
``Sergio and I had a wonderful match out there today. But I think
there are too many young players in the 20s. I think there is going
to be a handful of players that are going to lead golf into the
next millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   The list, Woods said, includes GarqIc.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes such established stars as David Duval, Justin
Leonard, Phil Mickels{.]
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
