<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE NATIVE AMERICAN REMAINS EXPECTED TO BE FOUND AT BLAINE, WASH.,
SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHUONG LE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLAINE, Wash. _ Archaeologists expect to find more skeletal
bones among dirt excavated from Blaine's waste-water treatment
plant.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Lummi Tribe continues to wait for an apology from
the city, which failed to notify the tribe when workers dug up
skeletal remains of 28 Native Americans and allowed some of the
bones to be shipped out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is determining who and where best to send it (the
apology),'' said John Hobberlin, the mayor of Blaine, a city of
3,500 located near the Canadian border.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal prosecutors are investigating whether the
city, its contractor or hired archaeologist violated criminal and
civil laws when they did not report initially finding the remains
July 26.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, government officials and tribal leaders were among
three dozen people who Wednesday visited the excavation site at
Semiahmoo, located a few miles southwest of Blaine.
</P>
<P>
   City officials were not invited to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of unanswered questions,'' said Timothy
Ballew, chairman of the Lummi Indian Business Council, the tribe's
elected ruling body. ``It's frustrating that they (city officials)
haven't talked to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The tribe is pushing for criminal charges, Ballew said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney General Susan Roe said investigators are
looking into whether federal laws protecting archaeological sites,
and the Native American Graves Protection and Repatriation Act were
violated.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meeting was called to determine how to proceed,
particularly with repatriating other remains.
</P>
<P>
   State, federal and tribal archaeologists believe more skeletal
bones will be found amid mounds of dirt piled at the site and a
nearby landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Kinley's grandfather and great-grandmother were born and
reared in the coastal village where the waste-water treatment plant
now stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our family,'' Kinley said, gesturing toward the site
where dirt is piled 15 feet high between dormant yellow and red
cranes. ``So it's very difficult. The people who were buried here
and who were disturbed were our family.''
</P>
<P>
   City, federal and tribal officials signed an agreement in
January requiring the city to notify the tribe should remains be
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The city discovered that the site was a Native American burial
ground when it built the first phase of the waste-water treatment
plant in the 1970s. At the time, skeletal remains and artifacts
found at the site were sent to researchers at Western Washington
University in Bellingham without the tribe being notified.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe fought several years to repatriate the remains and
signed an agreement this year to prevent that from happening again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that there were remains here,'' state senator Georgia
Gardner said as she visited the site Wednesday. ``Instead of making
sure that history didn't repeat itself, we've allowed it to happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the $7.6 million project was halted two weeks
ago. State and federal officials said they did not know when it
would resume.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe first learned of the skeletal remains when a member
visited the site two weeks ago and heard that bones had been found.
The remains could be from 150 to 4,000 years old, the tribe said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Two tribal officials flew to the Denver offices of Golder
Associates, the archaeological consultant firm, and discovered some
of the remains in boxes and paper bags in the back of a pickup
truck.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the city should be held accountable for its
actions, Hobberlin declined to comment. Blaine and Golder
Associates have both retained an attorney, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said the city is waiting to hear from all the agencies
involved to figure out what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we find out what we're supposed to do, we'll take the
appropriate action,'' Hobberlin said, adding that the city also had
heard from the White House on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The remains discovered at the construction site come from 28
burials and range from bones of individuals to full skeletons. The
remains were removed between July 26 and Aug. 2, Ballew said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
