<SLUG> BC-SOC-MUTINY-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION BARELY KICKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution hoped to begin a tradition
when they started MLS play four years ago. They probably did not
have losing streaks in mind at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But after falling to Tampa Bay, 1-0, Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, the
Revolution are two thirds of the way toward equaling their
league-record nine-game losing streaks they had in 1997 and '98.
Their streaks extended to six successive defeats, four successive
home defeats, and 284 consecutive scoreless minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution displayed some resilience, though, and the
addition of Leonel Alvarez in defensive midfield could allow them
to regain their playoff hopes. But Alvarez and Jeff Baicher,
acquired last week in trades, could not save the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay went on the defensive, absorbing the Revolution's
pressure for most of the first half, then scored in the 43d minute
and held off a committed Revolution effort in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't score, again, what can I say?'' forward Joe-Max
Moore said. ``We need to take more initiative and be more dangerous
in the box. They stayed compact and together, and that is what a
good team is supposed to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good feeling going into the game. Now we have to stay
positive. We have only one way to go _ ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore had been one of the more in-form strikers in the US in
recent weeks, scoring goals for the US national team against
Argentina and Germany, plus converting 10 times for the Revolution.
But Moore has not scored in an MLS game since a 5-2 loss to Los
Angeles July 11.
</P>
<P>
   The Mutiny moved into a tie with Miami for third place with 22
points, 4 ahead of the Revolution in the race for the final playoff
place in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   This was a potentially fatal blow for the Revolution, who have
only two regulation-time home victories this season. But they have
another chance to recover with games against low-standing teams _
at San Jose (Saturday) and at the MetroStars (Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution displayed enough cohesion to be a threat, but
after surrendering a goal to Ritchie Kotschau, they faced a
difficult uphill battle.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution received a break on the play leading to the goal
but simply failed to defend well against a free kick, leaving
Kotschau to convert a header off an excellent bending cross from
Dominic Kinnear. The move started when John Harkes fouled Carlos
Valderrama, and referee Marcel Yonan, instead of playing advantage,
ordered the Mutiny to take a free kick. This should have allowed
the Revolution to recover, but instead Valderrama played the ball
to Raul Diaz Arce, who found Kinnear.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the Mutiny had played conservatively, with Jeff
Causey forced to make only one difficult save, off Musa Shannon in
the 37th minute. And Valderrama's influence had been limited by
Alvarez, his former teammate for dozens of national team games with
Colombia. But on the goal, both outside backs moved into attack,
apparently surprising the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution had three good opportunities in the first half,
but most of their chances came at random, rather than through
impressive buildups.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the contest, the Revolution were desperately
attacking with some effectiveness but were stymied by a Tampa Bay
defense led by Joseph Addo, whose last game at Foxboro Stadium was
as a member of the Revolution in an exhibition against Ajax July
21.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Revolution have players with a lot of fighting spirit and
that can carry a team far,'' Mutiny coach Tim Hankinson said.
``They were obviously not going to give up without a fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
