<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPE-HOAX-TWO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOM: `RAPE' WAS A HOAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RACHEL OCHOA AND KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Mesa mother who claimed she was sexually assaulted last week
in a school restroom admitted Tuesday that she made it all up.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Kari Rae Bodenski, 31, was seeking attention,
particularly from her husband, when she told authorities that a man
attacked her Friday afternoon during ``Meet Your Teacher'' day at
Mendoza Elementary School in northeast Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safe to go to school,'' police Sgt. Earle Lloyd said.
``Nothing happened on that campus. We have no crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Police will ask that Bodenski, who has a kindergartner and
another child at Mendoza, be charged with false reporting. They
also will try to recoup some of the costs of the massive air and
ground search for the assailant.
</P>
<P>
   She is not in custody now, Lloyd said late Tuesday, but
authorities are trying to get her to seek psychological help.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd said Bodenski slugged herself in the head, leaving a large
bruise, scratched herself in the crotch area and cut her shirt and
bra with a pair of scissors. She then wrapped them in toilet paper
and left them in the corner of a stall. Police found them Tuesday,
after she confessed.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of evidence tipped police, who had grave doubts but had
to take Bodenski's claim seriously because of her injuries.
Authorities also wondered how the attack could have gone unnoticed
by the 500 or so parents on campus at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bodenski had emerged from a doorless restroom that opens onto
the school's inner courtyard and said that a man with cigarette
breath, dirty fingernails and long, messy hair had placed a sharp
object to her neck, knocked her unconscious and assaulted her.
</P>
<P>
   Bodenski spent two nights at Desert Samaritan Medical Center.
The hunt for the assailant continued over the weekend and during
the first two days of the new school year.
</P>
<P>
   The incident traumatized the school community, frightening
educators and parents alike. On the first day of school, parents'
cars clogged the street in front of Mendoza, making sure their
youngsters got to and from school safely. Police officers were on
hand, and safety was on the minds of everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Judi Willis, spokeswoman for Mesa Public Schools, was relieved
after hearing Tuesday's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along that schools are safe places for
students, teachers and parents,'' she said. ``I hope this will
restore some of that confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, Willis said, she had her doubts about Bodenski's
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just didn't seem right,'' she said. ``But you had to take
it seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the atmosphere at Mendoza will return to normal
today.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, some of the security measures that emerged may still remain
in place.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it's likely that staffers at Mendoza will wear
identification badges around their necks. It wasn't known late
Tuesday whether a parent meeting scheduled for tonight will still
be held.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Meko, who opened Mendoza 12 years ago and left this summer
to be principal of another Mesa school, has heard from many
distraught parents in the past several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled and relieved that Mendoza can get back to
normalcy,'' he said. ``I'm thankful that the good community of
Mendoza can send their kids back to a safe place.''
</P>
<P>
   He applauded the district and the city for stepping up security
after the ``assault'' and treating it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Meko didn't recognize Bodenski's name, saying that he believed
she and her children were new to the school this year.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is not the first hoax in the Mesa Unified School
District.
</P>
<P>
   In March, two fifth-grade girls concocted a detailed story about
a knife-toting transient who grabbed them as they were leaving
Porter Elementary School. They fought off the man, whom they said
chewed his nails, and sprinted to a neighbor's house to get help.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, the children broke down and admitted their lie was
part of a game of Truth or Dare, after several interviews with
police officers. &QL; 
(at)4 Rachel Ochoa can be reached at (602) 444-8048 or
rachel.ochoa(at)pni.com. Kelly Pearce can be reached (602) 444-7981
or kelly.pearce(at)pni.com. &QL; 
(at)2 Color photo by Michael Chow/The Arizona Republic &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
