<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2492 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RUN-HAYES-LADN-(SLANG     08-19 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-HAYES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT HURDLE FOR HAYES COMES IN SPAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ The Olympics have always been etched in Joanna
Hayes' mind, if not on her body.
</P>
<P>
   Stenciled in black ink on the upper right thigh of the UCLA
senior hurdler are tattoos of a dove and Olympic rings. Hayes said
tattoos are symbolic because releasing of doves is a traditional
part of the opening ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   If Hayes qualifies for the Olympics, she plans to add color to
her tattoo of the Olympic rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``People dream in black and white,'' said Hayes, 22. ``It is
reality when it becomes color. If I am going to put a tattoo on, it
might as well mean something.''
</P>
<P>
   There are deeper meanings than the just the Olympics. Dove is
her middle name as well as the name of her late grandmother. One of
Hayes' most treasured possessions is a ceramic dove made by her
grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes also has also a passage from the second book of Samuel
tattooed on her: ``He maketh my feet like hinds' to setteth me upon
high places.'' It is a passage Hayes learned in childhood, which
she uses as inspiration in track.
</P>
<P>
   For Hayes, who will compete in the World Track and Field
Championships beginning Saturday in Seville, Spain, the verse is
fitting. Hayes finally appears to be fulfilling a prophecy of an
illustrious high school career after an injury-riddled collegiate
career in Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to UCLA thinking, `I am going to be great...'''
said Hayes, named the 1995 Track &AMP; Field News Athlete of the Year
as a Riverside North High senior. ``I had all these expectations
and they just failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Those expectations were rekindled in June when Hayes won the
NCAA title in the 400 hurdles and finished third in the 100 hurdles
to lead UCLA to a runner-up finish in the team standings.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, Hayes followed her performance with a
third-place finish in the USA track and field championships to earn
a spot on the U.S. team for the World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes lowered her personal best in the 400 hurdles to 54.57
seconds to finish second in the World University Games last month
and was fifth in the Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year at NCAAs, they had to carry Joanna off the track,''
UCLA women's coach Jeanette Bolden said. ``It is not how hard you
fall but how far you bounce back. I think she has learned that.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hayes, the NCAA title will be remembered as the turning
point in her career, providing a confidence boost heading into the
USA championships. She had planned to stop running after 2001 if
she had not made an Olympic or World Championship team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My one NCAA title is worth more than anything else that I
could have gotten,'' Hayes said. ``If you work hard for something,
you appreciate it much more. If I didn't win the NCAAs, I would
probably not have made the world team because I would have been so
frustrated. I had to let it all go. This is where it all begins.''
</P>
<P>
   In last year's NCAA championships, Hayes finished eighth in the
100 hurdles after straining her right hamstring in the Pac-10
Conference championships. Hayes also missed the entire indoor
season after bunion surgery on both feet.
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore in 1997, Hayes hyperextended her right knee after
winning a heat in the 400 hurdles. In her freshman season, she did
not advance to the finals in either the 100 or 400 hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had a lot of faith that my third time I was going to do
something,'' Hayes said. ``Had I gotten hurt again, it would have
been pretty frustrating. I would have probably taken some time off
to think about what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes has never had to look far for inspiration at UCLA,
training with Jackie Joyner-Kersee and Gail Devers under the
supervision of Bruins hurdle coach Bobby Kersee.
</P>
<P>
   Running in practice against Joyner-Kersee, the world-record
holder in the heptathlon, and Devers, the 1992 and 1996 Olympic
100-meter champion, was a humbling experience. But it helped make
Hayes a better competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Although initially awestruck, Hayes found mentors in Devers and
Joyner-Kersee of the track. This summer, Hayes stayed at the
Kersees' home in St. Louis while preparing for the World
Championships. Joyner-Kersee, now retired, videotaped Hayes'
workouts to analyze hurdle technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give them all the respect that is due,'' Hayes
said. ``They're like friends and it's cool to be on the level where
you can sit down and hang out with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyner-Kersee is impressed with the 5-foot-5 Hayes' range, to be
competitive in the explosive 100-meter hurdles, in which she
clocked 12.89 in the NCAA championships, to the grueling 400-meter
hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is truly a talent to have the speed of a sprinter and the
endurance of a half-miler,'' Joyner-Kersee said. ``It still remains
to be seen what she is capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be a stern test for Hayes in the World Championships.
Hayes will likely have to run close to or under her personal best
in both the first round and semifinals to the reach the
eight-runner final.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no pressure for me to go out and do anything
spectacular,'' Hayes said. ``I want to have fun and use it as a
learning experience. But if I get to the final, anything is
possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
