<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2497 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-BREWERS-ASTROS-HN     08-19 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BREWERS-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The National Weather Service should have put the Astrodome area
under a tornado warning for most of Wednesday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But after being shut down for seven innings by Hideo Nomo _
nicknamed ``The Tornado'' for his corkscrew-like pitching motion _
the Astros made a lightning strike to steal a 6-4 victory from the
Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Down by three runs entering the bottom of the eighth, the Astros
struck for five runs in a rally highlighted by Carl Everett's
two-run double to move back into first place in the National League
Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won their third straight game to move a game ahead of
Cincinnati, which lost 12-6 to Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee dropped its fourth in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small margin is better than no margin,'' said Astros manager
Larry Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo took a 4-1 lead to the eighth before the Astros loaded the
bases with no outs on singles by pinch hitter Russ Johnson and
Craig Biggio and a walk to pinch hitter Ken Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   With Jeff Bagwell at the plate, reliever Eric Plunk threw a wild
pitch, scoring Johnson. After Bagwell struck out, Everett lined a
two-run double down the right-field line to tie the game at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Everett stole third base, Lance Berkman walked and Bill Spiers
struck out before Paul Bako hit a bouncer off reliever Bob Wickman
that sailed over the head of second baseman Ron Belliard for the
go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Gutierrez followed with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Everett said he wasn't surprised with the decision to pitch to
him _ even though first base was unoccupied and he is hitting .475
with 22 RBIs since returning from the disabled list Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured they pitched to Bagwell, so they would pitch to
me,'' Everett said. ``They rolled the dice and lost.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only the 11th time this season the Astros have rallied to
win in their final at-bat. They had 48 come-from-behind victories
in 1998, 27 in their final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't had many late-inning comebacks this year,''
Dierker said. ``We have a very good record that has been built
mostly on good pitching and getting ahead and staying ahead. We
haven't had too many dramatic finishes like last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a good time to have one because we may need to
have a couple more if we are going to win the division.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Williams (2-1) picked up the victory in relief of Mike
Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Wagner matched his career high with his 30th save in 32
chances, striking out three in the ninth. Wagner has struck out
seven of the eight batters he has faced in the series on only 26
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth inning was a complete reversal from the first seven,
when the Astros were frustrated by Nomo. The Astros regularly
showed impatience at the plate while trying to pick up the
righthander's forkball, and Nomo retired 13 of 14 batters at one
point.
</P>
<P>
   During a stretch in the third and fourth innings, he set down
five batters on five pitches. He ended up allowing four runs and
six hits in seven-plus innings, three of the runs scoring after
Plunk (2-3) took over.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton failed in his second try at becoming the first 17-game
winner in the NL. After a rocky first inning that included three
hits, two walks and two runs, Hampton retired 15 of the next 16
batters.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who has won his last seven decisions, gave up five hits
and tied a season high with nine strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys bailed me out again,'' Hampton said. ``This is
probably one of the most exciting games I've been a part of. The
first inning I fell behind in the count, but I felt as good as I
have all year after that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers jumped on Hampton when Belliard led off the game
with a single and Hampton loaded the bases with walks to Mark
Loretta and Dave Nilsson. Alex Ochoa gave the Brewers the lead with
a sacrifice fly, and Marquis Grissom had a run-scoring single for
the 1,500th hit of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Grissom went 3-for-4 with two RBIs. Bako and Gutierrez led the
Astros with two hits each.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros cut the Brewers' lead to 2-1 in the second on a walk
and Spiers' RBI double to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five innings, Nomo was in control. He retired the
side on three pitches in the third and six pitches in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee added a run in the sixth inning when Grissom tripled
to the right-field wall and Lou Collier hit an RBI single for a 3-1
lead. Grissom provided the Brewers' final run in the eighth with a
single off Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But then the floodgates opened for the Astros. The five runs
were the most they had scored in an inning since a six-run seventh
inning Aug. 5 against Los Angeles. -%HRP
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
