<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2498 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ATHLETICS-     08-19 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX TAKE ADVANTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ATHLETICS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Red Sox spent months talking about trading for
veteran pitcher Kevin Appier. They talked last December at the
winter meetings in Nashville, last March during spring training in
Florida, and right up to the midnight trading deadline in July,
when Appier was finally dealt by Kansas City to the Oakland
Athletics for three pitching prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's August, and while the Sox may still one day regret
their failure to add a pitcher of his pedigree, especially with
Bret Saberhagen on the shelf, they did not allow Appier to squirrel
their wild-card chances Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, beating the A's, 7-4,
before a crowd of 32,405.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox seized a 4-0 lead against Appier, gave it back in
one swoop after third baseman John Valentin dropped a popup by
Miguel Tejada to start the A's four-run sixth, then drove him out
of the game with three runs in the seventh inning, when Valentin
atoned at least in part for his glaring goof.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin followed that rarest of Fenway Park sights,
back-to-back triples by rookie Trot Nixon and Jose Offerman that
broke a 4-4 tie in the seventh, with a double to the
right-center-field gap that made it 6-4. Troy O'Leary followed an
intentional walk to Nomar Garciaparra, who already had scored one
run and driven in another, with an RBI single to right, the last of
a dozen hits off Appier.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin ended his night by making a leaping catch of Tejada's
liner and throwing out Eric Chavez on a ground ball for the final
out of Boston's ninth win in its last 12 games and second in three
against the A's, who trail by two games in the wild-card race. But
did he go home happy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Valentin, who said gusts blowing in from
the northwest carried the ball away from him, back toward the
plate, and ``I must have blinked at the end . . . unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I haven't been swinging the bat well,'' said
Valentin, who was 2 for 19 on the homestand until his double off
Appier. ``I'm not happy about that.
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . You always reflect on the negative. Obviously, I'm not
too happy about what happened, although it's baseball, anything can
happen, and obviously it did. It was nice to come up with a guy on
third base and drive him in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox relied on their newly retooled bullpen, now minus its
knuckleball closer, Tim Wakefield, to close out the A's. Rheal
Cormier, the first reliever out of the chute, had faltered during
the A's rally in the sixth, giving up a three-run double to Jason
Giambi, the first batter he faced, after starter Pat Rapp walked
three of the next four batters following Valentin's error. Rapp had
been working on a one-hit shutout until that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying so hard to pick him up,'' Rapp said of Valentin.
``He told me he knew he booted the ball, and asked me to pick him
up. I just couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Rich Garces, who wound up being credited with the win, worked a
1-2-3 seventh, and Derek Lowe pitched the final two innings,
allowing one hit and hitting a batter, for his sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe said he's now ready to take on the closer role ceded by
Wakefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do get the ball now as closer,'' he said, ``I'm much more
confident now. I wasn't throwing my changeup for strikes early in
the season, and I was walking guys. Now I'm throwing strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapp, whose wife Rebecca is undergoing a difficult pregnancy
back home in Louisiana, wasn't sure earlier in the week whether
he'd be able to make his start. His wife, who is nearly seven
months pregnant, was hospitalized with high blood pressure and
there was some risk, the pitcher said, of kidney failure that would
have placed both his wife and their unborn child in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   But his wife's condition stabilized, Rapp said, to the point
where she was able to return home, and he flew back to Boston
Tuesday night. ``After I talked to her, I called (Jimy Williams)
and told him I was flying back,'' Rapp said. ``But shoot, this is
my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   She remains confined to bed, and Rapp said he may return to
Louisiana Thursday, though after talking to her Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night,
he thought that might be unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to make it look like I show up only on the day I pitch,
like Nolan Ryan or Pedro Martinez,'' Rapp said. ``But Jimy knows
family comes first in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had taken a 1-0 lead in the third on Jason Varitek's
single, Darren Lewis's double, and Offerman's sacrifice fly.
Garciaparra opened the fourth by beating out an infield hit, which
shortstop Tejada fielded on his heels. Garciaparra took second on
an infield out and scored on Butch Huskey's two-out double that
caromed off the left-field railing. Varitek then singled home
Huskey, making it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The lead became 4-0 on singles by Offerman, Brian Daubach, and
Garciaparra, though the Sox lost a run when Garciaparra was out
trying to advance to second on O'Leary's fly ball to deep center
before Daubach had crossed the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But both Nixon and Offerman flew around the bases after their
seventh-inning gappers, which for Williams put into context
Garciaparra's aggressive mistake on the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pretty aggressive all night, and that was the one
situation that didn't work out, that's all,'' Williams said.
``Think about those two triples, rather than focusing on something
that didn't work out. Good effort, all the way around.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
