<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2499 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-MERCURY-COMETS-HN     08-19 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The exercise meant practically nothing to the Comets, who long ago
wrapped up superlative positioning for the upcoming WNBA playoffs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But their 70-60 victory over the Phoenix Mercury at Compaq
Center on Wednesday night was delivered with all the fervor and
intensity _ particularly on defense _ the Comets showed in their
previous 29 games while racking up the WNBA's best record (now
25-5).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable that we had everything clinched (for the
playoffs) and we were out there pressing like it was the first game
of the season,'' said Comets coach Van Chancellor, whose team
extended its league record for consecutive home victories to 12.
``That shows you the character of this team. I let 'em play
tonight. I didn't do a very good job of coaching in the second
half, because I got to watching them play.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two games, I've just enjoyed watching them play. I
mean, when you see (Sheryl) Swoopes, (Cynthia) Cooper, (Tina)
Thompson Lord, is that fun to watch. To press full-court and have
that much energy, boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, but I'm just a little pumped up tonight. And it
doesn't take much to pump me up, by the way. But to press, to run
and jump, to double the ball like we did _ and we had 10 steals.
Not bad for a team that should be tired and all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The final words of Chancellor's statement were a catch-all for
the emotional pall under which the Comets continue to labor with
point guard Kim Perrot on life support at M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets had fed off those emotions Monday night, getting a
WNBA season-high 42 points from Cooper, Perrot's close friend, in
an 80-71 victory over the Utah Starzz.
</P>
<P>
   Those emotions again played a role as the Comets beat the
Mercury for the eighth time in as many meetings at Compaq Center
over the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have love in our hearts for Kim, and you know what's
going on with her,'' said Comets reserve center Tammy Jackson. ``So
we just have to come out and do our jobs. That's what Kim would
want us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes (a game-high 24 points), Cooper (16) and Thompson (14)
combined for all but 16 of the Comets' points to throw a roadblock
in the path of the Mercury's late-season rally.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix (15-16), a multifaceted outfit the Comets defeated in
the WNBA championship round in 1998, had won two in a row and four
of its last five prior to Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is a good team,'' said Thompson. ``They got off to a
bad start this year, had to rebuild. Although they're not the same
team as 1998, the core is still there. So we know if we don't come
out and play hard against a team like that, they can probably beat
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not, however, on a night when Swoopes had another of her
all-around games (six rebounds, four assists, three steals). And
not on a night when Cooper handed out a game-high seven assists and
was 6-for-6 from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly not on a night when the Comets were penning
another chapter for their ongoing instructive manual on how to play
defense. The full-court trap, keyed at different times by Sonja
Henning, Cooper and Janeth Arcain out front, forced the Mercury
into 15 turnovers, a springboard to 23 Comets points.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jennifer Gillom, Phoenix's scoring leader, got 13 points
in the first half. But the Comets' help defense held her to a
single point over the final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard playing on the court where there's a lot of
emotion going on,'' Gillom said. ``I think this deal (Perrot's
situation) affected our team almost as much as them. I think we
were really sad after we went to the chapel (services) before the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix was not to be totally denied. After trailing 38-29 at
halftime, the Mercury pulled even at 42 on a follow shot by Maria
Stepanova (12 points, 12 rebounds) with 15:08 left in the final
half.
</P>
<P>
   But by outscoring the Mercury 16-2 over the next seven minutes,
the Comets built a 58-44 advantage with 8:25 left in the ballgame.
Phoenix would get no closer after that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just amazed,'' said Chancellor. ``I felt we were going to
have a letdown somewhere. I keep saying we're going to have a
letdown. We haven't had one yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
