<SLUG> BC-BBA-ATHLETICS-APPIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPIER SAYS HE HAD RIGHT STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, it was time to put a name with a
face. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Appier, the man with the awkward motion and habit of
appearing in Red Sox trade rumors, finally took his place on the
Fenway Park mound. Wearing the green, gold, and gray of Oakland,
the righthander pitched six-plus innings and picked up his first
loss since joining the wild-card contenders from the West Coast.
The crowd liked what they saw from the new Athletics' ace, who
reportedly held the Red Sox' interest before the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But what's not to like when the opposing pitcher allows a
season-high seven earned runs and implodes in the seventh with the
score tied? Then again, neither Appier, Oakland manager Art Howe,
nor pitching coach Rick Peterson saw much wrong with the starter's
part in the 7-4 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, I felt fine,'' said Appier. ``I didn't make
horrible pitches. Two balls were struck real well and (Jose)
Offerman hit a ball where nobody was. I felt strong. I thought I
had better stuff (than my last start). Overall, I had pretty good
command . . . It was extremely frustrating. They hit balls hard
where people weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloopers, bleeders, and balls hit to defensive holes doomed
Appier, automatically referencing the seventh inning when
critiquing his performance. From the visitors' viewpoint, bad
breaks and lucky hits hastened the end of the righthander's night.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon led off the decisive seventh with a triple to center.
Offerman followed with a triple down the right-field line. And John
Valentin doubled to right before the Oakland starter handed the
ball over to the bullpen. Appier finished with 94 pitches, 61
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he battled,'' said Howe. ``The only balls hit hard
were in the seventh inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Peterson: ``When you look at tonight's games, they had a
ton of ground ball bleeders in the infield and a couple bloops.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Oakland clubhouse, Peterson and Howe reflected on what
could have been. A call here. A few more inches to the right there.
A blooper that fell in.
</P>
<P>
   But the fans in Fenway would have agreed that everything fell
into place just fine for the win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-SABERHAGEN     08-19 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN TO MISS AT LEAST ONE START 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-SABERHAGEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The news was delivered without any drama or delay.
After all, Bret Saberhagen has been unfailingly honest about the
weakened condition of his right rotator cuff. The pitcher has
chronicled the growing pain and inflammation in his throwing
shoulder since the All-Star break, his discomfort on the mound
appearing most obvious during his start Tuesday against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   So Wednesday, when Saberhagen matter-of-factly announced he will
miss his next start, the clubhouse reacted with little surprise.
And Saberhagen did not voice false optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss one start and play it by ear after that,'' he said.
``If it's still not up to par after that, we'll take a little bit
more time. I really think we'd get it right if we'd take about a
month, but we don't have a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was the beginning of the season, it might be a different
story. I'd be able to take the proper time. But we don't have a
whole lot of time left in the season and I need to be out there.
We're going to do what we can in the short term.''
</P>
<P>
   With a late-season injury to a pitcher considered a medical
miracle after major shoulder surgery in 1996, the phrase ``short
term'' takes on an indefinite meaning. The consummate competitor,
Saberhagen wants to return to mound as quickly as possible and help
the Red Sox in the American League wild-card chase. But he has
little confidence that a mere 10 days rest and rehabilitation will
be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the pitcher would prefer a month off and will push
himself only because of the playoff race, missing two starts
remains a strong possibility. Knuckleballer Tim Wakefield will be
relieved of his duties as closer and moved back to the starting
rotation. The disabled list does not appear a likely option for
Saberhagen, considering the rosters expand Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said (missing) the next start was no problem,'' said
Saberhagen. ``They don't have to make a move or anything. With
September right around the corner, there's really no need for the
DL.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Saberhagen has set his limit at two missed turns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bottom line, I'll be back _ the longest missing two starts,''
he said. ``If I've been able to pitch with what I have now and if
it doesn't get any stronger, I'm just going to come back and deal
with it the way I have been. I was pitching effectively enough
until Wednesday night feeling like crap. I can be effective without
good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The shoulder feels weaker than it has at any point in the
righthander's career. Pain that initially was confined to one spot
now encompasses the entire area. Inflammation has spread and every
time Saberhagen throws the ball, he must deal with an unstable
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Star break Saberhagen has compiled a 3-3 record
with one no-decision. His most recent win came Aug. 11, when he
pitched eight innings and allowed just four hits against Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increasing pain, Saberhagen had pitched well
recently. Mid-July losses to Philadelphia and Baltimore were
followed by a no-decision at Toronto. Then he defeated the Yankees
to start this month. Saberhagen followed that start with a
seven-strikeout performance against Anaheim and the victory over
the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   But the positive results came to an abrupt halt Tuesday.
Saberhagen followed his longest start of the season with his
shortest. His 2 innings resulted in six hits, three earned runs,
and just one strikeout. Signs of Saberhagen's trouble came early
and often. The Athletics noticed Saberhagen took longer to loosen
up and never had to face his best fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen knows his time off will be filled with exercises
designed to strengthen the area around his rotator cuff. At the
same time, Saberhagen must balance workouts with rest. He continues
to take anti-inflammatory medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year, I'll be 100 percent,'' said Saberhagen. ``I'm not
going to be 100 percent this year. It's not happening. If we were
out of it (I wouldn't be rushing back). There's really no sense in
going out there and pitching if we're not fighting for something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2504 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-SCHOOLCHILDREN-SPI &LR;      08-19 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLCHILDREN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS URGED TO TALK TO CHILDREN ABOUT SEXUAL AWARENESS, SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SARAH SKIDMORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Preparing children for the school year is a hefty
task. After arming them with school supplies, backpacks and
lunches, parents also are encouraged to counsel their children
about sexual awareness and safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so important to talk to children before there is a time
when you won't be with them,'' said a representative from the
Domestic Abuse Women's Network, a support service.
</P>
<P>
   Children have received personal safety information in
Washington's classrooms since the early 1980s. While this
information has helped students, research shows that parent
discussion and reinforcement of these ideas are more successful at
helping children protect themselves from sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``If parents have established good communication with their kids
and continue to remind them, then the kids will see them as a
resource,'' said Debbie Halela, coordinator of sexual abuse
services for Youth Eastside Services.
</P>
<P>
   Schooltime issues can range from choosing a safe walking route
to and from school to dealing with new relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``The schools can give the information to the kids, but parents
know the best way to address the message to their individual
child,'' said Lindsay Palmer, director of education at King County
Sexual Assault Resource Center.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing an open line of communication allows children to
feel safe asking their parents questions about these new
experiences or problems. But creating this open communication can
be difficult or embarrassing for many parents and kids, Palmer
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't talk to a child just one time about crossing the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming that embarrassment can mean prevention from serious
future damage. Of the 41,407 cases investigated last year by the
state Child Protective Services, 6,767 cases involved allegations
of sexual abuse, according to the state Department of Children and
Family Services. The Sexual Assault Resource Center reports that
one in three girls and one in five boys will be sexually assaulted
by the time they are 16 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children are never too young to learn about appropriate
behavior,'' said the Women's Network representative, who didn't
disclose her name, citing security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Each parent will know the best means of communicating with their
child, Palmer said. But all information should be represented
clearly, factually and should help develop children's personal
safety skills and sense of self. Frequently the information can be
given just as any other instruction or conversation would take
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you sit down and say `This is the sexual information talk,'
it is going to make it uncomfortable for everyone,'' Palmer said.
``But by having an ongoing conversation, it is more natural and
leaves room for discussion in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no script or cure-all to use in every situation, Palmer
said. But arming children with a strong sense of self, the idea
that their bodies are their own and providing them with a safe
confidant are tools that will help them across the board.
</P>
<P>
   For young children, establishing what is appropriate behavior
can include touching or other personal safety related behavior. For
children just heading off to school, Palmer recommends identifying
issues such as safe travel routes, traveling with buddies and
checking in with a designated adult.
</P>
<P>
   At pre-adolescence children become aware of intimate
relationships and these issues should be addressed. If they are
unwilling to talk, continue to try or find someone they feel
comfortable talking with. For children of all ages, Palmer
recommends telling them to trust their instincts: If something
doesn't feel right, leave and tell someone.
</P>
<P>
   Information on age-appropriate material can be found through the
sexual assault resource center or may be recommended by school
counselors or health teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding this outlet relieves some of the pressure off the
child to handle it by themselves and shows that parents or the
community is willing to help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
