<HEADLINE>
BAKER RE-SIGNS WITH SONICS, VOWS TO `MAKE AMENDS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALIYA SAPERSTEIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Vin Baker said he was sorry, it won't happen again, so
the Sonics signed him to a seven-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who shouldered the blame for the Sonics' disappointing
25-25 record in the shortened 1998-99 NBA season, chose not to take
advantage of his free agent status and instead re-signed with the
Sonics Wednesday. The contract keeps the 6-foot-11 forward in
Seattle through 2006.
</P>
<P>
   No other terms were disclosed, but it is believed he stands to
make as much as $87 million over the duration of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, agent Aaron Goodwin and team president Wally Walker spent
most of the day in Sonics headquarters, drafting formal language on
the contract they had negotiated since July. They signed off on it
about an hour before an evening news conference, called hstily to
allow Baker's return home to Connecticut with his mother, Jean, in
attendance to lend moral support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a happy day ...'' Walker said. ``We won't insult your
intelligence and tell you what a great year last year was, but Vin
has made a commitment (to turn things around).''
</P>
<P>
   Baker took the blame for the Sonics missing the playoffs for the
first time in nine years and said he wouldn't allow himself to be
the reason again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to a tremendous career here, and to
returning to the form of the player I was two years ago,'' the
four-time All-Star said. ``I've made a commitment to this team to
get back to being the player I know I can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big weight off my shoulders,'' he added of closing the
deal. ``I can make amends for last season, get back to the playoffs
and get back to playing as best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he has been doing ``two-a-days'' with a trainer at
home in Connecticut, and he plans to be in Seattle for the next
month to work with Sonics strength and conditioning coach Dwight
Daub. Baker said he weighs 266 but hopes to lose six pounds before
camp opens Oct. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, after the protracted lockout, Baker reported about
20 pounds overweight, missed 16 games with thumb and knee injuries
and averaged 13.8 points and 6.2 rebounds _ his lowest marks since
his rookie season with the Milwaukee Bucks in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month prior to last season, I didn't work out at all,''
Baker said, ``and I suffered for it the whole season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be in the best shape of my career on October 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation had the Sonics wanting to include a weight clause in
the contract languagem but neither side would talk specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I will say is that there are bonus incentives in the
contract,'' said Walker, who explained that the clauses were
phrased as positives and not negatives.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said, ``I'm going to be in the best shape no matter what
the incentives or clauses are. The biggest thing for me is coming
back to this gym and coming back to KeyArena.''
</P>
<P>
   The team Baker is coming back to, of course, has a very
different look. Ten players are gone, and Walker signed six
newcomers. Though the Baker contract pushes the Sonics over the
salary cap, Walker said he plans to acquire a few more players
willing to make the league minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a great team. We're going to contend and compete.
I'm excited about the people they brought in,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some people are going to be disappointed a lot of
veterans are not here, but we've got a lot of good young guys
who're going to make it exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1993 first-round draft pick out of the University of
Hartford has career averages of 18.1 points and nine rebounds per
game. The Sonics acquired him from Milwaukee in a three-team trade
that sent Shawn Kemp to Cleveland in September of 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
