<HEADLINE>
PINIELLA PICKS UP 1,000TH WIN AS BIG-LEAGUE MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ On radio talk shows and Internet Web sites in recent
weeks, fueled by a blowout here and a Yankees sweep there,
disgruntled fans had come up with a thousand reasons for Lou
Piniella to lose his job.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the Mariners manager answered back with 1,000 more
for staying.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella reached a personal milestone, claiming his 1,000th
managerial victory as his club downed Toronto, 5-1, completing a
three-game sweep of the floundering Blue Jays, closing out a 4-2
road trip and climbing back to the .500 mark (60-60) for the first
time since July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days shy of his 56th birthday, Piniella got emotional while
addressing his players in the clubhouse. In return, they drenched
him with champagne. Another bottle on ice awaited him on his office
desk, compliments of the Mariners front office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud if it, but at the same time in a very humble way,''
Piniella said, between swigs. ``I thank the organizations that gave
me a chance to manage and I thank all the players who played hard
for me. I know this, you have to manage a long time to get 1,000
wins. I kept the job, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   His 13-year record stands at 1,000-926, 521 of those victories
coming with the Mariners, the rest with the New York Yankees and
Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   For those eager to see him go, Piniella apparently has no plans
for an abbreviated departure.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game Wednesday, he sat in the visiting manager's
office mulling the future, giddy about the possibilities. He rocked
back and forth in his chair. He smoked fiendishly. He used words
like ``quality,'' ``depth'' and ``hope'' to sum up his young
pitchers, something he couldn't do 12 months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   For the next few hours, Piniella, a guy who has built a
managerial career around veteran arms, watched rookie starter
Freddy Garcia claim his 12th victory in 19 deciw) &UR; 9s. The manager
received a crucial out from rookie reliever Steve Sinclair, the
lefty striking out Toronto's Willie Greene to snuff a bases-loaded
threat in the sixth. Piniella got a 1-2-3 inning in the seventh
from rookie Tom Davey, forced to handle the pressure of being a
former Blue Jay, as did Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans chipped in as well. Jay Buhner put the Mariners on the
scoreboard first with a two-run homer in the second. Brian Hunter
made a heroic catch in the seventh, running down a two-out fly ball
with the bases loaded and holding on after crashing into the fence
in left. Reliever Jose Paniagua went five-up, five down to close it
out as Jose Mesa got a day off.
</P>
<P>
   Players said they were glad to see Piniella rewarded, a little
in awe of the time involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows a lot of longevity,'' pitcher Jamie Moyer said.
``That's 9,000 innings of baseball. If you want to make it more
ridiculous, how many pitches do you think he has seen? It's pretty
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Buhner: ``To me, it's nice to see Lou do it, to be a part
of it, to get a big hit to get us out in the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Several managers have crossed the 1,000-victory threshold.
Mariners research indicates Piniella is just one of 18 managers who
have collected 1,000 wins and 1,000 hits as big-leaguers, 14 after
the turn of the century. Piniella and Yankees manager Joe Torre are
the only active members of this club.
</P>
<P>
   His hair matted and jersey soaked by champagne, Piniella
reminisced about his first victory as a manager, one that came with
the Yankees, decided by an eighth-inning Butch Wynegar home run.
</P>
<P>
   He paid homage to the late Billy Martin, the former Yankees
manager who made Piniella one of his coaches in 1985. Piniella get
started as a manager the next season, replacing a fired Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was my mentor in New York,'' he said of Martin. ``He's the
one who got me prepared for this. You can see I picked up a few of
his (bad) habits.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Piniella said his style is playing percentages, rather
than managing by hunch, which is a sign of the
information-overloaded times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use statistical data more than anybody else,'' he said. ``I
believe in percentages more than anything else. ... I like
information. The more information to me, the better. It avoids a
lot of second-guessing. Everybody's a manager, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has 1,000 wins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
