<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QBS MUST STEP IT UP; HUARD TO SEE ACTION AHEAD OF FOLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHENEY, Wash. _ The past. The present. And the future.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bare bones meaning of the Thursday night's nationally
televised game against the 49ers in San Francisco for the Seahawks
quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Kitna will start and play much of the first half at 3Com
Park. In a reversal of roles from the preseason opener, rookie
Brock Huard will follow Kitna and be followed by Glenn Foley, if
time allows.
</P>
<P>
   Each must play better than he did last Saturday night in a 24-10
loss to the Buffalo Bills in the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just talking to Jon and I said, `OK, now we take another
step this week, and against a real good football team,''' coach
Mike Holmgren said Wednesday as he left the practice field at
Eastern Washington University after the team's light 35-minute
workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build on what we've accomplished,'' he said.
``There were some good things in the first game, and certainly we
made some errors. Now we have to be better in this game in those
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna and Foley faced the 49ers last year with varying degrees
of success and frustration.
</P>
<P>
   During a preseason game in Vancouver, B.C., last August, the
49ers baited Kitna into throwing a pass that was intercepted and
returned 70 yards for a score by cornerback Marquez Pope in a
three-point San Francisco victory. It was the kind of mistake a
young quarterback could learn from.
</P>
<P>
   Except that Warren Moon had ended his holdout a few days
earlier, so Kitna did not start another game until Week 12 of the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Moon is now gone (to Kansas City), and so is the coach who
discovered Kitna but had a difficult time forgiving him for
throwing one bad pass in one preseason game (Dennis Erickson, now
at Oregon State). Also missing Thursday night will be Pope, who
signed with Cleveland in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I learned more in that game than I did in the five
games I played (and started) at the end of the year,'' Kitna said
this week. ``I think there was somewhat of an overreaction to it.
... That's not something that sticks out in my mind as a negative.
It was just another game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of greater concern to Kitna, and more important to his team, is
how he reacts Thursday after producing just three points against
Buffalo. The Bills blitzed more than the Seahawks expected, forcing
Kitna to scramble more than he or Holmgren want.
</P>
<P>
   Against the 49ers, Kitna will be staring into the face masks of
a defense that last year collected 51 sacks, third-best in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to move the ball,'' Kitna said.
</P>
<P>
   That might sound simplistic, but the first thing the No. 1
offense needs to do is eliminate the mistakes that stalled drives
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never established any rhythm against the Bills,'' Kitna
said. ``This week we need to do that, get some first downs, get
some six-, seven-, eight-play drives going so we can establish some
tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers are good, but far from infallible. Foley proved that
last year, when as the starter for the New York Jets and threw for
415 yards and three touchdowns against San Francisco in the opener.
Despite his career-best effort, the Jets lost a wild 36-30 decision
in o6e{time.
</P>
<P>
   As with Kitna, Foley, obtained in a March trade for a
seventh-round draft pick, can't be concerned with his last game
against the 49ers. After his three-turnover performance against the
Bills, Foley must play better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled the other night. That's the way it works, when you
don't play well, you're not going to play,'' Foley said of being
leap-frogged by Huard, a left-hander from the University of
Washington and Puyallup High School. ``There's no defending it,
you've got to play better. Until I do that, I'm going to be on the
bench.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
