<SLUG> BC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLMGREN PATIENT AS YOUNG QUARTERBACKS STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In preparation for a pretend game Thursday night
against the esteemed, venerable San Francisco 49ers, Seattle
Seahawks fans are traditionally urged to be patient and maintain
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   But that suggestion is wasted on a lot of seasoned fans, who are
used to and unruffled by the Seahawks' annual preseason bludgeoning
from Steve Young, Jerry Rice et al.
</P>
<P>
   Save the advice for Mike Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   The new coach was so torqued after losing the exhibition opener
to Buffalo Saturday in the Kingdome that his wife, Kathy, had to
talk him off the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went home ... I was upset,'' Holmgren said. ``My wife is a
very good listener. Finally she said, `Do you remember how it was
the first couple of games in Green Bay?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I took a deep breath. She reminded me of several things, which
is all of what I told the team the next day: it was preseason, we
can't lose sight of our goals, that sort of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Could be that the Seahawks might be overpaying Holmgren and
underpaying his wife. Then again, Holmgren's bloomers were bunched
for a sound reason.
</P>
<P>
   Installing a new offense heavily dependent on intelligent,
experienced quarterbacking, Holmgren has in Jon Kitna, Glenn Foley
and Brock Huard three quarterbacks who have 14 NFL starts among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Anakin Skywalker won the big desert race have pilots
so young been counted on for so much so early. And the Seahawks do
not have the benefit of special effects to vaporize mean, icky
aliens such as the 49ers' Charles Haley.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks offense will not be pretty. Not just Thursday
night, but probably all the way though September and perhaps
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   For public consumption, it is said that all the quarterbacks are
doing well. But there are private doubts that training all three
youngsters simultaneously will persuade many viewers that ``It's
Now Time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the toughest offense I've had to learn,'' said Foley, who
at 28 is the graybeard with five seasons and eight starts, all with
the New York Jets. ``It's an aggressive philosophy. I've never been
in an offense that throws this much.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Huard, a rookie from Washington: ``It can be pretty
intense. It's a lot. When you formulate it in a meeting room, it's
enjoyable because it makes sense. But on the field, everything is
done in split seconds. Big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Kitna, with six previous NFL starts: ``Every time you learn
something new, it takes time. We'll get there.''
</P>
<P>
   But not nearly as fast as a seasoned QB. And not nearly as fast
as local expectations, including the franchise's own hype machine,
would have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, `It's Now Time,' and all that,'' said Holmgren.
``But with young guys, you have to walk before you can run. Even
though it's now time, I'm not taking any shortcuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I have to fight the urge (to take shortcuts). I can't
give them things they're not ready for. I know people might get
impatient with that. It will click in at some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's problem parallels the one he had when he took over in
Green Bay in 1992. His three young quarterbacks there were also
blank pages. As it turned out, Brett Favre, Mark Brunell and Ty
Detmer flourished. Brunell and Detmer ended up doing it elsewhere,
and Favre took the Packers to two Super Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situations are similar,'' Holmgren said. ``The difference
there was once Brett got it, he was so physically talented, you
really felt this was going to be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark had great ability as well. Ty was the one who grasped
everything a little sooner. But he wasn't as physical as the other
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one has identified the Seahawks QBs as the next Favre
or Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel the same way about Jon's ability to grasp the offey
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
