<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS CRUSH PADRES, 9-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It has become a sort of race within the race.
</P>
<P>
   As the New York Mets and the Atlanta Braves vie daily for the
National League East lead like two thoroughbreds fighting down the
stretch, Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura keep piling on the home runs
and runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ventura and Piazza homered on Wednesday night and they both
drove in three runs. The Mets accordingly obliterated the San Diego
Padres, 9-1, at Qualcomm Stadium. And because Atlanta lost, 4-1, in
Colorado, the Mets (74-48) could fly home to New York early
Thursday morning after a 4-2 Western swing in sole possession of
first place. It was their eighth series victory on the road, a
franchise record.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long for Ventura to reclaim the team lead in
homers with his 28th of the year, a three-run first-inning shot to
right off the San Diego rookie Stan Spencer that set the tone for
the evening's rout.
</P>
<P>
   The third baseman's lead did not last long. Piazza's solo homer
in the third was his 28th of the season, too _ and the All-Star
catcher's fifth in the last six games.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza cannot seem to make much of a dent in the club rbi lead,
however. Ventura, whose candidacy for the league's most valuable
player award grows stronger by the day, has led the team nearly all
season. He now has an even 100 rbi to 91 for Piazza, with a little
more than six weeks to go in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   While Ventura and Piazza provided the runs, Masato Yoshii made
the most of them. After allowing a run-scoring double to Tony Gwynn
in the first, Yoshii (8-8) settled down to retire the next 16
Padres in a row. In all, he allowed one run on six hits as he
tossed the Mets' second complete game of the season with his second
straight strong start.
</P>
<P>
   The only bad news came in the fifth when Rickey Henderson
strained his left ring finger trying to turn a single into a double
in an 8-1 game. Henderson, who was thrown out by Gwynn, had to
leave the game. There was a touch of irony in that, though. Had
Henderson hustled out his leadoff double in the ninth inning on
Tuesday, he might have had a triple instead _ and the Mets might be
enjoying a two-game lead over the Braves as they flew home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Rickey today,'' Valentine said on Wednesday
afternoon, hours after Henderson had admired the flight of his near
home run on Tuesday. It caromed off the left-field wall and never
reached the seats, as Henderson was hoping. He cruised into second
with a double and was stranded there to end the Mets' 3-2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he could have been on third, I wish he was,'' Valentine
said. ``We talked and we're fine. We're absolutely on the same
wavelength. If that was a triple, I think he'll be on third base
the next triple he gets.''
</P>
<P>
   The key word was if.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I keep prefacing this thing,'' Valentine said.
``It's over. I don't know if he would have made it.''
</P>
<P>
   No one will ever know what would have happened had Henderson
been standing on third. But while many people felt Henderson should
have had a leadoff triple, Henderson was definitely not one of
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably wouldn't have made a difference,'' the 40-year-old
left fielder said when he was asked if he could have made it to
third if he was running full-speed. ``I don't get out of the box
that good anymore when I hit a fly ball like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? We're talking about baseball's career stolen base leader
here, the guy who led the major leagues with 66 of them last
season, the same guy who had a respectable 29 steals coming into
Wednesday night. But Henderson has been plagued by nagging injuries
to various quadriceps, hamstrings and knees this season. And this
afternoon, Valentine said Henderson's hip flexor injury is ``not a
thing of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's flap was, as far as Valentine was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson put it behind him rather quickly, too. He led off
Wednesday night's game with a single, took second one out later on
a John Olerud single, advanced to third on a Piazza line out, then
scored with Olerud on Ventura's three-run first pitch blast.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres rallied for a first-inning run of their own on a
one-out Eric Owens single, a stolen base, and Gwynn's run-scoring
double to left. But the Mets made it 4-1 in the top of the second
on Benny Agbayani's leadoff double and Rey Ordonez's run-scoring
single.
</P>
<P>
   And then Piazza unloaded off Spencer with one out in the third
to tie Ventura for the team lead in homers, as the Mets went up by
5-1. Spencer (0-6) departed for a pinch-hitter in the bottom of the
inning, after 75 pitches. Carlos Almanzar fared little better in
the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza grounded a single between short and third with the bases
loaded in the fourth for his 90th and 91st runs batted in of the
season. The Mets led by 7-1. And they were about to head home all
alone in first after making their first Western swing of the season
a smashing success.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
