<HEADLINE>
SPARKS USE BENCH IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Sparks got a big boost from
their bench and moved one step closer to their goal of hosting the
first round of the WNBA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   With reserve forward Allison Feaster leading the way with a
career-high 16 points, the bench contributed 41 points in the
Sparks' 72-54 rout of the Minnesota Lynx in front of 8,943 at the
Forum Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that we've been concerned about is getting
our bench involved,'' Sparks coach Orlando Woolridge. ``We're going
to need everybody to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (19-11) are within a win from securing home-court
advantage. They host Western Conference champions Houston Friday
and end the season at Utah Saturday. If they win at least one game
they will host the Sacramento Monarchs in the single-elimination
playoff game Tuesday. The Sparks, second in the Western Conference,
are one-half game ahead of the Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   They won it without needing much from Lisa Leslie, who was sick
with a cold. The 6-foot-5 center scored only two points in 14
minutes. But the rest of the Sparks stepped up with everyone
contributing except for Nina Bjedov, who sat out her fourth game in
a row with a strained back.
</P>
<P>
   Tamecka Dixon scored 10 points and Penny Toler had nine, plus
three assists and three rebounds, while Gordana Grubin had 13
points among the starters. Feaster, who averages 12 minutes, played
23 as she went 6 of 9 from the field, including two 3-pointers in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad that coach gave me the opportunity,'' Feaster
said. ``I just tried to be aggressive and make the best of my
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks outrebounded the Lynx 44-16.
</P>
<P>
   The rout started in the midway through the first half when the
Sparks stretched the game out with a 16-0 run to go ahead 38-18
with 2:19 to go before the half. The Lynx (14-16) went seven
minutes without scoring a basket until Katie Smith, who will be
teammates with Leslie and DeLisha Milton on the USA national team,
broke the drought with a 3-pointer from the left baseline a minute
late.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big impact in the game and we never had an answer
for it,'' Lynx coach Brian Agler said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of reason is because he held leading scorer, Brandy Reed,
out of the lineup for the fourth consecutive game. Reed has been
disciplined for violation of team rules in the past. The Lynx are
2-2 without her.
</P>
<P>
   Agler declined to comment on why he held Reed out again, but he
did forecast the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is the team to beat, but if any team can beat Houston,
it's L.A.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
