<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR ON RELIEF FLIGHT WILL DO `THE BEST I CAN' IN TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN IWASAKI  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A retired Pierce County physician will be part of a
medical team traveling from Seattle to the heart of
earthquake-ravaged Turkey on Thursday on the maiden flight of a
Boeing 737-800 bought by Turkish Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be facing desperate people, hurting people, many
of whom have lost loved ones,'' Dr. Michael Spiger said. ``It's
something I've never faced before. I will go and do the best I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiger will join four or five nurses and paramedics from Oregon,
Idaho and California in a relief effort coordinated by Northwest
Medical Teams, a Portland-based non-profit organization.
</P>
<P>
   He practiced internal medicine for 22 years in Puyallup, Wash.,
before retiring two years ago, and has long been interested in
international relief work. He has been a full-time volunteer with
Northwest Medical Teams since his retirement, helping to coordinate
shipment of surplus supplies and equipment to needy countries.
</P>
<P>
   This will his first trip as part of a medical relief team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine it will be like a first-aid station, working as a
team,'' said Spiger, who lives in Graham, about 20 miles southeast
of Tacoma. ``You can imagine the need, with thousands and thousands
of people injured.''
</P>
<P>
   The team will be based in Izmit, the epicenter of Tuesday's
7.4-magnitude quake that killed nearly 4,000 and injured more than
18,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially our team will be working with medical professionals
that are already at work, helping with crush wounds,'' said Eric
Odell, spokesman for Northwest Medical Teams.
</P>
<P>
   Spiger's team, which is bringing a shipment of medical supplies,
also will assist with stemming diseases associated with
contaminated water lines and decaying bodies, Odell said.
</P>
<P>
   In a related effort, the Turkish American Cultural Association
in the Seattle area is planning to load the same Boeing plane with
more than 80 boxes of donated clothing, blankets, sleeping bags and
canned food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't even (stop to) eat something,'' said John Gokcen,
vice president of the 1,000-member association, panting after an
afternoon of packing boxes at his Kirkland home. ``If we can help
the people who need it, it will be a relief for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gokcen's group on Wednesday received 55 boxes of canned food
from Fred Meyer stores, 100 T-shirts from Tully's Coffee and
packing containers from the U-Haul Co., in addition to private
donations.
</P>
<P>
   The plane that will carry the relief supplies and medical team
was bought by Turkish Airlines. Its initial cargo was only going to
be 3 tons of textbooks sent by San Diego State University to a new
university in Istanbul. When disaster struck, Thursday's scheduled
delivery of the plane became fortuitous.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a brand-new airplane is leaving the factory and going to an
area in need, we try to make sure _ with the airline's approval _
that it doesn't go empty,'' said Carol Cella, a Boeing spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work with the airline delivery schedule,'' she said. ``It's
not often that a delivery will coincide with a disaster, but we're
very grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with its airline customers and relief agencies, Boeing
is involved with 30 to 40 international relief efforts a year and
has transported nearly 1,000 tons of supplies worldwide since 1992,
Cella said.
</P>
<P>
   Two Christian relief and development agencies based in the
Seattle area are accepting donations to help earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
   World Concern will transfer all donations received in the next
two weeks to International Protestant Fellowship, an organization
already at work in Turkey. Donations can be sent to World Concern,
19393 Fremont Ave. N., Seattle, WA 98133. Checks should be
earmarked for ``Turkey earthquake relief.''
</P>
<P>
   World Vision will use donations to send supplies or to assist
relief organizations in Turkey. Donations can be sent to World
Vision, P.O. Box 9716, Federal Way, WA 98063. For more information,
call 888-56-CHILD.
</P>
<P>
   Those wishing to help Northwest Medical Teams can make a
donation to the organization's account at any branch of U.S. Bank
of Washington. Gifts should be designated for the Turkish relief
fund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 0158EDT &QL; 
