<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE2-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT MAKES PITCH TO STAY IN ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
 WRITETHRU (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Darren Dreifort doesn't want to broach the subject
of bullpen vs. starting rotation. He has heard it for too long.
</P>
<P>
   A few more efforts like the seven-hit, 7-0 shutout the Los
Angeles Dodgers right-hander threw against Florida on Wednesday and
Dreifort won't have to worry about being banished to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dreifort's second shutout and second complete game of his
career. It also helped the Dodgers avoid being swept three games by
the Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might make a starter yet,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said with a chuckle. ``He stayed in a good grove, threw some
quality breaking balls against a good fastball-hitting club. That,
to me, is what I call an outstanding pitching performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most impressive start of Dreifort's career came in
front of his dad, John, who flew in from his Kansas home to see his
son pitch at Dodger Stadium for the first time since his rookie
year.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort, plagued by control problems for most of his career,
did not walk a batter. He has walked just five in his last five
starts. Dreifort (10-12) struck out four, didn't allow a Marlin
past second base and had four perfect innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a double-edged sword,'' Dreifort said of
pitching so well. ``It feels good to get it, but I wish I would
have gotten it a couple of months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's other shutout came in May 1998, when he beat Arizona
5-0.
</P>
<P>
   __ Looking toward September: Rosters expand from 25 to 40 on
Sept. 1, and the Dodgers have started to talk about possible
call-ups. Johnson recently met with Dodgers farm director Bill
Geivett to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a dual purpose (for call-ups),'' Johnson said. ``You
look and see if a guy should be on the 40-man in the winter, and
look at what kind of role they may have on next year's club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers don't have many options at the minor-league level,
but Johnson said he expects to go heavy with middle infielders and
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most intriguing pitcher is Greg Gagne, who's 12-4
with a 2.71 ERA with Double-A San Antonio. Gagne is the only player
below Triple-A Albuquerque expected to get a late-season look.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Jeff Williams (9-5, 4.66 ERA), Matt Herges (8-3, 4.73)
and Ricky Stone (5-8, 5.41) and infielders Adam Riggs (.286), Alex
Cora (.329) and Juan Castro (.283) are all probables.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Dodgers are expected to bring catcher Angel Pena back
once rosters expand.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added that lefty Carlos Perez, who's in the first year
of a three-year, $15.5 million contract and is the minor's
highest-paid pitcher, isn't likely to make it back to the Dodgers
before Sept. 1. Perez, who pitches today, is 1-2 with a 7.94 ERA
with Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, Carlos, it looks like he needs a couple more
starts,'' Johnson said. ``Carlos may be a September call-up.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow:!Dugout club seats:The Dodgers announced their plans for
the Dugout Club seating that will close the distance between the
catcher and backstop by 25 feet. It's part of the continuing
renovations at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dugout Club Lounge will have a bar, restaurant and bar-style
seating, a buffet area and 23 television monitors, and seat 565
fans. The first row is 58 feet from home plate. Tickets for the
first two rows will be $225. The remaining 485 seats will be $195.
It's expected to be ready for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Extra bases:Right-hander Robinson Checo will pitch in a rehab
assignment for Class A San Bernardino today. Righty Antonio Osuna
will accompany Checo, but Dodgers officials said they weren't sure
whether Osuna would pitch. . . . The Dodgers will wear a patch
honoring Pee Wee Reese, who died Saturday at the age of 81. The
black-colored ``Pee Wee 1'' patch is sewn onto the Dodgers uniform
above the existing Dodgers hero patches.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
