<HEADER>
A2618 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-BRADLEY-COLUMN-COX     08-19 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patchwork Reds can't be ignored
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves are locked in a divisional chase with the
Mets, and yet the Mets aren't the immediate threat. The Braves can
finish five games behind New York and still reach the World Series.
Danger lies elsewhere. Danger sits in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Figure it this way: The Mets and Astros, high-salaried clubs
dotted with name players, will make the playoffs. Their star
wattage dimmed by injury, the Braves mightn't fend off both
worthies over the course of 162 games. Fine. That isn't required.
To qualify for postseason the Braves must stay ahead of the
second-best team in the NL Central, which most years would be a
simple task. But this isn't most years, and the Reds aren't most
teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds entered the season with the 11th-fattest payroll in a
16-team league. The Braves' three priciest pitchers will earn a
collective $25.3 million this season. Cincinnati's entire
opening-day roster was slated to make $33.2 million. Yet the Reds
awoke Wednesday to find themselves tied with Houston atop the NL
Central, owners of the fewest losses among NL teams.
</P>
<P>
   On talent, the Astros should nose past the Reds to take the
Central, but this band of overachievers can still author the
ultimate in overachieving by wresting the wild card from Atlanta or
New York. Small-market franchise trumps big-ticket rival: It'd be a
nice story for baseball, a sport annually cheapened by its monetary
imbalance. If you're Cleveland, where's the glory in winning a
division in which nobody else is trying?
</P>
<P>
   The Reds are trying. The Reds are playing beyond their meager
means. Aaron Boone, the third baseman, earns one-tenth what older
brother Bret does, but Boone the younger is outhitting his sibling
by nearly 50 percentage points. Sean Casey is hitting .341 and
making $220,000. Right field is a cobbled-together collective _
Jeffrey Hammonds, Dmitri Young and erstwhile Brave Michael Tucker _
that has produced 84 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about this team seems dazzling, nothing save the
results. Tuesday's game can stand as a case study. The unheralded
starter Ron Villone left after six innings, the score tied.
Relievers Danny Graves, Scott Williamson and Gabe White limited
Pittsburgh to two hits and no runs over the next six innings. Chris
Stynes, hitting .176 at the time, won it with a homer in the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   A bullpen that looked shaky three months ago _ remember, the
Reds were desperate enough to trade for Mark Wohlers _ has been
Cincy's salvation. The Reds have gotten 33 saves and 19 wins from
Graves and Williamson, who together are making $482,000 less than
Russ Springer. Collectively the Reds' relief has propped up a
rotation that, with the addition of deadline tradee Juan Guzman and
the return of Denny Neagle from injured reserve, has recently
solidified.
</P>
<P>
   Even in their weakened state, you wouldn't pick the Braves to
finish behind the Reds. (Behind the Mets, you probably would.) This
is baseball, where generally teams get what they pay for. But there
is about these Reds a look that should be unsettling to their
richer brethren. It's a look seldom seen in this sport anymore.
It's a lean and hungry look.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
