<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2646 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-MICKEY-TEX     08-19 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MICKEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT YOU THIS, HUGH IS UNASSUMINGLY CHARMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In interviews promoting the gangster romantic comedy ``Mickey
Blue Eyes,'' Hugh Grant has often been quoted as saying that he
rewrote his character and his lines to make both funnier. He might
as well say that he rescued the film, because without him, it would
have sunk like a pair of cement boots.
</P>
<P>
   Even with him, it just barely keeps its humorous head above
water. Although the screenplay has its share of funny moments, it's
so slight and contrived that its plot sequencing seems to be held
together by paper clips. It's also so similar to this spring's
``Analyze This,'' which was just released on video, that it even
features some of the same actors. Like ``Analyze This,'' Mickey is
about a ``civilian'' who gets mixed up with the mob. Like ``Analyze
This,'' ``Mickey'' features the teaming of a comic star and a
``Godfather'' series alumnus. And, as in ``Analyze This,'' a
wedding hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Which of the two you prefer will probably depend on your taste
for pacing and for Grant's diffident acting style. ``Mickey'' is a
less frantic film than ``Analyze This,'' and director Kelly Makin _
who made the drastically uneven ``Kids in the Hall: Brain Candy'' _
handles it with a steady, journeyman style that places the movie
completely in its actors' hands. It's not like Makin has a sense of
vision so much as it's like he knew that with a talented cast, all
he had to do was make sure the cameras were running.
</P>
<P>
   Grant plays Michael Felgate, an art-house auctioneer who's
happily involved with schoolteacher Gina (Jeanne Tripplehorn, more
appealing than usual because she turns down her shrillness a
notch). Everything is going fine till Michael proposes to her (in a
Chinese-restaurant scene that's funny despite its racial
stereotyping), and she freaks out. It's only after she freaks that
Michael _ who's a little slow on the uptake _ discovers that Gina's
father (James Caan) is a big guy in the mob. Michael also gradually
discovers that ``family ties,'' in this case, has more than one
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between ``Analyze This'' star Billy Crystal's
acting style and Grant's shtick is the difference between an actor
saying ``Aren't I cute?'' and an actor saying ``I know I'm cute,
but I'm embarrassed about it,'' and it's Grant's sheepishness that
makes ``Mickey'' preferable to the earlier film. Grant has an
offhand way with a punch line that makes it seem unscripted, so
that you don't think you're watching a movie that's designed to
have a laugh track. Caan teams with him with such ease that you
forget it's Caan up there; when he tries to teach Michael some
Brooklynese, it's a highlight, even though it's a direct steal from
a bit in ``Donnie Brasco.'' Other funny bits come in an
Italian-restaurant scene and in the movie's climax, although sharp
viewers will be able to figure out how things will end up.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Makin and screenwriters Adam Scheinman and Robert Kuhn
deserve at least a little credit for the movie's funniest moments,
and character actors Burt Young and James Fox offer solid support
as bosses of different types (former ``Kid in the Hall'' Scott
Thompson, a very funny guy, is wasted in a straight role as an FBI
agent). But this is Grant's show; he and longtime love Elizabeth
Hurley took a lot of care in their production work on it, and his
affection for the material shows. It's as charming and lightweight
as Grant's on-screen persona, and in this season of comedies that
try to ram themselves down your throat, one that's this
ingratiating is a welcome albeit not overwhmlling sight.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Mickey Blue Eyes''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Kelly Makin
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Hugh Grant, James Caan, Jeanne Tripplehorn
</P>
<P>
   Length: 105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ strong language, violence and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
