<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 10:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN22-CO     08-19 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Hey, it's the Son of Sam hour!
 &HT;    (For release Aug. 22, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of those channel-surfing nights. Weary of the
slam-bam action movies, the silly sitcoms and sports events that
held no interest, I surfed over to ``Larry King Live'' on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   And who was it Larry was talking with? I couldn't believe it.
David Berkowitz, a.k.a. Son of Sam; murderer of six women, fiend.
In Texas or Florida, he's dead meat by now. In no-death-penalty New
York, however, he gets to spend an hour on the air with Larry King
while waiting out his 300-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, many have accused King of throwing up
marshmallows to his guests. I don't think that; what I really
believe is that King asks decent questions but accepts marshmallows
for answers.
</P>
<P>
   This was the case with King and Berkowitz. Example: King asks,
``But for people watching, especially younger people who don't
know, why _ first, what was it like to kill someone first time you
killed someone? We all wonder about something like that. What was
it like?''
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz clutches his Bible. ``Larry, I don't want to dwell on
that much, and _ I don't dwell on it at all. It was a horrible
thing. It was a horrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gee, I feel so sorry for Berkowitz, that horrible thing he had
to go through. It must have been rough shooting all those women.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the interview was atrocious, if not promotional.
Spike Lee's film version of Berkowitz's rampage hit theaters a few
weeks ago, much to the horror of the victims' survivors who had to
relive their most dreadful memories. Now, seemingly riding
piggyback on the movie's notoriety, CNN and King gave Berkowitz the
air time. The message of the hour: Poor old David, he had his bad
days but that's all behind him now. He's in touch with a forgiving
God.
</P>
<P>
   King lets Berkowitz get away with the tiresome alibi of a lousy
childhood. It's not King's questions that are appalling; it's
Berkowitz's answers. And always, Berkowitz is referring to the
Scriptures. Sometime in his 22 years in prison, the fiend found God
and Jesus. Guys in the slammer for a long time usually do. The
trick is to find God before you do the things that put you in the
slammer.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, I'm glad Berkowitz listens to God now. When he was
doing his murdering, he said he was acting on orders of his
neighbor's dog _ Sam.
</P>
<P>
   I've known King since his days in the 1950s when he'd show up at
the Miami baseball park with his pack of cigarettes rolled up in
the sleeve of his T-shirt, when he was doing sports for a one-lung
radio station. When I was managing editor of The Miami News, I
hired him to write a notes column for the newspaper. I often was a
guest on his Miami radio interviews, and never really had a
marshmallow tossed at me. We talked about controversial subjects
and he kept me on my toes.
</P>
<P>
   But this Berkowitz thing. Why did they foul the air with Son of
Sam? Who's CNN and King going to give air time to next? How about
the guy who shot up the Jewish Community Center and killed the
mailman? He's going to find God any minute now.
</P>
<P>
   As King prompted to his last commercial, he left us with this
astonishing utterance:
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be back with our remaining moments. We'll have a prayer
as well _ stay with us _ after this.''
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't get to the TV set fast enough. Click!
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to have David Berkowitz sermonizing to me. I've
already had enough of his implying that God had forgiven him for
what he had done. I don't think the victims have forgiven him,
though. And neither have I and neither have you.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, out of curiosity, I went to CNN's online site
and read the text of Berkowitz's prayer. It was from Second
Chronicles, Chapter Seven, about humbling yourself and turning from
your wicked ways. Nice passage, David, but years too late to help
six women.
</P>
<P>
   As the bizarre program closed, Berkowitz proclaimed, ``God bless
you, Larry. You're in my prayers.'' And Larry answered back: ``God
bless. Thank you, David.''
</P>
<P>
   And I wondered to myself, what in hell are some of our media
coming to?
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
