u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN22-COX     08-19 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Execution as a solution to mental illness
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Death has taken a rare holiday in the Texas criminal justice
system, but don't expect it to stay long at the beach. The Texas
death penalty has a work ethic like no other.
</P>
<P>
   By a one-vote margin the state's Court of Criminal Appeals has
delayed an execution until a lower court decides whether the
murderer, Larry Keith Robinson, is competent to be killed _ that
is, is not so crazy he doesn't understand he is being executed.
</P>
<P>
   That Robinson is mentally ill, and gravely so, is not in serious
doubt. His mother had tried for years to have him committed to a
mental hospital for treatment of his paranoid schizophrenia, only
to see him bounced out within weeks each time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Robinson, in a particularly revolting rampage,
repeatedly stabbed, beheaded and sexually mutilated his roommate,
then killed four neighbors, including an 11-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Texas ranked 48th among states in mental health
services and it has not been exactly setting speed records to catch
up since then.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any one humane principle that ought to restrain
capital punishment, it is that we will kill no one so profoundly
impaired they could not stop themselves. Instead, states typically
rely solely on the very narrow issue of whether a murderer could
tell right from wrong, even if he or she was unable to act on that
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   Politics runs strongly contrary even to that baseline decency.
Remember when Bill Clinton, first seeking the presidency, flew home
to preside theatrically over the execution of a man so impaired he
asked that his last-meal dessert be saved so he could have it after
the execution?
</P>
<P>
   Now it's the turn of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, running for the
presidency, to shrug off even the most dubious executions, as he
has in all but one case; as he did again in this one.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is especially energetic in its death chamber. It has
killed 184 people since 1974, 98 just since January 1995, 21 so far
this year. Executions have become so commonplace that little notice
was taken when four were carried out in short order early this
month.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Texans are simply worse people than other Americans,
though there's no reason to think so. In any event, they are not
better people for all their killing. There is no more respite from
crime in Texas than in most states.
</P>
<P>
   The courts and prisons are our mental health system of last
resort _ in a nation where there often isn't a first resort. We
have failed to establish a broad-based, easily accessible and
determined mental health system. We substitute prison for
treatment, with execution as the ultimate cure.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's crimes were hideous almost beyond imagining,
pathological by their very nature. But figure this: If he is now
found incompetent to be executed, Texas will finally labor like the
very dickens to make him sane enough to understand execution _ and
then it will kill him.
</P>
<P>
   There is more than one pathology at work here.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
