<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 11:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN20-COX     08-19 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An idyllic trip back to a far cooler climate
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPKINTON, N.H. _ It is 45 degrees at 5:30 a.m. on the 10th of
August as I begin my walk-jog down Farrington Corner Road. I am
wearing a sweatshirt and shorts, the sweatshirt purchased in the
old ship-building town of Portsmouth the day before, when I
realized my East Texas-thinned blood was actually cold while
walking around.
</P>
<P>
   A novel feeling: cold in August.
</P>
<P>
   For five days, I've reveled in being somewhere you can see
breath vapors during the dog days while exercising, the Walkman
broadcasting NPR news, fog rising off Boutwell Pond across the road
from my grandmother's house _ the pond where I ice skated as a
child and once nearly died when I fell through the ice into the
frigid water. My cousins hauled me out like I was a sack of
potatoes and got me back to my grandparents' house, where I sat
shivering in front of the fire for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe death wasn't imminent when I fell through the ice, but it
felt that way to me, a chill seeping through me, their disembodied
voices calling frantically from above as I thrashed about, looking
for a handhold.
</P>
<P>
   The pond that tried to kill me is low this summer because of the
drought. This spot of land is now a wildlife refuge maintained by
the Audubon Society, after a generous resident saved it from being
turned into a subdivision. The John Brockway Nature Preserve is
home to beavers, though they've apparently taken a summer vacation,
their felled trees piled up against a man-made stone dam; to black
bears who on occasion raid my uncle's garden or my grandmother's
bird feeder; to deer and even an occasional moose. On this trip,
though I make a point at the end of each dawn hike to walk through
the preserve, the only four-legged wildlife I see are deer.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better walk I've found than Farrington Corner Road
in August when you've escaped an East Texas summer for a few days.
So little has changed since I left 30 years ago to become a
transplanted Texan. The prettiest farm in America is still down the
road from my grandmother's _ Maplewood Farm _ with its stone fence,
verdant pasture, saltbox house and munificent barn, both painted
yellow. It is the end point of my walk each morning, just so I can
drink in its beauty.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother is waiting for me when I return about 6:30,
reading The Concord Monitor and munching on a piece of toast. As
she has every morning for 43 years since my long-dead grandfather
built this house, she sits at the tiny chrome-dinette table in
front of a picture window that looks out over a modest brook
(that's what we call a creek in East Texas) and an explosion of
flowers. A pair of chickadees peck at the bird seed on the feeder
just outside the window. Since I was a child, there has been a pair
of chickadees eating bird seed at that feeder. I figure this must
be the 105th or so generation to feast at the Bourque window.
</P>
<P>
   Hedwig Bourque, my grandmother, is 92, and lives by herself
though son Emil lives next door, and two other children are just
minutes away. It's strange to think of my aunts and uncles as
children, since all my grandmother's offspring are in their 60s or
pushing 70.
</P>
<P>
   Grammy has shrunk a bit since my last visit three years ago, her
spine more curved as the day progresses so that I positively tower
over her by nightfall, me at an exceedingly modest 5'6''. She's a
little harder of hearing, but she still has a sparkle in her eye, a
work ethic that won't quit and a French-Canadian accent that seems
to get thicker with age. She's cute as a bedbug.
</P>
<P>
   She is happy to have her three grandsons from Texas visiting,
though she at times forgets which one is which and refers to the
one temporarily absent as ``the other one.'' As in, where did ``the
other one go?''
</P>
<P>
   When we get in each night from visiting or sightseeing, Grammy
is propped in front of the TV, watching sports and crocheting an
afghan. She has made untold numbers of afghans for grandchildren,
great-grandchildren and even generations beyond that. Grammy loves
to watch golf, basketball, baseball and pro wrestling. She says it
beats the heck out of all that ``gossip'' on the soap operas and
prime-time shows. I can't argue with that.
</P>
<P>
   As the vacation ends, we all hug and head to Boston to catch
planes to our three different homes in Texas. Grammy smiles and
tells us to come back anytime. We promise to be back next summer,
and she says in her broken French accent that she plans on being
around.
</P>
<P>
   I believe she will be there next summer and summers after that,
feeding the chickadees in the morning and watching the Red Sox at
night. She's a tough one.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
