<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN20-COX     08-19 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ?Que paso? It turns out I'm passe
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I've been many things in my life. I've been a
Latin, Latin American, Spanish boy, a Mexican American, Chicano _
and these days people think it's trendy to call me Hispanic or
Latino.
</P>
<P>
   (Q: When does a Mexican become a Hispanic? A: When he marries
your daughter.)
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen years ago, I read in no less a publication than Time
magazine that we were all about to embark on the Decada Hispana _
the decade of the Hispanic. Things worked out for me, more or less,
but that good fortune was not universally shared, unfortunately.
Demographic data reveal some economic progress but not the boom
that was predicted. The progress was hindered, of course, by that
economic bust that got everybody, but was particularly hard on
those at the bottom of the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Now I read in no less a publication than Newsweek about how
bright a future Hispanos have. We are hip, we are trendy, we are
what's happening in entertainment, politics, business. Ay, Dios
mio, the picture painted was so bright, I reached for my Ray-Bans
halfway through the piece. Had to give that up, though, because I
couldn't get my reading glasses back on.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just as well, because Newsweek wasn't talking either
to or about me, or anyone who has passed over the dreaded 30-, 40-
or 50-year threshold in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   That piece focused on Hispanics in their 20s, who, Newsweek
pronounced, are going to reshape America. Newsweek, it seems,
reported that Time's prophecy was to come true _ just a few mananas
late.
</P>
<P>
   I have to confess to having mixed feelings about that.
</P>
<P>
   I'm excited by the prospects projected by Newsweek. I cheer the
move toward political and economic independence. I rejoice that
Latino entertainers like Ricky Martin are achieving the crossover
success that largely eluded artists like Little Joe and Sonny
Ozuna.
</P>
<P>
   Both those Texans (Little Joe is from Temple and Ozuna is from
San Antonio) had brushes with crossover fame. Little Joe and Willie
Nelson teamed up on an English/Spanish version of ``Solamente Una
Vez'' and Ozuna had a crossover encounter in the 1950s with ``Talk
to Me,'' but the attention they got was minimal when compared with
the adulation heaped on Martin and Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Good for them, though. I wish Martin, Lopez and every other
Latino entertainer great success. The same goes for that generation
of young Latinos of all endeavors who are going to enter their own
in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Newsweek article moved me to mutter a
barrio-ism: ``?Y yo, que?'' That translates roughly to ``What about
me?''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from all those other things I've been (and those are just
the printable ones), I'm now over the hill _ or bien veterano _
written off by a national magazine. I guess the time has come and
gone for Chicano Baby Boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Darn, just when things are getting good, we get run off again.
La madre, as they say.
</P>
<P>
   Guess I'll call Gonzalo Barrientos, the senator, Jesus Garza,
the city manager, Amalia Rodriguez-Mendoza, the Travis County
district clerk, Ricardo Romo, president of the University of
Texas-San Antonio, Al Gonzales, the Supreme Court Justice, Tony
Garza, the railroad commissioner, Ernest Garcia, the state district
judge, Olga Garza, the school board member, Gilberto Ocanes, the
businessman, and some others who are of my generation, and invite
them to come over and listen to Little Joe CDs and talk about the
Hispanic Decade that Newsweek implies we are going to miss.
</P>
<P>
   It will be news to them.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at agarcia(at)statesman.com
or at 445-3667.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
