A2682 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-MILNER20-COX     08-19 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MILNER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Authenticity shines through in tale of cowboys and Indians
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Olden Daze, as my grandkids like to call it, when I was a
youngster, playing cowboys and Indians was the thing to do.
Nowadays, best I can tell, the kids are playing like they're space
cadets or aliens or they don't play anything at all and spend their
time on computers and Nintendos, or however you spell it and
whatever that is.
</P>
<P>
   In the above mentioned Olden Daze, picture shows were often
about cowboys and Indians and TV shows were too, when that medium
came along. There were John Wayne, Buck Jones, and later
``Gunsmoke'' and ``Bonanza'' and all them on TV. These daze there
aren't any cowboys shows at the movies or on TV. The ones that are
on TV feature women doctors and such as that and most of the cowboy
shows are silly, with the hero getting beat up all the time. Boy,
you never saw Buck Jones or any of them get beat up, that's for
sure.
</P>
<P>
   And there used to be lots of books about cowboys and Indians,
and the old Street and Smith magazines had those good short stories
and rugged looking cowboys on their covers. Now there are few books
and no magazines starring cowboys and Indians. And the ones that
are, the books, are usually about cowboys in today's time frame
that are depressed about the passing of the Good Old Days.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few exceptions, of course, to prove the rule. Larry
McMurtry's ``Lonesome Dove'' series is about as good as cowboy
books get, although they are kind of bloody and gory and the heroes
are always getting beat up or worse. Then, there's the books about
modern day Indians in New Mexico by Tony Hilleman, but they aren't
really cowboy and Indian stories in the traditional sense.
</P>
<P>
   But there remains in the foreground of American fiction at least
one cowboy author who has the respect of just about everyone who
loves good books _ our own Elmer Kelton, the San Angelo, Texas,
writer who never disappoints.
</P>
<P>
   Kelton has recently come out with another humdinger, ``The
Buckskin Line,'' a Forge Press of New York book that tells a dandy
story while reminding us of a lot of early day Texas Ranger
history.
</P>
<P>
   The story is set on the Texas frontier in the 1840s through the
early 1860s. The main character is a red-haired youth whose family
was massacred by Comanche raiders when he was four years old. He is
rescued by Mike Shannon, a Mexican War veteran riding with a
``ranging company'' of Texans loosely organized to protect settlers
from Indian raids. The Shannon family adopts the lad and he grows
up as a member of that family by the name Rusty Shannon. In 1861,
Rusty's adoptive father is murdered and he follows in his footsteps
as a member of a Ranger troop stationed near the Red River to keep
the Indians from raiding south out of the reservation in what would
one day be Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   It is a riotous time in the new Republic of Texas, that has
recently joined the USA and is now torn apart by the looming War
Between the States. Some Texans want to secede from the Union and
others, a minority, are just as dedicated to the idea of sticking
with the union. Kelton is particularly good at developing
characters that are sympathetic and real.
</P>
<P>
   Elmer Kelton is probably the most honored contemporary Western
author. He has written over 40 books and is a six time winner of
the Spur Award and four Western Heritage Awards from the Cowboy
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I prefer his books to those by the late Louis
L'Amour. They are more authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
