   MOVIE REVIEWS AND NEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BLUEEYES _ Movie review of ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' with Hugh
Grant as English gent suckered into the mob. It's so-so. Grade: C+.
(Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-ILLUMINATA _ Movie review of ``Illuminata'', John
Turturro's weirdo turn of the century tale of a playwright. Grade:
B-. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TINGLE _ Movie review of ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle.'' Kevin
Williamson (Hollywood's Mr. ``Scream'') is writer/director of this
schizoid high school movie about a trio of teens who hold their
devilish history teacher (Helen Mirren) hostage. The film can't
seem to find its groove. Is it a horror flick? A nasty-nice Disney
flick in disguise? One thing it's got for sure is a very grown-up
sex scene between young stars from ``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Seventh
Heaven.'' Grade: C-. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 11.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TRICK _ Movie review: ``Trick.'' A gay story of simple
lust that turns into a simple love story. Grade: B. (Ringel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-TINGLE _ A review of ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' a source
of controversy because of its changed name, changed ending and
banned ad. (Luksic, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MICKEY _ A review of ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' the new Hugh
Grant movie. (Luksic, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-BUENAVISTA _ A review of ``The Buena Vista Social Club.''
(Luksic, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTENING-GIFTS _ Christening gowns destined to become
heirlooms. We take a look a what's out there, what are the fabrics,
what they cost, etc. Tips on preserving these gowns. Also, sidebar
on christening gifts with emphasis on heirloom items like silver
spoons, tiny white Bibles, etc. (Johnson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED WEDNESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-GOLFSTYLES _ Every day, more and more Americans are heading
to the fairways and greens, and although most golfers don't have a
problem choosing the right club, the choice of wardrobe may be a
little more difficult. ``There is a high percentage of people who
just change their shoes to play golf,'' said PGA golf professional
Denny Biller at Dick's Sporting Goods on Springboro Pike. Yet
because most golf clubs have strictly enforced codes indicating
what attire is appropriate for their course, how should you dress?
(Dayton Daily News). 21. PHOTOS.
</P>
