<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0817 -- An american visitor finds a festival and
colorful costumes help forge a new friendship with a Japanese
family. (Gordon, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes
four-column color photo of guest posing with Japanese family and a
2-column photo of man cutting a tuna at a Japanese fish market.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INFO BOX -- A list of groups that help match tourists and
residents for a cultural exchange.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- For those who enjoy wine and would like
to learn more of its history, a new attraction in London, Vinopolis
_ City of Wine, is the place to go. (N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LLAMA _ PISGAH NATIONAL FOREST, N.C. _ B.B. the llama is
famished. Or so it seems. The 13-year-old, 400-pound pack animal
that trails me through a deliriously lush stretch of maintain
wilderness in the Pisgah National Forest is snarfing every
chlorophyll-producing thing in sight _ pine needles, hemlock
leaves, clumps of pungent sassafras, you name it. It's part of the
charm of English Mountain Llama Treks, unusual guided excursions
begun four years ago. Drawing from a stable of 30 llamas, the
owners add an element of animal magnetism to day hikes through
Pisgah and overnight hikes through the nearby Nantahala National
Forest. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EARTHSHINES _ LAKE TOXAWAY, N.C. _ A visit to Earthshine
Mountain Lodge in Western North Carolina, a family retreat at Lake
Toxaway, where guests stay in a 10-room cedar-log lodge on 70-
mountiantop acres surrounded by the Pisgah National Forest. Special
activities are planned for kids, including cookouts and sleepovers
in the barn loft.(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH
COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-EARTHSHINES-AURA _ LAKE TOXAWAY, N.C. _ The
celestial-sounding name is alluring: Earthshine Mountian Lodge.
Definitely has that organically grown, Birkenstock sandal-wearing,
granola-eating ring to it. A place so pastoral and picture-perfect
rustic that L.L. Bean has photographed two catalogs of country
couture here. Yet, first-timers never know exactly what to expect
from this back-to-nature getaway in the Blue Ridge
Mountians.(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BLACKBEAR _ If you're planning a fall trip to the Great
Smoky Mountains, beware of the black bears that populate the
national park.(H.Morris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL _ CHEROKEE _ CHEROKEE, N.C. _ A visit to the Musue of the
cherokee Indian in cherokee, N.C.: Computer-animated forest
creatures. An electric-light campfire that billows smoke. A talking
rock that sounds out the Cherokee language in stereo. This is not
your fathers Native American Museum.( Hamilton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   POPMUSIC-ASSESS _ We take the occasion of the Tori Amos/Alanis
Morissette concert Saturday in Atlanta to look at the status of pop
music. Why do singer/songwriters with something to say (Amos,
Alanis) take a back seat to the vapid likes of Britney Spears.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TV-CNN-CHANGES _ Two years into the reign of Rick Kaplan at
CNN/U.S., he has changed the corporate culture and the network's
on-air look, although not its ratings as much as he would like. Not
everyone at CNN likes the changes, but having survived Tailwind and
bested Lou Dobbs, it appears that Kaplan will continue to mold the
network the way he wants. A look at two years of changes, what's
coming in September, and what staffers are whispering about.
(Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50.
</P>
<P>
   TV-DANDRIDGE _ Review of HBO's ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge,'' starring and produced by Halle Berry. Review will go
into the effort Berry had to go through to get it produced, etc. We
like it a lot. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ-ROLLINS _ A reported yet lyrical profilish, q-and-a piece
on the great jazzman Sonny Rollins, pegged to his Saturday
appearance in metro Atlanta. The tenor sax man is one of the last
great jazz artists of his generation. (Dollar, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available Today after 3 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   Art includes four color photographs.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0819 -- You can understand why KISS once
held a nation of teen-age boys in its black-fingernailed grasp. Now
Gene Simmons, Paul Stanley, Peter Criss and Ace Frehley are
powdering 50-year-old faces. And their most devoted followers are
pushing middle age with no sign of surrendering their allegiance to
the KISS army. (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post) Art includes 4-column
color photo of a KISS fan with KISS merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DETROIT ROCK CITY REVIEW -- A review of the latest movie
featuring the rock group KISS. (Larson, Dayton Daily News.) Art
includes 2-column color photo from ``Detroit Rock City.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON VIDEO -- With summer movie audiences utterly bewitched
and definitely bothered by the sleeper hit, ``The Blair Witch
Project,'' we've decided that broomsticks aren't just for Halloween
anymore. Here are a few rental ideas presenting a wide range of
witchy women (Ringel Gillespie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS -- You get mob jokes, therapy jokes and
parodies of scenes from ``The Godfather,'' but ``Analyze This''
never hits the giddy heights a top farce reaches, but the stars
make it worthwhile. Also, reviews of ``EDtv,'' ``Office Space'' and
``Simply Irresistable'' (Staff, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes 18-pica color photo from ``Analyze This.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS -- Reviews of the new releases from MeShell
Ndegeocello, Kool Keith and Taj Mahal. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0817 -- In ``Name-Dropping: From FDR On,''John
Kenneth Galbraith gives a personal look at some of the century's
most powerful people. (Davis, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HOLOCAUST ANALYSIS -- Author Peter Novick, a historian at
the University of Chicago, has written ``The Holocaust in American
Life,'' trying to explain how the Holocaust has taken center stage
and why. This is not a history of the Holocaust, but rather a
history of the idea of the Holocaust and what Novick calls its
``perverse sacralization.'' (Rothstein, N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CORRUPTION -- In ``The Corruption of American Politics:
What Went Wrong and Why,'' Political reporter Elizabeth Drew
examines a political system in which it's not who you know but how
much you've got. (Carr, Cox Washington Bureau)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PARENTING GUIDE -- If you are sick of reading parenting
books that are peppered with lists and advice, Dr. Kyle Pruett has
a solution.(Rahimi, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- There's no mystery like the kind found
on a summertime trip to Baker Street. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ When Communism collapsed, a lot of techno-thriller
writers began scrambling for new material and new villains. For
some, like Stephen Coonts (``Flight of the Intruder''), they
weren't hard to find. ``The collapse of Communism didn't lower the
level of tension in the world, it raised it,'' says Coonts, who new
novel, ``Cuba,'' is about what happens in that country once Castro
dies. Other items: Georgia writer Terry Kay has signed a two-book
deal with Morrow; Not only is ``A Man in Full'' being published in
paperback in October, but look for new editions of all of Tom
Wolfe's prvious works. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
This week: Elmer Kelton's ``The Buckskin Line.'' (Milner, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE REVIEWS AND NEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BLUEEYES _ Movie review of ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' with Hugh
Grant as English gent suckered into the mob. It's so-so. Grade: C+.
(Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
