<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2567 -- August 19, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1 GORBACHEV'S SAD MISSION : TO SOOTHE HIS AILING WIFE, RAISA
Giulietto Chiesa, Moscow correspondent of the Italian daily
newspaper La Stampa, has become, over the years, one of the closest
friends of Mikhail Gorbachev. Chiesa spent two days with Gorbachev
in Munster, Germany, where Raisa Gorbachev is receiving hospital
treatment for a serious disease. ``I've told her the truth since
the beginning,'' says Gorbachev. ``She closed her eyes and for 40
minutes remained silent.'' In his conversations with Chiesa,
Gorbachev speaks about his private tragedy, the messages he
received from Clinton, Bush, Eltsin, Thatcher and many others.
``When we get out of here,'' said Raisa to Gorbachev, ``I would
like to live in a little house near the sea, where there is a lot
of sunshine, so that we can enjoy these last years we have.'' By
Giulietto Chiesa. From La Stampa. 3,000 words. (English translation
available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 2. A
PICNIC IN QUICKSAND : DARK VISIONS OF EUROPE'S FUTURE What will the
Europe of 2003 or 2006 or 2010 look like? Futurologists named by
the European Commission to peer into that crystal ball have come up
with some surprising predictions, many of them dark and gloomy. One
scenario foresees a war between Western Europe and its neighbours
over scarce water resources that leaves 25,000 people dead. Yet
another starts in chaos, as the poor riot against the rich, but
leads to drastic reforms that produce a sort of Social-Democratic
dream world. The visionary futurologists admit that their
predictions are provocative. Whither Europe? By Michael
Schmidt-Klingenberg. From Der Spiegel. 700 words. (English
translation available.)
_____________________________________________________________ 3.
U.S. POLICY TOWARD IRAQ IS INEFFECTIVE AND CONTRADICTORY Last week,
eight senior U.S. senators and representatives from both parties
delivered a letter to President Clinton that decried the
``continued drift in U.S. policy toward Iraq.'' The letter
expressed concern that despite rhetoric from the administration
about the imminent danger posed by Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction, no progress has been made toward getting meaningful
inspections back on track or, in their absence, quantifying and
dealing with the Iraqi threat. By Scott Ritter. New York Times
Op-Ed. 800 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 4.
OIL FIGURES IN THIS BATTLE IN RUSSIA'S WILD WEST Robert D. Kaplan,
a correspondent for The Atlantic Monthly and the author of ``The
Ends of the Earth,'' argues that Russia's new assault on Chechen
and Dagestani rebels in the republic of Dagestan warrants more of
the West's attention, given the Caspian Sea oil boom and the
growing influence of Iran in the region. New York Times Op-Ed.
1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________ 5. From
NATURE NEWS SERVICE (N/A France and Spain)
</P>
<P>
   A. It's A Gas For Battery Power Low-pollution vehicles and power
plants that run on natural gas will get a boost from work reported
in Nature magazine. Researchers say that they have devised an
efficient methane-powered electric battery. By Phillip Ball. 600
words.
</P>
<P>
   B. When The Mediterranean Was A Desert If the connection to the
Atlantic Ocean through the Strait of Gibraltar were to become
blocked, the entire Mediterranean Sea would eventually evaporate.
However unlikely that might sound, it did indeed happen some five
and a half million years ago. New findings should lead to a better
understanding of the global events that precipitated this bizarre
chapter in the history of the Earth. By Phillip Ball. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   C. How Sulphur From Ships Affects Climate The exhaust gases
escaping from the funnel of ships could be having a significant
effect on the global climate. The full impact of this finding has
been felt only recently with the appearance of comprehensive
inventories of the emissions of sulphur from shipping worldwide. By
Henry Gee. 400 words.
</P>
<P>
   D. Making Wounds Heal Faster Biologists investigating how skin
wounds heal have discovered that nature is not as efficient as it
might be. One of the proteins normally produced as a wound heals
seems, in fact, to be slowing down the healing process. By Eleanor
Lawrence. 400 words.
_____________________________________________________________ 6. IT
IS THE COMMON SENSE GAP THAT MATTERS Much concern is voiced at the
growing discriminatory consequences of the technology gap, the
handicap of all those who aren't wired and are computer illiterate
in the increasingly globalized marketplace. There is also reason to
be concerned at the straightforward knowledge gap, not only what
people don't know, but what they do not want to know. More than
access to technology, the gap that matters now is how people choose
to think about human aspirations. By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
