<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-VENTURE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 6 Venture Capitalists Gut Firms, Form Own
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Firing a generational shot across the bow, six young Silicon Valley
venture capitalists are splitting from their high-profile,
diversified firms to launch an Internet-only venture firm.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Yang of Institutional Venture Partners and John Walecka of
Brentwood Venture Capital, two golfing buddies who are known in
Silicon Valley as hotshot Web investors, have recruited four
colleagues to create a new, Internet-only venture firm.
</P>
<P>
   The departure of the executives, who are all between the ages of
39 and 45, is notable because it sounds a death knell for Brentwood
and IVP, two venerable old Menlo Park firms.
</P>
<P>
   While it is not uncommon for young VCs to leave established
firms and start their own, this is the first time the leading
lights of two firms have joined forces and effectively killed their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   IVP and Brentwood will continue to manage their existing funds _
each has three _ but will not launch any new projects. The
departing partners will continue their oversight of the funds, the
last of which matures in 2008. At that point, IVP and Brentwood
will cease to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Brentwood was founded in 1972, and IVP has been around since
1980. Since most old-line VC funds are controlled by their founding
partners, ``that has kept some of the guys who joined later from
making their own mark,'' said Reyes. ``They can do some deals, but
at end of the day ... (the founding partners' name) is still on the
front door.''
</P>
<P>
   IVP is currently the 20th-largest venture fund in the United
States, with $845 million under management, and Brentwood is 26th,
with $715 million, according to Venture Economics, a New Jersey
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Both are ranked in the top 25 percent of VC firms as measured by
net return on investment, said Jesse Reyes, Venture Economics'
director.
</P>
<P>
   Brentwood's investments include Apple Computer, WebTV and
Stamps.com, while IVP's portfolio has included Seagate, Excite and
Ask Jeeves.
</P>
<P>
   The new partnership, which will operate under the nickname
Project T-Rex until its formal launch in the fall, reflects two
fundamental splits in the venture capital sector, said people
familiar with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Young, entrepreneurial VC executives are growing tired of
working in the shadow of older partners. At the same time, many Web
VCs feel they are being held back by diversified funds that also
invest in &UR;  &LR; less-robust sectors such as biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating when the area you're in is making all the
returns and is where all the excitement is happening,'' said a
local venture capitalist who is friends with several members of the
Project T-Rex group. ``You think, `Why am I paying all this
overhead''' to support the less-profitable businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, some of Brentwood and IVP's biotechnology partners
will announce a combination similar to the one disclosed today &LR; 
 &LR; yesterday by the Internet group. Its code name is Project
Pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Brentwood and IVP's information-technology
specialists is less clear, but they may also combine to form a
spin-off, said a person involved in Project T-Rex.
</P>
<P>
   Project T-Rex was hatched on the Sharon Heights country club in
Menlo Park. ``John and I were on the golf course saying, `Wouldn't
it be terrific if we could put these organizations together and
have a dream team?''' said Yang in an interview yesterday. Each of
the six executives, which include Jeff Brody and Tom Dyal from
Brentwood and Tim Haley and Brad Jones from IVP, specializes in a
different aspect of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling was that by putting the best of the firms together
and forming a focused Net tech fund and a focused life sciences
/health care fund, each could be one of the dominant few firms in
their respective industries,'' Yang said.
</P>
<P>
   The aim is to attract the top entrepreneurs with the hottest Web
startup ideas, said Walecka. ``They'll think, `These are powerful
people who can add the most value,' and that's the name of the game
in our business.`'
</P>
<P>
   The new group hopes to raise $500 million for its first fund.
</P>
<P>
   People familiar with the new venture believe Yang and his
partners are capable of reaching their lofty goals. But while
focusing narrowly on the Web may seem to make sense now _ many
other funds are doing the same thing _ it is a riskier strategy in
the long run than remaining diversified.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens when the Net gets to be mainstream, like
microprocessors and PCs (two previously hot sectors for venture
capital) are today?'' said the venture capitalist familiar with
Project T-Rex. ``Then they will have to expand their field of
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   IVP founding partner Reid Dennis and Brentwood co-founder Kip
Hagopian will have ``advisory partner'' status with the new
company. Sam Colella, another longtime IVP partner, will be a
special partner and will help manage the biotech group.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
