<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Psst! Read the latest? If not, you haven't read
Hot  Stuff, the San Francisco Chronicle's weekly roundup of great
new 
 home-and-garden items and places to visit.    HOT STUFF: Home Accessories of the Future  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Calling itself the supermarket of the new
millennium,  Spaceprojekt  in San Francisco sells a selection of,
well, spacey lifestyle accessories.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The eye-catching pieces range from hand-sewn meditation cushions
(from $85) to jazzy aluminum drink trays (from $120). Look for
orange blossom oil shampoo, the store's own labels of wine and
water and much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have really eclectic, artsy items,'' says publicist Nikki
Chouinard. ``It's kind of for someone who thinks out of the box and
wants rare finds or one-of-a-kind things.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrons are encouraged to touch, try on and experiment with the
home furnishings, makeup and hair products, says owner Brent Haas.
</P>
<P>
   Among the choices for the home: adjustable floor mirrors with
stainless bases; colored Plexiglas fluorescent lamps; and
sculptural compact discs holders. Prices range from $32 for simple
wooden trash cans to $500 for creative lighting fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Spaceprojekt is open from 11 a.m. to 7 p.m. Tuesday through &LR; 
 &LR; Saturday. 1141 Polk St. (near Sutter Street), San Francisco. &LR;   &LR; For
more information, call (415) 674-1997 or visit &LR; 
www.space-usa.com &LR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ Mary Corcoran, San Francisco Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; KALEIDOSCOPE CRAZE: Store Takes a Closer Look &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; BURLINGAME, Calif. _  &LR; The owner of  &UR; Kaleido &LR; , a new store in
Burlingame, is a woman obsessed. ``It's not a business, it's an
addiction,'' says Mary Wills. ``I sell kaleidoscopes to feed my
habit. I have 154 scopes just in my bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   The store carries the work of 75 kaleidoscope makers. The
pictured ``It's a Wrap'' kaleidoscopes ($235) are wrapped in
colorful fabric, and each has a glass cell on the end filled with
charms suspended in fluid. The scope's inner mirrors reflect the
charms in a dynamic five-pointed star pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Kids will enjoy the ``It's a Wrap'' series, although most of
them really appeal to adults, Wills says. One called ``Chinese
Takeout'' reflects prismed images of miniature chopsticks, rice and
fortune cookies, while ``Concerto'' has tiny images of musical
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the new thing to collect. Scopes are left-brain and
right-brain objects; they appeal to people who like both finely
tuned machines and art,'' says Wills.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not you're ready to start a collection, the store is
a bit like an old-fashioned laboratory, with elegant wood cabinets
and beautiful, well-crafted instruments to look through and marvel
at.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Kaleido is open from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily. 1412 &LR; 
 &LR; Burlingame Ave. (near El Camino), Burlingame; (650) 558-0864. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Tara Duggan, San Francisco Chronicle &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
