<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMBINE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: This story includes an optional tip bar at the end.   Two Into One: Flat combines furnishings from an Arts and Crafts 
 house and a city loft  
   
 By Holly Ocasio Rizzo  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Jo Wunderlich bends toward a hallway shelf holding
seven photographs, her eyes softening as she peers into the gilded
frames.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``These are all pictures from Ireland,'' she says, scanning
green hills hugging a church, fenced pastures snuggling the feet of
a lighthouse. ``We lived in Ireland a couple of months. They're all
from Donegal. My family's from Donegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip, part of a yearlong business assignment, brought
Wunderlich to her ancestral home but began a journey she and her
husband, Dennis Stradford, have just completed. In July, they moved
into a 2,200-square-foot flat in the Duboce Triangle area of San
Francisco, combining the familiar, comforting objects of the past
with new furnishings for a new urban lifestyle. This picking and
mixing confront everyone from newlyweds furnishing a first
apartment to retirees downsizing for simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in the flat was perfect, but our living
requirements were different from the previous owner's,'' says
Wunderlich, who runs a food bank in Alameda.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done with it is a great combination of our
history,'' says Stradford, chief executive officer of Supplybase, a
San Francisco software startup.
</P>
<P>
   Wunderlich and Stradford lived in London in 1997, and the
excitement of city life bit hard. When they came home, the empty
nesters' 1913 Arts and Crafts house in Alameda seemed stodgy, and
the 700-square-foot Asian-inspired South of Market loft they bought
for fun weekends in San Francisco felt cold and cramped. The
furniture and accents were homey, but the places weren't. They
didn't seem to fit the couple's spirit anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living abroad changed everything,'' Wunderlich says.
</P>
<P>
   She and Stradford, missing city life, decided to roll their
house and their loft into one. They fell in love with the hilltop
flat, which has a view of the Bay and plenty of sunshine, thanks to
the fog-splitting hill in Buena Vista Park.
</P>
<P>
   They were ready to leap to a new home. ``In Alameda, we were
entrenched,'' Wunderlich says. ``We bought that house six months
after we were married, and we had lived there 24 years. The people
we knew there we'd known since our daughter, Karen, was a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   To help make a successful transition, the couple called on the
decorators who had helped them plan their loft.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted us to help them define their aesthetic,'' says
Marion Philpotts, president of the San Francisco design company
Your Space Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Philpotts and Jonathan Staub, the company's vice president,
first interviewed Wunderlich and Stradford, asking how they
envisioned their new lifestyle, what their budget was and which
services they needed _ from color consulting to full-service
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Then the designers delved into personality. The starting point
of design, Staub says, is knowing the homeowners' heads and hearts,
helping them understand how their living space reflects and
enhances their lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw they wanted some newness in their life,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to be more stylish, a little more elegant,''
Philpotts adds.
</P>
<P>
   The next step: developing a furniture plan. Wunderlich and
Stradford decided which pieces they no longer needed _ called
``editing'' by interior designers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the choices were dictated by space, like leaving the
dining set,'' Wunderlich says. ``It was a big Arts and Crafts-style
table that just went with perfectly with our old house, and we sold
it to the new owner. Some other pieces had outlived their life
expectancy.'' Bye-bye to an outworn couch; hello to a new dining
set for the flat's spacious dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Philpotts helped choose where the pieces would go in the
new scheme. She designated such changes as moving artwork by Plein
Air-style painter Jack Cassinetto to the new master bedroom from
the old living room. ``It was fun to watch her go through the house
and say, `This will work here' and `That will work there',''
Wunderlich says.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture required more precise decisions. ``For example, the
piano,'' Philpotts says. ``We made a big paper template of it in
Alameda and took it to the new flat to see how it would fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steinway grand piano ``is the heart of Dennis,'' she says.
He poured out classical compositions from the piano's perch in a
bay window at the Alameda house. Now it sits bathed in light from
the flat's broad front window, his favorite place in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Philpotts gave Wunderlich and Stradford homework; she advised
them what type of piece they needed and where they might find it,
but it was up to them to pick it out. ``She sends me out on
errands,'' Wunderlich says.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the designers encouraged nontraditional uses for
home accents.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the couple wanted something to do the work of a
table next to a red mohair chair that's one of Stradford's
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `Get something Asian' to go next to the chair. So I
went in this store in Chinatown, past all the tourist things, to
the back and found this.'' The flat-top set of three stacking
baskets fills the gap perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Wunderlich and Stradford found a low, wide chest to
use as a coffee table in the music room and a smaller chest for a
coffee table in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Philpotts and Staub also advised the couple to add fresh touches
_ a casual couch for the living room, one wall in the master
bedroom painted dramatic deep gold.
</P>
<P>
   The designers helped Wunderlich and Stradford streamline their
home. For example, they advised the couple to use low-care sisal
rugs in the high-traffic music room and living room.
</P>
<P>
   Yet pieces of the past surround Wunderlich and Stradford: a
library table and two bedside tansu from the Alameda house, a bar
from the loft. A painted Asian screen from the loft, which used to
add interest to a long, high wall, now enlivens the space behind
the mohair chair. In the guest room _ Wunderlich's office _ a
Japanese gate hangs over the bed; it used to hang over the couple's
bed in Alameda.
</P>
<P>
   Wunderlich's collection of Limoges boxes, some from a favorite
Paris shop and others received as gifts, used to sit on a tiered
table in the living room. The table didn't make the move; now the
boxes stay on a window shelf in the butler's pantry, away from the
danger of errant knees and elbows.
</P>
<P>
   On the balcony, a tabletop fountain reminds Wunderlich the new
yard needs renovation; she'd like to build a pond like one she had
in Alameda.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Wunderlich and Stradford contemplate the garden-to-be _
and much of their new city _ from the balcony, where two chairs
from the house face the bay. ``This really feels good,'' Wunderlich
says. ``It really feels like home.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; TRICKS OF THE TRADE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Here are tips for combining two homes into one from San Francisco
interior designers Jonathan Staub and Marion Philpotts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edit'' before you move. Get rid of objects that are outdated,
worn out and no longer relevant to your life. Start with a clean
plate, and keep it simple.
</P>
<P>
   Think outside your normal box. Mix up your furniture from its
previous settings. Consider new combinations; move your old dining
room table into the entry hall or arrange your artwork in different
combinations or locations.
</P>
<P>
   Play with floor plans. Use tape or paper cutouts to get the feel
for the space and how your furniture will fit into it. Try
arranging your pieces at an angle; pull them off the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Reupholster or slipcover key pieces to give them a new look.
</P>
<P>
   Use paint to give old furniture a new backdrop, or use color as
an accent on a wall to offset an area without undertaking an entire
paint job. Take into consideration the light quality in your new
space. Use saturated colors to add drama.
</P>
<P>
   Consider purchasing new furniture to show off your new home or
style.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, life is not fixed and your environment is no
exception. Reinvent yourself and have fun with the process.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
