shelf holding seven photographs, her eyes softening as she peers
into the gilded frames. ``These are all pictures from Ireland,''
she says, scanning green hills hugging a church, fenced pastures
snuggling the feet of a lighthouse. ``We lived in Ireland a couple
of months. They're all from Donegal. My family's from Donegal.''
 &HT;    The trip, part of a yearlong business assignment, brought
Wunderlich to her ancestral home but began a journey she and her
husband, Dennis Stradford, have just completed. In July, the empty
nesters moved into a 2,200-square-foot flat in the Duboce Triangle
area of San Francisco, combining the familiar, comforting objects
of the past with new furnishings for a new urban lifestyle. This
picking and mixing confront everyone from newlyweds furnishing a
first apartment to retirees downsizing for simplicity.
 &HT;    This story describes how the couple chose what to take and how
they worked with interior designers to plan a living space
reflecting their new outlook.
 &HT;    With tip sidebar of designers' tips on combining households.
