r f BC-ANGINA-ANGINA_SFCHRON     08-19 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGINA-ANGINA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 New Angina Drug Getting High Marks
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
CV Therapeutics, the Palo Alto biotech company, yesterday announced
encouraging results for an experimental drug that apparently makes
weak hearts pump more efficiently for people with angina.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock jumped $1.25 to close at $8.88 yesterday,
even before the firm released the results of a Phase III, or
late-stage, study of a new drug called Ranolazine.
</P>
<P>
   The drug is designed to ease the symptoms of angina, a pounding
chest pain that occurs when cholesterol clogs the arteries that
supply blood to the heart muscle. Deprived of blood, the heart
muscle, in effect, suffocates for lack of oxygen, causing pains
that can numb the chest _ or be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   The 7.2 million Americans who suffer from angina now spend about
$6 to $9 a day on medications to control the pain, according to Dr.
Louis Lange, chairman of CV Therapeutics.
</P>
<P>
   Lange explained how Ranolazine would differ from current angina
drugs, like nitroglycerin, beta blockers or calcium blockers.
</P>
<P>
   The difference all begins with the pumping action of the heart.
Angina occurs when a heart, weakened by oxygen deprivation, is
asked to pump harder during stressful situations like climbing
stairs or lifting groceries. Current drugs relieve angina pain by
cutting down the pumping action of the heart, Lange said.
</P>
<P>
   But that action can have a variety of negative side effects, he
said. People who use nitroglycerin can get low blood pressure or
headaches. Calcium blockers or beta blockers may take away the
angina chest pain but leave a person so weak or lethargic that they
can't perform ordinary tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Lange said Ranolazine tries to curb angina pain in a novel way _
by allowing weak heart muscles to make better use of their limited
oxygen supply.
</P>
<P>
   The heart's muscles are fueled by a mix of fat, sugar and
oxygen. To prevent angina pain, Ranolazine adjusts the ratio of
these three fuels so they produce more pumping energy for each unit
of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Parker, a Canadian cardiologist who participated in the
study results that were released yesterday, said the 175 patients
studied showed ``dramatic'' improvements in their ability to
exercise before the exertion caused angina. Patients also had far
fewer side effects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a unique drug,'' he said. ``It seems to have more
potency and fewer drawbacks than current remedies.''
</P>
<P>
   Although yesterday's news was encouraging, CV has at least
another year's worth of tests to perform before it can even ask the
Food and Drug Administration for permission to sell Ranolazine,
Lange said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
