<HEADER>
A2742 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES     08-19 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Shell Using MoJo Wire To Woo Public 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Odd couple of the year: MoJo Wire, the online companion to
muckraking magazine Mother Jones, and megalithic corporation Royal
Dutch/Shell, the epitome of Big Oil.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Mother Jones and the MoJo Wire
(www.motherjones.com) generally portray Shell as evil. The
accusations include destroying the environment and colluding with
Nigerian dictators in terrible human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet now, Shell is buying ads on the MoJo Wire in an effort to
improve its relations with the public.
</P>
<P>
   The basic message: Never mind what you've read in mags like
Mother Jones, Shell really cares about the planet.
</P>
<P>
   One of the kinder, gentler Shell ads features water rising up
and over polar icebergs, asking ``Ignore? Ignore again?'' before
concluding, ``Too late.'' The kicker: ``Can we afford to ignore
Global Warming? Click here to see how we're cleaning up our act.''
</P>
<P>
   Another features newspaper headlines about torture and people
held under suspicion, ``No-one cq  &LR; can ignore Human Rights. Read
our commitment here.''
</P>
<P>
   Shell ``had become public enemy No.1 to a lot of people,'' said
Tom Kearney of Fishburn Hedges in London, Shell's communications
consultants. ``Shell had some catching up to do in the way it
behaved in stakeholder society.''
</P>
<P>
   The company not only posted a Web page about its environmental
principles but actively promoted it with ads on Web sites for such
media companies as CNN, the Financial Times, the New Zealand Herald
_ and Mother Jones' online outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Jones? Mother Jones doesn't run tobacco ads. Mother Jones
implicated Shell in the murder of Nigerian activist Ken Saro-Wiwa.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Jones was not sure if it could take Shell's advertising
offer seriously _ or if it could accept. Publisher Jay Harris said
he was concerned the ads could ``make it seem like Mother Jones was
selling out to this oil company.''
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, Harris figured, ``We want to make Mother Jones
a home for debate of important current issues. ... We believe in
free expression and we take ads from companies that are
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not making any judgment by taking the ad,'' Harris said.
``The only judgment we make is, their commercial presence is not
going to stop us from printing anything we deem appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   He did praise Shell for its aggressive steps in trying to reach
its critics, rather than merely preaching to the choir.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of Kearney, the Shell representative, the old
battles with the media had left Shell feeling ``so bloodied and
battered, you just want to pull away and stop people from hitting
you. We're trying to rebuild that dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NO FANGS: A hot rumor swept the city's media circles earlier this
week: Ted Fang, publisher of the San Francisco Independent, was
about to buy the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not true,'' Fang said Monday night. ``I'm not
interested in making any offer. ... I'm not looking into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation was stirred in this column last week, when analyst
David Cole identified Fang as the most likely buyer. After all, the
Independent already publishes neighborhood editions throughout San
Francisco, has its own printing and delivery apparatus, and could
easily buy the bargain-basement Examiner from Hearst Corp. (Hearst
is selling its flagship paper to ease antitrust objections to its
purchase of The Chronicle.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed my 15 minutes of fame,'' Fang said. ``It seems to be
time to put an end to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FATE OF THE GATE: When Hearst announced its deal to buy The
Chronicle, included in the $660 million price was SF Gate, the
newspaper's Web site. The site posts content from The Chronicle,
Examiner, KRON-TV and BayTV.
</P>
<P>
   What the transition will mean to the 40 people working at SF
Gate remains uncertain. SF Gate General Manager John Coate said
Hearst officials can't make plans for the site until the deal
closes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publisher and the head of the newspaper division came to
see us,'' Coate said. ``They welcomed us, and told us they have a
tradition of autonomy in their properties, and are very excited
about the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a deep commitment to new media, a lot of resources
in their system _ and they can't discuss strategy at all.''
</P>
<P>
   SF Gate is likely to keep its offices in the KRON building on
Van Ness Avenue for up to a year _ even after KRON, which is for
sale, has a new owner _ and it's likely to keep KRON content on the
site for the time being, depending on the new buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the buyer of KRON is known, there's no way to know what
kind of strategy will be mutually acceptable,'' Coate said. ``We're
just trying to do the best we can with what we've got.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NO NO NOLAN: And now, the piece we've all been waiting for is on
newsstands today: Chris Nolan's essay in Fortune, describing the
easy money she made in her infamous ``friends and family'' stock
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan, who until last month was a star tech columnist at the San
Jose Mercury News, has in the past week written about the Woodside
town council race, the opening of a youth center in San Carlos, and
a flap over multiscreen theaters proposed in San Mateo and Redwood
City.
</P>
<P>
   Her banishment to the paper's Redwood City bureau came about
because she made $9,500 by trading in Autoweb.com's stock at its
initial public offering, thanks to her friendship with Autoweb CEO
Dean DeBiase. And that deal only reached the public because Nolan
agreed to write about it in Fortune, and then talked about the
Fortune article before its publication to a Wall Street Journal
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune, in its September 13 issue, notes that Nolan pitched the
story to the mag after she already made her money. ``While Fortune
has strict guidelines governing its employees' stock trading, we
commissioned Nolan's story because it offers a fascinating glimpse
into Silicon Valley's money culture,'' says an editor's note that
accompanies the story.
</P>
<P>
   In the story, Nolan says she felt qualms about her
participation, but ``these weren't qualms about the journalistic
ethics,'' because she was comfortable that DeBiase was a longtime
personal friend and that she'd informed her editors of the
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Nolan wrote, ``the whole process seemed too easy. ...
For this one deal, you see, I was considered special.''
</P>
<P>
   The people on DeBiase's list, she wrote, were ``a small but
influential group. And if they make money, they may be tempted to
return the favor.''
</P>
<P>
   We may never know if Nolan had adequate permission from editors
to participate in the Autoweb stock deal (that aspect of the case
is now the subject of a union grievance).
</P>
<P>
   But I'm inclined to think that if Nolan would give her own story
one more reading _ especially the part about favors given and
expected _ she may understand why her bosses made an example of
her.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GOODBYE GROKKER: The Industry Standard bids a fond farewell to Mark
Glaser of San Francisco, who helped launch its popular Media Grok
e-mail newsletter that critiques newspaper and online coverage of
the big high-tech stories.
</P>
<P>
   Glaser is off to Topica, a Multimedia Gulch company that plans
to turn e-mail newsletters into a big business. Topica offers a
free service making it easy to find, join or start an e-mail list.
At its Web site, one can sign up for any of hundreds of lists in
dozens of categories including jokes, women entrepreneurs, art
museums and safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   The Grok still lives; Glaser was one of four contributors and
the others remain.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the Standard, which is looking mighty fat and healthy,
went on a hiring binge. Most notably, the mag hired pundit James
Fallows _ a famed press critic and former top dog at U.S. News and
World Report _ to file a column every other week. But it also
snagged journos from Brill's Content, the Wall Street Journal, the
San Jose Mercury News, the New York Daily News, Inc. magazine and
PC World. And it's establishing a London bureau with Polly
Sprenger, late of Wired News.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Standard President John Battelle: Want to buy an
afternoon newspaper?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
