r f BC-SCHOOL-SCHOOL_SFCHRON     08-19 1521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SCHOOL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Tips on Choosing a Back-to-School Computer
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Henry Norr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
It's back-to-school season, and for many families that means not
only new shoes and lunch boxes, but also a new computer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're buying your first home machine, replacing an
aging clunker or adding a second system upstairs, you'll find that
this year's computer crop delivers more bang for fewer bucks than
ever before.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the most important thing parents shopping for
technology this fall need to know is that any new PC or Mac will
meet the computing needs of most students, whether they're in
kindergarten or in college. Even the cheapest models provide more
than enough processing power, storage space and communications
capability for the tasks typical of student computing: word
processing, Web research, e-mail, and also basic graphics,
multimedia and educational software.
</P>
<P>
   But you'll still have choices to make. Over and above the
forests of technical mumbo jumbo and marketing hype, selecting the
setup that's best for your family means answering some basic
questions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; High-end or low-end?  &LR; If bargain-basement models can do
everything your budding scholar is likely to require, is there any
point in considering higher-end configurations?
</P>
<P>
   Only if you expect Junior to take on some extra-demanding
applications _ things like speech recognition, 3-D modeling, MP3
encoding or digital-video editing.
</P>
<P>
   If your kids will be spending a lot of time with the latest 3-D
action games and if you're willing to support or even join them in
this habit, you'll all be happier with hardware that offers faster
graphics and more processing power than a lowball system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Processor and memory.  &LR; Today's PCs use a much wider range of
microprocessors than in past years: Intel Pentium II and III and
Celeron; K6 and now Athlon from Advanced Micro Devices; and the
Cyrix MII. Clock smWeds (megahertz) range from 300 MHz to twice as
many.
</P>
<P>
   For the home user, any of them should be fine. The newest chips,
the Pentium III and Athlon, have some multimedia-oriented
enhancements the others lack, but so far, there's little software
that takes advantage of them.
</P>
<P>
   More megahertz are always nice, but don't waste a lot of money
on them.[U )Wk W;H:WRnualYN]SIti77sB]oted above about advanced
applications, ylENGl probably find that any chip running at 300 to
400 MHz is more than fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Main memory, or DRAM, is the one area where today's cheapest
systems fall a little short. Most now come with 32 megabytes of
memory.
</P>
<P>
   That's plenty to run most applications by themselves, but not
enough to keep more than a couple of them in memory at once. If you
have, say, Microsoft Word, Outlook, America Online and a CD-ROM
encyclopedia open simultaneously, the system will have to shuffle
data between memory and hard disk every time you jump from one
program to another, resulting in some annoying delays.
</P>
<P>
   With 64 megabytes of RAM, which is standard in Compaq's Presario
5300 series _ even the $499 Presario 5304 _ and some other low-cost
systems, operations are noticeably more fluid. If you end up
choosing a model with only 32 megabytes, consider asking the dealer
to add another 32 megabytes (around $75 extra, including
installation).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Windows or Mac?  &LR; Now that Apple's future seems assured, the
choice basically is a matter of taste.
</P>
<P>
   Cheap PCs are still cheaper than any new Mac _ though the gap
isn't as large as it seems when you remember that the iMac has a
high-quality monitor built in. And many software programs,
particularly specialized applications but also some popular games
and new Web plug-ins, still aren't available on the Mac, or they
arrive long after and with fewer features than the Windows version.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there is a lot of good software _ more than
most students need _ available for the Mac, especially in the
graphics category. The Apple user interface is still easier to
learn, more consistent and more aesthetically pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to plug in a new peripheral, try out a new program
or update your system software, you'll probably encounter fewer of
the time-wasting, sanity-jeopardizing hassles that still are too
common with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of Apple's renewed strength in the
consumer-computing category: FamilyPC, a monthly magazine that's
generally Windows-oriented, recently declared that the iMac ``may
not be the perfect back-to-school system, but (it) is pretty darned
close.'' According to Robin Raskin, the magazine's editor in chief,
the iMac is now one of the publication's three top picks, along
with the Compaq Presario 5300 and Gateway's much more expensive
Profile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Desktop or notebook?  &LR; Most major manufacturers now offer
lower-cost models pitched as consumer products. ``Lower-cost,''
however, means relative to business notebooks, not consumer
desktops. Even with low-cost chips such as the Intel Celeron or AMD
K6, they generally cost at least $1,600 for a base configuration _
two or three times as much as a desktop PC and monitor.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can afford the premium, notebooks have many
advantages for students, especially in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``For college, you can't go wrong with a notebook,'' says Bob
O'Donnell, author of ``Personal Computer Secrets'' and host of the
``O'Donnell on Computers'' radio show (Saturdays 1 to 4 p.m. on
KSFO-AM). ``It becomes your digital notepad _ you can take it to
class or the library to take notes.''
</P>
<P>
   In a crowded dorm room or student apartment, the space a
notebook saves is another important consideration.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, increasing numbers of college students are buying into
those arguments. According to April Roy, general manager of the
Scholar's Workstation, the official campus computer store of the
University of California at Berkeley, about 60 percent of the
systems the store sells to students are notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   If you or your college-bound offspring opt for a laptop,
remember that risks of theft and accidental damage are much greater
than for desktop systems. Use a security cable to keep the machine
attached to a desk or other relatively immovable object. And carry
it in a plain carrying case or backpack rather than one emblazoned
with the manufacturer's logo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Peripherals. &LR;  Beware of ultracheap monitors, especially those
bundled ``free'' with low-cost PCs. A monitor that's fuzzy or
distorted around the edges is no bargain, especially if young eyes
are going to spend many hours in front of it.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, there's no easy way to tell a good monitor from a
bad one by the specs. Look for a ``dot pitch'' of .28 millimeters
or less, but that, in itself, is no guarantee of image quality.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is to spend some time at the computer store
considering the alternatives, or to look closely at recently
acquired monitors at your workplace or friends' homes. Don't just
look at the pretty pictures you're likely to find on screen on the
showroom floor _ open up a word processing program or spreadsheet
and see how normal text and numbers look.
</P>
<P>
   With printers, the risks aren't so great _ nowadays even the
lowest-cost models, retailing for as little as $49 or bundled with
systems, generally produce decent text. But if you expect your
child to be printing lots of pages and especially graphics, you'll
be much better off with a printer in the $150 to $300 range. (We'll
have more advice about printers in an upcoming article.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_ &UR; Software. &LR;  In most cases, it's not worth choosing a PC just for
its bundled software, because you can add software later. But if
you're debating between two closely matched packages, a good bundle
deal might make the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Look for antivirus software, such as Norton AntiVirus or Network
Associates' VirusScan.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also want a good suite of basic productivity programs,
including a word processor, spreadsheet program and database, or at
least a strong word processor. Many colleges sell such programs to
students at very low cost, but you'll need to provide for younger
students.
</P>
<P>
   Check with the school to see if there's a standard format that
teachers require for assignments handed in electronically.
</P>
<P>
   If the choice is yours, all of the major commercial programs _
Microsoft Office and Word, Corel Office and WordPerfect, or the
less-powerful but still versatile Microsoft Works _ have more
features than your child is likely to need. None is as easy to
master as kids deserve, but they'll all do. (IMacs come with the
former ClarisWorks, now AppleWorks, which offers a nice balance of
features and ease of use.)
</P>
<P>
   As for educational and reference programs, the big problem with
bundled software is that it may not match your children's grade
level and interests. This year, though, Compaq and Radio Shack have
come up with an innovative approach to the issue: With selected
Compaq PCs sold at the electronics chain, you can try out as many
as 38 separate educational programs and take home the 12 you like
best.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
