r f BC-PUBLISH-PUBLISH_SFCHR     08-19 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLISH-PUBLISH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Publish Magazine Merging With Rival
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Dan Fost  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Publish magazine, a San Francisco technology monthly, is merging
with its rival Desktop Publishers Journal and relocating its
editorial operations to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The magazines, which report on the software that enables
millions of ordinary people to become publishers themselves, have
struggled in recent years as the graphics software market shrinks,
leaving them with fewer ad revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Harrigan, the president of Desktop Publishing Institute,
based in Topsfield, Mass., said his organization will oversee
publication of the newly merged venture.
</P>
<P>
   Uniting the two magazines under Publish's name could enable them
to cash in on a new opportunity: selling to corporations who are
now de facto publishers by virtue of their Web sites, Harrigan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a marriage of necessity,'' Harrigan said. As his
Desktop Publishers Journal tried to compete with Publish, which was
owned by magazine powerhouse International Data Group, ``we might
have followed them over a cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed. IDG, based in Framingham,
Mass., retains a majority interest in Publish; Desktop Publishing
Institute has a minority interest.
</P>
<P>
   Both magazines had mostly free circulations. At 95,000, Publish
eked out Desktop Publishers Journal by about 5,000 copies a month.
The overlap between the readership was about 30 percent, Harrigan
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 to 15 people in Publish's San Francisco offices at
Second and Bryant streets have lost their jobs; the remainder of
the staff of 25 will stay on, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales and marketing will be run out of San Francisco, said
Publish Publisher Wesley Walton, who is staying on. The magazine
will retain an editorial and a Web presence in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``By bringing in the assets of Desktop Publishers Journal, we're
actually making our magazine bigger and stronger,'' Walton said.
``We're going to offer a deeper level of expertise and a broader
span of market coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrigan will take on the editor in chief title but will start
looking for a permanent editor immediately, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
