<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKENED-MEAT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BLACKEN WITHOUT SCORCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Paul Prudhomme stood in front of the portable
stove on stage and said, ``Blackening is not burning.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years earlier Prudhomme had popularized blackening, a
method of cooking that, as Prudhomme described it, caramelized
sugars and seared spices onto foods. Ever since, people have been
setting off smoke alarms and ruining perfectly good cuts of meat,
poultry and fish.
</P>
<P>
   While Prudhomme is adept at cooking over extremely high heat, it
seems that many Americans (including a large number of chefs) are
not. The result was a lot of food burned to a shiny ebony on the
outside but raw on the inside. Fortunately, there is a way to
``blacken'' and get edible results.
</P>
<P>
   Buy ``blackening spices,'' which have sugar listed as an
ingredient. Dry the meat before starting and heat the oven to 325
degrees. Coat one side of the meat with the spices, then place,
spice-side down, in a very hot cast-iron skillet. The meat will
sizzle and smoke but not to excess. Leave in the pan 30 seconds to
1 minute, just long enough for the sugar in the spice mixture to
caramelize and turn dark brown. Turn meat and sear lightly on the
uncoated side. Place skillet in the oven and bake until meat is
cooked to desired doneness (time depends on what you're cooking).
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly Prudhomme's method, but it's not burned. I
think he would approve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2781 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-PC-SANDWICHES-HNS &LR;      08-19 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PC-SANDWICHES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 DOWNLOAD TASTE, NUTRITION WITH THESE `PCs'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ These days a grilled cheese sandwich has about as
much appeal as a rotary phone. Oh, it's filling enough, but it
won't put you on the superhighway to good nutrition. What you need
is a hand-held PC (power combo), a sandwich that will output more
vitamins and proteins than fats and carbohydrates.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, a sandwich made with pork or chicken or most any other
protein is going to contain some fat. But you can downgrade fat
content while augmenting flavor using these processes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy the leanest cuts of meat you can find. Lean pork chops,
chicken and turkey breast, and lean roast beef slices are all good
choices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trim visible fat from the meat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Add flavor and tenderize meat simultaneously by marinating in
citrus juices.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use seafood such as fish fillets or crab meat as sandwich
fillers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cook without added fat. Grilling, steaming, poaching and
blackening are all good methods to use. Skip frying and sauteeing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pile on the vegetables. Tomatoes, bell peppers and onions have
exuberant flavors, but don't forget less obvious vegetables such as
portobellos, jicama, cucumber, carrot and radishes. These add
texture and interest to your sandwich. For a more subtle flavor,
grill vegetables before adding them to the sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reserve the sandwich bread for peanut butter and jelly.
Instead, try some of the many specialty breads in supermarkets
these days, including Tuscan, seven-grain, pita bread and
Portuguese rolls.
</P>
<P>
   The variety of ingredients make creating a hand-held PC as easy
as dialing the phone, but the combinations are as endless as sites
on the Web. Here are a few suggestions to get you surfing for a new
sandwich:
</P>
<P>
   _ Blacken one chicken breast per person. Slice chicken breast
and toss with julienned red bell peppers and onions. Line a pita
bread with lettuce and stuff with chicken mixture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Poach a 4-ounce tuna steak for each sandwich. Cut into cubes.
Toss tuna with diced cucumber, diced red onion, grated carrot,
sliced black olives and feta cheese. Mash 1 clove garlic to a
paste. Whisk with 2 teaspoons balsamic vinegar, 1 1/2 tablespoons
lemon juice and 3/4 teaspoon Dijon mustard. Drizzle in 1/3 cup
olive oil while whisking. toss with tuna and vegetables. Stuff
mixture into a pita.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN PORK SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   4 center-cut, boneless pork chops
</P>
<P>
   1 cup lime juice plus more for avocado
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 large tomato
</P>
<P>
   1 Haas avocado
</P>
<P>
   4 Portuguese rolls
</P>
<P>
   Hot sauce
</P>
<P>
   Trim all visible fat from sides of pork chops. Butterfly each
pork chop by laying on a cutting board. Cut from one side, almost
to the other, as close to the center as possible. Pound the chops
lightly with a meat mallet to make the chops as even in thickness
as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Combine lime juice and cumin in a resealable plastic bag. Add
chops and marinate, refrigerated, 2 hours. Slice tomato. Peel and
slice avocado. Coat avocado slices with lime juice to prevent them
from browning.
</P>
<P>
   Light coals or gas grill and bring to medium-high heat. Toast
rolls on grill. Remove pork from marinade and grill until cooked
through, about 2 minutes per side. Place pork on rolls, top with
tomato and avocado. Serve with hot pepper sauce on the side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
