A2783 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MICKEY-BLUEEYES-LADN &LR;      08-19 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICKEY-BLUEEYES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLICHE MOB COMEDY HAS GRANT'S CHARM, LITTLE ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
OUR RATING: 2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' follows in the
fish-out-of-water, mob comedy footsteps of this spring's ``Analyze
This,'' where an innocent gets recruited for wise guy duty against
his own better instincts. It's as if Hollywood screenwriters have
been watching marathons of ``The Godfather'' movies and were
particularly inspired by hearing Al Pacino bellow, ``Just when I
thought I was out, they keep pulling me back in!''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of effectiveness, ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' falls somewhere
in between the manic vitality of ``Analyze This'' and the rote
send-ups in ``Mafia!'' It coasts by largely on the droll charms of
its star, Hugh Grant, but the winsome actor can only do so much in
a movie hampered by poor comic pacing and gags stolen from better
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Grant plays Michael Felgate, an Englishman enjoying a productive
career (he runs a posh New York auction house) and a dizzying
romance with an attractive schoolteacher named Gina (Jeanne
Tripplehorn). Things are going so well that Michael decides to
propose, but Gina, much to his surprise, rejects him. It's not that
she doesn't love him, but, well, she just can't marry him.
</P>
<P>
   Michael decides to learn why and discovers that Gina's father is
mobster Frank Vitale (James Caan). Marry Gina and Michael would be
marrying the mob. He thinks it could work. Gina has her doubts, and
it turns out those concerns are pretty well-founded when her
relatives begin to use Michael's art house to launder money.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the movie's funniest moments comes early, contrasting
the debonair Michael and future ``Family'' members Vinnie, Carmine,
Louie and Uncle Vito. Grant's comic timing is, as always,
impeccable, and later, when he must force his English accent to
bend around ``Donnie Brasco'' banter, he displays an eerie ability
to channel Elmer Fudd.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, little else in the movie works. The screenplay by
Adam Scheinman (``Little Big League'') and Robert Kuhn (Grant
apparently did a rewrite as well) offers too few laughs and too
many gangster cliches. Once it moves beyond its initial set-up, the
movie goes nowhere fast, lapsing into a creaky, ridiculous story
revolving around murder and revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Caan certainly seems comfortable enough playing a mobster, but
Kelly Makin's (``Brain Candy: Kids in the Hall'') weak direction
gives the veteran actor little to do and no real chemistry with
Grant. In fact, besides Grant, no one here fares particularly well.
Tripplehorn virtually disappears after the movie's initial half
hour, and the various members of the Vitale family are stereotypes
struggling for identities.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences looking to see mob foibles played to better effect are
advised to rent ``Analyze This'' (out this week) or catch ``The
Sopranos'' on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey Blue Eyes''? Fuhgeddaboutit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The film: &LR;  ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' (PG-13; language, violence,
sensuality). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Hugh Grant, James Caan, Jeanne Tripplehorn. &UR;  &QL; 
Behind the scenes: &LR;  Directed by Kelly Makin. Screenplay by Adam
Scheinman and Robert Kuhn. Released by Castle Rock Entertainment. &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 43 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;   &UR; 2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
