A2784 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MRS-TINGLE-LADN &LR;      08-19 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRS-TINGLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET MRS. TINGLE, THE TEACHER FROM HELL 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
OUR RATING: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This week's teen movie, ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,''
is far from a total waste of celluloid. It's not very good, but at
least it keeps crudity to a minimum and exhibits something
resembling sardonic wit.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the occasional intelligent flourish, though, the story
is irredeemably dumb. The movie never quite overcomes its
sophomoric premise, which is normally to be expected of one of
these things. But not this particular one; ``Mrs. Tingle'' marks
the feature directing debut of Kevin Williamson, the writer whose
``Scream'' movies and ``Dawson's Creek'' television series have
supposedly set new standards of smarts for youth-skewed
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   But the only really canny aspect of ``Mrs. Tingle'' is the title
character herself. Played by the great British actress Helen Mirren
(``The Madness of King George,'' PBS' ``Prime Suspect''), she's a
small-town history teacher with an ingenious sadistic streak. Her
ability to criticize a student in the most devastatingly personal
way is her demonic glory _ kids actually dive out of her path when
she walks down the hall, and dignity is the only thing that
prevents fellow faculty from doing the same _ and Mirren plays her
with delectably cruel hauteur and relish.
</P>
<P>
   One of Tingle's least-deserving victims is smart, industrious
Leigh Ann Watson (``Creek's'' Katie Holmes). With an absent father
and a waitress mother, Leigh Ann needs the college scholarship
she's worked so hard to get. But Tingle's unfair disdain for her
carefully constructed history project jeopardizes that; when the
evil teacher discovers inaccurate but damning evidence that Leigh
Ann might be cheating, the girl's future fate is sealed.
</P>
<P>
   But when Leigh Ann and two friends, dim-bulb hunk Luke (``7th
Heaven'' heartthrob Barry Watson) and overdramatizing would-be
actress Jo Lynn (Marisa Coughlan) visit Tingle at home to plead for
leniency, things get out of hand. Before they know it, they've got
the teacher tied to her bed with a minor head wound. As the ensuing
hostage situation intensifies, however, Tingle's manipulative
faculties prove unhindered. What little suspense the film generates
rests on just how she'll psych her captors into turning on one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a number of Mirren's deft insinuations, the ensuing
complications range from unconvincing to lame. A ``comic'' bit with
an amorous, easily deceived coach (Jeffrey Tambor) makes for
particularly misfired burlesque. Overall, the universal fantasy of
revenge-on-teacher doesn't receive the cleverness needed to make it
feel fresh here. And the cautionary aspect _ no, kids, don't try
this at your school _ gives way to cliched, teen triumph pandering.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes is adequate, though unfortunately saddled with the burden
of having to be the girl who thinks seriously about this nonsense.
Watson proves deft at playing dumb. Coughlan, who'll appear in
Williamson's upcoming TV series ``Wasteland,'' is energetic and
bright. Her one-woman replay of greatest moments from ``The
Exorcist'' is an impressive interpretation of a really desperate
idea.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' dithers on, you appreciate moments
like that more and more. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
The film: &LR;  ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' (PG-13; violence, language,
sex). &UR;  &QL; 
The stars: &LR;  Helen Mirren, Katie Holmes, Barry Watson, Marisa
Coughlan, Jeffrey Tambor. &QL; 
!bold! &UR; Behind the scenes: &LR;  Written and directed by Kevin
Williamson. Produced by Cathy Konrad. Released by Dimension Films.
 &UR;  &QL; 
Running time: &LR;  One hour, 43 minutes. &UR;  &QL; 
Our rating: &LR;  2 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 12:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2785 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-USER-FRIENDLY-CHURCH-     08-19 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USER-FRIENDLY-CHURCH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY INDEPENDENT EVANGELICAL CHURCHES ARE GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Religion Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SAN ANTONIO -- Last May I visited Harvest Fellowship Community
Church, where my son, Adam, worships. I immediately saw why
independent evangelical churches like his are booming across
America, while many traditional liturgical churches are slowly
eroding down to a loyal band of the white-haired, bald and stooped.
 &HT;    First, the atmosphere is open and inviting. Somewhat startling
to this easterner, no man had a tie on but me. People were dressed
not in their Sunday best, but Saturday casual -- shorts and
T-shirts. The message: Come as you are.
 &HT;    Except for one hymn, ''Amazing Grace,'' all the rest were praise
songs with snappy rhythms, backed up by guitars and drums, not an
organ.
 &HT;    The words flashed on a user-friendly screen so we had no need of
hymnals. People stood and sang for an astonishing 25 minutes.
 &HT;    Mothers were told there was a room in the rear if they were
nursing or had wiggly kids, and a children's ministry for infants,
and Sunday School for all in a new building next door.
 &HT;    The place simply doesn't look like a church. There is no cross,
no pews, no stained-glass windows, in fact no windows at all. It
resembled a dinner theater, which, in fact, it once was.
 &HT;    There was no liturgy, no standard prayers repeated every week.
Often, at the beginning, there is a 5-7 minute skit, a modern
parable, on the theme of the sermon that engages the 90's mind. A
bunch of songs followed by a sermon, the height of informality.
 &HT;    When a visitor attends Harvest Fellowship, a church member drops
by their home with a loaf of bread on a board, as a gift. Why? ''We
have become a society of disconnected people,'' observes Pastor
Peter Spencer, 45. ''This is a way of greeting people, of being
gracious in a genuine way. If they ask us to come in, we say, `No,
we are not Jehovah's Witnesses. Enjoy the bread.'''
 &HT;    Unlike Catholic and mainline Protestant churches, which follow a
''lectionary'' in which the same Gospel and Epistle readings are
repeated over and over, which can become numbing over the years,
evangelical sermons draw from a much wider range of Scripture,
which makes them inherently more interesting.
 &HT;    Harvest Fellowship goes a step further to preach practical
messages of hope on the toughest issues. Christian dating, marriage
and divorce are not avoided, as at most churches. The sermon I
heard was on John 10:10: ''I have come that they may have life, and
have it abundantly.''
 &HT;    ''If that is God's desire, why is it that most people are not
having an abundant life?'' asked the associate pastor, John Cannon.
Good question.
 &HT;    His answer: Many are waiting for life's conditions to change,
rather than realizing that they have to change first. Many find
their feelings about God change with circumstances, rather than
realizing that God gave us a spirit of wisdom and revelation (Eph
1:1-17) that will enable us to be obedient, with unwavering faith.
God will sustain us through changing circumstances.
 &HT;    In an evangelical church, worshipers are constantly looking up
Scriptures and underlining their Bibles. Therefore, they are
learning. In the liturgical churches, no one even brings a Bible.
 &HT;    What was most striking, however, was the deep faith and
transparent spirit of those who spoke. These are people for whom
faith had made a difference in their life. They radiate both a joy
and conviction.
 &HT;    Exhibit A is Pastor Peter, who had his own ad agency and from
1976-1981 he was the lead singer in such musicals as ''Fiddler on
the Roof'' at the Fiesta Dinner Playhouse in San Antonio.
Apparently on top of the world, he and his Brazilian wife quit and
became missionaries in Sao Paulo, working with orphans. They
returned in 1985.
 &HT;    The Fiesta was bankrupt. Peter walked through a kicked-down
door, went on the stage where he had sung hundreds of times. A
vision came that one day he would preach the Gospel there.
 &HT;    He was leading a small church of 100 people in 1992 when the
opportunity came to buy the building for $1.5 million. He offered
$300,000 and got it for $315,000. At the first service, 500 people
showed up. Today, 2,100 attend weekly.
 &HT;    ''The purpose of church is not to show up,'' he says. ''but to
grow up, be impacted and change.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Mike McManus
<TEXT>
