<HEADLINE>
BEVERAGE MAKER LOOKS FOR NEW MARKETS WITH FRESH JUICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Six months after completing its $19
million purchase of New Jersey-based Fresh Juice Co. Inc., Saratoga
Beverage Group Inc. is ready to roll out a product that's meant to
blend the best of both companies: Fresh-squeezed juice in a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   The Ultimate Juice is expected to hit store shelves soon, chief
executive Robin Prever told about 30 shareholders Wednesday at
Saratoga Beverage's annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The product combines Fresh Juice's strength _ high-quality
fresh-squeezed juices _ with Saratoga Beverage's expertise in
marketing bottled products.
</P>
<P>
   The new product won't stay on the shelves long, even if it
doesn't sell _ the quick expiration time of fresh, all-natural
juice is one of the challenges the company faces in distributing
it. Fresh Juice had sold the fresh-squeezed product primarily at
high-quality restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The other big challenge of bottling the juice is distribution,
Prever said. With fresh orange juice, no more than 48 hours should
elapse between when the oranges are picked and when the juice is
bottled, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Prever told shareholders that the company, which she rebuilt
after purchasing it in 1992, was ready for the new challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done it before,'' she said. ``We've learned how to fight
and kick in a competitive industry.''
</P>
<P>
   New product launches and plans to leverage the Saratoga brand
name were key topics at the company's annual meeting. It also
continues to look for future acquisition targets.
</P>
<P>
   Saratoga Beverage is a far different company than it was at last
year's annual meeting. The purchase of Fresh Juice brought it
plants in New Jersey, Florida and California, and increased its
annual revenues from about $12 million to about $40 million. Prever
predicted sales would hit $60 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company is now a key competitor in the fresh-juice business,
while it had been a niche player in bottled water, Prever said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to The Ultimate Juice, the company is also rolling
out new iced tea and lemonade drinks intended to stand out from the
competition by featuring all-natural ingredients. Saratoga Beverage
failed once with lemonade and fruit drinks called Toga, but company
officials attribute the problems to marketing. The drinks were
promoted using characters on the bottles instead of an effort that
would have focused on the quality of the drink.
</P>
<P>
   It also recently launched a line of pureed fruit drinks, or
smoothies, under the name ``Saratoga Fruit for Thought.'' As for
its labels, Saratoga Beverage also is hoping to promote its name
more. It is negotiating to sell the name of one of its Fresh Juice
products on the West Coast, and add the century-old Saratoga brand
name there, for instance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
