<SLUG> BC-DAIRY-FARMERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK DAIRY FARMERS STRUGGLE WITH HEAT, DROUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The good luck didn't last for New York's dairy
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the best year for Northeast dairy farmers in a
long time, according to new statistics. This year is another story.
Milk production is off because of the heat, prices paid to farmers
have been erratic and sporadic drought conditions are hurting some
operations that grow their own feed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was the best year in a decade,'' said Peter Gregg,
spokesman for the New York State Department of Agriculture and
Markets. ``It's the complete opposite this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices paid to farmers were good last year, and production costs
were stable, according to a new report from Connecticut-based First
Pioneer Farm Credit. That yielded a profit of $438 per cow in the
Northeast, up sharply from 1997's ``humbling figure of just $42,''
according to the release accompanying the report, and even from the
$167 per-cow average over the past five years. The same report puts
the average milking-herd size at 161.
</P>
<P>
   But 1999 has proved so complicated that profit projections are
cloudy at best, said Tom Borden, a dairy farmer in Easton,
Washington County, He has a milking herd of 160 Holsteins.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dry weather has been quite variable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers have gotten enough rain to grow the hay and corn
they need to feed the livestock throughout the fall and winter, but
just a few miles away others have missed out on some crucial
thunderstorms, Borden said.
</P>
<P>
   Borden has enough hay, but it's not the same quality as last
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corn crops can also be hurt by the drought, with some stalks
failing to yield an ear of corn _ the protein source the animals
need.
</P>
<P>
   If the supply of feed is low or of poor quality, some farmers
are going to have to buy feed elsewhere to supplement. But the
drought conditions _ while spotty _ have spread so far across the
Northeast that farmers ``are not going to be able to go to the next
county to buy hay,'' predicted Gary Dake, who, as vice president of
Stewart's Ice Cream, is in charge of buying milk directly from some
50 farm producers in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is it going to come from?'' Dake said. And the next
question would be, how much more expensive is hay going to be if
there is a shortage? That's not clear at all yet, and that's why
Borden described the profit picture as cloudy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the prices paid to farmers this year for milk have
varied more erratically month to month than in 1998, partly because
of a national over-supply this spring. The price paid per hundred
pounds of milk will probably reach $15 to $16 in the fall, when
school increases milk demand, observers said. But prices were below
$12 in April, severely cutting into farmers' sales.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, farmers like Borden say milk production is off
because of the heat. The cows simply don't feel like eating as much
when it's hot, and so they produce less milk.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmers aren't likely to have cash reserves left over from
1998's plump profits, Gregg said. After so many poorer years,
farmers are apt to have used the money to pay down debt or make
repairs to equipment and buildings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farm advocates said there will be less money circulating for
those kinds of things in 1999 and 2000 in New York _ still the
nation's third-largest dairy producing state after California and
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agricultural support economy is quite extensive,'' said
Chuck Randall, a part-time dairy farmer in Saratoga Springs with a
milking herd of 15. Sales of hardware and building materials, for
instance, will fall when farmers have less money, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
