<HEADLINE>
WEB ZANINESS BEHIND THE GOLDEN GATE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You know your town is in deep trouble when the
virtual mayor's race is more interesting than the so-called real
thing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the most fun in the San Francisco mayor's race was the
revelation that challenger Clint Reilly had registered such Web
Wide Web domain names as williebrown.com, frankjordan.com and even
williesucks.
</P>
<P>
   This sent supporters of Mayor Willie Brown into a tizzy, while
Reilly supporters accused Brown of being behind the times and out
of touch with the dot-common people.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the real story. It took them five months to find out,''
Reilly spokesman Tom Pier said.
</P>
<P>
   The downside for the new, squeaky-clean Clint Reilly is that his
cybersquatting may remind people of the old Clint Reilly, back when
he was a down-and-dirty campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, Brown and former Mayor Frank Jordan finally
created Web sites to try to catch up to clintreilly.com.
Unfortunately, because of Reilly's coup, Brown and Jordan are stuck
with the unwieldy reelectwilliebrown.com and mayorfrankjordan.org.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to make typos, if for some reason you want to call
them up. For some reason, I called them up.
</P>
<P>
   Let me say that I would no sooner pick a mayor by the coolness
of his Web site than by the cut of his suit _ just to pick a
comparison. A candidate can go out and buy a Web site the way he
can buy television advertising. But it is curious how those TV ads
and those Web sites seem to indicate something.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is far ahead in the cyberspace race. His 4-month-old Web
site is good-looking, offers detailed position papers, names all
his campaign contributors and has a feature that allows people to
rank issues in their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Reilly's campaign won the award for Web site of the
month from Campaigns and Elections, a magazine I'll look for in my
dentist's office next time I'm having a root canal.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's recently launched Web site is a worthy second to
Reilly's, with zippy graphics touting Brown's accomplishments.
Maybe he'll have to arm-wrestle President Clinton for some of them.
Brown takes credit for three years of budget surpluses and a 40
percent reduction in crime.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, some of these claims rotate in a little ad space
on the top of the site, giving it the appearance of an
old-fashioned political flier fluttering on your doorknob.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site also has a couple of nice stories about Brown by
community activists, one of whom denies he's arrogant. The feature
I really like, though, is one called ``Ask Willie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to a handsome man. Send him your question, and ``your
e-mail will be answered personally within five days.''
</P>
<P>
   Answered personally by whom?
</P>
<P>
   Frank Jordan's new Web site is so low-tech it's almost charming
instead of embarrassing. Almost. It's a short letter in early
Selectric typeface that begins ``San Franciscans will no longer
stand for a City Hall that supports special-interest greed over
neighborhood priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Jordan doesn't support special interests like Web
site designers. Sadly, he missed his chance to attract people to
his site with a teaser of wet skin.
</P>
<P>
   That famous picture is available on an out-of-date mayoral
fashion critique Web site which popped up when I searched with the
key words ``Willie Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when the madness began in earnest. I found critiques of
Brown in WillieWatch and The Usual Suspects, as well as satirical
letters from ``the Imperial Poohbah of San Francisco'' addressed to
``Dearest Minions.''
</P>
<P>
   I found something called the ``Pieman's Homepage,'' which is a
delirious screed about every stuffed shirt in the world ever hit
with a pie _ accompanied by synthesized music more ominous than
anything ever piped into Marie Callender's.
</P>
<P>
   When I searched for ``Frank Jordan,'' the first thing that came
up was something about Ballpark Franks and Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   No, I wouldn't judge a candidate by his Web site any more than
I'd judge Ballpark Franks by the failed baseball player who
advertises them. But Web sites do tell you something.
</P>
<P>
   When I finished sending my e-mail to ``Ask Willie Brown,'' and
checked the calendar to see when to expect a personal reply, I went
to the official City of San Francisco Web site. This is where you
can judge the efficiency of government departments.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department has a great site that gives up-to-date
block-by-block crime statistics. You might want to call it up
before you walk to the corner store.
</P>
<P>
   The Human Rights Commission has an informative and gorgeous
site. The section that refers to gay, lesbian and transsexual
rights is bracketed by rainbow flags flapping in an electronic
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   The Housing Authority's Web site looks like meaningless scrawls
on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   I avoided the site for the Department of Parking and Traffic
because I didn't want to get a ticket for double-clicking.
</P>
<P>
   Muni, the public transit system, has a great Web site designed
by its pricey consultants, Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton. Like those
electronic sign boards in the stations, it shows moving Muni Metro
cars. I almost ran to the Powell Street station to see if a train
really was pulling in.
</P>
<P>
   All I can say is, at least the mayor and Muni make those blips
run on time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
