u a BC-COMPUTERS-LINUX-BOS &LR;      08-19 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-LINUX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINUX GAMESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Backers of the upstart Linux operating system like to joke
that their ultimate goal is world domination. They're getting
there. In fact, anyone with a Linux computer can create an
interplanetary empire, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   All the Linux user needs is a copy of Civilization: Call to
Power, a popular new computer game that lets the player launch a
campaign of cosmic conquest. Granted, it's a make-believe empire,
but the very fact that companies are releasing Linux versions of
their new computer games demonstrates how much market power Linux
has acquired in the past couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent LinuxWorld trade show in San Jose, Calif., Linux
devotees lined up to play Civilization and two other popular
computer games _ Myth II and Railroad Tycoon II. Meanwhile, Linux
versions of the immensely popular Quake series of combat games are
now on sale.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Linux games is still small, but Scott Draeker
plans to change that. Draeker, a software licensing attorney, is
president of Loki Entertainment Software, a Tustin, Calif., company
that produced the Linux versions of Myth II and Railroad Tycoon II
and plans to keep rolling out Linux versions of major games.
</P>
<P>
   Draeker, a former customer support worker at Apple Computer
Inc., was a long-time fan of Apple's Macintosh computer. But after
years of slow Mac sales, most leading game makers stopped producing
Mac versions of their products. ``People were constantly
complaining that there were no games,'' Draeker said. At the same
time, Draeker grew disenchanted with Apple's management. ``I wanted
to leave the Mac behind,'' he said. Draeker switched his loyalty to
Linux because of its ``open source'' policy, which lets Linux users
modify the software to fit their own needs. Apple's Macintosh
software generally doesn't allow this.
</P>
<P>
   Draeker realized that when it came to games, Linux was in the
same boat as Macintosh _ virtually no major game companies offered
Linux versions of their products.
</P>
<P>
   He founded Loki to redress the balance. Draeker negotiates
licensing deals with the companies that created the original games.
These companies provide the original ``source code'' _ the raw
programming instructions that control each game. This code is then
modified so that it will run on a Linux machine, a process known as
``porting.''
</P>
<P>
   It's far easier to port a game than to build one from scratch.
Top-quality games can cost millions of dollars to produce and
require dozens of workers. By licensing existing games, Loki can
get into the business on the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The game producers also profit from royalties on the sales of
Linux versions of their games. They get to sell their games to
Linux users, without having to bear the expense and complexity of
creating Linux versions themselves.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how large a market there is for Linux games. Linux
is mainly popular as an alternative to Microsoft Corp.'s Windows NT
operating system for running powerful server computers. Few people
run Linux on the home machines on which they play games.
</P>
<P>
   But Draeker said Linux is spreading beyond corporate server
machines and onto home desktops, in place of Microsoft's Windows 95
or Windows 98 software. He cited a report from Corel Corp. that a
million people have downloaded the Linux version of Corel's
WordPerfect word processing software. ``They're not running that on
a server,'' Draeker said.
</P>
<P>
   Loki is working on Linux versions of eight more games and is
constantly looking for new products to port to Linux. Draeker said
most game software makers are quite interested in working with his
company _ with one major exception: Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I approached their booth at E3 (a leading electronic-industry
trade show) and asked them about porting Age of Empires,'' one of
Microsoft's most popular games. The response? ``I got a belly
laugh,'' said Draeker.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
