<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RE-CREATING A NEIGHBORHOOD FOR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My grandkids are attending Camp Fun-on-the-Rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The campers, dressed in matching yellow T-shirts that have
``Summer '99'' on the front pocket and a picture of a tide pool on
the back, set off Monday morning to explore Salem's Pioneer
Village. Later this week they'll visit a petting zoo, have lunch on
a ferry, and go to the beach. Apart from field trips, the eight
campers, raging in age from 5 to 9, will hear a storyteller, do
arts and crafts projects, keep a journal, and have a day of
noncompetitive games.
</P>
<P>
   Camp Fun-on-the-Rocks isn't listed in any camp directory. It is,
in fact, an invention of my daughter and her neighbors, who came up
with a creative solution to the challenge of keeping their kids
occupied for two weeks this summer. Luckily Valerie, a favorite
baby sitter who's now a special education teacher, was available to
be head counselor for two weeks. Two neighborhood teenagers are
sharing the role of junior counselor, and I volunteered to tell
Br'er Rabbit stories, usin' mah awthentic Suthin accent. The camp
is headquartered in one family's shed, temporarily furnished with
tables and chairs borrowed from a school. The stay-at-home moms
take turns driving.
</P>
<P>
   And so my granddaughter, Jessie, and grandson, Danny, and DT and
Amy, Philip and Natalie, Tucker and Claire will have the
opportunity to become a smoothly functioning team, regardless of
age or sex or family ties. The bigger kids will help the smaller
ones and act as mentors, which is, of course, exactly what the
littlest campers long for in their hearts. The skills they learn _
in sharing, cooperation, and mutual respect _ will hopefully
continue to deepen their friendships as the years go by.
</P>
<P>
   This summer has been the season for more than one homemade
recreational opportunity. Jessie got invited to join a book group
formed by parents who wanted to make sure their children actually
read a substantial number of books on our local elementary school's
recommended second grade reading list.
</P>
<P>
   Since Laura was busy one evening, I took Jessie to a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The kids sat in a circle on the floor while the moms formed an
outer circle on the couches. The seven girls wanted a chance to
read out loud, and so they each got a chance to read a page from
the first selection, ``Betsy Ross,'' and to discuss the meaning of
words they'd had trouble with, like ``Continental Congress'' and
``Colonel.''
</P>
<P>
   Their collective judgment? ``Too many facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the discussion, there was a craft project _ making a
flag windsock out of white stars, blue construction paper, and red
paper streamers. After a snack, the girls put their heads together
to choose for themselves the titles that looked most interesting.
One of the moms took responsibility for ordering copies of each
book. The group will be meeting one evening a week until school
starts.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the media are deploring the decline of the family,
I can't help but admire moms who are giving real thought and energy
to the quality of their children's lives. Although most of these
kids will also take part in privately organized activities this
summer, these parents are committed to a level of participation
that didn't exist in my mother's generation. I'm impressed that
they have the confidence to design and execute programs without
feeling they need the guidance of experts.
</P>
<P>
   In a world that is becoming increasingly more fragmented, I'm
also impressed that these moms are trying to create an
intergenerational, neighborhood-based community for their children.
Instead of locking themselves into individual family units, these
mothers are willing to extend their sphere of nurturance outside
the nuclear family's confining walls. They're making the effort to
know and interact with kids other than their own, and as a result,
they're exposing their own children to the influence of other
caring adults. They're strengthening their own friendships as well
as modeling for their children the idea that there's nothing
standing in the way of creating something special for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Laura where she got the idea of starting a camp from
scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fondest memories are of spending lazy summer days, playing
with kids of all ages from this neighborhood,'' she says. ``I moved
back here in part because I wanted my kids to have that same
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there some experience you treasured as a child that
modern-day life no longer offers? Do you want to find a new way to
interact with your children and their peers? Put your imagination
to work. I would be surprised if you couldn't figure out a way to
make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
