<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITCHING THE STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks ago we told you we were thinking about taking our
column, Boston Capital, public. Our motivation was simple: We
wanted to get rich fast.
</P>
<P>
   Our goal hasn't changed but our strategy has. Our new plan? We
are going to sell ourselves to Lucent Technologies or Cisco Systems
or any of the other technology giants who seem to have an
insatiable appetite for small Massachusetts companies.
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't been paying attention, these firms have been
devouring local businesses the way a bird gobbles up worms.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Lucent paid $1.7 billion for Excel Switching Corp. in
Hyannis, the sixth time this year Lucent has purchased a
Massachusetts company. Cisco Wednesday paid $143 million for
MaxComm Technologies of Chelmsford; Cisco also paid $49 million for
a 4 percent stake in Akamai Technologies of Cambridge. If you are
doing the math, the Cisco investment puts Akamai's market value at
better than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Siemens, the German telecom company, spent
just over $1 billion on three tiny Massachusetts tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here? To paraphrase James Carville, ``It's the
Internet, stupid.'' The rise of the Internet has touched off a mad
scramble to boost the speed and power of the networks that carry
voice and data.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a revolution that is analogous to the industrial
revolution,'' says James Dolce, cofounder of Redstone
Communications. Dolce sold his Westford company in March to Siemens
for $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   All of the world's big telecom companies want to win this race
to the future and none want to risk falling behind. In theory, the
companies could develop the necessary technology themselves. In
practice, that would take too long. And in this race, time is
money. If you are late to market with the latest gizmo, the cost
could be enormous.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the little Massachusetts companies come in. Think
of them as research labs with expertise in communications, much of
it gained in the region's computer and networking companies. The
little guys develop new products quickly, test them, and prove that
they work. Then they sell out to the giants, often for astounding
amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollars involved are really small potatoes,'' insists
Howard Anderson, managing director of the Yankee Group, a Boston
consulting firm. The giants make most of the purchases with stock,
says Anderson, and in the case of Cisco and Lucent, that stock has
been steadily rising in value in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson makes a second point: By waiting, the big companies
face the prospect of paying even higher prices tomorrow. Example
number one: Lucent's January purchase of Ascend Communications for
$19.6 billion. Had Lucent acted a few years sooner, says Anderson,
it could have had Ascend's critical technology for a fraction of
that price.
</P>
<P>
   The curious economics of this competition explain why the local
companies sell out so early in the game. At one time young
technology firms hoped to grow into mighty oaks. Today they are
happy to sell themselves in the seed stage.
</P>
<P>
   When Dolce sold Redstone, the company had 70 employees and had
yet to ship a product.
</P>
<P>
   Like Redstone, Boston Capital is small. There are just the two
of us here. We too haven't shipped any product. We are in the
communications business and we do use the Internet on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   But that may not be enough. We've noticed that many of the local
firms that attract big offers make switches _ switches that hook up
one network to another. We don't know a heck of a lot about
switches, but that shouldn't stand in our way.
</P>
<P>
   We'll go down to the local Home Depot store and buy some
switches _ garage-door switches, light switches, any kind of
switches we can get our hands on. We'll pick the one we like best,
call it an Internet switch, and put the company up for sale. Our
slogan will be: ``Boston Capital: Throw the Switch, Make Us Rich.''
</P>
<P>
   We'd prefer to sell out to Lucent or Cisco to keep the business
in America, but, in truth, we'd accept a foreign bid too. We're
patriotic but not excessively so.
</P>
<P>
   We don't need $1.7 billion. We'd take less, a lot less.
</P>
<P>
   In this age of voice and data convergence, we'll be waiting by
the phone and computer for an offer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
