<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2838 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-     08-19 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TARGET PRACTICE FOR BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ Midway through their 11-on-11 drills
Wednesday morning, the Patriots lined up wide receiver Terry Glenn
to the far right. Opposite the offense's best was the defense's
best, cornerback Ty Law.
</P>
<P>
   The call was for Glenn to run a deep post pattern. The receiver
that quarterback Drew Bledsoe calls ``the most talented guy I've
ever thrown to'' quickly zoomed into overdrive and easily opened up
three or four steps on Law and neither Law nor anyone was about to
catch up to Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   The question _ the only question _ was whether Bledsoe's pass
would be on target. That's because if Bledsoe the passer has had a
weakness over the years, it has been with the accuracy of his deep
throws, especially deep throws near the sidelines. More than a few
times, Glenn and other New England receivers have had a free step
or more as they roamed deep, and Bledsoe's passes might or might
not be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Throwing the deep ball) is something that I don't feel I've
been extremely efficient at in my NFL career,'' said Bledsoe. ``I
feel I need to be more consistent in getting the deep ball and
taking advantage of those big plays. That's something that I will
continue to focus on.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Bledsoe's pass was perfect. Glenn still had three or
four strides on Law as the ball arrived deep downfield and Glenn
never had to break stride as he made the catch. For several reasons
_ Glenn easily slipping into overdrive and Bledsoe's perfect pass _
Patriots fans could forget the many defensive questions the team
has and dream on.
</P>
<P>
   A play or two later, Shawn Jefferson lined up on the far left,
with Steve Israel the cornerback on Jefferson. Over the last few
days, the receivers' legs have come back to them after the
inevitable heavy legs that follow the opening of camp, and it was
time to test them.
</P>
<P>
   The call for Jefferson was the same as it had been for Glenn _
run a deep post pattern. Just as Glenn had done, Jefferson zipped
past the cornerback and slipped into the open by two or three
steps. And once again, Bledsoe's long pass was perfectly on target
and Jefferson, like Glenn, never had to break stride for the
easiest of touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe thought long and hard about this chink in his passing
armor. His short and medium passes are, as Jefferson put it, ``just
beautiful,'' but his long passes were not. Finally, Bledsoe
concluded, he was trying too hard to make the perfect pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come out of college and you have a strong arm, you
try and throw everything real hard,'' said Bledsoe, ``and make the
perfect throw all the time. The thing that I had to learn'' was not
to try and throw the perfect pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you take it and put more air in the ball (throw it
higher), then you have more room for error,'' explained the
quarterback. ``And with the talented guys we have (at wide
receiver) I feel if I give them an even chance to make the play,
then they're going to come down with the ball. Like if I give Terry
Glenn a 50-50 chance with a defensive back, then I feel he's going
to make the catch. Tony Simmons is the same way . . . Troy Brown,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   What all this means for the Drew Bledsoe of 1999 ``is that I'm
not always going to try and make the perfect throw right on the
sideline all the time. I'm going to leave it inside a little bit
more and rely on them to go up and get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots ``are going to put more emphasis on the deep ball''
this season, said Jefferson. And the key for a quarterback to
complete that deep ball ``is to know your personnel,'' said
Jefferson. ``Like Terry . . . Drew can throw his arm out trying to
get the ball to Terry. And Tony, too, the young guys. But if a guy
might not be as fast as Terry, the thing is to know your guys. Then
maybe hang the ball up and give the guys a chance to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the strengths of this Patriots team are far, far,
far, and away its receivers, its tight end, and its quarterback.
And Bledsoe, now in his prime, is the key to all.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said he has ``extremely high expectations for my
performance now'' because he has seen virtually anything and
everything a defense can show. ``In just about every situation,''
he said, ``I at least expect myself to make the right decision. I
might not always make the exact right throw, but I expect to be
almost perfect in my decision-making with the experience I have.''
</P>
<P>
   The perception of Bledsoe changed last season with his
come-from-behind wins over Buffalo and Miami in the last seconds
while playing with a severely damaged finger. ``I think the guys
who I've played with the last few years know what I'm about,'' said
Bledsoe. ``I think they've had confidence in me. I think the
perception change is more on the outside than it is within the
team. ``I expect us to win the division this year, it's as simple
as that.''
</P>
<P>
   But it seems, early in the exhibition season, that if that is to
happen, the Patriots may have to score points and more points and
then even more points.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe is now into his second season of running Ernie Zampese's
offense ``and we're ahead in our offense simply because we've
worked with the same system for two years,'' he said. ``The bread
and butter of our offense is timing on the out routes, curls, and
posts, and I feel we're much more efficient with that stuff than we
were in the past. That's what Ernie hangs his hat on _ the timing
stuff _ and if we can be efficient with the quick timing stuff,
it'll open up more of the field for us.''
</P>
<P>
   With a receiving corps so deep, it might be tempting for the
Patriots to consider the Vikings' approach, which is to intimidate
defenses with so many threats in the passing game. Indeed, Bledsoe
envisions sending Glenn deep on one play and then maybe having the
speedy Simmons in from the bench on the next before defenders can
get their legs and wind back from running downfield with Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   But few are giving the Patriots much chance this season. And, as
Bledsoe noted, New England seldom has done what it has been
expected to do _ either good or bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer to be the underdog,'' said Bledsoe of the early
predictions that the Patriots will finish no better than fourth in
the AFC East. ``From the time I've been here, we've responded well
when we've been the underdog. Maybe it'll be a rallying point for
us this year and a motivation point to prove people wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, it'll have to be Bledsoe doing the most.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
