<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING A VIRAL TIE TO BREAST TUMORS  
 SNACKING AT NIGHT, AND WHY THEY DO IT  
 WEIGHING THE RISKS OF HORMONE THERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Exploring a viral tie to breast tumors
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is the Epstein-Barr virus, which causes infectious
mononucleosis, related to breast cancer?
</P>
<P>
   In the current Journal of the National Cancer Institute,
European researchers report that they found the virus in 51 of 100
breast cancer tissues studied, particularly in more aggressive
tumors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too soon to say cause and effect. It is a correlation,''
Irene Joab, one of the authors of the paper and a researcher at the
Saint Louis Hospital in Paris, said in an interview. ``We have to
do more work.''
</P>
<P>
   While this study confirms some earlier researchers' findings, at
least five other groups of scientists have looked for the virus in
breast cancer and not found it, according to an editorial
accompanying the article, by two National Cancer Institute
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the virus does not turn out to be a cause of breast
cancer, the cancer institute's scientists said that it could still
serve as ``a useful prognostic indicator'' or target for cancer
therapy. And if it does turn out to be a cause, efforts to develop
a vaccine against the virus should be stepped up, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from its role in mononucleosis, popularly known as the
``kissing disease,'' the virus has been linked to Burkitt's
lymphoma, which is usually found in Africa and causes a jaw tumor,
and a rare nose-and-throat cancer usually found in China.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Snacking at night, and why they do it
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 45 years ago, night-eating syndrome was first described,
but it had never been subjected to careful study _ until now.
</P>
<P>
   As first identified in 1955 by Dr. Albert Stunkard and
colleagues, the syndrome consists of morning anorexia, evening
overeating and insomnia, and is found to occur during stressful
periods and to be linked with failed efforts to lose weight.
</P>
<P>
   In the current Journal of the American Medical Association,
Stunkard joins colleagues from the University of Tromso in Norway
and the University of Pennsylvania to further elucidate the
behavioral and hormonal characteristics of the night-eating
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   In analyzing the behavior of those who suffer from night-eating
syndrome and those who do not, the researchers found that those who
have the syndrome consumed 56 percent of their calories between 8
p.m. and 6 a.m., while those who do not consumed only 15 percent in
that time period.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 10 night eaters in the study woke up 178 times in a
week, and more than half of those awakenings led to a
carbohydrate-rich snack. The 10 people who did not suffer from the
syndrome experienced a total of 13 night awakenings, and none of
them led to a snack.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the researchers found the night eaters' moods
got worse as the day progressed.
</P>
<P>
   On the hormonal front, the researchers found that night eaters
were out of synch for melatonin, leptin, and cortisol, compared
with non-night eaters.
</P>
<P>
   These findings suggest that night-eating syndrome ``appears to
represent a new eating disorder,'' different from the already
recognized eating disorders of anorexia, bulimia, and binging,
wrote the researchers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weighing the risks of hormone therapy
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the controversy over hormone replacement therapy for
postmenopausal women, several medical organizations urge physicians
to counsel women about the risks and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But a new study by researchers from Harvard Medical School and
Harvard Pilgrim Health Care found that the organizations'
guidelines for physicians are inadequate at meeting the needs of
patients.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the American College of Physicians recommends that
women be actively involved in the decision making, but provides few
specifics to doctors on how to do that.
</P>
<P>
   The group's physician guidelines even fail to steer clinicians
toward the group's own patient-oriented brochures on hormone
replacement therapy, according to the report in this week's Annals
of Internal Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The study, led by Dr. Maureen T. Connelly, involved in-depth
interviews with 26 Harvard Pilgrim patients who had received
prescriptions for hormone replacement therapy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
