<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEATHROW-DETECTIVE-AR     08-19 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEATHROW-DETECTIVE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETECTIVE FROM BAY STATE TAKES UP FLORIDA MAN'S CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Attn.: Fla.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While Crosley ``Pappa'' Green sat on death row in Raiford, Fla.,
private detective Joe Moura studied long into the night, flipping
through pages and pages of documents chronicling the 10-year-old
Florida murder case from his office in Stoughton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   After many nights poring over old testimony, Moura, 46, along
with three other top investigators from Chicago, Denver, and San
Diego, came to a conclusion: Green may die for a crime he never
committed. This weekend, Moura met the other detectives outside of
Orlando where they tracked down witnesses who recanted statements
as a camera crew from the television show ``48 Hours'' recorded
every word.
</P>
<P>
   Though their work is far from completion, they already believe
they have enough evidence to prove that Green, 41, was wrongly
convicted of killing Charles ``Chip'' Flynn in April 1989.
</P>
<P>
   It a belief that innocent men are being sent to their deaths
because of unequal representation in the nation's court system that
has launched Moura and his friends on a crusade that has landed
them in the small town of Titusville, Fla., fighting for the life
of a man they have never met.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me just say this,'' Moura, who is working pro bono on the
case, said Wednesday from Florida. ``I've been in this business for
26 years, and this is one case in which the facts prove this man
should not be in prison for murder . . . I firmly believe that
Pappa Green is going to walk out of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Moura believes that, like many poor, black men with little or no
money for a good defense, Green never had an equal chance to prove
he didn't kill the 22-year-old Flynn, who was white.
</P>
<P>
   A Portuguese immigrant who grew up in Stoughton, Moura has been
investigating crimes and fraud cases ever since he was 14.
</P>
<P>
   Most times, Moura travels all over the world assisting
high-powered private clients or helping Boston police crack cases.
But the Florida case has convinced him that men like Green are
fighting a losing battle when the best lawyers and investigators
are all on the prosecution's side.
</P>
<P>
   Green's case, said Moura, should be a lesson to Massachusetts to
stay away from the death penalty. It should also indicate to states
like Illinois, where 12 men have been released from death row, that
a case should be investigated exhaustively before sending a man to
his death.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the addresses of witnesses, including Green's sister,
Moura and an old friend, Chicago detective Paul Ciolino, who helped
a Northwestern professor gather enough evidence to free a Chicago
man days before he was scheduled to be executed last September,
knocked on doors and interviewed people who now say they were
pressured by police and the prosecution to lie. Furthermore, both
men argue that there never was any physical evidence _ blood spots,
finger or shoe prints _ that tied Green to the crime or the crime
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne Holmes, an assistant state attorney in Brevard County,
said the key eyewitness picked Green out from a stack of
photographs, and the Florida Supreme Court affirmed the conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Now Green's case is up for appeal. If new evidence can prove he
was falsely accused, that there are new witnesses, or that his
lawyer was insufficient, Green could be granted a new trial. But
Holmes insists such claims are typical of death-row defendants _
that Moura and his friends are grasping at straws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody seems happy with their counsel after they didn't walk
free,'' Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   It may be 15 years before Green is executed, said Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   According to news and court records of the notorious murder
case, Green, of Titusville, Fla., kidnapped and robbed Flynn and
his girlfriend, Kim Hallock, on the night of April 3, 1989. Police
said he stole the truck the two were sitting in and forced them to
ride along as he drove to a remote area. Green tied Flynn's hands,
but Hallock was able to hand him a gun.
</P>
<P>
   When Green stopped the truck, he yanked Hallock out. Flynn fired
a shot before falling to the ground. Hallock testified she was able
to hop in the truck, drive away, and call police. But Flynn had
bled to death before police arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Hallock picked Green out of a photo lineup, and then testified
against him at trial. Green's defenders, however, insist that the
photo lineup was ``suggestive'' _ that Green was the only
dark-skinned black man in the bunch, and that Hallock's
identification was influenced by the photo.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tim Curtis, a Florida car dealer who was Flynn's best
friend, now says he may have been mistaken in testifying against
Green. Curtis said he was so angry that a black man could have
killed his pal that he now worries that maybe he was blinded from
the truth, and somehow altered Green's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there are a few things that got my heart and mind
troubled,'' said Curtis, who was also interviewed by Moura.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1990 trial, he testified that he saw Green hours
before the murder, a statement he still believes to be true. But
Curtis, who months before sold Flynn the truck Green is accused of
hijacking, now also believes Green is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Green's fingerprints were not found inside or outside the truck,
a fact that Curtis said was kept from him, though court and news
reports show it was entered into court. ``It's virtually impossible
to drive that truck without leaving fingerprints. I knew that
truck. You had to manhandle it. It was my truck,'' he said. ``I
have a whole sick guilt feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis knew Green and said he was no angel but he shouldn't die
for a crime he didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody in Titusville, said Ciolino, the Chicago detective,
thought Green _ who came from a tumultous background _ was headed
for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   His father killed his mother and turned the gun on himself. His
nine brothers and sisters were raised on the streets, and his
nephew landed on death row, too. Green was a drug user and had a
rap sheet dating back to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   It was precisely this background, Moura and his fellow
detectives say, that caused police to focus on Green as a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was an insignificant criminal and also happened to be poor,
black, and had the reputation of a big mouth,'' said Ciolino. ``His
family had a bad reputation, so to make him the bad guy was not
only convenient but healthy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1329EDT &QL; 
