<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2847 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GORILLA-BIRTH-BOS &LR;      08-19 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORILLA-BIRTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ZOO'S DOCTORS, GORILLA BIRTH IS ALL IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KRISTIN VAUGHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He is in the midst of both people and gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   It makes no difference to Dr. Machelle Seibel, a reproductive
endocrinologist, who balances being on-call at a suburban clinic
with answering the call of the wild at the Franklin Park Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Seibel, and two other doctors who typically work with humans _
Dr. Ralph Philosophe and Dr. Boris Swarztman _ formed an emergency
response team recently to help Kiki, a pregnant gorilla, in case
she experienced complications from childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   In this instance, their expertise wasn't needed.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 8, the 17-year-old western lowland gorilla gave birth to
a healthy 4-pound baby _ Franklin Park Zoo's first gorilla birth.
</P>
<P>
   The baby has been nursing and progressing well and has remained
healthy despite last week's threat from the extreme diarrhea that
afflicted the five older gorillas in the troop _ including Kiki.
All have recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo visitors can catch the first glimpses of the new baby
gorilla with its mother Thursday as they go on exhibit from 10 a.m.
to 5 p.m. weekdays or 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The gorilla birth wasn't the first time that Seibel, who works
with human reproductive disorders at the Fertility Center of New
England, has volunteered to make his medical knowledge available to
patients of a hairier kind.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, on the same night that Kiki delivered, Seibel had been
at the zoo earlier to perform an ultrasound on a pregnant,
cat-sized primitive monkey called a potto.
</P>
<P>
   And in the past, he's done everything from removing a vaginal
tumor from a 220-pound gorilla named Gigi to prescribing birth
control pills for a painted-face primate called a mandrill, who was
experiencing excessive bleeding during her menstrual cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I called in the prescription, I said, `I'm
calling this in for `Mandy the mandrill' and the pharmacist asked,
`What's her insurance?' '' said Seibel, who seems tickled when his
animal and human worlds meet.
</P>
<P>
   Although using doctors trained for human beings to treat zoo
animals might seem odd at first glance, Seibel said that some
physiological differences between these zoo animals and people are
so small that it doesn't make sense not to use them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certain anatomy that is similar, like there is only a
small difference in the pelvis and the size of the babies at birth.
The length of pregnancy is about 8 1/2 months. . . . If you are
familiar with humans, then primates, particularly gorillas, are
really quite similar,'' Seibel said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorillas are also susceptible to many of the same illnesses as
humans and they receive human vaccination shots for such diseases
as measles and polio. Females have menstrual cycles, although they
don't always bleed.
</P>
<P>
   The normally 230-pound Kiki was even given a human pregnancy
test and would have had a Caesarean delivery conducted by the
emergency response team if there had been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   A ``tag team'' system was developed in case one of the doctors
was on vacation during the projected delivery period _ anytime
between July 15 and mid-September. Zoo officials and an outside
veterinarian worked with the team, who ran through emergency
scenarios and got updates on Kiki's condition from the zoo staff,
who were on a rotating 24-hour watch for weeks leading up to the
birth.
</P>
<P>
   Seibel, who worked with the first test-tube human babies born in
Massachusetts, said zoo officials first approached him about six
years ago to help them improve the fertility of their six western
lowland gorillas, an endangered type found in thick jungles in
coastal western Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are in captivity and there is a limited number of male
and female'' gorillas, which leads to a lot of inbreeding. Seibel
said. Zoos across the US share data about the genetic history of
their gorillas in captivity and then loan the animals to each other
so they can reproduce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is exciting and it's extremely interesting,'' Seibel said
of the opportunity he has to volunteer with the zoo. ``I'm learning
about animal behavior and it's a way to get to be a part of the
zoo's health and development.''
</P>
<P>
   Seibel said his colleagues at the fertility center also ``think
it's kinda neat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
