<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2860 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-19 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 IPSWICH, Mass.: ... Old Sturbridge Village.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But his crowning achievement, and the one that kept his Boston
firm solvent through the Depression, was building the gardens and
grounds of Colonial Williamsburg for the Rockefellers. Shurcliff
started with next to nothing and made a re-creation that looked the
way he thought an 18th-century town should look. Which was
tasteful.
</P>
<P>
   So when a genuine 17th-century building (not a reproduction!)
landed just up the road from his summer house, Shurcliff couldn't
resist.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, he presented the historical society with a landscape
design. A few years later, he drew up an even more extravagant plan
to turn the Whipple House into a mini-Williamsburg, complete with
outbuildings _ including a row of slave cabins that would have been
more appropriate for a Southern plantation. (The Whipples of the
17th and 18th centuries owned several slaves, including a native
American, but they lived inside the main house.)
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the society adopted only the basic layout for a
kitchen garden, which includes six raised beds separated by walks
of crushed clamshells. Shurcliff planted them with his favorite
Harrison's yellow roses, which were pretty but wildly out of
period.
</P>
<P>
   Then the house suffered one of its worst episodes. It was found
to have termites, and it was closed for several years during the
last and most damaging of three ``restorations.''
</P>
<P>
   When the house was reopened to visitors in 1955, shortly before
his death, Shurcliff passed the baton to his good friend and
neighbor Isadore Smith, asking her to replant the garden beds
``authentically and symmetrically.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith ran with it, plunging into original research to discover
exactly what herbs housewives grew in the 17th-century Bay Colony,
reading old medical and herbal manuals and wills. In the process,
she became something the property badly needed: a champion for
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   She learned so much that she wrote a book, published in 1970.
``Early American Gardens: For Meate or Medicine'' documented the
plantings of 17th-century housewives' gardens, with herbal dyes and
recipes tested by Smith's friend Elizabeth Foster.
</P>
<P>
   Two more books followed, each covering a different century:
``American Gardens in the Eighteenth Century: For Use or Delight''
in 1976 and ``American Gardens in the Nineteenth Century: For
Comfort and Affluence.'' The first two were published by Houghton
Mifflin. The last was published in 1986, the year after her death,
by the University of Massachusetts Press, which still keeps all
three volumes in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing about (the Whipple garden) is that it
started her writing the first of those three books,'' says garden
historian Ruthanne Rogers, who knew Isadore Smith briefly. ``She
was a very strong-minded woman. We formed a committee to do a
little park garden. I asked her to be a member. Wow! She was very
opinionated! You had to walk carefully around her at times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She wrote standing up, not sitting down,'' recalls her son
Jim. ``She worked on an old-fashioned four-poster bed. She'd have
her old Royal manual typewriter on the bed and pile all her sources
on the bed. And, at night, she'd clean the bed off and go to
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Why did Smith use a pen name? Jim Smith theorizes: ``If your
name is Smith, it's hard to find you in the index. My father was
also a writer, and when I ask my book collector friend to find me
copies of his old novels and tell him my dad's name was A. W.
Smith, well, my friend just grinds his teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Isadore Smith, a.k.a. Ann Leighton, oversaw maintenance of the
Whipple House garden as a collection of 17th-century herbs until
she collapsed, a year before her death, from the effects of Lyme
disease. ``If you're going to do gardening in that part of the
world, you're going to get Lyme disease. It comes with the
territory,'' her son says, matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even after she was moved to Florida to live with
relatives, the enfeebled author continued to write. ``She didn't
have the strength to push the keys on her old Royal. So she bought
a laptop computer and learned how to use it, at age 84, so she
could write until she died,'' says her son.
</P>
<P>
   Today the Whipple House garden is maintained by a dedicated crew
of volunteers, many of whom used to pull weeds alongside Isadore
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   But the Leighton books are far better known and more influential
than the actual garden, according to some historians. And through
the books, the house that suffered so many historical indignities
has, with a measure of poetic justice, helped other historic
properties to enjoy more tender treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those books are fabulous. I use them all the time,'' says
Betsy Igleheart, director of landscapes for the Society for the
Preservation of New England Antiquities. ``I also refer people to
them when they call and say they have an early house and ask what
to plant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isadore Smith is recognized as an important figure in garden
history today. Her 19th-century book was her best book,'' Rogers
says, adding, ``I've used all of them, and every garden historian
has.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Ann Leighton trilogy is for sale at the Whipple House, One
South Village Green, Ipswich, Mass., just off Route 1A. Guided $7
house tours are held on the hour, Wednesday through Saturday 10
a.m. to 3 p.m., Sunday 1 to 3 p.m., and include the 1800 John Heard
House across the street, with its collection of 19th- and
20th-century artifacts. Among events marking the house's centennial
will be an end-of-summer seafood and chicken cookout to raise money
for house repairs Sept. 11, 5-9 p.m. Tickets are $30 in advance.
For more information, call the Ipswich Historical Society at
978-356-2811.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT'S IN THE WHIPPLE GARDEN &QL; 
(A partial list) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ajuga, angelica, balm, bedstraw, betony, borage, bouncing Bet,
bugloss, burnet, chamomile, catmint, chives, clary, columbine,
comfrey, dandelion, doves dung, maidenhair fern, fennel, feverfew,
yellow flag, flax, hollyhock, hyssop, lavender, lavender cotton,
lily, lily of the valley, liveforever, lovage, lungwort, mallow,
marigold, marjoram, mint, monkshood, parsley, peony, sweet rocket,
rosemary, roses, rue, sage, Saint Johnswort, summer savory,
Solomon's seal, strawberry, sunflower, tansy, tarragon, teasel,
thyme, tobacco, valerian, violets, yarrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
