<HEADLINE>
``I'M JUST THE SAME OLD, SAME OLD'': CHER BELIEVES IN LIFE AFTER
50 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;     Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Cher in HBO
Special ``Cher: Live in Concert.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    She's the queen of re-invention.
 &HT;    Just when you think she's finished, she bounces back.
 &HT;    Now, in the summer of '99, she's more popular than ever, with an
eye-popping live show that's receiving the reviews of a lifetime.
 &HT;    The Washington Post calls her ``the eternal diva'' whose
extravagant tour appearances are filled with ``glitz and glamor the
likes of which we seldom see anymore.''
 &HT;    Her enormously popular single ``Believe'' has been called a
masterpiece of technopop and became her biggest hit in a
four-decades-long recording career.
 &HT;    As she sweeps her way through the United States and on to
Britain in the fall, television viewers will see the full extent of
Cher's top-this theatrics on her HBO special airing on Aug. 29.
 &HT;    And while she seems to enjoy the almost universal acclaim, Cher
says the pernennial stories about an eternally reincarnated disco
queen are just good press.
 &HT;    ``I'm just the same old, same old,'' she says. ``I always laugh
when people say I'm reinventing myself. It's just a matter of being
popular or not popular.
 &HT;    ``And every time I've had a time of not being popular and then
being popular again, people say I've reinvented myself ... To tell
you the truth I'm pretty much the same person I've always been, and
I'm doing pretty much the same things.''
 &HT;    In truth, Cher has enjoyed more comebacks than Bill Clinton.
 &HT;    She's gone from pop to disco and back, from network icon to
movie star.
 &HT;    Her highly respected work alongside Meryl Streep in ``Silkwood''
(l983) was followed up by her portrayal of a biker mother in
``Mask'' (1985), which in turn led to her role as a lawyer in the
thriller ``Suspect'' (l987).
 &HT;    In 1987 she won an Academy Award for her work in the bittersweet
comedy ``Moonstruck.''
 &HT;    And in between, she's made a fortune starring in hair product
infomercials, squeezed in some Las Vegas-style nightclub dates and
played the trashy rocker in concert.
 &HT;    ``I do what's in front of me at the moment,'' she says
defiantly, looking trim and wearing an eye-straining, plum-colored
wig in a satellite interview from New York.
 &HT;    ``This is my work and all facets of it are the things that I do
best, things I've done all my life. So at the same time, I have my
tour and my new movie `Tea with Mussolini' (a Franco Zeffirelli
film in which she plays a free-spirited art collector in the
1930s.)
 &HT;    ``I'm an artist. This is just what I do and I don't care how
it's wrapped or when it comes out,'' Cher says.
 &HT;    Dressed in a 1930's designer suit and coiffed to perfection as a
grande dame, she certainly looks re-invented. At 53, she's had
extensive plastic surgery and appears to have recaptured the
fountain of youth.
 &HT;    She has announced that she is celibate after a string of very
public relationships with younger men, personal choices that she
admits have been less successful than her professional ones.
 &HT;    ``Look, I don't do real life so well. But I don't believe an
artist's life is supposed to go smoothly. It's only after years
after you're dead that your life makes any sense or has any real
meaning,'' Cher says.
 &HT;    ``My life is not smooth or neat and tidy. I don't care about
that kind of stuff.''
 &HT;    From the 1960's ``I Got You Babe'' (a duet with her late
ex-husband Sonny Bono) to ``Half Breed'' and ``Dark Lady'' in the
1970s, from the 1980s' ``If I could Turn Back Time'' to this
spring's lavish ``Believe,'' Cher is the only female singer to have
enjoyed a top ten hit in each of the last four decades.
 &HT;    And she's still wowing them on the concert circuit, where each
show features eight costume and wig changes, three video film
retrospectives, flying acrobats, a man on stilts, a huge inflatable
lava lamp ... and Cher's exhausting workout.
 &HT;    ``For me every night it's aerobics for an hour and a half.
Because you can sing and stand or you can run around, but you mix
the two together and it's really a brand new experience.''
 &HT;    ``The older you get, the harder it is,'' she adds. ``But I'm in
really good shape just having to get out there every night.''
 &HT;    There are few 53-year-olds in tights doing what Cher does
nightly on the concert circuit, but the veteran performer says
she's not ready to slow down yet.
 &HT;    She wants to do Broadway, she wants to direct ...
 &HT;    ``And don't ever try to count me out,'' Cher says. ``I'm not
finished yet.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE FOR NYKTIMES SYNDICATE SALES:
 &HT;    Concert dates for Cher shows: Aug. 21: The Pond, Anaheim Aug.
24: Cox Arena, San Diego Aug. 28/29: MGM Grand, Las Vegas Sept. 1:
The World, Chicago Sept. 2: Kiel Center, St. Louis Sept. 4: First
Star Music Center, Cincinatti Sept. 10/11: The Palace of Auburn
Hills, Detroit Sept. 12: Deer Creek, Indianapolis Sept. 20: The
Mark, Moline, Ill.
 &HT;     c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Cher's special, consult
www.hboc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York Times
Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Hollywood Stars and other features. &QL; 
