<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S SOCCER STARS JOIN ELITE CEREAL THRILLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One man's breakfast of champions is another's breakfast of
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Making it onto the front of the Wheaties box is as much a part
of media-age folklore as adorning the cover of Time, being chatted
up by Barbara Walters, or, for that matter, showing up at the post
office on an FBI most-wanted poster.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, General Mills announced that five members of the 1999
US women's soccer team will each be appearing on special-edition
boxes of the breakfast cereal.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Akers, Brandi Chastain, Mia Hamm, Kristine Lilly, and
Briana Scurry join a select company of athletes who since 1958 have
found their faces on the famous orange box.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to regional editions and such promotional gambits as
``Search for Champions'' boxes, some of the Wheaties elect aren't
exactly household names. Still, just as much as Joe Montana and
Babe Ruth, Peter Gagarin and John Lugbill have a place in what
might be described as the breakfast nook in America's favorite hall
of fame.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHO'S BEEN THERE &QL; 
 &QL; 
