<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK ISN'T CHEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not exactly sticker shock. But Talk isn't so cheap anymore.
Having debuted with a newsstand price of $2.95, Tina Brown's hot
new chronicle of the cultural zeitgeist is shattering the record
for the quickest price hike in publishing history. When the second
issue of Talk magazine hits the stands in mid-September, readers
will have to cough up $3.50. The early buzz on the magazine _
generated largely by Hillary Rodham Clinton's remarks about her
husband's philandering _ convinced Talk to print an additional
300,000 copies and is probably responsible for the price inflation.
Says Talk spokeswoman Hillary Bass: ``We think the marketplace can
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For an operation that's been criticized for bureaucratic inertia
_ and been the subject of incessant rumors that it is looking to
unload its 105 local newspapers _ Fidelity's Community Newspaper
Company is about to unveil a dramatic move. Starting the first week
in October, all of the group's 76 tabloid publications will be
transformed into broadsheets, including the 20-year-old chain of
Tab newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The idea _ which has been test marketed to numerous focus groups
_ is ``to provide a better package for the readers and
advertisers,'' says the company's editor and vice chairwoman Mary
Jo Meisner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Readers responded very favorably to the broadsheet prototypes
we've established,'' adds president Kirk Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Community Newspaper Company executives point out that they are
not trying to change the character of their local publications. But
they do say the broadsheet format will allow for better design,
organization, graphics, and sectioning. And the new unified format
will allow for more standardized and improved ad placement and ``be
much easier to sell to advertisers,'' says Davis. In addition, the
broadsheets will each contain a separate ``Community Classified''
section. (Skeptics could wonder whether this might make it easier
to sell the Community Newspaper Company empire in a single package
since a buyer would no longer be getting a hodgepodge of formats
and the accompanying corporate identity and advertising problems.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the trickiest transformation will involve the 16 weekly
Tab newspapers. Given that the chain originally derived its name
from its tabloid format, will the new full-sized papers now be
called the ``Broads?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've kind of joked about that,'' says Meisner. But given that
focus groups revealed that readers considered the Tab a newspaper
``brand'' rather than shorthand terminology for its size, no name
change is planned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You might imagine that a newspaper that has redivided its
newsroom into journalistic teams called ``neighborhoods'' would
literally chase its reporters into the neighborhoods. Beginning
this week, reporters at The Orange County (Calif.) Register are
being handed their Toshiba laptop computers and told to take it to
the streets.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of a Register effort to base its reporting resources
in the community and provide the technology to routinely produce
stories from there. The laptops ``are meant to allow people to move
into the community,'' says executive editor Ken Brusic. When asked
if this plan will eventually render the newsroom obsolete, Brusic
says, ``I don't know . . . we're planning for people to have work
stations. But the idea is once you're on the network . . . you can
do all the things you normally could do at what you think of as
your work station.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispersing of reporters outside the office is beginning with
business staffers, a department that ``has a history of being
guinea pigs'' at the paper, Brusic says. ``I saw a couple of them
last night carrying their little laptops with them. They were a
little confused.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Go Net, young man. That's the advice for journalism students in
the wake of the University of Georgia's Annual Survey of Journalism
and Mass Communications Graduates. The study of about 2,400
students found that the median salary for bachelor degree
recipients who took jobs in Web publishing was $30,000 _ $6,000
higher than the median salary for all journalism and communication
school graduates. (This less than overwhelming remuneration may
explain why only 20 percent of the graduates expected to stay in
the information business.)
</P>
<P>
   According to survey director, professor Lee Becker, nearly 60
percent of J-schools now provide specific courses in on-line
journalism. ``Students come into the classes pretty much demanding
some (on-line) awareness,'' he adds. ``And I think the salary tells
you why.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In her first published piece since she resigned from The Boston
Globe after fabricating characters and quotes in her column,
Patricia Smith expounds on that bitter experience and her
subsequent battle for redemption in the September issue of Essence
Magazine. Typical of Smith's work, ``Journey Back From Shame'' is a
powerful story certain to provoke responses ranging from outrage to
sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   In tone, the article is eerily familiar to the farewell column
she penned to Globe readers in June 1998. It begins with
confession. (``I'd created them (the false characters), lied about
their lives . . . Of course, I had to be fired.'') And it moves
into anger. (``For the time, it seemed the world was obsessed with
me, addicted to the mechanics of my destruction. No one would just
let me go and be gone.'')
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
