<HEADER>
A2870 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     08-19 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S JUST NO ACCOUNTING FOR BRUINS' DELAY ON DAFOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- There is a huge difference between a cheap date and a
stingy one. Cheap Date: You're being treated to an all-you-can-eat,
$3.95 buffet dinner. Stingy Date: You might actually make it to an
upscale restaurant, but your date will constantly remind you of the
hard work it took to afford a night out like this.
</P>
<P>
   So where does that leave the Bruins?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not cheap,'' Harry Sinden says, ``we're responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that depends on whom we're discussing. The Bruins were
certainly not being cheap this week when they elected to cut Dmitri
Khristich instead of paying him $2.8 million. ``Players always say
it's not about the money,'' Sinden, the team's president, said.
``Do I get the chance to say that now about this case? It was the
principle of the thing. We didn't think he was worth the money
($1.95 million) he made last year.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, we'll give him that. Khristich may have been the
team's top goal scorer, but he was soft in the playoffs. He played
timidly in the corners, as if he expected to see a mouse once he
got to them. I don't think Khristich will come back to haunt the
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   But I wonder if the Bruins are trying to save a few dimes by not
picking up the phone and making a local call. It's been a month
since they last talked contract with Byron Dafoe. They said what
all dates say _ ``I'll call you'' _ and didn't follow up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent talked to them on July 16,'' Dafoe said. ``We haven't
heard from them since. I'm waiting to hear from them.''
</P>
<P>
   If you care about the Bruins, the month-long silence between the
team and its top goaltender should make you nervous. Training camp
begins in two weeks. Dafoe is a restricted free agent without a
contract. Sinden was asked if he expects any problems in his
negotiations with Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said Wednesday. ``His demands and our proposal are
far apart. Usually that spells trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where the cheap/stingy line becomes blurry. Dafoe won 32
games last season and had a goals-against average of 1.99. He says
he has no desire to be paid as well as Dominik Hasek, who bounced
pucks off his head last season as if he were Briana Scurry on ice.
The Bruins want to pay Dafoe about $3 million a year for three
seasons. Dafoe wants somewhere around $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm being fair,'' Dafoe said. ``I'm not comparing
myself to the top guys in the league, like Hasek and (Curtis)
Joseph. I don't want $6 million a year. I'm restricted, so I
realize that this isn't going to be my big payday. That will come
when I'm unrestricted.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said he hasn't thought of leaving Boston. He is one of the
most productive and popular athletes in town. But, he was asked, is
his employer cheap?
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston has a reputation among other players,'' he said. ``Guys
talk about it. But there is also a history of competitive and
winning teams here.'' He paused and said, ``Was that a politically
correct answer?''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the Bruins have good reason to be so obsessive
about their budget. The NHL recently signed the richest television
contract in the history of the league. The Bruins' share, about $4
million, is only enough to cover the contract of Dafoe. Sinden
calls the NHL ``a gate-receipt league,'' which partially explains
why the team's least-expensive ticket is $20 and its priciest is
$77.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any TV income,'' Sinden said. ``That's a fact.''
</P>
<P>
   But if team owner Jeremy Jacobs and Sinden truly want to win the
Cup, they are going to have to make a sacrifice. They have made
money for years with the Bruins. Now they are going to have to give
some back. They are going to have to lose a little if they want to
win. If that means paying Dafoe $500,000-$800,000 more than they
want to, they'll have to do it. The alternative is a holdout.
</P>
<P>
   Think of how the Kyle McLaren and Anson Carter holdouts affected
the team last season. The Bruins began the season with a 4-6-2
record; they ended with a 8-3-2 flourish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure makes life easier when we're all there at the start of
camp,'' Dafoe said.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Bruins aren't exactly cheap. Ray Bourque is one of the
highest-paid defensemen in the league. And Joe Thornton and Sergei
Samsonov were given fair rookie contracts in 1997. Are the Bruins
stingy? Yes. Sinden is not ashamed to tell you how difficult it is
to make money in the NHL, the same league in which the Colorado
Avalanche nearly went bankrupt in their pursuit of the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough position,'' Sinden said. ``You're trying to
manage a team and make a business out of it. We want to win, but we
don't want to lose (money).''
</P>
<P>
   That position will have to change soon. If it doesn't change
this offseason with Dafoe, it will change when Thornton and
Samsonov go to the restricted free agency land where Dafoe now
waits. You can present the NHL version of your Stop &AMP; Shop card,
save a few dollars, and make it to the playoffs. But you can't do
that and win a Cup. And you can't win a Cup without a good
goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here,'' Dafoe said, ``but my phone hasn't been
ringing.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an obvious compromise to all of this. The Bruins can
call Dafoe _ collect _ and announce that they are going to give him
the contract he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
