<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-AUGUST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNING THE VACATION GARDEN, TASTING TOMATOES, SAVING TREES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The garden dreams of May have become the happy or sad realities
of August. Each year is different, and each individual plant has
either a year of exuberant extravagance or a year of shame and
sadness. It all depends on the weather and how a garden is
designed. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vacation home gardens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People with second homes like to fuss with their vacation
gardens. It's always amazing how city folks, even apartment
dwellers, come alive as gardeners when they go to their familiar
summer spot.
</P>
<P>
   However, this back-to-nature mentality shouldn't become just
another chore. Vacation home gardens need to be carefully planned
for low maintenance and to flower during the months one is likely
to be in residence. And the plants should survive neglect because
you're not always there to baby them.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most perennials are very high maintenance and are
finished blooming by mid-July or don't really start until late
August. Summer folks want plants that bloom during summer.
</P>
<P>
   To find those that survive neglect, look for ones that return
each year, then divide them and spread them around. Some good
candidates are hosta, especially H. grandiflora, which has fragrant
white blooms during August. Old-fashioned phlox is another
candidate, which will self-seed if you leave things a little messy
underneath. Oenothera, also called sundrops, is a tough July
blooming survivor.
</P>
<P>
   Late-blooming day lilies as well as the really tough
old-fashioned orange one (that blooms in July) will fill big spaces
with flowers and foliage. When flowering becomes sparse, the
foliage is useful as a ground cover. Or to get more blooms, dig up
the bed, divide them, fertilize the soil, and replant (in August).
It's a lot of work, so you may mean to do it but not actually get
around to it. A shortcut is to apply some liquid fertilizer and
hope they'll flower more.
</P>
<P>
   Ferns give that rustic look we all think of when, in our mind's
eye, we picture Cape Cod, Maine, or the islands. Hay-scented fern,
which grows in sun or shade, may be planted along the foundation or
lining paths. Easily divided, it's a tough survivor once
established.
</P>
<P>
   Summer-flowering bushes are useful, too, particularly hydrangea
and althea (also called rose of Sharon). Old-fashioned varieties of
althea can make a nice tall, unpruned summer hedge between two
properties or to screen a bad view.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent plantings such as these will provide a basic
landscape. Then, when you arrive for the season, buy some annuals
already grown to a good size by the nursery. Maybe throw in some
tomatoes. If the annuals die, just buy a few more.
</P>
<P>
   If you simply must have roses by the sea, pick vigorous ones
like `Bonica,' `Betty Prior,' `The Fairy,' `Carefree Beauty,' and
tall-growing `New Dawn.' They need sun, fertilizer, and some
pruning. Next spring, replace those that don't survive.
</P>
<P>
   In summer the living should be easy and laid back. One doesn't
need another house with a compulsive maintenance schedule.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
Threatened trees &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because of the severe drought, plus the coming hurricane season,
it's worth giving some thought to tree preservation. First and
easiest, give the roots a good, deep soaking, and I do mean good
and deep. If you have no town water restrictions, put the hose on a
good drip and let it soak into the root system overnight. One good
August watering will really help tree health and long-term
survival.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service is predicting several severe storms
this season. A full head of thick leaves acts like a sail and
catches the wind, which can break branches or blow over the tree.
However, if strong winds can blow through the leaves, the tree is
less likely to be toppled.
</P>
<P>
   Call an arborist to check your trees and to ``open the crown''
for safety. This means some of the branches will be removed so you
can see through (and the wind can blow through). Tree pruning is
expensive, so if you can only afford to do a few you may need to
prioritize. Choose your favorite specimen trees and those that
might fall on your house. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Ruth S. Foster has been a landscape consultant in the Boston area
for many years and has written numerous articles on gardening in
New England.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
