<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2875 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      08-19 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONSIDER A PATIO INSTEAD OF A DECK FOR OUTDOOR LIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The patio, a paved, ground-level place for outdoor living, has
yielded to the raised wooden deck as the playpen and dining room of
backyard America.
</P>
<P>
   Decks are cleaner and neater, and being at floor level of the
house, more convenient than a patio. At least that is the claim of
the deck people.
</P>
<P>
   But decks are not the be-all and end-all for backyard living,
say the patio people. Decks get dirty; they might splinter and
sometimes decay; and with all the fancy treatments that don't last
more than a year or so, their claim to low maintenance is
ridiculous. &QL; 
 &QL; 
No maintenance &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, reconsider the patio. It may be on ground level and a bit
inconvenient to get to, but once it is in, it needs no maintenance,
except an occasional sweeping or hosing off of leaves and yard
detritus. There is no need to seal it, paint it, stain it, or
fiddle with it in any other way. Oh, it might get dirty, but it can
be pressure-washed when you feel like it.
</P>
<P>
   OK, what shall we pave the patio with?
</P>
<P>
   Popular for patios is any kind of paving material set in sand or
stone dust: flagstone and slate are nice but difficult to set
because their shapes are irregular, creating wide joints.
</P>
<P>
   Patio blocks of concrete in various shapes and sizes are easy to
lay in sand but quite ordinary, and their large size makes them
unstable in sand.
</P>
<P>
   A good cover is paving stones, blocks of cut granite usually
rescued from very old city streets. They are excellent, but
expensive, and they look old. Also, there are concrete pavers, not
made of regular concrete that doesn't last very long, but of
pressurized concrete, making them last as long as a hard brick.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete pavers of the hard type are shaped like bricks and
tiles. There are many colors and styles to choose from, all easily
set in sand or stone dust. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Try for hard brick &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That leaves bricks as the pavement of choice. If you opt for
brick, make sure it is a hard brick. Avoid the ``antique,''
salmon-colroed bricks, usually from old houses. They will
deteriorate in months.
</P>
<P>
   The pavement of choice is brick, give or take an opinion or two,
and the brick of choice is City Hall Pavers, a very hard, molded
brick that is not quite even in shape. At about 50 cents each, they
are more expensive than other hard bricks because they are molded
in the old-fashioned way, a technique that increases their cost.
Less costly hard bricks are cut.
</P>
<P>
   They could last forever, or maybe 100, or 1,000 years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good for do-it-yourselfers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A good thing about bricks and other small pavers is that they
are not only relatively inexpensive, but also can be installed,
single-handedly, by even the greenest handyman.
</P>
<P>
   All he needs is sand, lots and lots of bricks (there are five
standard-sized bricks to the square foot), a tamper, a
rubber-headed mallet for tamping bricks, a string, a straight edge,
a level (a four-footer is better and more accurate than a
two-footer), and brick chisels for cutting brick.
</P>
<P>
   And, a lot of time and energy. Building a patio of brick is hard
work, but the rewards are worth all that sweat equity.
</P>
<P>
   It takes five bricks for each square foot. To figure how many
bricks you need, determine the area of the patio, say 20 by 20
feet, or 400 square feet, and multiply 5 by 400 to get 2,000
bricks. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A simple underlayment &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crushed stone and sand for the patio base is sold by the scoop
or by the cubic yard.
</P>
<P>
   How much base material you need depends on how deep you make it.
Instead of trying to figure out exactly how much you need, order a
scoop or two. If you run out, you can always order more.
</P>
<P>
   Stone dust, by the way, can be substituted for sand. It is an
excellent base because it packs down readily. One problem is that
it is difficult to sweep into a tight joint because it becomes
rather pebbly as it is swept. It is a minor problem.
</P>
<P>
   Now you're ready to start. Outline the patio area with little
fences of string on stakes. If the area is curved, outline it with
a garden hose. If you want the patio to be flush with the ground,
dig out earth deep enough to accommodate the thickness of the
brick, about 2 inches, and the thickness of the base material, 2 to
6 inches.
</P>
<P>
   There are two recommended bases for a brick patio: 2 inches of
sand or stone dust, or 4 inches of crushed stone topped by 1 or 2
inches of sand or stone dust. The latter is slightly better because
the crushed stone allows for good drainage under the patio;
drainage will keep water from under the brick that would otherwise
freeze in winter and heave the bricks out of position. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Borders needed &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether the patio is flush with the ground or not, you will
still need to put in a border of some kind after excavating.
Without a border, bricks will tend to ``walk'' over time,
separating and getting all out of skew.
</P>
<P>
   For a flush patio, use soldier bricks, bricks set lengthwise
into the earth, or 8- by 16-inch concrete patio blocks on their
long edge, or pressure-treated timbers.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a homeowner will raise his patio to help distinguish
it from the rest of the yard. It also might be to be level over
uneven ground. You might also want to raise a patio to avoid
cutting and digging into tree roots close to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   If you are raising the patio just a few inches, the border must
be deep enough to hold the bricks in place without leaning over
from the pressure of the bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure-treated timbers are a good choice for such a raised
border.
</P>
<P>
   Now you can set in the crushed stone and sand topper, tamp it
thoroughly and smooth it out. Rent a plate tamper, or, simpy walk
over the stone and sand until it is as tamped as it will ever get. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Finally, the laying of the brick &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smooth out the tamped sand and start laying the bricks. The
easiest pattern is a common or running bond, each row of bricks
offsetting its neighbor by a half-lap.
</P>
<P>
   Others are also attractive, as illustrated, but with more
elaborate designs, more cutting is needed.
</P>
<P>
   To cut a brick, score it at the proper place with a cold chisel,
chip the score mark a little deeper with the chisel, then set a
wide chisel on the mark and whack it with a hammer. You will
succeed maybe 90 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Set a brick in a corner, tap it lightly with the rubber mallet
or the handle of a mason's hammer to set it in the sand, making
sure its top is level with the border. Set the bricks so they are
touching each other, creating a minimal joint.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to line up bricks with a border, but when you get into
the interior, you have to line them up with each other. It is easy
to go astray.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent uneven bricks, stretch a taut string along the length
of the patio from border to border, at the level of the tops of the
bricks.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a good guide, but be careful that you don't raise
the string as you place the brick. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Straight edge to the rescue &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A straight edge will help keep bricks even with each other.
</P>
<P>
   If the patio is next to the house, you must slope it so water
will drain away from the house. While water will soak through the
brick joints, the sloping patio will handle a lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   So, put a straight edge on the bricks as you continue to set
them. And, put the edge at right angles to the brick rows.
</P>
<P>
   If you see a gap in the middle of the straight edge, the bricks
are too low in that area. Take them up, add a little stand, and
relay them. If the straight edge rocks on the bricks, the middle
bricks are too high; take them up, take a bit of the sand away,
resmooth the sand, and relay the bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sweep dry sand into the joints between the bricks. Wet down
the patio with a fine spray from the hose. After a day or so, sweep
in more sand. Eventually there will be enough sand to fill the
joints and stabilize the bricks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, enjoy that tall, cool drink on your new patio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
