<HEADER>
A2881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CALIF-HMOs-HNS &LR;      08-19 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-HMOs-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR UNVEILS PLAN TO OVERHAUL MANAGED CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Gray Davis, proposing an overhaul of
managed health care in the waning days of the state legislative
session, is calling for a new system that includes second opinions
from doctors, a state agency to review disputed medical decisions
and the right to sue if something goes seriously wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But with just three weeks left in the session, dozens of
questions remain unanswered by the governor's office, such as how
much the system would cost taxpayers and managed care providers,
and whether health plans would be forced to pay for medical
treatments that currently are not covered.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, met privately with angry Democratic lawmakers
on Tuesday to make peace over his recent comment that their job was
to ``implement my vision.'' At the same time, however, he was
unveiling a rough draft of his vision for changes.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Wednesday was important because it gives
lawmakers and the public their first glimpse from Davis about what
he wants in the way of overhauling managed care. Armed with polls
showing little public support for major changes, the governor only
recently got around to making the issue a priority.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats were elated at the proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this plan is ambitious and bold, and consumers are big
winners,'' said state Sen. Jackie Speier of Daly City.
</P>
<P>
   Davis administration officials said the plan was not the final
word on managed care. His staff has been meeting with consumer
groups, lawyers, lawmakers and representatives of the managed care
industry, which recently gave the governor more than $100,000 at a
political fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, as outlined Wednesday, would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Create a new state review process if someone is denied
treatment by a managed care provider, known in the industry as
health maintenance organizations, or HMOs. The service would be
free, and managed care providers would be subject to $5,000-per-day
penalties for non-compliance with the panel's ultimate order for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Managed care providers would be required to tell patients
within five days if they are denied coverage for something. There
are no time limits now. If coverage is denied, the state review
panel would be required to make a decision in 30 days or less.
Emergency medical cases would be expedited.
</P>
<P>
   _ Create a new consumer advocate to represent the 17 million
Californians under managed health care. A new department would be
created with added enforcement powers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Allow patients the right to a second opinion and the right to
sue providers for harm caused by ``denying, delaying or modifying''
a doctor's recommendation. Patients, however, could sue only if
there were also ``substantial physical harm, such as death, loss of
limb or bodily functions.''
</P>
<P>
   This section is certain to cause the most problems in all
segments of the health care debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan looks like it was drafted behind closed doors with
HMO executives and no patients, doctors or nurses present,''
consumer lobbyist Jaime Court said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Zelman, president of the California Association of Health
Plans, said he was concerned about this section but noted
restrictions would be placed on who got to sue and when.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis administration said this section was balanced between
the two forces.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Kennedy, the governor's cabinet secretary, said ``the
concept is to have a high threshold of harm (before someone can
sue). The purpose is to get treatment. ... We just don't think
litigation is the answer to our health care system.''
</P>
<P>
   With little time left in the session, which must end Sept. 10,
Senate President pro tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, said it
might be too late to figure out what Davis really wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said he might just send the governor reforms that
Democrats had been working on for years, and see what he would do
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Those may include items Davis has not yet asked for, such as
requiring managed care providers to pay for mental health drugs,
diabetes medicine and contraceptives. Davis' staff said such
mandates remained under discussion and that the entire reform
package was a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who has represented Davis in health care discussions
with lawmakers, said the governor and his staff had not yet taken a
position on mandates. She said that mandatory coverage of
contraceptives, for example, appeared to be a ``no-brainer'' but
the administration wanted to be careful before mandating any
coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
