<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2883 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-19 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST ARE TOO GOOD TO BE TRUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many, many times over the years I've received letters, phone
calls, e-mails recounting the $250 Nieman Marcus/Mrs.
Fields/Marshall Fields cookie recipe story. Each person has told
the story with fresh enthusiasm, and each has suggested that it
would be a good subject for a column.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good story, so good it falls under the heading ``Too
Good To Be True,'' which is the title of Jan Harold Brunvand's most
recent book, subtitled ``The Colossal Book of Urban Legends''
(Norton, $29.95). Brunvand, professor emeritus at the University Of
Utah, has spent years collecting and writing about these tales, and
attempting to track them to their sources. Some have ancient roots,
back to the Middle Ages and perhaps even beyond. Others are as new
as ``The Blair Witch Project.'' But they all have one thing in
common, they're too good to be true, and thus irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   The cookie story has varied slightly in the telling, but the
most popular version has a shopper enthusing about a special cookie
served at the Neiman-Marcus Cafe in Dallas. She asks for the recipe
and is told that it costs ``two-fifty.'' Some time later her credit
card statement arrives, and she finds she has been charged $250.
</P>
<P>
   This story, cookie recipe appended, has been widely circulated
for years via chain letter and more recently on the Internet. It
refuses to die, no matter how many times it's debunked, because
it's a good story, and the recipe, while perhaps not worth $250, is
a winner. You can't keep a good urban legend down. Any minute now I
expect to hear from someone who'll say, ``But it really happened,
to a friend of a friend of my mother's . . .'' (The ``friend of a
friend,'' FOAF to folklore scholars, plays a crucial role in the
spread of urban legends.)
</P>
<P>
   Brunvand traced the cookie story back to prototypes in the
1940s, when it featured expensive recipes for candy, fudge, ice
cream, or cake. He thinks its longevity is rooted in our mistrust
of big business, a mistrust that has fueled the spread of other
familiar urban legends about fast-food fried rodents and
worm-burgers and satanic symbols in company logos.
</P>
<P>
   Urban legends are woven into popular culture. They turn up on
television, in movies, fiction, songs, comics, supermarket
tabloids, newspapers. The Internet has speeded their progress and
broadened their range. According to Brunvand, the stories have also
been a source of fascination, and material, for writers such as
Gabriel Garcia Marquez, Carson McCullers, John Steinbeck, Truman
Capote, and Toni Morrison.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than 200 urban legends in ``Too Good To Be
True'' are so familiar that just a few words suffice to evoke the
entire story. ``The Killer in the Back Seat.'' ``The Choking
Doberman.'' ``Alligators in the Sewers.'' ``The Kidney Heist.''
``Spiders in the Hairdo.'' These, and so many others, are
appealingly weird, which accounts in part for their appeal. They're
also neatly plotted, too neatly plotted, Brunvand observes. That
concision is one of the earmarks of an urban legend.
</P>
<P>
   If a story seems too good to be true, probably it's exactly
that. But there are exceptions, as Brunvand notes. ``The Baby on
the Roof'' is one. A parent leaves a baby in a car seat on the car
roof and drives away. The baby flies off the car, but is uninjured.
This is no legend, unfortunately. Most of us have seen it in the
news at least once. ``The Pregnant Shoplifter'' is in the same
category. In 1985, the Washington Post reported that an employee in
an Arlington, Va., sporting goods store forced a pregnant woman to
prove she wasn't shoplifting a basketball. She sued the store for
punitive damages. She lost. That's how you can tell it's not an
urban legend. If it were, she would have won.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
