<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALING WITH MOSS ON THE ROOF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I had to scrape moss from the asphalt-shingle roof of my
summer place in New Hampshire. It was 1/4-inch thick and came off
easily enough, but I am afraid I'll damage the shingles. Is there
an easier way to take it off, and keep it off?
</P>
<P>
   BARRY SIMPSON, Warren, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   A. You did the right thing in scraping the moss off, because it
is relatively easy to get off. You might also sweep it off with a
large push broom. After you remove it, treat the area with a
solution of 1 part household bleach and 3 parts water. This will
kill any residual roots or moss, but it won't do much in keeping it
from coming back, sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   However, while looking desperately in catalogs for an item he
did not find, the handyman came across this product: Moss and
Mildew Killer in the Improvements catalog. The blurb says it will
not harm plants, so it is probably not bleach, and inhibits growth
for a year. Anyway, it is item 174129, $12.99 for 1 1/2 pounds of
powder concentrate that treats up to 1,500 square feet. It may be
worth a call, 800-642-2112.
</P>
<P>
   While the Improvements catalog carries interesting and useful
things (if they work), one still has to approach such catalogs with
a grain of salt.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing that will inhibit the growth of moss, as well as
mildew and algae, is a zinc strip called Shingle Shield, sold in
hardware and lumber stores and home centers. It is a strip of zinc
that is tucked under the shingles of a roof, near the ridge,
leaving a few inches of the zinc exposed. Rainwater washes over the
zinc, distributing traces over the entire roof and deterring the
growth of any fungus or green plant.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find Shingle Shield, call the maker, Chicago
Metallic, at 800-638-5192. Another brand is Z-Stop, by WESPAC of
Seattle, Wash., 206-244-4013.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My pressure-treated deck was painted, and I would like to
stain it. How can I get the old paint off? How can I treat the ends
of the boards, where it is difficult to get off any paint?
</P>
<P>
   CARL DETTMAN, West Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Chemical paint remover will do it fast and safely. You could
use regular remover such as Stripeeze or 5F5. Or, a milder one that
may take more work to remove the paint: Citristrip.
</P>
<P>
   Also safe, if you do not char the wood, is a hot-air gun. But
since such a gun fires a stream of air heated to between 700 and
1,000 degrees, and wood burns at about 500 degrees, you want to be
extremely careful to guard against fire and also against charring
of the wood, because burning pressure-treated wood is the fastest
way to release arsenic, one of the chemicals used in the treatment.
The nice thing about a hot-air gun is that when you scrape off the
softened paint and remove the heat, the scrapings will cool off
quickly and turn crispy, so they can easily be swept up.
</P>
<P>
   Or, sand the paint off. The anti-pressure-treated wood people
will scream at this suggestion, because the sanding dust contains
arsenic. Yes, it does, but if you wear a mask and sweep up the dust
and dispose of it carefully, there will be no harm done. Besides,
there is very little arsenic in the sanding dust.
</P>
<P>
   As for the board ends, leave them painted and let the paint wear
off; or sand to remove the paint. I am not convinced the extra
effort is worth it. And you could paint them to match the stain you
will use and forget about removing the paint. Whatever stain you
plan to use, be sure it is a semitransparent house stain, which
will not peel and will last for three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The grand discussion of the pros and cons of asbestos-cement
siding continues, after initial remarks in the Globe Handyman's
column of July 29. In it, the handyman said there are very few pros
about asbestos siding. In fact, he felt, none.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Gutierrez of Arlington, Mass. called to give us two pros:
1. It holds paint wonderfully and for a long time, longer than
paint lasts on wood. 2. It is fire resistant.
</P>
<P>
   Good point. Paint will stick well to asbestos-cement, because it
is mostly cement (concrete). But it will stick equally well to
mineral siding that does not contain asbestos. But this
stick-to-it-iveness works only if the paint job is right;
basically, thin coats of a latex housepaint are required. The
handyman has seen too many asbestos-cement houses with woefully
peeling paint not to feel strongly about this.
</P>
<P>
   As for being fire resistant, that may be more a con than a pro.
After all, most siding materials are not fire resistant, and while
the United States has a lot of fires, wood structures have stood
the test of time; when they do burn, in the vast majority of cases
firefighters have come through to save houses and lives.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the handyman feels such siding is a liability: Most
fire-resistant materials on houses today are asbestos-cement siding
and aluminum siding. Aluminum siding helps make the house more
airtight, and a fire could gut the inside of such a house much
faster than in a wood-sided house, because the fire is contained in
the house, unable to be vented outdoors. The same goes with
asbestos-cement siding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
