<HEADER>
A2887 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-UNPRIVATE-2TAKES     08-19 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-UNPRIVATE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE WHO LIVE IN GLASS HOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Alex van Es, a systems analyst in the town of
Apeldoorn in the Netherlands, has linked his doorbell,
refrigerator, toilet, alarm clock, and six cameras in his house to
the Internet. The whole world can keep track of him. Visitors to
his Web site can even pick the music that will wake him in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   In the catalog for ``The Un-Private House,'' Museum of Modern
Art curator Terence Riley, who organized the show, offers Van Es as
example of a brave new attitude toward the home. Once a sanctuary,
it is now permeable. Furthermore, both the MoMA exhibition and its
catalog propose this as a good thing. Is Van Es's lifestyle Big
Brotherish? Riley responds that ``in a world of isolation, having
someone watching can be reassuring . . . the interactive gaze of
the media has now come to represent a comforting presence as much
as an intrusive surveillance.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll get to the part about bathrooms anon, but first, the facts.
``The Un-Private House'' documents, through models, photographs,
diagrams, floor plans, and videos, 26 houses all over the world,
all designed in the last decade. Some are undulating curves, inside
and out; others are strictly rectilinear. All are radical not just
in materials and technology, but in rethinking the way we live.
Amazingly, 16 of these extreme schemes have already been built,
while four are under way. Six remain unbuilt, including the ``Slow
House'' Elizabeth Diller and Ricardo Scofidio designed for a Long
Island site with a water view. The cornucopia-shaped structure ``is
conceived as an apparatus for producing a view,'' the architects
write. ``The house is a door that leads to a window, physical entry
to optical departure.'' In front of that window, though, and partly
blocking it, the architects would put a video monitor playing the
same view you'd already be looking at _ two ways of framing the
seascape. (Yes, there are bedrooms tucked in there somewhere, but
they're not the point.)
</P>
<P>
   On my two weekday visits to ``The Un-Private House,'' the place
was packed, and primarily with young people. The installation is
tongue-in-cheek homey, with a bed, sofas, and other domestic
furniture. The centerpiece of the show is a huge round table with
eight ``place settings.'' You pick a coaster from a Lazy Susan in
the center and put it down at your place, and an interactive
``place mat'' about a house appears for you to play with. The
table, and the show's woozy, projected ``Welcome Mat'' that warps
toward any presence it senses _ including yours _ are
collaborations with the MIT Media Lab.
</P>
<P>
   However whimsical the presentation, the show is a serious
reflection on a moment when a quarter of American households
consist of one person, and half the families in the country are
couples without children under the same roof. These demographics
alter the notion of and need for ``privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a relatively recent concept anyway. Through the
Renaissance, even the wealthy inhabited medieval-style communal
halls, where everybody did just about everything, including giving
birth, in view of everybody else. After the 17th century, when
European merchants became wealthy enough to extricate their
businesses from their homes, those homes became havens. In crowded
towns, the row house became the norm, with a common wall separating
the units. Contemporary architects Bjarne Mastenbroek and MVRDV
deliberately skewed the common wall between the two units of their
``Double House'' in Utrecht, the Netherlands, creating a zigzag
shape that encourages neighbors to be aware of each other's
presence on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, Frank Lloyd Wright designed an idealized ``Home in a
Prairie Town'' for Ladies' Home Journal. Set back from the street,
with a recessed entrance, it was a virtual fortress. Privacy was
political and even patriotic for Wright. ``America,'' he wrote,
``places a life premium on individuality. . . . It means lives
lived in greater independence and seclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-century later, the glass house Mies van der Rohe designed
for Edith Farnsworth in Plano, Ill., caused an uproar for its
perceived lack of privacy. But the Farnsworth house was meant for
solo occupation, and it was set in sizable grounds, a buffer from
the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   I've spent several nights alone in a glass house, while on
safari in Africa. It was a fabulously liberating feeling, dancing
around naked, showering in a glass cylinder, with only the wart
hogs to watch. Had the house not been secluded and out of sight of
other tourists, though, the experience could have been embarrassing
rather than exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   The MoMA show attempts to vindicate the glass house and push it
even further, by presenting examples built, or being built, in
crowded urban settings. One is Michael Bell's ``Glass House (at) 2
degrees'' in Houston. The glass house has been associated with
sophistication, even wealth, but Bell's project is low-income,
federally funded housing. He uses standard-size sliding glass doors
to control costs, and rationalizes the increased visibility of the
inhabitants by asking, ``Why should an invisible group of people
choose to live behind walls rather than reveal their lives?''
</P>
<P>
   Only the homeless are more exposed than the occupants of Shigeru
Ban's ``Curtain Wall House'' in Tokyo can be. The house angles into
a street like the prow of a ship; its exterior walls are billowing
white curtains that suggest both sails and a variation on the
traditional shoji screen. When the curtains and sliding glass
panels behind them are opened, the inhabitants live their lives in
public. When the curtains are closed, the windowless house is
mysterious; it looks like a Christo ``wrap.'' At night, it glows
from within.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2891 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-UNPRIVATE-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     08-19 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-UNPRIVATE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... from within.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another Tokyo design, Kazuyo Sejima's and Ryue Nishizawa's ``M
House,'' is more concerned with privacy. Four double-height
interior light wells bring natural light to the underground level
of the house. The only window facing the street is translucent
polycarbonate covered in perforated metal, which lets in light but
deflects prying eyes. The ``M House'' is one of several in the show
that dive underground, acknowledging that we're running out of room
up above. It's quiet and naturally cool down there, and natural
illumination can be provided by digging light wells. In Joel
Sanders's unbuilt ``House for a Bachelor'' in Minneapolis, an
excavated, subterranean, and hence private backyard becomes an
Astroturf-lined exercise area that flows into the master bath,
creating a spa for one.
</P>
<P>
   The most radical of all the plans in the show is the conceptual
``Digital House'' that Gisue and Mojgan Hariri designed for House
Beautiful magazine. It would consist of a central core and plug-in
rooms, factory-delivered, that could be switched as easily as
appliances. Walls would be made of liquid crystal displays capable
of collapsing time and space. ``In the kitchen,'' Riley writes, ``a
virtual chef from a favorite restaurant could aid in the
preparation of meals, and the residents could entertain friends who
live thousands of miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend that separated workplace from home has now reversed,
thanks to computers, and several ``Un-Private'' houses reflect
that. The downtown Manhattan apartment that Frank Lupo and Daniel
Rowen designed for two currency traders on Wall Street has six
strategically placed video monitors _ including one in the bathroom
_ so the couple can keep track of world markets 24 hours a day,
from various vantage points in their open-plan home. The result,
Riley writes, ``is not some sort of mercantile bedlam breaking out
in the living room but the silent flicker of an aestheticized flow
of information.'' ``Aestheticized'' is a key word here. In these
houses, video monitors and computer screens aren't camouflaged in
armoires; they're flaunted as prime parts of the design.
</P>
<P>
   Video-as-art drove Jacques Herzog's and Pierre de Meuron's
design for the ``Kramlich Residence and Media Collection,'' being
built in the Napa Valley. The owners collect in the new world of
electronic art, and their house/gallery will accommodate Gary
Hill's 47-foot video panorama ``Viewer'' and other huge works, some
in a vast underground gallery animated by moving images. Upstairs,
eccentrically curved glass walls will also serve as screens for
video installations, making the place into a veritable museum.
</P>
<P>
   A museum-like feature in some other ``Un-Private'' houses is the
portable wall, standard equipment now in galleries, where it allows
a reconfiguration of space for each show. In a Manhattan loft that
Thomas Hanrahan and Victoria Meyers designed for a single
professional man, full-height painted panels can float
independently in space or come together to form one or two
completely closed-off guest rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The show offers other ingenious solutions to design problems.
One apartment has a partition wall whose center pivots to a
horizontal position, becoming a dining table. Simon Ungers and
Thomas Kinslow solved the storage problem of a writer with 10,000
books with the ``T-House.'' On top of, and perpendicular to, a
long, horizontal residence partly burrowed into the earth, they
built a double-height library. The upper level, shelf storage, has
no windows, in order to protect the books. The lower-level reading
room is filled with light. The monolithic design is pleasing. But
aren't books supposed to be replaced by computer screens soon? Will
that render the library obsolete?
</P>
<P>
   I personally like to read something I can touch, stroke, even
smell, a real book whose pages I can turn, listening to the
crinkling sound they make. And in the age of electronic
surveillance, I want more privacy, not less, more freedom from the
tyranny of the screen. Where I particularly want privacy, and where
I think all but the most exhibitionist would as well, is in the
bathroom. I think the Japanese got it right, with each bathroom
function given its own roomlet, so two or more people can use the
facilities at the same time. I've noticed an increase in this sort
of divvied-up design in hotel rooms of late, enabling two people to
prepare for the day without waiting for each other.
</P>
<P>
   There is an erotic element to bathing and showering, to watching
a partner through the kind of translucent bathroom wall some of the
``Un-Private'' houses boast. But sometimes a bath is just a bath,
and all you want is to get clean. So I draw the line at the forced
voyeurism of a Manhattan pied-a-terre designed by Sulan Kolatan and
William Mac Donald. The master sleeping and bathing area are a
single, seamless sweep of cast fiberglass, quite beautiful as
sculpture. But the horizontal plateau of the bed is separated from
the dip of the tub only by a sheet of clear glass. Just give me a
solid door that closes, please.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(``The Un-Private House,'' organized by Terence Riley, is at the
Museum of Modern Art in New York City through Oct. 5. The museum's
Web site has a subsite devoted to the show. Visit it at
www.moma.org/exhibitions/un-privatehouse/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
