<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2892 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2TAKES-     08-19 1303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD GARDEN'S MODERN CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IPSWICH, Mass. _ The 1655 Whipple House, which is celebrating
its centennial this year as one of the country's first house
museums, has many lessons to teach _ not the least being how
preservationist thinking has changed. In its hundred years of
ownership by the Ipswich Historical Society, the old house has been
greatly loved, and occasionally violated, by an extraordinary
collection of Bay Staters who have become part of its story.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the garden! It's less than 50 years old, yet
its history is just as interesting as that of the 344-year-old
house.
</P>
<P>
   The front garden was the pioneering project of two indomitable
Ipswich residents: Arthur A. Shurcliff, who also designed the
gardens of Colonial Williamsburg, and Isadore Smith, a garden club
lady and the heroine of this tale. Her original research for the
garden, in search of herbs actually grown by Colonial housewives
for cooking and remedies, led her to write several books (under the
pen name Ann Leighton) that have become classics of the flourishing
garden restoration movement.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the first people on the scene were the Whipples
themselves. They were all named John. John the Elder, a devout
Puritan, built a half-house with a great chimney in the heart of
fledgling Ipswich around 1655. His son, Captain John, was a
flamboyant businessman and cavalry officer who made money, doubled
the size of the house to six rooms, and turned it into a showpiece,
with vermilion trim, a painted interior, and luxurious imported
furnishings. His son, Major John, completed a saltbox addition of
nine more rooms before the end of the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   Then the son-less house went to three generation of Crockers,
through the female side of the family. It also went through a
remodeling in the Georgian style, before being purchased by Abraham
Bond, a stocking weaver from Nottingham, England, in 1841, a time
when Ipswich was shifting from lace-making to hosiery production.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1890s, the Whipple House was in run-down but sturdy
condition, thanks to the durability of its rich building materials,
which included foot-wide chestnut and oak beams. It was serving as
a tenement for immigrant families working in the hosiery mills that
had sprung up around it when Ipswich minister and historian Thomas
Franklin Waters convinced the nine-year-old Ipswich Historical
Society to buy the house from the son of Abraham Bond, James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   The opulent Whipple furnishings were long gone, but the house
was soon filled with antiques from society members. It opened to
the public July 5, 1899.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many people who loved the Whipple House was young
Isadore Leighton Luce, who would look forward to glimpsing it on
train rides between Boston and her native Portsmouth, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Then she went on a world tour. By the time she returned, the
Historical Society had moved the house to its current site, a more
spacious lot that was also near busy Route 1A, where people
traveled by car and, it was hoped, would stop to buy an entrance
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But then Isadore Luce's vacation had been a long one. It was
while she was touring a teak lumber yard in Rangoon, Burma _ one
that still used elephants as live forklifts _ that Luce met British
Colonel A. William Smith. Actually, he was conducting the tour. But
as soon as it was over, he asked her for a date. They were married
in Bombay in 1925, then lived in India and Burma until coming to
the United States in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Smith was a writer who turned out adventure novels and
short stories for popular magazines, mostly about the Raj. One
summer weekend, while Isadore was away visiting her sister, Bill
bought a large house on Essex Marsh on Argilla Road. This was a
colony of a different sort, where Boston bluebloods summered near
Crane's Beach. Bill Smith hadn't had much experience with New
England winters, and his purchase turned out to be a summer house,
completely devoid of insulation.
</P>
<P>
   But the Smiths lived there year-round anyway, raising three
children. In 1939, the colonel, who had already served in World War
I, was called up by the British military for World War II. Lonely
Isadore wrote her first book, a novel, during the six years he was
gone.
</P>
<P>
   But just up Argilla Road was delightful company. There Arthur A.
Shurcliff, one of the most influential American landscape
architects of the 20th century, had his summer home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were good friends, Mom and Arthur. They got along very
well, though he was awfully old,'' her son Jim Smith recalls. His
own favorite was Mrs. Shurcliff. ``Margaret was a live wire. She
was one of the first suffragettes. My brother and I used to listen
to her stories about marching in Boston and being arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many esthetes of his time, Arthur Shurcliff was fascinated
with the decorative arts of 18th-century America. Until the
centennial of the American Revolution in 1876, Victorians had been
throwing out their antiques and going ``modern.'' But suddenly the
tide turned, and Americans started to make a fetish out of all
things associated with the Colonial era.
</P>
<P>
   Though Shurcliff and his contemporary designers thought they
were creating landscapes and architecture of true Colonial
elegance, their creations were so romanticized that they were in
fact creating something new, something that would much later be
dubbed the Colonial Revival style.
</P>
<P>
   Their ``Colonial reproductions'' were cleaner, more opulent, and
more beautiful than the real Colonial era ever was. Reeking of old
money and ``good'' bloodlines, the Colonial Revival style became
wildly popular with the aspiring middle class, resulting in an
America still dotted today with millions of so-called
Colonial-style homes. When pitted against the perceived demands of
good taste, historical authenticity never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Few things illustrate these priorities better than the
relocation of the Whipple House in 1927 to a more genteel
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The move was very controversial. William Sumner Appleton,
founder of the Society for the Preservation of New England
Antiquities and a great friend of the Rev. Waters, attended all the
meetings, saying that this is not what he would have wanted,'' says
James Kyprianos, present-day curator of the Ipswich Historical
Society.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a nationwide letter-writing campaign by leading
architects orchestrated by Appleton, the Whipple House was ripped
from its archeological foundations (which now lie under a parking
area). So a town house that had originally been sited sideways on a
small downtown lot now sat like a country squire on 5 acres near
Argilla Road.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it needed landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   Shurcliff was drawn to it like a cat to catnip.
</P>
<P>
   An eminent Bostonian with Harvard and MIT credentials, Shurcliff
was prodigious, one of the last great public park builders in the
vigorous Victorian tradition of Frederick Law Olmsted. In fact,
Shurcliff began his career studying under the wizard of the Emerald
Necklace and worked in his firm, an even better credential than
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   During his very busy career, Shurcliff redesigned Boston Common,
the area where Storrow Drive was built, and other Boston parks. He
designed more than 50 private estates, some of which, such as
Castle Hill in Ipswich, have been preserved as elegant open land.
He fashioned town plans for Fort Worth, Texas, and many other
communities across the country, and was the campus planner for many
colleges and schools, including Tufts, Brown, Amherst, Mount
Holyoke, Colgate, Groton, and St. Paul's. He loved antique
re-creations and assisted in the development of Old Sturbridge
Village.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
