   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LUTHERAN-ESPICOPAL (Denver) _ Amid intense and unusual church
politics, the legislative assembly of the nation's largest Lutheran
denomination is set to vote on one of the most important ecumenical
proposals of the last 50 years, a sweeping agreement for close
cooperation between the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and
the Episcopal Church. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-HURRICANE-SHELTERS (Miami) _ A new report says that 90
percent of Florida's hurricane shelters will not withstand a
hurricane. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUG-RESISTANT-BACTERIA (Washington) _ The CDC reports on
four deaths among previously healthy children, over a period of two
years, from a drug-resistant bacteria. The report is alarming
because these children appear to have acquired their infections not
from hospitals or nursing homes, the only places such cases had
previously occurred, but in their communities. By Sheryl Gay
stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit ballooned
unexpectedly to all-time high in June as imports of goods and
services topped $100 billion for the first time. The deficit had
been expected to shrink somewhat from May's $21.2 billion, the
previous record, but instead it swelled 16.3 percent to $24.6
billion. The larger-than-expected number is expected to bring down
previous estimates of economic growth in the second quarter. By
Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-YEN (Undated) _ Looking at the recent rise of the yen
against the dollar. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOA-REYNOLDS (Undated) _ Alcoa prevails in its bid for
Reynolds Metals Inc., reaching an agreement to acquire the company
for $4.4 billion in stock. Investors are apparently unhappy:
Reynolds shares move down about 6 percent. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   ALUMINUM-UKRAINE (Kiev) _ While Alcoa and its Western rivals
circle each other warily to retain supremacy in the aluminum
business, a relatively obscure but powerful competitor that
operates extensively in the former Soviet Union has been increasing
its control in a region responsible for much of the world's supply.
Trans-World Group, already the largest seller of aluminum ingots,
has been concentrating its effort in Ukraine, forming an alliance
with the government that could hurt its few remaining regional
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Three financial giants _ Industrial Bank
of Japan Ltd., Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank Ltd. and Fuji Bank Ltd. _ are
considering an alliance that would effectively create the world's
largest banking group. By Howard French.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ECON (Beijing) _ Looking at how state planning can or
cannot stop deflation. A folo on Beijing's announcement Wednesday
of broad curbs on new industrial, retail and luxury construction.
By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   WANG-FRAUD (Undated) _ Victor Wang, a key figure in the
securities fraud case of Duke &AMP; Co., is expected to plead guilty to
state and federal charges. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   NESTLE-HAAGEN-DAZS (Undated) _ Nestle announces an ice cream
joint venture in the United States with Haagen-Dazs aimed at
narrowing the gap with Unilever. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   PARIBAS-RESIGN (Rome) _ Paribas's chairman, Andre Levy-Lang,
will resign next week, the first executive casualty arising from
the failure of the French bank's planned merger with Societe
Generale. By John Taliabue.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:20 p.m., stocks were lower, with the
Dow industrials down 72, the S&AMP;P 500 down 13, Nasdaq 36. At
mid-morning, the 30-year bond was little changed, yielding 6
percent. The dollar, which fell as low as 110.74 yen after the
release of the United States trade data, stood at 111.35 yen.
European markets were also lower, with London down 1.38 percent and
Frankfurt down 0.83 percent. In Asia, Tokyo's Nikkei slipped 12.52
points, while the Hang Seng in Hong Kong surged 3.16 percent. By
Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
