 Thursday, Aug. 19, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Chuck Lewis
or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all
sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ It is difficult to respect a
presidential candidate who lacks the courage to say whether he or
she believes in biological evolution. George W. Bush, Elizabeth
Dole and Steve Forbes ducked the question, saying they would leave
it to the states rather than the scientific community to decide
whether Charles Darwin was a jerk. Such ignorant mush could be
expected of Forbes, who is pandering to the religious right, but
Dole promised us she would give us straight talk. She's a big
disappointment. By MARIANNE MEANS
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OLDER-WORKERS (Washington) _ Gene Nelson, an experienced
computer programmer, has been looking for work for two years. He's
irked at the claim of the computer industry that 400,000 software
engineering and programing jobs go unfilled in the United States.
``There's no shortage of high-tech workers,'' Nelson says.
``There's a shortage of high-tech workers under the age of 35.'' We
examine the problem of older computer engineers looking for work in
an industry that favors the young. By MARK HELM. (Also filed in the
``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOMBING-RANGE (Vieques, Puerto Rico) _ Puerto Rico's political
leaders and allies in Congress point to Hawaii's ouster of the U.S.
Navy from a bombing range on the island of Kaho'olawe in 1994 as a
precedent for Puerto Rico's campaign to evict the Navy from a
58-year-old bombing range on the island of Vieques. The future of
Vieques is headed toward President Clinton's desk. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
