<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAR THAT WHISTLE? STANLEY STEAMERS STRUT THEIR STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was like time passing time. The thundering diesel engine
pushed a line of railroad cars through an intersection near the
paper mills of Berlin, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting at the crossing in his hissing 1922 Stanley Steamer sat
David Nergaard of Littleton, Mass. What the modern diesel and the
old car had in come was their whistles. Except that when Nergaard
pulled the cord to unleash steam through his whistle, and the big
train replied in kind, it was clear in the mountain air that the
Stanley's whistle was the louder.
</P>
<P>
   Steam is powerful. It has driven our industry, our mills,
trains, ocean-going ships, lake launches, and cars. In 1906, it
powered a Stanley called the ``Rocket'' to 127.6 miles per hour on
a Florida beach.
</P>
<P>
   Steam is also ephemeral, here and then gone.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are those who have found a way to hold onto steam, and
in more than 80 steam cars, they plied the notches, valleys, and
mountains of northern New Hampshire all last week. What brought
them there was the 100th anniversary of the first automobile ascent
of Mount Washington. Where they came from was all over the United
States and Europe. What their owners had in common was the clutch
of steam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steam is a bad disease . . . once you get it, you can't get
rid of it,'' says Nergaard.
</P>
<P>
   They gathered first at the base of the Mount Washington Auto
Road and, in this driest of summers, were met with rain. Weather in
the Whites can be like that _ unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   It did not stop hundreds of spectators from coming to the public
exhibit, and they moved among the cars and their hisses, whistles,
and gasps. Some of the cars, puffing steam, sounded like a panting
dog would on a hot summer day.
</P>
<P>
   Here was Arthur Edlredge of Peterborough, N.H., with his 1901
Lane, one of two Lanes known to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Here were Robert and Eulalia Collins of South Amherst, Mass.,
with ``Yellow Legs,'' the 1911 Stanley Model 71 that they saved
from beneath a tree on a chicken farm in 1958. Eulalia's father
found the car, Robert and Eulalia did their own work restoring it:
woodwork, leather upholstery, pinstriping. They have been driving
it since.
</P>
<P>
   Lorne Richard of Poughkeepsie, N.Y., came in a 1910 White;
William Handley of Manchester, N.H., in a 1932 Derr American _
again, one of two known to exist.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was for some of the cars to climb Washington on Monday,
but Monday was the mountain's day: early August, yet, as Washington
can be, 32 degrees at the top in winds up to 76 miles per hour.
Re-enacting the first ascent _ by F. O. Stanley and his wife, Flora
_ would have to wait for another day.
</P>
<P>
   So historical reenactment became social event and tour as
participants shifted gears.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Gilheeney, the maintenance manager for the Mount Washington
Summit Road Co., worked to get the company's 1899 Locomobile
running, even though it would not attempt to re-create the climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want you all to step back, it's like a fire-spittin'
dragon,'' he warned of the process of warming and lighting the
gasoline that heats the water that turns to steam that runs the
auto.
</P>
<P>
   He said he'd only recently grown his eyebrows back from one such
flaming spit and then told of seeing a man a day earlier burn the
hair off one side of his head.
</P>
<P>
   In a few minutes of warming and fiddling, Gilheeney had the
Locomobile, which may be the one the Stanleys used to climb the
mountain, up and running. Minutes after that, backed from the
garage, it was spitting flames because it was getting too much
gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The steam crowd is an eclectic bunch, beards abound, as do
period clothes, bug-eyed goggles and strange hats. And as in any
eclectic bunch, stories, tales, and myths abound.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley invented the steamer, some said, because his wife was
twice thrown from a horse. No, no, said others. It was because she
could not learn to ride a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn Benson of Limerick, Maine, raced through notch and valley
in his 1906 Stanley racer, baseball cap on backward, beard flowing
in twin wings up over his face, goggles fastened tight, giving him
the look of a speeding bug.
</P>
<P>
   It was all part of what may have been the largest gathering of
steam cars ever held, and as they made their way along roads among
heavy summer tourist traffic they were centers of attention. Other
drivers waved to them; some looked at them curiously, perhaps
mistaking the steam that occasionally poured from beneath them for
the smoke of an engine gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever they stopped, crowds formed: children goggle-eyed,
elderly couples holding hands and walking around them in reverence
or remembrance or both.
</P>
<P>
   They toured through the week, inspected one another's cars, were
gracious to the curious.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're leaving, some on trailers, some, like Nergaard's
Stanley, being driven all the way home.
</P>
<P>
   And 100 years after the first car, a steamer, climbed Mount
Washington, they will be gone _ like steam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
