<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIGGEN: LOTS TO LIKE, ESPECIALLY IF YOU LIKE SAABS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a Saab guy, I go back to the late '60s, and through three
decades I owned several of them, from the popcorn poppers to the
900 turbos, and they lost me only when they came out with the 9000,
which just didn't feel like a Saab.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I learned in driving these slightly quirky cars is
that if you take front-wheel drive and add power, you get torque
steer, a tendency of power transmitted to front wheels to give
those wheels wandering minds of their own.
</P>
<P>
   In the low-powered Saabs, this meant you could make the front
wheels actually chatter if you turned hard and accelerated from low
speeds. In the mid-'80s turbos, it produced an offline tug that
could be sensed even when accelerating from higher speeds.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Saab company guy stood before us to unveil the Saab
Viggen, the line's new hot rod, I was skeptical when I heard him
say that, despite 225 horsepower and 252 lb-ft. of torque, this
Lightning Blue wedge of a rocket did not have torque steer.
</P>
<P>
   Weight shift, he called it. Wait a minute, I say.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. There is a lot to like about this car. But
Saab should just admit that, hey, it's got torque steer and that's
part of the quirkiness that has made so many folks so loyal to
Saab.
</P>
<P>
   Round a sharp, climbing left-hand curve at 60 miles per hour,
drop to third and kick in the turbo, and the Viggen pulls out to
the right. In the same turn, there is a disquieting shift of weight
to the right rear wheel even as the front wheels unweight. Hit
bumps at speed and those front wheels start thinking on their own
again, a hop here, a skip there, and hold that steering wheel. Even
when accelerating straight ahead, there are times when you sense
competing forces at work up there in the front.
</P>
<P>
   As David Crosby sang:
</P>
<P>
   (itals) ``It's like one of those nights you drive by your own
street; and you wonder who's running your hands and your
feet.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   That said, for Saab loyalists, this souped-up version of the 9.3
is the best Saab yet. It's got power, it's got performance (0-60 in
6.5 seconds), it's wonderfully comfortable, and in trained hands it
can be fun.
</P>
<P>
   One thing it doesn't have is the turbo lag of old. Its
2.3-liter, four-cylinder engine _ with reinforced pistons and oil
jets pumping from beneath to cool those pistons _ barks to the
commands of an electronic throttle. Stomp the gas and the throttle
opens wide, sucking in air for a lean, turbo-boosting leap even
before extra fuel starts to flow.
</P>
<P>
   To limit torque steer at the lower end, the engine's torque is
limited in first and second gears. But when the Mitsubishi turbo is
free to run, the car leaps ahead in a way that makes clear why they
named it after the Saab 37 Viggen fighter jet. There is power to
spare here and it jumps from 60-80 miles per hour in a flash,
cruises at 75 m.p.h. in fifth turning just under 2,800 rpms. And
even with all this power, I got just over 23 miles per gallon
driving the Saab on country lanes and major highways.
</P>
<P>
   Saab has stiffened the suspension well beyond what is standard
in the 9.3 _ MacPherson struts, shortened coil springs, tube shocks
and antiroll bar up front; a torsion beam axle, coil springs, tube
shocks, and antiroll bar in the rear.
</P>
<P>
   Yet my sense is it should be stiffer still, considering all the
power Saab has given us to play with in the Viggen. The ride is
softer than it should be and in a performance car, this translates
into body roll.
</P>
<P>
   I'd also like stiffer clutch performance and I remain baffled at
Saab's continued insistence on putting out long-throw, sloppy
sticks for shifting. In a car like this, you want a transmission
you can click through, up and down, for all five gears _ not one
that has you reaching for some distant correct spot with each
shift.
</P>
<P>
   What this whole setup means is that, to drive this car out on
the edge _ where I assume Saab means for us to drive it _ you have
to know its quirks and you have to be aware when they kick in.
</P>
<P>
   In true Saab fashion, the Viggen is built to protect its
occupants: dual front airbags, side airbags, active head
restraints, and a braking system, with ABS, that brings it to fast,
shoulder-belt tightening stops. Key to this fine braking system are
four ventilated rotors with enlarged calipers to squeeze the Viggen
to straight, sure stops.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, all is elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Black and blue leather seats with firm thigh pads and bulging
lateral supports make you feel like you're strapped into a racecar.
These are some of the most comfortable seats I've ever sat in and,
in what is not really a large car, the rear seat legroom is
remarkable. Even the door inserts are rich, blue leather.
</P>
<P>
   The dash and controls are a fine lesson in simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Gauges packaged simply in a single semicircle; climate controls
easy to read and easy to use _ red arrow up for heat, blue arrow
down for cool _ up and down arrows abound, in easy to understand
universal language.
</P>
<P>
   The curved, light-gray dashboard allows all-black switches to
stand out and a night panel system lets the driver turn off any
distracting lights and instruments.
</P>
<P>
   With its sloping hood, the Saab gives the driver a clear view of
the road ahead and with this car's power and quirks, you'll want to
pay attention to that view and to the feel of the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Saab offers Viggen buyers two free days of driving school at
Road Atlanta, and if you buy one of these, I'd recommend you take
the course. For the relatively cheap price of $38,000 _ there are
virtually no options on the Viggen _ you are getting a lot of car
that needs a trained hand to use it right.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touches:
</P>
<P>
   --The rubber toggle switches that control the direction of all
vents in the dash.
</P>
<P>
   --The in-dash cupholder that folds out, wafer thin, looking like
a CD holder until the catch drops down to hold the cup.
</P>
<P>
   --The driver's left foot rest. Why doesn't everybody do this?
</P>
<P>
   Annoyances:
</P>
<P>
   --The AM radio reception is atrocious. I expected to here Ol'
Dead Wolfman Jack crackling through the night air, ala a la 1960s,
as the signals of skipping stations faded in and out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The numbers &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $38,000 &QL; 
Price as tested: $38,750 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 225 hp/252 lbs.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 102.6 inches/182.3 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 67.4 inches/56.2 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 2,900 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 5 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
