<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TINGLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECTING AND SCREENWRITING: D-MINUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his writing for ``Scream,'' ``Dawson's Creek,'' ``I Know
What You Did Last Summer'' and ``The Faculty,'' Kevin Williamson
has made a career out of irony. Not content with employing it, he
is now defining irony for us. In his directorial debut, the
teen-age dark comedy ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' he tells us (over
and over) that irony is ... an outcome different from what was
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an outcome different from what was expected: That a
once-promising screenwriter like Williamson would turn into a
sanctimonious bore, giving us in ``Mrs. Tingle'' shallow, unlikable
characters doing illogical things in overdone situations as he
tries to teach ``us'' a lesson about respect.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the movie's lead character, Leigh Ann
(''Dawson Creek's'' Katie Holmes). She's the smart daughter of a
waitress, and she pins her hopes for a scholarship on getting an
``A'' in Mrs. Tingle's history class; if she doesn't get it, she
won't be valedictorian. Uh, hello? Did colleges stop handing out
scholarships to people just because they were ``second'' in their
class? (Judging from the intelligence level at this school, by the
way, all grades are on the curve.)
</P>
<P>
   Or take Mrs. Tingle herself, a teacher loaded with such
bitterness at being stuck in a small town that she wants even her
best students to fail and be stuck there with her. She browbeats
the kids during class, but this isn't the sort of tough-love John
Houseman showed in ``The Paper Chase''_ it's a particularly
vindictive form of teaching, one that has nothing to do with giving
hard lessons and everything to do with spite. Again, what's keeping
her in this podunk town? She certainly seems to have enough money
to get out, judging from her Gothic house.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry between Leigh Ann and Mrs. Tingle escalates when
Leigh Ann is falsely accused of cheating. The Noxzema-faced teen
shows up at Tingle's home to mount a defense with a couple of dense
buddies (Marisa Coughlan as the best-friend/sidekick who's a
wannabe actress, ``7th Heaven's'' Barry Watson as the rebel stud
who attracts both girls), and one thing leads to another. Next
thing you know, the kids have tied Mrs. Tingle to her bed, she
plays mind games with the kids and vice versa, and Coughlan does
bad Linda Blair impersonations.
</P>
<P>
   As with so many of this year's teen movies, the ghost of John
Hughes haunts this one (just when you're thinking, ``Hey, this
looks like a John Hughes movie,'' Molly Ringwald's name pops up in
the opening credits). Holmes, Coughlan and Watson make up such an
Ally Sheedy-Ringwald-Judd Nelson sort of trio you keep wondering
when Emilio Estevez and Anthony Michael Hall are going to walk in.
As Mrs. Tingle, Helen Mirren acts rings around the rest of the
cast, even though she spends a good deal of the movie bound and
gagged; the big question is why an actress of her caliber decided
to be in something this lame. The supporting cast is peppered with
Hughes-ish adults such as Michael McKean (thoroughly wasted as the
school principal) and Jeffrey Tambor (as a lascivious coach).
Williamson treats these characters as crumpled-up waste paper _ he
tosses them out, unwrinkles them when he decides he needs them
again, then throws them away once more.
</P>
<P>
   As a director, Williamson is simply routine, letting many scenes
run on too long, leaning too much (as always) on his pop-culture
knowledge and getting the most mundane performances from everyone
except Mirren and, to a lesser extent, Holmes. It's time Williamson
grew up _ his work here and in ``The Faculty,'' which also involved
vindictive teachers but in a more amusing way, shows that this guy
is still stuck on his high-school issues. And he's 34! His biggest
mistake with ``Mrs. Tingle,'' though, is the number of times he
shows characters yawning or complaining that they're bored. Here's
an irony, Kev: This time, your audience is likely to agree.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Kevin Williamson
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Helen Mirren, Katie Holmes
</P>
<P>
   Length: 92 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ strong language, violence, sexual situations and
teen drinking
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
