<HEADER>
A2952 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-ILLUMINATA-TEX     08-19 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ILLUMINATA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLAY-WITHIN-THE-PLAY'S THE CONFOUNDING THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For movie fans who want something a little more sophisticated
than ``American Pie,'' John Turturro's theater-world satire
``Illuminata'' is a textbook example of ``Be careful what you ask
for _ you might get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a film that's smart, often funny, unconventional and
unpredictable. It's also pretentious, often boring or crude,
bizarre and meandering. These virtues and flaws are not mutually
exclusive. Consequently, your tolerance for the movie depends, more
than usual, on the mood you're in when you go to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Illuminata'' is, in part, a comedy about a writer's
difficulties in staging his new play, don't expect the exuberance
of ``Shakespeare in Love.'' This is a movie that's stagy and
cynical, and it makes no bones about possessing either quality. The
real-life actors playing the fake actors say all their lines as if
the words were among the most profound ever spoken. Even the
funniest lines sound as if they are meant to be written in italics.
</P>
<P>
   Turturro _ who directed, produced and with Brandon Cole co-wrote
this adaptation of Cole's play _ plays Tuccio, the playwright for a
motley repertory company. He's trying to get an unfinished play,
``Illuminata,'' produced but is having trouble with stubborn
theater owners who believe the play isn't ready. During his
attempts to get the show produced, he'll have to deal with a
flamboyant drama-queen critic (Christopher Walken, hamming it up
but looking like death warmed over), a scheming diva (Susan
Sarandon, hamming it up but looking great), a
not-always-understanding lover/actress/theater manager (Katherine
Borowitz, in one of the film's few subtle performances), and with
the bawdy antics of the company's actors.
</P>
<P>
   The film was obviously as much a labor of love for Turturro as
its play-within-a-play was for Tuccio. But unless you're absolutely
obsessed with theater, you're likely to find it a little
irritating. Even though it's scarcely an hour-and-a-half long, the
movie gives you the feeling that Turturro never had an idea he
wanted to throw out _ the movie echoes commedia dell'arte and
theater of the absurd, with cinematic hints of Bergman (watch how
Turturro stages a deathbed scene) and Fellini, and Turturro has
also cited visionary filmmakers Jean Renoir and Michael Powell as
influences. That's a lot to stuff into 95 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The result is one of the darnedest movies to come out this year,
with a script so wordy that its best lines seem to be beneficiaries
of the law of averages and performances so florid that they defy
criticism. And yet, for all its farcicalness, it shows every sign
that Turturro took it way too seriously. The climactic scene, which
drags on and on, is merely the screenplay's way of saying that,
sometimes, art and life overlap. Not exactly a new statement, but
Turturro stages it as if he were delivering an earth-shattering
prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Illuminata''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: John Turturro
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: John Turturro, Christopher Walken, Susan Sarandon
</P>
<P>
   Length: 95 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, nudity and lots of sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
