<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2955 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-BLUE-EYES-PROFIL     08-19 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BLUE-EYES-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANT TELLS ALL _ AND SOME OF IT'S TRUE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The heat index outside is over 100 degrees, and even
inside Hugh Grant's two-story hotel suite, it is uncomfortably
warm.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, dressed head to toe in black, has his shirt sleeves
rolled up above his elbows, and the top buttons of his shirt open.
But he seems relaxed as he plops down into an easy chair, slips off
his loafers, and puts his stockinged feet up on a coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bumbling, overshy impression many people have of
Grant from his performance in ``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' he
does not act cute or coy or lovably inept in person. He doesn't
even run his hands through his famously floppy hair. Most of that
is just acting, and Grant is rather tired of the image.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about me being an English wimp,'' he says. ``As you
know, we're all homosexuals. Tea-drinking homosexuals.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new film, ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' Grant plays an Englishman
living in New York. He finds himself mistaken for a gangster called
``Mickey Blue Eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone will think of me as a wimp after this,
because I'm pretty damn hard in it,'' he says. ``Don't you think?
Pretty scary.''
</P>
<P>
   He's kidding. In interviews, Grant jokes, exaggerates and
embellishes stories with a dry humor and an almost perpetual grin
that he struggles vainly to suppress. It's not the listener he is
trying to amuse, but himself, by trying out this or that new
version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Take the story about the London house that his longtime
companion, actress and model Elizabeth Hurley, insisted they buy,
despite his protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made me do it,'' Grant says. ``And then swindled me.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, really?
</P>
<P>
   ``We said we'd share it, and when it came time to write this
massive check, she pulled the old `I don't have my checkbook on me'
stuff. With amazing bare-facedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few weeks later she was sitting with her checkbook in front
of her. I said, `Any chance you could pay me back?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And she said `You know, I've decided not to.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of Grant's answers, this sounds, frankly, like more
lie than truth. He savors the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he says, chuckling. ``You're right. I like to sprinkle
little falsehoods like currants on a cake. That's actually another
lie _ that last one.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep that in mind, whatever Grant says. You may not be able to
see the grin in print, but most of the time, it's there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' and the recent ``Notting Hill'' mark
Grant's return to romantic comedy after four years. In fact, except
for the flop drama ``Extreme Measures,'' Grant had not made a new
film since 1995, when he was arrested in Los Angeles for lewd
behavior with a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Grant had plenty of acting offers after that incident, he says,
but he just couldn't find a script he liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I got a bit too picky,'' Grant says. ``I mean, I'm not
the world's most enthusiastic actor anyway. I've never been one of
those people who thinks I have to be out there acting, otherwise
I'd die. In fact, I'm quite delighted when I'm not acting.''
</P>
<P>
   With only the slightest prodding, Grant admits the arrest also
affected his decision not to make more films for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in no hurry to go back out there,'' he says.
``Careerwise, I don't think it affected me that badly, because I
was offered `101 Dalmations' the very next week. (He turned it
down.)
</P>
<P>
   ``But in terms of me being even less inclined to be in the
public eye, I think that may account for one of the reasons I took
so much time off.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his reluctance to be in the limelight, Grant is working
hard promoting ``Mickey Blue Eyes.'' For one thing, he produced it
(although he declined a screen credit) along with Hurley, through
their own company, Simian Films. More important, this film is an
important comeback for Grant after his long absence.
</P>
<P>
   True, ``Notting Hill'' made more than $240 million worldwide,
but Grant is not taking credit, since the movie co-starred Julia
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, she could do a romantic comedy with Mussolini and the
script could be written by my mother, and $35 million would change
hands the first weekend,'' Grant says. ``It kind of detracts from
any contribution one might make to the film.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' was written by Richard Curtis, who also wrote
``Four Weddings and a Funeral,'' with Grant in mind. He was signed
before Roberts was asked, but he admits it was a relief when she
decided to co-star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' was shot before ``Notting Hill'' but held
for release to benefit from Notting Hill's expected success.
</P>
<P>
   As Grant tells it, at least today, working with Hurley is a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exactly the kind of nightmare you would imagine working
with your nearest and dearest. It's amazing we still talk to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite a combination, the two of us, because she's very,
very opinionated and enthusiastic and just plain terrifying to
people _ which is a very useful characteristic on a film.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrifying? Hurley?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of her wrath. (He pronounces it `roth.') Which has to
be seen to be believed. You've got mobsters trembling at her every
word. I'm much quieter and more affable. Inside I'm seething.''
</P>
<P>
   The British press _ famous for being nasty, especially to Grant
and Hurley _ portrays them as constantly fighting. But they have
been together for 12 years, since long before either was famous.
They met while they were making a Spanish film, ``Rowing With the
Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You find someone you kind of click with,'' Grant says of their
mutual attraction. ``We knew from the outset. We just laughed at
the same things and happened to have read the same books. We had
incredibly similar upbringings. Her father was an ex-soldier, and
her mother was a teacher. My father was an ex-soldier, and my
mother was a teacher. On a number of levels we were exactly the
same. Our tastes in many things,'' he says with a short, private
chuckle, ``were similar. I'm very attracted to naughty girls, and
she had a very, very naughty look in her eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley's pet name for Grant is Monkey Boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, please!,'' he says, squirming again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, she does call me Monkey Boy. It's quite interesting
because she's been doing that for years and no one can see any
monkeylike features in me. But I think with her it's gone much
deeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to her the other day on a plane, `When someone says
`Hugh,' what do you see?' And this was her serious answer. She
thought about it a long time and said, `I definitely see your face.
And a monkey's body'.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether any of this is true or not, Grant is almost out of
breath from laughing at the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a little stooped chimp,'' he gasps. ``It just
shows the true depth of her insanity, which has never been
sufficiently recognized by the press. She's out of her tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their new home, Grant says he has kept their old
apartment, so he can sneak away to it and sit around drinking beer
and watching sports in his underwear. (When Grant's cell phone
rings, it plays `Take Me Out to the Ball Game.' ``I thought that
was a good American tune,'' he says. ``I've got Scotland the Brave
on my British one.'')
</P>
<P>
   Grant says Hurley would not like to see him watching TV in his
underwear. He, on the other hand, would never complain about her
lying about in her underthings.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. That's what all girls should be doing,'' he says with
glee.
</P>
<P>
   With Hurley recognized as one of the most beautiful women on the
planet, does he ever feel the need to stay in shape?
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to do a little exercise recently, because I was
getting old and repellent. But that's for my own vanity, because
I'm quite certain that girls are not really interested in what men
look like. At all. Not even slightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant has already shot his next film. He has a leading role in
Woody Allen's unnamed next project. He has been quoted as saying he
plays a villain, but that got him in trouble with the secretive
Allen, so he begs off confirming it.
</P>
<P>
   But it's no secret that he longs to play things that get him
away from his boyish image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put that in the patronizing category _ especially when
you're 38. I'd like to be cool and dangerous and sexy rather than
boyish and lovable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
