<P>
   BBN-CHASS-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The Times column: Mark
McGwire is in another home-run race, on pace to top 62 home runs
again. Yet this time around, his smile isn't so easy, and playing
for a losing team is perhaps taking its toll. By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE (Bristol, Conn.) _ Toms River East, the 1998
Little League World Series champions from New Jersey, faces
Massachusetts in the Eastern Regional final. The winner advances to
the Little League World Series in Williamsport, Pa., starting on
Sunday. By Chis Broussard.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-ROYALS (New York) _ Kansas City at the Yankees, 12:05
p.m. EDT start. By Jack Curry.
</P>
<P>
   RUN-TRACK-JONES (Seville, Spain) _ Marion Jones was already
track and field's golden girl, the athlete following in the
footsteps of Jackie Joyner Kersee and Wilma Rudolph and expected to
put the sport back in the spotlight at the 2000 Sydney Games. With
drug questions again swirling around track, Jones talks about the
burden of trying to be the sport's savior and model citizen. By
Christopher Clarey.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-CURCIC (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ Instead of hustling quietly
out of Giants Stadium after yet another MetroStars loss on
Wednesday night, Sasa Curcic was hanging out with fans in the
parking lot, being his usual animated, over-the-top self. Why not?
He had not even played, having been suspended because of previous
on-field antics. Curcic may be playing for the worst team in Major
League Soccer, but the 27-year-old Yugoslavian has not curbed his
reckless style or his emotions. By Alex Yannis.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-VENUS-WILLIAMS (Undated) _ Venus Williams talks about the
upcoming United States Open, and says she plans to take college
courses in fashion this fall. By Robin Finn.
</P>
