   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit ballooned
unexpectedly to all-time high in June as imports of goods and
services topped $100 billion for the first time. The deficit had
been expected to shrink somewhat from May's $21.2 billion, the
previous record, but instead it swelled 16.3 percent to $24.6
billion. The larger-than-expected number is expected to bring down
previous estimates of economic growth in the second quarter. By
Melody Petersen.
