<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUNE IN FOR FUN WITH `EDTV' COMEDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `EDTV' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 1999, PG-13, Universal, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $34.98
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it sounds like ``The Truman Show.'' But ``EDtv'' is
different _ and better.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McConaughey is Ed, an affable, scrappy guy getting by in
San Francisco, where his dysfunctional family also lives.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the blue, Ed is chosen to star in a 24-hour, reality-TV
show that will follow his life _ which is more interesting,
humorous and romantic than many soap operas.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely hit show comes with a price: Ed's budding romance
with Sherry (Jenna Elfman) suffers in the glare, and his family's
skeletons start clattering from the closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``EDtv's'' concept is closer to Albert Brooks' 1979 film ``Real
Life'' than to ``Truman,'' in large part because Ed knows he's on
camera and often plays to it. But director Ron Howard and a fine
cast add new dimensions to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey and Elfman make a terrific couple, and Ellen
DeGeneres and Rob Reiner stand out as combative TV execs.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Harrelson puts his annoying nature to good use as Ed's
annoying brother. But Elizabeth Hurley, still more model than
actress, is irritating as a model (who wants to be an actress) who
seduces Ed.
</P>
<P>
   But that's minor static on ``EDtv's'' screen. It may sound
overly familiar, but this film is fun, full-bodied entertainment
that's worth tuning in. Disregard the overrated ``Truman'' and give
Ed a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`200 CIGARETTES' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Paramount, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD $29.95
</P>
<P>
   An unsung winner, this works as a period piece, as a comedy and
as a showcase for a wealth of pop songs and a delightful ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Janeane Garofalo, Paul Rudd, Christina Ricci, Jay Mohr, Kate
Hudson, Dave Chappelle, and Ben and Casey Affleck are among the
young people trolling Manhattan for parties, sex and sensation with
varying degrees of success and desperation on New Year's Eve 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are sympathetic, the situations ring true, and
the almost nonstop music should give you a new appreciation of '80s
pop-rock. Heck, even the dated fashions have a certain pizazz.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, this film has an infectious affection for its
characters for all their faults. Think ``American Graffiti'' 20
years later and ask, ``Where were you in '82?''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
`ANALYZE THIS' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999, R, Warner, CC, VHS priced for rental, DVD priced for sales
</P>
<P>
   Robert De Niro can play gangsters in his sleep, but he's no
comedian, and his crass belligerence bogs down a cute premise about
a mobster (De Niro) hiring a shrink (Billy Crystal) to cure his
unseemly fearfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Needlessly bullying and violent, De Niro takes over Crystal's
life just as Crystal is nearing the altar with Lisa Kudrow.
</P>
<P>
   The film's mob menace is heavy-handed and all too real,
especially when sinister rival Chaz Palminteri enters the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Too many murderers and ruthless criminals _ not enough of
Crystal's haplessness.
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 stars.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VIDEO RATINGS &QL; 
 &QL; 
4 stars _ Excellent &QL; 
3 stars _ Good &QL; 
2 stars _ Fair &QL; 
1 star _ Poor
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
