<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2970 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TREK-DUNE-RESURRECTED     08-19 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-DUNE-RESURRECTED-ART-ADV23-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV23 
 INSIDE TREK &AMP; SCI-FI 
 SANDWORMS AND GUERILLAS: RESURRECTING SCI-FI'S CLASSIC `DUNE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., AUG. 23, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of co-writers
Brian Herbert and Kevin J. Anderson.) 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Revisit the ``Dune'' universe.
 &HT;    On a desert planet thousands of years in the future, where giant
sandworms provide the spice of life, the House Atreides faces off
against the forces of House Harkonnen.
 &HT;    The classic science-fiction saga ``Dune'', with its rich mix of
quasi-religious space adventure, guerilla combat and ecology, lay
dormant for years after the death of its creator, Frank Herbert.
 &HT;    While Herbert's son Brian, an author in his own right, had long
suppressed the temptation to recreate the wildly popular series,
Kevin J. Anderson, a prolific sci-fi author, yearned to pick up
where the elder Herbert had left off.
 &HT;    The two made first contact in January 1997. They swapped
concerns and ideas during several conversations.
 &HT;    ``Kevin and I are `Dune' fans and we knew `Dune' was sacred
ground,'' Herbert says by telephone from his home in Washington
state. ``We had to be very careful. We wanted to nurture the seeds
Dad had already planted and not disturb what was already there.''
 &HT;    Anderson suggested dipping back to the period just before the
events of ``Dune.''
 &HT;    Herbert imagined a ``Dune'' sequel set 10,000 years after
``Chapterhouse,'' the sixth and last ``Dune'' novel by Frank
Herbert, who died in 1986,
 &HT;    Herbert bought into Anderson's notion and they began in earnest,
bolstered by Herbert's access to his father's extensive notes and a
stroke of luck: weeks into the process, computer disks hand-labeled
``Dune 7'' by Frank Herbert were discovered in a safe deposit box.
They provided the younger Herbert and Anderson with even more
thematic material and guidance.
 &HT;    The authors assigned themselves individual chapters based on
personal interests and individual writing strengths, then sent
disks back and forth. Herbert reworked Anderson's text and vice
versa.
 &HT;    And so it went until their two distinct voices became one _ and
echoed Frank Herbert's.
 &HT;    The result is ``Dune: House Atreides'' (Bantam Books; $27.50),
the fall's most hotly anticipated sci-fi title and, arguably, the
season's most anticipated novel of any kind.
 &HT;    Talk about pressure. -----
 &HT;    ``I think `Dune' fans will have high expectations,'' says
Anderson by telephone from his home in the Rocky Mountains, near
Denver.
 &HT;    He and Herbert are on the line together via conference call.
 &HT;    ``But the pressure the fans are putting on us cannot even come
close to the pressure Brian and I are putting on each other and on
ourselves ... `Dune' is my favorite sci-fi book of all time and
it's such a legacy for Brian,'' Anderson says.
 &HT;    Anyone who read ``Dune'' knows it's not a ``start and finish''
book. Herbert devised an entire universe and the first novel barely
scratched the surface. ``House Atreides,'' part one of a planned
trilogy, builds upon the ``Dune'' history by setting that history
in motion.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to go back to the core ideas, subjects and
characters, to the elements everyone fell in love with in the first
place,'' Anderson says.
 &HT;    Thus, ``House Atreides'' introduces readers to younger versions
of Baron Harkonnen, planetologist Pardot Kynes, Master of Assassins
Thufir Hawat and Leto Atreides.
 &HT;    It whisks readers back to Arrakis and weaves fresh tales of the
spice, the melange.
 &HT;    Herbert and Anderson had their respective preferences.
 &HT;    ``Pardot Kynes is a fascinating character, and exploring Leto
was fascinating to me,'' Herbert says.
 &HT;    ``He's a man of honor who's not always accessible to Jessica.
And he's (`Dune' hero) Paul's father, so there will be complex
interactions between Leto and Paul, which I can relate to because
my father was so complex.''
 &HT;    ``The villains were a lot of fun, too,'' Anderson says. ``We
spend a lot of time with Baron Harkonnen and his nephew, Beast
Rabban. We really tried to flesh them out.''
 &HT;    Though both Herbert and Anderson are busy with various solo
projects, ``Dune'' will be a part of their lives for eons. They're
currently writing ``House Harkonnen,'' due out in October 2000,
tossing around ideas for book three, due out in October 2001, and
contemplating penning as many as 10 ``Dune'' novels, including
``Dune 7.''
 &HT;    All of the novels, the writers insist, will benefit from Frank
Herbert's notes and research, as well as from the 40,000 words of
ecologically-themed storytelling Herbert excised from ``Dune'' for
fear of ``preaching'' to readers.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, there are naysayers who argue ``Dune'' died along
with Herbert and that reviving the saga is heresy.
 &HT;    ``Again, `Dune' is sacred ground and I didn't want to do this in
a cavalier fashion,'' Brian Herbert says. ``As far as misusing the
property, the way I see it is that Dad created a family business
and I'm carrying on the tradition.''
 &HT;    Anderson says the resurrection of ``Dune'' could entice novices
to pick up the original series.
 &HT;    ``What we're doing by calling attention again to `Dune' is
bringing in new readers. A lot of people saw the (1984) movie and
never read the book, and we may convince people to read Frank
Herbert's work.
 &HT;    ``We're also giving something new to the millions of Frank
Herbert fans who kept `Dune' and the `Dune' universe alive for 35
years. What we're doing in no way diminishes from what Frank
Herbert created, and we hope we're adding to it.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Dune,'' consult the
official Website at www.randomhouse.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
