<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2973 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-TRICK-TEX     08-19 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRICK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOY MEETS BOY, AND THE REST IS REDUNDANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Trick'' is tricky. On the one hand, this gay romantic comedy
about two guys falling in love as they attempt to have a one-night
stand is sweet and amusing. On the other hand, it's kinda ordinary.
The odd thing is, the ordinariness works for it as well as against
it.
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows a night in the life of Gabriel (Christian
Campbell, Neve's brother), a young, shy, frustrated musical writer
so fresh-faced that he could give Howdy Doody a run for his money.
Although Gabriel acts like he's comfortable with his sexuality, he
acknowledges that he has never felt quite like he fits in with the
gay scene _ but that doesn't stop him from visiting a few clubs. In
one, he meets Mark (John Paul Pitoc), a go-go boy with whom Gabriel
eventually pursues romance after a later encounter on a subway.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, things keep getting in the way of this liaison. Or,
more accurately, people get in the way: Gabriel's straight roommate
is too selfish to give up the apartment for the night. Gabe's best
friend (Tori Spelling) is a whiny actress with a clinging tendency
(and yes, she and Gabe used to date before he came out). A drag
queen (Clinton Leupp, humorously dolled up as Spelling) spreads
nasty rumors about Mark. And for some reason, Mark doesn't want to
go to his own place. We don't learn the reason till late in the
film, because if we learned it early, well, we'd have no film. Of
course, if these guys just checked into a motel, we'd have no film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trick'' appears to be advancing the cause of ``mainstreaming''
gay films, because it tells its story casually, without trying to
make any strident points, just like a straight-oriented movie
would. In fact, it tells it with more charm and subtlety (it's like
a much less raucous and crass ``Booty Call''). It's good to see a
movie showing gays and straights getting along together, but
``Trick'' still portrays its straight characters as irritating
and/or buffoonish (although Spelling and Dallas' Lorri Bagley, as
the roommate's helium-voiced but common-sensical girlfriend, score
a couple of affecting moments).
</P>
<P>
   But if this were a boy-meets-girl story instead of a
boy-meets-boy story, would anyone care? Campbell's presence helps
immensely _ his boyish looks belie a performance that finds depth
in Gabriel's questing and confusion. Pitoc is also good as the stud
with a sensitive heart, and Stephen Hayes is amusing as an
emotional friend of Gabriel's. But their performances and Jim
Fall's pleasantly sympathetic direction, which favors mellow wit
over chaos, hide the fact that we've seen this story way too many
times before. Just because the orientation is switched doesn't make
it anything new.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Trick''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Jim Fall
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Christian Campbell, John Paul Pitoc, Tori Spelling
</P>
<P>
   Length: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, sexual content and nudity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
