<SLUG> BC-FILM-XIUXIU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PAINFUL LIFE, BEAUTIFULLY FILMED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not every movie set in the '70s has a cast lifted from
Entertainment Weekly's list of hot young actors, peeking through
bad shag wigs and coping with the angst of being different, man!
``Xiu Xiu, the Sent Down Girl'' _ the directing debut of actress
Joan Chen (''The Last Emperor'') _ reflects another kind of exile.
It's the story of a teen-aged girl in China, the smart, curious and
free-thinking Xiu Xiu (Lu Lu), who's shipped off to the countryside
_ sent down _ for Communist indoctrination. And, in a low-key way,
it has an almost painful directness. The dialogue tends to point
things out, as if it were actually written by the Communists.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that bent _ and sometimes in spite of it _ ``Xiu
Xiu'' is moving. It's a standard story of a kid trying to figure
out her place in the world, but it's also a blunt depiction of a
young person undergoing oppression. It's crude and powerful; Lu
Lu's enormous camera presence gives the movie an extra fillip of
pain, as she starts to realize exactly what it will take to get out
of the Tibetan outpost to which she's been exiled. Her girlish
innocence is compromised as she has to trade sex for the
possibility of freedom. Meanwhile, the cold herdsman (Lopsang) to
whom she was apprenticed and who first loomed as a sexual threat _
it's made clear why he is not _ becomes more sympathetic as it
becomes obvious that there's nothing he can do.
</P>
<P>
   Chen surrendered narrative complexity for a methodical depiction
of hope getting crushed. Shot with breathtaking and unspoiled
natural beauty as a backdrop, the movie thus takes on a fuller
poignancy. Perhaps the psychological primitivism can be explained
by the fact that Chen and her team shot the film on the run in
Tibet, without official permission from the Chinese government. As
a result, the Shanghai native was denounced and banned from filming
again in China. Despite its occasional crassness, ``Xiu Xiu'' is
worth the risk she took. Lu Lu's broken spirit stays with you, as
does Chen's burgeoning talent. She has an instinct for using
actors' faces for their strength and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Xiu Xiu, the Sent Down Girl''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joan Chen
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Lu Lu, Lopsang
</P>
<P>
   Length: 99 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ adult language and sexual situations; in Chinese,
with subtitles
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
