<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-KIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDS NEED THE RIGHT FUEL TO GET THE MOST FROM SCHOOL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JANE P. MARSHALL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Schools filled this month with wriggling, giggling
children.
</P>
<P>
   In each classroom, each stomach will be full of breakfast, each
lunch sack full of beloved and nutritious food. Each student is
bright-eyed, germ-free and ready to ace every course.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a ridiculous scenario. It could happen to you, Dad
and Mom.
</P>
<P>
   But first hear this (again): Children see and copy your eating
habits. Maybe they don't babble before a daybreak jolt of caffeine.
But they see you tear off without breakfast. They eye you avoiding
broccoli and adding the second scoop of Vanilla Bean Vanilla to the
peach cobbler. They know everything on your plate is fried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eat your breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But Dad didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   So, behave.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to your dreams, food is not broken into the two food
groups of chocolate and not chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   The main basic food groups are: breads, cereal, rice and pasta;
vegetables; fruits; milk, yogurt and cheese; and meat and other
protein sources, including poultry, fish, dry beans, eggs and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Basic guidelines for school children, according to Joy Bauer in
``The Complete Idiot's Guide to Total Nutrition'' (Alpha, $18.95),
are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Six or more servings per day from the bread and grain group.
These provide carbohydrates, B-vitamins and iron. One serving
equals 1 slice bread, 3/4 cup cereal, 1/2 cup cooked rice or pasta,
or half a small bagel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three or more servings of vegetables for Vitamin C, vitamin A,
folic acid, magnesium and fiber. One serving equals 1/2 cup cooked
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two or more servings of fruit for vitamin C, vitamin A,
potassium and fiber. One serving would be 1 small piece of fruit, 1
cup berries, 3/4 cup fruit juice or 1/4 cup dried fruit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Three or more servings from the milk group for calcium,
riboflavin and protein. Until age 24, young folks are growing
strong, healthy bones that will last them a lifetime. Boys and
girls ages 9-13 need 1,300 milligrams of calcium daily. One cup of
skim or 2 percent milk or of calcium-fortified orange juice has 300
milligrams; 1 ounce of Monterey Jack cheese has 212 milligrams; 1/2
cup ice cream has 88 milligrams. One serving is 1 cup of milk or
yogurt, or about 2 ounces of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two servings from the meat group for protein, B-vitamins, iron
and zinc. One serving is 2 to 3 ounces cooked lean meat or poultry,
1 egg, 2 tablespoons peanut butter or 1/2 cup cooked beans.
</P>
<P>
   The family cook and lunch maker can divide the servings in any
way. But notice how difficult it would be if your student skipped
breakfast and ate 1 slice of pepperoni pizza with a soda for lunch.
Dinner would need to consist of 2 fruits, more than 3 glasses of
milk, 1 egg, 1 piece of chicken, 2 1/2 cups pasta and 2 cups
spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Make breakfast count.
</P>
<P>
   The Three Worst Things To Do With Breakfast, according to
Virginia Van Vynckt in ``Feed Your Kids Right'' (Macmillan,
$12.95), are:
</P>
<P>
   _ Skip it. Your kids will be hungry and distracted by
midmorning.
</P>
<P>
   _ Define it as a doughnut and soft drink. That's sure to induce
midmorning ``crash.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Confine it to nothing but eggs, cereal and toast. Come on, be
creative.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests these inventive alternatives: rice cakes and
yogurt; leftover noodles reheated in the microwave and tossed with
a little cottage cheese and some pineapple chunks; a bagel with
peanut butter; or a frozen whole-grain waffle with fruit and a
small slice of cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as long as we're nagging: Turn off that TV and get some
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
