<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-PAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY NOTES HUGE GAP IN PAY, EDUCATION FOR HISPANICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Refiling to fix slug)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EMILY GURNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The wages of Hispanic workers in California lag
far behind those of other ethnic groups, and a corresponding lack
of education is the main culprit, according to a report done for
state legislators.
</P>
<P>
   With a median income of $14,560 per year, Hispanics make about
$8,000 less than the next-lowest group, blacks, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Increasing the wages of Hispanics, who will make up the state's
largest group of workers by 2025, will mean big dividends for
California, said state Senate Majority Leader Richard G. Polanco, a
Democrat from Los Angeles, who requested the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are able to realize a long-term goal of raising the
level of educational attainment of Latinos to that of non-Latinos,
the result would be $28 billion in increased earnings circulating
in our economy,'' Polanco said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics comprise 28 percent of the 15.6 million workers in the
state and their numbers are growing daily. ``The earnings and the
tax base that they represent, therefore, are vital to the state's
economy,'' the authors of the report wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by the California Research Bureau, an
office of the state library, was presented to the Senate Education
Committee, the Latino Legislative Caucus and the Hispanic
Republican Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest factor in the relatively low earnings of Hispanic
workers is education, said Elias Lopez, one of the authors of the
report that was released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the study, which was based in part on a U.S. Census
Bureau survey of 13,000 Californians in March 1998, more than 45
percent of Hispanic workers do not have a high school diploma, and
41 percent have only a high school diploma. Just 8 percent have a
bachelor's degree or higher.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, 33 percent of white workers have a bachelor's
degree or higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done is we've provided Latinos with prison
opportunities rather than educational opportunities,'' said Robert
Gnaizda, policy director for the Greenlining Institute, a public
policy and advocacy center based in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prison system has eaten up a huge amount of discretionary
money that could have gone to the expansion of higher education,''
said Gnaizda, who was not involved in the study. Since the early
1980s, California has built 23 prisons and no new universities, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of education is not limited to recent immigrants, but
persists even for third-generation Hispanics, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The authors recommend that California:
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to increase the numbers of Hispanic students who graduate
from high school and enroll in a four-year university.
</P>
<P>
   _ Encourage Hispanics currently in the work force to further
their educations.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia Becerril, a member of the San Francisco Board of
Supervisors, said the study was ``hardly a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The issues of low wages and dropout rates have been pointed
out over and over again,'' she said. ``There is a growing gap
between Latino families and other groups. It's an issue that should
be of concern, not just for Latinos, but for all Californians. It
will have an impact on the future of the quality of all our
lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BLUE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-19 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PERFECT BLUE': THIS CARTOON DIDN'T COME FROM DISNEY  
 (PRODUCTION NOTES AT END) 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mima is a wide-eyed, chirpy-voiced young woman with ambition. It
isn't enough that she's one-third of a fabulously successful
Japanese Spice Girls-like pop music group, Cham, whose members
bounce around the concert stage in pink dresses with huge bows in
the back and long white gloves. Mima is leaving Cham to begin an
acting career, and her story is ``Perfect Blue,'' a peculiar
example of Japanese animation _ realistic drawing, childish voice,
flashes of narrative skill.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things moviegoers will notice about Mima is
that she is either not very bright or she has been extremely out of
touch while becoming a music star. Someone actually has to explain
to her what the Internet is (which is why it's only now that she
discovers a worrisome Web site devoted to her). And as she prepares
to do a rape scene in her first acting role, on a television soap
opera, she observes, ``It's not as if they're really going to rape
me or anything.'' But maybe it's not Mima; maybe ``Perfect Blue''
is made for violence-happy 6-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble begins when Mima goes home after her final concert
with Cham. She receives a weird letter that says ``I love looking
at Mima's room,'' a telephone call from a heavy breather and a fax
that calls her a traitor. The next evening, after her first day on
the movie set, she gets home to find that all the fish in her
aquarium are dead and that her reflection _ some manifestation of
an alter ego? _ is talking to her. What the reflection says is
priceless: ``You're no longer a pop idol,'' it accuses. ``You're a
filthy woman now, like a slut. No one likes a pop idol with a
tarnished reputation.'' (They don't?) Then the alter ego emerges
into the room, floats across it and goes out the window. The alter
ego also giggles a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The plot goes on to involve a deranged young man who looks like
Michael Jackson with bad teeth, a truck accident, a murder by a
pizza delivery man and a diagnosis of dissociative personality
disorder. But it may be that none of this is real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perfect Blue'' eventually turns into a very interesting play
on levels and perceptions of reality. Before that, it includes
profanity, stabbing, strangling, hitting, lots of animated blood
and some animated nudity. With smarter dialogue, it might have made
a fascinating film.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   PERFECT BLUE
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Satoshi Kon; written by Sadayuki Murai based on the
novel by Yoshikazu Takeuchi and character design by Hisashi Eguchi;
dubbed in English; director of photography, Hisao Shirai; edited by
Harutoshi Ogata; music by Masahiro Ikumi; animation director,
Hideki Hamazu; production designer, Mitsusuke Hayakawa; produced by
Hiroaki Inoue and Masao Maruyama; released by Manga Entertainment.
Running time: 80 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1537EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2995 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      08-19 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARING VOICE IN YOUR HEAD NOT SO BAD IF IT'S PLEASANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Could it be true?
</P>
<P>
   Was I really hearing voices? I was dialing my friend Robert's
phone number when I heard it the first time. It was a woman's
voice, slow, low, and barely audible, even though I was alone.
</P>
<P>
   But just as soon as it started, the voice suddenly stopped, and
I kind of forgot about it when Robert picked up. He was the only
person I know who could get me out of my computer mess. He is so
technologically capable that he once built a kitchen clock out of
Nixie tubes. I didn't know what they were, either, but to me, that
just proves how smart he is.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard urban legends in which people buy a computer, take it
out of the box, plug it in and it actually works.
</P>
<P>
   Things like that just do not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Especially not to me.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way things work in my world. I'm never surprised
when I buy something new, I plug it in and it shorts out my
electricity, is missing a part or suddenly bursts into flames and
melts other appliances around it as well.
</P>
<P>
   So, really, how could I have been shocked when I unpacked my new
computer and spent four hours setting it up, only to discover that
as a couple, we were not hitting it off?
</P>
<P>
   It stared at me with a blank screen, hummed a little, and then
gently eased back into its technology coma. That's when I got up
and called Robert.
</P>
<P>
   He heard my cry and was at my door in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes,'' he said, probing and poking where all the wires are
attached to the monitor. ``I can see the problem here. At this
point, you have two alternatives: Send the computer back, or learn
how to push the monitor's ON button.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I settled down and went to work. I tried to print,
only to have my happy new computer inform me that it was going to
be utterly, utterly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   I was in the kitchen dialing Robert's number when I heard her _
the Voice _ speak to me again.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped and tried to make out the words, but I could only
understand one: ``serve.''
</P>
<P>
   This is impossible, I thought. There has to be an explanation
for this, a rational one like my dog yawning, or maybe she has some
bad gas.
</P>
<P>
   In an hour, Robert was poking at the wires again when he
mentioned, ``The printer only works when you plug it into the hard
drive. You plugged the printer back into itself. It's not a worm,
you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Much later that night, I was getting ready for bed. As I brushed
my teeth, the Voice came to me again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warning,'' she said to me in a mumble I could barely
understand. ``Serve the apple!''
</P>
<P>
   This time, I totally freaked out. Oh my God, I thought to
myself. Am I going crazy? Serve the apple? Is this like Son of Sam,
but only with a fruit? Son of Red Delicious? Am I possessed? Am I
going to start killing people on the advice from a member of one of
the four basic food groups?
</P>
<P>
   Then I heard her speak again: ``Serve the apple. Respond.''
</P>
<P>
   I was NOT imagining it. I HEARD it.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't sleep at all that night. I didn't understand what the
Voice wanted me to do. I decided that the Voice wasn't nasty, so it
probably wasn't a demon, and because it was a lady's voice, I
deduced that it probably had to be the Virgin Mary. I also decided
it would be smart not to say anything because I saw what happened
when someone thought they saw Jesus' face on a dirty wall someplace
near Nogales. People flocked from all around and they brought
tents. The last thing I needed was a yard full of people yelling
for me to heal them and asking to use my bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, I felt kinda holy. I felt chosen, and I was
excited about what the Mother of God had to say to me next, unless
it was, ``You could be so pretty if you just lost some weight.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as usual, as soon as I sat down to work, my computer
crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert,'' I said into the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be right there,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   Then I looked at the computer, and I got really mad. Nothing
works for me. Nothing, ever. It was really unfair. Stupid thing! I
hate it. I hate it. I HATE IT.
</P>
<P>
   And, before I even knew what I was doing, I had reached out and
smacked the screen with my very own hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not very saintly,'' a nosy-body voice in my head said.
``I'm telling the Virgin Mary!''
</P>
<P>
   When Robert arrived, he looked curiously at the computer and
then at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you been hurting this computer?'' he asked me, point
blank.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' I replied. ``No, I haven't been hurting it! It's been
hurting me!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I suspected a while ago that something wasn't right
here,'' he said sharply. ``You had all of these problems with it,
and I'd come over and fix them every time. But now, I see your hand
print on the screen, and you know what I think? I think you like
the attention you get when your computer's broken. In fact, I think
you break it on purpose. And that hand print is the proof I've been
waiting for!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert . . .'' I started.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no!'' he said standing up. ``You're sick! It's Munchausen
syndrome by proxy, I've seen your kind before! I'm calling CPS!
Computer Protective Services, you foul abuser!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Robert, that is ridiculous!'' I said adamantly, stamping my
foot. ``Do you think the Virgin Mary would talk to someone that
abuses her very own computer? I'm holy! I'm going to be serving the
holy apple, or something like that. She told me herself!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Serving the apple? With the Virgin Mother?'' Robert said,
unbelievingly. ``So what's she look like? Hmmm?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen her,'' I stammered. ``But I hear her all the
time!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah?'' he said, staring at me. ``Does she sound like. .
.this?''
</P>
<P>
   And then he reached over, pushed three keys.
</P>
<P>
   A voice suddenly popped up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warning! The server is not connected to the Apple remote
access and does not respond,'' my computer said in a lady's voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God,'' I said. ``I hit the Virgin Mary!'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her
column to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or by
e-mail to laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
