<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINGLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TEACHING MRS. TINGLE': EVERYONE GETS AN  ` A ' FOR THE DARK AGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There once was a nasty high school teacher who told Kevin
Williamson he couldn't write, little dreaming that Williamson had
the ``Scream'' movies, ``I Know What You Did Last Summer'' and
``Dawson's Creek'' in his future. As if these weren't hits with
enough of a vengeance, Williamson also dreamed up a story about a
teacher who is tied to her bed by three students and peppered with
taunts like: ``You know, you hide behind your degree. But the
reality is you're jealous of every student you teach!''
</P>
<P>
   In his first screenplay, best described as ``early,'' Williamson
delivered the dramatic equivalent of a mustache scrawled onto this
teacher's portrait. And he created the proudly teen-centric
attitude that would later give him such currency. (Girl, worried
about doing something unethical: ``It's not right.'' Boy,
shrugging: ``What's right any more?'') As for whatever else he
intended, there may someday be enough spare time for a director's
cut of the film that was to be called ``Killing Mrs. Tingle,'' and
has since been bastardized in response to rising high school
violence. Now, as ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' it's the incongruously
toothless version of a sadistic fantasy. Not the easiest mix.
</P>
<P>
   Newly benign, and noticeably clumsier than the hits he has
written, ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' Williamson's directorial debut,
relies hard on innocent coincidences. It begins with three high
school heroes in Mrs. Tingle's history class, where the aspiring
actress Jo Lynn (Marisa Coughlan, a strenuously vampy newcomer)
tries to make a point about the Kennedy administration by dressing
up as Marilyn Monroe. Leigh Ann (Katie Holmes) is the good student
working hard to win a scholarship, while Luke (Barry Watson) is the
white-bread rebel; when asked to hand in his history project, he
slaps a stone on Mrs. Tingle's desk and just says ``Plymouth
Rock.'' As for the teacher, she turns her acid tongue on one and
all.
</P>
<P>
   But by the purely accidental happenstance that has been
shoehorned into this story, the three students wind up with an
advance copy of Mrs. T's final exam. Not wanting to be caught
cheating, they make a house call. Meanwhile, one of the history
projects Mrs. Tingle took home with her happens to be a working
crossbow. Presto! It isn't long before one of those unexpected
crossbow accidents causes the teacher to injure herself through no
fault of the students, and they are forced to strap her wrists to
the bedposts.
</P>
<P>
   (What choice do they have? ``She'll press charges. Maybe we
should just finish her.'')
</P>
<P>
   Showing a rare sign of the tongue-in-cheek movie awareness that
worked for ``Scream,'' the film turns this into an occasion for Ms.
Coughlan's full-throttle ``Exorcist'' imitation of Linda Blair
thrashing and shrieking her way through demonic possession. (``You
know, she kind of looks like that movie. The demon chick that
upchucks over everything.'')
</P>
<P>
   Having locked his actors into position, Williamson comes up with
surprisingly little for them to do. His film, however, does prove
that Ms. Mirren can outshine a cute teen-age cast with her hands
tied. She is so prickly and versatile, in fact, that she's far too
good for these circumstances and seems badly miscast in the role of
a one-note classroom martinet.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the Mrs. Tingle seen grading papers in silk
pajamas has nothing to do with her schoolroom incarnation, but
that's no more inconsistent than the rest of the story. And the
students' plot to take pornographic pictures of the teacher with a
goofball gym coach (Jeffrey Tambor) may once have been more
honestly kinky. But here, played as idiotic slapstick, it's beneath
one and all.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut,'' which so
winkingly mocked crassness in popular culture, ``Teaching Mrs.
Tingle'' is content to be part of the problem. Played almost
straight are Jo Lynn's complaint about the lack of a television
chez Tingle (``I mean, it's like not having toilet paper!''), the
film's efforts to turn the teacher's capture into a romantic
occasion for her students, and a sex scene so laughably perfunctory
that the characters barely remember it when it's over. Nor is the
script quite kidding when it has Leigh Ann say, ``I'm gonna burn in
hell for this,'' and Luke answer, ``It'll be a party.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `TEACHING MRS. TINGLE'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' is rated PG-13 (Parents
strongly cautioned). It includes profanity, brief sexual
situations, violence played for laughs, and the idea that
assaulting a teacher is a smart way to solve problems at school.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Kevin Williamson; director of
photography, Jerzy Zielinski; edited by Debra Neil-Fisher; music by
John Frizzell; production designer, Naomi Shohan; produced by Cathy
Konrad; released by Dimension Films. Running time: 93 minutes. This
film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Helen Mirren (Mrs. Tingle), Katie Holmes (Leigh Ann
Watson), Jeffrey Tambor (Coach Wenchell), Barry Watson (Luke
Churner), Marisa Coughlan (Jo Lynn Jordan), Liz Stauber (Trudie
Tucker), Michael McKean (Principal Potter), Molly Ringwald (Miss
Banks) and Vivica A. Fox (Miss Gold).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
