<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBING-RANGE-$ADV22-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUERTO RICO HOPES TO COPY HAWAII'S VICTORY OVER U.S. NAVY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Aug. 22)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ As Puerto Rico battles the U.S. Navy over
a World War II-era bombing range on this Caribbean island, local
residents talk of ``Kaho'olawe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaho'olawe?''
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico's political leaders and allies in Congress are
pointing to Hawaii's ouster of the U.S. Navy from a bombing range
on the island of Kaho'olawe in 1994 as a precedent for the Puerto
Rican effort to evict the Navy from a 58-year-old bombing range on
the island of Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Ricans, civil rights leader Jesse Jackson and some
members of Congress are demanding a permanent end to the Navy's and
Marine Corps' target practice on 22,000 acres owned by the Navy.
Some 9,300 civilians share the island with the military.
</P>
<P>
   The eviction demand stems from a Marine Corps' bombing mishap in
April that killed a Puerto Rican security guard on contract with
the Navy, David Sanes Rodriguez, 35, and injured four others.
Target practice has been suspended since.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Vieques is very similar to the island in
Hawaii that the Navy bombed from 1941 to 1990,'' says Puerto Rico
Attorney General Jose A. Fuentes Agostini. The big difference is
that the Navy ``gave that island back to the people of Hawaii,''
says Agostini.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carlos Romero-Barcelo, D-Puerto Rico, the non-voting
representative in Congress for 3.8 million U.S. citizens in Puerto
Rico, says Hawaii prevailed in its dispute with the Navy because of
the political clout of Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, then chairman
of the Senate Appropriations Committee's panel on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his persistence _ coupled with the intense lobbying of
the congressional delegation from Hawaii _ that ensured that the
Navy would stop using an uninhabited island for military maneuvers
and return Kaho'olawe island to the state of Hawaii,'' says
Romero-Barcelo.
</P>
<P>
   The island of Vieques, once a sugar cane-growing center, lies
thousands of miles from Kaho'olawe, a 28,776-acre former Hawaiian
penal colony located about 90 miles southeast of Honolulu.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are many parallels.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy began using both islands for target practice at the
outset of World War II. Later, the islands helped combat units
prepare for wars in Korea and Vietnam. For years, the Navy resisted
local demands to cease live-fire operations and return the islands
to local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   But the fate of the island bombing ranges differs _ at least so
far.
</P>
<P>
   President George Bush ordered an end to live-fire training on
Kaho'olawe on Oct. 22, 1990. Three years later, Inouye inserted a
provision in the fiscal 1994 defense budget that required the Navy
to turn over the island to local authorities by 2004 after a $400
million cleanup of unexploded ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's far-flung Pacific fleet has since shifted live-fire
training operations to San Clemente Island, a 36,000-acre island
about 60 miles off the southern California coast owned by the Navy
since the early 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy had a fall back at San Clemente,'' says Navy Lt. Cdr.
Herman Phillips, a Navy spokesman at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials say they don't have a comparable fall back
training facility along the Atlantic Coast to match the $720
million Vieques range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pacific fleet had redundancy in the system and the ability
to shift operations to San Clemente,'' says Phillips said. ``We
don't have the ability to fall back to another location for the
Atlantic fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Puerto Rico's political leaders attribute Hawaii's success
to the fact that it has the political power of a state compared to
the limited political power of a U.S. territory like Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Puerto Rico are U.S. citizens. But they do not pay
federal taxes; they do not vote for president; and they do not have
full voting members in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Romero-Barcelo, Puerto Rico's lone non-voting representative in
Congress, says demands for Navy withdrawal from Vieques would
``already have been heeded if we had two senators and a
congressional delegation with the power to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jose Serrano D-N.Y., whose New York City congressional
district includes a large number of voters born in Puerto Rico,
says the bombing accident on Vieques would trigger an immediate
outcry in Congress if Puerto Rico had full representation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would bombing continue if someone had been killed during a
military exercise on Long Island?'' Serrano asks. ``Of course not.
The Navy must stop treating the residents of Puerto Rico as
second-class citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   But Navy Secretary Richard Danzig says Puerto Rico's status as a
U.S. territory without full voting representation in Congress is
irrelevant to the issue at hand. American armed forces conduct
live-fire training at 57 sites across the United States, with 56 of
the locations ``well-represented by congressmen and senators,''
Danzig says.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's contention that live-fire training is essential ``is
really not influenced by the character of their congressional
representation,'' Danzig said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Navy won a powerful ally last week. Army Gen. Wesley Clark,
commander of NATO forces that prevailed in a 78-day bombing
campaign against Serbian occupation forces in Kosovo, credited live
fire training on Vieques for helping to ``ensure that the forces
assigned to this theater were ready on arrival and prepared to
fight, win and survive.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, Clark warned that loss of live fire training such as
provided on Vieques would be ``unconscionable, cause undue
casualties and place our nation's vital interest at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton awaits recommendations from a four-member
Pentagon review panel appointed to craft a compromise between
Puerto Rico and the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official said last week the panel expects to submit
its report to Defense Secretary William Cohen by Aug. 31. Cohen
will then review the recommendations before submitting a proposed
compromise to the White House, probably after Labor Day, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
