<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     08-19 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _
</P>
<P>
   Sweating Out The Numbers
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Grant was padding around his sleek and expansive suite at
L'Ermitage in Beverly Hills this week, barefoot in a pair of simple
white pants and a wrinkled blue T-shirt. He had been promoting his
brains out for weeks now _ ``I'm even talking to the British press,
which is astounding'' _ and could hardly wait for the opening on
Friday of his new film, ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' a romantic comedy
about a high-art auctioneer who discovers that his schoolteacher
girlfriend is the daughter of a mobster .
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the point now where we're getting the tracking
information every day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The studio's market-research team was finding out whether people
had heard of the film, whether its name sprang to their minds
unaided or had to be prompted, whether they intended to see it and,
if so, whether it would be this weekend. The tension was palpable,
and rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately we had some good numbers this morning, but it's
still so stressful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant had been absent from movie screens for nearly three years
before appearing earlier this summer with Julia Roberts in
``Notting Hill.'' ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' which was made by Grant's
production company, was finished before ``Notting Hill,'' but wise
heads had concluded that it might be better to release it second,
getting a nice bounce off Ms. Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   The story was one of several that Grant had been developing; the
idea was to show ``a Brit meeting the mob, which is something we
haven't seen on the screen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Why was he gone so long? He hadn't been taking a vacation, he
said, as much as waiting for something he truly loved to come
along. ``I'm not one of those people who must act to live,'' he
said. ``I must truly love something before I can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   So now, the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be over until Friday,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   Studio people will fan out across America to the first
screenings at important theaters, and by the time heads are counted
at that first 11 a.m. screening, they will know, almost to the
cent, whether their tracking research was correct and how much the
film will make in its opening weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frightening,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't like all the focus groups, market research and
overriding emphasis on the opening weekend. ``It's so destructive
to the filmmaking process,'' he said. ``What was wrong with the way
they used to release films, more slowly, let them build?''
</P>
<P>
   But he is the beast's meal of the week and doesn't much enjoy
the sensation. ``It is really quite true and palpable that you can
walk into a restaurant on the Monday after your film opens and tell
by the way people look at you and the table that you get how your
film did over the previous weekend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So why go out to a restaurant that Monday? He shrugged. ``If I
didn't,'' he said, ``my life would be nothing but room service
meals and deciding which of the three big-screen TV's in this suite
to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, he said, at least one good acting role was
``knocking at my door,'' but he was not sure that he wanted to do
it. ``What I'd really like to do is spend the fall in the South of
France, writing a script,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Take That, Teach!
</P>
<P>
   The screenwriter Kevin Williamson didn't get along with an
English teacher he had for two years in North Carolina. ``She
didn't like me for some reason,'' he said. ``I couldn't figure out
why. When you're 15 or 16 you never know why the teacher is being
mean to you.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he said, he worked his heart out on a short story
about an ugly-duckling student involved in a date rape. His teacher
read the story aloud and ``could find not a single good word to say
about it,'' eviscerating him in front of the whole class. ``She
ripped it up and said to me that I had a voice that shouldn't be
heard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, he believed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stopped writing for many years,'' he said, and was 28 or 29
before be picked it up again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a hard place, working as an assistant to someone here
in Hollywood, a desk job, sort of in the wasteland of life,'' he
said. ``I decided: I've got to do something. I'm got to figure out
what I'm going to do with the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, now 34, is one of Hollywood's latest interpreters of
the young-adult mind-set, with his successful screenplays for
``Scream'' and ``I Know What You Did Last Summer'' and the
television series ``Dawson's Creek.'' Now he has directed his first
feature film, ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' a kind of poison-laced
revenge saga aimed at that English teacher from long ago. The film
opens on Friday .
</P>
<P>
   This script was the first thing he wrote when he returned to
writing five years ago. The title used to be ``Killing Mrs.
Tingle'' but was changed after the student killings in Littleton,
Colo. The movie is a dark comedy about three students who
accidentally injure their hated history teacher, played by an icy
Helen Mirren, and then take her hostage.
</P>
<P>
   He sold the script immediately, Williamson said. But producers
were put off by the way his teen-agers talked. ``They didn't find
it realistic,'' he said. ``They had this adult view of what the
teen-age experience would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Only after ``Scream'' and ``Dawson's Creek'' did Williamson's
clever and media-savvy teen-agers ring true to the studio
executives; ears, and so ``Tingle'' was finally made.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is at work on ``Wasteland,'' a new television series,
and plans to direct a second film, a romantic comedy, later this
year or early next.
</P>
<P>
   The English teacher who belittled him, he said, died several
years ago, but he really bears no lasting anger. Truly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She turned out to be a very positive experience in my life,''
he said. ``Yes, I learned, there is another way to teach children
so that they can learn the lesson without being infected with the
seeds of hatred. The trick is to believe in yourself and not let
them tear you down. Good will always rise above.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Do-Right Thing
</P>
<P>
   A group of hustling young producers was trying to come up with a
high-concept idea to transform into a studio deal when the
girlfriend of one of them suggested, hey, why not make a movie
based on the ``Dudley Do-Right'' cartoons?
</P>
<P>
   OK, it wasn't an apple falling on Newton's head or Watt
contemplating a steam kettle. But inspiration comes where you can
find it in the movie business.
</P>
<P>
   This was six or seven years ago, when J. Todd Harris was in
partnership with a couple of other guys. He approached the people
who controlled the rights to the work of Dudley's creator, the
animator Jay Ward, who died in 1989. They already had a
relationship with Universal Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We managed to finesse the beginnings of a deal into place,''
Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably there were false starts and hiccups. Finally, hot
from the success of ``First Wives Club,'' the director Hugh Wilson
became interested in the project. And Brendan Fraser , who had
already played another Ward character, ``George of the Jungle,''
came aboard. Universal, which has a film based on his Rocky and
Bullwinkle, mixing animation and live actors, in the works for next
summer, became more interested in the Ward canon. And so the film
about Dudley, the bumbling Canadian mountie, was made, with Fraser
starring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing was that I had come to Hollywood after
Stanford Business School with the intention of making studio
movies, but instead I got involved in one small independent film
after another, and this turns out to be the first studio film I
ever was involved with,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   He had been running a theater company in Palo Alto, Calif., for
a few years when he decided it was time to try to crash Hollywood.
He borrowed $20,000 from his grandfather and spent nine months
courting people, raising a pool of production money. ``I really
wanted to be a producer, so I put together this business plan where
I figured I could get 25 or 30 people to give me $2,500 or
$3,000,'' he said. ``In the end a couple even gave me $10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   He made the rounds, got studio deals put together but quickly
realized that the studios were buying 10 ideas for every movie that
was made. It was frustrating. And his investors were no closer to
making money on their investment.
</P>
<P>
   So he turned to independent films, had some small successes like
``Digging to China'' and ``Denise Calls Up.'' But only now, with
the release of ``Dudley Do-Right'' on Aug. 27, will he be able to
begin passing some significant money to his investors, most of whom
were Stanford classmates.
</P>
<P>
   If he has one more studio release, he'll be able to pay them out
in full, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making `Dudley' has certainly refired me to do other large
studio movies,'' he said. ``Every time I make an independent film,
it's like starting a new company with $2 million. With Universal
backing a film, you have a lot of that done for you. I remember
going into my first meeting at Universal after the movie was
green-lit and there were something like 30 people around the table.
I almost broke into tears of joy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
