<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3031 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COX-CYBERSQUATTERS-08     08-19 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CYBERSQUATTERS-0820 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CYBERSQUATTERS AND NET PARODIES MAY FACE THE LAW
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) Politics categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Last October, an enterprising Californian named Chris
Hayden paid $70 for exclusive two-year rights to the Internet
address www.hillary2000.com. For good measure, Hayden bought
www.clinton2000.com and www.hillaryclinton2000.com , also for the
same low price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it on a lark,'' Hayden, an environmental consultant,
said in a cell phone interview as he drove down a freeway in Costa
Mesa. ``It looked to me as if she had a future in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, as the First Lady prepared to seek a Senate seat
from New York, the Clinton camp offered to buy www.hillary2000.com
. ``Their price was unreasonable and I declined to sell,'' Hayden
said.
</P>
<P>
   So Hayden listed the three Clinton names with an online broker,
asking $15,000 apiece for them. Meantime, the political Web sites
remain dormant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, everybody in politics needs a Web name,'' Hayden
said.
</P>
<P>
   The nascent Clinton Senate campaign chose www.hillary2000.org .
As it happens, typing www.hillary200.org, skipping the last ``0,''
brings up precisely the same graphical layout _ but it is a parody
page with a different message.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Rodham Clinton will continue her listening tour in
some god-forsaken upstate cow towns this week, touting a carpetbag
full of magical adventures,'' the fake Clinton site reports.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton caricatures, and others like them in the growing
realm of cyberspace, pit constitutional guarantees of free speech
against charges of intellectual property theft. These
countervailing issues are being widely tested in the courts, with
no clear outcome in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Hayden's purchase, known as ``cybersquatting,'' would also be
illegal if a bill that enjoys wide bipartisan support in Congress
becomes law. The measure, which cleared the Senate Judiciary
Committee last month, would bar the use of Internet addresses,
known as domains, that are identical to, or confusingly
</P>
<P>
   similar to, distinctive trademarks or service names.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who helped steer the
anti-cybersquatter measure through his committee, voiced an even
greater interest in its passage after a Miami entrepreneur named
Joseph Culligan sought $45,000 to enable the senator's presidential
campaign to deploy www.presidenthatch.com on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just happening to me,'' the senator told the
Associated Press. ``It's happening to most celebrities and people
known in business. Someone tries to tie up their name. It isn't
right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are search engines and hot links available online that
will let you find your way around without typing in an address,''
said Dan Turkette, a Web developer in Fort Wayne, Ind. Thus, simply
typing a candidate's name into a search engine can bring up
literally scores of Web addresses _ some genuine, others decidedly
off-color.
</P>
<P>
   Turkette, who owns www.politicallycorrect.com and is offering to
sell it for $2.5 million, noted: ``Consumers deal on the basis of
brand awareness. That's why domain names can be quite valuable.''
Last week, for instance, an anonymous buyer paid $823,456 in an
auction for www.drugs.com. . The cost of initially registering a
Web site is only $35 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Wild West out there,'' said Benjamin Ginsberg,
general counsel for Texas Gov. George W. Bush's bid for the
Republican presidential nomination, referring to Internet
practices.
</P>
<P>
   In December, Zack Exley, a Boston computer programmer,
registered www.gwbush.com . Ginsberg said Exley sought to sell the
name to the Bush campaign for $380,000, only to later cut his
asking price to $80,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was just hysterical for me to be negotiating with
the Bush campaign,'' Exley, 29, said. He disputes Ginsberg's
figures as ``way too high.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp claimed www.georgewbush.com as its official
campaign Web site. Belatedly, a top Bush honcho, Karl Rove, bought
up another 260 Bush-related domain names and linked them all to the
prime address.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hayden, Exley isn't a ``cybersquatter.'' Having failed to
make a bargain, he operates www.gwbush.com as a parody site. It has
received more than 1.2 million visits, well beyond the circulation
of many political magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Exley also sells satirical Bush T-shirts on the Web. ``It's just
for fun,'' says the online entrepreneur. ``I doubt I'm breaking
even and I won't be giving up my day job.''
</P>
<P>
   At a May press conference in Austin, Bush branded Exley ``a
garbage man'' and said ``there ought to be limits to freedom.''
Exley said he plans to offer Bush's taped comments to visitors,
``pointing up his incredible position on free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Ginsberg has written the Federal Elections Commission
seeking a ruling that would compel Exley to register as a political
action committee and to disclose his Web expenses. The commission
is expected to rule soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running a Web site is no different then sending a letter,''
Exley said in rebuttal. ``The FEC shouldn't get involved in this.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all observers see it his way.
</P>
<P>
   Said Paul Kedrosky, a professor at Canada's University of
British Columbia who specializes in online business concerns:
</P>
<P>
   ``Something must be done. The issue matters to everyone, from
corporations to political campaigns. It matters to businesses
trying to protect trademarks and expensively gained brands on the
net. It matters to news organizations trying to make sure that when
you say something comes (from them), it actually (does).
</P>
<P>
   ``Because without the kinds of property protections that exist
in the offline world, the online world is just a cheap bazaar, and
a home for intellectual property break-and-enter masquerading as
free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
