<HEADER>
A3049 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLARK-READINESS-HNS &LR;      08-19 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLARK-READINESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO CHIEF ENTERS DISPUTE OVER BOMBING RANGE IN PUERTO RICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The commander of NATO underscored the Pentagon's
widening campaign to regain use of an island bombing range in
Puerto Rico, warning in a letter obtained Thursday that American
forces ``may not be fully combat ready'' without resumption of
live-fire training on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the commander of American and allied
military forces in Europe, said in the letter that realistic
combat-style training on Vieques enabled Navy aviators and the
Marine Corps to arrive in Kosovo ready for combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The live-fire training that our forces were exposed to at
training ranges such as Vieques helped ensure that the forces
assigned to this theater were `ready on arrival' and prepared to
fight, win and survive,'' Clark said in a letter to Gen. Henry
Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs, that was dated Aug. 16. A
copy of the letter was obtained by the Hearst Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he was ``concerned'' that the four-month moratorium
on training on Vieques means that ``the naval forces that will be
assigned to (the European Command) in the future may not be fully
combat ready to perform their assigned missions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said deploying U.S. forces with ``less than this optimum
training in the future would be unconscionable, cause undue
casualties and place our nation's vital interests at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's letter to Shelton is the second time in less than a
month that a senior U.S. military officer has expressed concern
that Atlantic-based forces will suffer diminished combat readiness
without the use of the 11,000-acre maneuver area and 899-acre
live-fire impact range on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Adm. William J. Fallon, the Atlantic fleet commander
responsible for preparing naval forces for deployment to Europe and
the Middle East, warned a Pentagon panel on July 23 that live-fire
training must resume on Vieques by September or the aircraft
carrier USS Dwight D. Eisenhower will deploy to Europe later this
year with ``serious deficiencies'' in combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of a Marine Corps' bombing accident on April 19
that killed a Puerto Rican security guard and wounded four other
civilians, Puerto Rico's political leaders and allies in Congress
are demanding that the Navy withdraw from the 58-year-old bombing
range on Vieques and relinquish 22,000 acres of property to local
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Navy officials say they cannot find alternative bombing ranges
along the Atlantic Coast to match the $720 million facility on
Vieques where land, sea and air forces can practice combat
operations with explosive ordnance.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton awaits recommendations from a Pentagon review
panel that is scheduled to submit a preliminary report to Defense
Secretary William Cohen by Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Navy and Marine Corps' combat commanders planned to
underscore the value of live-fire training on Vieques in
closed-door testimony to the Pentagon panel scheduled Friday. The
island is located 8 miles off the east coast of Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
e-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
