</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE CAUCASUS REGION: WHERE OIL, WATER NOT MIXING?
 &HT;    With RUSSIA-CAUCASUS-$ADV22.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE TROUBLED CAUCASUS
</P>
<P>
   Armenia, Azerbaijan and Georgia declared independence as the
Soviet Union disintegrated early in this decade. Russia managed to
retain control within its federation several other territories in
the northern Caucasus Mountains, but lost Chechnya in a bloody war
that ended in 1996, and now is fighting to retain control of
Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   A LOOK AT THE REGION:
</P>
<P>
   The Independent Republics:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Armenia _ Population: 3.8 million; predominately Christian
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Azerbaijan _ Population: 7.7 million; predominately Muslim
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Georgia _ Population: 5.4 million; predominately Christian
</P>
<P>
   The Breakaway Republic:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chechnya _ Population 1 million; predominately Muslim
</P>
<P>
   The Russian Federation Republics:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Russia _ Population 146 million (about 8 million in Caucasus
region)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stavropol: 2.6 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dagestan: 2 million
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  North Ossetia-Alania: 660,000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Adygeya: 450,000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Karachayevo-Cherkessia: 440,000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kabardino-Balkaria: 800,000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ingushetia: 300,000
</P>
<P>
   CAUCASUS CONFLICTS SINCE THE DECLINE OF THE SOVIET UNION
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Russia vs. rebels in Dagestan
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Russia vs. Chechnya
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Georgia vs. Abkhazia
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Georgia vs. South Ossetia
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  North Ossetia-Alania vs. Ingushetia
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Azerbaijan vs. Nagorno-Karabakh with Armenia
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
