<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COOLER-REVIEW-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A COOLER CLIMATE': WORTHWHILE, BUT A LITTLE TOO PAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Isn't it great when people say, ``What's the worst that could
happen?'' Go on, talk to him (or her), they say. What's the
absolute worst thing that can possibly happen as a result? It won't
go well; you'll get dismissed (or divorced); you'll move on.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the puritanically named Iris Prue (Sally Field), a
fairly upscale, jewelry-wearing 45-year-old wife and mother. Iris
has an affair with a younger man, divorces her husband and refuses
alimony or even community property because ``Oliver and I want to
start fresh.'' Then Oliver leaves her.
</P>
<P>
   With no money, no house, no car, no sympathy from her daughter
the lawyer, and absolutely no job skills, Iris discovers what the
worst is: taking a job as a live-in maid at a rich couple's summer
house in Maine. She works for the haughty sunglasses-wearing,
convertible-driving, tennis-playing Paula Tanner (Judy Davis), who
makes Iris scrub the kitchen floor on her knees and never says
thank you for anything.
</P>
<P>
   That is Iris' fate in ``A Cooler Climate,'' a Showtime movie
with impeccable credentials that has its premiere on Sunday night.
The script, based on a novel by Zena Collier, is by Marsha Norman,
a Pulitzer Prize winner for her play ``'Night, Mother.'' The
director is Susan Seidelman, best known for the film ``Desperately
Seeking Susan.'' The combination of this team with Ms. Field and
Ms. Davis might have added up to award-worthy drama. But ``A Cooler
Climate'' is not particularly complex, its solutions are too pat,
and it ends up simpering rather than affecting.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the opportunity to watch two fine actresses make these
characters and situations sympathetic and believable while tackling
issues like class, divorce and mother-daughter relationships makes
it more worthwhile than the average television movie.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Things do not remain the same in the Tanner household for long.
Paula's husband, Leo (Jerry Wasserman), comes back from Paris long
enough to bring some Broadway friends home for a weekend (they
adore Iris) and to get caught calling his latest girlfriend on the
home phone. Soon Leo decides to end the marriage, and Paula takes
to her bed in an ugly bathrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Iris, in the tradition of all 20th-century feminist
heroines, is transformed. She meets a great guy at a bookstore.
(This little town in Maine seems to be filled with available,
attractive middle-aged residents.) ``We're all dreamers and
runaways,'' explains Jack (Winston Rekert), the executive turned
sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   Iris takes a class to learn computer skills. She gains the quiet
confidence of Gloria Steinem. She develops a better relationship
with Paula's daughter, Beth (Carly Pope) _ a reckless young thing
who brings home a boyfriend who likes to walk around the house
naked _ than she has with her own daughter. All in just a few
fun-filled months. Not to give away the exact ending, let's just
say that only in movies do employers decide that all those years of
giving dinner parties and serving on charity committees make a
woman qualified for an executive job with an assistant of her own
and a desk the size of China.
</P>
<P>
   Jack is so sensitive that his fondest wish is for Iris to stay
with him all night, so he can wake up with her. And their sex scene
features a much-too-artfully draped sheet. But the worst scene of
all is the bookstore reading. As Graham, the store owner, Gerard
Plunkett manages to set back the portrayal of gay characters on
screen about a hundred years. The reading is the balcony scene from
``Romeo and Juliet.'' (Ooh, these small-town people are well read.)
And Graham announces that he's working on a version of
``Moby-Dick'' but without the whale. You don't want to know the
title.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `A COOLER CLIMATE'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Sunday on Showtime
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by Marsha Norman and based on the novel by Zena
Collier. Susan Seidelman, director; John Bartley, director of
photography. Music by Patrick Williams. Susan Rose and Daniel
Paulson, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sally Field (Iris), Judy Davis (Paula), Winston Rekert
(Jack), Jerry Wasserman (Leo), Carly Pope (Beth), Jessalyn Gilsig
(Callie), Gerard Plunkett (Graham), Alec Willows (Marcus) Denalda
Williams (Yvonne) and Peter Yunker (Oliver).
</P>
</TEXT>
