<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i BC-IRELAND-PEACE-$ADV22-     08-19 1721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-PEACE-$ADV22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROSPECTS FOR PEACE IN NORTHERN IRELAND IN DANGER OF COLLAPSE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Aug. 22 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland _ On a sunny mid-August afternoon,
two painters on scaffolds work on a three-story mural portrait of a
girl with a haunting gaze.
</P>
<P>
   A lone figure watches intently from the sidewalk below. William
McGavigan stoops slightly with his hands tucked in his trouser
pockets. He stands motionless in the cool breeze, which whips the
locks of his white hair. The girl is his daughter, Annette, who was
shot to death 28 years ago during the dark days here in the
Bogside, the Catholic neighborhood that has endured the worst of
The Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   McGavigan, a retired truck driver, says he will never forget
Annette, who was 14 when she was struck by one errant police
bullet. ``She was just eating an ice lolly, and then she was
dead,'' he says. ``She was such a lovely girl.''
</P>
<P>
   As he watches and remembers, McGavigan also worries. Northern
Ireland's fragile peace is in clear danger of collapse. A short
walk from the mural, workers on Wednesday were clearing charred
debris from a shop torched during an outbreak of rioting last
Saturday. A block away, the road was scorched by the outline of a
car set afire during the disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   These images raise the chilling specter of the sectarian
violence that killed Annette and thousands more over the years. The
peace process was supposed to render such images a thing of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's going well, not well at all,'' McGavigan
says as he watches the artists work around his daughter's soft
brown eyes. ``So, many people have suffered, so many people have
been lost.''
</P>
<P>
   A year after Northern Ireland was supposed to begin charting its
own future with a government comprising both sides of the bitter
divide, the momentum in the peace process has ground to a halt and
threatens to slip into reverse.
</P>
<P>
   The peace deal was heralded by President Clinton during his
triumphant tour of Ireland last September, and it won Nobel Peace
prizes for its main architects, Unionist leader David Trimble and
Republican John Hume.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrations now seem premature as the process has been
reduced to a sobering struggle with old realities of mistrust and
enmity.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble's Unionists, who support Northern Ireland's continuing
as part of Britain, refuse to enter into the government with its
longtime adversary Sinn Fein, the political arm of the Irish
Republican Army. Both Sinn Fein and the IRA want Northern Ireland
to become part of the Republic of Ireland to the South.
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point is the Unionist demand that the IRA surrender
its weapons before Sinn Fein takes its place in the would-be
government.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sinn Fein has argued that such a disarmament _ referred
to here as ``decommissioning'' _ is not required by the 1998 Good
Friday peace accord. Sinn Fein insists that decommissioning will
commence once the Unionists show good faith by allowing the
coalition government to be seated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's an ideal world and a perfect political process
where people trusted each other then maybe we would be further
along,'' said Mitchell McGlaughlin, the Sinn Fein chairman for
Northern Ireland. ``But why do people have guns in the first place?
It bespeaks a lack of confidence, a lack of trust in rival
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have seen from the IRA is a cessation of their
military campaign. We don't see operations carried out at the rate
of four or five a day. We don't see mortar bomb attacks. We don't
have car bomb explosions. We don't have sniper attacks on the
security forces. People want more, yes. But at what cost?''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of talks, in which British Prime Minister
Tony Blair has taken a major personal role, there seems little room
for progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think clearly the situation _ and the agreement _ is
unraveling and I think there is a failure of politics,'' said Sinn
Fein official Martin McGuinness last week(CQ) during talks in
Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   Things have deteriorated so far that former U.S. Sen. George
Mitchell, the arbiter of the peace accord, has been summoned to
help. Mitchell is scheduled to conduct a review of the situation
next month, with both sides expressing confidence that he will find
the other at fault.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating an already complex issue, the Unionists are
accusing the IRA of violating its two-year-old cease-fire, an
allegation that could lead to Sinn Fein's being expelled from the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA has been implicated in five murders since the start of
the peace process in April 1998 as well as a foiled attempt to
smuggle arms from the United States. The IRA has denied having a
role in these incidents, but the denials have been widely
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   The Unionists last week(CQ) repeatedly expressed their
determination to stick by their guns. ``The Ulster Unionist Party
is steadfast in its resolution that no terrorist-linked party will
participate in executive government in Northern Ireland now or
ever,'' said Ken Maginnis, the party spokesman. ``Government must
deal with terrorist organizations and terrorist-linked parties
according to the promises that were made to us the day the
agreement was signed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leaders argue that the incidents -- even if proven
true -- do not constitute a violation of the IRA's pledge to end
its military campaign. They also seem to argue that the cease-fire
remains in force because the five people killed were Catholics, in
one recent case a police informant.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Unionists are pressuring Marjorie ``Mo''
Mowlam, the British Northern Ireland secretary, to declare that the
cease-fire has been breached. Mowlam met through the week with both
sides as well as police authorities. She is expected to issue a
ruling early next week after consulting with Blair.
</P>
<P>
   She has little choice but to infuriate hardliners on one side or
the other. If she fails to appear tough enough on the IRA, the
Unionists have hinted they will walk away from the peace process.
If she moves to expel Sinn Fein she will provoke the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians worry that if something doesn't happen people
will give up on the political process. ``Unless we are producing
evidence that the political process is working people are going to
conclude that the politicians have let them down yet again,'' said
McGlaughlin, the Sinn Fein leader who is also a city councilman in
Londonderry. ``I can see quite clear evidence that there is an
evaporation of the confidence that was so manifest a year or a year
and half ago,''
</P>
<P>
   The process and its rhetoric have tended to confirm rather than
dismiss the distrust that has plagued any move for compromise for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes our job of selling the idea of political discourse
between the Republicans and the British government and Republicans
and Unionists that much harder,'' McGlaughlin said. ``For all of us
this entails great risks and challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   For Margaret Wair the failure of the political process is a
foregone conclusion. Her apartment in a drab Protestant
neighborhood of Belfast is festooned with Unionist flags
celebrating the Marching Season. Each year, Unionists hold marches,
often through Catholic neighborhoods, to commemorate the 1689
Protestant victory over the Catholics in Ireland that maintained
British rule. This season, which closes at the end of the month,
has been one
</P>
<P>
   of the most confrontational in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I love the marching season,'' she says, admiring the
flags. ``I'll keep them up 'til I replace them with my Christmas
lights.''
</P>
<P>
   She has three sons, but Wair sees little prospect that they will
grow into manhood in an undivided community. ``There can't be no
peace, never,'' Wair says. ``There's just too much hatred, too much
hatred on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, Martin Watson shares a Guinness or two with
his friends in a Catholic pub. The entrance is protected by a steel
cage and above the bar where you would expect to find a soccer game
on the television is the pale blue flicker of a security monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Watson has enjoyed the peace and hopes it will last. ``Now I can
walk the street without worrying every time a car stops behind
me,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He remains hopeful about the process. ``Nobody wants to go back
to war,'' he says. ``I can't see Mo Mowlam coming out against the
IRA. But if she does, that could be the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Already there are signs of a return to the old ways. Last
weekend, a march by the Apprentice Boys through Londonderry sparked
a riot that led to the unleashing of more than 100 gasoline bombs
and the burning of businesses and cars in the city's center. On
Wednesday, police officers and British soldiers in armored cars set
up a roadblock on the road between Londonderry after a long
absence.
</P>
<P>
   These were familiar and unsettling images.
</P>
<P>
   ``My clear view is that if we don't make the Good Friday work,
then those conditions for conflict which continue to exist will
reassert themselves,'' McGlaughlin said. ``We know what fills a
political vacuum anywhere in any society and we certainly have
experience with that over the last 30 years here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Bogside portrait of Annette McGavigan are two important
symbols: A rifle and a butterfly. Tom Kelly, one of the artists,
says the rifle represents violence and the butterfly represents
metamorphosis _ the prospect of change.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly worries that rifle may yet win out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people out there who are planning to foster the
notion that the peace is dead and create the climate for that to
happen,'' Kelly said. ``But the overwhelming majority are aspiring
for peace and are fed up with the politicians. If you were to round
up all our politicians and give them a long weekend here on their
own or in Bosnia, it might do them a world of good.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might just learn that peace is essential, and that the
prospects of change and growth far outweigh one or two issues no
matter how serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might learn that answers have to be found, and that
violence is used only by those who feel powerless.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
