u e BC-MICKEY-FILM-REVIEW-NY     08-19 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICKEY-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MICKEY BLUE EYES': BRITON, TO WED A MAFIA DOLL, GOES TO A
TRATTORIA ... 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Try as he might, Michael Felgate (Hugh Grant), a cultivated,
mild-mannered Englishman engaged to the daughter of a genial Mafia
chieftain, can't seem to deliver the phrase ``forget about it''
with the sinister heft that his future in-laws can. Michael's
inability to give ``fuhgeddaboutit'' and other spicier phrases a
suitably streetwise punch is one of the cute running of jokes of
``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' a lightweight comedy that has more than
enough laughs to justify its silly, scatterbrained premise.
</P>
<P>
   The role of Mickey, an ingenuous English twit who runs a snooty
auction house in midtown Manhattan, fits Grant almost too smoothly.
Bringing his signature bashful-boy mannerisms to the role _ the
half stammer, the tilted eyebrows, the bowed choirboy lips curled
into a beseeching little smile as his blue eyes simultaneously
implore and twinkle _ the actor makes Michael, aka his Mafia
nickname, Mickey Blue Eyes, an appealing, if totally synthetic
creation.
</P>
<P>
   As usual in Grant's screen performances, beneath the surface
wimpiness and ineptitude lies a core of unflappability. Michael
reacts to the most excruciating embarrassments, like an
ill-concealed gun that continually slips down his pants leg onto a
restaurant floor, with a quip, accompanied by a weak, helpless
smile. Hollywood's other Grant (Cary) had the same gift for
maintaining his dignity in the midst of abject humiliation. If Hugh
Grant lacks the dramatic range of his forerunner, his comic timing
is comparably suave.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, that Mafia! The movie, directed by Kelly Makin from a
screenplay by Adam Scheinman and Robert Kuhn, is only the latest
Hollywood product to portray mobsters as a bunch of almost lovable
but deadly buffoons. Here, they're sort of like grizzly bears
noisily rattling around in an urban jungle theme park. Although the
beasts have been put there for show, the signs warn you to pet them
at your peril.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a frisson of weirdness is the fact that several of the
actors playing mobsters also have continuing roles in the far more
serious and substantial television series ``The Sopranos,'' and at
certain moments their familiarity makes the movie feel like a spoof
of a spoof of a spoof. Further enriching the referential Mafia mix
is James Caan's appearance as a more mature, much less jumpy
descendant of Sonny Corleone.
</P>
<P>
   Michael stumbles into this clan when he falls in love with Gina
Vitale (Jeanne Tripplehorn), a surprisingly genteel Mafia princess
(she teaches school), who refuses to marry him because she fears
her father Frank (Caan) and his pals will corrupt him. Michael
forges ahead anyway and visits Frank's restaurant ``La Trattoria''
in Little Italy. Searching for the men's room, he opens the wrong
door, sees a man imprisoned in the restaurant's freezer, and,
mystified, greets him cheerily before proceeding on.
</P>
<P>
   Gina's fears quickly prove well-grounded. In the movie's
funniest moments, Frank and his pals trick poor Michael into using
his business for money laundering by having him auction off a
mobster's hilariously awful religious paintings in which Jesus and
his disciples are gun-toting gangsters. One sale involves a batty
old lady whose misconstruing of the predetermined bidding signals
leads to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' is little more than a series of
stitched-together gags. One of the funniest, set in a Chinese
restaurant, involves the secreting of an intimate message into a
fortune cookie that is delivered to the wrong party. In another,
Michael, after an accidental homicide, is asked if he has any
plastic bags. Returning from the kitchen a moment later he is
clutching a sandwich bag like a good little puppy.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' accelerates into a frenzied
farce whose convoluted plot involves Michael's faking his own death
during his wedding celebration. As the tempo accelerates and it
turns frantic, the movie loses much of its charm and becomes a
comedy machine that confuses humor with desperately pumped-up
adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `MICKEY BLUE EYES'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It has strong language and some gore.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Kelly Makin; written by Adam Scheinman and Robert
Kuhn; director of photography, Donald E. Thorin; edited by David
Freeman; music by Basil Poledouris; production designer, Gregory
Keen; produced by Elizabeth Hurley and Charles Mulvehill; released
by Castle Rock Entertainment. Running time: 102 minutes. This film
is rated PG-13. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Hugh Grant (Michael Felgate), James Caan (Frank Vitale),
Jeanne Tripplehorn (Gina Vitale), Burt Young (Vito Graziosi), James
Fox (Philip Cromwell) and Joe Viterelli (Vinnie).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
