<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3137 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SPEECHWRITER-0820-COX     08-19 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEECHWRITER-0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TERRY EDMONDS: THE MAN WHO PUTS WORDS IN CLINTON'S MOUTH
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Terry Edmonds chuckles when he recalls listening to
the first presidential speech that he crafted and realizing that
the spoken words weren't the ones he had written.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens a lot with President Clinton. He has the tendency
to put the script aside and go off on his own,'' Edmonds said.
``It's disconcerting at first. But now I understand it's not
something that reflects on the writers. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``When you become a speech writer, you pretty much have to leave
your ego at the front door.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the soft-spoken practitioner of an anonymous art admits
to taking some pride in recently becoming the first African
American to lead the White House corps of speech writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I don't stake my claim to fame on my race but on my
abilities and my track record. But this is an historic appointment
and I recognize that,'' he said. ``My feeling is that I want to be
an example to young African Americans, especially African American
males, that you can rise to great heights if you believe in
yourself, if you have a spiritual foundation, if you don't limit
yourself in any way and keep a positive attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Clinton named the 49-year-old Edmonds to
replace his veteran chief speech writer, Michael Waldman, who
decided to leave the administration. Since 1997, Edmonds has been
associate commissioner for public affairs at the Social Security
Administration, but earlier he worked in the White House Office of
Speech Writing, including a stint as deputy director. At the start
of the administration, he wrote speeches for Donna Shalala, the
Secretary of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Still unpacking at his new office in the Old Executive Office
Building across from the White House, Edmonds reflected this week
on his personal journey from an impoverished childhood to a seat in
Oval Office meetings and on the selfless skills involved in putting
eloquent words in someone else's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in Cherry Hills and other public housing projects on
the tough streets of South Baltimore. His biological father left
when he was young. Along with a sister and two brothers, he was
reared by his mother and stepfather.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had somewhat of a tumultuous relationship back then,'' he
said. ``They have since calmed down and are a very loving couple
now. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Books were a refuge for me as a child growing up in the inner
city. I sort of escaped into the world of words,'' he said. His
mother brought home ``a series of classics'' _ Robinson Crusoe,
Treasure Island, Robin Hood.
</P>
<P>
   He read the Bible, too, and heard sermons every Sunday. The
Presbyterian Church played a large role in his boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always determined to rise above the circumstances that
we were in,'' he said. ``Some of (this ambition) I can't explain
but a lot of it comes from my mother and her dedication to her
family and her encouragement. She always told us we could go as far
as we want to be whatever we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the first in his family to graduate from college _ Morgan
State University, an historically black college in Baltimore. His
sister later earned a master's degree. He worked in public
relations and as an aide to Kweisi Mfume, then a Democratic
congressman from Maryland who is now president of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   His first full time speech writing job was for Shalala, he said.
``For me, the greatest speech giver was Martin Luther King. I would
hear the voice of Martin Luther King as I was writing. I quickly
learned that everyone is not Martin Luther King.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people don't speak in long, flowing, run-on sentences
that are eloquent and poetic. Some people are more direct, short,
to the point, concise. I learned that Secretary Shalala preferred
that type of speech. It took me awhile to turn off the voice of
Martin Luther King in my head and get the voice of Secretary
Shalala right.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving to the White House, he had to quickly ``understand the
voice'' of the president _ ``get to know the nuances of his speech,
the way he talks, the language that he uses.''
</P>
<P>
   The job entails more than pretty phrases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just wordsmiths,'' he explained. ``In this
administration, the speech writers have had more of a voice at the
policy-making table. We are included in policy meetings (and are)
asked to bring more than just words to the table. But the finished
product isn't ours. The finished product is the president's.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds manages a staff of five speech writers. He also attends
meetings with the staff and president to ``get the message right''
for the speeches. The pace can be grueling.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Clinton delivers ``three or four speeches a day for
weeks at a time,'' he said. ``This president is undoubtedly the
most loquacious in history.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, in the cable TV era of ever-shortening news cycles,
the number of presidential speeches is increasing in reaction to
more demand for information coming out of White House, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds demurs when asked about memorable words that he has
penned and Clinton delivered. Such disclosures should come only
after an administration leaves office, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He does have a list of the ``most gratifying speeches I've
worked on.'' At the top is the commencement speech Clinton gave at
Edmonds' alma mater in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a thrill to go back and to have him mention me in the
speech and to see the pride in the eyes of the president of Morgan
and of the students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his other favorites were the speech Clinton delivered at
the University of Texas in Austin in 1996 on the day of the Million
Man March of African American men on Washington _ ``when he first
laid out his vision for racial reconciliation in the country'' _
and the eulogy Clinton gave for Barbara Jordan, the former Texas
congresswoman. After the Jordan eulogy, he said Clinton called him
and described ``how well it was received.''
</P>
<P>
   From William Safire in the Nixon administration to Peggy Noonan
in the Reagan White House, presidential speech writers often have
moved on to other writing triumphs. Edmonds isn't sure what's ahead
for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had a lot of time to think about life after the
White House,'' he said. ``We've got 18 months to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
