<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BROOKLYN-BLACK-CULTUR     08-19 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-BLACK-CULTURE-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ROOTS FOR BLACK CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GARRY PIERRE-PIERRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In villages across Africa, storytelling has long been
an integral part of daily life. At nights, even to this day, people
gather in circles in courtyards illuminated by a full moon and
bright stars to hear gripping tales from wise men and indelible
stories from adventurous young men who have returned to their
hamlets from faraway places.
</P>
<P>
   This and other African traditions are being kept alive in Fort
Greene, Brooklyn, which for years has been a mecca for black life
but which within the last three years has experienced an
extraordinary burst of cultural energy.
</P>
<P>
   Poetry readings have become ubiquitous, performed at spots like
the Brooklyn Moon Cafe and Demu Cafe, both on Fulton Street, and at
the BAM Cafe on Lafayette Avenue, where the famous and
not-so-famous share their works with the crowd. The poems address
themes of love and race, and for many residents they spring from a
cultivated African-American identity.
</P>
<P>
   The Paul Robeson Theater, on Greene Avenue, also offers poetry
readings, as well as plays like a recent production of ``For
Colored Girls Who Have Considered Suicide/When the Rainbow Is
Enuf,'' by the poet Ntozake Shange. And haunts like Brooklyn Mod
and Sol Restaurant and Bar, both on DeKalb Avenue, feature
rhythm-and-blues, Caribbean and African music, some of it live,
increasingly attracting a crowd from across the city.
</P>
<P>
   Live music is most common at the BAM Cafe, but the new bars hope
to capitalize on neighborhood talent to create a more vibrant
scene.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the 135-year-old Brooklyn Academy of Music,
which has made its name as a center for cutting-edge arts programs
like the Next Wave Festival, has reached out to the surrounding
neighborhood with programs on black culture.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the academy, which is just south of Fort Greene,
opened the BAM Rose Cinemas, a 750-seat theater that is the
borough's first art house, as a testament to the area's cultural
self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This neighborhood has a lot of creativity and energy,'' said
Gabrielle Kersaint, executive director of the Haitian Women's
Program, a social services agency in nearby Park Slope and a
resident of Fort Greene. Ms. Kersaint, who recently attended a
poetry reading at the Brooklyn Moon Cafe, hoping, she said, to
``get inspired to write creatively,'' added: ``There are a lot of
writers around here. It's nice to see a lot of black folks in the
neighborhood doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Greene, shaped roughly like a triangle bordered by
Washington Avenue in the east, Fulton Street in the southwest and
Myrtle Avenue in the north, was originally home to a predominantly
upper-middle-class white population, but has long maintained a
middle-class black presence.
</P>
<P>
   From 1880 to 1930, Fort Greene contained about a third of
Brooklyn's black residents, giving rise to the term ``Brooklyn's
black belt.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Depression, the area declined as ornate brownstones
were carved into rooming houses. Urban renewal programs later
eroded some of the neighborhood's physical fabric, and crack and
other drug dealers made it a dangerous place. Today, deep pockets
of poverty remain, and the area's housing projects have one of the
highest infant-mortality rates in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even in its worst days Fort Greene was somewhat of a
cultural center, home to artists like the jazz singer Betty Carter
and the painter Ernest Crichlow, and more recently the filmmaker
Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lee moved a few years ago to the Upper East Side of
Manhattan, the neighborhood's latest rebirth can be tied directly
to him. Lee based his film company, 40 Acres and a Mule, in Fort
Greene in the mid-1980s, when it was better known for its crack
trade than for its creative tradition. The neighborhood was the
setting for some of his films and has since attracted other
directors.
</P>
<P>
   With the revival, Fort Greene stands to challenge Harlem as the
pre-eminent center of black life, at least in New York, if not
internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, shops and restaurants have sprouted, injecting
commercial vitality. Many of the new businesses have distinctly
African themes, like hair salons that specialize in weaves and
dreadlocks and Moshood Creations on Fulton Street, named for its
Nigerian-born proprietor who designs the fashions. The shop offers
traditional African prints integrated into modern wear.
</P>
<P>
   Moshood also contributes to the buzz of Fort Greene. Every day
in front of the shop live mannequins model the fashions, creating a
bit of street theater that draws crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cultural neighborhood in that the shop owners really
focus on making them artistically appealing,'' said Selma Jackson,
a co-owner of 4W Circle of Art Enterprise, an art and fashion
boutique. ``It's like an adventure when you come here; there's so
much to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Some new businesses seem imported from SoHo, like the Simbi Art
and Stone, which sells Haitian art and sculpture on Fulton Street,
and the sleek Lucian Blue Restaurant and Bar on Lafayette Street.
And changes in the neighborhood have drawn young, black
professionals from the film, music and art worlds and from Wall
Street. Real estate values have risen, as once-decrepit brownstones
have been restored.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Because of the new energy, many local people find the name Fort
Greene, in honor of the Revolutionary War general Nathanael Greene,
a bit too bland and outdated. In keeping with their home's newfound
hipness, some residents and merchants refer to their enclave as
Bogolan (pronounced bogo-LAN), an abbreviation of bogolanfini,
which means ``mud cloth'' in the Bambara language that is widely
spoken in Mali. The fabric is worn by dignitaries in the Sahelian
region of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Fred G. Williams, 41, an architect who has lived in Fort Greene
for 20 years, said, ``I've seen a lot of attempts over the years at
improving this neighborhood, but this is the first time we've had
such a large influx of quality stores and restaurants to complement
the brownstones.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``It's really important for a neighborhood to have
these things. They tend to foster a greater sense of community
pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is a sampling of the attractions of ``Bogolan.''
</P>
<P>
   Potent Poetry
</P>
<P>
   The Brooklyn Moon Cafe is one of the most popular spots in Fort
Greene on Friday nights. The tiny den attracts people from around
the corner, and from as far as Atlanta, who come to recite or
listen to poetry readings.
</P>
<P>
   With its weather-beaten walls, a few water-damaged spots on the
ceiling, a piano that looks as if Cab Calloway himself had struck a
few notes on it during his heyday and a worn-out floor, the cafe
has a faux-antique air, but it is genuine. The black creative elite
congregate here.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Friday night, people began milling inside the cafe
at about 9. Some were frantically writing and rewriting their poems
for the readings at 10 or 10:30. Others were more casual, chatting
and catching up on the latest gossip. On most Fridays, the crowd
flows out the front door onto the sidewalk and Fulton Street. The
habitues seemed relaxed, suggesting that they had done this over
and over.
</P>
<P>
   The first act that night was a petite woman, Traci Currie, who
was introduced as ``T C.'' Ms. Currie appeared nervous as she began
her recitation at a hurried pace, but she eased into the
performance and, like every other poet that night, acted out every
word, as if she were appearing in a one-person Broadway show.
</P>
<P>
   She stepped up front, grabbed the microphone, took a deep breath
and held the microphone high. She raised her head and began her
poem, ``New Generation,'' which challenges the notion of racial
superiority and other stereotypes:
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Created to raise up in fists the way Hitler professed a
nation of Aryans to conquer a racially or culturally identifiable
group that really ain't no different than by linguistic
semantic-ism, romanticism or utopianism, as in up here _ the
mind(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   When she finished, there was no applause, just finger snapping,
a Blue Moon tradition. Cafe etiquette dissuades the conventional
cheers in deference to people in the apartments upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I like most is that this is not just a reading, but
a performance,'' said Charles Witherspoon, 28, a Fort Greene
resident and regular at the readings. ``You feel connected to the
artists. Their motion and facial expressions are captivating.''
</P>
<P>
   Being Neighborly
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Brooklyn Academy set out to answer critics
who argued that in a push to draw audiences from Manhattan, it had
ignored the residents in its home borough and surrounding
neighborhood. One of its efforts was the BAM Cafe, on the second
floor of the academy's main building, which started a series of
performances on Friday and Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   The program has included a reading by the poet Nikki Giovanni
and appearances by Brooklyn artists like Tracie Morris, a poet;
Brandon Ross, a guitarist, and Graham Haynes, a cornetist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The BAM scene was cultivated out of a burgeoning black
cultural scene in Brooklyn,'' said Ms. Morris, who lives in Fort
Greene and has performed her poetry at the BAM Cafe about five
times. ``It's great that BAM is investing in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The events usually draw 100 to 200 people, most from Fort Greene
and nearby Clinton Hill, Park Slope and Prospect Heights, all
within walking distance. In the fall, the academy plans to add a
Thursday night show, said Limor Tomer, program director at the BAM
Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   The cafe, which seats about 500 people, has an intimate
ambiance. With red brick walls, the space has an assortment of
couches and love seats, bistro tables and cane chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The academy's other effort was the BAM Rose Cinema, which
features avant-garde and foreign films.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start, the cinema has been attracting the crowd
envisioned when it opened in November. It recently featured a
retrospective of Spike Lee's films, with Lee leading two
question-and-answer sessions on opening night. Bringing Lee back to
his old neighborhood was a way for the academy to connect with the
community and attract more people.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now a 365-day-a-year operation,'' said Karen Brooks
Hopkins, the president of the academy. ``It's really important that
the community is part of the institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing a Double Take
</P>
<P>
   Few people would consider a fashion boutique a place for
theatrical performance. But for the last few years, the store
window of Moshood on Fulton Street has been dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   The show in Moshood's modest window consists of live mannequins,
an oddity that is effective advertising and has become part of the
tour for local residents and tourists. The models have puzzled
schoolchildren, stopped passers-by and prompted drivers to slow
down and wave.
</P>
<P>
   Every day lithe young men and women take turns sitting pretty on
a high-backed wooden chair or leaning majestically against a fence.
They stand still like statues, glowing under a bright light, then
simultaneously twirl and pout to show off Moshood's latest
African-inspired couture.
</P>
<P>
   Since the store opened five years ago, Moshood has been the host
of fashion shows and free jam sessions. The live mannequins began
as a gimmick when the store's owner, Moshood, cajoled a few models
from fashion shows to replace the wooden mannequins, and now
aspiring models stroll in asking for a stint.
</P>
<P>
   For people who have lived through Fort Greene's ups and downs,
the latest rebirth has been made so much sweeter by watching the
reactions of those who moved out during the bad times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them can't believe their eyes,'' said Ms. Jackson of
4W Circle of Art Enterprise. ``All they can say is, `Wow.''' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
