<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      08-19 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INTRODUCING DOROTHY DANDRIDGE': AFTER CLIMB TO STARDOM, A TUMBLE,
THEN DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seen today, Otto Preminger's film ``Carmen Jones'' engulfs
viewers in the quaint aura of the 1950s, with Bizet's music plopped
down in a modern army barracks, where characters burst into song on
a Cinemascope screen. Even now, however, its entirely black cast
(including a young Harry Belafonte) remains a rarity.
</P>
<P>
   And one other element has not aged. When Dorothy Dandridge
sashays into view as the femme fatale Carmen, swinging her hips in
a tight red skirt and gesturing with a single red rose, she is
unmistakably a movie star. Like most stars, she conveys an
enigmatic quality: Dandridge's delicate beauty and natural elegance
add a hint of mystery to the languorous sexuality of her
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Halle Berry makes a different yet equally telling entrance early
in ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge,'' HBO's engaging, socially
aware look at an accomplished yet tortured life. When Dandridge
arrives at the 1955 Academy Awards ceremony, an announcer
identifies her as ``The first-ever colored nominee for best
actress.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the Dandridge story is encapsulated in the scene, from
the racial barriers she confronted to her ladylike presence. (Ms.
Berry's fine features and poise make her an eerie double.) And
along with her accomplishment (other nominees included Audrey
Hepburn and Grace Kelly, who won for ``The Country Girl''), there
is the personal distress.
</P>
<P>
   Preminger, then her lover, showed up with his wife; Dandridge
arrived with her sister. Everything is set up to explain who the
enigmatic Dandridge was.
</P>
<P>
   The film goes a long way toward doing that, though it is never
as dynamic as it should have been. It relies on too many tired
conventions of the docudrama, and its portrait of Dandridge is
simplified (especially when compared with the complex woman who
appears in Donald Bogle's authoritative 1997 biography).
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge'' is worth watching for its
affecting performances and for the sheer drama of Dandridge's life.
As executive producer, Ms. Berry had the clout to get the film made
and, true to its title, introduce Dandridge to a generation that
never knew her.
</P>
<P>
   In the hokey narrative frame, Dandridge is making a nightlong
phone call to a friend while putting together a collage of old
photographs, which send her into flashbacks. The earliest scenes
are the liveliest. In the 1940s, as part of an act called the
Dandridge Sisters, she performs at the Cotton Club and meets Harold
Nicholas (Obba Babatunde, so memorable in ``Miss Evers' Boys''),
her future husband and part of the famed dancing team the Nicholas
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   The director Martha Coolidge brings great exuberance to the
musical scenes, including Dandridge's movie appearance with the
Nicholas Brothers, singing and dancing to ``Chatanooga Choo-Choo.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet while her career was taking off, in private Dandridge was
being beaten by her mother's lesbian lover. Ms. Berry, who gives a
shining, controlled performance throughout, is especially strong in
these early scenes as she juggles the excitement of a new career
and love with the fearful, explosive situation at home.
</P>
<P>
   That pattern of professional success and personal sorrow lasted
for much of her life. She and Nicholas had a daughter who,
Dandridge reluctantly acknowledged, had been born brain damaged.
Soon the marriage ended.
</P>
<P>
   Guiding her rise in Hollywood is her manager, Earl Mills. Brent
Spiner (Data from ``Star Trek'') is so effective as the loyal,
lovelorn Mills that he overcomes the liability of a ridiculous red
wig. Mills is with her when, already a star, she plays a Las Vegas
nightclub and is warned not to use the swimming pool because it
would have to be drained if a black person set foot in it. She
splashes her toe in the water and soon sees black workers scrubbing
the bottom of the drained pool.
</P>
<P>
   Though such scenes depict piercing realities, they also suggest
the film's flat-footed narrative. ``You think I've never been to
the South?'' Dandridge says, ostensibly to Mills but actually to
the film's audience, during a club appearance in Miami. ``I can't
use the front entrance and I can't speak to the patrons, right?''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the characters are needlessly burnished. The Bogle
biography reveals that Dandridge could be as self-absorbed as the
next movie star, but here she is saintlier. Even Preminger (Klaus
Maria Brandauer) seems like a pussycat in private.
</P>
<P>
   When he walks out on Dandridge for good, it seems an act done
more in sadness than in racial hypocrisy or cruelty. And as good as
Ms. Berry is overall, she is too restrained to capture Dandridge's
down-and-dirty sexuality when recreating scenes from ``Carmen
Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   But the film is straightforward about Dandridge's decline. She
never equaled her success in ``Carmen Jones'' and died in 1965 when
she was 42 from an overdose of prescription drugs. It has never
been clear whether the overdose was intentional or accidental.
Realistically, the film leaves that haunting question open.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `INTRODUCING DOROTHY DANDRIDGE' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Home Box Office, Sunday at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Written by Shonda Rhimes and Scott Abbott and based on the book
``Dorothy Dandridge,'' by Earl Mills; Martha Coolidge, director;
Larry Albucher, producer. Moctesuma Esparza, Robert Katz, Joshua D.
Maurer, Vincent Cirrincione and Halle Berry, executive producers.
An Esparza/Katz Production in association with Berry/Cirrincione.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Halle Berry (Dorothy Dandridge), Brent Spiner (Earl
Mills), Obba Babatunde (Harold Nicholas), Loretta Devine (Ruby
Dandridge), Cynda Williams (Vivian Dandridge) and LaTanya
Richardson (Auntie). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
