<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3163 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-SHELBURNE-FARMS-ART-3     08-19 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELBURNE-FARMS-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INN AT SHELBURNE FARMS: DREAM HOUSE WITH DREAMSCAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHELBURNE, Vt. _ I had been enumerating the glories of the Inn
at Shelburne Farms, a country estate in Vermont on the banks of
Lake Champlain, practically since the day my friend Nate and I had
met, and now, on a summer evening three years later, we were
finally driving through the Green Mountains, an hour or so from
arriving.
</P>
<P>
   I was worried. Maybe I had oversold the place. Was Shelburne
Farms _ the turn-of-the-century dream house of Dr. William Seward
Webb and his wife, Lila Vanderbilt Webb _ as majestic and welcoming
as I remembered from my last visit four years ago?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Nate, just back from a Maine fishing trip, would find it
pretentious, with its surrounding farmland and forests laid out
with help from Frederick Law Olmstead, and its lake and mountain
views.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the inn had changed. Maybe it had been gussied up with
Laura Ashley, stuffed teddy bears and potpourri, like so many other
New England inns. Maybe Shelburne Farms had gone quaint. We had
left Boston three hours later than planned because of last-minute
work complications. How was I going to impress my friend with his
first glimpse of Shelburne Farms when it would be barely visible in
the darkness?
</P>
<P>
   It was close to 11 p.m. when we turned onto the long, winding
gravel road that marks the beginning of the estate, at the southern
end of Lake Champlain, seven miles outside Burlington. But as we
left behind Route 7, with its dispiriting artificial lights,
fast-food outlets and strip malls, we found that the countryside
was illuminated by a full moon: the lake on one side; pastures,
woodlands and huge barns on the other.
</P>
<P>
   In the distance, rising above a grassy hill, just as I
remembered it, was the rambling, Queen Anne-style, stone and
red-brick building, with its turrets, towers and 13 chimneys.
Inside the curved and diamond-shaped windows, the lights glowed.
</P>
<P>
   Nate reacted on cue: ``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   The young woman at the check-in desk greeted us warmly and
inquired about our trip. Overtired and disheveled as we were, in
shorts and T-shirts, there was a complete absence of the sort of
cool appraisal that would have greeted similarly attired visitors
at less self-assured places billing themselves as country inns.
</P>
<P>
   She asked if there was anything she could do for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starving,'' I confessed.
</P>
<P>
   She disappeared into the kitchen, and returned with a couple of
smoked turkey and cheese sandwiches on thick whole-wheat bread. The
cheese was Shelburne Farms Cheddar, made from the milk of the brown
Swiss cows grazing in the nearby pastures. The bread was from the
O'Bread Bakery, in one of the barns we had driven past.
</P>
<P>
   Once you check in at Shelburne Farms, you become part of the
household, free to wander. Beginning to feel very much at home in
the 19th century, we decided to have our midnight supper on the
south porch.
</P>
<P>
   We wandered through the main hall and the library, both rooms
with oak-paneled walls and fireplaces, and both decorated, as are
all the rooms, with the Webbs' original furniture.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to pull out one of the family's 6,000 books, perhaps an
Edith Wharton novel _ the Webbs were avid readers _ and curl up on
one of the soft, low-to-the-ground mauve and pale-green velvet
sofas. But I had a more pressing engagement with turkey and cheese.
On the porch we settled into wicker chairs and pulled up a wicker
table. The sandwiches were delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Reviving, we walked across the lawn in the moonlight, past the
clay courts that were so bright under the moon we could have played
tennis, and down to the lake lapping against the shore in the wind.
I felt soothed by the land unfolding around me and sheltered by the
mountains looming in the darkness. We looked up at the stars and
back at the inn silhouetted against the big Vermont sky.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed by it all, as I was, Nate assured me that I had
brought him to the right place. Of course Shelburne Farms wasn't
pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the real thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A century ago Vermont was hardly the country mecca for escaping
urbanites that it is today. Mrs. Webb's Vanderbilt siblings built
opulent mansions on Fifth Avenue in Manhattan, in Newport, R.I.,
and in Asheville, N.C. But the Webbs, who were married in 1881 at a
high-society wedding in New York, had been captivated by Vermont on
their travels and decided to move to Burlington.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Webb's $10 million inheritance provided the cash for the
couple to buy about 3,800 acres in the Champlain Valley. Through
the late 1880s and early 1890s Webb oversaw the construction of the
family house and what became the biggest, fanciest barns in
America, transforming the land into a model experimental farm where
all the latest agriculture and horse breeding techniques could be
practiced.
</P>
<P>
   Webb died in 1926, his widow 10 years later. Their youngest son,
Vanderbilt, inherited the farm, and in 1939 his son, Derick Webb,
took over as farm manager. But Derick and his family occupied
another house on the property, and the Big House, as they called
it, fell into disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   With skyrocketing taxes and expenses, it became increasingly
difficult to keep up the farm, and in 1970 Derick called his six
children together on the south porch. Marshall Webb, who was 21 at
the time, remembers his father telling them that he was considering
selling 500 acres to a developer who wanted to build ``a golf
course and fancy houses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically told him that was absolutely what we did not want
to happen,'' Marshall Webb recalled when I telephoned him, after
our weekend, to ask about the meeting, which I had read about in
``The House at Shelburne Farms,'' by Joe Sherman, a book sold at
the inn. The children offered their father a deal: If the land
remained open and agricultural, they would stick around and help
out. If not, they would all leave.
</P>
<P>
   The dream of Marshall and his siblings was to preserve the land
as a working farm and turn the estate into the nonprofit
environmental center that it is today. The inn supplies the income
for the center.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We were young idealists,'' Marshall Webb said. ``All we were
thinking about was that this land was too valuable to split up and
develop. We wanted it to work its magic on other people and
hopefully influence them to make sound decisions back in their
hometowns about what to do with their own land.''
</P>
<P>
   My environment at the inn _ the Webb Room, once occupied by Webb
_ certainly worked its magic on me. The day after we arrived, I
opened my eyes to an absolutely perfect morning in the country and
my ears to a bird symphony.
</P>
<P>
   I had spent the night on the carved rosewood bed of William
Henry Vanderbilt, Webb's father-in-law, one of the richest men in
the world in the Gilded Age. The room was enormous, four times the
size of a standard hotel room, large enough to take a walk in,
which I did.
</P>
<P>
   The pale green carpet matched the pale-green velvet chaise
longue and the 19th-century reproduction flowered wallpaper. There
was no minibar and no television, although the inn keeps two
televisions in a closet for emergency requests. A bank of windows
opened onto the lawn sweeping down to the lake. The outdoors
beckoned.
</P>
<P>
   Nate and I had breakfast on the terrace on the lawn. He raved
over his oatmeal and dried-cherry pancakes and gobbled up a basket
of homemade croissants. I had my idea of the perfect breakfast: a
bowl of fresh fruit, plain yogurt and granola, and plenty of Nate's
syrup-drenched pancakes. We wondered aloud about the tree directly
before us on the lawn, and suddenly three waiters were hurrying
over to make the identification. It was a linden.
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a morning newspaper? We sat there for two hours,
drinking the good, strong coffee and watching the peaks of the
Adirondacks emerge from the mist across the lake. Our waitress
smilingly kept refilling our cups. She would have been content, it
seemed, to have us sit there all day.
</P>
<P>
   The natural beauty notwithstanding, what makes Shelburne Farms
the successful enterprise it is today took a lot of work. After the
family meeting on the south porch, Derick Webb told his children he
was willing to become further indebted while they tried to realize
the family's dream. And so they all pitched in, fixing up
buildings, restoring barns, raising money and managing the crops
and cows. They started a summer camp for children that would
eventually become a year-round teaching program.
</P>
<P>
   When Derick died in 1984, he bequeathed all the land to the
nonprofit center, as his children, who relinquished all claim to
ownership, had hoped he would. In 1985 they began restoring the Big
House as an inn with 24 guest rooms and a dining room open to the
public. As faithfully authentic as the restoration was, and with
the inn to be closed during the winter, no thought was given to
heating. As for air-conditioning, who needed air-conditioning in
Vermont?
</P>
<P>
   As we got up from breakfast, we began planning our day. Should
we explore the cafes and markets of Burlington, Vermont's Queen
City, and ride bicycles along the path around Lake Champlain? Or
hike the extensive walking trails of Shelburne Farms? Perhaps we
could fit in a ferry ride across the lake, to the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   But nature intervened. Despite all the genuine comforts of
Shelburne Farms, we could not deny the obvious: It was hot. Really
hot, heading toward the high 90s. On the south porch, where Mrs.
Webb had once spent entire summer afternoons reading and writing
letters, we overheard another guest, a man, complaining, ``I've
never paid so much to sweat in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Our visions of hyperactivity vanished. But still I was
determined to visit the studio of Sarah Wesson, an artist whose
paintings of the Vermont landscape I was introduced to first by her
note cards and then by one of her prints, ``First Red Barn on the
Left,'' which hangs in my dining room, a gift from a friend. I'd
seen plenty of paintings of bucolic Vermont in galleries, but for
me no one captured the essence of the natural landscape _ the
motion of the clouds, the shapes of the fields, the colors _ as Ms.
Wesson did.
</P>
<P>
   We drove south to tiny Panton, passing fields of corn that swept
down to the lake shore. It was a Sarah Wesson landscape of greens,
blues and purples, earth and sky playing with the New England
summer light. We arrived at the small house at the end of a country
road and climbed the wooden stairs to her second-floor studio.
</P>
<P>
   There again were the colors, but this time they were in her
paintings: oils and watercolors that seemed to have taken their
light from the landscape outside her big windows. ``The wide open
fields here in Panton remind me of the sea,'' Ms. Wesson has
written about her work. ``Slight undulations are waves on a calm
day; the facing mountains are waves not quite broken.''
</P>
<P>
   I longed to buy them all, to bring her shimmering Vermont home
to my apartment in Cambridge. Fortunately, you don't have to be a
Vanderbilt to acquire a Sarah Wesson.
</P>
<P>
   Next we headed back to Shelburne for the obligatory visit to the
Shelburne Museum, three miles from the inn, a staggering collection
of Americana, from a Shaker door-latch collection to quilts and
weather vanes, housed in 87 exhibit buildings. I was sure that the
barn, the woodworking tools and the 892-ton steamer Ticonderoga
would appeal to Nate's masculine soul.
</P>
<P>
   We had just finished touring the un-air-conditioned room packed
with dozens of fancy carriages with fur spreads, and were looking
at what appeared to be a blur of hammers in an equally sweltering
room when I said to Nate, ``I've got to get out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   He, far from being seduced by the hardware, gratefully escaped
with me to the air-conditioned gift shop. Cooling off amid the
displays of scarves, cards, books and Vermont chocolates, we looked
at each other. We were both thinking the same thing: Why are we
here, why are we anywhere other than Shelburne Farms, especially
when we only have 24 hours left?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Relieved to be away from the hustle and bustle of Shelburne and
the traffic of Route 7, we collapsed into the beauty and poetry of
the place. We enjoyed a tasty picnic lunch on the south porch,
sharing a grilled eggplant sandwich with goat cheese, tomatoes and
basil, and pasta salad with arugula, feta cheese, black olives and
artichokes. We carried a Tolstoy novella, ``Happy Ever After,'' out
to the tall locust tree on the lawn _ the aforementioned linden
tree was nearby _ and read aloud.
</P>
<P>
   The heat that had been unbearable beyond the gates of Shelburne
Farms was here just a part of the atmosphere. We took a lazy walk
down to the Coach Barn, where Webb once kept his carriages, and
onto the Farm Barn, where we peeked at the goats and lambs that
delight visiting children and, on the other side, the O'Bread
Bakery, and the Cheddar cheese making operation.
</P>
<P>
   We made it back to the inn by teatime for cucumber and caviar
sandwiches, scones and lemonade. We debated whether to take a nap
or swim in the lake. We did both. As hot summer days sometimes do,
this one drifted by.
</P>
<P>
   Even modest dreams can be fulfilled at the Webbs' Gilded Era
home, and I found myself fulfilling one of my own that evening:
walking barefoot across the beautiful lawn, sipping a glass of
wine. We strolled through the formal gardens beside the lake that
Mrs. Webb had nurtured over the years, inhaling the scent of roses,
and watched as the sun melted into the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that we had been grazing since 9 a.m., we
eventually took our seats in the dining room among the other
guests. The candlelight and the Webbs' original red silk damask
wallpaper made the room feel grand and cozy at the same time. The
French doors were flung open to the night, bringing in the
fragrance of the garden and the lake breeze.
</P>
<P>
   We feasted together on a wonderful beet salad made from beets
grown on the farm. Nate devoured his roasted rack of lamb with
asparagus and mushrooms, and I polished off a filet of Atlantic
salmon with wild rice pilaf and asparagus. We shared a rich
chocolate dacquoise with raspberries for dessert. Our sense of
well-being was complete.
</P>
<P>
   The next day we did more lounging, on the south porch, the north
porch and the lawn, reading aloud and wandering around the inn. As
other guests checked out, the doors of their rooms were
deliberately left open, and we explored the Overlook, Lila Webb's
bedroom; the Rose Room, which had belonged to the Webb's only
daughter, Frederica, and the White Room, where Webb's valet had
slept.
</P>
<P>
   In the Game Room, where Webb and his friends gathered after
dinner for port and billiards, we stared at the big-game heads on
the wall. We did make one brief foray off the grounds, to the
Artisans Guild in nearby Ferrisburg, filled with paintings by local
artists, including Ms. Wesson. All too soon it was time to leave.
We took a last look at the lake, the lawn, the gardens and the
mountains beyond, said goodbye to the friendly young woman at the
check-in desk and got into the car.
</P>
<P>
   We were silent, even a bit melancholy as we headed down the
gravel road, back to traffic and tension and the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' I said to Nate, cheering up a bit at the prospect
of the fires in the 30 fireplaces, the landscape ablaze with color,
the cups of hot chocolate on the south porch, ``it's even better in
the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   The Inn at Shelburne Farms, in Shelburne, Vt., is 296 miles from
New York City. Here is a sampling of attractions in the area, as
well as travel information:
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY AND EAT
</P>
<P>
   INN AT SHELBURNE FARMS, Route 7, Shelburne, seven miles south of
Burlington, and three miles northwest of Shelburne Village, (802)
985-8498. Open mid-May to mid-October. With 24 rooms, 17 with
private baths. Daily rates: double room, private bath, $195 to
$350; double room, shared bath, $95 to $175; an extra person in
same accommodation, $30. The dining room serves breakfast and
dinner daily; picnic lunches are available upon request, and Sunday
brunch is available by reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ATTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   FERRISBURG ARTISANS GUILD, 5467 Route 7, Ferrisburg, Vt., (802)
877-3668. Open year-round, 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily. Beginning on
Aug. 28 and on view for four weeks, an exhibition of collage art by
Anna Fugaro. Free admission. Opening on Sept. 17, the Starry Night
Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   SHELBURNE MUSEUM, Route 7, Shelburne, (802) 985-3346. Open daily
10 a.m. to 5 p.m. through Oct. 24; 1 to 4 p.m. from Oct. 24 through
Dec. 31 and early April through Memorial Day; closed January
through March. On view through Oct. 17, ``Kid Stuff: Great Toys
From Our Childhood,'' a collection of items from the 1940's to
60's. Admission: $17.50; $7 for children 6 to 14; free for children
under 6; fee includes second consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   SARAH WESSON'S STUDIO, Panton, Vt., (802) 475-2201;
SWstudio(AT)together.net. Hours by appointment.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO GET THERE
</P>
<P>
   BY CAR: From New York City, take the Major Deegan Expressway to
the Thomas E. Dewey Thruway (I-87) and continue north on the
Thruway to the Northway; continue on the Northway to Route 9 North;
take Route 9 north to Route 149 and continue on Route 149 East to
Route 4 East; take Route 4 East to Route 22A North and continue on
Route 22A North to Route 7.
</P>
<P>
   BY BUS: Vermont Transit runs three buses daily from the Port
Authority Bus Terminal in Manhattan to Shelburne. The trip takes
seven to eight hours. Round-trip fare, $118; half-price for
children 11 and younger. Information: (802) 864-6811.
</P>
<P>
   BY TRAIN: Amtrak offers a daily train from Penn Station in
Manhattan to Essex Junction, Vt., which is about eight miles from
Shelburne. The train leaves New York at 11:30 a.m. and arrives in
Vermont at 8:55 p.m. Round-trip fare, $128 weekends; $116 weekdays.
Amtrak information: (800) 872-7245. Taxis meet the train; taxi fare
to Shelburne is about $19. Taxi information: (800) 696-7433.
</P>
</TEXT>
