<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Aug. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Significant rain will fall Friday in the central Appalachians
from Pennsylvania into western North Carolina as a developing
low-pressure system crosses the mountains. The flow of moisture
from the Atlantic will enhance the showers along the east slopes
with some sections receiving more than two inches of rain by later
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will spread east to southern New England, but a dome of
dry, mild air over northern Maine should keep brighter skies and
pleasant weather over the northern half of New England. A
freshening onshore breeze will keep readings below seasonal levels
near the coast.
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of strong thunderstorms should develop over the
Carolinas in a wedge of sultry air ahead of an approaching cold
front. Hail and damaging winds are possible in some communities,
especially in east-central North Carolina. More thundershowers will
erupt in the steamy air over the South. Thunderstorms will be more
numerous in southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will persist over lower Michigan and the Ohio Valley as a
large disturbance in the jet stream settles into the region. Very
pleasant late summer weather is expected in the Middle West, but
hotter air will return to the western Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The monsoon will be very active with afternoon thundershowers
from Arizona and New Mexico into Wyoming and Idaho. A few potent
storms will drift into Kansas and northern Texas. The West Coast
will notice more clouds and it will be seasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Tricky Winds
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday a hurricane-hunter aircraft measured
tropical-storm-force winds at Veracruz, Mexico, about 90 nautical
miles south of the center of a tropical depression over the Bay of
Campeche. Yet the system was not upgraded to a tropical storm. The
reasoning was sound. Veracruz is located at the top of the Isthmus
of Tehuantepec, where the Bay of Campeche narrows markedly. Thus,
when winds blow from the north, they must funnel into the area,
causing them to accelerate. So Thursday's strong winds were more a
function of the lay of the land than the strength of the tropical
system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
