<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram plans to move the following stories
for clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Friday,
Aug. 20, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Lou
Hudson, Paul Wagner or Jim Peipert on the Star-Telegram's
National/Foreign Desk at (817) 390-7785. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MICKEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In interviews promoting the gangster romantic comedy
``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' Hugh Grant has often been quoted as saying
that he rewrote his character and his lines to make both funnier.
He might as well say that he rescued the film, because without him,
it would have sunk like a pair of cement boots. Even with him, it
just barely keeps its humorous head above water. By ROBERT PHILPOT.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HUGH GRANT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Despite a plethora of interviews accompanying his new
film ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' Hugh Grant has plenty to say, much of it
humorous, often at his own expense. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story will
move in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ILLUMINATA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ For movie fans who want something a little more
sophisticated than ``American Pie,'' John Turturro's theater-world
satire ``Illuminata'' is a textbook example of ``Be careful what
you ask for _ you might get it.'' Here's a film that's smart, often
funny, unconventional and unpredictable. It's also pretentious,
often boring or crude, bizarre and meandering. By ROBERT PHILPOT.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TRICK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Trick'' is tricky. On the one hand, this gay
romantic comedy about two guys falling in love as they attempt to
have a one-night stand is sweet and amusing. On the other hand,
it's kinda ordinary. The odd thing is, the ordinariness works for
it as well as against it. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-XIU XIU &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Not every movie set in the '70s has a cast lifted from
Entertainment Weekly's list of hot young actors, peeking through
bad shag wigs and coping with the angst of being different, man!
``Xiu Xiu, the Sent Down Girl'' _ the directing debut of actress
Joan Chen (''The Last Emperor'') _ reflects another kind of exile.
It's the story of a teen-aged girl in China, the smart, curious and
free-thinking Xiu Xiu (Lu Lu), who's shipped off to the countryside
_ sent down _ for Communist indoctrination. And, in a low-key way,
it has an almost painful directness. The dialogue tends to point
things out, as if it were actually written by the Communists. By
ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TINGLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ With his writing for ``Scream,'' ``Dawson's Creek,''
``I Know What You Did Last Summer'' and ``The Faculty,'' Kevin
Williamson has made a career out of irony. Not content with
employing it, he is now defining irony for us. In his directorial
debut, the teen-age dark comedy ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' he tells
us (over and over) that irony is ... an outcome different from what
was expected. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   C O M M E N T A R Y &QL; 
