<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3176 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-STAR-OF-DAVID-NYTSF &LR;      08-19 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-OF-DAVID-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVERSE SOCIETY MUST UNDERSTAND AND ACCEPT ITS RELIGIOUS SYMBOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By DIANA BUTLER BASS &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In Gulfport, Miss., this week, school officials at Harrison
Central High ordered Ryan Green, a Jewish student, to wear his Star
of David tucked inside his shirt. They feared the six-pointed star
resembled a gang symbol and refused him permission to display it.
</P>
<P>
   His father explained that the Star of David represented the
boy's faith,akin to a Christian wearing a cross. The school still
refused.
</P>
<P>
   This act of ignorant discrimination should shock all
Americans,especially as it followed the shooting at the Jewish day
care center in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, like all Americans, is protected by the Constitution to
freely express his religious beliefs. A Star of David hardly
symbolizes violence. In the post-Holocaust world, it embodies faith
and suffering in the face of oppression.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi officials appear to have confused the six-pointed
Star of David with the five-pointed pentagram often favored by
violent gangs and Satanists.
</P>
<P>
   Such groups also use upside-down or twisted crosses. Will
Mississippi school authorities forbid Christian students their
crosses because they resemble satanic symbols?
</P>
<P>
   In a religiously diverse society, we all need to understand such
symbols and their meanings. For a faithful Jew to wear a Star of
David is one thing; for a member of a white supremacy group to wear
it, another. The Jew intends it as a witness to faith. The white
supremacist intends insult to that faith. One display is welcomed
by civilized people; the other (although protected in some
instances by the Constitution) is not.
</P>
<P>
   If Judaism confuses school officials in Mississippi, what if an
American Indian student had appeared on the first day of class
wearing a swastika? Would anyone have understood that in his
religion this ancient symbol conveys blessing and not
anti-Semitism? Would they have assumed him a Nazi? If Buford Furrow
had worn the same swastika while shooting at the Jewish community
center, it would carry an entirely different meaning.
</P>
<P>
   We live in a culture full of conflicting religious symbols. When
they collide, we tend to respond as the Mississippi authorities.
Hide them. Tuck them away. Do not display your beliefs in public.
We strip the public square of crosses, crescents, and stars and
threaten legal action if another faith offends us.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy seems, however, to have failed. Radically
privatizing faith has contributed to greater misunderstanding and
prejudice. Tucking faith away has relavitized all religions to
``personal belief systems.'' If recent events in Littleton and Los
Angeles prove anything, they prove that all faiths are not equal.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, especially conservative members of Congress,
believe that putting faith back in school will solve our problems.
But whose faith? Christianity? Judaism? Buddhism? Nazism?
</P>
<P>
   Religion should be expressed in public institutionsbut neither
as some nostalgic return to dogmatism nor an all-out conflict
between ``equal'' religions. We need to learn to live together with
difference while finding common morality in our diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Good teachers are key in this national task. Although not
allowed to share their personal faith in public-funded
institutions, we endow all teachers with the responsibility to
teach critical thinking, to discern between truth and falsehood
(yes, even in a pluralistic culture).
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who teach ``irrelevant'' subjects like philosophy,
religion, literature, poetry, history, and fine arts, find
ourselves daily immersed helping students sort through issues of
meaningboth the beliefs of others and their own spiritual quests.
</P>
<P>
   Intentionally or not, teachers mentor students and help them
choose good over evil. We are a kind of secular clergy, diverse and
pluralistic among ourselves, still idealistically hoping for a
better world.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Green's act of faith can teach us all what kind of nation
we need to become. And a world religions course for Mississippi
school officials probably would not hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass writes a religion column for the Santa
Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious studies
at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is ``Standing
Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th Century
America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
