<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-19 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADAM AND EVE, LITERALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It is difficult to respect presidential candidates
who lack the courage to say whether they believe in evolution or in
creationism.
</P>
<P>
   The former is the underlying principle of biology and other
sciences and the latter is a literal interpretation of the biblical
account of the rib, the snake and Adam and Eve.
</P>
<P>
   If our putative leaders don't believe in evolution, their
know-nothing attitude in the White House could endanger our very
national survival. If they do, their failure to defend it reflects
a scary indifference toward education and our ability to compete in
the high-tech, super-informed world of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Yet three leading Republican presidential hopefuls expect us to
honor and maybe elect them despite their professed indifference
toward the fundamental factual evidence tracing the development of
human life.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, Elizabeth Dole and Steve Forbes
ducked this week when confronted with questions about the Kansas
Board of Education's decision to eliminate evolution from the state
school curriculum and to encourage teachers to lecture on the
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Their answer, phrased in practically identical words, was
``leave it to the states.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a great governing philosophy when applied to practical
problems best addressed at the local level, such as police
deployment and the distribution of welfare funds. But that is not
what we are dealing with here. This is about whether to teach our
young the central organizing principle of all biological science.
</P>
<P>
   In poll after poll, education ranks as the highest priority of
American voters. A secular nation about to enter the 21st century
requires the practical knowledge about the complexities of the
universe that comes from scientific study. There is an important
role for spiritual guidance in our church-going nation, but it must
be complementary rather than supplementary.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, Dole and Forbes didn't get it. They allowed as how
they would let local officials determine what to tell our young
people about the origins of life rather than endorse the extensive
paleontological, biochemical, geographical and other factual
evidence upon which the scientific community relies.
</P>
<P>
   The three candidates are so intimated by the religious
conservatives that they are not willing to contest the Kansas
school board's suggestion that Charles Darwin was a jerk who held
nutty, unverifiable theories no better than anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   What's next? Will our political heroes tell us they can't decide
whether the Earth is flat or round? What if some school board
somewhere declares Lucy, the famous 3.2 million-year-old Ethiopian
mummy once admired by President Clinton, to be a fraud made of
plastic?
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas School Board justified its retreat from scientific
reality by noting that since ``no one was present when life first
appeared on Earth,'' any theory about it is just a guess, including
the process of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   This nonsense did not offend our GOP trio, although it outraged
the National Academy of Sciences, the state's university presidents
and educators everywhere. The trio's bland acceptance of eyewitness
accounts as the only possible evidence of evolution is frightening.
Haven't they ever heard of fossils? Carbon dating? Discoveries of
cachesof 2.6-million-year-old humanoid tools?
</P>
<P>
   It was no surprise that Forbes, who panders to religious
conservatives, would cower behind states' rights on a hot subject
in the Bible Belt. He said ``in terms of evolution, there's a huge
debate now ... so I'll trust the parents on that one ... leave it
to local parents and local school boards.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's a ``huge'' debate on evolution, most of us have
missed it. Religion and evolution can comfortably co-exist. Some
religions interpret the Bible literally but many more teach it as
an allegorical tale with a timeless spiritual message. The ``day''
in which God created Earth, for instance, may not have been 24
hours but several billion years. His divine supervision remains the
same.
</P>
<P>
   It is the cowardice of Bush and Dole, however, that is horribly
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Both of them know better. Both have been making a big deal of
appealing to centrist voters who are uncomfortable with narrow,
intolerant religious dogma. Both were well educated at Ivy League
colleges where the process of evolution is unquestioned and new,
challenging evidence welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet asked if he is a creationist, Bush did not deny it. He told
USA Today that ``I believe children ought to be exposed to
different theories about how the world started.'' In effect, he
dismissed evolution as just another ``theory,'' of no more weight
than Uncle Henry's notion that the moon is made of green cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Dole also weaseled when asked if she personally believes the
literal biblical explanation of how the world was created. ``This
is a state issue,'' she said. ``I'm a person of strong faith and
each person just has to ... parents can teach their children the
Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the woman who has been promising us straight talk. She
says she wants to look people in the eye. How can she do that and
pretend that it's OK to produce a generation of dumb kids by
failing to teach them evolution in science classes?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
