<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE: BOOK REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stevenson's reviews:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO OTHER BOOK &QL; 
 &UR; By Randall Jarrell &QL; 
 &UR; (HarperCollins, $27.50) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I no longer remembered much about writing ``The Woman at the
Washington'' ``Zoo'' _ a poem is, so to speak, a way of making you
forget how you wrote it _ but I had almost all the sheets of paper
on which it was written, starting with a paper napkin from the
Methodist Cafeteria. If you had asked me where I had begun the
poem, I'd have said: `Why, sir, at the beginning'; it was a
surprise to me to see that I hadn't.'' This charming passage
introduces Jarrell's essay about the work for which he won a
National Book Award in 1961, and little gems such as it are
everywhere in this collection of criticism and prose. Part of the
pleasure is that you seem to stumble on them unawares, but, of
course, that's an illusion _ such things are never so accidental.
Perhaps it's because Jarrell died in 1965, and his essay
collections have been out of print. More likely, it's because, as
volume editor Brad Leithauser points out, Jarrell was deeply
passionate about the rewards and challenges of literature and
deeply generous in his attention to them. Jarrell notes, for
example, that Marianne Moore's poems ``judge what is said about
them almost as much as poems can so that even one's praise is
hesitant, uncertain of its welcome.'' When you've read William
Carlos Williams' ``Patterson,'' he says, ``You know for the rest of
your life what it is like to be a waterfall.'' And Malraux ``writes
a passage of ordinary exposition so that we breathe irregularly and
jerk our heads from side to side like spectators at a tennis
match.'' Other subjects include Robert Frost, W.H. Auden and
reading itself. ``Mediocrity,'' he writes, ``may often give us
unqualified pleasure; it does not disturb our self-satisfaction but
rather encourages us with the thought that we are as good as
another. . . . Properly speaking, we learn only from those books we
cannot judge.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GONE BOY &QL; 
 &UR; By Gregory Gibson (Kodansha, $24) &QL; 
On Dec. 14, 1992, Gibson's 18-year-old son, Galen, was killed by a
fellow student at a small college in Massachusetts (the murderer,
Wayne Lo, went on a random shooting spree that left four people
wounded and two dead). With the dreadful phone call that woke them
that night, Gibson, his wife and their younger children embarked on
a process that all parents dread, one that took them through
disbelief, anger, confusion, frustration and obsession. Gibson
filed a lawsuit against the college (its staff had intercepted
ammunition that Lo had ordered through the mail, then passed it on
to Lo unopened), but the case dragged on until Gibson was so filled
with rage that he felt capable of murder himself. He set out to
free himself, in a sense, by looking at the facts of his son's
death and writing this book. In it, he interviews witnesses, Lo's
friends, attorneys, the gun dealer who sold Lo his weapon _ and
finds himself reacting to them in surprising ways. But the climax
of his book comes when he meets the parents of Wayne Lo _ sweet,
wounded people whose son, like Gibson's, is lost to them. Sad,
sometimes funny, beautifully written (Gibson is an antiquarian book
dealer) and ultimately triumphant, this is the story of a father's
journey through grief and his refusal to be destroyed by it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ONE YEAR OFF &QL; 
 &UR; By David Elliot Cohen  &QL; 
 &UR; (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We read the parts about Italy first and were dismayed to learn
that Cohen was so cowed by Italian drivers that in Florence he
actually paid one of them to park his car for him. This did not
bode well for our enjoyment of his book, and sure enough, we found
it to be a bit of a trial. Here's the hook: Cohen turned 40 and,
sensing a midlife crisis on the horizon, decided he should sell his
small publishing business and his house, take his kids out of
school (the oldest was 8) and spend a year traveling around the
world. His wife agreed to this, which seems shockingly adventurous
for people who can't park a car in Florence. But we digress: This
book is a collection of ``adventures, anecdotes and minor
epiphanies'' from their year off, served up as e-mail letters they
sent to their friends. Some of it is great fun. Some of it is . . .
well, ``kid'' anecdotes, which as we all know are entertaining in
direct proportion to your degree of affiliation with the kids in
question. Kara and Willie were bored at a volcano in Costa Rica but
fascinated by the ubiquitous dog poop in Paris, and Cohen has
quotes to prove it. More interesting is the fact that the family
traveled more than 50,000 miles in 13 months for less money than it
would have cost to live in California for that time. And they'd do
it again in a heartbeat despite the ennui and the dog poop. This is
not a true travel book, but if you have kids and are looking for
inspiration, it might be for you. &QL; 
 &UR; ANNE FRANK &QL; 
 &UR; By Melissa Muller (Owl, $14) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Muller's biography of Frank, new in paperback, includes
references to five previously unpublished pages of Anne's diary in
which she criticizes her parents' marriage and expresses her wish
that the diary be kept out of her family's hands. Anne's father
kept these pages separate from the rest of her diary and gave them
to a friend just before his death in 1980. News of their existence
caused a stir last year, and holders of the Anne Frank copyright
denied Muller permission to quote them directly. That seems shoddy
in light of the final pages of this book, which contain a note from
Miep Gies, the woman who helped the Frank family during the two
years when they were in hiding. How did she find the courage to do
it? ``Of course, it takes courage to do one's duty as a human
being, of course, one has to be prepared to make certain
sacrifices,'' she writes. ``But that's true in many of life's
situations.'' &QL; 
You can reach Anne Stephenson at amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net,
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
