<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3186 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CANADA-BUNNY-BOS &LR;      08-19 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-BUNNY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE MORE, BUGS BUNNY ONE HOP AHEAD OF TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Bugs Bunny may be politically incorrect, but he won't
be bounced from the Canadian airwaves after all.
</P>
<P>
   The wascally wabbit got off with a paw-slapping this week after
being hauled before the Canadian Broadcast Standards Council for
insinuating that women are ``witches.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bugs first uttered the offending remark 45 years ago.
But his misogyny is only now catching up with him.
</P>
<P>
   A formal complaint against Bugs was lodged with the
quasi-judicial tribunal by an Ontario woman angered by the closing
line of the cartoon ``Bewitched Bunny,'' which has aired hundreds
of times in Canada and the United States since its release by
Warner Brothers in 1954, apparently without previous complaint.
</P>
<P>
   The animated yarn is a Looney Tunes twist on the fairytale
classic ``Hansel and Gretel.'' In it, Bugs saves a pair of kids
from being gobbled by the wicked witch, then, just on the verge of
getting cooked himself, douses the hag with magic powder _
transforming her into a very nubile female bunny.
</P>
<P>
   After cavorting a bit, the cartoon pair amble off arm-in-arm
into the sunset. Instead of just thanking his lucky rabbit's foot,
though, Bugs looks back over his shoulder with what might be fairly
described as a leer, saying, ``Ah sure, I know! But aren't they all
witches inside?''
</P>
<P>
   That was just too much for a female viewer in Toronto,
identified in news reports as Judith Hansel, who fired off a
missive to the Global Television broadcast company in July 1998
after being ``horrified'' by the hijinks on The Bugs Bunny and
Tweety Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Televising this anti-woman cartoon demands that you personally
offer a televised apology to woman viewers,'' she wrote, insisting
the apology be read at the start of the evening national newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Bell, Global's director for regulatory affairs,
responded with a letter saying the company was sorry the viewer was
offended, but denying the cartoon was demeaning to women.
</P>
<P>
   Unsatisfied, the angry watcher filed a formal complaint with the
Broadcast Standards Council, Canada's TV watchdog body, charging
that Bugs was not just a carrot-chomping wiseguy but a violator of
the industry's Sex Role Portrayal Code.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cartoon gives a wrong idea that all females are evil and
destructive... and that women are evil inside,'' her complaint
stated.
</P>
<P>
   It looked liked curtains. But wily old Bugs, as he has so many
times since making his cartoon debut in 1938, once again managed to
hippity-hop his way out of trouble _ barely.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal allowed that he's a hare-brained troublemaker, all
right, and way out of step with the times. But he hadn't broken
Canadian television content rules. Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is undeniable innuendo in the closing line... which some
may find offensive,'' the six-member panel wrote in a
densely-worded report officially closing the case. ``That being
said, the Council is not of the view that a breach of the broadcast
Code it administers is entailed.''
</P>
<P>
   How's that again, Doc?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, bottom line: Bugs walks.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first time that the world's most recognizable
rabbit has roused ire. Several Bugs Bunny cartoons are no longer
aired because they rubbed people the wrong way with racial or
ethnic stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Canadian case apparently marks the first time Bugs has
faced formal charges of sexism.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been complaints about insensitive characterizations
in old cartoons such as this one, but I don't know of any other
serious attempt to silence Bugs Bunny,'' said Stephen Charla,
curator of the International Museum of Cartoon Art in Boca Raton,
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Created by animator Chuck Jones, the smartmouthed rabbit
features the voice of Mel Blanc and, in addition to cartoons, has
appeared in comic books, motion pictures and newspaper strips.
</P>
<P>
   The panel that ruled on Bugs's fate consisted of two former TV
station managers, a lawyer, a self-styled ``feminist media
activist,'' a filmmaker and a television producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of a fence-sitting decision,'' said Ron Cohen,
national chairman of the Broadcast Standards Council, telling the
Ottawa Citizen that Bug's remark ``wasn't a positive thing to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Global TV, meanwhile, is happy to see the long-eared star escape
the regulatory briar patch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the tape, it's done so tongue-in-cheek, the way
it's presented could never be offensive to women,'' Bell told
Canadian reporters. ``We're happy with the decision. That's all,
folks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
