<TEXT>
<P>
   (gm) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, Aug. 20, Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Serbia's two main
opposition leaders finally come together on one platform for the
first time in three years when the Serbian Renewal Movement's Vuk
Draskovic addressed a mass rally after saying he would not.
(Summary from wires.) By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-GOLCUK (Golcuk, Turkey) _ The story from a town where
hundreds or even thousands may still be trapped beneath the rubble,
including sailors at a collapsed naval base. Residents here are
angry that the rescue efforts seem to be more focused on
servicemen. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUG-RESISTANT-BACTERIA (Washington) _ More than 200 people
in Minnesota and North Dakota have become sick _ and four otherwise
healthy children have died _ over the past two years after becoming
infected with a drug-resistant germ that, until now, has been
confined to hospitals and nursing homes, federal health officials
said Thursday. By Sheryl Gay stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   LUTHERAN-EPISCOPAL (Denver) _ The nation's largest Lutheran
denomination votes to enter a sweeping agreement with the Episcopal
Church, under which the two churches, which together represent
nearly 8 million American Protestants, would fully recognize each
others members and sacraments, exchange clergy members when needed
and join in missionary and social service projects. By Gustav
Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   DEMS-VALUES (Washington) _ Democrats are still drawing low marks
from the public on values, causing nervousness about the upcoming
elections in which the party enjoys advantages on many other
issues, according to recent polls. By Alison Mitchell. 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ENVIRON (Albany, N.Y.) _ Under a change of a few words of
state law, money that New York state voters approved to help clean
up the environment will instead be used to supply water to new
industries. By Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
</TEXT>
