<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOSTON-SARGENT-2TAKES     08-19 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-SARGENT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ONCE-IN-A-LIFETIME SHOWING OF SARGENTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston is in a tizzy over Sargent this summer. A
traveling retrospective, ``John Singer Sargent,'' already seen in
Washington and London, is making its final stop at the Museum of
Fine Arts, and three smaller shows are on view elsewhere. Even
enthusiastic natives are finding it all a bit much.
</P>
<P>
   Sargent was born in Italy in 1856; his parents were expatriate
Philadelphians. But Boston has always embraced him as an adoptive
son, and not without reason. He put in quality work time here. He
whipped up portraits of the local swells, notably Isabella Gardner,
whom he depicted as a wasp-waisted bodhisattva with a smeary face
and milky skin. He produced his only mural cycles _ three of them _
for the city. He considered them his highest monument.
</P>
<P>
   The murals, all still in place, are getting a lot of attention
these days, not because they are things of undying beauty (they
aren't), but because they complicate the usual image of Sargent as
a souped-up van Dyck, a Gilded Age yuppie with a magic touch and
not much else. Highly socialized, in love with surfaces of every
kind, he was never the mystery-wrapped-in-an-enigma type. But the
murals suggest that he had his depths, intellectual and otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   One cycle is permanently installed in the Museum of Fine Arts
itself. In 1916, Sargent created paintings and sculptural reliefs
for the building's main rotunda. Partly to complement the
neo-classical architecture, he concocted allegorical scenes related
to art: ``Architecture, Painting and Sculpture, Protected by Athena
From the Ravages of Time.'' That sort of thing.
</P>
<P>
   The results were an instant hit. Sargent was asked to do more
and eventually came through with 20 paintings _ executed on canvas
in the studio, then glued into place _ and 18 reliefs. He was about
to sail from London to Boston to install the last paintings when he
died in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has cleaned the ensemble, and it looks great, really
seeable for the first time in years. What does one see? A curious
melange of Classical muscle, Baroque attitude and contemporary wit.
(Sargent is rumored to have used touring ``Ziegfeld Follies'' girls
as models for some of his peplos-clad maidens.)
</P>
<P>
   All of Sargent's murals have a straitjacketed feel. He developed
a new, clean-lined style for them, which was brave of an artist at
mid-career. But the painterly brio that had made his name and
remained his strong suit was left out.
</P>
<P>
   That's why these projects look most dynamic in their planning
stages, as a wealth of preparatory studies in the retrospective
suggests. A nude oil sketch of Thomas McKeller, the black Boston
hotel worker who posed for many figures in the rotunda paintings,
including that of Apollo, carries a thrill of sensuality that the
finished murals lack.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Public Library
</P>
<P>
   Of the three mural cycles, the most ambitious and interesting is
also the hardest to see. Titled ``Triumph of Religion'' (1890-1919)
and covering the walls of the so-called Sargent Gallery on the
third floor of the Boston Public Library, it is in desperate need
of cleaning, repair and relighting, all of which the library plans
to undertake at some unspecified future date.
</P>
<P>
   The task will be a ticklish one: the murals are an intricate mix
of paintings and reliefs in varying states of decay. No less
complex is the now-obscured thematic program, which dramatizes a
fanciful historical transition from Judaism to Christianity, with
figures of pagan gods, Hebrew prophets and Spanish Madonnas folded
in.
</P>
<P>
   The whole cycle was meant to conclude with a painting of the
Sermon on the Mount, though this was never executed. Sargent, who
had a horror of controversy, was accused of using anti-Semitic
stereotypes in the mural and dropped the project. But even
incomplete and with serious conceptual flaws, ``Triumph of
Religion'' is an impressive thing, the work of an erudite if
somewhat conventional thinker who was also a virtuoso technician.
</P>
<P>
   The clearest view of the murals is to be found not on the walls
but in vitrines. As part of the exhibition ``Sargent in Context,''
there is a modest display of documentary material in the Sargent
Gallery itself. A dozen or so Michelangelesque figure drawings are
in cases downstairs. An exquisite oil and graphite study, tucked
away in a vestibule not far from the murals, shows how the Sermon
on the Mount might have appeared in situ. The design is lucid; the
colors are bright.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University
</P>
<P>
   The third ``Boston'' mural cycle, and the smallest, is in
Harvard's Widener Library. A memorial tribute to lives lost in
World War I, it consists of two tall vertical panels, ``Death and
Victory'' and ``Coming of the Americans'' (1921-22), set on either
side of a central staircase.
</P>
<P>
   The war hit Sargent hard; a beloved niece was killed in a
bombing raid in France. He caught a sense of its waste in the
monumental 1919 painting ``Gassed,'' commissioned by the British
War Memorials Committee and on view in the retrospective at the
Museum of Fine Arts. The Harvard murals aren't in this league. With
their strapping soldiers and stagey allegorical figures, they are
scaled-up propaganda posters. Even critics at the time seem to have
thought so.
</P>
<P>
   It is the rough draft that retains the sap of life, as one sees
in ``Sargent in the Studio: Drawings, Sketchbooks and Oil
Sketches,'' organized at the Fogg Art Museum by Miriam Stewart and
Kerry Schauber. The bulk of these treasures were given to Harvard
by the artist's two sisters, and mural studies, some of them
knockouts, are the focus of the selection here.
</P>
<P>
   But another Sargent is present, too, the artist whom everyone
knows, some people are mad for and history will probably remember.
This is the Sargent of the portraits: formal, in the case of an
evanescent watercolor of the ultrachic Virginie Gautreau, better
known as Madame X, and informal in seductive studio drawings of the
young working-class men who served as his favored models.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the artist who, in watercolors as fleet as snapshots,
captured family and friends snoozing on country picnics. There is
the somewhat less familiar painter of landscapes: a view of an
Alpine glacier in the Fogg show, executed when Sargent was 14, has
the sparkle of a cut diamond.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gardner Museum
</P>
<P>
   Mature work in this genre has been gathered in ``Sargent: The
Late Landscapes'' at the Isabella Stewart Gardner Museum (where,
incidentally, the immense ``El Jaleo'' (1882) is permanently
installed). These paintings, like the murals, seem to have been the
artist's attempt to distance himself from portraiture and to fully
explore progressive terrain already mapped out by figures like
Monet.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the landscapes, executed on trips to Europe, the Near
East and the Canadian Rockies, play the Impressionist game, as in
the oil-on-canvas ``Yoho Falls'' (1916), a half-abstract jumble of
rocks and mists conjured up in stabs and spatters and relieflike
ridges of paint.
</P>
<P>
   But Impressionism was old, old news by this time; in Paris,
Cubism had already reached its golden age. Whether Sargent's late
landscapes represent a new direction for him, or simply confirm
that his gracile hand and eye for light could adapt willy-nilly to
any subject, remains a matter for debate. There is little debate,
however, that the concentration of Sargent's art in the Boston area
this summer is a rare and possibly once-in-a-lifetime event.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Anyone bent on one last Sargent fix can find it in a diminutive
but very pretty show of his paintings and drawings, ``John Singer
Sargent,'' at the Portland Museum of Art in Maine, an hour or so
north of Gloucester.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the artist's trademark subjects are in place: Venice and
the Alps, well-heeled clients (Mrs. Henry St. John Smith and her
boyish but sad-looking husband), and a few old friends. One of them
is Elise Meyer, who is seen in a pencil sketch here but who appears
with her mother and brother in a traffic-stopping family portrait _
Sargent made them all resemble some fabulous species of orchid _ at
the Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
