<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3204 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-BLUEEYES20-COX     08-19 0372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BLUEEYES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grant's affable-guy shtick takes a hit in `Blue Eyes'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An effete British auctioneer experiences culture clash when he
finds himself married to the mob, literally, in ``Mickey Blue
Eyes.'' Call it a sleeping-with-the-fish-out-of-water comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Grant plays Michael Felgate, a courteous chap who's
surprised when his girlfriend, Gina (Jeanne Tripplehorn), calls off
their relationship after he pops the question. The reason: Her
family are all members of the mob, and she's afraid Michael will
get drawn into their web.
</P>
<P>
   Gina's father, Frank (James Caan), warmly welcomes his
prospective son-in-law. But, sure enough, Michael soon finds
himself doing little ``favors'' for colleagues of the family. It's
around this point that the movie slips its moorings, accumulating a
body count and also a tone that wobbles between farce and thriller.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Analyze This'' took mafia cliches and gave them a '90s
update, the makers of ``Mickey'' don't seem to realize that their
jokes are treadworn. So is Grant's one-trick performance as an
elegant bumbler. He's terrific at it, yes; but it's time to show
more range. Tripplehorn doesn't help him any; her fretting
performance squelches the comedy. But Caan is enthusiastic, and the
great gallery of mafioso faces includes gravelly Burt Young as
Vito, head of the Graziosi family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' (which is the name Michael goes by when he
has to pretend to be a mob member) is the second movie produced by
Grant's girlfriend, Elizabeth Hurley. The first was ``Extreme
Measures,'' a medical thriller that let Grant switch gears into
drama. It tanked at the box office. That's a shame, because the new
movie seems designed to present the prepackaged Grant persona, the
professional, shrinking male virgin of the late 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mickey
</P>
<P>
   Blue Eyes''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Hugh Grant, James Caan and Jeanne Tripplehorn. Rated
PG-13 for brief strong language, some violence and sensuality. At
metro theaters.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An awkwardly manufactured mob comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
