<HEADER>
A3210 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-TRICK20-COX     08-19 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TRICK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For new friends, `trick' is finding spot to be together
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Jim Fall's new film ``trick'' may not be a huge treat,
but it's a sturdy and often well-acted example of post-AIDS,
post-``queer''-bashing cinema.
</P>
<P>
   In this romantic comedy, the characters' sexuality isn't the
only thing that's a given; so is a prominent aspect of gay single
life. That is, while lots of guys are looking for true love, on any
given night they'll certainly settle for a quickie with a real
cutie (actually, a good many straight singles feel the same way).
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel (Christian Campbell), an aspiring musical-comedy writer,
is a real cutie in a sort of fresh-faced, dimpled Mousketeer way
(we're talking the Annette era). Mark (John Paul Pitoc), however,
is more than a cutie. He's a well-muscled hunk of boy-toy who
dances at a local bar wearing little more than a smile and a skinny
pink thong.
</P>
<P>
   The two pick each other up, both clearly intending nothing more
than a mutually gratifying one-night stand. But that's the rub.
Mark lives in one of the outer boroughs of New York, so Gabriel's
Greenwich Village place is the obvious choice. Unfortunately, it's
occupied _ first by his ditsy best friend (Tori Spelling), who's
busily photocopying her resume, then by his boorish straight
roommate, whose girlfriend has just returned from Europe. For the
rest of the movie, Gabriel and Mark roam the streets. Every time a
possible solution arises, so does an obstacle (that's why some
reviews have compared this to ``After Hours,'' a shaky comparison
at best).
</P>
<P>
   ``trick'' becomes more endearing as its simple lust story turns
into a simple love story. Forced to get to know each other before
sex, they learn some surprising things. Further, director Fall uses
their nighttime odyssey as an amusing insider's tour of gay Chelsea
and Greenwich Village. Stops along the way include a piano bar
where everyone knows every show tune ever written and a crowded
disco where shirtless men dance to Helen Reddy's ``I Am Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   What weakens the picture is that, as it goes along, the
obstacles become more and more contrived. After a point you begin
thinking, hey, fellas, why not just spring for a hotel room? Still,
Campbell (Neve's brother) and Pitoc are pleasant company, and their
self-revelations are appealing.
</P>
<P>
   One final problem: Spelling seems to think that going the indie
film route will do for her career what it's done for Christina
Ricci and Lisa Kudrow. One small difference: They can act.
</P>
<P>
   ``trick''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Christian Campbell and John Paul Pitoc. Directed by Jim
Fall. Rated R for sexuality, language and mature themes.
</P>
<P>
   1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Appealing romantic comedy about two gay guys
looking to make love in all the wrong places.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
