A3211 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-HUGHGRANT-TEX     08-19 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HUGHGRANT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALK WITH THE DISARMINGLY CHARMING HUGH GRANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most newspaper and magazine stories about movie stars like to
pretend that they're the only ones covering the subject. We are not
going to do that to you with Hugh Grant.
</P>
<P>
   At one point this month, photos of Grant graced the covers of
Esquire, Detour and Entertainment Weekly. During the past couple of
weeks, he has appeared on ``The Late Show With David Letterman,''
``The Tonight Show With Jay Leno,'' CNN's ``TalkBack Live'' and
``Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee.'' He has also spoken with dozens of TV and
newspaper reporters.
</P>
<P>
   And this is just for his latest movie, ``Mickey Blue Eyes,''
which opens Friday. Grant previously made the publicity rounds just
last May for ``Notting Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   What could he possibly have left to say? The Divine Brown
incident is old news. The rumors that he and Julia Roberts clashed
on the set of ``Notting Hill'' apparently are false.
</P>
<P>
   He and James Caan also got along on the set of ``Mickey Blue
Eyes,'' in which Grant plays an art-house auctioneer who gets mixed
up with Caan's mob figure. He helped longtime love Elizabeth Hurley
produce the movie, although he gives her most of the credit (she
charmed real-life goodfellas during research).
</P>
<P>
   And journalists are obsessed with his hair.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out, though, that Grant has plenty to say, much of it
humorous, often at his own expense. So we'll let him do the
talking. Here are some observations he made during a Dallas stop.
They are best read with a British accent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Esquire cover: ``That's by far the worst cover, not only
ever taken of me, but of any human being in the history of
magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Entertainment Weekly cover: ``I look like Ellen
DeGeneres.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Detour cover: ``I look like Princess Margaret after she
had the very bad scalding in her bath.''
</P>
<P>
   (Note: We happen to think all the covers are just fine. Well,
maybe not on Detour, where Grant looks more like Christopher
Walken).
</P>
<P>
   On magazine photos, in general: ``Have you seen the picture
inside (Esquire) with me as a Fort Worth cowboy? Did you find that
particularly hilarious? They always do this thing of saying
(imitates a pretentious American photographer), `Do you want to do
something really different? 'Cause you're always in a suit, it
would be so great if you're like, crazy and wacky.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I want to say, `Oh, p--- off. Just make me look nice.' But
then you're so tired, you give in and they bring out the spurs and
the cowboy hat.''
</P>
<P>
   On being photogenic: Even the people I hire, the PR people, are
unable to lie about some of these pictures. Particularly the girl
who works permanent for us in London. She just sits there, looking
at the contact sheets, crying with laughter at how bad my pictures
are.''
</P>
<P>
   On unfortunate show-biz slang: (Reads from a Variety review of
``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' which has just arrived by fax): ```Grant's
new vehicle should hit a commercial bull's-eye. ... bolstering the
actor's popular resurgence and solidifying his b.o. (box office)
bankability.' `B.o.'s' an unfortunate term, especially today, when
I've run out of my Estee Lauder.''
</P>
<P>
   On music: ``Music is a terrible black hole for me. I don't know
why, but I've never been good on music. I think I've got two
records to this day. One of which is `Godspell.' So I'm not exactly
a rocker. I guess I'm slightly more into it now than I used to be,
because I got quite heavily involved with the director of `Mickey
Blue Eyes.' I got quite heavily into all that Sinatra, Dean Martin
type of stuff. I listen to all that in my car.''
</P>
<P>
   On books: ``I've got to that stage now where I can't bear to
read any book by anybody younger than me. I find that too
upsetting, particularly if it's good. I don't mind if it's (junk).
If it's good, it's just too annoying.'' (For the record, Grant's
favorite writers are Martin and Kingsley Amis, Evelyn Waugh, Nancy
Mitford and Bill Bryson.)
</P>
<P>
   On rumors that he'll retire from acting and take up writing: ``I
don't know, I will have to decide then whether to put my money
where my mouth is and go and do it or not. I could say to ... my
agents and everyone, `It's over, I've stopped acting. Goodbye, I'm
off to write my bad novel.' Or I could do a halfway house, keep my
(production) company going and go and write my own script, which is
also quite tempting. Or I could just chicken out and accept this
job I've been offered with this very funny script, and shoot that
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   On his earliest fans: ``(After this tour) I go to Japan to
promote `Notting Hill' for a couple of days. ... Japan might be
fascinating. I've always wanted to go there. You know, they were
the first people to ever like me. Way, way back, way before `Four
Weddings and a Funeral,' when I did (1987's) `Maurice' with
Merchant-Ivory. I got unbelievable numbers of letters from Japanese
girls. I don't know why, they have this sort of thing about English
gentlemen. Anything English _ golf, whiskey, that sort of stuff.
And they went nuts. I used to get sackfuls of mail with origami and
stuff inside it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny enough, `Four Weddings and a Funeral' _ the only country
it failed in was Japan. They apparently didn't get the jokes. They
thought it was rather a sad film.''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
