A3217 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-COX     08-19 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDENT ENROLLMENTS TO RISE AGAIN THIS FALL
 &HT;    EDS: Data for textbox or graphic at end of story
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The nation's schools and colleges will set new
enrollment records this fall, President Clinton said Thursday as he
released the government's annual back-to-school report.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic president and Republicans in Congress quickly
moved to claim that the report supported their rival visions for
the size of tax cuts and the rules for federal aid to education.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, 53.2 million public and private school students are
expected in kindergarten through 12th grade, according to the
report. That is about 446,000 more than last year's enrollment, an
increase of just under one percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another 14.9 million students up 273,000, or 1.9 percent over
last year's record are expected at two-year and four-year colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Federal researchers expect the number of students in schools and
colleges to rise until 2006, dip slightly for three or four years,
and then begin to rise again.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the increase is due to immigration, the lure of higher
earnings for educated workers, and the state and local funding
increases that were made possible by continued prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest single factor cited in the report is that more
members of the ``baby boom echo'' generation are old enough to go
to high school or college. They are the grandchildren of people who
had lots of children during the ``baby boom'' that followed World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no end in sight to the increasing number of young
people attending our schools, `` said Education Secretary Richard
Riley, who is expecting his 11th grandchild soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the announcement of the administration's program to
save the future for Secretary Riley's grandchildren,'' Clinton
joked to sympathetic educators gathered next to the White House in
the Old Executive Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   He said the report reinforced his decision to veto the tax-cut
bill Republicans plan to send him next month. It would deprive the
government of revenue that could be used to finance education and
other domestic programs, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately the congressional majority wants to back off the
commitment we made to hire new teachers and build new schools,''
said Clinton, painting a nightmare vision of children who are
taught year after year in trailers parked outside overcrowded
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larger classes, fewer teachers, more trailers,'' he said. When
he repeated the phrase, it came out, ``Larger taxes, fewer
teachers, more trailers.'' Beaming, he added, ``Sounds like a
country song. I like country music, but we can do better than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans later counter-attacked vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   They said their plan to give small tax incentives for
construction bonds in all school districts was better than
Clinton's plan to give big tax incentives for construction bonds in
100 poor school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is permanent and applicable to all school districts
... not just the ones the president picks,'' said Rep. Bill Archer,
R-Texas, chairman of the tax-writing Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans want to let school districts mingle federal
teacher-training funds with the federal subsidies earmarked for the
hiring of 100,000 more teachers, said Rep. William Goodling, R-Pa.,
chairman of the Committee on Education and the Workforce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some school districts will choose to use the funds to hire
additional qualified teachers,'' Goodling said. ``Others may decide
they would prefer to enhance the professional skills of their
existing teacher corps.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said he looked forward confidently to reaching a
compromise with Republicans ``after the August break.'' Congress
returns Wednesday Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get this worked out,'' Clinton told reporters. He said
the compromise could require Republicans to accept smaller tax
cuts, stronger protections for Social Security and more spending
than they intend for education, agriculture, medical research and
incentives for business investments in poor nations and
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The full back-to-school report, ``The Baby Boom Echo: No End in
Sight,'' is posted on the Education Department's Web site at
http://www.ed.gov/pubs/bbecho99/.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Data for textbox or graphic
</P>
<P>
   NUMBER OF U.S. STUDENTS RISING AT ALL LEVELS THIS FALL
</P>
<P>
   LEVEL....................................................Fall of
1998 ................. Fall of 1999 ........... Increase
</P>
<P>
   Kindergarten-grade 8 ........... 38,110,000 ...................
38,323,000 ............. 213,000
</P>
<P>
   Grades 9-12 ................................. 14,658,000
....................14,891,000 .............. 233,000
</P>
<P>
   Colleges, Universities ......... 14,608,000
....................14,881,000 .............. 273,000
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: U.S. Department of Education enrollment projections.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
