<HEADER>
A3224 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-BLACKBEARS22-C     08-19 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BLACKBEARS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tourists' food and trash is bad news for Smoky bears
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Holly Morris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're planning a fall trip to the Great Smoky Mountains,
beware of the black bears that populate the national park. Wild
bears in the Smoky Mountains and other national parks are naturally
afraid of people, but may turn dangerous when they learn to eat
food we humans eat. And they can smell food _ or garbage containing
food _ from far away.
</P>
<P>
   Black bears were once hunted close to extinction in the Smoky
Mountains. Protected since the park was founded in 1930, their
population has grown to more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really not any place you can go in the park that there
are not black bears. We have one of the highest densities of black
bears in North America,'' says Kim DeLozier, wildlife biologist for
the park.
</P>
<P>
   One way we can help keep bears alive is by not feeding them.
Instead, DeLozier says, keep them at a distance _ from yourself,
children, pets, cabins and campsites. And never leave anything that
smells of food where bears might find it.
</P>
<P>
   When you're in bear country, put all food, food wrappers,
cooking foil and strong-smelling items such as toothpaste, soap and
shaving cream out of the reach of bears. Bear-tempting garbage
should be left in the bear-proof containers _ cans or Dumpsters _
the National Park Service provides within the park or locked up
inside a bear-proof vehicle or structure.
</P>
<P>
   Bears live a lot longer if they eat grasses, seeds, berries,
ants, acorns and other natural foods, rather than hot dogs,
Twinkies and potato chips. It's not so much a question of a
healthful diet as of preserving a healthy distance between bears
and humans. Bears that become accustomed to human food become
threats to people and to themselves: They may seek food along
roadsides until they're accidentally killed by a car, or they may
injure park visitors and have to be euthanized.
</P>
<P>
   If you find yourself face to face with a bear, the National Park
Service advises you to back away slowly (don't run) and seek
shelter in a car or a house. If the bear looks as if it's going to
attack you, get aggressive. Try to fight back with any object
available; wave your arms, and make as much noise as you can. Do
not play dead.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Great Smoky Mountains National Park:
423-436-1200, or its Web site: www.nps.gov/grsm
</P>
<P>
   Holly Morris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
