</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CHEROKEE22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High-tech Cherokee museum mixes history, entertainment
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEROKEE, N.C. _ Computer-animated forest creatures. An
electric-light ``campfire'' that billows smoke. A ``talking rock''
that sounds out the Cherokee language in stereo. This is not your
father's Native American museum.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of the Cherokee Indian, a static exhibition of
baskets and arrowheads encased in glass from its opening in 1976,
got a high-tech face-lift in the summer of 1998. The $3.5 million
renovation, designed ``to mix education and entertainment,'' says
museum director Ken Blankenship, incorporates traditional artifacts
with computer animation, holograms, dioramas and audio voice-overs
to tell the history of the Cherokee people from the Paleo-Indian
period through the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   To make the museum more fun for children, Blankenship consulted
designers and artists from around the country. Among them was
Disney Imagineering, the company that designs Disney's theme park
attractions and created the set for the Alliance Theatre production
of ``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd seen lots of kids come through here and not really learn
anything,'' explains Blankenship, who became the museum's director
in 1986. Attendance has plateaued in the past few years at about
140,000 per year; Blankenship hopes the more child-friendly
displays will draw 200,000 people annually within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   The experience begins in a small theater, where visitors gather
around a smoldering ``campfire'' (computers control the flickering
lights and smoke emissions) to watch an animated video that depicts
the creation of the world from the Cherokee point of view. A
medicine man introduces the tiny water spider that brought fire to
the Cherokee people, the buzzard that beat the Earth with its wings
to make the Great Smoky Mountains and other natural legends.
</P>
<P>
   Exiting the theater, visitors stroll through time, past
pre-Columbian pottery and spears to multimedia displays such as a
``talking rock.'' Inscribed on this rough-hewn block of stone are
the characters of the Cherokee alphabet, created by Chief Sequoyah
in the early 1800s. A honey-toned voice recites the alphabet and
each character lights up in turn.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's centerpiece is the multipart display on the
Cherokee Removal of 1838. In the Chamber of Dissenting Voices,
visitors hear taped re-creations of speeches from key political
figures of the time, including President Andrew Jackson, who
favored transplanting the Cherokee tribe from western North
Carolina to Oklahoma, and Cherokee Chief John Ross, who opposed the
move. A massive mural of the Trail of Tears looms in an adjoining
room, accompanied by a taped voice that reads the names of the
thousands of Cherokees who died during the infamous march westward.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit can be an emotional experience, particularly for
people with blood ties to the Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come over here several times a year,'' says Monette Knaps,
38, of Sevierville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Stuart, 36, have Native Americans in their
family trees. Stuart's great-grandmother and Monette's grandmother
are full-blooded Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just something about the area that we find
interesting,'' Monette explains. ``I guess we're trying to relive a
little bit of our past.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information:
</P>
<P>
   Museum of the Cherokee Indian, U.S. 441 North at Drama Road in
Cherokee. 828-497-3481. Open 9 a.m-8 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays, 9
a.m.-5 p.m. Sundays, through Aug. 31. Open 9 a.m.-5 p.m. daily from
September to June. $6 adults, $4 children.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
