<HEADER>
A3226 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-EARTHSHINES-AU     08-19 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EARTHSHINES-AURA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laid-back adventure awaits at Earthshine
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE TOXAWAY, N.C. _ The celestial-sounding name is alluring:
Earthshine Mountain Lodge. Definitely has that organically grown,
Birkenstock sandal-wearing, granola-eating ring to it. A place so
pastoral and picture-perfect rustic that L.L. Bean has photographed
two catalogs of country couture here.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, first-timers never know exactly what to expect from this
back-to-nature getaway in the Blue Ridge Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Take Cheryl Dunson. The Peachtree City mom was more or less
flying by the seat of her pants when she booked a weekend at the
rough-hewn retreat for herself and her 9-year-old son, Kent.
</P>
<P>
   And as it turned out, the seat of her pants took a beating:
whooshing down sliding rock on the North Fork of Flat Creek;
careening down the hill behind the lodge on baby shampoo-and-water
slicked sheets of plastic; and bouncing in the saddle atop a white
horse named Casper.
</P>
<P>
   Fanny fatigue notwithstanding, Dunson was upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling it an adventure,'' she says gamely, dripping and
slightly sudsy as Kent made his umpteenth turn on the slippery
slope. ``I wanted to do something different. I didn't want to do
Disney World or the beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, she was a little taken aback at first that there was no
air-conditioning or locks on the doors.
</P>
<P>
   But 24 hours into the adventure, she was settling into Earth-
</P>
<P>
   shine's unhurried, carefree rhythm and, like the rest of us,
enjoying the simple pleasures _ nature hikes, catching up on
reading, striking up conversations with the other guests, telling
ghost stories, feeding barn animals and plowing into meals that
would fill a farmhand.
</P>
<P>
   It's amazing what happens on a Saturday night when TV is not an
option.
</P>
<P>
   After an afternoon storm left the landscape rather sodden, the
evening's plans were changed from a barnyard trek and ``fairy
hunt'' to a ``broom dance'' and circle games upstairs at the lodge.
Watching our kids prance about, trying to avoid being the one stuck
with the broom as a partner when the music stopped, was gratifying
to us parents. (Most Saturday nights, you'd have to surgically
remove the remote control from my 11-year-old daughter's right hand
and wrest the phone from the other.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so nostalgic,'' says Sally Simpson of Jacksonville,
who was visiting with her daughter and grandchildren. ``This is how
we grew up _ families interacting, playing cards and games, doing
magic tricks. A rainy day didn't bother us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain or shine, after just a few hours at Earthshine, the outside
world seems very far away. Nobody is held captive, but there's
simply nothing appealing about getting back in your car and leaving
this haven of peace and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   The small but comfortable rooms with unpainted plank walls and
exposed wood beams are decorated in early log cabin with rag rugs
on board floors, quilts on the log beds. Don't worry, there are
electric lights, indoor plumbing and private bathrooms. Window fans
move breezes through the room. Rustic elegance, they call it.
</P>
<P>
   Three bounteous meals a day plus fruits and beverages are
included in the overnight price. Mealtime at communal tables under
the vaulted ceiling of the lodge's great room is a much-anticipated
event; like Pavlov's dog, when the triangle rings, we salivate.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived on Saturday just in time for a hamburger and barbecue
chicken cookout. Suppertime brought a feast of salmon with
hollandaise sauce, Moroccan stew, couscous, green salad, wild rice
salad and chocolate walnut cake with ice cream for dessert. Sunday
night dinner was an ample offering of cider-baked ham, yams, green
beans and blackberry cobbler.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast includes pancakes, sausage, homemade applesauce,
oatmeal, granola and fresh fruit. Hearty grub to fortify us for a
busy day.
</P>
<P>
   The activities list _ posted daily in the lodge _ is a
smorgasbord of fun: creek hikes, treks to King's Falls, water
games, fishing in the catfish pond, mornings at the re-created 1840
pioneer homestead or Cherokee village and, for kids only, cookouts
and barn loft camp-outs.
</P>
<P>
   But guilt-free indolence is also encouraged: rocking on the
deck, reading by the fireplace or napping in a hammock or curled up
on your oh-so-comfy bed. (I indulged in the latter during a summer
afternoon thunderstorm that dropped the temperature about 20
degrees, and it was one of the best snoozes I've had in a long
time.)
</P>
<P>
   We were glad we weren't too lazy to join the kids for the
Cherokee experience led by Benny Upton, whose tribal name is
``Amasissido.'' Everyone calls him Water Rabbit, because he's also
the guy who mans the hose during the afternoon water play.
</P>
<P>
   The band of tenderfeet who followed Water Rabbit into the secret
Cherokee hideaway in the forest Sunday morning included a
13-year-old named Austin Massey from Durham, N.C., who was trying
hard not to look overly interested in the proceedings. ``He's from
the Cynical Tribe,'' quipped Water Rabbit. ``He's a teenager.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon we all were learning to build a fire, grind corn, weave
fishing nets, throw tomahawks, use twigs to draw designs on clay
beads, hunt salamanders in the spring and tell a tulip popular from
a red maple.
</P>
<P>
   And as we headed back to the lodge, Kent Dunson _ flush with
success from nailing his tomahawk into a tree-stump target _ begged
his mom: ``Can we stay a week next year?''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-85 north, then just across the South
Carolina line, take Exit 1 (S.C. 11, the Cherokee Foothills
Parkway). Follow S.C. 11 to U.S. 178, then north to U.S. 64 in
Rosman. Travel west about 3 miles until you see a BP station on the
right. Turn right and travel .7 miles, then turn left onto a gravel
road. Go 1.6 miles to the Earthshine driveway, turn right and go up
the hill.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What it costs: The all-inclusive rates are $130 per night
adult double occupancy ($170 single), plus $70 per night for ages
6-15 and $40 per night for 5 and under. Pay-extra options include
horseback riding ($40 per person for a two-hour guided trail ride),
High Ropes Challenge ($40 per person), zip-line course ($50 per
person) and climbing wall ($25 per person).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What to bring: Clothing that can get wet and dirty, blue jeans
for horseback riding, a sleeping bag for the kids' campout, boots
or sturdy shoes for hiking, fishing poles for the catfish pond and
alcoholic beverages if desired.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 828-862-4207 or www.earthshinemtnlodge.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
