</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EARTHSHINES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A pastoral mountain place, Earthshine positively glows
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE TOXAWAY, N.C. _ Dusk creeps in slowly this lazy Sunday
evening as a round butterscotch candy moon rises above the pines.
We are gathered around a campfire beneath a tin-covered open-air
shelter next to the barn, listening to Appalachian folk tales and
hungrily assembling s'mores _ despite having eaten a big country
dinner only a couple of hours before.
</P>
<P>
   Goats and sheep watch curiously from the grassy hillside,
chickens scratch around the barnyard, and Liza Jane, the roly-poly
Mediterranean burro, mooches marshmallows. She is too plump for her
own good, and we have been instructed not to feed her _ no matter
how pitifully she begs.
</P>
<P>
   When darkness finally enfolds the barnyard, laughing children
with cupped hands outstretched dart about in pursuit of lightning
bugs. And as the fire dies down and the embers glow orange, the
grown-ups sit back, smiling contentedly, perhaps remembering
similar summer nights long ago.
</P>
<P>
   This is how the weekend ends at Earthshine Mountain Lodge _ not
with a bang but a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of Marion Boatright and Kim Maurer-Heinitsh,
Earthshine welcomed its first visitors in 1990. The centerpiece of
the 70-acre retreat bordering the Pisgah National Forest in the
Blue Ridge Mountains is a hand-built cedar log lodge with 10 cozy
rooms, most with lofts that are perfect for children.
</P>
<P>
   Earthshine _ defined as what you see when you look at a crescent
moon and see the rest of its sphere lightly lit _ was envisioned as
a place where guests might see things in a different light and
learn fresh perspectives on how we all relate to ourselves, the
natural world and to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Hunley of Aiken, S.C., made the mystic connection
immediately when she first encountered Earthshine about six years
ago. Back on the lodge's expansive deck after our barnyard trek,
she recalls, ``I was trail hiking in the area, and all of a sudden
we saw it. This place just glowed on the horizon.'' Soon, she
returned as an overnight guest, and has been coming back ever since
to bask in the warmth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' she says, gazing out on the purple peaks that ring the
farm and sighing with contentment, ``we're just hugged by
mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
