<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3228 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-JAZZ-ROLLINS20-COX     08-19 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-ROLLINS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sonny Rollins on his place in jazz, yoga and what he likes to
listen to
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have no doubt in your hearts. Sonny Rollins is the last man
standing.
</P>
<P>
   Not to get agonizingly pre-millennial about it, but when it
comes to jazz that pretty much everyone can agree is jazz, the
lineage of legendary figures is nearly shot. Masterful musicians
abound, as well as individuals who most certainly will map out the
next evolution of this extravagantly American music, but we are
perilously short these days on indisputable giants.
</P>
<P>
   Robust and engaged as he approaches his 69th birthday, Rollins
is not only critically acclaimed as the greatest living jazz
improviser, he's a vital link to the tumultuous days when jazz as
an art form with its roots in popular song and social dance steamed
ahead rather than glanced back at a long plateau, its engine room
almost recklessly stoked by an inspired, possessed assortment of
Promethean innovators: John Coltrane, Miles Davis, Thelonious Monk,
Dizzy Gillespie, Bud Powell, Charlie Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his pathbreaking contemporaries, significant influences
like drummer Max Roach and alto saxophonist Ornette Coleman, are
still at it. But Rollins, who performs Saturday at Spivey Hall in a
rare Southeastern date, has cut the widest swath for the longest
time to the loudest applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a really good night, he's the finest tenor saxophone player
alive,'' says John Armwood, a Marietta jazz educator and radio host
for WCLK-FM (91.9). ``His improvisations have a logic to them
that's fascinating to watch. He'll take a theme and deconstruct it
in a very logical and thematic way. He just works it and takes it
apart. His placement of notes and juxtapositions of rhythms can be
so profound. You can see the sparks shoot out of his horn.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Giddins, longtime jazz critic for the Village Voice and
author of the National Book Award-winning collection ``Vision of
Jazz,'' hails the saxophonist as an artist of Olympian stature.
Rollins, he writes, ``invokes tempests of sustained exhilaration
that have not often been heard in jazz since the glory days of
Louis Armstrong.''
</P>
<P>
   This, obviously, isn't the case every night Rollins plays, and,
as Giddins observes, hasn't extended to his latter-day studio work,
a steady stream of yearly albums that rarely fail to spark critical
debate. ``Enigmatic'' is the phrase that most often recurs in the
hefty summations of Rollins' career, which has been marked by
several extended sabbaticals _ most notoriously in the late 1950s,
when the saxophonist could be seen practicing from the exalted
vantage point of the Williamsburg Bridge. As with Bob Dylan (a
vastly more inconsistent performer equally committed to ripping up
his songbook), the decades of output make him dangerously easy to
underrate as a recording artist. Each new disc usually boasts
something inspired. But Rollins' epic endeavors of the 1950s _ the
decade when he made his reputation, following through on the
lessons of Charlie Parker and his early inspiration, Coleman
Hawkins _ really did earn him the title he gave to his breakthrough
album: ``Saxophone Colossus.'' He's had to compete with his own
shadow, one cast by a face whose strong nose, authoritative
whiskers and shaded gaze is, even now, impressively forceful enough
to occupy a spot on Easter Island.
</P>
<P>
   The saxophonist seems keenly aware of the struggle. He still
practices for three hours a day and limits his concert dates to
about 40 a year, the better to conserve his strength. He's an
unsparing critic of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the records I make fall into the category of not being up
to snuff,'' Rollins says, talking recently from his home in upstate
New York. ``All of them. I forget about the end result. I'm a very
sort of hard guy on myself, shooting for the stars all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In a rare interview, Rollins shared his thoughts on several
subjects, from the rich cultural legacy of his Harlem, N.Y.,
childhood to his abundant affection for calypso rhythms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On his use of calypsos, a staple of his concert repertoire
and, in tunes such as ``St. Thomas'' and ``Don't Stop the
Carnival,'' akin to personal signatures:
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents are from the Virgin Islands, and as a small boy I
heard some of that music. My mother used to take me to the dances.
I relate to it. The reason I like it is it's sort of liberating.
People like it. They really enjoy it. I don't see anything wrong
with that. I still really enjoy playing music in 4/4 time. I like
playing with the backbeat. Jazz is fighting to survive out here.
You've got rap and hip-hop and this and that. Everybody's trying to
keep jazz in the basement. Anything you can do to play jazz and
make people like it, you're accomplishing something. It's a
both/and situation. To me, there's nothing declasse about going
into a jazz setting and playing music that makes people dance. Some
purists feel any kind of funk rhythm is not what people should be
playing, but they can't do that to me because my credentials are
too secure.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the importance of yoga in his life, a discipline he pursued
after reading ``The Autobiography of a Yogi'' in the late 1960s,
and its connections to his music:
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been able to draw a straight line between something
that I play and yoga. The two are separate in many ways. If I go to
a studio and try to do hatha yoga before a recording date, it takes
away from the energy I need to put into the music. After reading
that book, I decided to go to India. I was interested in finding
another way of living, something besides the materialistic way of
life. I was in an ashram for four months and it centered my life so
when I came back, I was ready to get back into my music.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the art of improvising:
</P>
<P>
   ``I learn the melody. I learn the words. I learn different
versions of it. But on the bandstand I forget. I don't think
anymore. Then I let the song play me. It's a Zen approach. I'm not
consciously thinking of the melody or the words or the chord
changes. I try to make my mind empty so the song can come out from
where I want it to come from.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On his musical roots:
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it, playing as a little boy with my friends, but
I grew up at the right time and in the right place. When I was
born, we lived on 137th Street in Harlem ... and I came into
contact with a lot of the great stuff that was happening then. The
Cotton Club, the Apollo, there was so much music around Harlem.
Even as a little boy, I realize I gleaned a lot of it just being
around. It was a great upbringing. Music came naturally. I'm
fortunate. In my immediate crowd of people, everyone wanted to be a
jazz musician, but not everyone had the talent. My eyes were set on
that prize. I would practice prodigiously. It was fun to me. Nobody
had to say, `Sonny, practice that saxophone!'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On why he decided to become a saxophone player, picking up the
alto at age 11:
</P>
<P>
   ``Louis Jordan was playing in a club across the street from my
school. There was a picture showing him with a saxophone and
cutaway tails and tuxedo. I thought, `Wow, that's it! I'm going to
be a saxophone player.' It all came together with Louis Jordan. I
begged my mother to get me a saxophone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the last thing he hears before going to sleep at night:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a music listener. I have so much music that I'm
thinking about, I really try not to listen to music. That might
sound like heresy. I read a lot of books and, at night, I listen to
old-time radio shows on cassette. Radio detective shows, from the
'30s, '40s and '50s. It keeps me from watching television. It's a
security blanket of sorts. It's what I heard when I was a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT
</P>
<P>
   SONNY ROLLINS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: Theodore Walter Rollins, Sept. 7, 1930, in New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Married to: Lucille Rollins, who is also his manager.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Resides: Modestly, he says, in upstate New York for the past
27 years. Maintains a Manhattan apartment that he uses for
rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nickname: ``Newk,'' because of his resemblance to Brooklyn
Dodgers pitcher Don Newcombe, a star in the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What he'll be the last person in the United States to buy: A
personal computer. ``I'm one of those people they call a Luddite.
I'm completely computer ignorant and proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A favorite ballad: Bunny Berigan's version of ``I Can't Get
Started.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Recommended albums: Here are four to start with:
</P>
<P>
   ``Way Out West'' (1957; Contemporary/OJC) _ An engaging
introduction, as Rollins tackles some really corny repertoire
(``I'm an Old Cowhand'') and marvelously transforms it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saxophone Colossus'' (1956; Prestige/OJC) _ The album that
made Rollins' rep _ and introduced the abiding ``St. Thomas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Sonny Rollins RCA Victor Recordings'' (1998
reissue of tracks recorded 1961-64; RCA) _ Includes the 1961
``comeback'' ``The Bridge,'' the saxophonist's wide-open session
with trumpeter Don Cherry and drummer Billy Higgins (from Ornette
Coleman's quartet) and a meeting with tenor idol Coleman Hawkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``+ 3'' (1996; Milestone) _ Worthwhile recent Rollins; features
old-time bandmate Tommy Flanagan and current group member Stephen
Scott on pianos.
</P>
<P>
   CONCERT
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Rollins
</P>
<P>
   8:15 p.m. Saturday. Sold out. Spivey Hall, Clayton College &AMP;
State University, 5900 N. Lee St., Morrow. 770-961-3683.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
