r e BC-POPMUSIC-ASSESS20-COX     08-19 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-ASSESS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Alanis Morissette, Tori Amos double up on tour, packing powerful
message
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alanis Morissette and Tori Amos pose little threat to the sales
dominance of sexpots such as Britney Spears and Ricky Martin. The
music dominating the charts these days doesn't approach the
challenging social and psychosexual realms that Amos and Morissette
frequent.
</P>
<P>
   Morissette, crown princess of angst, and Amos, free-spirited
musical adventurer, have joined forces against the teeny-bopper
tide. The pair's ``5 1/2 Weeks Tour'' rolls into Lakewood
Amphitheatre on Saturday. The joint endeavor is part of a trend
that has seen artists that may not be able to sell out a large
venue alone mustering their combined drawing power.
</P>
<P>
   Amos, in a recent online chat, explained the origin of the tour.
``This was truly Alanis' idea, the concept of us doing a double
show together,'' she said. ``She let me get a little frisky by
letting me call it `5 1/2 Weeks.' I made tea for her a few years
ago when she popped back after a show ... and we got on really
well. So when she put this idea out there, it was quite good
timing.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing seems especially auspicious for Morissette, whose
latest release has had lackluster sales. ``Supposed Former
Infatuation Junkie,'' Morissette's follow-up to her
16-million-plus-selling 1995 breakthrough, ``Jagged Little Pill,''
sold only a fraction of the numbers of its predecessor, while Amos
consistently sells between 500,000 and 1 million copies. Amos' fan
base, built throughout the '90s, is loyal. But Morissette's
meteoric rise didn't allow time to develop a fan base. Many of the
fans that bought ``Jagged Little Pill'' have moved on without her.
With this tour, it seems that Morissette is trying to make a new
start, snagging some of Amos' fiercely loyal fans along the way.
</P>
<P>
   When Morissette bounded to the upper reaches of the singles
charts with the stinging ``You Oughta Know'' in 1995, things were
looking rosy for women in rock. The cookie crumbles quickly in the
world of pop music, though.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent New York Times article, critic Ann Powers summed
things up nicely, writing that the ``moment when women confronted
male rockers on their own terms, displaying a sexual forcefulness
and self-respect that threw the genre's historic chauvinism into
question, has faded. In its place is the culture's new custom of
either placing female artists and fans within a female ghetto, or
ignoring them.''
</P>
<P>
   Have women made strides in pop music? Sure. A glance at the
charts makes that clear; you'll find lots of women there. But let's
take a closer look: Britney Spears, Shania Twain, Christina
Aguilera, Jennifer Lopez _ these women are selling sex and
disposable pop. Still, as Powers writes, even ``the Lolita-like
Britney Spears sends a message mixed enough to be considered
empowering by some of her teenage admirers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Amos, Morissette and their ilk are sexless. Instead,
they use their insight into the female psyche to explore sexuality
in a more serious vein. Amos' thumping ``Raspberry Swirl'' or her
harrowing first-person tale of rape in ``Me and a Gun'' and
Morissette's bile-filled kiss-off in ``You Oughta Know'' were a bit
more thought provoking than Spears' ``Baby One More Time.''
</P>
<P>
   The successful women-of-rock tour Lilith Fair is touted for
raising the profile of female musicians, a task it accomplished.
But, who, exactly, benefited most? It was the sweet, nonthreatening
Jewel, the gently spiritual tour founder Sarah McLachlan and the
ham-handed and thankfully forgotten Meredith Brooks, to name a few.
There were cutting-edge performers on the tour and stalwarts like
Chrissie Hynde. Hynde didn't need Lilith Fair; it needed her.
</P>
<P>
   The chart-topping women of R&AMP;B are setting their own agenda. In
their heels and high splits, R&AMP;B quartet Destiny's Child may look
like they're out to catch any man's attention.
</P>
<P>
   But it's another ``m'' they're after: money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to just beat brothers down or anything,''
says Rozonda ``Chilli'' Thomas, whose Atlanta pop group TLC had a
hit with its own hard line on broke men, ``No Scrubs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because a scrub can be a guy or girl who's not trying to do
anything for himself,'' the singer continues. ``It just so happens
that we are women, so we're going to talk about men, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Morissette and Amos are going to talk about men, too, but we
just have to dig a little deeper and listen a little harder to hear
it.
</P>
<P>
   IN CONCERT
</P>
<P>
   Alanis
</P>
<P>
   Morissette, Tori Amos
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. Saturday. $28.50-$51. Lakewood
</P>
<P>
   Amphitheatre, 2002 Lakewood Way S.W., Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Sonia Murray contributed to this article.
</P>
