   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   COCAINE _ As Gov. George W. Bush continues his tour of smaller
cities to raise money for his presidential bid, the cocaine
question continues to dog him. In Roanoke, Va., on Thursday, the
question arose again, and Bush's campaign said he would be saying
more than he had before. The substance of this more detailed
response? That he had done some things 20 years ago that were
irresponsible. A look at Bush's strategy on the question and
whether it's hurting him. At the least, the question is interfering
with his message on other issues. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman). 20-25
</P>
<P>
   w/BUSH-DRUGS _ COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush is in
Columbus as the latest report of ancient drug use swirls around
him. The Dallas Morning News wrote a story this week about Bush's
FBI background report that said he hadn't used drugs in seven
years, which is as far back, apparently, as the FBI goes. Here he
visits a training center, has a press conf and gets money from Lee
Wexler. (Hershey, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   SPEECHWRITER _ WASHINGTON _ Terry Edmonds, the first
African-American to serve as chief presidential speechwriter, talks
about his journey from the Cherry Hills housing projects in
Baltimore to putting words in Bill Clinton's mouth. (Dart, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   BUSHCLINTON _ Some are fed up with the president's womanizing.
Others had problems with the GOP's embrace of social conservatives
in 1996 and perceive more moderate views from Texas Gov. George W.
Bush. Whatever their reasons, a few hundred large campaign
contributors who supported the Clinton-Gore ticket in 1996 have
opened their checkbooks this year for Bush. (Sherman/Foskett,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NORWOOD _ Charlie Norwood came to Congress with one thing on his
mind: overhaul managed care. That single-minded vision has taken
the former dentist to a politically precarious spot. Norwood has
upset the Republican leadership by negotiating with senior
Democrats to get a bill to the floor despite Speaker Dennis Hastert
(R-Ill.) making it clear there would be no bill. w/Q&AMP;A. (Carr, Cox
News Service). 35.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   STEM - WASHINGTON - Research on human stem cells is potentially
as important to human health as the development of antibiotics and
vaccines and should continue with federal support, according to a
committee of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science. However, because of ``public anxiety,'' federal money
should not be used to actually derive the cells from human fetuses
or embryos, the committee said. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHOOLS _ WASHINGTON - Schools and colleges will set new
enrollment records this fall, said President Clinton, as he
released the administration's ``Baby Boom Echo'' report Thursday.
He predicted that after he vetoes a GOP tax-cut bill next month, he
and Republicans will reach a compromise with higher education
spending and lower tax cuts than the GOP wants. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With stats for a textbox at bottom of story.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSQUATTERS _ WASHINGTON _ Internet pioneers once made a tidy
profit by registering domain names with brand identification, only
to ``flip'' them back to Fortune 500 companies. Congress is now
bent on passing a law to ban such ``cybersquatting.'' The practice
struck home with pols when the most natural names presidential
candidate web states of such pols as Hatch, Gore, and Alexander got
taken over this year. Sometimes, the idea is not to resell the name
but to mock the candidate by attracting innocent eyeballs to
negative sites. (Glass, Cox News Service). 25.
</P>
