<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-LLAMA22-COX     08-19 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LLAMA22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My new friend is a llama
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 22
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISGAH NATIONAL FOREST, N.C. _ My llama is famished.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it seems. The 13-year-old, 400-pound pack animal that
trails me through this deliriously lush stretch of mountain
wilderness is snarfing every chlorophyll-producing thing in sight _
pine needles, hemlock leaves, clumps of pungent sassafras, you name
it. B.B. is his name, short for Baby Boy, but it also could stand
for Big Belly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They like anything that's green,'' says guide Bob McIntyre.
``Just don't let him get near the mountain laurel or the
rhododendron. They'll make him real sick.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre patiently points out the forbidden flora, though I have
to strain to hear him over the breathy chewing noises B.B. makes as
he chows down about 3 inches from my right ear.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but that's part of the charm of English Mountain Llama
Treks, the unusual guided excursions begun four years ago by
McIntyre, 50, and his wife Cathy, 46. Drawing from a stable of 30
llamas, the McIntyres add an element of animal magnetism to day
hikes through the Pisgah National Forest and overnight hikes
through the nearby Nantahala National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Each hiker on our 4.5-mile trek _ myself, Helen and Norman Moore
of Columbia, S.C., and Andy and Nicole Boatright of Baxley _ is
paired with a woolly companion, who follows us on a lead rope over
fallen logs, up steep embankments and down weedy trails, eating and
defecating all the way.
</P>
<P>
   The llamas carry the gear _ lunch, along with a portable table
and chairs, is provided on the day hikes; tents, sleeping bags and
food rations on the overnight hikes.
</P>
<P>
   An early-morning shower douses the path into the Pisgah, and our
hiking boots go thwock-thwock in the mud as we head up to a
250-acre natural bald called Max Patch. (The llamas, with their
padded, two-toed feet, glide gracefully through the slosh.)
</P>
<P>
   To get there, we have to traverse a portion of the Appalachian
Trail _ and separate temporarily from the llamas, because pack
animals and horses aren't allowed on the trail. Cathy takes B.B.
and company to meet us on the lee side of the bald. At the summit,
we smile as we watch her slowly progress down an alternate trail
far below, scolding and cajoling her frisky charges as she goes.
</P>
<P>
   The sun breaks briefly over the bald, and as we survey the
panorama of gorgeous rolling meadows, a few of us break into the
Julie Andrews twirl from ``The Sound of Music.'' Feeling heady and
not at all embarrassed by our movie-musical outburst, we descend to
reclaim our animal sidekicks.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit that I'm surprised by how much fun I'm having.
Before I went on a llama trek, I'd failed to see the full value of
this burgeoning mini-industry. (There's a smattering of trekking
outfits across the country, mostly out West.) After all, you don't
get to ride the llamas _ they can carry up to a third of their body
weight, but their spines aren't built to handle the direct pressure
of a human posterior _ and I can carry my own lunch without too
much exertion. Why not just hike the trail without the four-legged
tagalong?
</P>
<P>
   But as B.B. and I march on _ me huffing and puffing on my first
nature walk in ages, him acting like he's at the world's biggest
salad bar _ I find myself growing more fond of this odd creature.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever seen a llama's mug up close? They wear this
endearingly enigmatic smirk that is equal parts impish and aloof,
as if they were secretly amused by the pink-skinned creatures
before them. They're extremely head-shy _ try scratching them
behind the ears and they'll bolt. They're competitive, jockeying
constantly for position as leader of the pack. (That spitting you
hear so much about? It's basically a llama-to-llama power thing.)
Even their poop is interesting _ it looks like polished ebony
aquarium stones.
</P>
<P>
   Each llama on our trek has a distinct personality quirk. B.B.
chomps endlessly. E.T. hams it up for the snapping cameras. Thor
whines. Topcat is ... extra woolly.
</P>
<P>
   No children accompany us _ the Boatrights left their five kids
at home so they could enjoy some rare time alone _ but Bruce
Freeman of Hillsborough, N.C., can vouch for the trek's kid appeal.
The 39-year-old Procter &AMP; Gamble account executive and his family
signed up for a day trip with the McIntyres last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman says his daughter Kane, 7, usually starts complaining
about 100 yards into any hike. ``But she took to the llamas
immediately. It was so funny, she's not even as tall as a llama's
leg, but at one point she was leading three of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kane's parents were so happy with their complaint-free day that
they came back for an overnight hike this July. ``This will be a
yearly tradition for us,'' Freeman says. ``From now on, no llama,
no hike.''
</P>
<P>
   And kids will get a thrill out of the other wildlife here, too.
The Pisgah offers up gaggles of grouse _ which scare the bejesus
out of the llamas when they beat a winged retreat from the high
grass _ as well as turtles, wild turkeys, deer, snakes and, on rare
occasions, the elusive black bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen four bears up here in four years,'' Bob McIntyre
says as he surveys the dense underbrush. But toward the end of our
hike, we see a rough-hewn divot in a dirt embankment, where he
suspects a bear recently dug for grubs.
</P>
<P>
   As if the natural attractions weren't enough, the McIntyres toss
in some homespun extras: Our picnic lunch of cold-cut sandwiches,
Sun Chips and pasta salad is capped by Cathy's scrumptious homemade
Hershey Bar pie. (During warm weather, you may get brownies and ice
cream.) Along the trail, Cathy snaps photos of our group, which
will be mailed to each member later. And at the end of the hike,
everybody gets a souvenir mug.
</P>
<P>
   The McIntyres began raising llamas in 1993, after moving to
Newport, Tenn., from Sarasota, Fla. ``We had read a few articles
about packing (the insider's term for hiking with pack animals),
which piqued our interest,'' explains Bob, a former postal worker.
``Then we visited a few llama farms and saw some of the babies. It
was all over after that.''
</P>
<P>
   They started buying up llamas _ $500 to $800 for the males,
$1,200 and up for the females _ and opened the trekking business in
1995. (It's named after their English Mountain home in Tennessee.)
They guided about 50 hikes last year, the lion's share during the
high season of April through November. And business is picking up _
this year, they estimate they'll guide 75 trips, with lots of
repeat hikers.
</P>
<P>
   The McIntyres think that many people return because they, too,
fall for the beasts. Count Helen Moore among them. This is the
second llama trek for the 47-year-old physician's assistant _ last
year, she hiked the Nantahala National Forest with a different
North Carolina company. ``I love animals, and llamas are so
interesting,'' she explains as she cozies up to Topcat. ``Mine
hummed the last time I went. It's just really neat to hike with a
buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even one who treks with his mouth full.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  English Mountain Llama Treks. 1-800-653-9984 or
www.hikinginthesmokies.com. A day trek (about five hours) is $60,
an overnight trek is $200, and a two-night trek is $300.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there. The Pisgah National Forest is roughly halfway
between Asheville, N.C., and Knoxville, about an hour's drive from
each. Take I-75 north to I-40, go east to Exit 7, the Harmon Den
exit. If you are going on the llama trek, arrangements must be made
to meet the McIntyres at the exit.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accommodations. Cathy McIntyre recommends the following
lodgings near Newport, Tenn., about 25 miles east of the Pisgah:
Christopher Place, a bed-and-breakfast in Newport, 423-623-6555;
Four Seasons Vacation Rentals (with cabins suitable for families),
Newport, 423-625-9390; Fox Den Campground (for RV camping), Cosby,
Tenn.,
</P>
<P>
   1-888-369-3361. In North Carolina, accommodations can be found
in Waynesville and Maggie Valley, about 15 miles from the Pisgah.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
