<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3235 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-19 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAST IN THE `BULL' EVOKES EMPATHY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We just called it the Bull.
</P>
<P>
   That was short for Istanbul, the venerable, magnificent city
that sits at the choke point connecting the Mediterranean Sea and
the Black Sea, straddling Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   I once called it ``San Francisco with minarets'' because of its
hills and the way it commands the view of its own bay (the 20-mile
channel known as the Bosphorus and the Sea of Marmara).
</P>
<P>
   We _ meaning some members of my small detachment of airmen
stationed near the town of Yalova _ headed for the ferry for the
two-hour cruise over the Sea of Marmara for two days of fun and
adventure the instant that our three-day shifts were completed.
</P>
<P>
   I could tell you what we were doing there, but then, like they
say in the spy movies, I might have to shoot you.
</P>
<P>
   Every trip to the Bull during my two years was a stimulating
experience. Sometimes too stimulating _ in fact, downright
dangerous. There was always something different to do and learn, if
one were willing to expand his horizons.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry ride itself was often breathtaking, with dolphins
racing the boat, gulls hovering and plummeting down on their
scavenging runs, and the people on deck _ the din of the heated
conversation, backgammon games, waiters scurrying and boys hawking
snacks and periodicals.
</P>
<P>
   Sliding in toward the city, one was overwhelmed by the sight of
the ancient fortifications, and the rolling vaults of the mosques
with their sleek minarets _ rocket-like structures seemingly poised
for launch into space.
</P>
<P>
   Memories of the sights, sounds, smells and feel of the city in
which I crossed the threshold from adolescence to adulthood and
acquired a veneer of cosmopolitan sophistication flooded me when I
read the news of the devastating earthquake that shook western
Turkey this week.
</P>
<P>
   I had felt the earth move a few times when I was there, but not
seriously. Even then it was an extremely disorienting feeling to
totally lose your moorings during what seemed to be a suspension of
the law of gravity.
</P>
<P>
   I'm ashamed to admit it, but my first thoughts about the
earthquake were concerns about the Blue Mosque, the Suleymaniye
Mosque and Ayasofia, the sixth-century Byzantine cathedral that was
converted into a mosque by the Ottomans in the 15th century and
later into a museum.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after I knew that the earthquake spared all of
Istanbul's most impressive architecture and that the city itself
did not bear the brunt of the earthquake's impact that my concern
shifted to the people who have suffered this great calamity.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered some of my Turkish friends from the old days and
wondered if they or their children or relatives had been among the
victims. And I prayed a Christian prayer for them all, although
most of them were Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   That's another thing that happened to me in Istanbul, which may
seem blasphemous or heretical to some. My Christian faith was
strengthened through exposure to Islamic influences.
</P>
<P>
   There was something about the hundreds of muezzins summoning the
faithful to their prayers in the misty early mornings that called
me to prayer as well. I did not, of course, pray in the same way.
But I knew in the depths of my being that we were importuning the
same God.
</P>
<P>
   That realization has led me over the years to be utterly baffled
by the amount of blood that has been and is still being shed over
the different ways people chose to express their devotion to the
same supreme being. The Balkans wars in that sense seem utterly
senseless.
</P>
<P>
   So too does the continuing tension between the Greeks and the
Turks and untenable political situation on Cyprus that is the
product of that historical antagonism.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, it is encouraging to note that Greece was among
the first nations to respond to Turkey's need for massive emergency
assistance. Greece already has sent three C-130 transport planes
with medicines and two 11-doctor emergency medical teams.
</P>
<P>
   Natural disasters of the scale that has hit Turkey often have
the effect of making historic antagonisms irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   For most Americans, Turkey is just another faraway place whose
name evokes exotic imagery. The deaths of thousands of Turks in an
earthquake there amount in their minds to no more than statistics
for a headline.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a different thing for one who has spent a lot of time
in the Bull, tasting its food, wandering its narrow side streets
and drinking its coffee, its tea and the wine called Binbirgeje,
``A Thousand and One Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
