leveled buildings and not enough rescue teams in the world to
handle them all. By Jonathan Gorvett. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ Kremlin reverses assurances that it
will quell the Islamic rebels in Dagestan within a week. Now they
say it'll be a long, drawn-out struggle. By David Filipov. 1000
words.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DETAINEE (Hong Kong) _ Daja Meston is mild-mannered,
private, soft-spoken and gentle, friends say, hardly the radical
intent on fomenting unrest in China. But Chinese authorities
apparently disagree. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-BUNNY (Montreal) _ Should Bugs Bunny be banned for
insinuating that women are ``witches''? An Ontario woman who saw
Warner Brothers' ``Bewitched Bunny'' thought so, but happily for
the wascally wabbit, Canadian censors didn't agree. By Colin
Nickerson. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DRUGS (Washington) _ It has become a staple of the campaign
trail: Reporters ask George W. Bush if he ever used cocaine; he
testily replies that he'll never answer the question. But he's
gradually giving ground, now indicating he hasn't used drugs for at
least 15 years. By Mary Leonard. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GREEK-ARCHBISHOP (Undated) _ In an unprecedented move,
Archbishop Spyridon, the leader of the 1.5 million-member Greek
Orthodox Archdiocese of America, resigns after more than two years
of criticicism that his authoritarian ways were out of step with
today's church. By Tatsha Robertson. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VACATION (Edgartown, Mass.) _ The Clintons begin their
fifth vacation on Martha's Vineyard on the president's 53d
birthday. By Bob Hohler. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CALTEC-NO1 (Undated) _ The US News rankings are out, and this
year, geeky California Institute of Technology is the nation's No.
1 school. Harvard, usually No. 1, sniffs that rankings don't mean
much, anyway. By Kate Zernike. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAA-NOISE (Undated) _ FAA says the nation's airplane fleet has
never been quieter. In the past year, 479 noisy so-called stage 2
aircraft were removed from service and 745 quieter Stage 3 aircraft
entered service. By Matthew Brelis. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
