<HEADER>
A3240 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES18-COX     08-19 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coonts takes international intrigue to `Cuba'
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Cold War ended and the Berlin Wall came tumbling down,
a lot of spy novelists and techno-thriller writers began scrambling
for new villains. They weren't hard to find, says Stephen Coonts,
author of seven New York Times best sellers, including ``The Flight
of the Intruder'' and ``Under Siege.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clarksville, Md., writer insists that the collapse of
communism did not lower the level of tension in the world; rather,
it raised it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communism collapsed because it couldn't take care of the
people who lived in its shadow. Those people are still hungry,
naked and cold. We plump, comfortable, warm people should
contemplate that hard fact.''
</P>
<P>
   In Coonts' latest thriller, ``Cuba'' (St. Martin's, $24.95), the
bad guys are Cuban officials jockeying for power as Fidel Castro is
dying. Meanwhile, Coonts' recurring character, Rear Admiral Jake
Grafton, is dispatched to Guantanamo Bay to keep secretly stored
chemical weapons from falling into the hands of the Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain amount of military jargon in the book, but
Coonts doesn't consider himself a techno-thriller writer like Tom
Clancy. ``I don't like those types of books,'' says Coonts, a
former naval aviator who flew combat missions in Vietnam. ``I
prefer more character development.''
</P>
<P>
   Coonts relied on books and Internet sites for most of his
research on Cuba. He wanted to visit the island, but his wife
opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me I absolutely could not go,'' Coonts says. ``She
said some of the people there might have read `Under Siege,' where
I had Fidel executed by a firing squad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the news: Georgia writer Terry Kay (``The Kidnapping of
Aaron Greene'') has signed a deal with William Morrow for a novel
due in January and a nonfiction book at a later date. The novel,
``The Package,'' will deal with a man who commits suicide after
being forced into early retirement, and what happens to the people
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep hearing the same story from people who are downsized,''
Kay said. ``They are so shocked they don't know what to do. When
they calm down, they all want some measure of revenge. The
companies haven't taken just their jobs away _ that's part of it _
they've taken away their dignity. Most people don't act on that,
and sooner or later they'll get a job doing something, but they
still hold that bitterness.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wolfe galore: Not only will Tom Wolfe's Atlanta novel, ``A Man
in Full,'' be released in paperback in October, but all of his
previous works will be published in new paperback editions as well.
Available soon are ``The Kandy-Kolored Tangerine Flake Streamline
Baby''; ``The Electric Kool-Aid Acid Test''; ``The Pump House
Gang''; ``Radical Chic &AMP; Mau-Mauing the Flak Catchers''; ``The
Painted Word''; ``Mauve Gloves &AMP; Madmen, Clutter &AMP; Vine''; ``In Our
Time''; and ``From Bauhaus to Our House.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Small towns, big deals: Dolly Parton has bought the film
option to Stella Suberman's ``The Jew Store.'' Published by
Algonquin Books, the memoir tells the story of a Jewish store owner
and his family in a small Tennessee town in the 1920s. ... Durham,
N.C., writer and NPR's ``All Things Considered'' contributor Haven
Kimmel has sold her memoir of growing up in Mooreland, Ind., to
Doubleday for six figures. Senior editor Amy Schiebe told
Publishers Weekly she was impressed by Kimmel's writing style and
the way ``she captures that caught-in-amber quality of little
towns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Hughes hoax: More than 27 years ago, Clifford Irving
convinced the publishing world that he had written ``The
Autobiography of Howard Hughes.'' This was quite a coup, since the
reclusive billionaire was never seen outside of his hotel suite and
never gave interviews. Just before the book was published, however,
Hughes conducted a conference call to several journalists and
announced that he had never met Irving and the book was a fake.
Irving went to jail for 17 months and most of the manuscripts were
destroyed. Now living in Santa Fe, N.M., Irving has revived the
bogus autobiography and is marketing it through the Internet at
www.terrificbooks
</P>
<P>
   .com. Irving still claims this is the autobiography Hughes would
have written _ ``if he dared'' _ but even ignoring the fact that
the anecdotes and interviews are fake, the story is more
entertaining than many novels.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1827EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-STEM-0820-COX     08-19 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEM-0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENTIFIC SOCIETY SAYS NO CHANGES NEEDED IN STEM CELL RESEARCH
RULES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (l) Lifestyle
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The federal government should fund research on
human embryonic stem cells but, because of ``public anxiety''
surrounding the subject, should avoid financing the actual
collection of the cells, a committee of scientists, lawyers and
ethicists said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Human stem cell research, which some biologists say could lead
to cures for some of humanity's most fearsome diseases, is
nonetheless controversial because it begins with cells
``harvested'' from aborted fetuses or discarded human embryos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The science leading to the understanding of human stem cell
biology is about to enter a phase of research and development that
could lead to unprecedented cures'' for diseases like cancer,
diabetes, heart disease and diseases of the nervous system, the
committee said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
   Embryonic stem cells are the primitive cells that have not yet
become specialized. They are the precursors of many different kinds
of tissue, such as skin, muscle, nerve, bone.
</P>
<P>
   The report, released by the American Association for the
Advancement of Science (AAAS) and the Institute for Civil Society,
was virtually identical to previous recommendations that federal
funds be used for stem cells research _ but not to finance the
collection of the cells on which the research is done.
</P>
<P>
   The two organizations will sponsor a public meeting to discuss
the implications of stem cell research next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By manipulating the cells, scientists are learning how to clone
``designer'' cells and tissues, an ability that many experts
believe will lead to the discovery of entirely new classes of drugs
and other cures.
</P>
<P>
   However, since all stem cells are grown from cells taken from
electively-aborted fetuses or embryos discarded by reproduction
clinics, critics fear the emerging science will lead to cloning,
abuse of human research subjects, commerce in human life and a host
of other problems.
</P>
<P>
   A National Bioethics Advisory Commission created by President
Clinton has earlier called for federal funding of research using
human stem cells, so long as no government money is used in the
actual collection of the cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that this approach will allow publicly-funded
researchers to move more quickly toward discoveries that will lead
to alleviating the suffering caused by human disease,'' stated the
report issued Thursday. ``We understand that there are many
individuals who believe that any use of human embryos other than
for achieving a pregnancy (is) unethical, believing that the human
embryo is a full human being from the earliest moments of the
conception process.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee said research could go ahead while such issues are
being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
