   IN THE PITS _ Odds and ends column from the world of NASCAR
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   BUSCH GRAND NATIONAL STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   BOXING
</P>
<P>
   BOX-TONY-AYALA _ The opportunity to see if Tony Ayala had indeed
become a changed man during 16 years in prison came even before the
first fight in his improbable comeback. At a pre-fight interview
his opponent, Manuel Esparza, took the mike. Esparza, 21, was only
4 years old when Ayala fought his last fight in San Antonio, one in
which he unleashed all the savage fury he had in and outside of the
ring and when he continued to batter a helpless Robbie Epps even
after the referee had declared Ayala a winner in a first-round
technical knockout. Esparza was still shy of his third birthday
when Ayala pounded Jose Baltazar into submission in two rounds and
then spit on him to avenge a pre-fight insult to a boxer known as
Torito. Like a wine-sodden tourist in Pamplona Esparza couldn't
resist running in front of a bull. ``I just want to ask you one
question,'' he said, turning to Ayala. ``Do you like mayonnaise or
mustard, because I'm going to be feeding you some fist sandwiches
all night, brother. Hopefully a lot of people will come out to see
the fight to see what happens to the ex-champ and the new champ.''
Ayala and Esparza fight Friday night in San Antonio. (Maher, Austin
Anmerican-Statesman).
</P>
