A3254 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-MICKEY-SPI &LR;      08-19 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MICKEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGH GRANT COMES OFF SURPRISINGLY WELL IN `MICKEY BLUE EYES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the summer of Hugh Grant. He entered it with a rather
shaky career as a B-level star bent on self-parody, and he's
leaving it as Hollywood's premier light-comedian leading man _ the
David Niven (Grant's hero) of his time.
</P>
<P>
   First there was the triumph of ``Notting Hill,'' which he stole
right out from under Julia Roberts. Now he's followed it up with
``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' a Mafia comedy that is not as good a movie
but is every bit as strong a personal star vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   He plays a British manager of a posh New York auction house who
has found the girl of his dreams in Gina (Jeanne Tripplehorn), a
beautiful and self-sacrificing teacher in a public high school who
is reluctant to introduce him to her family.
</P>
<P>
   It quickly turns out that she's the daughter of a top-level
gangster (James Caan) in one of New York's biggest crime families.
And when he finds out about it, she tries to break the engagement
because she knows _ the Mafia being the Mafia _ that he will
inevitably be corrupted by the connection.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, of course, exactly what happens. The lovers go ahead
with their marriage plans and the mild-mannered Englishman is
sucked into and exploited by the family, targeted by the FBI,
forced into gun fights with competing gangsters, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you're right. It's the same formula as ``Analyze This.''
And, like that movie, ``Mickey'' becomes progressively less
sophisticated and more slapsticky (after a terrific first act)
until it finally threatens to self-destruct _ here with Grant's
mugging through several scenes as a pathetic imitation-gangster.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the most part, he comes off amazingly well. He's
enormously endearing (especially when he's under the tightest
control), and the audience seems to just love him. He's also
surprisingly good in some of the more physical comedy, displaying
for the first time a surprising Harold Lloyd quality.
</P>
<P>
   In at least one way, ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' is also vastly
superior to ``Analyze This'' _ it really never romanticizes,
glamorizes or trivializes the Mafia. Thanks largely to an
absolutely icy performance by Burt Young as the Godfather, the
hero's predicament seems genuinely frightening. The film has a
slight bite.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Blues Eyes. Directed by Kelly Makin. Written by Adam
Scheinman and Robert Kuhn. Cast: Hugh Grant, James Caan, Jeanne
Tripplehorn, Burt Young, James Fox. Castle Rock. 110 minutes. Rated
PG-13 for gangster violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3255 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-TINGLE-SPI &LR;      08-19 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TINGLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`KILLING MRS. TINGLE' HAS A BRAVURA PERFORMANCE BY HELEN MIRREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the fact it deals with a trio of oppressed students who
resort to violence against an unfair teacher, the release of the
high-school black comedy, ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle,'' in
post-Columbine 1999 makes for some lousy timing.
</P>
<P>
   Up until a few months ago, it was called ``Killing Mrs.
Tingle,'' and even the week before its release, the producers were
still dickering with the ending, and touching up the ad campaign to
make the actors look more wholesome. Clearly, the studio is scared
to death of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing to fear. It's forgettable but somehow totally
innocuous, with a few mild chuckles, a bravura performance from
Helen Mirren, and able support from a trio of young stars who are
more attractive and engaging than the teen movie norm.
</P>
<P>
   The title character (Mirren) is a domineering, small-town high
school teacher who holds some unknown resentment against young
people everywhere, and likes nothing more than publicly humiliating
her students _ stripping them of every vestige of their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   And when the sweet young heroine, Leigh Ann (Katie Holmes) _ who
is dirt poor and desperate for a college scholarship _ invests six
months making a senior project so spectacular it could win the
Nobel Prize, Mrs. Tingle positively delights in trashing it with a
C grade.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but this teacher-from-hell conspires to have
Leigh Ann kicked out of school for cheating on a final exam, even
though she knows full well the kid is perfectly innocent. This is
not just a mean teacher, but a pathological nut case.
</P>
<P>
   So, through a series of fumbling incidents, Leigh Ann and two
friends (Marisa Coughlin and Barry Watson) take Mrs. Tingle
prisoner, tie her to her bed, take pornographic pictures of her,
threaten her with blackmail and otherwise try to to talk her into a
deal _ which, of course, she rejects.
</P>
<P>
   That's pretty much the movie. As written and directed by Kevin
Williamson (the writer of ``Scream'' and ``I Know What You Did Last
Summer''), it's played mostly for laughs _ with a heavy infusion of
teenage romance _ and it's never quite as mean-spirited as my
synopsis makes it sound.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the best thing on the screen is Mirren. She's
an authentic star, and one who has become ever more charismatic and
appealing as she's aged in the movies of the past 25 years. This is
the meatiest role she's had in ages, and she makes the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   But she's almost too much actress for the part. As played here,
Mrs. Tingle is so confident, so cunningly resourceful and so
physically attractive that its impossible to believe her as a
small-minded shrew in a dead-end job. This woman should be running
General Motors, or, at the very least, a movie studio.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching Mrs. Tingle. Directed and written by Kevin Williamson.
Produced by Cathy Konrad. Cast: Helen Mirren, Katie Holmes, Marisa
Coughlan, Barry Watson. Dimension Films. 93 minutes. Rated PG-13
for sex scenes and some violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3256 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-ILLUMINATA-SPI &LR;      08-19 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ILLUMINATA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN TURTURRO'S `ILLUMINATA' IS AN INCOMPREHENSIBLE MESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Turturro is a reliable and often inspired supporting actor
(``Quiz Show,'' ``The Color of Money''), and he made a credible
debut as a director in 1992 with his autobiographical first film,
``Mac,'' which won the Camera d'Or at Cannes that year.
</P>
<P>
   But with his second directorial effort, `Illuminata,'' he's been
hit by the sophomore curse, big time. The movie is an
incomprehensible mess _ so boring and numbingly unworkable that
it's hard to imagine what he could have been thinking.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a freewheeling ensemble piece, set in the backstage
world of a New York repertory company around the turn of the
century _ but I had to learn this from the press notes, because it
seems to take place in Italy in some time warp (i.e., the company
ingenue has a tattoo on her chest).
</P>
<P>
   Turturro, who co-wrote the script and co-produced, plays Tuccio,
the resident playwright, who is eager for the company to stage his
unfinished play, ``Illuminata,'' but is having resistance from the
theater owners (Beverly D'Angelo and Donal McCann), who consider it
chaptrap (they're right).
</P>
<P>
   There's also Rachel (Katherine Borowitz), the company's lead
actress, for whom Tuccio has written the play; Old Flavio (Ben
Gazarra), the company's chest-pounding senior actor; and Celimene
(Susan Sarandon), the aging star of another company who sees
``Illuminata'' as a potential vehicle for herself.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the mix are the juvenile leads (Rufus Sewell and
Georgina Cates); the flamboyantly swishy and hugely powerful drama
critic Umberto Bevalaqua (Christopher Walken); and Marco (Bill
Irwin), a handsome actor who this corrupt critic wants to seduce.
</P>
<P>
   When an actor collapses during a performance of ``Cavalleria
Rusticana,'' Tuccio contrives to instantly substitute
``Illuminata,'' and the movie chronicles the various clumsy
seductions, farcical backstage scheming and other intrigues that
ensue.
</P>
<P>
   If this synopsis makes the movie sound like it has a clear
focus, then I shamelessly flatter it. Mostly, it just rambles about
aimlessly, with no real storytelling momentum, and scene after
scene that fail to be in any way engaging or even slightly amusing.
</P>
<P>
   The roles are broadly written by Turturro, and hammily acted by
the cast _ even such sure-fire performers as Sarandon and Walken
can't make anything of the script. Turturro himself doesn't have
the stature of a lead, and his overemphasis on his own character
seems narcissistic and self-indulgent.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, his film contains long, long scenes on-stage in which
we're forced to watch actors perform monologues and slices of
``Illuminata'' that have no context or meaning to us, but which
Turturro seems to think are profoundly moving. But then he's read
the play; we haven't.
</P>
<P>
   Illuminata. Directed by John Turturro. Screenplay by Brandon
Cole and John Turturro. Cast: John Turturro, Susan Sarandon,
Christopher Walken, Beverly D'Angelo, Katherine Borowitz. Artisan.
95 minutes. Rated R for sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
