<HEADER>
A3257 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HUGH-GRANT-LADN     08-19 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUGH-GRANT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUGH GRANT: FROM GOOD FELLOW TO GOODFELLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Stories about Hugh Grant typically include
certain inescapable adjectives _ ``floppy-haired,'' ``bumbling''
and the like _ that have come to define the 38-year-old actor's on-
and off-screen persona in a way that irritates him to no end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuttering is another one,'' Grant grumbles. ``Completely
unfair. `Effete,' used, of course, wrongly. `Boyish.' I've also
been referred to several times as pocket-sized, which is quite
weird for someone who is 5-feet-11. I can show you some
pocket-sized stars, but I'm not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what words would Grant use to describe himself?
</P>
<P>
   ``Moody. Dangerous. Brooding. Super sexy. Those will do fine,''
Grant says. ``One other _ slightly cruel. Yes. I rather like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   None of those words, of course, remotely resemble the public's
image of the charming Grant, who's back in theaters this summer
(after a three-year absence) in two romantic comedies. ``Notting
Hill'' you probably know about. ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' comes from
Simian Films, the production company Grant formed with longtime
girlfriend Elizabeth Hurley. Grant plays an art auctioneer caught
up in the New York mob through his fiancee's family.
</P>
<P>
   One magazine called ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' Grant's ``moment of
truth,'' another description the English actor finds laughable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my life's burning ambition was to be a movie star, then it
would be a very big moment,'' Grant says. ``I want the film to do
well, but I like to think there are other aspects to life as well.
I'm always boring on about how I should give up this business and
do something more grown-up. So, if I'm forced into that, it really
wouldn't be the end of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for Grant to retire any time soon. Here, he drolly
explains the subtleties of underworld fashion, how Julia Roberts
could have made Benito Mussolini a star and why hugs from James
Caan should be approached with some caution.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' co-star, James Caan, says that the
trick to the movie was to keep you nervous all day long. His quote:
``I scared him out of his skin some days.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Grant: Lovely man, Jimmy. I believe he took the role just
to torment me for a few months, and he did so with some relish. I
thought it was nice that we gave him a job in the first place, sort
of plucking him from the old people's home as it were.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And he calls you a ``little wimpy guy.'' That's the thanks
you get.
</P>
<P>
   Grant: I think he was in love with me. That's why he can't leave
the subject alone now. His whole thing about me being an English
wimp is his cover-up for the fact that he has a crush on me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you suspect this because ...
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Well, you know, there's a lot of hugging and kissing in
these mob movies, and I got the impression halfway through the
shoot that the hugs were lasting just a little bit longer than they
needed to.
</P>
<P>
   Q: He wouldn't be the first person to fall in love with a
co-star.
</P>
<P>
   Grant: No. Making a movie brings you together. And I'd catch
looks across the set from him, and the thing got worse and worse,
and I'd go back to my apartment in New York and find him curled up
in a little ball outside.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was this hard for Elizabeth?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Well, it was obviously embarrassing for her. And then the
poems came.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If you were going to have an on-set crush develop, I'd
imagine you'd pick Julia Roberts over Jimmy Caan.
</P>
<P>
   Grant: One would think so. But she tormented me as well. I just
realized that all these American actors torment me. When I got in
bed with her for our big love scene, she said, ``Hey, someone
around here has been to the gym and it's not HUGH.'' That was very
depressing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The success of the movie must have cheered you up.
</P>
<P>
   Grant: It was a relief, of course, after having been away for so
long. Everyone from the beginning said ``Notting Hill'' was going
to be huge. But what I hadn't calculated on, and what I now
realize, is that Julia could make a romantic comedy with Mussolini
and the film would make $150 million. And that's rather annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Being cast as Mussolini.
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Yes. Because my part in the movie was actually bigger
than hers, and I naively thought, ``This is my movie with Julia in
it.'' And when the film was being marketed, I suddenly realized,
``No. I'm just Mussolini.'' I'm the little guy walking by her giant
poster.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since ``Mickey Blue Eyes'' came from your production company,
you must have insisted on poster approval.
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Yes. It's nice to have power, to feel like you're one of
the grown-ups on the film set. Although, producing is torture, too,
with literally 700 things to worry about in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And Elizabeth is a details-oriented person?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Not at all. She's very good at being a producer in that
she inspires fear in nearly everyone she meets. There's always the
latent threat of physical violence. But she's much less organized
than I am. And that's hard on me because I'm not accustomed to hard
work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You consulted with actual mobsters to give ``Mickey Blue
Eyes'' a realistic feel. Did they have any problems with the humor
in the script?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Mobsters are very funny people. That's why just about
everybody who plays a mobster in the film is, frankly, a mobster or
closely connected to their world. No one could be funnier. And a
lot of them, particularly the low-grade ones, knew Jimmy Caan. In
fact, he was raised by mobsters, not unlike Mowgli being raised by
wolves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did these wise guys offer any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: You'd have dinner with them and, after a few drinks, one
would say, ``There's a moment in the movie where the guy gets
whacked. It don't happen like that. If I was going to whack you,
I'd come up behind you, boom, you're gone. You wouldn't know what
hit you.'' You say, ``All right then, we'll change that.'' It is
quite a weird piece of dinner conversation, not something you'd
come across very often in Hammersmith.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about fashion tips?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Well, I don't think I could pull off the banana yellow
suits. But I quite want to do the jewelry route. I dropped into
Harry Winston and inquired about some diamond cuff links, but then
Elizabeth found out and said it was a waste of money that would be
better spent on her.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who had better accessories _ the mobsters or Elizabeth?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: I don't know about better, but the men certainly had
more. They used to compare jewelry _ and manicures. There would be
this ongoing debate. Elizabeth took a couple of them to the Estee
Lauder spa at Bloomingdale's and gave them the new Estee Lauder
manicure. After that, she could do no wrong in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And in your eyes?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Well, she does come in quite handy at events like
premieres. That's a talent she has that I don't. She tells me what
face I should make when facing banks of paparazzi. I'm useless in
that regard. I always look like a constipated lesbian for some
reason.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And what ``look'' have you decided works best for you?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: I go through phases. Sometimes I think smiling is the
best answer because then you look happy and successful. But
unfortunately, I also look enormously fat-faced like that, and I
have very bad teeth. So, Elizabeth begged me not to smile, and I
put on a mean and moody look. But then underneath the photo, the
caption always says, ``Gloomy Hugh. What's up?'' So I'm back to
square one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there anything Elizabeth refuses to do with you?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Whenever I'm in Los Angeles, I'll go watch the big
football (soccer) games at the Cat and Fiddle. Being broadcast live
from England, the matches begin here at 5 or 6 in the morning. Once
I dragged Elizabeth along and she never forgave me. So, now I
usually go by myself because it's difficult to convince anyone to
wake up that early.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are the expatriates surprised to see you?
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Well, it's an interesting crowd. I'll be at the bar, it's
6 a.m. and there are people ordering three pints of Snakebite,
which is a half-beer, half-cider mix that most English pubs refuse
to serve because it's so lethal. That's their breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'd hate to hang around for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Grant: Things get a bit rowdy, but only if England is winning.
Complete strangers will be hugging each other, buying the room
pints of Snakebite.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sounds like a place your friend James Caan would like.
</P>
<P>
   Grant: He'd love it. He enjoys a good hug. God knows. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
