<HEADER>
A3262 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS &LR;      08-19 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DAGESTAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR WILL BE LONG, RUSSIA NOW ADMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia Thursday acknowledged that its campaign to
suppress an Islamic rebellion in Dagestan was not working, a stark
reversal of almost daily assurances that it would crush the rebels
within a week.
</P>
<P>
   As federal troops reported their heaviest losses yet in the
13-day conflict, a senior Russian commander said Moscow was
rethinking the tactics it was using to dislodge armed militants who
have declared an independent Islamic state in the rugged Caucasus
region.
</P>
<P>
   It was the clearest sign that the military has begun to accept
what independent observers have been saying all along: that Russia
faces a long, drawn-out struggle against the 2,000 followers of
renegade Chechen commander Shamil Basayev.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of artillery and air strikes and other types of
weapons which are in place is not effective enough,'' said Colonel
General Igor Zubov, the Russian deputy interior minister who
returned from the fighting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters in Moscow that Basayev's men had fortified
positions on the hills around the several villages they control
inside Dagestan's border with separatist Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov spoke after Russian troops were repulsed in an effort to
take one of the villages, Tando, which is strategically located on
the rebels' supply line to Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian army said 17 of its troops were killed and 18
wounded during the failed assault _ losses that had made the
commanders think again. A major offensive planned for this week had
been put off until next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The villages) could be taken by a direct assault but it would
bring big losses,'' Zubov said. ``Therefore . . . I must say we
have decided to make sure our losses come to a minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Zubov said the mountainous terrain in Dagestan gives the rebels
many places to hide from Russian warplanes and gunships during the
day. At night, he said, they emerge to launch deadly raids against
the Russians. Even troops who fought in the 10-year Soviet campaign
in Afghanistan and Russia's 1994-1996 conflict with rebels in
Chechnya say mountain warfare in Dagestan is much harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The veterans say, `We have not seen anything like this,' '' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov's somber assessment contrasted with the almost daily
assurances of senior commanders and recently appointed Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin, who promised that the rebels would be
destroyed by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   As Moscow's optimism waned, Dagestani leaders, who have chided
the federal commanders for moving too slowly, expressed their
irritation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The generals were in an excessively good mood when they made
their declarations about how Dagestani territory would be cleared
of militants in a week,'' observed Mukhu Aliyev, the speaker of the
regional parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov's remarks came as the military released casualty totals
for the first time. The figures of 40 dead and 160 wounded were
shockingly high for the kind of mop-up operation the Kremlin has
been describing. Even observers who remember how badly Russian
leaders underestimated their opponents in their disastrous
1994-1996 campaign in Chechnya expressed surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a real war in the Caucasus,'' commented an
anchorwoman on Russia's NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov said the military had ``achieved its strategic goals'' by
breaking the rebels into small, disjointed groups. But he did not
explain why the Russians were unable to overwhelm them.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested Russia was repeating the mistakes of Chechnya.
The Moscow daily newspaper Kommersant described Thursday's failed
assault as a mirror of so many botched attacks in that conflict,
noting that the Russians believed air strikes had sufficiently
weakened the rebels to permit a ground assault, only to have the
militants emerge from basements and caves to beat back the
government troops.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians say that more than 500 rebels have died in the
fighting, but there has been no independent confirmation. Moscow
also says it has surrounded the rebels, in part by mining the roads
that connect Dagestan and Chechnya. But NTV Thursday reported that
Basayev easily moves between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
   Basayev helped orchestrate the Russian defeat in Chechnya but
now operates outside the control of the breakaway region's
self-proclaimed independent government. He told reporters this week
that he would not leave Dagestan until Russian troops leave.
</P>
<P>
   Basayev wants to unite Dagestan and Chechnya. He uses code names
for his operations based on names of 19th century religious leaders
who led the resistance by Chechen and Dagestani warriors against
Czarist armies.
</P>
<P>
   But Dagestani leaders say that despite their historic ties to
the Chechens, their people have no interest in seceding from Russia
now. Pro-Moscow Dagestani leaders Thursday warned civilians of
possible attacks by the rebels in other parts of the region. That
warning was made after Basayev, speaking to Russian reporters,
threatened to begin a new operation, code-named ``Imam Gamzat
Bek,'' which Russian intelligence believes will involve attacks on
large cities on the plains in northern Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's press ministry responded by warning television stations
to stop broadcasting interviews with rebel leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
