<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAA-NOISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PASSENGER JET FLEET LESS NOISY, FAA SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After spending nearly $100 billion in the last decade, the
nation's major airlines are nearing the goal of having all
airplanes meet quieter federal noise standards by Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to Congress this week, the US Department of
Transportation said that all of the 10 major airlines in the United
States _ those with revenues of $1 billion or more _ met the goal
of having 75 percent of their fleet be comprised of quieter,
so-called Stage 3 aircraft, at the beginning of this year. By Jan.
1, 2000, the fleet must be all Stage 3 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, and the Air Transport
Association, the trade association for major carriers, expects all
the airlines to meet the Jan. 1, 2000 goal of having all Stage 3
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Aviation sources, however, said that as many as 16 smaller
carriers have approached the FAA about obtaining a waiver
permitting them to fly in 2000 with some Stage 2 aircraft, but
officials are not inclined to grant any exemptions. As a result, it
is possible some planes will be grounded to meet the regulation.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this year, the FAA was more charitable,
allowing an airline that was one conversion away from meeting the
75 percent threshhold still fly, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of 1999, Alaska Airlines was the only major airline
to have completely converted its fleet from Stage 2 airplanes to
Stage 3 airplanes. Trans World Airlines brought up the rear, with
25 percent of its fleet still the noiser Stage 2 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Of national airlines, with revenues between $100 million and $1
billion, Midwest Express, which flies into Logan Airport, had 77.8
percent of its fleet Stage 3 aircraft. Of the cargo carriers,
United Parcel Service's entire fleet was quieter airplanes,
Airborne Express was at 83 percent, and Federal Express was at 89.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Stage 2 airplanes are restricted from operating at Logan from
10:30 p.m. and 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Residents near the airport said they can't tell any difference
between the airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone in close proximity is going to suffer from considerable
noise pollution and it doesn't matter whether it is Stage 2 or
Stage 3,'' said Preston Galarneau, a councilman in Cheslea, who
lives on the water near Logan International Airport in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is admirable what they are trying to do, but it does not
have much of an impact. They are pretty low and very loud when they
come by my house.''
</P>
<P>
   Older planes that do not meet the new noise requirements must
either be retired, refitted with new engines, or have something
called a hushkit installed that acts like a muffler to reduce
noise. There is some controversy over airplanes fitted with
hushkits, and the European Community is considering banning them
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   During 1998, 479 noisier Stage 2 aircraft were removed from
service and 745 Stage 3 aircraft entered service. At the start of
the year, there were some 511 Stage 2 aircraft used by major
airlines that were still in service, and US cargo arilines had
another 131 in service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FAA and the entire aviation community are committed to a
cleaner, less noisy airspace system,'' FAA administrator Jane F.
Garvey said Thursday in a prepared statement. ``This report show
that we are living up to that commitment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
