u a BC-MENTAL-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      08-19 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTAL-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS MENTAL HEALTH AGENCY VOWS NOT TO CUT SERVICES _ FOR NOW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The state's mental health agency, which is
facing a $30 million annual budget shortfall, promised Thursday not
to cut any services for the next three months and to restore full
funding to a ``new generation'' drug program.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation
said it had found an additional $9 million to fund programs for the
mentally impaired in the fiscal year beginning Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Of that, $7.2 million will restore all of the $27 million
allotted by the Legislature for a new generation of greatly
improved anti-psychotic drugs during the fiscal year 2000. Another
$1.8 million will prevent a cut in community mental health services
through November.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is undergoing an independent state audit to find out
why and how it miscalculated its budget by $30 million this coming
year and potentially the same amount for the next year. Although it
is too soon to tell whether cuts in services will be avoided
altogether, some officials expressed optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think at the end of the day, unless things change, we
will be dealing with a reduction in services from what the
Legislature intended,'' said Don Gilbert, commissioner of Health
and Human Services, which oversees MHMR along with 12 other social
service agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, who headed the mental health agency before assuming
oversight of all the social service agencies, said he believes the
audit will show the shortfall resulted from overestimating
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the new drugs for treating psychosis induced by
schizophrenia, bipolar disorder or major depressions should cut
costs. Revenues, meanwhile, should rise under a new government
health plan for previously uninsured children with mental health
problems. The board of the mental health agency already has
announced cuts in central administration and information
programming.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we know is these new generation medications have a
profound impact on people with serious mental illness,'' he said.
``Their demand for in-patient psychiatric services is definitely
going to decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Gilbert said, the lower expected cost in the
second year of psychiatric treatment should begin to ``chip away''
at the budget problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's right, I think. There should be significant savings, but
we don't know what that will be,'' said Rep. Garnet Coleman,
D-Houston, who specializes in mental health issues as a member of
the House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to work with the state auditor's staff and
state leadership to address the remaining budget issues and to seek
additional long-term solutions,'' said MHMR Commissioner Karen
Hale.
</P>
<P>
   About $4.4 million of the new funding for drugs and continued
service will be transferred from the umbrella Health and Human
Services Commission, although Gilbert said he didn't know yet from
which programs or agencies the money will be shifted.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the money is savings resulting from the agency
prepaying its leases for next year with money left over in this
year's budget, said Laurie Lentz, spokeswoman at the mental health
agency.
</P>
<P>
   The reprieve for mental health services brought relief for
advocates of the mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that the department has responded to the community's
concerns and the legislators' concerns about the budget cuts and
they reinstated those funds for community services, even if it is
only for three months,'' said Lynn Lasky, public policy director at
the National Association of the Mentally Ill of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   House Appropriations Chairman Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, said it
is important that the agency reassure those who need mental health
services, but said the problems are fundamental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that nobody has a handle on the big picture. If
you don't fix what's wrong with the fiscal accountability, that's
systemic and you're just going to have those problems over again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
