<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3270 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     08-19 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SIDES OF MICROSOFT: AUTHORS LOVE, HATE SOFTWARE GIANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beauty is in the eye of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   That's about the only way to explain the widely divergent views
of Microsoft Corp. that are emerging from the ever-expanding crop
of books being written on what has become the world's most valuable
company.
</P>
<P>
   It's only natural that a company worth $500 billion _ as
Microsoft was for a fleeting period this summer _ would have its
share of admirers and detractors.
</P>
<P>
   In one camp, Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates is portrayed as a
savvy visionary capable of shifting the focus of an established
software company to capitalize on the seemingly sudden rise of the
Internet. In another camp, the world's richest man is derided as
the embodiment of an evil emperor digging for new ways to crush
insurgent rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The truth probably lies somewhere in between. But you probably
wouldn't guess that from a pair of the latest pieces focusing on
the development of the Microsoft empire. For these authors,
recently studying the Microsoft phenomenon, the truth lies at one
end of the spectrum or the other.
</P>
<P>
   If you love Microsoft or have developed a good old-fashioned
distaste for the software giant, the local bookstore is likely to
have a new title that suits your taste.
</P>
<P>
   Be forewarned, though. If you're looking for objective
storytelling that helps explain the lessons that can be learned
from the evolution of the computer industry, you may just have to
keep on looking.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, for the lazy reader at least, the new Microsoft
titles pretty much lay their views on the line from the front
cover. The first is called ``How the Web Was Won. Microsoft From
Windows to the Web: The Inside Story of How Bill Gates and His Band
of Internet Idealists Transformed a Software Empire'' (Broadway
Books, New York, 352 pages, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds to you a little like the title of a book that
would be written by a hometown reporter, you're getting the idea.
It was penned by Paul Andrews of the ``Seattle Times,'' one of the
newspapers that closely tracks the Redmond, Wash.-based Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   It's familiar territory for Andrews, who earlier co-authored a
book with Stephen Manes titled ``Gates: How Microsoft's Mogul
Reinvented an Industry and Made Himself the Richest Man in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that Andrews appeared to have extensive
cooperation from Microsoft executives, who gave him interviews and
access to key e-mail messages chronicling Microsoft's early
internal debates on how to address the rise of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews' book is enlightening in that it provides insight in how
Microsoft wrestled with the emerging threat of the Internet in 1993
and 1994 _ long before most consumers were aware of the World Wide
Web as a communications medium.
</P>
<P>
   But the text provides a narrative that only a techie could love.
The book plumbs the depths of the internal debate over the Internet
at Microsoft while giving a blow-by-blow account of incremental
steps, such as how a piece of networking software known as
``WinSock'' came to be integrated into the Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   From the other end of the Microsoft love-hate spectrum comes a
more readable offering from author Gary Rivlin called ``The Plot to
Get Bill Gates: An Irreverent Investigation of the World's Richest
Man and the People Who Hate Him'' (Random House, 360 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   With chapters that carry titles like ``Bill Gates for Dummies''
and ``Bill Gates is Satan,'' Rivlin's work does not carry the
methodical precision that Andrews brought to his work.
</P>
<P>
   But a reader is likely to make it through more chapters and
maybe learn a little bit more about the broader landscape of the
computer industry in the process.
</P>
<P>
   And those readers who make it through Rivlin's entire book are
rewarded with three pages of Microsoft jokes in a stand-alone
appendix. In a book market flooded with Microsoft-related titles,
those three pages just may represent the most engaging material
available on the software giant today.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Customer Capitalism: Increasing Returns in New Market Spaces''
</P>
<P>
   By Sandra Vandermerwe
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Brealey, $25
</P>
<P>
   For years, management gurus have been telling businesses to pay
attention to their customers. Imperial College professor Sandra
Vandermerwe gives readers a clearer path to what she terms customer
capitalism. Using such examples as Amazon.com, Microsoft and
Monsanto, Vandermerwe shows how to link customers to product
development using the new tools of the information age.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Listening to Conflict: Finding Constructive Solutions to
Workplace Disputes''
</P>
<P>
   By Erik J. Van Slyke
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $22.95
</P>
<P>
   Learning to listen will take practice for many of us, especially
as managers. But listening is simply the best way to resolve
conflict. This book, written by human resource consultant Erik Van
Slyke, focuses on how to listen, as well as building a framework on
how to use the tools you've learned in conflict resolution. It's
helpful for any team leader or manager.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Do IT Smart: Seven Rules for Superior Information Technology
Performance''
</P>
<P>
   By Rolf-Dieter Kempis and Jurgen Ringbeck
</P>
<P>
   Free Press, $35
</P>
<P>
   Does information technology really affect a company's bottom
line? That's the heart of a 15-month research project examining
international companies, conducted by Rolf-Dieter Kempis and Jurgen
Ringbeck, both consultants with McKinsey &AMP; Co. The two have
developed an application for measuring IT effectiveness, which they
offer up in the book. They also include numerous comparative
examples of which companies are doing the best and worst at using
IT.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0234 </DOCNO>
