<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- HOMEVIDEO-NYT (jt) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORE ON THE BOY AND HIS BEAGLE: Once again a boy and his dog and
their nice little movie, ``Shiloh 2: Shiloh Season,'' have
infiltrated the nation's theaters, hung around for too short a time
to be noticed by many people but just long enough to gather an
accolade or two before beating a precipitous but well-planned
retreat to more hospitable territory in video stores.
</P>
<P>
   The first time was in April 1997, when ``Shiloh,'' based on
Phyllis Reynolds Naylor's Newbery Medal-winning book about a beagle
and the boy who rescued him from an abusive master, opened on the
big screen. This year ``Shiloh 2'' entered theaters on July 2,
right when one big film after another was vying for screen time at
the height of the summer crush. In many places it lasted little
more than a week. ``We couldn't hold theaters in New York,'' said
Carl Borack, one of the producers. But then the plan was only to
till the ground for video.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the cassette was released by Warner. In the film, a
seventh-grader named Marty (Zachary Brown) does his level best to
befriend a misanthropic, gun-brandishing alcoholic named Judd
(Scott Wilson), who once owned Shiloh and resents Marty and his
family for taking him in for the dog's own good. Judd gives the
impression that he'd do a lot of damage with his gun if that was
his notion, but the boy and his father (Michael Moriarty) practice
restraint and patience. ``This is a smart, sensitive movie,'' Anita
Gates wrote in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The first film was a smart one, too, and a success in theaters
and on video, but that didn't help the sequel when it was shopped
around Hollywood by Dale Rosenbloom, who directed ``Shiloh'' and
wrote ``Shiloh 2.'' So-called family films, of course, run all the
way from ``Tarzan'' to the most modest productions never intended
for the big screen. Before the ``Shiloh 2'' script was written, the
studios envisioned it as a cable and video property, not a film
suitable for a theater release. ``Too soft, not hip enough, not
edgy,'' Borack said.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was made with independent financing and won some
prizes at festivals. Still it was rejected at the studios. ``They
said it would take $15 million to promote,'' Borack said. Finally,
it was suggested that if Rosenbloom wanted to hold out for the
movie screen, he should go through the back door, so to speak, and
approach studio video divisions, which might sponsor a scaled-down
theater appearance to help announce the cassette. Warner, which had
released ``Shilo'' on tape, accepted.
</P>
<P>
   At Warner the film's story, which is more substantial than those
in many movies of this kind, performances by an accomplished cast
and finished appearance marked it as a rare case. ``We do quite a
few direct-to-video movies, but for only a very few of them do we
try to get a theatrical release,'' said Dan Capone, a Warner vice
president in charge of family entertainment. ``For this movie, it
was important to get it into theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents probably were pleased. ``It's one of those movies they
can watch without saying, `Oh, my God, that was a painful two
hours,''' Borack said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   THE CELEBRATION
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the adventurous standards of Dogma 95, the
Danish filmmakers' collective, the young director Thomas Vinterberg
turns a birthday reunion dinner into a wildly active battle royal
between Helge (Henning Moritzen), a prosperous, self-satisfied
patriarch and his rebellious children, including Christian (Ulrich
Thomsen, left). ``It's quite a job being toastmaster tonight,''
says one guest, and so it is when Dad stands accused of incest and
responsibility for a child's death. Reflecting Dogma 95's
adventurous approach to editing, Vinterberg, Janet Maslin wrote in
The New York Times, ``hurtles the film forward in a manner that
seems seamless but calls for immense skill.''
</P>
<P>
   1999. Polygram. $101.76. 106 minutes. Danish with English
subtitles. No rating. Release date: Aug. 24. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE DREAMLIFE OF ANGELS
</P>
<P>
   Two scrappy young Frenchwomen, Isa (Elodie Bouchez) and Marie
(Natacha Regnier), break out of boring routines to live for the
moment and grab at betterment. Soon the confused Marie gets into a
bad match with a club owner (Gregoire Colin) while the
rough-featured Isa takes on a radiance as her confidant. Later,
though, Marie's sexual desperation drives a wedge between the pair
and they battle over their differences. ``As that bond frays, this
impassioned first feature by Erick Zonca reveals a soulful, moving
vision of our shared responsibility for one another's lives''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 113 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Aug. 24. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GO
</P>
<P>
   Doug Liman's film takes a circular route to nowhere and back in
the company of quick-witted young people who arrive at the starting
point somewhat wiser for their experiences. After a botched drug
deal, Ronna (Sarah Polley) has an altercation with Todd (Timothy
Olyphant) and lands in a police sting operation. Meanwhile, Simon
(Desmond Askew) has gone to Las Vegas, where he and friends
misbehave with lap dancers and get into trouble that follows them
back to Los Angeles. Along the way, Liman ``creates a film that
lives up to the momentum of its title and doesn't really need much
more.''(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 103 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: Aug. 24.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EDTV
</P>
<P>
   When a programming executive (Ellen DeGeneres) has the idea to
follow every move of an ordinary person on television, she may not
have meant someone quite as ordinary as Ed Pekurny (Matthew
McConaughey), the 31-year-old video clerk who is selected for the
project. With cameras recording his every move, Ed does little more
than scratch himself in unsightly places until he gets involved
with his brother's ex-girlfriend (Jenna Elfman). Suddenly the
country is hooked on Ed in Ron Howard's film, which ``brings the
effects of such cultural topsy-turviness right home'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Universal. $107.37. 122 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time, appeared on television or been on
videocassette in earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE LIFE AND TIMES OF ALLEN GINSBERG. Toward the end of Jerry
Aronson's film, shown on PBS in 1997, the poet, who died in 1996,
says, ``I had my chance and I lost it.'' That's a harsh
self-assessment from a man who had such a strong influence on
intellectual thought since publication of his first poem, ``Howl,''
in 1956. Here the life and times move from the Ginsberg's early
poems to his placement among Jack Kerouac and William S. Burroughs
as a prototypical Beat, his homosexuality, the protests against the
Vietnam War, his experiments with LSD and his devotion to Buddhism.
1997. First Run Features. 82 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A MIDSUMMER NIGHT'S DREAM. This isn't Michael Hoffman's recent
film starring Michelle Pfeiffer but Adrian Noble's production for
the Royal Shakespeare Company, with Alex Jennings as
Theseus/Oberon, Lindsay Duncan as Hippolyta/Titania, Barry Lynch as
Philostrate/Puck and Desmond Barrit as Nick Bottom. ``A slick,
arrestingly pretty comedy machine,'' Ben Brantley wrote in The New
York Times. 1996. Miramax. $104.16. 103 minutes. Closed captioned.
</P>
<P>
   PAUL ROBESON: HERE I STAND. An illuminating if worshipful
biography, on PBS in February, records Robeson's accomplishments as
an athlete and artist and then moves carefully into the political
arena, with Robeson as both champion of human rights and apologist
for Stalinism and the Soviet Union. ``As in the other tributes, the
political part of his career continues to cast a shadow,'' Walter
Goodman wrote in The New York Times. 1999. Winstar. $19.98. 117
minutes. Release date: Aug. 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
