<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANALYZE THIS': SIMPLE PLOT, GREAT CASTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Wise guys are funny _ and they have feelings, too,
at least according to ``The Sopranos'' on HBO, or a 1997
made-for-cable-comedy called ``The Don Analyst,'' or the recent hit
film ``Analyze This,'' which hits video and DVD shelves this week.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to imagine James Cagney in the 1931 classic
film ``The Public Enemy'' having a crying jag like mob boss Robert
De Niro does in ``Analyze This,'' but, hey, we're all more
sensitive now. ``Public Enemy,'' by the way, is the film in which
the brutal Tom Powers (Cagney) smashes a grapefruit into the face
of his mistress (Mae Clarke). Try to get away with that now.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the mob has become something to laugh about in
Hollywood today, or not laugh about if you count last year's
alleged comedy ``Mafia.'' The laughs in ``Analyze This,'' though,
are mostly right on target. The most brilliant casting coup was De
Niro _ who is known for his wise-guy characters in ``The
Godfather'' and ``GoodFellas'' _ as the conflicted mob boss. It's a
wonderful self-referential joke that resonates throughout the film.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is simple. De Niro plays Paul Vitti, a New York City
mobster facing a midlife crisis after his best friend is whacked by
a rival gang leader (Chazz Palminteri). Billy Crystal is
psychiatrist Ben Sobol, who unwittingly becomes Vitti's shrink
while in the midst of trying to tie the knot with his fiancee (Lisa
Kudrow). Director Harold Ramis (``Groundhog Day,''
``Multiplicity'') keeps the gags coming, but the best part is the
Cyrstal-De Niro relationship, which grounds the comedy. In lesser
hands, some of the material would fall flat, but with De Niro
playing off his tough-guy image and Crystal at his nebbish-y best,
the film's fanciful premise flies. In particular, a clever parody
of one of the most famous scenes in ``The Godfather'' is all the
more funny because of the pair's screen personas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' also boasts a solid supporting cast. Kudrow, in
a relatively minor role, is the perfect combination of unflappable
and hysterical, and Joe Viterelli _ as De Niro's right-hand man,
Jelly _ segues from mayhem to slapstick with ease.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, ``Analyze This,'' don't forgetaboutit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Everybody's watching: Ron Howard's ``EDtv,'' which also arrives in
video stores this week, unfortunately hit screens less than a year
after ``The Truman Show,'' and audiences apparently weren't
interested in another hit on the television industry. ``EDtv'' is
hardly in the class of the Peter Weir film _ ``Truman'' is an
interesting parable that has something to say about our media
culture, while ``EDtv'' never does much more than throw a few barbs
at the boob tube and our obsession with fame. Nevertheless, ``EDtv
_ the story of a man, Ed Pekurny (Matthew McConaughey) who agrees
to have his life filmed 24 hours a day, seven days a week by a
desperate cable channel _ is both funny and entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey shines as the charming Ed, a 31-year-old
going-nowhere video-store clerk who is spotted for the show by a TV
producer (Ellen DeGeneres). After passing the audition, Ed is
signed to the channel, which also gets releases to film him and his
relatives and friends, including his brother Ray (Woody Harrelson),
Ray's girlfriend Shari (Jenna Elfman), his mother (Sally Kirkland)
and his stepfather (Martin Landau).
</P>
<P>
   At first the show is slow going, with the opening shot being Ed
waking up and scratching his private parts before realizing the
cameras are on him. Predictably, a baffled audience can't take
their eyes off him, and _ also predictably _ things get crazy.
Early on, he walks in on Ray cheating on his girlfriend, who
happens to be watching. Ed then has to hightail it over to Shari's
apartment to try to calm her, but she instead announces to the
world that Ray was lousy in bed. After that, the TV audience is
hooked, just waiting for the next shocking revelation while
debating aspects of Ed's life in man-on-the-street interviews or
polls in USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   ``EDtv's'' looniness and terrific acting allow you to forget
that the film has little to say. But Howard's strong suit has
always been his ability to turn out consistently entertaining
films, and with ``EDtv'' he has a full house. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
