A3280 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BOOMER-COLLECTIBLES20     08-19 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOMER-COLLECTIBLES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sleepers: 10 often-overlooked collector cars
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Automakers are more than willing to help baby boomers
relive their youth.
</P>
<P>
   From the burst of high-performance roadsters to the new
Volkswagen Beetle, manufacturers are bringing out a variety of new
``toys'' to appeal to a market niche with more disposable income as
their children grow up and out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Some, however, prefer the originals.
</P>
<P>
   Hemmings Motor News, which publishes a catalog of collector cars
and parts, has listed 10 ``sleepers'' it describes as overlooked
collector cars. The 10 were chosen for potential appreciation in
value.
</P>
<P>
   The editors advise buyers to choose the very best example of a
car that you can find within your budget. If you have to farm out a
great deal of the work, the cost could exceed what the car is worth
today or in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Buying a collector car is a matter of the heart, not the head,
for anyone other than the pros, they say. ``These cars should be
picked primarily because they appeal to you, so if you never make a
cent on the car, you'll still have a car you enjoy owning and
driving.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemmings had two criteria: The car must be available for less
than $10,000, and the would-be collector should have a good chance
of finding an example of the car. The cars are listed in
alphabetical order:
</P>
<P>
   _ Austin-Healey Sprite/Mark I MG Midget, 1962-64
</P>
<P>
   The second-generation Austin-Healey Sprite built from 1962 to
1964 evolved from a bug-eyed, rounded roadster to a squarer, more
conventional appearance. Sharing the body shell and running gear
was the MG Midget, which differed in badging and trim levels. These
cars offer top-down fun, crisp handling, a choppy ride and
excellent fuel mileage as well as a vast availability of spare
parts. They're simple to restore and maintain and are in demand as
economical entry-level collector sports cars. Check carefully for
rust and rot as they can render these cars unrestorable if
advanced.
</P>
<P>
   _ BMW 2002, 1968-76
</P>
<P>
   The car that put BMW on the map in the United States quickly
proved itself a sensation on roads and racetracks throughout the
country. The slick two-door offered a combination of performance
and roadability that appealed to commuter and weekend racer alike.
Today, these cars are sought after by collectors but are not yet
out of reach for the enthusiast of modest means. These cars enjoy
an excellent parts supply and support from a large nationwide club.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buick Regal T-Type coupes, 1983-85
</P>
<P>
   The 1983-85 Buick Regal T-Type coupes were built to give Buick a
more youthful, sporty image. These street fighters had a
turbocharged V-6. Visuals included a blacked-out grille and
headlamps, hood bulge and bright rocker panel trim. These hot
Buicks have yet to catch fire with collectors.
</P>
<P>
   _ DeSoto V-8s, 1951-54
</P>
<P>
   DeSoto V-8s from 1952 through 1954 _ a smaller displacement
version of the legendary C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKE     08-19 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING CARS TAKE OFF AT AUCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While no personal trainers are expected, an auction
next weekend at Pebble Beach, Calif., may give new definition to
the term ``body beautiful.'' There will be lots of tycoons, and the
testosterone will be flowing. But the bodies they will be ogling
will be auto bodies, many costing $1 million and up.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 29, Christie's will conduct its annual ``Exceptional
Motor Cars'' sale at the Pebble Beach Equestrian Center. The
auction will be held after four days of events, including a 50-mile
drive for entrants in this year's Concours d'Elegance, a beauty
contest for cars, and the Monterey Historic Car Races at Laguna
Seca, a nearby track. At last year's auction, Christie's sold $15
million in cars in two and a half hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pebble Beach attracts car enthusiasts from all over the
world,'' said David Gooding, Christie's top car specialist. ``Tens
of thousands come.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's will offer 73 cars, among them a 1935 Bugatti Type 57
Atalante, a two-seater with its original black paint and cognac
leather seats; a 1937 Alfa Romeo 8C 2900B Cabriolet, a 1921
Rolls-Royce Silver Ghost tourer, and Marilyn Monroe's favorite car,
a golden yellow 1953 Cadillac Eldorado custom convertible.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in the world of dot.com billionaire collectors, a
car's mere beauty is not enough. Bruce and John McCaw of McCaw
Communications, who sold part of their company to AT&AMP;T; Anthony
Wang of Computer Associates, and Jon Shirley, a board member of
Microsoft, all collect vintage racing Ferraris, which have become
the ultimate status symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a postwar car, Ferraris tend to lead the way,'' said Miles
Morris, a Christie's car specialist. ``They have a special mystique
and allure. Ferrari was always particularly successful as a racing
car from the 1940s to the late 1970s. Ferraris go for higher prices
because people remember the races in their youth. They grew up with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Bluntschli, a former Ferrari owner and racer who now works
at Cavallino, a magazine for serious Ferrari aficionados, said:
``There's nothing better than a throaty, open-air Ferrari. The
handling in the car is just incredible. You can't beat its
responsiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Cote, the manager of Ferrari of Los Gatos, Calif., said,
``These cars are a total passion.'' He explained: ``When you drive
one, the hair goes up on the back of your neck. You get a tingly
feeling. There's the sensation of speed. It sounds like you are
going through a tunnel. It strikes almost a sexual kind of emotion.
In 15 minutes you get a visceral rush like you've never felt
before. Drugs have nothing on this; you have no idea how addictive
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sheehan, a Ferrari specialist in Newport Beach, Calif., put
it another way. ``Men are insane,'' he said, ``which is why they go
racing and spend $1 million on a car. Ferraris are in a world of
their own. It's like a religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing Ferraris have been built since 1947; to be considered
vintage, a Ferrari must be at least 25 years old. There are eight
vintage Ferraris in Christie's sale.
</P>
<P>
   People discuss Ferraris as they would champion thoroughbreds; in
fact, the car's symbol is a prancing horse. ``For me, a car must
have a great racing history,'' said Sheehan, who maintains a Web
site on the cars, www.ferraris-online.com. He said he liked Lot 38,
a 1966 Ferrari 275 GTB/C Competition Berlinetta, Chassis No. 9007,
which won the ``first in class'' title 15 times in 22 races between
1966 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 9007 has a spectacular history,'' he said. ``It has a good
engine with a lot of power, unusual sound, enough brakes to stop it
and really balanced handling.''
</P>
<P>
   Lot 54 is a 1952 Ferrari 340 Mexico Berlinetta Carrera Pan
Americana, Chassis No. 0226 AT, one of four of that model made. It
is estimated to sell for $1 million to $1.5 million. ``It's a great
car,'' Sheehan said.
</P>
<P>
   The car was designed to compete in the 1952 Carrera Pan
Americana, a 2,000-mile race on the new Pan American Highway. The
route was from the southern border of Mexico to Texas. The driver,
Albert Ascari, a Grand Prix world champion, crashed after 92 miles
but was not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some wicked hairpin turns; the tires blew out at
160 miles an hour,'' said John Starkey, the author of ``Ferrari: 50
Years on the Track (Renwick &AMP; Starkey Ltd., 1998). ``It was a heck
of a race.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans also study the lineage of the Ferrari jockeys who handled
the cars. The 9007 was raced by a famous Italian driver, Sergio
Tullio Marchesi, who won the 1967 and 1968 Italian National Grand
Touring Championship titles.
</P>
<P>
   Provenance is another consideration. Was the car ever owned by a
celebrity like Ralph Lauren, Paul Newman, David Letterman or
Nicolas Cage, who all have vintage Ferraris? Is it part of the
stable of a major collector like David Scaife, a member of the
Mellon family and a Gulf Oil heir?
</P>
<P>
   Scaife is selling Lot 64, a sleek red hardtop convertible 1962
Ferrari 250 GT Nembo Spyder, Chassis No. 3771 GT.
</P>
<P>
   Other East Coast collectors include Scott Rosen, the co-owner of
National Wholesale Liquidators in New Jersey, and Oscar Davis, the
chairman of Hayward Industries of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market for Ferraris is worldwide,'' Morris of Christie's
said. ``It may be strongest in the U.S. but it's also good in
Japan, Australia, Europe and Great Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   International collectors include the Sultan of Brunei and his
brother Prince Jeffrey; Yoshiho Matsuda, a Japanese construction
tycoon; Brandon Wang, the diaper king of Hong Kong, and Lorenzo
Zimbrano, the head of Cimex of Mexico, one of the world's largest
cement companies.
</P>
<P>
   Does condition count?
</P>
<P>
   ``Few Ferraris are 100 percent original,'' Morris said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bluntschli pointed out, ``Over the past 40 years, a lot of
Ferraris crashed and burned.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Ferraris are often rebuilt, she said she preferred cars
with matching chassis and engine numbers, that is, cars that have
retained their original engines.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan said, ``It's like a Louis XIV antique chair,'' adding,
``If they are asking a million dollars for a chair from Versailles,
you want to make sure the top and bottom match.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the beauty issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``A beautiful body on a car counts tremendously,'' Sheehan said.
``Some collectors buy cars only for show. Others race them. Before
I sell a car, I ask the person what he wants to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris summed it up: ``At the end of the day, we're not owners
of these cars. We're really only custodians.''
</P>
<P>
   Show Time
</P>
<P>
   Saturday and Sunday 200 exhibitors will participate in Antiques
Weekend in Somerset, N.J., at the Garden State Exhibit Center
between 11 a.m. and 6 p.m. The show's Web site is
www.stellashows.com.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at 3 p.m. John R. Clark of Kitty Kat Kollectibles will
lecture there on his specialty, Roseville art pottery made in Ohio
between 1890 and 1954. A piece of Roseville can range from $50 to
$2,000, depending on its rarity, period, color and decor.
</P>
<P>
   Lynde McCormick of Boston is selling Chinese vernacular antiques
at the show, including an 18th-century Ching elm painting table
priced at $3,400, and a 19th-century eight-foot-long elm altar
table, $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a lot of demand in our area,'' McCormick said. ``Our
things are really different.'' His Web site:
www.chinesecountryantiques.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
