<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRTH-CERTIFICATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INS WARNS MEXICAN CITIZENS ABOUT USING PHONY U.S. BIRTH
CERTIFICATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Drue Brown is cq) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Immigration officials are giving 2,000
Mexican citizens who bought fraudulent Texas birth certificates
from crooked midwives a choice _ surrender the phony document or
face arrest.
</P>
<P>
   A list of the midwives' clients has been distributed to
Immigration and Naturalization Service inspectors at the
international bridges in Brownsville, part of the legal fallout
from perhaps the largest birth certificate fraud ever uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and 1997, federal prosecutors in Brownsville obtained
guilty pleas from 13 lay midwives in Cameron County _ including a
San Benito woman on a state health department midwifery advisory
board _ after charging them with selling hundreds of phony birth
records to Mexican parents at prices ranging from $400 to $1,500.
In exchange for probated sentences, the midwives agreed to hand
over lists of clients they falsely claimed had children born on the
U.S. side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican parents who attempt to bring their children into the
country using birth certificates they purchased from local midwives
now will be subject to arrest, INS officials warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to . . . have these people surrender the
document, that is the Texas birth certificate, which they had
obtained through fraudulent means and no questions will be asked,''
said Immigration and Naturalization Service spokesman Art Moreno.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, any attempt to use these illegally obtained
documents to get their offspring into the United States would
result in a prosecutable offense,'' Moreno warned, adding the
parent's local crossing card could also be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, INS officials contacted the primary media outlets in
Matamoros, across the Rio Grande from Brownsville, to publicize
their intention to stop those using the fraudulent birth documents
to bring their children into the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we started this little media blitz, it's my
understanding that slightly more than 50 individuals have come
forward to surrender their Texas birth certificates at the
bridge,'' Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   The fraudulent birth documents gave the children born in Mexico
an automatic claim to U.S. citizenship, one that could eventually
extend to the child's parents and close relatives. And it also made
them eligible for an array of benefits and entitlements afforded
U.S. citizens, including welfare, food stamps, Medicaid and other
taxpayer-funded programs.
</P>
<P>
   Using the names provided by the INS, state welfare officials
found 100 families who used the false credentials to apply for
benefits, said Michael Uhrbrock, public information director for
the Texas Department of Human Services in Edinburg. Depending on
the amount of benefits paid, the families were either referred for
prosecution or asked to repay the benefits and removed from the
program, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The scam was simple for midwives to work, since they are allowed
to file delayed birth certificates attesting they assisted in a
birth outside a hospital. In one case, midwives recruited clients
at a Matamoros hospital by contacting new parents whose children
were born there, INS investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Trevino, the INS investigator who headed up the midwife
inquiry, told the Brownsville Herald that as many as 30,000 births
were recorded by a group of 20 midwives in Cameron County during
the past 10 years, and that most of them proved to be fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Houston Chronicle in 1996, Trevino
cited the prodigious pace of Brownsville midwife Margarita
Garcia-Rojas, then 61, who filed 3,400 birth certificates between
1985 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's almost like delivering a baby a day for 10 years,''
Trevino said. adding the midwives' activities failed to raise any
red flags with local officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to some people at City Hall in Brownsville and said
`How can a person file 3,400 records in a 10-year period and nobody
take notice, or suspect something is up?' They told me, `Well,
we're not investigators, and we don't have the authority to do
investigations.' But they do have a responsibility to the
taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownsville Independent School District officials said they
don't know if the INS effort to identify children with fraudulent
documents has affected enrollment in the Rio Grande Valley's
largest district. Currently 38,732 students have enrolled, slightly
fewer than the 38,898 enrolled at the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are 166 students less now, the fourth day of school, than
at this time last year,'' said Drue Brown, public information
officer for the district. ``But we are starting school a full week
earlier (this year) and our totals are rising daily.''
</P>
<P>
   INS officials say the delay in placing the lists at the border
crossing was due to the lengthy investigation of the midwife's
records, which included births they did attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have the task of insuring the information provided by
midwives does not cause any undue hardships on those children who
were delivered by those midwives and born in the United States,''
Moreno said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
