<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-DATELINE-REVIEW-NY     08-19 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DATELINE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DATELINE NBC': A LOOK AT SCHIZOPHRENIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(EDS: The spelling of Luca, in the 1st graf, is correct.) 
(lh) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting into the mind of someone afflicted with schizophrenia is
no easy assignment, but Friday night's ``Dateline'' gives it a
dutiful try. The mind is that of the 26-year-old Luca Moylan, who
at the age of 14, after a seemingly happy childhood, began to
experience terrifying voices and hallucinations. At 17, he was
diagnosed as suffering from schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   When John Hockenberry, Friday night's reporter, met him two
years ago, he had already been wandering New York City's streets
for a decade, sometimes on drugs. He remembers his life then as
befogged and disconnected; he felt trapped in what he calls an
``ultimate loneliness.'' Then with the help of a new medication and
a psychiatrist associated with Fountain House, a mental-health
center on New York City's West Side, Moylan experienced a
remarkable turnabout.
</P>
<P>
   His allies were his mother, Donna, who had no unrealistic
expectations of success but, from the pictures of their spaghetti
dinners together, provided a sustaining, if often disappointed,
hope of some sort of improvement, and Dr. Ralph Aquila, who
provided medication, exhortation and a faith that Moylan was
capable of taking control of at least some basics of his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The medication helped him to the first steps to recovery, but as
Aquila kept emphasizing, recovery from the symptoms of
schizophrenia is slow and hard work. In a few weeks Moylan's mind
seemed to be clearing, and he felt ready to leave his halfway house
and go off on his own. But then despite the psychiatrist's
warnings, he began to be late or miss days at his mail room job and
to sample some marijuana, a dangerous recreation given his
condition. He resisted therapy; delusions returned.
</P>
<P>
   The therapy sessions, vividly recorded, become a battle of sorts
between the patient, who feels he is being manipulated, and the
doctor, who recognizes that the young man's try for freedom is
premature and dangerous. When Moylan demands a new life, Aquila
insists that he concentrate on more manageable goals, like holding
a job and getting to appointments on time: ``Let's do the concrete
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The desperation of that low point seems to have marked a new
resolve on Moylan's part. Why he escapes a breakdown is not
entirely explained in this report, but presumably the medication
and the therapy have been doing their job. Now he can work for a
few hours a week and talk to Hockenberry in a coherent way.
</P>
<P>
   He says he feels as if he had been in a coma for years. The
reporter describes him as having a ``newfound confidence in his own
mind.'' He hugs his mother, who, still realistic, speaks of his
seeming recovery as ``a quiet joy'' but ``fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `DATELINE NBC'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Friday on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Neal Shapiro, executive producer; Geoff Stephens, producer;
Jessica Gerstle, associate producer; Andy Finkelstein, editor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
