<HEADER>
A3291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-EVERNHAM-N     08-19 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-EVERNHAM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERNHAM STAYING PUT, FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hottest rumor in Winston Cup racing burned itself out last
week when Tommy Baldwin, Ward Burton's crew chief, announced he was
staying with Burton in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That ended speculation that Baldwin was leaving Burton to
replace Ray Evernham as Jeff Gordon's crew chief, with Evernham
moving into management.
</P>
<P>
   The published report seemed to gain credibility when Evernham,
while implying nothing was going on, refused to deny that there had
been contact between Hendrick Motorsports, which owns Gordon's car,
and Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Further, both Bill Davis, Burton's car owner, and Burton were
clearly concerned about Baldwin's status. And Davis had been burned
by Hendrick before.
</P>
<P>
   It was Davis who gave Gordon and Evernham their start in NASCAR
when he teamed them in the Busch Series in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Gordon was on Ford's fast track, but it wasn't fast
enough. Hendrick and Chevy snatched him away from Davis and Ford at
the end of 1992 and reunited him with Evernham, who had moved to
Alan Kulwicki earlier that year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis jumped from Busch to Winston Cup in 1993, and while he and
Burton won a race in 1995, until this season, Davis and Burton have
essentially struggled with mediocrity _ at best _ until Baldwin,
32, came on board late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Under Baldwin's direction, Burton has made a solid move up,
which has increased Baldwin's stature in the garage.
</P>
<P>
   That fact, plus repeated statements by Evernham indicating his
desire to move into management, seemed to leave the door open for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   But Baldwin's decision to stay with Davis and Burton, at least
for now, almost certainly means that Evernham will continue in his
present role with Gordon through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, Evernham is no dummy. He understands that Gordon
factors into his success just as he plays a major part in helping
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that Dale Jarrett and crew chief Todd Parrott
have been the most-consistent team in NASCAR this year, Gordon
remains the most competitive.
</P>
<P>
   So, while Evernham may be getting tired of the daily grind, he
will not move up until he is certain there is somebody ready to
move in.
</P>
<P>
   And there aren't a lot of guys capable of doing that.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, if he stays with Hendrick, it would probably be
beneficial to Hendrick's overall operation if Evernham were in more
of a supervisory role.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Hendrick has Gordon and two other very sick cars.
There's a doctor in the house, but he doesn't have time to treat
anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   If Evernham was able to pay more attention to the other two
teams, it could give them a boost. But a boost like that is
unlikely unless it can be done in a way that won't jeopardize
Gordon's chances of staying on top.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
