<HEADER>
A3293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-WITNESS-     08-19 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-WITNESS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLPLAYER MANAGES TO BE THERE WHEN HISTORY IS MADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CHRIS ANDERSON   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Bobby Witt may hold the major-league record for
spine-tingling chills in a career. Baseball's version of Forest
Gump, Witt has witnessed some of the game's greatest moments.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Tampa Bay pitcher has been in the majors since
1986, so the chances of seeing something historic have been
favorable.
</P>
<P>
   But what Witt has watched is, well ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just weird,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While pitching for the Texas Rangers, Witt was in the dugout for
Nolan Ryan's 5,000th career strikeout, his 300th career win and his
sixth and seventh no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie in 1986, he saw Don Sutton pick up his 300th win.
</P>
<P>
   While pitching for Oakland in 1993, Witt saw Minnesota's Dave
Winfield record his 3,000th hit.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 7, Witt was Tampa Bay's starting pitcher when Wade Boggs
hit a home run for his 3,000th hit, becoming the only player in
history to reach it on a homer.
</P>
<P>
   To put it in perspective, only 23 players have reached 3,000
hits this century, and Witt saw two of the players do it.
</P>
<P>
   On June 23, 1998, Witt was traded from Texas to St. Louis, just
in time to see Mark McGwire go on a home run binge that landed him
in the history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the longevity factor,'' Witt said. ``Being able
to stick around you have a tendency to see more things, to see
certain historical moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you just happen to be in the right place at the
right time. There's probably some guys who have been playing as
long as I have who haven't seen anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Witt keeps memorabilia in a game room inside his Texas home. He
could open a small museum with what he has.
</P>
<P>
   When Witt pitched in Texas, the Rangers always put a player's
picture on each game ticket. On the night Ryan fanned Rickey
Henderson for his 5,000th strikeout, Witt's picture happened to be
on the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   To remember Ryan's 300th win, Witt has an untorn ticket from the
game and a signed commemorative bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with Nolan for four years, and watching the no-hitters
and the 5,000th strikeout, was awesome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Witt said it was hard to single out a highlight of all the
events he has seen, but McGwire's 70th home run at the end of last
year ranks high.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire hit his 50th homer, he signed a ball for Witt that
read: To Bobby, home run No. 50, first player in history to do it
three straight years, Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   When McGwire hit his 61st and 62nd home runs, he took all of the
balls that were not used in the game, signed them, and gave them to
his St. Louis teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after McGwire hit his 70th home run on the last day of
the 1998 season, Witt received a signed ball from the game in the
mail. He also received a dozen other baseballs signed by McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest surprises came one afternoon when Witt had
just finished working out. He returned to his locker to find the
spikes McGwire had worn for home runs 58-60. ``He just threw them
in there,'' Witt said. ``He was like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Witt was the starting pitcher for Tampa Bay on the night Boggs
homered for 3,000. Witt lasted only two innings and left the game
after getting pounded for six runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have loved to have still been in the game,'' said
Witt, who has a 7-9 record. ``Just the way he did it, to hit a home
run for 3,000, just the electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was already out of the game, and I came back down to get
dressed, and then I went back to the dugout. When he came to the
plate, it was the same feeling I had when McGwire came to the plate
for 61.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3294 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-SENIORS-BOS &LR;      08-19 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-SENIORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRWIN PART OF THE CHANGING FACE OF THE SENIOR TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ ``The good part about last week,'' said Hale
Irwin of his experience at last week's 81st PGA Championship, ``was
there was little expected of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of nice to walk in, be able to play, and not have
great expectations hanging over you. For myself, I expected to play
better. I hoped I'd play better. The first two rounds were shocking
to some people in that 1) I was able to walk 36 holes and 2) I had
a score where I could actually see the leaders. When you turn 50,
some people feel you become a non-entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was refreshing. I wasn't tired. It's just my game wasn't
quite where I needed it to be. Medinah finally exposed me. Had I
been in the hunt going into Sunday, it might have been different. I
lost it early on Saturday, and then it became a time of trying to
catch up. The great part of it was the reception I received on
every hole all week. Particularly on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there was a touch of deja vu out there in the northwestern
suburbs of Chicago, Irwin turning back the clock and even earning a
glance from Ryder Cup captain Ben Crenshaw. But it wasn't to be.
Irwin opened 70-69_139 to fan the fires of his youth, but closed
78-75 to finish tied for 41st at 4-over-par 292. This brought him
back to earth and sent him on his way to Thursday's Pro-Am before
teeing it up Friday in pursuit of a third straight BankBoston
Senior title at Nashawtuc CC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did make a comment early in the week to the press that I
wasn't playing my best golf,'' said Irwin of his performance at
Medinah. ``What I was doing was keeping it under control and
managing what I had quite nicely. I didn't putt particularly well
and I was keeping it in play. I led the field in driving accuracy
the first two rounds. I knew when the weekend started I couldn't
just fall back on that. I needed to step up my game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I three-putted a couple of holes right out of the box on
Saturday and never got the momentum going. I lost that good,
positive feeling I had created on Thursday and Friday. I did the
same thing on Sunday, and that's a tough course on which to get
anything back. I had pressures coming to bear, with talk about
Ryder Cup. They were just a few extra curves, and I was never a
good curveball hitter. That's why I left baseball. I just didn't
handle it all that well on the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   So the venue shifts from the par-72, 7,401-yard layout at
Medinah, the longest at sea level for any major championship, to
Nashawtuc's par-72, 6,773-yard tract for this 54-hole event. The
young turks Irwin will face the next three days aren't named Tiger
Woods or Sergio Garcia. They're named Bruce Fleisher, Allen Doyle,
and Christy O'Connor. You're a rookie on this circuit when you're
50.
</P>
<P>
   This is a formidable field. Fleisher, who has won five times, is
No. 1 on the money list with earnings of more than $1.7 million.
Irwin has also won five times and is No. 2 $1.5 million in
earnings. Doyle, with three wins, including the PGA Seniors
Championship, has three wins and more than $1.3 million. Larry
Nelson is No. 4 and Dana Quigley of Barrington, R.I., is fifth.
Twelve of the top 15 money winners on the Senior Tour are in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are not big so you have to play good iron shots,''
said Irwin, who can join Chi Chi Rodriguez (1986-88) as the only
players to win this stop three straight years. ``You have to make a
careful analysis as to how you're going to attack this golf course.
The fact is you can't be so conservative that you don't play
aggressively, but at the same time you have to be careful. That's
been my approach to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The field represents, to a great degree, the changing face of
the Senior Tour and with Tom Watson, Tom Kite, and Lanny Wadkins
ready to come on board in the coming months, the landscape will
again be altered. ``I never felt I belonged out here,'' said
Quigley, who is now in his third year on the tour and has won six
times. ``After I won for the first time, it didn't maked me
officially feel I belonged. But I felt I might be headed in the
right direction. I wasn't intimidated anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
