<HEADER>
A3298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CDC-CAMPING20-COX     08-19 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CDC-CAMPING20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CDC warns of dangers of stoves inside tents
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention is
using the deaths of six Georgians in camping accidents in March to
highlight the dangers of stoves and grills inside tents.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper released Thursday, the agency discusses, without
using names, the deaths of Robert and Adrian Green, Clarence
Williams and Nicolette Hawkins of Baxley on March 14 and Kenneth
Lang Sr. and Kenneth Lang Jr. of Marietta on March 27.
</P>
<P>
   All six, as well as a dog, were killed by carbon monoxide
poisoning after they pulled cooking devices _ a propane stove in
the first case and a charcoal grill in the second _ inside their
tents to keep warm as they slept. Carbon monoxide, a byproduct of
burning, forms a compound in the body that prevents blood from
carrying oxygen to tissues. All six victims had high levels of the
compound in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   From 878 to 1,513 deaths per year are because of carbon monoxide
poisoning, the CDC said, and about 30 each year happen in tents or
recreational vehicles. The most common scenario is that campers
unprepared for falling temperatures after dark pull the devices
inside and seal doors and zippers, not realizing that they are
trapping poisonous gases in their sleeping space.
</P>
<P>
   Recreational-goods retailers are aware of the danger and
routinely warn customers. ``We never recommend any kind of flame in
a tent at all, not even a stove or lantern,'' said Terrell Boyd, a
salesman at REI in northeast Atlanta. ``A lot of customers like to
use the vestibule of their tents for stoves, but we recommend they
use it only for storage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Langs died during a Cub Scout campout, and the Boy Scouts of
America have been developing additional warnings for their Guide to
Safe Scouting handbook as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
