<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV26-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY TIES RISE IN ABORTIONS TO DROP IN CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Aug. 26.)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now comes a scholarly study suggesting that abortion prevents
crime, a report stamped with a big ``Slippery Slope,'' causing both
sides in the abortion debate to run and hide in the same bushes.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the University of Chicago and Stanford
University, trying to understand the reason for a dramatic decline
in crime numbers during the 1990s, found an equally dramatic
increase in abortions in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, they suggested, all those people who might have been
born but weren't could have turned into criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the study could be stood on its head tomorrow by
another study, because that's what studies do to one another. But
for now, the numbers are worth looking at. There was a big drop in
crime 20 years after there were lots of abortions. Those
pregnancies that were terminated in the 1970s would otherwise have
resulted in people who were 18 to 24 years old in the 1990s. Ages
18 to 24 are considered the peak crime years.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggested that had these children been born they
would have grown up unloved and unwanted, making them antisocial,
which is probably not fair because there are many well-adjusted
young adults today who were initially a real setback to their
parents. But their research does support the popularly held theory
that children who grow up unloved and resented tend to take out
their hurts on society.
</P>
<P>
   The worse assumption is that the would-be mothers of these
unwanted pregnancies in the 1970s were mostly poor or very young or
women of color. The research surmised that these would-be criminals
would have been the unwanted offspring of teen-agers, minorities
and the poor because they get the majority of abortions.
</P>
<P>
   When you add that assumption, the slippery slope becomes a luge
track.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers knew they were holding a firecracker. They made
their presentation, said they doubted anyone would like it and
explained that they were only giving us the facts. It didn't mean
that they personally believed in abortion or that certain groups
should be encouraged to have abortions.
</P>
<P>
   But someone is sure to grab this study, like a sea gull on a
potato chip. And what will they do with it?
</P>
<P>
   It's fine to make a point that a woman's ability to choose is
good for society, but claiming that poor women tend to give birth
to baby criminals is unfair and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Over on the other side, what does this do to the
rights-of-the-unborn debate? Those who oppose abortion contend that
the unborn fetus might have gone on to greatness, but never to
breaking and entering.
</P>
<P>
   This is a creepy study that whispers things like superior race
and selective breeding. There's a ``those people'' hidden in the
interpretation. Hitler types would love it.
</P>
<P>
   Right off, it seems like another way to demonize the poor, the
young and women of color. You don't want them having babies. Their
kids just naturally go bad.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what. The kids of middle-income, wealthy, older white
parents also go bad. Read the news.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to argue than that. In the 1970s, after the
Supreme Court made abortion legal in Roe vs. Wade, lots of women
got abortions. In addition to poor, young women of color were a
large number of white, not-so-poor and not-so-young women getting
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   We know them. They had abortions for the same reasons women had
them before abortion was legal. They had them because their birth
control didn't work, their house was bursting or maybe their
marriage was in trouble. They were not ready because they were
still in school or just starting a job or because they were ill or
because they were raped by their mother's boyfriend or their date.
They were not prepared _ emotionally, financially or
psychologically _ and for the first time in the history of women
who pray to a special saint once a month, they could do something
about it.
</P>
<P>
   They had a safe, compassionate and legal choice. They had
clinics to go to. They had government funding to pay for the
procedure. Some of the rich still went quietly to their own doctors
or into a hospital and got a special diagnosis. But the
legalization of abortion assured all women the choice.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers went up because there was a way to count the numbers
and because more women lived to report their abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s there were many things that more women started
doing, and one of them was thinking for themselves. So a lot of
women had abortions because they could make up their own minds,
even if it meant going against what their parents, boyfriends and
churches wanted them to do.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the numbers zoomed. Some of them had husbands, some
did not and some had had sex only once. Some of them were Catholic
and some belonged to churches that would today be considered
stalwarts on the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   All incomes, ages and races filled the clinics, grateful for
places that were warm and caring, and which still are, even though
the staff now wear bulletproof vests.
</P>
<P>
   We may buy the notion that unwanted and unloved children can
grow up to be sad and desperate individuals. But not that one kind
of potential mother is likely to produce bad kids.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
