<HEADER>
A3307 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NKOREA-FAMINE-675&AMP;ADD     08-19 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-FAMINE-675&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREA APPEARS TO BE EMERGING FROM YEARS OF SEVERE FAMINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ North Korea appears to be emerging from a
prolonged severe famine with the help of international food aid,
but four terrible years of hunger from 1995 through 1998 may have
cost the country 2 million to 3 million lives, according to
accumulating evidence gathered by a range of experts.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the dead were old people and children, or urban dwellers
of any age with no way to forage off the land.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, North Korea got nearly 3.5 million metric tons
of donated food from abroad, mostly from China, Japan, South Korea
and the United States. It still needs more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food assistance is essential,'' said Catherine Bertini,
executive director of the U.N. World Food Program, who has just
returned from North Korea. ``It is the only reason why there might
be some stability now in the nutritional lives of many North
Koreans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago we saw no food in the country at all,'' she said
in an interview Thursday. ``There wasn't much food growing. There
weren't small animals around. I remember distinctly not ever
hearing a bird sing _ or seeing a bird. I can count on one hand how
many oxen we saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, there were quite a lot of oxen working in the
fields or pulling carts,'' she said. ``There were small herds of
goats. We saw a lot of pigs, dogs and many small animals of all
kinds. There seemed to be a stable food situation now. That does
not mean that it's good. That doesn't mean that there is enough
food in the country. And it doesn't mean that there aren't still
children who are malnourished, because clearly there are.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country does not grow enough to feed itself,'' she said.
``The aid is absolutely critical.'' North Korea could use even more
food, she added, since current assistance is based on subsistence
nutritional levels.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bertini said that North Korean officials now acknowledge
that people were dying of starvation in significant numbers,
although the figures they give are much lower than estimates by
international aid experts. North Korea says that 220,000 people
died in the four-year period. Outside the country, estimates range
from 1.5 million to 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Natsios, a former vice president of the relief agency
World Vision and the author of a new study of North Korea for the
U.S. Institute of Peace, a congressionally supported research
organization in Washington, said Wednesday that the North Korean
famine had become ``one of the great famines of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We now know that more than 10 percent of the population
starved to death,'' said Natsios, who served as President George
Bush's emergency aid coordinator in the Horn of Africa during food
crises in Somalia and Ethiopia. He said the North Korean famine was
comparable to the Chinese famine of 1958 and the famine in the
1930s in the Soviet Union. ``I hope and pray,'' he said, ``that
this is the last of the great totalitarian famines whose roots lay
in systemic dysfunction.''
</P>
<P>
   In his report, ``The Politics of Famine in North Korea,''
Natsios said that confidence in the government has been shaken. In
an interview, he added that the country's belligerence could be an
attempt to mask or deflect attention from its weakness and discord.
Other experts see the North Korean missile threat as blackmail
designed to get desperately needed hard currency from industrial
nations in return for concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The economy of isolationist North Korea, based on a bizarre
self-reliant socialism known as juche, lost what shaky props it
still had when the Soviet bloc disintegrated a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Its industries collapsed and its collective agricultural system
was devastated when tools, fertilizer and seeds could no longer be
bought and farmers started hoarding crops for their own use,
sometimes in league with soldiers sent to guard the fields.
</P>
<P>
   Then a series of natural disasters struck. In 1995, North Korea
was driven to ask for international help for the first time. By
then it was to late for many of its 24 million citizens.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Another recent study, by the Johns Hopkins School of Hygiene and
Public Health, found that between 1995 and 1997 infant mortality
rates rose, family size fell and death rates across the board were
at least seven times higher than those recorded by North Korea's
1993 census. The survey, published in the British medical journal
The Lancet in July, was based on interviews with people who had
fled North Korea for China.
</P>
<P>
   Similar surveys based on varying samples have been made by the
Korean Buddhist Sharing Movement, an independent South Korean
organization, and by officials representing aid agencies.
</P>
<P>
   A former North Korean government ideologue, Hwang Jong Yop, who
defected to the south in 1997, wrote last year in a book, ``North
Korea: Truth Or Lies,'' that a high-ranking agriculture official
told him that 500,000 people had starved to death in 1995, about
50,000 of them party cadres. The government expected another 3
million deaths in the next two years if foreign aid was not sought,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Bertini saw encouraging signs of recovery this
year, North Korea will not be out of danger for a long time, she
and other experts say. Typhoons are threatening crops again, and
China has had a poor harvest in corn, which is traded across the
border unofficially by ethnic Koreans living on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer term, those who survived, weakened and
malnourished, will find it hard to resist infections. Medicines are
scarce to nonexistent and water supplies contaminated. Without a
functioning economy, North Korea cannot engage in international
trade or find the money to repair public utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The famine, which reached its peak in late 1996 and 1997, led to
acute malnutrition and loss of body mass, known as wasting, in more
than 15 percent of children under age 5 and stunted growth in 66
percent of that age group, according to a survey by the United
Nations, the European Union and Save the Children/U.K. That study
was done almost a year after the peak had passed, and many children
were already dead.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger also forced between 100,000 and 400,000 people to flee
North Korea for China, although it is not known how many may have
returned or been sent back. Official North Korean figures
acknowledged about 200,000 refugees. Whatever the number, the
Chinese were sufficiently concerned to begin detaining North
Koreans and deporting them.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering evidence of a major catastrophe has diminished
disagreements about what actually happened in North Korea, Natsios
said. Some relief officials were at first convinced that the famine
alarm was exaggerated; others argued that it was a government ploy
to get food that would go to troops.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios said that much of what was known before experts began
analyzing data from refugees and others leaving the country was
based on what aid workers were able to see on occasional visits to
North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``While these visits do provide some information,'' he said,
``neither field visits nor the data provided by the North Korean
government about the food situation are conclusive evidence of
anything, because they present conditions as the central
authorities wish them to appear to the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bertini said last week that North Korea was still barring
foreigners from 49 of its 112 provinces and did not allow aid
agencies to employ Korean-speaking staff members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
