<HEADLINE>
MAKE MOVING EASIER FOR KIDS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Thursday, Aug. 26)  
(mk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three of my friends' families, as well as my own, have moved in
the past year _ taking with them some of the 10 million American
kids who move each year.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the move was across town or out of state, the children
involved had anxieties about leaving their familiar homes and
settling into a new room, street and school.
</P>
<P>
   A strange shared belief among the kids is that their old houses
were bigger, even when in every case the new homes were larger than
the ones left behind. And each has clung to one special friend from
the old neighborhood who is his or her best friend, never to be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   These glorified links to the past are a way of staying loyal. To
relegate a beloved room, yard or playmate to photo albums and
distant memories is a form of betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   So a bit of nostalgia is healthy and to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   But if it goes beyond that, to outright depression and not
accepting the new surroundings, the child may need extra help or
counseling to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   After all, a move means a loss of control in almost every area
of children's lives. They don't get to vote on leaving, let alone
on their new home and school.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare a child for a move, several books are available.
``The Moving Book: A Kids' Survival Guide,'' by Gabriel Davis
(Little, Brown and Co., 1997, $17) is a good one for a relocating
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Moving Book'' is interactive, and aimed at kids 6 to 12,
though it has activities in which all children can participate.
There are journal pages for kids to fill out, such as ``Why my
family is moving ...'' and ``Where I was when I heard the news
...'' and a pro and con list about the move.
</P>
<P>
   Other writing exercises include filling out comic-strip bubbles
about the move, and a memory book with a page about the old house,
favorite memories, friends, favorite restaurants, good neighbors
and school.
</P>
<P>
   The authors suggest that older students write to their new
schools and request a pen pal in the same grade they're entering.
</P>
<P>
   The guide takes kids through everything from packing their rooms
to having a garage sale, from travel games to play on the drive to
the new house to ways to explore their new surroundings after the
move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrate your arrival!'' says Davis. ``Raise a glass of
lemonade in a toast, take turns carrying one another over the
threshold, have a big family hug. Do something _ anything! _ to
mark the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The guide suggests that children draw a map of the new
neighborhood and make a plan to arrange their new room just the way
they want it. (A tip from my own experience: Paint the room in a
favorite color even before the moving trucks arrive, if possible.
It will be dry and ready for posters, bookshelves and bunk beds.)
</P>
<P>
   The final pages are address sheets and tear-out,
change-of-address postcards to make staying in touch easy.
</P>
<P>
   The days just before the move are extremely hectic, so
before-moving activities should start about a month ahead of time.
It's easy to pretend that the move is still a long way off, but
preparing can make for a smooth transition instead of a bumpy ride.
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 1941EDT &QL; 
