<HEADER>
A3310 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-TURKEY-RELIEF-BOS &LR;      08-19 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-RELIEF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUE LEADERS STRUGGLE TO BRING ORDER OUT OF CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN GORVETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ As search and rescue teams flooded into Istanbul on
their way Friday to quake-devastated zones south and west of the
city, UN crisis coordinators complained of a chaotic start to the
relief operation as emergency teams were snapped up by local
authorities desperate for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 2 1/2 days here, our main problem is we still don't know
what is really going on,'' said Richard Van Hazeprouk of the UN
crisis management team.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,700 foreign experts in search and rescue are now
deployed throughout the disaster area, with more arriving hourly.
However, in Van Hazeprouk's crowded and busy office, the first
battle has been to establish contact and coordinate the many
different groups and nationalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first teams that arrived here Tuesday went to whichever
Turkish authorities who met them at the airport were shouting the
loudest,'' he said. ``No one took contact numbers, a record of the
equipment the teams had or even a note of where they were going. We
lost them.''
</P>
<P>
   The disorganized start to the rescue operation left residents of
Golcuk, a naval town some 70 miles south of Istanbul, venting their
frustration. An Israeli team was sent straight for the collapsed
naval barracks in the town, under which some 200 people were
buried, including an admiral.
</P>
<P>
   Yet next door, in the town itself, some 50 percent of the
buildings were collapsed or damaged, the respected newspaper
Radikal claiming as many as 15,000 people were still trapped
beneath them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no water, no electricity, no food!'' shouted Golcuk
resident Altin Akbayrak in a makeshift tent hed set up in the town
square.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents in Golcuk, still waiting for assistance Thursday
afternoon, attacked passing cars and buses, jammed with citizens
trying to get back into the city to discover what had happened to
their relatives. Angry locals accused drivers of blocking the roads
to relief vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``In several situations where teams had been sent by the
authorities, we decided there was no big problem and then had to
move them,'' said Van Hazeprouk.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few of the teams out in the field have even had time to
report, Hazeprouk said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the scale of the disaster, both in terms
of casualties and the geographical area covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of places for the teams to go,'' said UN
Ankara office spokesperson Tugrul Kursanlu, and the area is so vast
_ the radius is several hundred miles.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding where to send teams uses straightforward criteria
though: Highest impact, highest casualties, highest destruction,
explains Van Hazeprouk.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have also been angered by the contrast between the
struggle to save lives and the seemingly blase statements of the
country's authorities. Nesut Pektas, the senior Turkish disaster
relief coordinator, said Thursday that in Istanbul the situation is
almost completely normal, and in the next two days the situation
will be under control in the other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the respected columnist for Radikal, Ismet Berkan, said:
``The organization of the authorities is very poor. ... They can't
just give us words in a situation like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Out in Izmit, the industrial city at the quake's epicenter, as a
rescue team picked more bodies from the ruins, Swiss rescue worker
Ellinor Von Kauffungen was more understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never have enough people in a place like this,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
