<HEADER>
A3311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-COX-NEWHQ20-COX     08-19 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-NEWHQ20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox lands new headquarters site
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cox Enterprises Inc. ended months of searching for a
new headquarters site Thursday, purchasing the former Central Park
development site in Sandy Springs. Cox will also retain its
existing headquarters complex on Lake Hearn Drive and is still
considering expansion there as well.
</P>
<P>
   On the new site, on Peachtree-Dunwoody Road, north of Interstate
285, Cox plans a 380,000-square-foot office building and another
50,000-square-feet facility for a fitness center and other
services. The new building will be headquarters for Cox Enterprises
and other Cox-owned businesses, including Manheim Auctions, Cox
Newspapers and Cox Broadcasting. Cox Communications will remain at
the Lake Hearn site. Cox's downtown operations, the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, WSB-TV (Channel 2), WSB Radio Group and Cox
Interactive Group, will not be affected by the company's new
development.
</P>
<P>
   Work will start on the new building in June and is scheduled for
completion in late 2001. The company did not disclose the price of
the land or its development.
</P>
<P>
   The property was acquired from New York insurance giant
Equitable Cos., after the sale to a developer planning a
high-density residential, office and retail project fell through.
That project was opposed by nearby residents.
</P>
<P>
   Cox needs additional facilities because of its ongoing growth,
said Tim Hughes, senior vice president of administration. Of the
825 employees based at Cox headquarters, 100 are working in nearby
buildings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the company has been considering two options for
additional facilities. One was an expansion at Lake Hearn, where it
has a 300,000-square-foot building and room for more on its 27
acres. The second was to build a 600,000-square-foot complex on one
of a half dozen proposed sites.
</P>
<P>
   The new 29-acre site offers more land for future development
than does Lake Hearn, which faces the uncertainty of potential road
widening and interchange expansion along I-285, Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Hearn site ``is in a state of flux,'' Hughes said.
``While not an optimal site for future expansion, it is valuable,''
he said, and could be expanded once road plans for the area are
settled.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Cox obtained a development permit from DeKalb County to
work on site preparation for a 17-story, 300,000-square-foot office
building and parking deck on its Lake Hearn property. That permit
was obtained ``to preserve the value at this facility,'' Hughes
said. That building is still under consideration, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cousins Properties Inc., was hired as developer for the Cox
facilities. The project will be designed by Duda/Paine Architects
LLP of Durham, N.C., with HKS Inc. of Dallas, Texas, as associate
architect, and Hendrick Associates of Atlanta as interior designer.
</P>
<P>
   An important factor in the site selection was convenience for
employees, Hughes said, noting that most Cox headquarters employees
live north of Midtown.
</P>
<P>
   While both the existing and new locations are near the Perimeter
MARTA station and have shuttle service to it, proximity to the rail
system was not a critical factor in site selection, Hughes said,
because many company employees don't live near transit stations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
