<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RUMORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH STILL DECLINES TO PUT DRUG-USE ISSUE TO REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
and MICHAEL D. TOWLE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROANOKE, Va. _ |After weeks of refusing to answer questions
about whether he had ever tried cocaine, George W. Bush invited
continued speculation on Wednesday by declaring he has not used
illegal drugs in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   In setting these parameters, Bush seemed to imply he could not
make the same claim for earlier years.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush told reporters he could answer ``no'' to a
standard question on federal background forms asking prospective
workers if they have used illegal drugs in the last seven years. He
was asked on Wednesday if he could have given the same answer when
his father was president and federal forms asked about drug use for
the prior 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, let's see here. ... Yes, I could have,'' Bush said after a
pause. ``Over 20 years ago, I did some things that _ when I was
young, I made mistakes. I have learned from the mistakes, and
that's all I intend to talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In retreating, however slightly, from his previous refusal to
talk about illegal drugs, the Texas governor clearly hoped to put
to rest the question that has dogged him since his first news
conference as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But despite polls that show the public doesn't want the news
media prying into personal behavior, Bush's equivocal answers are
helping to keep the subject alive. The strategy is reminiscent of
Bill Clinton's word-parsing answers in 1992 to questions about the
military draft and his marital fidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush's response might be setting a new standard for
delving into the private lives of public figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they have done is interesting,'' Earl Black, a professor
of political science at Rice University in Houston, said of Bush's
campaign. ``They have now created the Bush rule, a statute of
limitations on youthful indiscretions that kicks in at the 25-year
mark. That's a standard most Americans would find pretty
reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after the latest question-and-answer session with
reporters in Roanoke, a heckler confronted Bush on the issue during
his tour of the city's historic farmer's market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just answer the question!'' the man shouted as he held up a
sign with the word ``SNORT.'' Bush greeted the critic as if he were
a supporter and calmly told him he had nothing more to say on the
topic.
</P>
<P>
   The heckler declined to identify himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 53, backed away from his no-comment stance for the first
time Wednesday when asked whether he would continue the current
practice of asking government officials about drug use in the past
seven years during background checks. The Clinton administration
goes beyond the standard form for White House jobs by asking about
drug use after age 18.
</P>
<P>
   Bush elaborated on Wednesday by saying he could have passed the
background check when his father was president, when the standard
was 15 years. The elder Bush served from 1989 to 1993, meaning his
son would have to have been drug-free from 1974 on to meet the
15-year standard. Under the Bush administration, drug use meant
disqualification. Under Clinton, candidates may still get jobs in
the administration depending on the circumstances of their drug
use.
</P>
<P>
   Informed later that the current White House background check
covers behavior dating to age 18 for White House jobs, Bush
returned to his original response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told the American people all I'm going to tell them,'' he
said. ``I've made mistakes and I've learned from those mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Bush is determined to avoid additional comment on the
issue, even though some of his prominent supporters, including
Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating, have urged him to be more forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people really care about what he did 20 years
ago,'' Bush spokesman Mark McKinnon said. ``We have answered the
question we think people care about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jerry Falwell, one of the early leaders in the effort
to get Christian conservatives involved in politics, defended Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a preacher of the Gospel. The central message we have is
God forgives. And when God forgives, he forgets and so should we,''
Falwell said at a later Bush fund-raiser in Roanoke. ``I know him
very well. There is nothing in his past that I have ever heard
about that would embarrass me.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
