u i BC-CHINA-DETAINEE-BOS &LR;      08-19 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-DETAINEE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETAINED AMERICAN STUDYING POVERTY IN REMOTE PROVINCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The words that Daja Meston's friends and family use
to describe him _ mild-mannered, private, soft-spoken, and gentle _
hardly paint the picture of a radical intent on fomenting unrest in
China.
</P>
<P>
   But Chinese authorities did not view Daja Meston's visit to
rural Qinghai province in remote northwestern China as an innocent
research trip. Early this week, the 29-year-old from Newton, Mass.,
and Gabriel Lafitte, an Australian associated with the University
of Melbourne, were detained near the site of a controversial World
Bank project to alleviate the desperate poverty of the region,
closed to outsiders until recently.
</P>
<P>
   A Jewish American by birth whose parents raised him in a Tibetan
Buddhist monastery in Nepal, Meston married a Tibetan exile he met
in Boston nearly a decade ago. The highly unusual background of the
Brandeis University graduate and former monk got him an invitation
to appear on the ``Oprah'' show last year.
</P>
<P>
   His wife calls him an aspiring scholar profoundly connected to
Tibetan culture and spirituality. With his aversion to speeches and
demonstrations _ even photographs _ her husband was anything but a
hot-headed activist, Phuntsok Meston said Thursday from her home in
Newton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in great shock,'' said Phuntsok Meston, 30, who works in
an art gallery. ``It was publicly stated by the World Bank and
Chinese officials that this was an open area, that anybody is
welcome, so we didn't think anything would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel by foreign journalists and officials outside big cities
in China is generally prohibited without permission and official
escorts, but Chinese officials had pledged two months ago that
diplomats, politicians, journalists, and other ``legitimate''
individuals could freely visit the site of the disputed project.
Nevertheless, the two men were accused of conducting an ``illegal
investigation,'' according to information provided by Chinese
authorities to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Western Poverty Reduction project plans to commit
$160 million of World Bank money to resettle and improve living
conditions for peasants in three Chinese provinces. The Qinghai
portion has come under fire from Tibetan and environmental groups,
who accuse China of flooding Tibetan areas with Han Chinese
migrants and ignoring ecological impacts.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the June 24 vote, China's representative to the
World Bank, Zhu Xian, promised that ``authorities will sincerely
welcome and facilitate site visits by legitimate parties
concerned,'' including non-governmental organizations ``if they are
not politically hostile and not challenging China's sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   Tibetan rights groups said the two men and others had been
encouraged by China's World Bank representative to enter Qinghai on
tourist visas. The incident also called into question pledges
Beijing made while lobbying for the loan, critics said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are reneging on the spirit of that statement . . .
that's open hypocrisy,'' said Alison Reynolds, director of the Free
Tibet Campaign in London. It also raises concerns about China's
promises to safeguard the rights of Tibetans and Mongols affected
by the resettlement and of local opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a test of the entire project,'' said John Ackerly,
president of the International Campaign for Tibet in Washington,
D.C. The loan was approved, he noted, on condition that the Qinghai
component be delayed until ``outsiders were allowed to see
conditions and needs of the local people.''
</P>
<P>
   Meston and Lafitte met last May at a Brandeis University
conference and became close friends. Lafitte visited World Bank
officials and was encouraged to visit the project, Ackerly said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Qinghai earlier this month (8/7), Lafitte
said he doubted China had exhausted options for improving living
conditions without resettling people, and asked: ``Could we just
slow down the project?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, critics of the project insisted that Lafitte and Meston
were not rabble-rousers, only reseachers fascinated by Tibetan
culture and development.
</P>
<P>
   Dana Clark, senior attorney at the Washington-based Center for
International and Environmental Law, said she was told Tuesday by
China's office at the World Bank that an American and an Australian
had gone to Qinghai alone and ``had made mistakes,'' and now were
facing difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerly said Qinghai ``was a very, very high profile project,
and everyone has been scrambling to learn more about it. ``Daja . .
. was going to research, not to investigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Meston was highly sought as a translator for Tibetans visiting
America, Acklerly said. In 1997, US Rep. Frank Wolf, a Virginia
Republican, hired Meston to translate during Wolf's trip to Tibet.
After returning, Wolf condemned China for ``repressing'' Tibetans,
outraging Chinese authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say Daja Meston worried the Wolf trip might be held
against him, though he worked only as a translator.
</P>
<P>
   Daja Meston completed his degree at Brandeis and was considering
graduate study. He worked part-time at WorldTeach, an nonpolitical
educational program associated with the Harvard Institute for
International Development.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said
the Chinese have granted diplomatic access to Meston, and a
consular officer from Beijing would fly to Qinghai Friday to meet
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have urged the Chinese to release the American. We
understand they were preparing an independent study of the impact
of a proposed World Bank project,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Editorial assistant Joyce Hor-chung Lau contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
