<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3315 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-DANDRIDGE20-COX     08-19 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DANDRIDGE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Berry lovingly gives Dandridge her due
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dorothy Dandridge was the Joe Louis of post-war glamour girls, a
sepia-skinned knockout who proved black was beautiful at a time
when American society insisted otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Then after her death in 1965 at age 41, she was all but
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Dandridge doppelganger and one-time Atlantan Halle Berry may
change that with her dramatized biography, ``Introducing Dorothy
Dandridge,'' a lovingly indulgent portrait of the
singer-dancer-actress who helped break Hollywood's color barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Berry delivers what could be her most intoxicating performance.
Granted, she's no Meryl Streep, but Berry's sexy and subtle
portrayal of Dandridge makes it clear that she's more than just the
sum of her finely chiseled cheekbones.
</P>
<P>
   Berry gets solid backup from Cynda Williams (``Mo' Better
Blues'') as her envious sister Vivian, Loretta Devine (``Waiting to
Exhale''), pitch perfect as their actress-mother stuck playing
``mammy'' roles, and Klaus Maria Brandauer (``Out of Africa'') is
convincing as legendary director Otto Preminger.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd casting choice that works in spite of itself,
Dandridge's longtime manager Earl Mills is played by Brent Spiner,
best known as the emotionless android Data on TV's ``Star Trek: The
Next Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other celebrities, Dandridge's life followed a familiar arc
of bad luck, bad husbands and bad drugs. Credit Berry and her
capable co-stars for keeping the movie from overdosing on tempting
cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately the movie relies on trite and ineffective
flashbacks _ from the last night of her life _ to tell her story,
starting with the 1954 Academy Awards. After starring in ``Carmen
Jones,'' an all-black version of the classic Bizet opera, Dandridge
scored one of her many ``first Negro'' accolades when she was
nominated for a best actress award. She lost to Grace Kelly, but
firmly established herself as a leading lady.
</P>
<P>
   While her career seemed to be taking flight, her personal life
was in turmoil: She had divorced Harold Nicholas (Obba Babatunde)
of the dancing Nicholas Brothers, she gave birth to a severely
retarded daughter, and became Preminger's mistress, unaware he was
married.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you stand on the edge of a cliff and jump off
because you're tired of being scared,'' Berry as Dandridge says in
a one scene. ``Sometimes you jump just to see what it feels like to
fall.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie suggests that part of her descent was the racism that
all ``colored'' entertainers faced, but those injustices seemed to
torment Dandridge more acutely.
</P>
<P>
   Although the movie never reaches full boil, it's a well-told
story about a wounded beauty haunted by the knowledge that while
she could perform at the glitziest Las Vegas casinos, she still
couldn't swim in the pool.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge''
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Saturday on HBO.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
