<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSHCLINTON20-COX     08-19 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSHCLINTON20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some Democrats under Bush's campaign spell
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not even Democrats, it seems, are immune to Texas
Gov. George W. Bush's charms and his aggressive drive for campaign
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 75,000 people who have helped Bush ring up more than
$37 million in his presidential campaign are 277 contributors who
gave money to the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996. Some of those
donors also have contributed to Democratic candidates this year.
</P>
<P>
   Though relatively small in number, these donors offer some clues
to Bush's early fund-raising success and the potential he has to
mine support from conservative Democrats and independents. Some of
the contributions also reflect disapproval of Clinton, particularly
over his sexual improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the most part, the contributions show that while it's
still early, Bush's strategy of reaching out to moderate
Republicans without offending the party's conservative base also is
catching the attention of some Democrats and previously disaffected
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Yerrid, a third-generation Democrat from Tampa, Fla., is a
trial lawyer, a favorite target of Republican attack and,
seemingly, a sure bet to support a Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But, prodded by Republican friends, Yerrid paid $1,000 to meet
Bush at a June 25 luncheon in Florida. When Bush learned of
Yerrid's profession, the governor said, ``Now when I get up and
mention tort reform, I'm going to see if you turn red and walk
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yerrid recalled, ``Well, sure enough, when he got to that point
in his speech, he stopped and looked right down at me. I didn't get
red, get up or walk out because he gave a great speech and I was
interested in some of the things he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Courting both camps
</P>
<P>
   Like Yerrid, many of these donors haven't made up their minds
about which candidate they will ultimately support for president,
and many are contributing to more than one candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Troy LaGrone, a beer distributor in Denton, Texas, called Bush
and Gore ``the best candidates in their fields. I'm not sure where
I'll be if I have to pick between them.''
</P>
<P>
   August Busch III, the chairman of Anheuser-Busch, also has given
to candidates in both parties _ Bush and former Democratic Sen.
Bill Bradley _ a common practice among large contributors who wish
to keep open their lines of communication with both sides. In 1996,
Busch and other top company executives contributed to Clinton and
the campaign of GOP nominee Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Jere Drummond and Ronald M. Dykes, the chief executive officer
and chief financial officer of BellSouth Communications Group, gave
not only to Bush, but also to Gore and Arizona Republican Sen. John
McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Florida businessman H. Wayne Huizenga, who counts among his
holdings the Miami Dolphins, is another prominent Clinton-Gore '96
supporter who is backing Bush this year.
</P>
<P>
   Personal preference
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bush's Democratic donors said they gave $1,000 simply to
hear what the candidate had to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not committed to anything at this stage,'' said Ronald
Norby, a construction executive in Greeley, Colo. ``You've got to
find out what the platforms are, who the running mates are going to
be. There is a lot left to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Wyatt, a rancher from Hollister, Okla., who supported
Clinton in 1992 and 1996, said he thinks Bush will be a stronger
candidate than Gore on maintaining commodity price supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is a little bit more of a friend of agriculture
than the vice president,'' said Wyatt, whose 5,000-acre farm
straddles the Texas border. Gore is ``going to have to swing pretty
hard on the agriculture line to get my support.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gwen Cupp of Hot Springs, Ark., Clinton's affair with Monica
Lewinsky meant the end of her support for the president and his
fellow Democrats. ``The bottom line is we are just disappointed,''
said Cupp, whose husband also has abandoned the Democrats for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, Bush has lured back to the Republican fold
those who left the party in 1996 and voted for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Snyder, a corporate attorney from Atlanta, was an avid
backer of former President George Bush when he lost against Clinton
in 1992. But Snyder said he thought Clinton did well in his first
term, and he became disenchanted when he perceived that Dole, the
former senator from Kansas, cozied up to the religious right in the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush represents traditional Republican fiscal
conservatism without the Republican social agenda,'' Snyder said.
``I voted for George Bush in 1992, and I'm one of those that thinks
he's getting another George Bush like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still another category of contributors talked about the perils
of having politically active friends, particularly in a period of
intense pressure to raise more and more money.
</P>
<P>
   Martin McInerney, president of Star Lincoln-Mercury in
Southfield, Mich., said he got a call from a Republican friend who
said, ``I've got a table (at a fund-raiser) to sell, do me a
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   McInerney obliged. ``It was just, `I'll buy myself out of this
mess,''' said McInerney, a longtime Democrat who is still eyeing
Bradley and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
