<HEADER>
A3322 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SMUGGLE-CHARGES20-COX     08-19 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLE-CHARGES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seven accused of smuggling Chinese
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Authorities charged seven people Thursday in the
smuggling of 132 Chinese nationals found hidden on a ship in
Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Four members of the ship's crew, including the captain, and
three passengers face three charges each that carry a maximum
penalty of 30 years in prison and a $750,000 fine. They appeared
briefly before a federal magistrate Thursday afternooon in
Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from the discovery Aug. 12 of 132 illegal
immigrants aboard the Prince Nicolas, a ship registered in Cyprus
that was hauling pig iron. Agents found the passengers in cramped
rooms that shot off different sides of a ladder descending into the
bowels of the ship. They said the entrance was bolted closed and
hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Donnie Dixon of the Southern District of Georgia,
which covers 43 counties, declined to say whether investigators
will make more arrests. He said they have not finished their
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime the laws are being violated in such an organized and
calculated way, I think we are obligated to take it seriously,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Drake, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office, said the
seven defendants were charged with transporting, smuggling and
concealing illegal aliens. He identified the crew members as Zhang
Zhi Zhong, 33, the captain; Huang Shi Jian, 27, the second officer;
Shi Ya Dong, 57, the chief engineer; and Sun Cheng, 35, a cabin
boy.
</P>
<P>
   He said the passengers charged are Zheng Xiao, 33; Li Guo Guan,
whose age was unavailable; and Zheng Huan Jian, 24, who is not
related to the second officer. Drake would not say why the three
passengers were charged.
</P>
<P>
   Dixon said he might ask a grand jury for indictments next month.
Most of the 132 Chinese remain in jails in DeKalb and Fulton
counties. Many have asked for asylum. It may take years for the
government to resolve those requests.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to smuggle Chinese nationals have been uncovered in the
last two years in California, Guam, New Jersey, Washington state
and along the western coast of Canada. Investigators said the
Prince Nicolas case is the most sophisticated immigrant smuggling
operation in recent Georgia history.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese immigrants pay $30,000 to $50,000 to weather poor
conditions on trips here because they believe they will make lots
of money, said Lani Wong of Atlanta, the former national chairwoman
of the National Association of Chinese-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Many end up with low-paying jobs in garment factories or
restaurants in New York and other cities with established Chinese
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go to the village and tell them what opportunities they
have in the U.S.'' she said. ``They don't know that they'll
probably end up working in a sweatshop.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
