<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-SCENE-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE DEMONSTRATORS REPRESENT MANY BACKGROUNDS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS) 
(rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ They were mostly the educated urban elite
who turned out to demonstrate in central Belgrade: students, young
professionals and their parents, who looked as if they were walking
in the park after work.
</P>
<P>
   But they were also ordinary workers and activists who had driven
in from different parts of the country. They brought with them
flags and banners, even fireworks. They had rough hands and were
sunburnt, and brought a more down-to-earth attitude and blunter
opinions.
</P>
<P>
   And under the festive mood, the message from all was the same:
The demonstrators were opposed not only to the government; many
were irritated with the opposition leaders. Virtually everyone
interviewed said that they wanted to see a united opposition, and
that leaders should bury their differences and their egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not interested in any party and we are angry with the
leaders of the opposition parties,'' said Dejan Zhivkovic, a
retired lawyer who came with his wife. His two sons were also
somewhere in the crowd, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do not understand the main wish of the people is that
they unite their forces to bring about big changes,'' he said of
the opposition politicians. ``We are convinced the leaders should
change and new young and uncompromised people should come. We are
not here because someone called us, we are here because we are
unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   People were infuriated by the on-and-off performance of some of
the participants. Two brothers in their sixties, Radojica and
Dobrosav Dmitric, a construction worker and a truck driver, had
driven 60 miles from their town, Gornji Milanovac, which is also
the home town of the former Army chief of staff, Gen. Momcilo
Perisic.
</P>
<P>
   Perisic, who has recently entered politics in opposition to
President Slobodan Milosevic, announced a few days ago that he
would not attend the rally. The Dmitric brothers gave a hurt smile
at the mention of his name, and expressed their unhappiness that he
was not here.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd showed less tolerance for Vuk Draskovic, the leader of
the Serbian Renewal Party, booing and whistling during his speech
and as he left through the crowd. They said he had betrayed them by
joining the Milosevic camp, even for only a short time, when he
voted for war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Rebeka Srbinovic of the New Democratic Party, which took part in
previous governments, was also drowned out by booing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sign that people are growing mature politically,''
said Petar Milosavljevic, 57, as Draskovic swept past, flanked by
bodyguards and hectoring bystanders. ``They are recognizing who is
working in their interest. It is some kind of political sobering
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people mentioned the war in Kosovo, although one group
carried a banner showing they were from Kosovo. The reasons most
people gave for being there were economic.
</P>
<P>
   Mirna Obrenovic, 38, a travel agent, said her business had
shrunk to 20 percent of its level 10 years ago. A retired
architect, Karin Milutinovic, said she had only just received her
April pension on Wednesday, and last year only got six months'
worth of payments. ``It is not so important though, but that we
feel so helpless,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Srboljub Puresevic, a construction engineer from a town south of
Belgrade, came in his car with three men from work. Other
co-workers feel the same, he said, but did not dare to come. ``I
used to have a salary that was worth 1,000 Deutsche marks, now it
is worth 100,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Branka Apic-Krcedinac, a member of an organization for diabetes
sufferers, came with colleagues and friends in a convoy of 48 buses
from Novi Sad, in northern Yugoslavia. Holding up a home-made
banner, she said diabetes patients lacked insulin and medicines.
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed to think elections could change anything because
the ruling parties would control the results. Most people said
Milosevic would have to go first, whether forced or of his own
will. It would take vast demonstrations, one student said, ``that's
the only way.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gloomy statements, the crowd laughed and cheered,
whistled and cracked jokes. As the demonstration broke up after two
hours, people said they thought it was a success. ``It was
successful for the early stages because our politicians are just
getting started again after a long pause,'' said Nikola Markovic,
who attended with his wife. ``It would be an illusion to expect
something really big to happen. But it is like an announcement of
future developments to make people think.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
