u a BC-AGING-STUDY-BOS &LR;      08-19 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGING-STUDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAY HEALTHIER, LIVE LONGER, STUDY CONCLUDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Living proof of a new study's conclusion that centenarians live
longer than most people because they've been healthier,
104-year-old Dirk J. Struik said he continues to live independently
and is rarely in the hospital, except on a doctor's visit.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, however, he said he holds no special secret to
a long life.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Struik, a Massachusetts Institute of
Technology mathematics professor emeritus, has been a part of the
New England Centenarian Study, a project of Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center and Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest report from the project, in the current journal
Lancet, the researchers say they found that of the 37 centenarians
from eight towns in the Boston area who have participated in the
long-term study, 89 percent were living independently when they
were about 92 years old, and 35 percent were still doing so at
about 102.
</P>
<P>
   ``The study speaks against this adage that the older you get,
the sicker you get,'' said Dr. Thomas Perls, director of the
centenarian study and a geriatrician at Beth Israel Deaconess
Medical Center. Perls is coauthor of a book entitled ``Living to
100,'' published this year by Basic Books.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rachel Hitt, coauthor with Perls on the study agreed: ``They
are living the vast majority of their lives in excellent health.
These people aren't very, very sick for 10 or 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also found that most of the study participants
had avoided such illnesses as cancer and Alzheimer's disease. ``Had
they not done so,'' the researchers wrote in the Lancet, ``it is
unlikely they could survive to the practical limits of the human
life span.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier findings from the long-term study have identified a
sense of humor, a resilient personality and a history of family
members living a long life as being crucial components of living
for 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Struik might as well be living proof of another new study's
conclusion in the current British Medical Journal, that elderly
people who stay active are likely to live longer than those who do
not.
</P>
<P>
   Although Struik was not part of the study led by Thomas A.
Glass, Harvard School of Public Health assistant professor, he
exhibits many of the qualities identified there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep up with my profession,'' Struik said in an interview.
He reads mathematical journals, although he said he leaves the
solving of today's mathematical problems to younger people, and he
added that he also reads the newspapers every day.
</P>
<P>
   In this second study, Glass and his colleagues followed more
than 5,500 people in New Haven, Conn., and found that those who
engaged in such social and productive activities as playing cards,
preparing meals or doing community work were likely to live longer
than those who didn't. Surprisingly, such social and productive
activities were found to be just as important as physical
activities in prolonging life.
</P>
<P>
   ``More active elderly people were less likely to die than those
who were less active,'' write the researchers in the British
Medical Journal. ``Social and productive activities were observed
to confer equivalent survival advantages compared with fitness
activities. This observation is important because it suggests that
activities that entail little or no physical exertion may also be
beneficial.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3326 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NH-TAX-BOS &LR;      08-19 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-TAX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COALITION OF TOWNS SEEKS TO BLOCK SCHOOL TAX PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Taking aim at a controversial school funding
plan cobbled together by lawmakers earlier this year, a coalition
of five poor towns Thursday asked the state Supreme Court to
declare the plan unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In its complaint, the so-called Claremont Coalition of
property-poor towns sued New Hampshire, saying that its new school
funding system has been implemented too slowly, and is
fundamentally flawed. At issue is whether the state provides an
adequate education to students in less-affluent districts and
whether the system taxes all property owners equally to pay for
public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of our districts provide a constitutional
inadequate education,'' said Andru Volinsky, lead lawyer for the
coalition. ``We don't think it is constitutional to force those
children to participate in that kind of a limited education program
and we don't think it's constitutional to make them wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Motions filed by lawyers for the coalition ask the court to
among other things, force the state to begin immediate payments for
``compensatory services'' in 11 schools where fewer than 40 percent
of all students scored at a level of ``Basic'' or above on
standardized assessment tests.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also asks the court to begin imposing sanctions on the
state in the form of legal fees and costs as a result of its
continuing failure to meet an April 1, 1999 court-imposed deadline
to craft an equitable system of funding the schools.
</P>
<P>
   The state has struggled with the school funding issue since
1971. In 1997 the court declared unconstitutional the system of
funding public schools almost entirely through local property taxes
that varied wildly between rich and poor cities and towns.
</P>
<P>
   In response, during the most acrimonious legislative session in
the memory of veteran lawmakers, the 424-member House and 24-member
Senate passed separate versions of what would have been the state's
first general income tax. Faced with repeated threats of a veto by
Governor Jeanne Shaheen, however, the income tax effort died. So
did proposals to pay for schools by permitting gambling via video
slot machines, a capital gains tax bill and a proposed tax on
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the governor and legislature settled on an education
funding bill that required the state to begin paying some $825
million in school costs on July 1. The bill enacted a statewide
property tax that caused an uproar in property-rich communities and
raised the tax on cigarettes and the transfer of real estate yet
still left an estimated $100 million hole in the school funding
plan which has yet to be filled.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement seemed to please no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We predicted this would be in litigation and today that
prediction came true,'' House Speaker Donna Sytek said. ``The
question is how long they are going to be in litigation _
potentially forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen said the state's plan is working and constitutional.
``We have fundamentally changed the way we support education in New
Hampshire. . .and I am confident the Supreme Court will recognize
that,'' Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
   If the court were to require the state to spend even more than
$825 million on education it would resurrect both the campaign to
pass an income tax and the drive to pass a constitutional amendment
to override the court's ruling. As is, no consensus exists on how
to fill the existing $100 million gap.
</P>
<P>
   No schedule has been set for when lawmakers will reconvene. When
they do, the next battle is likely to be over the imposition of a
capital gains tax, a move that has Shaheen's backing, but one that
will face strong opposition in the Republican-controlled House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just isn't the willingness in the Legislature to raise
more money, at least there wasn't when we left in June,'' said Fred
King, a state senator who Thursday announced a $775 million interim
plan he hopes will earn the Legislature two more years to find a
solution if the impasse isn't resolved.
</P>
<P>
   King predicted that the historically frugal state would find
itself between $1 billion and $2.3 billion in debt by 2005 as a
result of the school funding decision unless legislators either cut
spending or raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects serious financial problems to arise until
sometime next year. A quick court ruling could change that,
however, forcing legislators back into a session that promises to
be even more fractious that the last one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
