<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3328 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ECON-FORECAST20-COX     08-19 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-FORECAST20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ratajczak: Housing boom over
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Despite a sharp drop in mortgage rates in metro
Atlanta this week, Georgia State University economist Donald
Ratajczak says the trend is upward.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the 30-year, fixed-rate loan averaged 7.55 percent,
down from 7.84 percent last week, according to a weekly survey by
BankRate.com.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year, fixed-rate mortgage closed at 7.16 percent, against
7.44 percent last week. The one-year, adjustable-rate loan was
relatively flat, ending the week at 5.97 percent, down from 6.01
percent.
</P>
<P>
   All the rates include discount points, or fees charged by
lenders at closing.
</P>
<P>
   Rising mortgage rates, perhaps to the 8.5 percent level, will
bring a housing market slowdown and an end to double-digit home
price appreciation within two years, Ratajczak said in his
summer-quarter forecast Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``An 8 percent mortgage rate is recessionary, and rates will
exceed 8.5 percent next year. When they hit 9 percent, that is the
real barrier. People will ... stop buying,'' said Ratajczak.
Double-digit interest rates, should they appear, ``would be a real
problem,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Since October 1998, when rates in metro Atlanta hit a 6.21
percent low, they have been steadily rising. ``What has happened is
that the market has moved up aggressively in the last 60 days. But
economic data suggest that inflation is not moving up now, so rates
have come back down,'' said Patrick Flood, president of HomeBanc.
</P>
<P>
   Ratajczak agreed but downplayed the weekly variations: ``Next
week, they will probably be higher again.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a 7 percent interest rate makes it harder for entry-level
buyers to afford home mortgages. But, Ratajczak declared, 8 percent
would affect adversely many move-up buyers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Single-family housing starts would fall 15 percent by 2001,
Ratajczak said, if rates hit the middle-8-percent range.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
