<HEADER>
A3340 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS &LR;      08-19 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PEDRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ ARRIVES ON TIME, SOUNDS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- At 4:05 p.m., all seemed well inside the Red Sox
clubhouse. Pedro Martinez leisurely strolled by a group of
reporters, went straight to his locker, and began to prepare for
his start against the Oakland A's.
</P>
<P>
   One minute later, all hell broke loose, triggered by the arrival
of Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette, who took the brunt of a
Martinez tirade that centered around manager Jimy Williams and his
decision to scratch Martinez from last Saturday's start against
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was angry not only at Williams, but also the media
horde that was waiting to see if he arrived within two hours of
game time, a team rule. Martinez took particular offense to the
newspaper and television cameras that awaited him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he going to come over?'' said Martinez in a voice loud
enough to be heard by the reporters. ``Is (Williams) going to
apologize? Is he going to shake my hand? Or is he going to blow me
(off).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want people following me around. I don't like the
cameras. I'm tired of these clowns following me around.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had more to say but because of the nature of the
conversation reporters were asked to leave the clubhouse by Kevin
Shea, the team's director of communications and baseball
information, who declared, ``This is a private conversation and the
locker room is now closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had arrived Saturday less than 35 minutes prior to game
time. Thursday, his car pulled into the players' lot at 3:50 and he
chose to sit in his White Mercedes, talking on a cell phone, rather
than enter the park immediately. Whether the 4:05 entrance, exactly
two hours prior to game time, was deliberate, has yet to be
determined. You didn't learn from much his remarks to Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned,'' said Duquette, ``Pedro is ready
to go out and pitch. He was still venting from the attention that
he's gotten from his last start. But he'll be ready to pitch
tonight. From Jimy's perspective, the situation is resolved. As for
the rest, it's really a position that Pedro should talk to the
manager about.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he did not go to the clubhouse to act as a
peacemaker between Martinez and the manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't even go there,'' said Duquette. ``If you're trying to
position me between the player and the manager, you're wrong. I'm
not between the two. Did I resolve anything? I don't have any
issues to resolve with (Martinez). As far as we're concerned, the
item last week is resolved. That's gone by. The rest of it is
difficult for me to discuss.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams took the same stance before and after batting practice.
Asked if he'd spoken with Martinez, Williams said any conversation
they have is private.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's said in the clubhouse should stay in the clubhouse,''
he said. ``You might not agree, but that's the way I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would handle what seems to be a growing problem,
Williams said, ``I have no problems, just challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Shira Springer of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
