<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3345 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      08-19 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, Aug.
20, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   POLICE (Seattle) _ An independent panel found the Seattle Police
Department kept shoddy records when investigating itself, were
restrained from having face-to-face interviews and failed to even
take complaints, leading the panel to suggest major reforms to the
way the department police itself. But the report emphasized no
widespread corruption in the department. The four-member panel,
appointed by Mayor Paul Schell, recommended the creation of a new
Office of Public Accountability that would be headed by a civilian
director.
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Snel, Elaine Porterfield, Kimberly A.C. Wilson. (Story
will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TRANSIENT-ATTACKS (Seattle) _ The savage attacks and murder of
transients by young people in recent years have grabbed headlines,
but police say homeless people are more afraid of other transients.
We look at the vulnerability of homeless people and how they are
perceived by the public: a mixture of fear, anger and resentment.
</P>
<P>
   By Vanessa Ho. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-FINE _ The Washington state Insurance Commissioner's
Office on Thursday fined QualMed $250,000 for improperly denying
emergency-room claims, ending an eight-month investigation into
improper handling of emergency visits. The fine, one of the largest
ever against an insurance company in Washington, is designed to set
an example so other carriers will not deny appropriate claims,
Insurance Commissioner Deborah Senn said at a news conference
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ENGINEERS (Seattle) _ A Seattle institution founded to foster
camaraderie among local engineers has gone the way of the slide
rule. Over roasted chicken and potatoes and leisurely afternoon
chit-chat, the Seattle Engineers Club met for its final lunch
yesterday after 87 years. The club, whose members shaped the look
and feel of the region, has called it quits, blaming dwindling
membership on changing times and a failure to attract ``young
blood.''
</P>
<P>
   By Phuong Le. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CHEMICAL-SENSITIVITY-ART (Seattle) _ Sickened by pesticides,
weakened by headaches and panic attacks, Don Paladin's sanctuary is
a bedroom with stainless steel walls and a spotless tiled floor.
Inside, he is safe from the chemicals that have turned his life
upside down and left him weak, sick, wary and frustrated.
Frustrated because his friends, co-workers and neighbors don't
understand that he suffers from an enigmatic and controversial
disorder called Multiple Chemical Sensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Stiffler. (Story has moved in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MICKEY (Undated) _ Hugh Grant has followed up his triumph
in ``Notting Hill'' with ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' a Mafia comedy that
is not as good a movie but is every bit as strong a personal star
vehicle for Grant.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TINGLE (Undated) _ ``Teaching Mrs. Tingle'' is forgettable
but somehow totally innocuous, with a few mild chuckles, a bravura
performance from Helen Mirren, and able support from a trio of
young stars who are more attractive and engaging than the teen
movie norm.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ILLUMINATA (Undated) _ John Turturro is a reliable and
often inspired supporting actor (``Quiz Show,'' ``The Color of
Money''), and he made a credible debut as a director in 1992 with
his autobiographical first film, ``Mac,'' which won the Camera d'Or
at Cannes that year. But with his second directorial effort,
`Illuminata,'' he's been hit by the sophomore curse, big time. The
movie is an incomprehensible mess.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SEAHAWKS (San Francisco) _ Seahawks play San Francisco on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   By Clare Farnsworth. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-THIEL-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Column from the
Seahawks-Niners game.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ABBOTT (Seattle) _ Les than a month from his 32nd birthday,
Paul Abbott has settled in as a starting pitcher for the Seattle
Mariners, enjoying his first extended stay in the big leagues. It
didn't have to take this long. His arm never really betrayed him.
Innocent fun just got in the way. ``I took the game for granted,''
pitcher Abbott says wistfully, ``which will never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
