<SLUG> BC-FBI-BULGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI ELEVATES FUGITIVE MOBSTER TO `TOP TEN' LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHELLEY MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Legendary South Boston crime boss James J. ``Whitey''
Bulger became Thursday the 458th fugitive to make the FBI's Ten
Most Wanted list, but he may well be the first former FBI informant
to rate such a billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to tell you we are out to catch him,'' said Barry
Mawn, special-agent-in-charge of the FBI's Boston office, hoping to
dispel public perception that the FBI isn't eager to nab Bulger, a
longtime informant who corrupted at least one agent with payoffs
and skipped town on the eve of his Jan. 1995 federal racketeering
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Mawn said he didn't know whether Bulger, whose 70th birthday is
Sept. 3, is the first FBI informant to be placed on the agency's
top 10 list since its inception in 1950, but that he ``probably
is.''
</P>
<P>
   The last confirmed sighting of Bulger was in Oct. 1998 at a
convenience store in Sloan, Iowa, according to authorities. Earlier
he was spotted in New York, Louisiana, Wyoming, Mississippi,
Florida, and even in his hometown of South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Mawn speculated that Bulger is hiding in the Southeastern United
States with his girlfriend, Catherine Greig, 48, who may well have
dyed her blonde hair to change her appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the kinds of looks that make it easy for him to blend
in,'' Mawn said of Bulger, a balding, blue-eyed, silver-haired man
who often wears a cap and glasses. ``There's nothing distinctive
that makes him stand out. It enhances his ability to be a fugitive.
If they're in the Southeast, every other person could look like
Whitey Bulger and Cathy Greig.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed numerous false Bulger sightings have been reported to the
FBI's Violent Fugitive Task Force, comprised of investigators from
the FBI, Boston Police, the Department of Correction and the state
Parole Board. Three investigators are currently assigned full-time
to the Bulger case.
</P>
<P>
   Mawn said authorities are convinced that it will take national
publicity -- the kind that being on the Top Ten brings -- to nab
Bulger. His photograph will appear in post offices and federal
buildings throughout the country and on the FBI's Internet web
site, www.FBI.gov. It will be circulated to law enforcement
agencies throughout the country and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Bulger will remain on the Top Ten list until he's caught. Of the
458 fugitives who have appeared on the list, 429 have been
captured, including 134 with the help of tips from the public,
according to officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting him on the Top Ten list certainly doesn't guarantee he
will be caught, but we believe it will help a lot,'' said US
Attorney Donald K. Stern, whose office indicted Bulger.
</P>
<P>
   In Bulger's absence, his longtime partner and co-defendant,
Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi revealed that he and Bulger were
longtime informants and claimed that the FBI allowed them to commit
crimes as long as they provided information about the criminal
activities of Mafia members.
</P>
<P>
   US District Judge Mark L. Wolf, who presided over lengthy
hearings exposing a corrupt and cozy relationship between Bulger
and Flemmi and the FBI, is expected to rule soon on a request to
dismiss the racketeering indictment against Bulger, Flemmi, and
three other men.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed Thursday by reporters about why the FBI has taken
so long to give Bulger top 10 status, Mawn said the fugitive
investigation has evolved from a covert search to a very public
one.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, the FBI announced that it was offering a $250,000
reward for Bulger's capture. Nine months ago, the Boston FBI office
began petitioning to elevate Bulger -- who has sporadically
appeared among 27 fugitives on the FBI's Web site -- to the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month when FBI Director Louis Freeh held a press
conference in Boston, he was grilled about why Bulger wasn't in the
top 10. He said Bulger was being considered.
</P>
<P>
   In his top 10 status, Bulger joins the likes of Saudi terrorism
suspect Osama bin Laden and Eric Robert Rudolph, who is a suspect
in abortion clinic bombings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
