<SLUG> BC-PLASTICIZERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIZING UP PLASTICIZERS: SOME BLAME BIRTH DEFECTS ON COMPOUNDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: N.C., Pa. and Tenn.) 
 
By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ Scientists are trying to reach a consensus on
whether compounds used to make numerous plastic products are
somehow causing birth defects or lowering sperm counts.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in reproductive health met this week to evaluate the
health risks of seven chemicals widely used to make plastic more
flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Some fear these chemicals, leaching from intravenous bags or
squeeze toys, could be contributing to fertility problems, which
plague an estimated 5 to 10 percent of couples, as well as major
birth defects, which affect 3 percent to 5 percent of newborns.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials argue vinyl products have been used safely
for more than four decades. And, they warn about the dangers of
substituting these materials with substances that have been studied
far less closely.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-member panel, convened by the National Toxicology
Program, however, failed to reach agreement on the risks.
</P>
<P>
   The experts were not so much divided in their opinions. Instead,
they said, they just did not have enough time during their 2
1/2-day conference to fully evaluate the volumes of research on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were not contentious discussions,'' said Dr. Lynn
Goldman, a pediatrician and senior science adviser to the National
Toxicology Program.
</P>
<P>
   The panel members refused to say how they are leaning in their
evaluations. The experts hope to reconvene before the end of the
year to finish their work, although no further meetings have been
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Though the panel has no authority to change government
regulations affecting plastic products, its recommendations likely
would have great influence with federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration and the Consumer Product
Safety Commission are conducting their own investigations into
these compounds, known as phthalate esters.
</P>
<P>
   Similar in appearance to vegetable oil, these phthalates, or
``plasticizers'' as they're known in the industry, are added to
polyvinyl chloride to make the hard plastic more elastic.
</P>
<P>
   Untreated vinyl is used to make household water pipes and home
siding. By adding these phthalate esters, manufacturers can produce
a myriad of more flexible products, from shower curtains to medical
tubing, rain coats to tile flooring.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's petrochemical companies produced about 1.5 billion
pounds of phthalates last year, according to SRI International, an
industry consulting company based in Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's major producers include Houston-based Exxon
Chemical Co., Kingsport, Tenn.'s Eastman Chemical Co., and
Pittsburgh-based Aristech Chemical Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Any effort to restrict the use of these plasticizers would
affect not just the phthalate industry but other products further
up the chain in the plastics industry.
</P>
<P>
   Propylene is one of the two major building blocks of plastics.
And about 8 percent of U.S. propylene production is used to make
the feed stocks needed to produce plasticizers.
</P>
<P>
   Aristech, for instance, doesn't manufacture phthalates in the
Houston area. But the company's plant in nearby Pasadena, which
employs 120 Aristech workers and another 45 contract employees,
produces two chemicals used to make plasticizers.
</P>
<P>
   Plastics makers could use other compounds to soften polyvinyl
chloride, but forcing the industry to switch to those chemicals
would drive up costs. And, industry officials point out that these
phthalates have been studied far more extensively than the
alternative products.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an extraordinarily bad move to seek substitutes
because we have almost 40 years of research to see that something
is safe,'' said Jack Maurer, Aristech's director of public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Washington-based Vinyl Institute, in a written
statement, said they were confident ``the conclusions of this
review will reflect the same findings as hundreds of studies have
in the past _ that the benefits of these products, especially vinyl
medical devices, far outweigh any alleged health risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Medical device makers point out that phthalates leaching out of
the plastic bags used to store blood actually help extend the
blood's shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's position was bolstered two months ago by the
findings of a blue ribbon panel chaired by former U.S. Surgeon
General C. Everett Koop.
</P>
<P>
   That group, convened by the American Council on Science and
Health, concluded that two of the plasticizers most widely used to
make vinyl toys and medical equipment were not harmful. In fact,
the group urged the continued use of these materials, citing their
benefits in the medical industry.
</P>
<P>
   But the plastics makers are being challenged by groups such as
Health Care Without Harm, a coalition of 180 health, religious,
labor and environmental groups that is trying to prod the Food and
Drug Administration to restrict the use of these compounds.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Health Care Without Harm point to a study that
indicated one commonly used phthalate, di(2-ethylhexyl) phthalate,
leached from intravenous bags into the solutions contained and then
into patients.
</P>
<P>
   They fear leaching phthalates, besides causing reproductive and
developmental problems, could cause damage to hearts, livers, lungs
and kidneys.
</P>
<P>
   Both the American Council on Science and Health and Health Care
Without Harm made presentations to the National Toxicology
Program's expert panel.
</P>
<P>
   Activists hoping to force a ban on use of the seven phthalates
expressed frustration Thursday with the speed of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Finaldi, the toxics coordinator for Greenpeace USA in
Raleigh, N.C., said 15 other countries in the last year have moved
to restrict use of plasticizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of discussions in other countries where
governments believe that precautions are more important than
protecting a product for industry,'' Finaldi said. ``We feel like
it's the other way around here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
