u e BC-HALLE20-COX     08-19 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALLE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Berry feeling good about life, `Dandridge' project
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Everyone knows Halle Berry is beautiful.
But you don't know how beautiful until you're sitting two feet from
the curvy siren in a plush California hotel suite.
</P>
<P>
   Her smooth, honey-colored complexion is without blemish. You
search for an imperfection on her oval face. A mole. A scratch. A
pimple. Anything!
</P>
<P>
   There are none.
</P>
<P>
   Berry's delicate frame is tiny, yet deceptively voluptuous in a
light blue, two-piece Armani pant suit. When asked if she still
hates her breasts, which Berry has been known to say are too big,
she stands up, saunters thisclose to her wide-eyed visitor, bends
over and breathlessly coos, ``What do you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Berry tilts her head back and laughs _ hard.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's clear that Halle Berry is feeling _ and looking _
good.
</P>
<P>
   But Berry wasn't always smiling. In fact, the 31-year-old
actress has battled diabetes, severe depression, insecurity and
narrow-minded movie producers. She even thought about taking her
own life after divorcing baseball star David Justice in 1996. Berry
actually sat in her car with the engine running in her garage and
thought about dying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the lowest, lowest low after my divorce,'' Berry says
quietly. ``Although that was one of the hardest experiences of my
life, it's been one of the best because ... it made me make some
real changes and inspired me to really stand up for me and figure
out who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Berry is Dorothy Dandridge, the sultry, yet
widely forgotten black actress, dancer and singer in HBO's
sympathetic, yet revealing film, ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge''
(Saturday, 9 p.m.). For a time, the stunning sex goddess was the
black Marilyn Monroe. Dandridge oozed sexuality, confidence and
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Called a ``sepia siren'' and the most ``beautiful Negro singer
since Lena Horne'' by Life magazine (she was the first black female
star to grace Life's cover), the tall willowy beauty reached the
pinnacle of stardom as the sultry seductress lead in two
exceptional Hollywood musicals, ``Carmen Jones,'' for which she was
the first black woman to receive an Oscar nomination for Best
Actress, and ``Porgy and Bess.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like Berry, Dandridge was a tortured soul who battled many
personal and professional demons. There were two failed marriages,
an abortion after a protracted affair with ``Carmen Jones''
director Otto Preminger, a mentally retarded daughter and racist
Hollywood's inability to find roles to match Dandridge's celebrity.
The stress took a toll.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 8, 1965, Dandridge was found dead on the bathroom floor
of her Hollywood apartment. The cause of death was an overdose of
Tofranil, an anti-depressant. Dorothy Dandridge was only 42.
</P>
<P>
   Was it suicide or accidental? No one knows for sure. But Berry,
who also executive produced the HBO film and gave up her salary to
get it made, has no doubt that Dandridge killed herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I believe that the night she died she took the
pills and said, `OK, I'm going to lie down on the floor and die
right now,''' Berry says. ``But I think it was a slow process.''
</P>
<P>
   Movie six years in planning
</P>
<P>
   It was a slow process getting ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge''
made. It took a hard-charging Berry six years to get Dandridge's
tragic story on HBO. The film is based on a biography by Earl
Mills, Dandridge's long-time manager (tenderly played by ``Star
Trek: Next Generation'''s Brent Spiner).
</P>
<P>
   Martha Coolidge, the film's director, also found the subject
compelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask yourself, `Why isn't Dorothy Dandridge the
household word that Marilyn Monroe is?''' Coolidge asks. ``And I'm
not saying they're the same. I think Dorothy Dandridge has, in so
many ways, more social significance, though she may not be as known
culturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry wasn't the only entertainer fascinated with Dandridge's
life. Whitney Houston and Janet Jackson are also looking to produce
and star in a Dandridge movie. Berry, however, wants to dispel the
notion that she beat out Houston and Jackson out for the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have rights to our respective books,'' she points out.
``I just got my project done first. It wasn't like there was one
role and we were all vying for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry says that Dandridge has been a role model of hers ever
since she was 18 and saw ``Carmen Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her contribution was so great and so meaningful, not only to
me, but to an entire community of people,'' Berry says. ``And
(Dorothy) gave me an opportunity to finally, after 10 years of
struggling in this industry, to be a leading lady.''
</P>
<P>
   While Berry has appeared in a string of films, including roles
as a crack addict in ``Jungle Fever,'' a crack mom in ``Losing
Isiah,'' a femme fatale in ``The Flintstones'' and a mouthy
militant in ``Bulworth,'' she has had a tough time finding meaty
dramatic parts.
</P>
<P>
   As Dandridge, Berry gives a wonderfully detailed and rich
performance. She sings, dances and shows a wide variety of
emotions. One of Berry's finest moments is when Dandridge is told
that although she's a guest at the Riviera Hotel in Las Vegas,
she's not allowed to use the swimming pool. A defiant Dandridge,
however, sticks her toe in it anyway, only to find out later that
the pool was drained and cleaned. It's a sobering moment. And the
quiet anger is etched all over Berry's face.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, Dandridge are alike
</P>
<P>
   Berry's obsession with Dandridge goes beyond the obvious
comparisons of two gorgeous black actress struggling to be taken
seriously in Hollywood. Like Dandridge, Berry has suffered her
share of personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even Geri Branton, Dandridge's best friend, sees the
similarities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Halle's personal life is shocking in that it's the
same as (Dorothy's),'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most red-blooded women, (Dorothy and I) shared the issues
of trying to find love in all the wrong places,'' Berry explains.
``We're both products of an idealistic way relationships are
supposed to be _ little girls growing up and finding Mr. Right and
being happy. And what you find out first is that you have to be
happy with yourself. She didn't know that. She was saying, `Love
me, love me, please somebody love me' and she didn't love herself.
I've been through that phase in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempestuous love life
</P>
<P>
   Berry has been involved in a string of rocky relationships,
including romances with Wesley Snipes and ex-husband Justice. In
1991, she was hit by a former boyfriend and lost 80 percent of the
hearing in her left ear. In 1993, Berry's dentist/boyfriend sued
her for $80,000 he said he loaned her during their relationship.
The suit was dismissed, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to not dig deep enough with people,'' she says. ``I
need someone who can deal with the woman that I really am, not this
image of Halle Berry that's put up on a pedestal. I need someone
with strong faith. That's what keeps people together, it's not
looks, how much money you have, it's what's in your heart. Now when
I meet a guy, I don't only listen to what he's saying to me, I look
at how he treats other people. How does he treat the sales clerk,
someone who means nothing to him. Is he respectful? Or is he
self-absorbed? I never really looked at those things before.''
</P>
<P>
   While it may be hard to fathom, Berry never believed she
measured up as an actress or a mate. She may have been smiling for
the cameras, but she was dying a slow death inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people look at me and say, `She should be happy,' but
what they don't realize is that I'm still a person inside just like
everybody else and people expect you to always be happy just
because you have what they think is physical beauty or you have
money and you're an actress,'' she says. ``But when people start to
make you feel like there's something wrong with you and you're not
as happy as they think you should be, then you start to get
insecure.''
</P>
<P>
   And lonely. Despite her stunning good looks, Berry says she's
often home alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men think I must have somebody, so they say, `I'm not even
going to step there,''' she says. ``And it's the opposite. I've
been dateless more than anybody I know. That's a hard, cold fact.
Many times my girlfriends are going out and I'm like, `Can I
come?'''
</P>
<P>
   After years of personal and professional stress, is Berry now at
peace? She says she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent the last three years of my life really just getting
to know myself and really appreciate who I am,'' she says. ``When I
stopped looking for love from everybody else and when I loved
myself enough, I stopped caring about what people thought about me.
If you like me, great, if you don't, so sad, so sorry, but my train
is still going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
