<HEADER>
A3362 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     08-19 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING READY FOR THE BIG ONES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Every dog has its day, and all things Cuban being  &LR; mas buenas &LR; 
than ever _ the music, the cigars and testimonials from supermodels
and movie stars _ it's time to say hello to a Cuban breed, the
Havanese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bonnie Levinson &LR; , who lives in San Francisco and is about to
become a Havanese owner, says there are fewer than five in San
Francisco, and only 4,000 in the United States. The American Kennel
Club describes the dog as part of the Bichon family, small, sturdy
and short-legged, ``with a soft, profuse, untrimmed coat. His
plumed tail is carried curled over his back. He is an affectionate,
happy dog with a lively, springy gait.'' This makes him likely to
be a much more popular pet than  &UR; Fidel Castro &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The first Bichons, ancestors to the Havanese, were brought from
Spain by sea captains as gifts for rich Cuban women in families
with whom the Spaniards wished to establish trade. Three families
that who  &LR; left Cuba during the '50s and '60s brought the dogs to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   - You're sick of Y2K predictions? W cites experts at Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter who say, ``The Ralph Lauren, Tommy Hilfiger and
Liz Claiborne brands are expected to still be around in the year
3000.''
</P>
<P>
   - Yes, it's almost Miss America time again, and say hello to
Miss California 1999,  &UR; Mary Anne Sapio &LR;  of Rohnert Park. Her
platform issue is breast cancer education and awareness, her
scholastic ambition is to get an undergraduate degree and a
master's in education and then a law degree, and her talent is tap
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Imelda Marcos &LR;  has confirmed reports that her shoe collection
is growing quickly and said the tally could some day exceed 3,000.
``I seem to get more and more shoes,'' she said in Manila on
Wednesday, ``and I'm afraid that I will have more shoes than
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcos left behind 1,220 pairs of shoes when she and her
husband, the late  &UR; Ferdinand &LR; , fled the presidential palace in
Manila. She said people gave her shoes when they imagined her
forced out and shoe-impaired. ``They thought I was shoeless. They
did not want a former first lady to be without shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   - In celebration of the 2,000th birthday of  &UR; Jesus &LR; , the
National Catholic Reporter is sponsoring a contest for an artwork
depicting him. The work will appear on the millennium issue cover
of the magazine, and the artist will win $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAN WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In response to complaints from animal rights advocates, Procter
&AMP; Gamble recently announced that it would stop testing products on
animals, reports Advertising Age. Now comes word that the company
is buying the pet product manufacturer Iams; P&AMP;G executives told Ad
Age that would give Iams the chance to apply tricks of the human
care trade _ hair products and the like _ to pet care products.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' concludes Ad Age, ``in just a little over a month, P&AMP;G
has gone from using animals to test human products to using humans
to test animal products.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. ``Every Breath Is a Prayer,'' a talk about Tibet and the
spirituality of everyday matters, was part of an American Himalayan
Foundation event on Tuesday, in conjunction with an exhibition of
``sacred and extraordinarily rare Tibetan Buddhist antiques.'' The
venue: Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ORDER AND LAW &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Evan Walsh &LR;  loves the personals ad in the Bay Area Reporter:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hall of Justice; early morning. Handcuffed: You going in.
Black eye: Me coming out. You smiled. I shrugged. Let's have a
drink.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jim Schock &LR;  found it in the Marin I-J police calls column:
``Larkspur. 8/13, 9:08 a.m., petty theft: Laundry was taken from a
dryer in the first block of Skylark Drive and laid out and folded,
with two bras missing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``After I got in (a) fight I was down in this discipline module,
which is like a hole. Three times a day, you see a pair of hands
and some food comes in. It's pretty awful. One day it opens and
there was this lieutenant, with some deputy he'd brought by to meet
me. I hadn't had a shower in five days, I was sleeping in my
clothes, my hair was all f_ up. But that Hollywood big-shot
entertainer thing came in, and I thought, `Well, I'd better come
to, I have company.' And this guy came in and said, `Listen, I know
you don't have a lot to read in here. I hope I wouldn't be crossing
the line if I brought a script by for you. It's about unicorns.
It's not what you think, there's a very human element to it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  -  &LR;   &LR; From an interview with  &UR; Robert Downey Jr. &LR;  in
``Projections 10: Hollywood Film Makers on Film-Making,'' to be
published by Faber and Faber in England.
</P>
</TEXT>
