<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3363 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-19 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE THIRD MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By A.M. ROSENTHAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The important thing to know is not who fired the shot but who
paid for the bullet.
</P>
<P>
   The novelist Eric Ambler wrote that in 1937. Ever since Dec. 21,
1988, the search for the answer has been central to the lives of
270 families _ the survivors of every person aboard Pan Am 103,
mostly Americans, and the 11 Scots killed on the ground by falling
pieces of plane and humans.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday in Washington, Scottish prosecutors will talk to the
families (no press) about the trial ahead in The Hague,
Netherlands, for two Libyan agents who have been indicted in
America and Scotland.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I doubt there will be a person in the room, including
prosecutors, or any intelligence official anywhere who does not
know that Moammar Gadhafi commanded his agents to blow up the
plane. They were on his secret service payroll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In The Hague, he controls their mouths as if they were in
Tripoli. They will deny he knew anything about anything _ if they
have any interest in the lives of family members back home in
Tripoli. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some relatives of the Pan Am victims have prepared questions for
the visiting Scots:
</P>
<P>
   _ Since a U.N. document approved in Washington and London
promises that the trial will not be used to ``undermine'' the
Libyan government, which means Moammar and only Moammar, will you
be free to follow a probing line about his guilt?
</P>
<P>
   _ Since the press is not around, do tell us, do you believe in
fairy tales? Do you believe that two men working directly under the
supervision of Gadhafi's relatives could get the money, equipment
and false passports to pull the plot together in Tripoli, Malta and
Frankfurt, organize explosive experts and airport connections to
get the device aboard an American plane at precisely the right
time, and whisk back to Libya all safe and sound _ all without a
word about the operation getting through to Gadhafi, who would have
chopped their fool heads off if they dared carry out, without his
permission, a crime that wrecked his economy with sanctions?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ If you can't really believe such a cockamamie story, why is
your government and ours demeaning the sorrow of the Pan Am
relatives by the charade of a trial? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Since there is no death penalty in the Scottish law under
which the two men are to be tried, and killers are being freed
early in Northern Ireland, Israel and the Balkans, what is the
longest they could serve?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Since Scottish law permits defendants to be acquitted on a
verdict of ``not proven,'' is it possible they won't serve a day? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Oh, and what about the long, strong belief of Western agents
that Syria and Iran were also involved in the explosion plot _
until the Westerners were suddenly persuaded to believe it no
longer? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Never has sorrow been more bitter to the Pan Am relatives than
now, when so many countries are becoming part of a conspiracy with
Gadhafi to rescue him by limiting the trial to his two agents _ and
accepting his golden word that he knew nothing, not a thing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions against Libya for refusing to give up the agents were
``suspended'' when Gadhafi decided that, given the U.N. ``no
undermining'' condition, the Scots could have a chance to question
the two after all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The rush to the Libyan trough began instantly. Zippo, full
diplomatic ties were restored with Libya, and construction and oil
contracts were signed.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pan Am families know _ as do we all _ that the international
decision to accept a trial without Gadhafi even mentioned in the
indictments was motivated by those Libyan contracts. Money was what
our friends and allies settled for. Gadhafi got the rebuilding of
the Libyan economy he had smashed himself. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For reporting that the Blair government has evidence that
Gadhafi personally ordered the Pan Am bombing, the Sunday Times of
London got a formal warning that any follow-up story would result
in the punitive injunctions allowed by British law. No denials;
just the warning.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So far, the United States has not suspended the U.N.-ordered
sanctions it had supported. Good; we shall see. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sanctions are not imposed out of peeve but to restrain rogue
nations and for the protection of their chosen targets. So it's a
wonder to relatives of the murdered, and to me, that America's
public and journalists do not think more about Dec. 21, 1988,
particularly when they board an American plane, and about who owns
the bullet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
