<SLUG> BC-MA-SULLIVAN-KENNEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SULLIVAN SAYS OUSTING KENNEDY WOULD BE `UPSET OF CENTURY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Michael J. Sullivan, the Massachusetts district
attorney, who hinted this week at a campaign against Senator Edward
M. Kennedy, says he and national Republican officials recognized
his campaign would be a ``huge uphill battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, who met here with officials of the Republican National
Committee and the National Republican Senatorial Committee to size
up his chances, said party leaders, while not discouraging, were
``frank'' about his odds of winning the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no rose-colored glasses I'm wearing, and they're not
wearing any rose-colored glasses, either,'' he told reporters at
the National Republican Senatorial Committee NRSC headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he recognized that ousting Kennedy, who is in his
eighth term, ``would clearly be the upset of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan, a former state representative and a twice-elected
district attorney in Plymouth County, Mass., said he will make his
decision in the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Sources told the Globe earlier this week that Governor Paul
Cellucci and Lieutenant Governor Jane M. Swift had recruited
Sullivan to challenge the senior senator. If Sullivan decides to
run, he would be the first Republican candidate with substantial
political experience and backing to run against Kennedy since the
senator was first elected in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan also said he is unsure about raising the millions of
dollars he would need to mount a successful campaign against
Kennedy, who already has $2.4 million in his campaign chest.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he is confident he could raise at least $3.5
million for the race, with an additional $650,000 from the NRSC,
but he would need more than that to pose a formidable challenge to
Kennedy, who is expected to raise at least $10 million for his
reelection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge uphill battle,'' Sullivan said. ``This is the
classic David vs. Goliath campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   If he decides to run, Sullivan said, he will stress health care
for the elderly, education, crime prevention and taxes, but he has
not yet formed a solid campaign platform.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Sullivan said he would not criticize
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about Senator Kennedy,'' he said. ``This is about
who Mike Sullivan is.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he opposes abortion except in the case of rape,
incest, or to save the life of the mother; supports the death
penalty; and is against creating more gun-control laws. Instead, he
said he supports stronger enforcement of existing laws on illegal
possesion and use of guns.
</P>
</TEXT>
