u s BC-BKW-PERROT-KIDS-HNS &LR;      08-19 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PERROT-KIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERROT'S DEATH MAY HIT CHILDREN ESPECIALLY HARD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JEANNIE KEVER 
and DAVID BARRON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ As news of Kim Perrot's death spread Thursday, two
things became clear:
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a basketball fan to mourn, and public shock
over the death of someone so young and physically fit _ Perrot, a
nonsmoker, died of lung cancer at the age of 32 _ will be tempered
by admiration for what she achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Kids, especially pre-teen and teen-age girls, were core members
of Perrot's unofficial fan club, and this twin legacy of grief and
inspiration may hit them especially hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think children are really struck by the fact that here was
this wonderful, talented athlete, and she died of cancer,'' Houston
psychologist Elizabeth Dybell said. ``One of the most important
things for children that it brings to mind is that we're all
vulnerable. Even if you're in terrific physical shape, something
terrible can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But kids should also remember that what they loved most about
Perrot will live on, Dybell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lived her dream and went for the gusto and was totally
involved in her passion. That's what we have to remind kids about.
She may have died young, but look what she did in her short life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a message to all of us to go out and seize the day,
because you don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot was a long-shot as a sports hero, a basketball player who
was really too short for today's game. At only 5-foot-5, she wasn't
a draft pick when the WNBA began forming teams in 1997, and she had
to muscle her way onto the Houston Comets.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. She quickly became not only a star point guard, but
the team's emotional center.
</P>
<P>
   Kids everywhere could relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just personified somebody who is really scrappy, a hard
worker, a really good person,'' family therapist Teddy Melhart
Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot's connection to the community may have begun on the
court, but soon, she was everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke at schools and other public appearances, pushing her
message of physical fitness, education, persistence and saying no
to drugs. Even after announcing in February that she had been
diagnosed with lung cancer that had spread to her brain, she
remained active and visible, refusing to let surgery to remove a
brain tumor and a subsequent round of radiation treatments keep her
in isolation.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote a popular column in Yo!, the Chronicle's weekly
section for kids, a chatty celebration of sports and determination
and trying your best. There, she also wrote of her battle against
cancer, displaying the same tenacity that had worked so well for
her on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of positive things she taught us, and the
sadness and grief comes as such a natural part of it,'' Dybell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew Perrot say her delight in her fans was genuine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim just had such a joy for life,'' said Angela Blakeney,
communication manager for the Comets. ``She enjoyed meeting people,
whether young or old. The stories they would tell, the smiles they
would bring, flooded her heart and encouraged her to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA has made its players accessible as role models, and
that captured the imagination of many kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the kids a role model of practicing, working hard,''
Dybell said. ``They don't see the hours of practice ... the
injuries. But they do see that they can set a dream and make it
happen. Kim's life and the women's team say you can make something
happen. You don't have to be passive.''
</P>
<P>
   The joy she and her teammates brought to so many is sure to
deepen the sadness they feel upon her death.
</P>
<P>
   Kids might also be angry, Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a natural part of the grief process. `Why was she taken
so soon? She was so young, and she was so good. Why did she have to
die?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Parents sometimes make the mistake of brushing aside kids' anger
over death, Wright said. ``I think hearing that out helps the child
to process that.''
</P>
<P>
   The best way to help kids, or anyone, deal with grief is simply
to be willing to listen, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as parents we have to be aware of the strong feelings
children may have about death and ... their intense sadness,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot's death may spark memories of the deaths of family
members or even family pets, Wright said. For young children, it
may prompt fears of their own deaths, or the deaths of their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The key is to listen and be accepting, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And parents can acknowledge their own sense of loss, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say, `Yeah, I'm really sad, too. It's a sad day,'''
Wright said. ``The other thing is to acknowledge the loss, that
it's not right for her to be taken so soon, but (to say), `You can
carry her in your heart and always remember how wonderful she
was.'''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot would like that, Blakeney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her determination to live continued until the very end,'' she
said, ``and she would want the Comets fans and the people who
remember her to keep that in mind and to be inspired by the
strength that she had.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
