<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEK-ARCHBISHOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEK CHURCH LEADER IN US RESIGNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an unprecedent move Archbishop Spyridon resigned under
pressure Thursday as leader of the 1.5 million-member Greek
Orthodox Church of America after a bitter two-year campaign to oust
him by critics who claimed his authoritarian leadership alienated
too many of the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Spyridon is the first leader in the 77-year history of the
organized US Greek church forced to resign because of poor job
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old American-born prelate submitted his resignation
to Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew, the Istanbul-based spiritual
leader of the world's 218 million Orthodox Christians and the man
who appointed Spyridon three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bartholomew appointed Metropolitan Demetrios Trakatellis, 71,
who leads the Orthodox Church in Greece and was passed over as the
US archbishop in 1996, as Spyridon's replacement. A former
professor at Harvard University and at Hellenic College in
Brookline, Trakatellis is well-known to priests, bishops and other
US church leaders as a highly-regarded scholar.
</P>
<P>
   For Spyridon, the beginning of the internal revolt that led to
his departure began in 1997 when he fired the president and three
professors at Hellenic College _ the church's flagship institution
_ after they allegedly refused to cover up an alleged sexual
misconduct incident involving a student and a visiting priest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite growing pressure from church members, including
metropolitans, priests, and many wealthy Greek Americans, to oust
Spyridon, Bartholomew stood by the embattled prelate for months.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, Bartholomew was warned by American church
activists that if he did not do something about Spyridon the US
Greek Orthodox Church could split from Istanbul _ something that
would deal a devastating blow to the patriarch's authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek Orthodox Church is by far the biggest, richest and
most influential of the more than a dozen Orthodox Christian
churches in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   As word spread of Spyridon's resignation, which is effective
Aug. 30, his critics and supporters alike expressed relief that the
controversy that was tearing apart the American church may finally
come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am elated with the election of Metropolitan Demetrios as our
next archbishop, but I am saddened things turned out the way they
did for Bishop Spyridon,'' said Metropolitan Methodios, the head of
the Greek Orthodox diocese of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully it opens a new life to the Greek Orthodox Church of
America,'' added Methodios, who was one of five US bishops that
called for Spyridon's ouster earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   While his resignation letter never touches on the controversy
that engulfed much of his tenure, Spyridon did address in strong
language his many critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those few of every grade who during these past three years
have opposed this vital mission of the Church and have spared
little ordinance in an attack of words that has done far more
damage to our Greek Orthodox family than it has to those entrusted
with its leadership, I extend my heartfelt archpastoral
forgiveness,'' said Spyridon, who has been recalled to Turkey for
another assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Spyridon assumed his post amid high hopes that his American
upbringing would help him understand the sense of independence and
participatory democracy that had come to influence the US Greek
Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   But his actions against the four men at Hellenic College and the
way he lashed out against critics soon turned the hope into
widespread dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the leadership was inappropriate for our particular
curriculum,'' said Thomas Lelon, executive director of Greek
Orthodox American Goal, a group led by promient Greek Americans
that coordinated the crusade to oust Spyridon. ``When a leader
makes decision without the advice and consent of the people that
constitute the church that becomes difficult for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   But other church activists were more sympathetic toward
Spyridon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Archbishop Spyridon resigned because he thought it was
for the good of the American church. He was unable to end the
controversy involving his tenure,'' said Michael Krone, a Boston
attorney and defender of Spyridon. ``I know alot of people are
happy but I am not. I think it's kind of sad what happened _ a
controversy was created and it never went away.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spyridon, his critics say, only exacerbated the acrimony
within the church by what they say was some of his heavy handed
dealing with critics.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when the Reverend G. Stephanopoulos, dean of New
York's Holy Trinity Cathedral and the fatehr of former White House
aide George Stephanopoulos, publicly opposed Spyridon, the prelate
responded by stripping the priest of much of his authority.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to derail what they perceived as a system of
one-man rule, several dissidents filed lawsuits against the
archdiocese. The archdiocese responded by suing Goal to try and
prevent the group from using the archdiocese's mailing list. A
judge ruled against the church.
</P>
<P>
   But the feuding led to dozens of stories both in the Greek and
mainstream press that sullied the church's reputation and
embarrassed the Patriarch.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end for Spyridon, Greek Orthodox Church
activists say, came in January when Spyridon and the five US
metropolitans met with Bartholomew in Istanbul. While Bartholomew
encouraged them to work out their differences, tensions between
Spyridon and the prelates instead seemed to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when Spyridon was summoned to Istanbul again, the
American leader was given one month to work things out. But fears
that the US church was close to breaking away from Istanbul finally
forced Bartholomew's hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
