<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3371 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-VALUES-ART-1     08-19 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-VALUES-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE FAMILY VALUES ARE CONCERNED, DEMOCRATS APPEAR VULNERABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: The margin of error for the December and July polls conducted
by the Pew Research Center are not available.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Every few months, small groups of local Democratic
officials journey to special seminars to learn how to combat a
party vulnerability: doubts among voters that the Democrats embrace
mainstream family values.
</P>
<P>
   Under the auspices of the Democratic Leadership Council, a
centrist party group, Anita F. Gottlieb, a consultant, takes the
Democrats through a mental exercise designed to stop them from
speaking in the numbing jargon of program names and acronyms and
instead to explain policy goals with value-laden statements about
social ills and about right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gottlieb tells them to visualize a ``values tree.'' The
roots of the tree are their values. The trunk is policy goals and
the branches are programs. With the tree in mind to reinforce the
idea that policy goals should grow from values, they then write
speeches to explain the ideas of their programs.
</P>
<P>
   That the council feels the need to run such workshops says
something about a persistent difficulty facing Democrats as they
head into the next election. Political strategists say the public
once again sees the Republicans as the party of values, considering
them more trustworthy on a range of moral and ethical matters like
honesty, belief in God, belief in personal responsibility and
knowing right from wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, this turn of events could not be more
frustrating. In his re-election campaign, President Clinton
neutralized the long-standing Republican strength on moral issues
like religion and violence in movies and on television by putting
together a set of policies that added up to a secular family values
agenda for his party.
</P>
<P>
   Now, polls show that the Democrats' traditional weakness in this
area has returned. And strategists say that just as many
Republicans had predicted months ago, some of the party's problems
stem from the public backlash against President Clinton's behavior
in the Monica Lewinsky matter, particularly among the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception problem here that the Democrats have, I
think, on moral questions,'' said Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think certainly a lot of it has to do with the last year and
a half and you cannot discount that,'' Dodd said, referring to
Clinton's affair with Ms. Lewinsky and his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Pew Research Center for the People and the Press, a
nonpartisan group, found in a July poll that a greater number of
people _ 44 percent _ now think that the House did the right thing
in impeaching Clinton. That figure was at 35 percent last December
at the height of the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures, coming six months after the Senate trial ended
with Clinton's acquittal, cannot be reassuring to Democrats. At the
same time, presidential preference polls show that Vice President
Al Gore is consistently running 15 percentage points or more behind
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Democrats go into 2000 with advantages.
Congressional Democrats have a decided edge on issues ranging from
Medicare to health care to education. And, the Republican cry for
deep tax cuts has not caught on with the public, according to
recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   Many public opinion surveys show that the two parties are about
even when voters are asked whether they prefer the Republicans or
the Democrats running Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democrats' disadvantage on values could become
magnified, depending on the mood of the voters, who, because of the
good economy, have turned their attention elsewhere. At times this
year, most particularly after the airstrikes against Yugoslavia and
the shootings in Littleton, Colo., anxiety over the nation's moral
compass has surged as a voter concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find as I go around Connecticut the public is really more
concerned about the moral future of the country than the economic
future,'' said Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn. ``I think we have to
speak to that.''
</P>
<P>
   A June poll of 1,002 people, taken by a bipartisan team of
Celinda Lake, a Democratic pollster, and Ed Goeas, a Republican
pollster, showed the Democrats' weakness and their areas of
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which party in Congress better represented the values of
personal responsibility, voters chose Republicans by 44 percent to
22 percent. On ethics and honesty, they favored Republicans over
Democrats by 39 percent to 20 percent. On faith in God, they picked
the Republicans by 40 percent to 18 percent. And on knowing right
from wrong, they favored Republicans over Democrats by 35 percent
to 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Only when asked which party better represented the value of
community, did those surveyed select the Democrats, 39 percent to
33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll's margin of sampling error was plus or minus 3
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Political strategists differ on how much to attribute these
findings to disillusionment with Clinton. They also cite factors
like public concern with the war in Kosovo, the Republicans'
greater comfort with emphasizing God and religion, and lingering
public doubts dating from the 1960s over whether the Democrats
embrace mainstream values.
</P>
<P>
   Changing a long-standing image of a party takes time, said Ed
Kilgore, the policy director at the Democratic Leadership Council,
adding, ``I think you have to reprove yourself for two to three
administrations before you fundamentally change the perception of
the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the council's seminars held this year in Arizona, Florida,
Pennsylvania, Utah and Wisconsin, Kilgore said, ``It's a
revolutionary exercise for a lot of Democrats. It's important to
make it clear that your policy positions reflect values the public
shares and that you are not proposing programs as an end in
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are heading into the elections with strengths on
an array of issues not explicitly related to values. Asked in the
June poll which party in Congress would do a better job of
improving the health care system, voters selected Democrats over
Republicans 53 percent to 24 percent. On which party would better
improve education, the Democrats won 46 percent to 31 percent. On
which would strengthen Social Security, the Democrats led
Republicans 49 percent to 28 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
