<HEADLINE>
NERDY CAL TECH TOPS HARVARD IN MAGAZINE'S RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the revenge of the nerds.
</P>
<P>
   The widely-watched US News and World Report Best Colleges
rankings are out, and the establishment is in for a surprise: the
California Institute of Technology, self-professed school for
intense science types, is the nation's number one, knocking Harvard
off the pinnacle from which it has preened for all but two of the
last ten years.
</P>
<P>
   The annual release of the top 10 list prompted the usual griping
Thursday about the unfairness of ratings. But almost no one
questions their impact, on campus self-confidence as well as the
volume of applications. And on the often-overlooked Pasadena
campus, already graced by 27 Nobel Prizes, there was a sense of
winning another long-sought prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal Tech is a genuine national treasure, but it's not as well
known as it ought to be,'' said David Goodstein, a vice provost and
physics professor. ``The spotlight will be on us now. We're
delighted, happy and grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, the customary number one, officials sniffed that
rankings can be misleading _ a sentiment Goodstein freely admits to
expressing in past years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Precise rankings, we've always felt, are unfortunate,'' said
Bill Fitzsimmons, dean of admissions and financial aid. ``It's
always nice to be seen as among the leaders, but everyone is aware
that no matter what the ranking is, there can always be
discrepancies.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, which fell below
its arch rival Cal Tech for the first time, there were even more
playful jibes to explain the upset. ``Yeah, David Baltimore is a
great guy,'' said spokesman Ken Campbell, referring to the longtime
MIT researcher who left Cambridge two years ago to become president
of Cal Tech.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the rankings are based on a range of factors. When the
magazine started rating the schools in 1983, it looked only at
academic reputation. In 1987, it began considering factors like how
many students the school accepts and SAT scores, the ranking system
has been tweaked several times since.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Cal Tech benefitted from a change that emphasized
per-student spending (a stratospheric $192,000 for each of 900
undergraduates, compared to $81,000 at Harvard.) Every single one
of Cal Tech's incoming freshmen ranked in the top ten percent on
high school graduation, a feat unmatched by any other school on the
list. Its student/faculty ratio was also unmatched, at a rare 3 to
one, compared to 8 to 1 at Harvard,
</P>
<P>
   But the magazine also notes that Cal Tech is not for everyone.
It ranks high, too, on the list of the nation's worst party
schools. The campus, US News says, is ``beautiful'' but also
``intense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Party animals and philosophy lovers who can't stomach quantum
mechanics are unlikely to find personal or academic happiness,''
the magazine concedes.
</P>
<P>
   And true, the news that the 108-year-old private institution
would be ranked number one _ vaulted from number nine on last
year's list _ probably prompted one of the most exuberant displays
of campus spirit in recent memory. ``We're thinking we should get
some of those foam fingers with `We're Number One,' '' said Jill
Perry, director of media relations, ``Even though we don't have
football!''
</P>
<P>
   Various classifications of schools _ by cost, by fun potential,
even by Internet access _ have flourished over the past ten years,
often to college officials' dismay. International students consider
the rankings even more than their American counterparts, admissions
officials say. But US News boasts the original and still the most
broadly-read of the rankings. The Web site that publishes the list
gets 250 hits every second, beginning soon after the list is posted
at one minute after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   All this may work to Cal Tech's advantage. In past years,
Goodstein said he has come east to try to recruit students in
Connecticut and Massachusetts and New York. Most applied to MIT and
Harvard, and if they applied to Cal Tech and got accepted, they
rarely decided to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``They grow up in the shadows of those universities, and often
they didn't know anything about us,'' he said. ``This will
undoubtedly help us in admissions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzsimmons, though, at Harvard, joins scores of other
admissions officials who worry that students pay too much attention
to the rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analogy I would use would be class ranking,'' he said.
``Some people feel that it's absolutely critical to be number one
or number two or number three. In some cases, a college is actually
better off, they may get better students, looking below.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
