<HEADER>
A3373 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEMS-VALUES-ART-2NDTA     08-19 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-VALUES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: to 28 percent. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democrats have been working on several fronts to respond to
the public doubts. Gore, most notably, has been making a sustained
effort to focus on values and define his own character.
</P>
<P>
   He sounds remarkably like Bush when he declares that America
should be judged ``not merely by the value of our possessions but
the values we possess.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Bush called for more reliance on churches and
religious organizations, the vice president said these groups
should be eligible to receive federal money to help the needy.
</P>
<P>
   And in June he called Clinton's extramarital affair
``inexcusable,'' adding that ``particularly as a father I felt that
it was terribly wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats have aggressively sought to turn the
policy agenda to issues on which they believe they have the upper
hand. They have pushed Republicans into high-profile legislative
battles over gun control and regulation of managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   And in his opposition to the Republicans' $792 billion tax cut
plan, Clinton has led the Democrats in portraying the proposal as
an obstacle to reshaping the Medicare system and creating a new
prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two challenges,'' said Ms. Lake, who does polling
for the Gore campaign on women's issues. ``One is to talk about the
issues in values-oriented terms and two, to move the agenda from
values to these other issues because we are only going to have so
much credibility on values.''
</P>
<P>
   The exercise run by the Democratic Leadership Council is just
one way that Democrats are trying to teach their elected officials
to show that programs like their education proposals actually
reflect their party's values.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, for their part, say they have to be cautious in
capitalizing on the Democrats' vulnerability, so that their efforts
do not backfire as they have before.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign commercials that House Republicans ran last year
alluding to the Clinton scandal were widely judged to have
backfired, helping cost the Republicans five House seats. And much
of the party establishment has been struggling to get safely beyond
Pat Buchanan's fiery but divisive 1992 convention speech declaring
a cultural war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans have to be extremely careful,'' Goeas said. ``Very
often when they see declining moral values they get put in a box on
abortion or gay rights. But when people talk values they really
talk as much about civility in society and virtue in society.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Republican presidential contenders like Buchanan or
Gary Bauer or Alan Keyes, who are vying for the allegiance of the
Republicans' social conservatives, still determinedly take stands
against abortion or else make a rejection of homosexuality a plank
of their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But others like Bush, Elizabeth Dole and Sen. John McCain make a
more broad-brushed appeal to those concerned with the nation's
direction. They do not mention impeachment, but their allusions to
it are clear.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talks of showing that ``politics, after a time of tarnished
ideals, can be higher and better.'' Mrs. Dole says, ``We've been
let down _ and by people we should have been able to look up to.''
And McCain says that to fight cynicism among young people ``we must
first challenge ourselves to give them an example worth
emulating.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, the Republican goal is to let the eventual
presidential nominee set the party's themes and do nothing to allow
Democrats to change the focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for Republicans in Congress,'' said Linda
DiVall, a Republican pollster, ``is not to do anything that upsets
the advantage we have on morals, integrity and ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans have passed a number of measures highlighting
their conservative cultural stands. They have approved a
Constitutional amendment against flag-burning, taken a stand to
allow the Ten Commandments to be posted in schools, passed a
measure prohibiting state and local governments from placing a
``substantial burden'' on a person's exercise of religion, and
approved a bill to make it a federal crime for an adult to take a
minor across state lines for an abortion in order to circumvent a
parental-notification law in the girl's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, of these measures will become law. And strategists
said they were likely to become campaign issues only on a
district-by-district basis, primarily in conservative areas of the
South.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly values is a major problem for the Democrats,'' said
one House Republican strategist. ``But because it's a major problem
for Democrats, that doesn't mean you launch an expensive national
campaign on this one issue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
