<HEADER>
A3383 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-DRUGS20-COX     08-19 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DRUGS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Drug use questions detract from Bush's message in Ohio
 &HT;    By William Hershey and Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Questions about illegal drugs dogged Texas Gov.
George W. Bush on Thursday as he brought his presidential campaign
to Ohio for two days of hunting for votes and money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked about my background all I'm going to talk about
it,'' said Bush, 53, shortly after he arrived here. ``I told people
I made some mistakes years ago. I did some things when I was much
younger ... I've learned from my mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's answer, repeated several times later during a Columbus
news conference, marked a retreat from a fuller statement he made
earlier in the day in Roanoke, Va., as he confronted what appeared
to be the first real media crisis of his campaign for the
Republican nomination and, he hopes, president.
</P>
<P>
   In Roanoke, he said, in effect, that he had not used illegal
drugs in the past 25 years since 1974 when he turned 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only could I pass the background check and the standards
applied to today's White House, but I could have passed the
background check and the standards applied on the most stringent
conditions when my dad was President of the United States _ a 15
year period,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 years before his father became president in 1989 would
have taken him to 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Bush declined to give the fuller explanation in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   In Roanoke, Bush referred to a question he answered on Wednesday
about whether he would conduct background checks for his staff at
the White House and whether he could pass such a test.
</P>
<P>
   His answer about himself and his ability to go beyond the
current standards appeared to refer to normal FBI background
checks, which go back seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration, however, requires the FBI to ask
applicants about drug use since their 18th birthday. Asked in
Columbus to state the he had not used illegal drugs since he was
18, Bush declined.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Tucker, Bush's campaign press secretary, said that all
presidential administrations ask potential staff members about drug
use dating back to their 18th birthday, but don't automatically
disqualify those who answer ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that when Gov. Bush's father was president, the senior
Bush disqualified many applicants with drug use during a 15-year
period.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said some people may like his answer to the drug question
and others may not. ``If they don't they'll find somebody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he didn't answer the question more directly, Bush
replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to send a signal to children that whatever I may
have done is OK. I think people in the baby boomer generation ought
to stand up and say drugs destroy your life and using alcohol will
make it hard to realize the American dream. I think that's the
message politicians ought to be sending. That's the message I'm
sending.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that when it comes to questions about politicians'
private lives, ``I believe it's important to say enough is enough.
I don't want to participate in national politics if this is what
it's coming to.'' Even as he said he was drawing the line, Bush
picked his own spot to cross over it. When asked about drug use and
his service as a pilot in the Texas National Guard before 1974, he
said: ``I never would have done anything to jeopardize myself. I
got airborne and I got on the ground very successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   The flare-up over Bush's possible drug use once again
interjected questions about a candidate's personal life into
presidential campaigns, as happened with Gary Hart's in 1988
campaign over alleged womanizing, and then-candidate Bill Clinton
in 1992 over charges of draft dodging and philandering.
</P>
<P>
   The drug use questions detracted from Bush's visit to The
Enrichment Association of Community Healing, a faith-based program
in a predominantly black east Columbus neighborhood. TEACH helps
neighborhood residents develop skills that move them from welfare
to work. TEACH President John H. Gregory said it is unfortunate
that prying into Bush's private life diverted attention from the
positive message Bush was trying to highlight.
</P>
<P>
   University of Dayton political scientist David Ahern said such
prying ``hasn't been appropriate for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean that it isn't something that will sell
newspapers and the newspapers will hold on to it for dear life,''
said Ahern, who added that his indictment also applied to broadcast
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living in an age of tabloid journalism,'' he said. ``It
really takes the politics out of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio Secretary of State J. Kenneth Blackwell, national chairman
for publisher Steve Forbes' Republican presidential campaign, said
Forbes has said he did not use illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   After years of defending President Clinton against an assortment
of charges, Democrats were in the unusual position of watching a
Republican deal with questions about his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anytime a person runs for president of the United
States as we have done now for over 200 years, that there is no
such thing as private life. Whatever goes on in your life is
subject to questions by the public,'' said Ohio Democratic Chairman
David Leland.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bob Taft, chairman of Bush's Ohio campaign, in an interview
separate from the Bush news conference, said that he thinks
questions about Bush's private life are a ``sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bush is to be in Akron to tour the Haven of Rest
Ministries and to attend a fund-raiser organized by Alex
Arshinkoff, Summit County Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
