<SLUG> BC-US-DEFICIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER SPENDING BOOSTS US TRADE DEFICIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US trade deficit climbed to a new high in June as voracious
American consumers riding a strong economy bought cheap imports
from China, Japan, and Latin America at record rates.
</P>
<P>
   According to US Commerce Department figures released Thursday,
goods and services purchased from other countries exceeded exports
by $24.6 billion in June, shocking analysts who had expected the
gap to be $4 billion smaller. The June figure is up from $21.2
billion in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a product of a very strong US economy and one that
doesn't seem to be slowing down any time soon,'' Rick Egelton,
deputy chief economist at Bank of Montreal and Harris Bank in
Toronto told Bloomberg News. It's an economy that's ``sucking in
imports at a tremendous rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first six months of the year, the trade deficit
totaled $118.1 billion. That is up from $75.3 billion during the
first six months of 1998, and leaves the deficit on course to top
last year's record of $164 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While the news is a symptom of seemingly endless domestic
prosperity, the dollar tumbled in world markets as foreign
merchants sold off dollars for their own currencies. The falling
dollar sparked fears of inflation, triggering a 28-point decline in
the Dow Jones industrial average, which closed at 10,963.84. The
falling currency also signals an almost certain interest rate hike
when the Federal Reserve's Open Market Committee meets next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tightening in August is pretty much locked in,'' Michael
Englund, chief economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's MMS in Belmont,
Calif., told Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the deficit, economies around the world,
weakened by Asia's economic collapse and a slowdown in Europe, made
imports cheaper at a time when demand in the United States was
growing, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists differ over what the deficit portends for the
nation's economic health. Some say burgeoning trade deficits cannot
be endured long-term because they must be financed by inflows of
foreign capital in the form of purchases of US stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are borrowing as a nation to consume so it does raise a
long-term financing question,'' Clyde Prestowitz Jr., president of
the Economic Strategy Institute, told the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Prestowitz acknowledged people have been warning of a calamity
from a growing trade deficit since the early 1980s, when the trade
deficit was about one-tenth as large as it is now.
</P>
<P>
   Other economists say the current high trade deficit is a
reflection of US prosperity, and American consumers' huge taste for
cheaper foreign goods has helped keep inflation in check during a
period of long expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surge of US imports is healthy for the world economy,''
KeyCorp economist Ken Mayland told the Post. ``Imports are acting
as a safety valve for the US economy, venting powerful domestic
demand pressures, thereby thwarting the return of inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   US exports did grow slightly to $78.4 billion during the month,
led by gains in exports of cars, food, and industrial supplies. But
the 3.9 percent surge in imports overwhelmed those gains as
Americans spent a record $103 billion on foreign goods, mostly
computers, cellular phones, imported cars, and industrial supplies,
the Commerce Department said.
</P>
<P>
   Deficits with Japan and China both widened in June. The gap with
Japan grew to $6.3 billion from $5.3 billion in May. The deficit
with China increased to $5.7 billion from $5.3 billion the month
before.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit with members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries rose to $2 billion from $1.6 billion in May and
$633 million in June 1998. The United States imports more than half
its crude oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
