<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-9     08-19 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMONSTRATION AGAINST MILOSEVIC SHOWS DIVISIONS AMONG OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also YUGOSLAVIA-SCENE) 
(rk) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Tens of thousands of people gathered on a
hot Thursday night in front of the federal Parliament to demand the
resignation of President Slobodan Milosevic, but they heard an
extremely mixed set of messages from rival leaders of the
democratic opposition here on how to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of at least 50,000 people _ some estimates exceeded
100,000 _ represented the largest anti-Milosevic rally since NATO's
air war against Yugoslavia, which forced Belgrade's troops out of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposition's rivalries and clashing strategies were also
on display, with the drama of the night being the effort of Vuk
Draskovic, leader of the Serbian Renewal Movement, the largest
party in the opposition, to hijack a rally he had sworn he would
not attend.
</P>
<P>
   In a clumsy bit of political fakery booed by many in the crowd,
Draskovic, who had withdrawn his name from the list of speakers,
essentially crashed the rally, coming on stage surrounded by
bodyguards, in response, he said, to the demands of his supporters
in the crowd. His ploy was an almost exact re-creation of a sudden
appearance by Milosevic at a rally on the same spot 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While Draskovic was almost forced by the size of the turnout to
attend, he also criticized many of the ideas of other opposition
leaders, saying that early elections under fair conditions were the
only sensible way to change Serbia and finally oust Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic commands more voters than any other opposition
politician, up to 18 percent of the vote in recent polls, more than
those who favor the parties of Milosevic and his wife, Mirjana
Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians had been wary of calling a rally in
sophisticated Belgrade, where huge street protests against
Milosevic in 1996 an 1997 failed to bring him down. But the numbers
Thursday night were enough to give the opposition a lift, showing
the disgust of many people at their current isolation and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   But the people are also disillusioned by the divisions among
opposition leaders, they said, and those divisions were on clear
display.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of the rally, the Serbian Orthodox Church and the
Group 17, a set of economists and professionals, are calling for
Milosevic to resign and appoint a transitional government of
experts to serve for a year and then organize new elections.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Democratic Party, Zoran Djindjic, Draskovic's
prime rival, called for Milosevic and the government to resign
within 15 days or face mass protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are still there after 15 days, then Serbia will go out
into the streets, not only in Belgrade, but in all towns, in 50
towns on the same day,'' Djindjic said. ``Everybody will go out
into the streets with one single message _ we will stay here until
you go. It's either Milosevic or Serbia, there can be no third
solution. This time we will go to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   But Draskovic heaped scorn on the idea of a transitional
government of experts _ ``of people no one had heard of a week
ago'' _ and said that it was clear now that Milosevic would never
agree to it. Draskovic also scoffed at the idea of a new government
formed in the streets, through civil unrest, saying: ``It's dust in
the eyes of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic then called for early elections in November, as
Milosevic's spokesmen are themselves suggesting, in their own
effort to divide the opposition. Draskovic then urged street
pressure to ensure early elections if Milosevic does not grant
them.
</P>
<P>
   And he called on ``all responsible leaders of the opposition''
to support his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   One speaker for the Alliance for Change called for a new
demonstration in Belgrade on Aug. 28, while another, for the Group
17, called for a new demonstration here on Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the rally, Zoran Stankovic said: ``The only real message
is change. It's time for this government to go.'' But he said that
Milosevic only benefited ``when the opposition leaders speak in so
many voices.''
</P>
<P>
   One important political leader of the Alliance for Change
coalition, Nenad Canak, leader of the League of Social Democrats of
Vojvodina, said in an interview: ``The rally was fine concerning
the number of people and their energy. But it was not OK in terms
of the absence of vision, of how to focus this energy in a serious
way.''
</P>
<P>
   As the rallygoers gathered, government officials continued to
float the idea of early Serbian elections, perhaps as early as the
first week of November, creating further divisions among the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Change is not ready for elections and not
especially eager for them, so the government would be calling its
bluff. Draskovic, however, favors early elections to capitalize on
his better polling numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But new elections would not affect the position of Milosevic,
whose single, four-year term as Yugoslav president runs through
July 2001. While the opposition is calling for his resignation or
removal, early elections may divert the population from that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Normally elections for the Serbian Parliament and municipalities
would take place in 2001, while federal parliamentary elections
would take place in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult for the self-styled ``democratic
opposition'' to oppose new elections, though its leaders would like
supervision of any vote by outside observers from the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe and a freer, more open
media, especially television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elections are the best way to sober political drunks,''
Milosevic's party spokesman, Ivica Dacic, said Thursday. ``Our
stand is that there are many more important things than elections.
But if the other political parties say elections are necessary, we
are ready to go to elections. But they want to come to power
without elections.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
