<HEADLINE>
HAMILTON FEELING COMPETITIVE FOR MT. WASHINGTON CLIMB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might be early in the morning, and it might be hot, but Tyler
Hamilton will have plenty to smile about when he prepares to
bicycle up Mt. Washington Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Hamilton won the race two years ago, and set a
course record with his time of 51 minutes 56 seconds. For another,
he just got home from Copenhagen, where he won the Tour of Denmark
five-day stage race that finished Sunday. Hamilton took the lead
when he won the time trial last Saturday, 50 seconds better than
Denmark's Rolf Sorensen. Hamilton finished 13th in last month's
Tour de France, won by US Postal Service teammate Lance Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's race, which starts at 7:30, covers 7.6 miles with a
12-percent grade. Riders don't win anything _ just a medal that
shows they finished _ unless the course record is broken. The man
or woman who accomplishes that is given an Audi.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how he finishes, Hamilton will stay on the move. He is
scheduled to fly to Chicago Sunday to ride in the national
criterium championships, then return home briefly before heading
back to Europe to race in the three-week Tour of Spain, followed by
the world championships.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who lives in Spain for part of the year but is from
Brookline, Mass., said being back in the States is good because he
can be with his wife, Haven. And when he goes on training rides,
he's gotten more attention as he pedals through Littleton and
Concord, Mass., out to Wachusett Mountain and back. ``I guess
because people notice the Postal Service jersey,'' he said. `But it
doesn't feel normal, because I'm never here. So it's still hard
because I can't really kick back, I still have important races to
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
