<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3397 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-2     08-19 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BELGRADE: without elections. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vojislav Seselj, leader of the ultra-nationalist Radical Party
that now helps rule both Serbia and Yugoslavia, said separately
Thursday that he favored early elections to resolve Serbia's
post-Kosovo troubles. He said there was no agreement with other
ruling parties to call them, but there was a deal to hold them if
the opposition wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are even going so far as to say, `Let the opposition
parties name a date for the elections and we will call them,''' he
said. Seselj then suggested that local elections come first _ since
the opposition has its only power base in cities across Serbia won
in local elections in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   They only took their seats after massive street protests against
election fraud forced Milosevic to back down _ while saving his own
seat, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic's power base is the city of Belgrade, with its
powerful television station, Studio B. His rivals believe he would
do almost anything to retain the station.
</P>
<P>
   So to divide the opposition further, government officials leaked
a story that Draskovic had secretly met Milosevic on Monday to
discuss early elections and to agree not to speak at the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic angrily denied the entire story, as did his top aides,
one of whom said ``it would be idiotic'' to have had such a
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic aides suggested the leak was from Djindjic. Whatever
the truth, the leak succeeded in further poisoning the
relationship, if that were possible, between Draskovic and
Djindjic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is a master political tactician,'' said one senior
Alliance official . ``He's great at changing the subject and buying
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, early elections are a serious risk for Milosevic. The
government, whose support is weak after the loss of Kosovo, could
lose its majority in the Serbian Parliament if the opposition could
ever mount a united, professional campaign. And there is said to be
a debate inside the government about the wisdom of early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior government officials privately expressed confidence
Thursday that they would win a majority or could create one,
despite all their problems, while some senior opposition officials
also believe, with despair, that Milosevic, his wife and Seselj
could retain power in a coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting longer, until winter bites hard and the country is
inevitably short of heat and electricity due to inefficiency,
sanctions and NATO airstrikes, could only harm the government's
standing.
</P>
<P>
   The government had made various efforts, both subtle and crude,
to cut down the size of the rally. Wednesday night, state
television announced the arrest of a Montenegrin man possessing ``a
highly explosive device'' with a timer and warned of other possible
bombing attacks at ``massive public gatherings,'' urging caution to
citizens and especially to parents.
</P>
<P>
   The government ordered the payment of overdue pensions for
Thursday and moved the televising of a popular lottery program from
Saturday night to Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the police did not interfere with what was a peaceful rally,
and they were not much in evidence, though riot police were
stationed in buildings should they have been needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
