<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPT. DISPUTES TIMES ARTICLE ON BOSNIA GRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: See also CORRECTION-BOSNIA-CORRUPTION-NYT) 
(pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said Thursday that
a New York Times article about corruption in Bosnia left readers
with the misimpression that $1 billion in foreign aid had been
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   In lengthy remarks at his daily briefing at the State
Department, Rubin said that the article, which appeared on the
front page of The Times on Aug. 17, referred to a report that does
not exist and lumped together money lost by foreign aid agencies
with far larger sums lost either through misuse of Bosnian public
funds or uncollected taxes.
</P>
<P>
   During the briefing, Rubin said that The Times article had hurt
the Clinton administration's efforts to gain support for foreign
aid in Congress because people had drawn the conclusion that an
enormous amount of foreign aid money had been lost in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Rosenthal, The Times' foreign editor, said: ``The article
drew a distinction, although perhaps not forcefully enough, between
foreign and Bosnian public funds. Rubin contacted us about a long
list of what he considered to be factual errors in our article.
After a lengthy review, we decided to print a correction of a few
errors in tomorrow's Times.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing Mr. Rubin said or our review caused us to question the
basic premise of the article, which is that investigators in the
Office of the High Representative in Bosnia believe that widespread
corruption has taken place,'' Rosenthal said. ``These conclusions
were contained in many thousands of pages of bound volumes from
which American investigators attached to the OHR read to our
correspondent during an interview in Sarajevo.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra Stiglmayer, the OHR spokeswoman, was quoted by The
Associated Press on Wednesday as saying that the report in The New
York Times was ``largely correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Paul Klein, who heads the U.N. mission in Bosnia, wrote
an article for the Sarajevo publication Dnevni Avaz on June 16
saying that ``hundreds of millions'' in the local currency,
exchangeable for German marks, ``are disappearing from public funds
every year.'' Klein also referred to a ``Federation Financial
Police report containing a weighty 4,000 pages of evidence'' about
corruption in the canton of Tuzla.
</P>
</TEXT>
