<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN PRESIDENTIAL CONTENDER ADMITS TEXAS STUDENT IS HIS
DAUGHTER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexican voters, who will choose a president next
year in the most democratic elections ever held in this country,
are getting a chance early in the campaign to decide how much they
care about candidates' personal transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida Ochoa, a leading contender for the governing
party's nomination, acknowledged Thursday that he has a daughter
out of wedlock and that her mother works in the Mexican consulate
in El Paso, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials said Labastida, 57, admitted that he is the
father of Paloma Labastida, a 21-year-old student at the University
of Texas at El Paso, in response to a report that appeared
Wednesday in Norte newspaper in Ciudad Juarez, the Mexican border
town directly across from El Paso. Labastida was never married to
her mother, Alma Rosa Chavira, who works in the consulate providing
support services for Mexicans in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chavira was transferred to the consulate in February of this
year, three months before Labastida resigned from his job as
interior minister, the most powerful cabinet post, and announced
his run for the presidential nomination from the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI. She and her daughter had been living
in Mexico City, according to university registration records in El
Paso.
</P>
<P>
   While four contenders are vying to represent the PRI, Labastida
is believed to be President Ernesto Zedillo's choice for the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in his campaign said Labastida's wife and other
children have long known that Paloma was his daughter, and he has
maintained a ``close relationship'' with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He recognized that daughter many years ago. That's why she has
his last name,'' one campaign official said. He said that Labastida
had taken pains to keep her existence from the public at the
request of Ms. Chavira.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials said that Ms. Chavira had a long career
working for the government and denied that Labastida had used his
influence to secure her a public job, or pressured her to leave
Mexico in advance of his primary run.
</P>
<P>
   But the Foreign Relations Ministry, which sent Ms. Chavira to El
Paso, did not provide any information about Ms. Chavira's career or
qualifications for work in the consulate. The ministry referred all
questions to the consul in El Paso, Armando Ortiz Rocha, who said
he said he knew nothing about Ms. Chavira's professional
background.
</P>
<P>
   He did say that she is a ``serious, honest and highly efficient
employee.'' He added that he knew of no special circumstances
surrounding her transfer to El Paso and said she receives the same
salary, about $3,000 a month, as other employees at the lowest rung
of the consulate's administration.
</P>
<P>
   He said Ms. Chavira had been the victim of ``persecution by
unscrupulous journalists.''He said a report by the newspaper Norte
that he had threatened to fire employees who discussed Ms.
Chavira's presence was ``absolutely false.''
</P>
<P>
   The Norte reporter, Rafael Nunez, discovered in a brief
telephone conversation with Ms. Chavira that she, in contrast to
virtually all other consular officials, did not speak English. In
response to a direct question from Nunez, Ms. Chavira denied that
she had a daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Paloma Labastida left blank the sections of her university
registration form where she was asked to give the names of her
father and mother.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, when Mexican presidents enjoyed the absolute power
of monarchs during their single six-year terms and hand-picked
their own successors, extra-marital affairs, and mixing private and
public business, were considered routine prerogatives. One former
president, Jose Lopez Portillo, installed his lover, Rosa Luz
Alegria, in a cabinet position.
</P>
<P>
   But as the voters' influence has grown, top-ranking Mexican
politicians have become more discreet. Zedillo leads a quiet family
life out of public view.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
