<HEADER>
A3403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-COCAINE20-COX     08-19 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COCAINE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush edges closer to answer on cocaine
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, moving the line in the sand
but declining to erase it, got more specific Thursday about when he
didn't use illegal drugs but continued to refuse to say when _ and
if _ he ever did.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Roanoke, Va., Bush, now 53, indicated he has not
used illegal drugs since he was 28. Beyond and before that, he's
not saying. Bush has acknowledged he drank too much until he gave
it up at age 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 20 years ago, I did some things. ... I made some mistakes
and I learned from those,'' Bush said. ``That's all I intend to
talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, possession of cocaine in Texas was a second-degree
felony punishable by up to 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the drug question has become the first thing in his
presidential campaign to compete with the message of compassionate
conservatism he is presenting to supporters and contributors at
events across the country. The drug question has become a drumbeat,
with reporters asking it repeatedly in recent days at news
conferences, on talk shows and in editorial columns _ even though
no one has produced evidence that Bush has ever used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   By not answering, Bush hopes to change the tone and tenor of
American politics, though he acknowledged that it ``may cost me
votes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to tell people that we need to clean up the
process,'' Bush said Thursday. ``I am going to tell people that the
politics of personal destruction has got to end. I am going to tell
people I made mistakes and that I have learned from my mistakes.
And if they like it, I hope they give me a chance. And if they
don't like it, they can go find somebody else to vote for _ that's
the wonderful thing about democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has steadfastly refused to answer questions about whether
he has ever used cocaine. But in the past two days, he has answered
some specific questions about whether he used cocaine during
certain times in his life.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Bush said he could meet the seven-year standard
currently used to measure prospective federal employees seeking
high-level security clearance. On Thursday in Virginia, Bush said
he could have been cleared under the background checks his father
used when he was president from 1989-1993. The elder Bush asked top
aides if they had used illegal drugs in the previous 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only could I have passed in today's White House, I could
have passed the standards applied under the most stringent
conditions when my dad was president, a 15-year period,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyden Gray, White House counsel for President Bush, said
Thursday the younger Bush _ an adviser to his father but never on
the government payroll _ was not asked to undergo a background
check while his father was president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it was not disqualifying,'' Gray said of the
background check on drug use. ``There were legions of people in the
Bush administration who had used illegal drugs, but for whom it was
not disqualifying because it was in the distant past.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, when he begin a stint with the National Guard, Bush
signed a statement saying he had not been ``addicted to the use of
habit-forming drugs such as narcotics or barbiturates.''
</P>
<P>
   The persistent press questions about Bush's possible drug use
have become the first thing to force Bush to detour from the
message on which he wants to focus. That message includes a warning
to children to avoid drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be governor too, but you've got to make the right
choices,'' he told kids Thursday at a Roanoke youth center. ``When
someone says drugs are cool, you've got to say drugs are not
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   But in downtown Roanoke, the drug question was toted around by a
man with a one-word sign: ``Snort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just answer the question. Did you do it? Don't feed the
frenzy, just answer the question,'' the man yelled.
</P>
<P>
   The same advice came Thursday from Bruce Gronbeck, a University
of Iowa professor of communication studies, who said the drug
question will cloud Bush's campaign until he answers it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as journalists pursue it, as long as it is an issue,
it is going to dog him,'' Gronbeck said. ``And the longer it dogs
him, the more important it becomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gronbeck said, however, that Bush will find a very forgiving
public if the answer to the drug question is a long-ago yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public will forgive past transgressions, but they won't
forgive incompetency,'' he said, predicting that Bush will be seen
by some as an incompetent politician if he doesn't answer the
question in an effort to make it go away.
</P>
<P>
   All other major presidential candidates have said they have
never used cocaine. Most have not questioned Bush's refusal to
answer the question. Some have been more aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Governor Bush is making a big mistake in not settling
the issue and getting it behind him,'' said Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch.
``Why not just say you didn't, if you didn't? And if he did, say
why, and how he overcame it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Texas voters, the story line is familiar. In the 1990
gubernatorial race, provoked by Democratic candidate Jim Mattox's
allegations, reporters continuously asked Ann Richards, who also
was seeking the Democratic nomination, if she had ever used
cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Richards, candid about her past as an alcoholic, steadfastly
declined to say whether she ever used illegal drugs. Richards won
the nomination and the election. In 1994, then-challenger Bush
declined to make the question an issue in his race against
Richards.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
