u i BC-CORRECTION-BOSNIA-COR     08-19 0339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTION-BOSNIA-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
 
(Eds.: Newspapers that used BC-BOSNIA-CORRUPTION-NYT, datelined
SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina, by Chris Hedges, which moved Aug. 16,
may wish to use the following correction.)  
(Eds.: See also tonight's story, BOSNIA-CORRUPTION, moved in `i'
news file) 
(pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORRECTION:
</P>
<P>
   The opening paragraph of a front-page article on Tuesday about
an international investigation of widespread corruption in Bosnia
referred incompletely to the losses estimated at $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   According to the anti-fraud unit of the Office of the High
Representative, which is the international agency helping to carry
out the 1995 peace agreement for Bosnia, at least $20 million of
that total was in foreign aid from a variety of countries. But the
vast majority of the money was either stolen from Bosnian public
funds or lost through Bosnian officials' failure to collect taxes,
either through corruption or mismanagement. These specifics
appeared later in the article.
</P>
<P>
   Those conclusions, among others, were drawn from thousands of
pages of case files prepared by the Federation Financial Police, a
Bosnian law-enforcement agency supervised by the Office of the High
Representative. Two American members of the anti-fraud unit of the
Office of the High Representative discussed the case files with a
correspondent for The Times and read from them during an interview.
</P>
<P>
   The article also referred imprecisely to a file of 4,000 pages
that dealt with Tuzla. The jurisdiction covered was the Canton of
Tuzla, not the city, which is part of the canton.
</P>
<P>
   Through an editing error, the article also characterized the tax
revenues of the Muslim-Croat Federation incorrectly. It indeed
raises revenue, but falls short of its budget.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial, based on the article, also referred imprecisely to
the loss of $1 billion. It should have said that total included
Bosnian public funds along with international aid.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Times News Service. Aug. 19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
