<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-HALL20-COX     08-19 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-HALL20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball greats to enter Braves Hall of Fame
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thirty-three years ago, Atlanta took possession of a
major league baseball franchise. Today, the Atlanta Braves
recognize what all that really means.
</P>
<P>
   The charter class of the Braves Hall of Fame will be inducted
this afternoon at Turner Field, left-hander Warren Spahn, third
baseman Eddie Mathews, right fielder Hank Aaron and right-hander
Phil Niekro all installed in the franchise's new tribute to its
past.
</P>
<P>
   For the club, the Hall of Fame is a place to show off more than
120 years of history spanning three cities, four ballparks and some
1,400 players who have worn a Braves uniform. Yet for the players,
a designated Braves hall means something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played for the Boston Braves, the Milwaukee Braves and when
the club moved to Atlanta, I felt like we were players without our
alma mater,'' said Spahn, 79. ``This makes me feel like we are a
part of the Braves organization.''
</P>
<P>
   The induction ceremony will be held in the park's monument grove
area and is expected to draw 400. The hall itself will be quartered
within the Braves Museum underneath the left field stands.
</P>
<P>
   Sports artist Bart Forbes was commissioned to produce oil
portraits of the first quartet, which will hang in the hall. Each
inductee will also be commemorated in a plaque to be installed in a
walkway leading into the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted to be one of the first people to be put in the
Braves hall of fame,'' said Spahn.
</P>
<P>
   The first class was a no-brainer. Though 42 players now in the
National Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y., played for the
Braves at one time, only four of those spent the bulk of their
careers with the organization. Those four were on the same
Milwaukee roster for just one season _ 1964 _ when the franchise
had ebbed from the championship teams of the late '50s and had
entered the financial slide that led to the move to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   One name conspicuously missing from the group was removed by
special request. The team had originally included center fielder
Dale Murphy to go in with the same group but the two-time National
League MVP asked if his induction might be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Currently serving on a Mormon mission in Boston, Murphy would
not be able to travel to Atlanta for the ceremony and the Braves
agreed to put off his induction until 2000, when he could take
part.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the charter inductees will stand up against any
team in the majors:
</P>
<P>
   _ Aaron: Baseball's all-time home run king is in the midst of a
special celebration summer, commemorating the 35th anniversary of
his record 715th homer. Though 755 remains his most conspicuous
number, Aaron also set the all-time marks for games played,
at-bats, total bases and RBI while accumulating a .305 career
average. (Cooperstown election: 1982).
</P>
<P>
   _ Mathews: He piled up nine straight 30-home run seasons en
route to becoming just the seventh player ever to reach 500. No
other Brave played in Boston, Milwaukee and Atlanta and Mathews
later returned here to manage. Philadelphia's Mike Schmidt might
have passed him for most homers by a third baseman (548) but Ty
Cobb never told Schmidt he had a perfect swing. That's what he told
Mathews (Cooperstown election: 1978).
</P>
<P>
   _ Niekro: Originally a free agent who took eight years before
landing a spot in the rotation, Niekro's 314 wins rank him 14th on
the all-time list. He owns virtually every Atlanta pitching record
and for many of the dark seasons in club history, provided the best
reasons for fans to come to the park. He finished 44 games over
.500, perhaps his grandest accomplishment of all, given some of the
clubs he played with. (Cooperstown election: 1997).
</P>
<P>
   _ Spahn: No left-hander did it better, Spahn's 363 victories the
most recorded by any lefty in history. He won 20 games 13 times,
including a series of six straight 20-win seasons, and still holds
the NL mark for career innings (5,243 2/3). Both his no-hitters
came after his 39th birthday. Somehow, he won the Cy Young only
once. (Cooperstown election: 1973).
</P>
<P>
   This first group was selected by the Braves' front office,
though the selection and timing of the ceremonies are still in
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple things we have not determined yet,'' said
Bob Wolfe, the team's senior vice president for administration.
``One, we expect this to be an annual induction but we don't know
that we'll continue to do it in August each year. We might
ultimately determine that it's best to do it in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we also have to determine how to go forward with the
selection process. We just wanted to get this first one behind us
first.''
</P>
<P>
   And the timing of the first one couldn't be better, for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pull for 'em. I've got some favorites,'' Spahn said. ``I
know Ryan Klesko by doing a card show with him. Chipper Jones I've
always admired. And Greg Maddux is definitely my favorite pitcher
in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
