<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graziani on hot seat
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ The Falcons are going to keep three
quarterbacks on the final roster, and Tony Graziani is one of three
on the current roster.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem to indicate that Graziani has a good chance to be
around to pick up his $325,000 salary this season. But he's not
assuming anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year, (coaches) have less and less patience for you, and
if you don't get the job done, they'll find someone who will,''
Graziani said. ``I'm not the new guy they need to check out
anymore. I've been here three years, and it's time for me to step
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-2, 215-pound reserve will get a chance Saturday night
against Baltimore. After starter Chris Chandler plays a possession
or two, the left-handed Graziani will get most, and perhaps all, of
the remaining time under center.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves has said Graziani is pressing Danny Kanell for
the right to backup Chandler. Graziani threw several nice passes
Thursday, but he's been erratic since training camp started July
29. ``I go out there and try to learn as much as I can,'' he said.
``It seems like every day ... something surprises me that
shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziani added 12 pounds by working out between his rookie
season, when he was drafted in the seventh round out of Oregon, and
last year.
</P>
<P>
   He started at Carolina as a rookie but was pulled at halftime
after completing four of 18 passes in the rain. Two interceptions
helped the Panthers win 21-12. He finished the season with a 3.7
passer rating.
</P>
<P>
   In his one start last year, Nov. 29 at St. Louis, he directed an
11-play, 54-yard drive as the Falcons took a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But he finished 8-of-18 for 108 yards and again was pulled at
halftime. His final play, as the Falcons were driving, was an
ill-advised pass across the field _ off one of his many scrambles.
It was intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani finished the season with a 42.4 passer rating. For his
career, his rating is 24.4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to be more consistent,'' he said. ``There's so much
to learn in this league that you've got to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell, who has a career rating of 66.1 and 20 starts in three
seasons with the Giants, got lukewarm reviews after last Friday's
35-31 win over Detroit. Two interceptions stood out.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, it'll be Graziani's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those unspoken things everybody understands,''
Graziani said. ``In this business, if you don't get it done, you're
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
