<SLUG> BC-TEN-VENUS-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS PLANS TO DRESS FOR SUCCESS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, Venus Williams made a smash debut at the U.S.
Open, where she was the first unseeded finalist in four decades.
But last year, when she designed a different dress for each of her
seven possible matches, Williams fell a round short and never
unveiled the red, white and blue costume she aimed to wear in the
final.
</P>
<P>
   With the Open set to begin at the U.S. Tennis Association's
National Tennis Center on Aug. 30, Williams, who will be seeded a
career-best third with the recent retirement of Steffi Graf, is at
it again. While in search of her first Grand Slam title, she has
helped Reebok concoct seven dresses for the tournament, including a
one-shoulder outfit she designed herself.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the week hard at practice in Florida for her Open
tune-up next week in New Haven, Conn., the 19-year-old Williams
will put herself and some of her Open outfits on display at the
Official All-Star Cafe in Manhattan on Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not she wins the Open, Williams said she intended to
wind down her 1999 season in October in order to sign on for a
semester of fashion design at a Florida college she would not name,
the better to keep the paparazzi in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday Williams said she hoped to be in the Open spotlight
from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to be on top of your game and be ready, and, most of
all, mentally prepared,'' Williams said. ``I'm definitely trying my
best to get to No. 1; I'm definitely trying my best to win Grand
Slams. Both are high on my priority list.''
</P>
</TEXT>
