<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES FALL FOR FIRST TIME IN 4 DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities fell Thursday for the
first time in four days, as traders reacted to the unexpected
widening in the nation's trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day the price of a 30-year bond was down 13/32 to
101 12/32, pushing its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction, up to 6.03 percent, from 6 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit deepened to $24.6 billion for June from $21.2
billion in May. Analysts had expected a narrowing, with a deficit
of $20.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Currency traders also reacted to the worsening deficit, sending
the dollar down against the yen, euro and most other currencies,
and that hurt investor demand for U.S. government securities,
especially among foreign investors who fear possible currency
translation losses when they sell their holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The counterbalance to the day's weakness was that the Federal
Reserve was in the market as a buyer for the second consecutive day
Thursday, purchasing coupons with maturities ranging from Feb. 28,
2001, to May 31, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Josh Stiles, senior bond strategist at IDEA Global.com, a
financial consulting firm, said that the trade report and the
weakening dollar did not have as much of an effect on Treasuries as
might have been expected because market participants limited their
trading ahead of next week's policy-setting Federal Open Market
Committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Stiles expects the Fed to raise the federal funds rate that
banks charge each other for overnight loans by a quarter of a
percentage point and to lift the discount rate that the Fed charges
member banks by a similar amount. ``However, I don't see how a 5.25
percent federal funds rate is going to significantly alleviate the
imbalances the Fed is worried about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In another report that traders were watching Thursday, the
Philadelphia Fed said that regional business activity indicated a
continued pick-up. Its index of general business conditions
increased to 12.0 in August from 7.8 the month before.
</P>
</TEXT>
