u a BC-CLINTON-VACATION-BOS &LR;      08-19 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VACATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS ARRIVE FOR ISLAND VACATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST TISBURY, Mass. _ Free from the tumult of personal scandal
that plagued his last visit, President Clinton Thursday returned to
the warm embrace of Martha's Vineyard for nine days of golf,
celebrity soirees, and a new summer endeavor: Hillary Rodham
Clinton's exploratory campaign for the US Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and daughter Chelsea arrived for their fifth
vacation at the island haven the same as they have for their
happiest sojourns: beaming, waving, anticipating sunset sails,
private strolls along stunning seascapes, and late-night laughs
with longtime friends.
</P>
<P>
   Like old times, hundreds of well-wishers cheered from behind
wooden barriers at the Martha's Vineyard Airport as Air Force One
touched down at 5:45 p.m., under a brilliant sun. For the Clintons,
who own no property, the Edgartown estate of Cambridge, Mass.
hotelier Richard L. Friedman has become the closest they have to a
home outside Washington, their summer White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we going to have a good time?'' Clinton asked reporters
aboard the presidential aircraft as the family's flight to the
Vineyard began at Andrews Air Force Base in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' the president said, answering his own queston.
``That's our story and we're sticking to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The airport crowd serenaded Clinton with ``Happy Birthday,''
before he was whisked off to celebrate his 53d birthday Thursday
night with his family and a dozen friends at the Chilmark summer
home of his longtime confidant and Washington lawyer Vernon E.
Jordan Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reported guests were Maurice Tempelsman, former
companion to Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis; former Clinton budget
director Franklin Raines; NBC sports chief Dick Ebersol and his
wife, actress Susan Saint James; CNN correspondent Charlayne
Hunter-Gault and her husband, Ronald Gault; investment banker
Steven Ratner and author William Styron.
</P>
<P>
   But there was immediate evidence that this vacation will be like
no other. As Clinton worked the crowd with his labrador Buddy, the
loudest cheer of the brief reception broke out for Mrs. Clinton,
whose blossoming political career is expected to doninate the
family's getaway.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who last August was privately seething over her
husband's affair with Monica S. Lewinsky, this year has positioned
herself as the Democratic frontrunner in the race to succeed
Senator Daniel P. Moynihan of New York, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go, Hillary, go!' supporters shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, but she got more applause than the president,''
said Jenni Correia, 40, of Simsbury, Conn., who waited two hours
with her four children to meet the Clintons. ``We're all rooting
for her.''
</P>
<P>
   With the president in a supporting role, Mrs. Clinton is
scheduled to fly to Nantucket Friday to raise an estimated $100,000
for her campaign, one of six vacation fundraisers that are expected
to net $700,000. She will be honored on Nantucket Friday night by
the American Ireland Fund, a non-profit peace organization whose
recognition of Mrs. Clinton is expected to boost her standing with
New York's Irish American voters.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's emergence in the political arena comes in the
eclipse of her husband's lame-duck presidency. But Clinton, who
seems to have effortlessly shifted from campaigning for himself to
campaigning for his wife and Vice President Al Gore, expressed only
joy as he bounded off Air Force One, greeted on the tarmac first by
Jordan, then Friedman and his wife, Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons took turns holding the Friedmans' five-month-old
son, Jake, before they met the rest of the official welcoming
party, including Martha's Vineyard politicos and two of Chelsea's
friends, Kiva Iscol and John Dower.
</P>
<P>
   In a classic Clinton moment, the president evoked tears from a
well-wisher, Fatima Figueroa, 56, of Worcester, who stuck a red
rose into the pocket of his business suit as he greeted the airport
crowd. Clinton hugged and kissed Figueroa as he thanked her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried like a baby because I was able to do what I've always
wanted to do, give the perfect rose to the perfect president,''
Figueroa said afterward. ``I don't care if I die tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, the impeachment cloud that hovered above
Clinton last summer has lifted. No more self-inmposed seclusion for
the president. No more golf deprivation. No chilly distance between
the Clintons, who interacted easily throught the trip from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joseph Lockhart indicated the president
was so committed to relaxing that he does not intend to ``generate
any news'' on the Vineyard, other than his weekly radio addresses
each Saturday. This would be in stark contrast with last year, when
Clinton anounced from the Vineyard the US bombing of camps in
Afghanistan allegedly run by terrorist Ahmed Bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   The Vineyard has been a source of solace for Cinton in his
darkest hours, from the atermath of the suicide of his lifelong
friend, Vince Foster, the deputy White House counsel, in 1993, to
the shame of the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the salty air on a schooner off the Vineyard that
James Taylor one summer sang for Clinton ``You've Got a Friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the Comeback Kid is back. His family has forgiven his
humiliating sex scandal. And Friedman's 20-acre compound on the
shores of Oyster Pond is no longer a refuge from the storm but a
haven for rest and rejuvenation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there lingers Mrs. Clinton's political agenda. Indeed,
the Clintons nearly forsook a Vineyard vacation for an extended
retreat in New York so Mrs. Clinton could enhance her standing
there. In the end, they compromised, deciding to spend the second
half of their vacation in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons are scheduled to leave the Vineyard Aug. 28 for
East Hampton, N.Y., where they will attend a Democratic Party
weekend retreat and stay at the summer home of Hollywood filmmaker
Steven Speilberg. From Long Island, they will travel to Skaneateles
in the Finger Lakes region of northern New York before returning to
Washington in time for the Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But first, there will be golf aplenty for Clinton, including a
weekend round wth Senator John F. Kerry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
