<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-MUSTANG-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIRIT LIVES ON AFTER 35 YEARS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 22) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you were born in 1964, you've probably begun to notice signs
of aging: fallen arches, a bald spot, a tummy that no longer tucks.
Isn't it inspiring to find a 35-year-old that still looks and feels
young?
</P>
<P>
   With its 1964{ Mustang, christened at the last World's Fair held
in New York, Ford invented the so-called ``pony car'' _ sporty
personal transportation at a reasonable price.
</P>
<P>
   Although the market is quite different these days _ people who
once had Mustangs, Camaros and Barracudas are more likely to drive
sport sedans or sport utilities _ the formula still works. Seven
million Mustangs have been sold since '64; sales were up 25 percent
this year, through July.
</P>
<P>
   Like all long-lasting models, there have been highs and lows,
including some bloated and toothless Mustangs in the early '70s,
followed by the silly Pinto-based Mustang II. The car's resurgence,
though, has coincided with a return to its roots, starting with a
thorough redesign for 1994.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Ford restyled the car for the anniversary with
touches from the past. The long hood and short deck are still
there, but are now set off by the sharp edges of New Edge design;
there is a prominent, nonfunctional hood scoop, triangular side
scoops and three-part taillamps much like the original's. Even the
emblem on the grille is familiar; on base and GT models, the pony
again gallops within a gleaming corral.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast this back-to-basics approach with that of two long-time
rivals, the Chevrolet Camaro and Pontiac Firebird, which have had
declining sales for years. While the Mustang looks and feels much
like its predecessors, the Camaro and Firebird are larger, sleeker
and altogether different in style from their 1967 progenitors.
General Motors is pondering the future _ if there is one _ of its
pony cars.
</P>
<P>
   All these cars have kept a rear-drive configuration; all have
adequate front buckets plus a cramped back seat and a small trunk.
All come with V6 or V8 engines.
</P>
<P>
   The new Mustang is not nearly as simple as the original, which
offered a limited-slip differential to improve traction; the new
car can be had with a sophisticated traction control. The '64{
offered power steering for $80 extra; power steering, much improved
over the years, has long been standard. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The original's base price was $2,368 (equivalent to about
$13,000 now). Today's Mustangs start below $17,000, but even the
Cobra can be had for less than $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the 1999 Mustang preserves much of the
original's free spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in total sales is due to a surge for the base coupe
and convertible, while GT and Cobra sales have been relatively
flat. The base model has the same look, although without dress-up
items like a rear spoiler and dual exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, my test car, an electric-green base convertible, got a
lot of looks. Its 3.8-liter V6 cranks out 190 horsepower _ 40 more
than last year _ and felt zippy enough. Showoffs can still fishtail
and burn rubber if so inclined. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The test car had a $22,000 sticker, about the same as a
yawn-inducing Taurus. The Mustang isn't as practical as that sedan,
but it will make you feel less old. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
