<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-ALABAMA20-COX     08-19 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ALABAMA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tide of turmoil slams Bama
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhardt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ A steady stream of cars pulls into the
parking lot off Paul W. Bryant Drive. After finding a spot, each
driver and his passengers jump out of the vehicle and walk quickly
toward the light.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't rushing to church. But they are heading for the next
thing to it here. The Alabama football team is holding its first
preseason practice in pads, and the whole family is invited.
</P>
<P>
   The people who have come out to the Alabama practice field on
this warm Tuesday night appear to be upbeat and ready to celebrate
the start of the season less than three weeks away. But underneath
the surface, tension again runs through the Alabama family.
</P>
<P>
   This season was going to be the one in which Alabama took a
major step toward what the faithful believe is its rightful place,
at the top of the football hierarchy. After seasons of 4-7 and 7-5,
Alabama had been picked by many experts to win the SEC's Western
Division and play for the conference championship. Breaking with
tradition, which is no small occurrence here, the school was
touting a player, running back Shaun Alexander, for the Heisman
Trophy. Optimism, in short supply for the past two years, was
rampant.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed Aug. 5 when coach Mike DuBose stood before
television cameras and admitted that he had engaged in an improper
relationship with a former secretary and had ``misled'' everyone in
May when he denied it.
</P>
<P>
   By then, university President Andrew Sorensen and athletics
director Bob Bockrath had worked out a plan they hoped would end
the episode. The former secretary, Debbie Gibson, would be paid
$350,000 to withdraw claims of sexual harassment and sexual
discrimination.The money would come out of DuBose's salary over the
next 30 months. The length of his contract would be reduced from
five years to three, but he would not be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the penalties) are pretty harsh,'' Bockrath said
later, ``not only from a monetary standpoint, but in the attention
it draws on one individual. I think (DuBose) has paid a substantial
price.''
</P>
<P>
   But for many people, it wasn't enough. Thousands of fans took
DuBose's indiscretion personally. On talk shows and in media polls
taken after the announcement, a majority said DuBose should have
been fired immediately.
</P>
<P>
   DuBose supporters asked for compassion and said that firing the
coach a month before the season would have been folly. But they
were drowned out by the passion of those who thought DuBose had
sullied the reputation of their most prized institution: the
Alabama football program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've hurt this university and the people who love it,''
DuBose said. ``That hurts, because I love this university. It still
hurts. But we've paid a price, and that part has been put behind
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. The controversy continues in several ways:
</P>
<P>
   _ The university's board of trustees met Aug. 10 for four hours
and grudgingly supported the plan of Sorensen and Bockrath. Board
president Sid McDonald said DuBose would keep his job. But it was
implied that the board could change its mind if other problems
occur. ``The scars won't heal quickly,'' McDonald said.
</P>
<P>
   _ At least one Alabama newspaper is digging around to see if
DuBose committed any other personal indiscretions. Nothing has been
reported.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several advertisers in the team's game programs have asked
that DuBose's picture be removed from their ads and replaced by a
generic football picture.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sorensen was quoted as wondering if he could trust DuBose in
any matter, even in following NCAA rules. Sorensen declined an
interview request for this article. Spokeswoman Janet Griffith said
the comments were taken out of context from a frenzied news
conference after the board of trustees meeting.
</P>
<P>
   After the publicity when the story broke two weeks ago, most
Alabama officials were unwilling to speak on the record this week
and hoped that the story would go away. DuBose was an exception.
</P>
<P>
   But discussions with those behind the scenes indicated that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Bockrath met with the assistant coaches last week and told
them that if they took care of business ``on the field'' things
would work out. The thinking is that if Alabama wins eight or nine
games _ including the Nov. 20 game at Auburn _ DuBose will keep his
job.
</P>
<P>
   _ Several big-money boosters sent letters of support to the
coaching staff. Their message was: ``Do your job and everything
will be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   _ If DuBose is retained after this season, odds are good that
the two years taken from his contract will be reinstated;
otherwise, the contract situation could damage recruiting. If
DuBose is not retained, his buyout would be reasonable for the
school to absorb.
</P>
<P>
   The administration apparently will wait until after the season
to decide DuBose's fate. Then, and only then, will school officials
make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   But DuBose doesn't think the situation has left him twisting in
the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be evaluated on what we do, but from that
standpoint, that's not different than any other year,'' he said.
``But given the circumstances, I can see why others would sit back
and say the verdict is still out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's players insist that the controversy is overblown and
that they do not have to win to save DuBose's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine,'' said Alexander, whose Heisman candidacy has been
minimized. ``Coach stood up before us, said he made a mistake and
apologized for it. Now we all move on. The only thing keeping this
thing alive is you guys (in the media).''
</P>
<P>
   At practice Tuesday evening, everyone was trying to put the best
face on a bad situation.
</P>
<P>
   Sorensen, looking somewhat out of place in a shirt and tie,
arrived early and gave his annual address to the team. The players
hung on every word as he gave DuBose an unequivocal vote of
confidence. Paul Bryant Jr., the wealthy son of the legendary
coach, watched quietly in the background, as king-makers do. Polly
DuBose, the coach's wife, dutifully made the rounds of friends, and
friends of friends, accepting hugs and reassurances at every stop.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, what matters is what happens on the field. September
promises to be interesting. After the Vanderbilt game are games
with Houston and Louisiana Tech at Birmingham's Legion Field. Then
Arkansas comes to Tuscaloosa on Sept. 25. It will be the first game
on campus and one that will be key to Alabama's hopes in the West.
If the Crimson Tide is 4-0 going into its Oct. 2 trip to Florida,
Bama has a chance for a very good season.
</P>
<P>
   But one stumble, or even an ugly victory against a lesser
opponent, and DuBose runs the risk of his detractors coming back in
full force. And the critics will be relentless. The only way to
keep the negativity at bay is to win _and win impressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've lost the trust of some people here, and that kind
of trust you don't get back overnight,'' said DuBose, who is 11-12
in two years as coach. ``It's going to take time.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those who do not win at Alabama, time is always running
out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
