A3437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GTECHLINE20-COX     08-19 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GTECHLINE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Call Georgia Tech's offense line the QB's bodyguards
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chris Brown remembers it all too well. It was a sight
he did not see during last season's loss to Florida State, and it
upset him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going back to the huddle,'' said Brown, Georgia
Tech's junior right tackle, ``and I didn't see Joe Hamilton in
there. I didn't know until then he'd been hurt and was out of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Not seeing Hamilton, the Yellow Jackets' quarterback and Heisman
Trophy contender, on the field indeed is frightening for Tech
players, coaches and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, at 5 feet 10 and 186 pounds, has been remarkably
durable _ even though he is exposed to plenty of contact in a
diverse offense, which can have him running the option, rolling out
or luring would-be tacklers with play-action tosses and short
screen passes to running backs.
</P>
<P>
   Add the senior's propensity not to shy away from contact, and
Hamilton often has Tech supporters holding their breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play the game of football, and injuries happen,'' says
Hamilton, who is 13-3 in his past 16 games as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those losses, however, came against Florida State, and
Hamilton was injured both times.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is among four returning starters to an offensive line that
helped produce 4,276 total yards and 39 touchdowns a year ago,
while allowing just 16 sacks in 280 pass attempts. He is aware that
if the Jackets are to supplant FSU atop the ACC, Hamilton has to
stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do our jobs, Joe won't get hurt,'' Brown said. ``We take
that thought to mind each and every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, offensive line coach Doug Marrone has a
talented and experienced bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a 6-6, 315-pound All-ACC candidate, has started 18 games.
At right tackle is 6-8, 335-pound All-America candidate Jon Carman,
a senior who has started the past 16 games. Right guard Brent Key,
a 6-4, 280-pound junior, has started 24 games in a row. Senior Noah
King, a 6-2, 277-pounder, moves to center after starting at guard
last season. At left guard is senior Jason Burks, a 6-5,
287-pounder who was named second-team All-ACC in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge is to pick up where we left off and get better
every day,'' said Marrone, a fifth-year member of the staff who
played at Syracuse when head coach George O'Leary was an assistant
for the Orangemen. ``We can't afford any inconsistencies.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, who played the offensive line and fullback at New
Hampshire, says consistent play will be the main challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have the physical tools,'' he said. ``Now, it's
just, mentally, can they get it done?''
</P>
<P>
   The backups are brawny, too: senior Bill Madigan (6-5, 298);
sophomores Jason Kemble (6-4, 299), Jesse Moody (6-5, 300) and
Brian Meager (6-5, 275); junior Kevin Knapp (6-4, 287); and
redshirt freshman Dustin Vaitekunas (6-7, 314).
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the No. 11-ranked Yellow Jackets are not overwhelmed
by high hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our personal goals are the same as every year,'' he said. ``We
want to set out and improve each Saturday. If we do that, we'll
even exceed all the high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
