<HEADER>
A3438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-FORBES-CAMPAIGN-ART-9     08-19 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-CAMPAIGN-ART-925(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIMING FOR A TWO-MAN RACE, FORBES PREPARES TO PRESS BUSH ON
ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the days since Steve Forbes' second-place finish
in the Iowa straw poll, the wealthy publisher's campaign aides have
done plenty of crowing.
</P>
<P>
   They have talked about a ``two-man race'' in the Republican
presidential primaries, reducing the eight contenders other than
Forbes and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to starry-eyed asterisks.
They have unequivocally designated Forbes the only candidate with
the organizational agility and economic stamina to keep pace with
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But with the next competitive statewide contest more than four
months away, Forbes faces serious tests, both political and
financial, in his effort to maintain the claim that he is Bush's
biggest threat.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' aides said this week that one way they will draw pointed
attention to contrasts between Forbes' and Bush's positions on
various issues in an effort to show that the Republican field has
narrowed. That approach has prompted complaints from Bush's aides
that Forbes is poised to take a negative tack and turn the race
ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' aides challenged that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we'll focus on is an issues agenda,'' said Bill
Dal Col, Forbes' campaign manager, ``and the one who has to respond
to it is the front runner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who has to be overtaken,'' Dal Col said. ``He
can't keep running and hiding. Eventually, he has to address
issues, and when he does, he's on our turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' aides would not say whether they intend to attack Bush
explicitly in forthcoming advertisements. But a spokeswoman for
Bush said that Forbes seemed to be laying the groundwork for a
repeat of his performance in 1996, when he unleashed withering
television commercials against Bob Dole, the Republican
front-runner and eventual nominee, that haunted Dole well into the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that he's on the road to doing the same thing,''
the spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tucker said that Forbes' campaign had begun conducting a
poll in Iowa this week to see if voters would feel more negatively
about Bush if they were given selective information about his
record. She said they were told, for example, that he had advocated
a raise in the sales tax in Texas but not that he had supported an
overall tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Appell, a spokesman for the Forbes campaign, said Thursday
that he would not discuss the specifics of any polls that the
campaign was doing. In a sign of the intensifying friction between
the two campaigns, Appell added that Bush's aides were overreacting
and obviously running scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to take the subject away from issues by
accusing of this, or accusing us of that,'' Appell said. ``They're
panicking a little bit because they're in trouble. Someone's come
along and popped their little bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   That is one interpretation of Forbes' performance in Iowa, the
true meaning of which has been dissected and debated more
vigorously than the showing of any other candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes won 20.8 percent of the vote, while Bush, the top
finisher, won 31.3 percent. Elizabeth Dole came in third with 14.4
percent, while Gary L. Bauer came in fourth with 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Mrs. Dole and Bauer and several political analysts said
that Forbes' success primarily reflected his lavish spending to woo
and entertain voters in a ritual that often rewards the candidates
who are the most extravagant, solicitous hosts.
</P>
<P>
   In national polls, Forbes continues to lag behind Bush, Sen.
John McCain of Arizona and Mrs. Dole. The latest survey of
registered Republican voters in New Hampshire, a state with an
early primary, shows Forbes near the bottom of the field, even
though he has advertised extensively there.
</P>
<P>
   The poll by the American Research Group, which was released
Thursday, interviewed 450 Republicans. Only 3 percent said they
favored Forbes, putting him seventh place in a field of nine
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nationally, there's no evidence that he's getting any
traction,'' said Roger Stone, a Republican strategist. ``I frankly
don't know how much more this guy has got to spend before he
figures out that money can't buy you love.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes' aides, however, noted that Forbes' poll numbers in Iowa
built steadily as he spent more time there and said that when
voters in other states take as careful a look at the candidates as
Iowans did, Forbes' support will grow in those places, too.
</P>
<P>
   They also said that Forbes was committed to spending whatever it
takes to remain competitive with Bush, who has raised more than $37
million so far. Forbes has raised more than $2.7 million, and has
added more than $6.5 million of his own money to that sum.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But to keep pumping cash into his campaign, he may have to
liquidate some assets, as he did during his 1996 bid for the
Republican presidential nomination. On the way to spending more
than $37 million that time around, he had to sell some of his
shares in Forbes Family Holdings, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated the amount of the company he currently owns to be
worth more than $50 million, according to the financial disclosure
form that he filed with the Federal Election Commission in May.
</P>
<P>
   But because the company is privately held, his stake in it is
less instantly converted into dollars for his campaign than are his
publicly traded stocks, bonds and mutual funds, a portfolio that
Forbes estimated to be worth between $5.8 million and $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dal Col declined to discuss the liquidity of Forbes' assets but
said that Forbes would not come up short on money for the campaign.
``He's got the personal resources,'' Dal Col said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Forbes seems at least as determined as he was in 1996, and
possibly more so. Then, he came across as the champion of a single
issue: his proposal for a flat tax. Now, he speaks just as loudly
about conservative religious themes, like opposition to legal
abortion, that seem to depart from past statements that the
Christian Coalition did not speak for most Christians and that Pat
Robertson was ``a toothy flake.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kennedy, a strategist for former Tennessee Gov. Lamar
Alexander, who dropped out of the race this week, said of Forbes:
``He's a better candidate than he was in 1996. His agenda is much
broader. His presentation is more polished.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy added that Forbes ``has a tendency to go a step too
far. You saw that in 1996, with his negative advertising campaign.
It ultimately sunk his candidacy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
