<HEADER>
A3439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-700&AMP;ADD-     08-19 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-QUAKE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC LOSS ESTIMATED TO REACH TENS OF BILLIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TURKEY-GOLCUK, TURKEY-BUILDINGS.) 
(th) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Economic losses caused by the devastating
45-second earthquake will reach tens of billions of dollars,
according to early damage estimates announced Thursday, and the
government probably will have to find several billion more in an
already tight budget to pay for emergency reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers continued to pull survivors and victims from the
ruins of buildings, bringing the number of dead to more than 7,000
and the injured to more than 30,000. Turkish officials said
thousands were still missing, and the hope that they will be found
alive is dwindling. Newspapers predicted that the death toll could
soar to 10,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The director of Turkey's leading observatory, Mehmet Ali
Isikara, said he had detected ``unusual movement'' in seismic
structures that could produce another tremor. More than 200
aftershocks were reported in the region on Thursday alone. In
response to the warning, the governor of Bursa, a province south of
Istanbul, urged the province's 2 million residents to spend the
night outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit sought to calm rising public anger
at the disorganized relief effort. Looking pale and shaken as he
emerged from a crisis session, he said that although the nation was
in mourning, ``good news comes from all areas'' as more survivors
are found.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of ordering an army mobilization or other drastic
measures to increase the pace of the rescue effort, as some have
urged, Ecevit announced only a plan to send tents to affected
areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tent cities will be set up in the worst areas,'' he said on
Thursday. ``From today, they will be able to make use of health,
cleaning and food facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the quake area, people complained bitterly about the lack
of relief workers and equipment. Television stations broadcast
scenes of people picking through rubble with their bare hands and
even fighting over scarce shovels and bulldozers. Many towns have
not seen a single government worker, and are relying on foreign
volunteers or none at all.
</P>
<P>
   In Izmit, near the epicenter of the quake, the country's biggest
refinery continued to burn. Thousands of residents were evacuated
as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers from abroad continued to pour into Turkey. The
United States announced plans to send three warships with 3,100
sailors and Marines aboard. The vessels are fitted with operating
rooms and medical equipment, and the crews include physicians and
paramedics.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department announced that five Americans were among
the dead.
</P>
<P>
   As the initial shock over the quake eased, government officials
and other specialists began planning what can be done to revive the
shattered economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy was already in a serious position,'' Ecevit said.
``Now it will be worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is negotiating with the International Monetary Fund for a
crucial $5 billion loan, and Turkish leaders have pledged to cut
the national budget and make other reforms that may now prove
difficult or impossible. At the same time, countless businesses
have been destroyed, most of them small and mid-sized companies
like those that have fueled this country's remarkable economic boom
in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than serious,'' said Abdurrahman Ariman, general
secretary of the Foreign Investors Association. ``The loss could be
$25 billion, but the effects will be much wider than that. This is
the most productive region of our country, and the destruction of
infrastructure there is complete, let alone the damage that
industries sustained.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We already had serious problems in other regions, and now we
have to talk about reconstructing the whole country,'' he said.
``It's not a one-dimensional problem. It will take years to deal
with, and Turkey can't handle all of it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's economy has boomed for most of the 1990s, racking up
growth rates of 7 percent to 8 percent in most years. Although
there has been a slump in exports since last summer's Russian
financial crisis, and a near-collapse of tourism after terrorist
attacks here several months ago, most experts have agreed that the
economy here is fundamentally sound and should continue to grow.
But in the wake of the earthquake, no one is certain if those
predictions remain valid.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Industry has been terribly affected, and I don't know how
we're going to put it together again,'' said Ayse Bugra, a
professor of economics at Bosporus University in Istanbul. ``There
are all kinds of problems. Roads are a mess, and there is no rail
transportation in the area even though it's the country's main
industrial region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The destruction of the petroleum refinery will probably mean
that oil prices will go up, which will fuel inflation. Many
companies were not properly insured, so there will be a lot of
bankruptcies and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even though this is a disaster for the economy, it can be
an opportunity if certain decisions are taken,'' Ms. Bugra said.
``The refinery should definitely be moved to another place outside
the earthquake zone. Incentives should be given to companies that
lost buildings to relocate in other parts of the country, which
would not only take them outside the danger area but would address
the great regional imbalances in our economy. Insurance and
construction regulations should be tightened. These would be
rational steps, and now, before people forget about this, is the
time to take them.''
</P>
<P>
   One sector of the economy that is likely to boom in the coming
months is construction. Gazi Ercel, president of the Central Bank,
said he expected the government to allocate about $4 billion to
rebuild ruined businesses and $2 billion to $3 billion more to
rebuild the destroyed refinery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a burden on our budget, but we have a GDP of $200
billion, so it should be bearable,'' Ercel said. ``We'll also have
a very low growth rate this year, probably less than one percent,
but investments in construction will help somewhat. All in all,
it's a sizable burden, but I think the Turkish economy, together
with generous and timely foreign aid, will be able to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Michel Camdessus, managing director of the International
Monetary Fund, suggested that the fund might modify its demands to
take the needs of earthquake victims into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF will do all it can to help the Turkish government deal
with this disaster,'' Camdessus said. ``We stand ready to help them
in any way that we can.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Turkey's principal business association, Erkut
Yucaoglu, said that even though losses would probably exceed $20
billion, the earthquake was ``not completely devastating in an
economic sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It will slow down the economy, but we can get through it,''
Yucaoglu said. ``I hope there will be a level of understanding
abroad for the budget increases and other steps we'll have to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey deserves some soft loans and long-term credits at this
moment to cope with the rehabilitation of various sectors of the
economy, as well as funds to cope with the social side of the
problem,'' he said. ``I think foreign lenders are ready to look at
things here with a softer heart at this moment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
