<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3446 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV22-     08-19 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MIDSTREAM-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBT: THE NEXT GENERATION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 22) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Md.)   (af) 
By JAMES SCHEMBARI  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baby boomers are returning to school in increasing numbers, to
work on graduate degrees or to finish their undergraduate work as
they try to advance their careers. But that zeal has created a
unique financial squeeze that education experts say can only
tighten: As they pay off loans for their own education, past or
present, parents are taking on additional debt for their children's
schooling.
</P>
<P>
   SLM Holding Corp., known as Sallie Mae, the nation's largest
financer of student loans, says that baby boomers (people born from
1946 through 1964) hold about 25 percent of its loans, or $11.5
billion. Boomers with both types of college debt _ for their own
and their children's educations _ are carrying an average debt of
almost $23,000, Sallie Mae says, of which $14,500 is for their own
educations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder if the parents can keep up with paying for
their children's education and still pay their own loans,'' said
Kenneth Redd, a senior research associate at Sallie Mae. ``It does
add up after a while.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Education, the number of students
in higher education who were 35 or older more than tripled from
1970 to 1996, from 823,000 to 2.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though Sallie Mae, citing privacy restrictions, would not
identify borrowers who were paying off both types of debt,
university officials say they see them regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every financial aid office has spoken to a family with
a child going to college while keeping up with their own loan
situation,'' said Ronald W. Johnson, director of financial aid at
the University of California at Los Angeles. ``It is going to
continue. We may eventually see grandparents, parents and then the
child all part of that whole scenario as well.'' Intergenerational
debt, he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Frishberg, director of student financial services at Johns
Hopkins University in Baltimore, said the situation would probably
worsen. The most common term for a student loan is 10 years, but
starting in 1993, students were allowed to take 25-year loans,
meaning that more people will be paying for school deep into middle
age. ``They can get into a 25-year loan repayment and really get
hit when their own children start school,'' she said. ``Now some
alumni are saying, `We can't give because we're already giving:
We're still paying back our loans.'''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Hauptman, a higher-education finance consultant in
Washington, said that if the federal government limited borrowing
by setting tighter rules for the loans, schools would have to
control their rising costs. But, he said, ``no one is willing to
take the steps to reduce the debt burden.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents having trouble with their own debt burdens do have a way
to reduce the immediate pressure. They can switch to different
payment schedules offered by Sallie Mae to reduce monthly payments
in the early years of a loan. The price, of course, is higher
payments later _ and a higher overall bill.
</P>
<P>
   A standard 10-year student loan for $10,000 at a maximum
interest rate of 8.25 percent results in monthly payments of $123.
By the end of the term, a borrower has paid $14,718.
</P>
<P>
   But under a different schedule, the same loan could have
payments of $69 a month for the first four years, then $177 a month
for the last six years. That would mean total payments of $16,012,
or $1,294 more than under the standard formula. So be careful.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, Sallie Mae says, is that even if parents have
outstanding debt from their own school years, it won't be held
against them when they apply for loans for their children. That is
true, of course, only if the parents haven't defaulted on their own
college loans. In some cases, parents can also consolidate their
loan with their child's, making one monthly payment.
</P>
<P>
   Redd of Sallie Mae said he worries that parents could eventually
have trouble meeting other obligations, like mortgages, because of
accumulated college debt.
</P>
<P>
   And Hauptman, the consultant, said it might take a while for the
impact of all this debt to be felt. ``To what extent does this
change people's behavior?'' he said. ``Do they postpone child
bearing, postpone marriage because of the debt? Those questions
have still not been answered.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   James Schembari is an editor at The Times. His column on the
prime earning, spending and striving years appears the fourth
Sunday of each month. E-mail: jimschem(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2134EDT &QL; 
