<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-JARRETT20-COX     08-19 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett pulling out of sight
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dale Jarrett's 300-point lead in the Winston Cup
standings is so large that the No. 88 Ford driver could finish last
and next-to-last in the next two races and still be No. 1 in the
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Some NASCAR drivers already are waving the white flag on the
1999 season, as the circuit prepares for Sunday's Pepsi 400 in
Brooklyn, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the ninth-highest scoring team since Daytona (on July
3), and we have fallen 166 points behind him in just those four
races,'' Steve Park said. ``I don't see any way he can lose the
lead as long as he finishes races.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, you think, 'Well, his luck could go bad.' Yeah, it
could,'' Kyle Petty said. ``But he'd have to be the unlucky 13th
cousin of that guy in 'Lil' Abner' who had the rain cloud over his
head all the time to be unlucky enough to lose it now. No matter
how good Mark (Martin) or the guys behind him are, he'd have to
fall off a cliff to lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has the biggest lead in August in modern NASCAR history.
In 1993 after the Michigan race, Dale Earnhardt led Jarrett by 259
points. Last year, Jeff Gordon won the Winston Cup championship by
364 points, but his lead was 97 points after 21 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Jarrett falls out of the next five races, it'll get
interesting,'' Gordon said with a chuckle. ``I don't see that
happening. They're on a roll. Things are going their way.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon captured the 1998 title by tying a record for season
victories with 13, while Jarrett is succeeding with consistency.
After wrecking in the season-opener at Daytona and placing 37th,
Jarrett has had 20 consecutive finishes of 11th or better.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett gained the top spot after winning at Richmond in May. He
then finished in the top five in nine of the next 10 races. He has
increased his points lead in each of the last nine races. His lead
over Mark Martin is a season high.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has five victories to Jarrett's four, but Jarrett is 482
points ahead of Gordon, who is fifth in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've analyzed over the past few years what we needed to do
and what others have done to beat us,'' Jarrett said. ``And it
certainly doesn't always come out to the guy that wins the most
races. Certainly, you've got to win your share, but it's the team
that has the fewest problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, to this point, we've been the team with the fewest
problems. If we can continue that trend, then we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the giant margin, the Robert Yates Racing team isn't
celebrating. Yates, a team owner since 1988, has twice seen his
drivers make a run at the title, and both outcomes were
heartbreaking. A wreck in the final race in Atlanta in 1992 cost
Davey Allison the title. Two years ago, Ernie Irvan was speeding
toward the championship before being involved in a life-threatening
crash during practice at Michigan in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the race for the championship is still very open,''
Yates said. ``I've run second too many times and blown big leads
enough times to know it's not over.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Todd Parrott said: ``I guess it's a nice lead to
have, but no lead is ever big enough until it is mathematically
over. A lot of things can happen; you just never know. But it is
still a good feeling to know we are racing hard every week and
gaining points every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
