<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ITEMS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elite family membership
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ned Jarrett won Winston Cup championships in 1961 and
1965. If son Dale can hold on this year, the Jarretts would be the
second father-son combination to win titles in the series. Lee and
Richard Petty were the charter members.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be pretty special for us to be in the same category
with the Pettys,'' said Ned, who worked as a spotter for his son at
Indianapolis, Charlotte and Rockingham this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all like to see our children do better than we did.
Of course, I was fortunate enough to win championships twice. But
if Dale could win it this year, it would mean more to me than both
of those championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A: TO THE POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup points standings are always a hot topic,
especially this year with Dale Jarrett's 300-point lead. Mike
Helton, chief operating officer for NASCAR, discussed the issue
earlier this week:
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution: With Jeff Gordon last year and
Dale Jarrett now, we've had two seasons in a row where dominant
drivers have virtually run away in the points standings by the late
summer. Is this good for the sport?
</P>
<P>
   Helton: It depends on whether or not the term ``run away'' is
accurate, and I don't think it is. Going back to dominance, with
the way Jeff Gordon has been winning so many races and
championships races in recent years, it puts an individual on the
map, so to speak. It makes him a cut above everyone else, or it
seems that way. You can debate whether (the dominance) makes a guy
more popular or unpopular, but what you can't debate is, at the end
of the day, more people know his name and associate him with
racing, which is a good thing. Dale Jarrett, by winning races and
sitting atop of the points standings, is experiencing that right
now. But it doesn't mean the points battle is over. Three hundred
points seem like a lot if you are running second, third, fourth or
fifth, but it doesn't seem like a lot to the guy who has the
cushion because you just don't know what can happen.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Isn't it awkward for Jarrett to be so far ahead, yet Gordon
has won the most races this year and is all the way back at fifth
in points?
</P>
<P>
   Helton: That's not awkward, and it's not uncommon. That's what
the Winston Cup points championship is all about, being competitive
consistently. Some of that comes from maybe having better luck (at
times) than the next guy, but the championship is about
consistently being the best guy out there. What Dale Jarrett has
done is be successful all along. Every race on every weekend, he's
up front in the top 10 or top five.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Is there any chance of NASCAR changing the points system to
reward a driver more for victories than consistency?
</P>
<P>
   Helton: We take a look at it quite often. We continue to study
and keep an open mind on what changes work well for the time. So
far, we're pretty comfortable with the points standings we have,
and we don't see any changes in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD NEWS, BAD NEWS
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that Bill Elliott leads all active drivers with
six poles and seven Winston Cup victories at Michigan Speedway. The
bad news for Elliott is that his last victory at the track was 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   BORED WITH POINTS RACE?
</P>
<P>
   If Dale Jarrett has you bored with the points standings, then
look a little further down the list. Rusty Wallace, Terry Labonte
and Mike Skinner are separated by five points in eighth, ninth and
10th.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT HE SAID
</P>
<P>
   ``In January, if someone had told me that I'd be sixth in the
points 21 races into the season, I'd have said they were crazy. We
just wanted to make each race and finish as many laps as possible.
Everything else has been a bonus this year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tony Stewart on his rookie season
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
