<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Evernham moving up?
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   WINSTON CUP
</P>
<P>
   Breaking up is hard to do, but it appears inevitable for Jeff
Gordon and crew chief Ray Evernham. The two have teamed to win
Winston Cup titles in three of the past four seasons. Evernham
again confirmed this week that he hopes to move into a managerial
position with Hendrick Motorsports. He declined to discuss a
timetable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no secret,'' Evernham said. ``For the last couple of
years, I've said I don't know how much longer I'm going to be a
crew chief. Right now, we're not ready to comment on what could or
would or should happen. As I said last week, I don't want to
comment or tell anybody the truth, because the stuff everybody is
making up is a lot better than I could come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon said, ``Everything that's going on right now at Hendrick
Motorsports, I'm 100 percent in support of.''
</P>
<P>
   Cup debut for Kenseth
</P>
<P>
   Matt Kenseth, who trails leader Dale Earnhardt Jr. by one point
in the Busch standings, is making his Winston Cup debut on Sunday.
Kenseth, who will compete on the top circuit for Roush Racing next
year, will be driving a No. 17 Ford from Mark Martin's stable
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Motor Speedway
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Boot has taken another big step in sponsorship with
Atlanta Motor Speedway. The Franklin, Tenn., footwear company will
sponsor the Nov. 20 season-ending ARCA race, now called the Georgia
Boot 400. Georgia Boot already sponsors the Winston Cup Pole Day on
Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   GRAND NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   Air Jamaica team back
</P>
<P>
   The AllCar Motorsports and Air Jamaica Vacations Chevy team is
returning to the Busch Series after two months of preparation and
will compete in all remaining races. Steve Grissom, who has been
the team's ``player-coach'' since mid-May, will drive the car in
the Michigan 200 on Saturday. ``It's asking a lot of a group of
racers to just work in the shop for two months, but they did it,''
owner Dave Carroll said. The team had a disastrous debut this
season, wrecking 13 cars in its first nine races and going through
three different engine builders. . . . The Lysol brand will
continue to sponsor the No. 98 car of driver Elton Sawyer and Akins
Motorsports through the 2000 season. Sawyer, in his 18th year of
competing in the Busch Series, is fifth in the points standings.
</P>
<P>
   CRAFTSMAN TRUCK
</P>
<P>
   Carelli to aide Harvick
</P>
<P>
   Rick Carelli and Kevin Harvick are rival drivers, but they will
be on the same team in tonight's Ram Tough 200. Carelli, who drove
the No. 6 Chevy to three career victories before getting hurt,
signed a one-race deal to be a consultant with Harvick's No. 98
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what my job responsibilities are. I'm just
gonna be there this weekend to sort of help them out,'' Carelli
said. ``It's really just a trial deal.'' Carelli is the defending
champion of the Ram Tough 200.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
