<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN:   McGWIRE'S ACT BACK AT SHEA 
 (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This is where we came in. Unlike the movies, however,
this is no time to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Before the days of tenplexes and sixteenplexes, some moviegoers
would arrive at theaters after the movie started, watch the rest of
it, then see the part they missed when it immediately started over
and leave when one of them said, ``This is where we came in.''
</P>
<P>
   But just because the St. Louis Cardinals come to Shea Stadium
Friday night on the exact same date that they visited Queens last
season is no reason for fans to leave and miss the rest of the Mark
McGwire Show.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's back, he's still hitting home runs and he's still
worth watching; his act has not grown stale. In fact, McGwire may
be even more remarkable the second time around. His record surge of
70 home runs last season certainly did not sate his appetite for
launching majestic 450-foot fly balls followed by those 360-foot
trots around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire meets the New York Mets with a steadily ascending number
of home runs, 48 at the moment but not for long. Last season, the
teams played a doubleheader at Shea on this date, Aug. 20, and
McGwire arrived with 49 home runs. Before the first game, he
maintained his cautious approach to talk of breaking Roger Maris'
record of 61, even though he needed only 13 home runs in the
Cardinals' remaining 38 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody gets to 50 by September, they have a shot down the
stretch run to either tie, break or get close to it,'' McGwire
said, stating what he said had been his longtime view and refusing
to acknowledge that he had a chance to break the record. But, it
was noted with Einsteinian mathematical deduction, 49 was only one
away from 50. ``I'll say it once I hit 50,'' he said. ``I gotta
stick with my statement.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning of the first game of the doubleheader,
McGwire drove away the cautious approach, hitting No. 50 against
Willie Blair, a Mets relief pitcher. In the first inning of the
second game, he connected for No. 51 against Rick Reed, putting him
only 10 away from the record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say I do have a shot,'' McGwire conceded after the
doubleheader, ``but it's going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough? It might have been tough for McGwire to play under the
pressure and the attention he created for himself, but it sure
didn't look tough. He didn't just break the record; he obliterated
it. Whacking a 509-foot home run here, a 501-foot home run there,
McGwire slugged 19 more home runs. When Maris broke Babe Ruth's
legendary record, he squeaked by it by one. After McGwire reached
62, he hit eight more home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost before No. 70 landed beyond the left-field fence at Busch
Stadium on the final day of the season, people were asking McGwire
if he thought his record would ever be broken. A silly question, of
course, and McGwire has refused to address the thought this season.
</P>
<P>
   But here he is coming into Shea Stadium with 40 games remaining
and needing 23 to reach 71. Sounds like a lot of ground to cover in
a short time, right? But last season, McGwire hit 23 home runs in
the Cardinals' last 40 games.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one difference between this series and the other
series the Mets and the Cardinals have played the past two seasons,
it's that Rick Reed will not be pitching in it. McGwire has hit six
home runs against Mets pitchers last season (four) and this (two),
and Reed has thrown three of the pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched to him in spring training, so it's no big surprise
to me,'' said Octavio Dotel, the Mets' rookie, who is scheduled to
face McGwire Sunday. But, a reporter said to the youngster, ``This
is for real.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' Dotel responded. ``I don't worry about all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Tam, who was playing cards with Dotel, looked up at that
point and said, ``He hits them off everybody, doesn't he?''
</P>
<P>
   Just about. McGwire has hit home runs so frequently the past few
seasons that few pitchers have been able to avoid his magical bat.
On May 8 of last season, he hit the 400th of his career against
Reed at Shea, and just 15 months later he hit No. 500. No one, not
Babe Ruth, not Henry Aaron, had ever reached those milestones in
successive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Now McGwire has 505 home runs. He is already 15th on the career
list. If he hits 17 more this season, he will catapult himself into
the top 10 at No. 10, leapfrogging Mel Ott, Eddie Mathews, Ernie
Banks, Ted Williams and Willie McCovey. And next season he can
surpass Jimmie Foxx, Mickey Mantle, Mike Schmidt, Reggie Jackson,
Harmon Killebrew and Frank Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, with just 65 home runs this season and another 65
next, or any combination of 130, certainly not beyond the realm of
McGwire's possibility, he can gobble up that historic home run
ground as if it were a game of pepper. At the end of the first
season beginning with a 2, McGwire can be No. 4, trailing only
Aaron, Ruth and Willie Mays.
</P>
<P>
   Like home runs or not, fans, baseball people and the rest of us
have to realize this is a prodigious feat we are witnessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a person just like me,'' Dotel said. ``I don't have to be
scared. I know he's a great player and I respect him, but I don't
have to be scared of him.''
</P>
<P>
   No pitcher should be. But pitchers and hitters alike should be
in awe of the heights McGwire has scaled. He has made the show
worth sitting through again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
