<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALT DISNEY TO SELL FAIRCHILD TO CONDE NAST
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co. says it will sell its Fairchild Publishing
division to Conde Nast Publications, the glossy, high-profile
publisher of such magazines as Vogue, Vanity Fair and The New
Yorker. The deal will rid Disney of a noncore business and will
merge some of the fashion world's most powerful publishing
entities, and two distinct publishing styles: the frills-free but
provocative style of Fairchild with the no-expenses-spared ethos of
Conde Nast, a company that will send luggage by overnight Federal
Express if a fatigued fashion editor does not want to carry it on a
flight.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE BANKS WEIGH MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Three major Japanese banks confirmed that they are in
discussions about a possible merger that would create the world's
largest financial institution, with $1.3 trillion in assets. An
alliance of the Industrial Bank of Japan, Fuji Bank and the
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank would be the biggest step taken by any
Japanese bank to overcome the effects of the country's protracted
recession, which has left the banking industry hobbled by bad
debts.
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN MARKETS, MADE IN GENEVA
</P>
<P>
   This week's volatility in stock markets across Asia can be
traced to a team of anonymous number-crunchers in Geneva, who made
changes in a closely watched Asian stock index. That a stock index
could exert so much influence across so many markets says a lot
about the changing nature of investing _ and the herd mentality of
investors as they venture back into recession-ravaged Asia. Market
Place.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE DEFICIT HURTS SHARE PRICES
</P>
<P>
   An unexpected worsening of the nation's trade deficit sent
stocks into a skid, and despite a partial recovery, prices closed
lower for the second straight session. The Nasdaq market slumped
36.3 points, or 1.37 percent, to 2,621.43, the biggest loss among
the main gauges. The Dow Jones industrial average, which was down
by as much as 118 points in the morning, ended with a loss of 27.54
points, or two-tenths of a percent, to 10,963.84.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of Treasury securities fell for the first time in four
days, as traders reacted to the unexpected widening in the trade
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO EXCHANGE TO EXTEND TRADING
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Stock Exchange, the nation's third-largest stock
market, said its board had approved a plan to offer after-hours
trading to both institutional and individual investors starting in
October _ the first exchange to do so.
</P>
<P>
   BROKER PLEADS GUILTY IN 2 COURTS
</P>
<P>
   Victor Wang, former chairman of Duke &AMP; Co., a defunct New York
brokerage firm, pleaded guilty to Federal charges of securities
fraud and money laundering in a case linked to Stratton Oakmont, a
defunct Long Island, N.Y., brokerage firm, and to New York state
charges of enterprise corruption.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT ADMITS SECURITY FLAWS
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft acknowledged there were security flaws in its recently
released Office 2000 software. Like those in the predecessor
program, Office 97, they would allow attacks from a malicious Web
site. Microsoft is releasing a patch to plug the holes.
</P>
<P>
   VISA WITH A LATIN BEAT
</P>
<P>
   Visa USA is taking Spanish-language advertising mainstream with
a Latin-culture commercial, specifically intending to reach people
in the 18-to-34-year-old range. BBDO New York, a unit of Omnicom
Group, created the spot, which is part of Visa's 14-year-old ``It's
everywhere you want to be'' campaign. Advertising. The ad is a nod
to the broad success of Latin celebrities like Ricky Martin and
Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   PARIBAS CHAIRMAN EXPECTED TO QUIT
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Paribas, Andre Levy-Lang, is expected to resign
next week following the company's takeover by Banque Nationale de
Paris. He had favored an alliance with another French rival,
Societe Generale.
</P>
</TEXT>
