<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-QUAKE-GAFAMILY20-COX     08-19 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-GAFAMILY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta family pieces together tragedy of Turkey earthquake
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice and Julie Bryant
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For 12 hours, as they lay pinned in the rubble of
their collapsed apartment building in northwest Turkey, Nizam Kilic
talked to his daughter-in-law, Jan. He told her to be strong.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kilic is married to one of Nizam's sons, Bubar, a Marietta
anesthesiologist. She and their five children were vacationing with
her in-laws in the resort town of Yalova when the five-story
building in which they were sleeping collapsed during Tuesday's
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Nizam Kilic did his best to comfort her amid the fear and the
pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she couldn't hear him anymore. He stopped talking,'' said
Cigdem Kilic, who is married to another of Nizam's three sons and
also lives in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Nizam Kilic and four of Jan's children died. Nizam Kilic's wife,
Turkan, suffered severe head injuries and is partially paralyzed.
She remained in critical condition Thursday night at a Turkish
hospital. Jan Kilic also suffered head injuries but was conscious
at American Hospital in Istanbul. One daughter, Natalie, 3 1/2, was
pulled out of the rubble. Her only injury: a black eye.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, as fresh details emerge, the magnitude of disaster
grows more clear.
</P>
<P>
   The death count climbed Thursday to more than 7,000. But that
number is expected to increase significantly, with 35,000 listed as
missing. Another 34,000 were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The five Kilic family members were the only confirmed American
fatalities so far.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Natalie's siblings _ Jeffrey, 6, Jennifer, 5, and
David, 2 _ died instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Jan heard the youngest baby cry a little bit,'' Cigdem
Kilic said. ``Then she didn't hear her anymore either.''
</P>
<P>
   That youngest baby, Katie, was born Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the confusion and lack of communication, word is
starting to get back to Georgia about what happened early Tuesday
morning halfway around the world. Jan Kilic's parents were able to
talk with her by phone for the first time Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's had some head swelling that's going down and some lower
back and neck problems, but she's expected to make a full
recovery,'' said her brother, Billy Kemp. ``She's tired, but
clinging to the fact that Natalie survived.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a hope she didn't have at first.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 hours, she lay trapped beneath rubble. Then she and her
mother-in-law were rescued minutes apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jan was on her way to a makeshift hospital and she thought all
of her children were dead,'' Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie was pulled out 12 hours later. Jan Kilic would not find
out about her daughter's survival for nearly two days.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Kilic's own rescue came about because of the valor and
determination of emergency officials and some of her husband's
family still living in Turkey. They refused to leave the area
despite a mandatory evacuation because of a gas leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was because of their extraordinary efforts that there were
three survivors out of 100-plus people who died in that building,''
Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kilics are the only known survivors of the building
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``His relatives risked their lives by climbing and digging
through the rubble,'' said Cigdem Kilic. ``One of them saw
something in the corner, but someone said that person was dead.
Then his cousin saw dust moving up and down around her nose and
realized she was breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   The rescuers lifted Jan Kilic up and found Jennifer underneath.
Jennifer and Jeffrey ``looked like they were sleeping,'' Cigdem
Kilic said. Katie and David were more badly injured.
</P>
<P>
   Bubar Kilic and his two brothers, also Marietta
anesthesiologists, arrived in Turkey on Thursday. Bubar, who had
stayed in Marietta, was supposed to join his family this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting Jan Kilic in the hospital, the three brothers
took an ambulance by ferry to the seaside resort of Yalova to bring
the bodies back to Istanbul. Yalova is a popular vacation
destination for many middle class Turkish families, and the Kilics
have a summer home there.
</P>
<P>
   Babur Kilic and his older brothers, Timur and Cengiz, found the
bodies at a makeshift morgue at an ice skating rink.
</P>
<P>
   Timur and Cengiz Kilic carried out the bodies in their arms and
transported them by ambulance to the morgue at American Hospital in
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babur has not seen the kids yet,'' said Cigdem Kilic, Timur's
wife. ``Tim did not want him to see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Timur Kilic described for his wife a scene of devastation unlike
any he could ever imagine.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband said this was the worst day of his life,'' she
said. ``He was crying. He's a doctor and he sees dead people, and
he said he's never seen anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kilics want to bring Jan and Turkan back to the United
States for treatment as soon as possible. They also want to bring
back the other family members for burial in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in touch with the State Department, arranging
transportation for the bodies to be flown back here,'' Billy Kemp
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Marietta, worried family and friends continued their vigil,
some searching for news, others seeking solace. Few found meaning.
</P>
<P>
   At the two-story east Cobb home of Jan and Bubar Kilic, a steady
flow of cars pulled into the driveway. Inside, family members who
had come from out of state tried to bring comfort.
</P>
<P>
   In a family room, they talked quietly as they watched CNN
coverage of the rescue efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, teachers and administrators from the Casa dei Bambini
Montessori, where four of the Kilic children attended, held a quiet
service at the Holy Family Church in Cobb County. School director
Florence Johnson said the school would continue to support the
family through prayers and close communication.
</P>
<P>
   Parishioners at Mount Vernon Baptist Church, where Jan Kilic
worshipped, remembered a vibrant and loving family.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Sam Boyd said Jan Kilic joined about six years ago and
is involved in a women's Bible study, Sunday school and worship
services. Her husband, known to his friends as ``Bobby,'' is not a
member but comes occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Jan and Babur met as students at the University of Alabama, Boyd
said. She's an electrical engineer and he was a math undergraduate
before receiving his medical degree there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a great blend in the sense that she's a very active
business person with a great amount of skill and knowledge, and
she's a very sensitive and nurturing mother,'' Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Others couldn't help but think of the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite devastating,'' said Gwen Jenkins, preschool
minister at Mount Vernon. ``I've been in a state of shock.
Different ones of them will flash in my mind, and I know I'll never
get to see them again _ not in this life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll not get to see Jennifer coming down the hall with her
blonde hair swinging. Little David always had a smile on his face.
He was learning to talk and was always trying to tell me something.
Of course, I didn't always know what it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Natalie is just getting to the verbal stage and is
expressing herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeffrey was always the big brother. He was always looking out
for the little ones. When Jan would drop them off at their
classrooms, he would tell them, `Go on in, now''' and make sure
they got in OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Katie, the youngest, was so sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be quite a loss for our preschool.''
</P>
<P>
   She said faith will help them get through this ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that one day we'll get to see them again,'' Jenkins
said. ``When we get to heaven, they'll welcome us. Were it not for
our faith in our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ, I can't imagine
being able to cope with something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The first test will come this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what Sunday morning is going to hold,'' Boyd
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff writer Gayle White contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   HOW YOU CAN HELP
</P>
<P>
   Donations to help earthquake victims can be made to:
</P>
