bought at least five of the most expensive works of art ever sold
at auction, but only one, van Gogh's ``Sunflowers,'' is still in
Japan, in the corporate collection of Yasuda Fire &AMP; Marine
Insurance Co. The other four -- including ``Portrait of Dr.
Gachet,'' Renoir's ``Au Moulin de la Galette'' and Picasso's
``Acrobat and Young Harlequin'' and ``Pierrette's Wedding'' -- have
left Japan, apparently ending up in Europe or the U.S., along with
countless other paintings bought by the Japanese when their bubble
economy was at its peak. (New York Times Photo)
