<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3469 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG)     08-19 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADY EXCITED ABOUT BIGGER OFFENSIVE LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A couple of times a day, Marcus Brady gets a
chance to see the improvement in Cal State Northridge's offensive
linemen. As the Matadors' starting quarterback, Brady couldn't be
happier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a big difference,'' Brady said. ``They're out there
working hard and getting them in shape. Coach (Bob) Connelly is
getting them ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady gained 392 yards rushing as a freshman last year. He lost
360, mainly because he was sacked 49 times.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the pounding he was taking last year, some
wondered if Brady, the Big Sky Conference's Newcomer of the Year,
was going to be able to take three more years of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Ponciano, CSUN's former head coach, hired Connelly away from
Texas A&AMP;M, where Connelly was a graduate assistant, and brought in
massive offensive linemen like Johnny Acosta (6-foot-5, 300 pounds)
and Ernie Fierro (6-4, 300).
</P>
<P>
   Acosta and Fierro, along with incumbent starters Julio Alcala
(6-4, 285) and Keith Kincaid (6-4, 285) have helped the offensive
line become a strength instead of a weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all started in the spring, when I got here,'' Connelly
said. ``It is a young group, but (the players) have made great
strides. Coach Ponciano wanted more toughness; a more physical
offensive line to help the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady says a better offensive line means a better running game _
CSUN averaged just 84 yards per game on the ground last season _
which, in turn, means less obvious passing situations where he can
get sacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we can keep defenses on their heels,'' Connelly
said. ``There's no question that will be a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   The line has been bolstered in the past two days by the addition
of Javier Ortiz, a sophomore transfer from Fresno State. Ortiz, who
is 6-2 and 290, already has shown versatility to play center or
guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors also could get more help if Taffe Aina (6-5, 305)
becomes eligible. Aina has dropped almost 50 pounds since spring
and if he is cleared to play will start at left guard.
</P>
<P>
   __ Butterflies: Bruce Molock hears the grunts, the snarls and
the chippy comments from the defense when he lines up in the
backfield during team drills.
</P>
<P>
   Molock is a freshman from Antelope Valley High. He and fellow
rookie running backs Marquis Brignac (Taft), Brandon McElvaine
(Highland) and fullback Crayton Milton (St. Francis) are targeted
when they get into the backfield _ simply because they are
freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, I was a little intimidated,'' said Molock,
an All-Golden League selection last year. ``It's like playing in an
all-star game but faster.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Bumps and bruises: Senior noseguard Sean Beard hurt his right
leg in a field-goal drill Thursday morning. Beard, who broke the
same leg when he was leg-whipped in the Southern Utah game last
season, was helped off the field and was walking with a cane an
hour later.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman offensive lineman Isaac Aronson, who at 6-7 is the
tallest player on the team, broke his right hand last week and
hasn't been able to do more than run. Aronson was expected to
redshirt this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ready to go: Sean Atkins shows up for every practice, knowing
that even if his eligibility issue is resolved, he won't be able to
play this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Atkins, a sophomore defensive back from San Fernando High,
is hoping to get three full years with CSUN instead of two. He
transferred in the spring from fellow Big Sky member Sacramento
State, and under NCAA rules, players who transfer within a
conference must sit out two years.
</P>
<P>
   But Atkins said he wasn't supposed to get any scholarship money
until the spring, after he played sparingly last fall. He decided
to transfer to CSUN when his younger brother, Bryson, a defensive
back from Alemany High, signed with the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Shannon, CSUN's compliance director, is working with the
NCAA to get Sean Atkins cleared to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Shannon) is working on it as we speak,'' Atkins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
