<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ALCOA-REYNOLDS-ART-65     08-19 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOA-REYNOLDS-ART-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALCOA AND REYNOLDS REACH MERGER AGREEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alcoa Inc., the world's oldest and largest aluminum company,
announced Thursday that it had agreed to merge with the No. 3
producer, Reynolds Metals Co., in a relatively swift negotiation
that left some Reynolds shareholders grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   In an all-stock deal, Reynolds' shareholders will receive 1.06
shares of Alcoa for each Reynolds share. At Wednesday's closing
price of $66.875 for Alcoa, this deal would be valued at around
$4.4 billion, or $70.8875 a share for Reynolds' stockholders. While
accepting this deal, however, Reynolds left open the door for
another buyer to come along, as both companies agreed to allow
Reynolds to solicit takeover bids for the next 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoa, which made its first bid for Reynolds last week, agreed
to this somewhat unusual clause because Alcoa executives believed
that Reynolds would find no other bidders, people close to the
merger talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 day shopping-window allows Reynolds, which has been
looking for a potential buyer for nearly a year now, to placate
shareholders who have been angry at Reynolds' management for not
selling the company earlier and for more money.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the charge against Reynolds is Richard Grubman, managing
director at Highfields Capital Management, a Boston firm that owns
6 percent of Reynolds. In a letter to the Reynolds' board Thursday,
Grubman said, ``You have allowed Alcoa to steal the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubman was especially angered by a rejection last March by
Jeremiah J. Sheehan, the chief executive of Reynolds, of a
1.42-a-share exchange offer from Alcoa. At the time Sheehan was
telling shareholders that no one was interested in acquiring
Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your behavior is reprehensible,'' Grubman wrote, adding, ``You
sold us out.'' Grubman also accused Reynolds of ``squandering $2
billion of shareholder value'' and said that Reynolds ``effectively
lied to shareholders'' and ``has reached a new low in corporate
governance.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Grubman nor Reynolds would comment on this letter
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-day solicitation window also allows McCook Metals, owned
by the Chicago investment firm Michigan Partners, to make a bid, if
it is interested. Last week, McCook wrote to Reynolds expressing
interest in topping Alcoa's bid, but provided no details.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers close to the deal said McCook did not seem serious:
``There was no price, no financing, no nothing. It was all air,''
one said. Calls to McCook Metals were not returned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to make it difficult for anyone to halt this merger, the
agreement between Alcoa and Reynolds also contains a $100 million
break-up fee, which would increase the cost of acquiring Reynolds
by about $1.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the deal is completed, Alcoa would still remain the
world's No. 2 aluminum producer after APA, a new company to be
created by the three-company, two-continent merger of Alcan
Aluminium Ltd. of Canada, Pechiney in France and Alusuisse Lonza
Group of Switzerland. That three-way $17.6 billion merger, was
announced last week and would create a huge global competitor for
Alcoa, with projected revenues of $21.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   An Alcoa-Reynolds merger would create a company with $20.5
billion in projected revenues and 120,000 employees in 36
countries. But nearly all those revenues would be derived from
aluminum production, while around $4 billion of APA's projected
revenues would come from non-aluminum assets. This merger wave was
brought on by global overcapacity for aluminum and prices that have
plunged to five-year lows.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is good for Alcoa, good for Reynolds shareholders
and good for the aluminum industry,'' said Richard Aldrich, an
analyst with Lehman Brothers. ``With fewer players, there will be
less redundant capacity, which is a long-term plus for the
industry.'' Aldrich dismissed Grubman's complaints as ``20-20
hindsight'' and said he doubted another buyer would come along, but
cautioned that ``anything is possible.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Alcoa and Reynolds executives said they expected that combining
the two companies would realize around $200 million in cost savings
_ a number some analysts said was low _ and they expected antitrust
problems to be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious antitrust problem is that the two companies
would represent more than 50 percent of the smelting capacity in
the United States, although analysts say the companies will
probably argue that smelting, a low-margin commodity business,
should be viewed as a global industry, and not as a domestic one.
</P>
<P>
   Other problem areas are minimal. Reynolds is best known for
making such consumer products as aluminum foil and beverage cans,
while Alcoa makes aluminum for heavy industries like planes and
autos. While both companies serve the auto industry, Alcoa is
bigger in castings like engine blocks, while Reynolds makes
aluminum components for wheels.
</P>
<P>
   The two overlap in producing alumina, a compound from which
aluminum is produced. In 1997, Reynolds sold an Alabama rolling
mill to another buyer, after the government rejected its sale to
Alcoa. As a result, say analysts, another antitrust impediment was
removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't mean that there won't be some asset divestiture,''
said James Kelleher, an analyst with Argus Research. ``But I do
believe that the companies are complementary. Alcoa's management
has said that Reynolds begins where Alcoa stops and I agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Alain J.P. Belda, Alcoa's chief executive, said, ``The new
company will be better positioned to address the ongoing
globalization of the metals industry and the new competitive
landscape this is creating.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds' chief executive, Sheehan, said, ``Reynolds
shareholders will receive an attractive price for their shares and
still have the opportunity to participate in the upside potential
of the combined company.''
</P>
<P>
   John Tumazos, an analyst at Sanford Bernstein, said the proposed
union ``creates no problems, only opportunities.'' His only concern
was that the automakers, as major users of aluminum, might seek to
lock in long-term, low-price aluminum supply contracts from the
combined company to protect themselves from any potential
monopolistic pricing.
</P>
</TEXT>
