<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOLLAR-YEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLLAR'S DROP AGAINST YEN RENEWS FOCUS ON U.S. POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also JAPAN-BANKS, ASIA-MARKETPLACE, TRADE-REPORT) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An apparent shift in Japanese policy and the report of a record
U.S. trade deficit helped send the dollar lower Thursday against
the Japanese yen and the new European currency, the euro.
</P>
<P>
   But the dollar, despite its recent 4 percent plunge against the
yen, remains healthy against the world's other major currencies.
Against the euro, which was predicted by many analysts to rally
after its January debut, the dollar is still up almost 10 percent
this year. The dollar also rose Thursday against the currencies of
two of the United States' major trading partners, Canada and
Mexico. Adjusted for trade patterns, the dollar is just above its
20-year average value against all its trading partners, according
to Chase Manhattan Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, there has not been across-the-board selling against
the dollar,'' said Paul Podolosky, a currency strategist at
BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts are worried that the growing American trade
deficit could be a problem for the dollar in the future, as it was
in the late 1980s. In addition, if the American economy begins to
slow down as the rest of the world is reviving, that could put more
downward pressure on the dollar as investors leave the American
markets and the dollar to invest in markets that appear to have
more potential for growth.
</P>
<P>
   In these circumstances, however, a falling dollar would not
necessarily be a problem for the United States, analysts said, as
long as the decline was orderly and not extreme.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading Thursday, it cost $1.06300 to buy one euro
compared with $1.05230 on Wednesday, a 1 percent fall in the
dollar's value. Against the Japanese yen, the move was smaller
because much bigger declines came earlier in the week. On Thursday,
the dollar slipped to 111.40 yen against the dollar, down from
112.03 on Wednesday. The dollar fell 1.8 percent against the yen on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It has been the selloff of the dollar against the Japanese yen
that has refocused attention on the dollar and, at the same time,
American policy toward it. During this slide against the yen, some
analysts have begun to raise questions about Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers' commitment to the strong-dollar policy of his
predecessor, Robert Rubin. Although Summers has supported the
policy in public statements, doubts about his commitment _ even if
mistaken _ have undermined the dollar a little, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar selloff and yen rally began in early July when the
dollar was worth about 122 yen. Since then, the value of the dollar
against the yen has declined more than 9 percent. The driving force
has been the move by big institutional investors back into the
Japanese stock market, which has soared this year. That move was
prompted by the expectation _ based so far on just one quarter's
economic data _ that the Japanese economy is turning around.
</P>
<P>
   The accelerated move this week was set off by comments from
Japanese officials that analysts have interpreted to indicate that
the government is not ready to intervene in the currency markets to
support the yen. That is a switch from a policy of aggressive
intervention to weaken the yen earlier this summer. In June and
July, the Japanese sold yen for dollars six times in an effort to
keep the value of the yen from rising.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government, through the Bank of Japan, had
intervened because of the fear that the rapidly appreciating yen _
as the dollar declines _ would undermine the economy. A stronger
yen makes Japanese exports more expensive and less competitive. And
a slump in exports could derail what is, at best, a struggling
economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think intervention is imminent,'' said Karen Parker,
director of currency research at Chase Manhattan Bank. Until this
week, many traders expected intervention at the 110-yen level.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for the switch, Ms. Parker said, is the
realization by the Japanese that intervention, without the
participation of the United States, is not working. In addition,
Japanese officials are hoping that their economy is on the rebound,
which would make the rebound in the yen less worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   With the apparent change in policy, Ms. Parker said she thought
the yen could move to a value of 105 to 108 to the dollar. At that
point, she said, intervention would be more likely.
</P>
<P>
   The rally in the euro on Thursday was started by a report that
the German business-confidence index, compiled by the IFO economic
research institute in Munich, rose to 93.6 in July from 92.9 in
June, the third consecutive monthly gain. A strong increase in the
confidence report in July helped set off the rally in the euro at
the end of last month. At that point, the euro, the new currency of
11 European countries, was down 13 percent for the year. Since
then, it has risen almost 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, the U.S. Commerce Department announced that the
trade deficit jumped to $24.6 billion in June, a record.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit has not been a problem for the dollar or the
American economy so far. In fact, as the deficit was increasing
over the last year, the dollar was strengthening.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parker said the deficit could be more of a drag on the
dollar now, given the changing circumstances of the world economy.
Last year, when Asian economies were in recession and Europe was
sluggish, it was easy to attract foreign investment here to cover
the deficit. But with Europe and Asia rebounding, that could get a
little more difficult. And to attract investors who are seeing new
opportunities elsewhere, the dollar may have to weaken, interest
rates rise and stocks stop climbing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
