<HEADER>
A3480 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-RECRUIT-RECRUIT_SFCHR     08-19 1675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECRUIT-RECRUIT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Looking for a Few Good Recruits
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Florenda De Vera woke before dawn two days ago, kissed civilian
life goodbye and took off on a journey that probably will change
her forever _ a four-year enlistment in the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more excited than scared,'' De Vera confided in a phone
call before her departure for Lackland, Texas, where the Air Force
puts recruits through six weeks of basic training.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old graduate of San Francisco's Lowell High School
explained why she took what some of her friends consider a radical
departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of cousins and friends who go through college but
don't have a stable job, they just party,'' she said. ``I don't see
myself that way. I want to succeed at an early age.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sentiment, music to the ears of military recruiters, is a
song they don't hear often enough these days. For the first time
since the draft ended in 1973, some services can't find enough
recruits to fill their ranks. The Pentagon was shocked last year
when the Navy fell 7,000 recruits shy of its target of 55,000 new
``boots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time any service missed its goal,'' said
Defense Department spokesman Tom Begines. ``We think the booming
economy is a major factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the draft ended after the Vietnam War, the military has
been able to fill its ranks by appeals to patriotism and adventure
as well as through offers of job training and cash inducements. The
most popular lure has been the promise that Uncle Sam will pay up
to $50,000 to help veterans go to college after their four years of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   But Begines, an Army lieutenant colonel, said today's bullish
job market makes military service less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jobs are plentiful, and young people who want to go to college
have a lot more money available to them, especially from the
states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Navy seems to have rebounded from its 1998
recruiting shortfall, this year the Air Force expects to miss its
goal of 34,000 recruits by 2,000. The Army also may be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   These woes have sparked a few comments about reviving the draft,
but military planners don't consider that a serious possibility _
leaving recruiting brass like Lt. Col. Robert Spracale, who
oversees Air Force recruiting in Northern California, to face 18-
to 25-year-olds who have many options besides the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to attract kids who can earn $10 an hour at the
In-n-Out Burger,'' Spracale lamented. ``Why would they leave home
and momma while they can stay at home, buy a car and go to
school?''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is so concerned about hitting its recruiting
target that it recently employed its favorite tactic _ it called in
an air strike. A TV air strike, that is.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the Air Force will buy TV advertising this
year. It has a $76 million budget to broadcast four 30-second
spots, including one in Spanish, touting enlistment as a way to
earn money for college or learn job skills.
</P>
<P>
   The new Air Force campaign is part of the $268 million that all
four armed services will spend this year on TV ads. The largest
share, $95 million, will go to the Army, which has the biggest
recruiting target _ and has achieved just 86 percent of its goal so
far this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these sudden recruiting shortfalls, there seems to be
little serious discussion of reviving the draft. At a recent press
briefing, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said that while a few
members of Congress were talking about the draft, the House
Appropriations Committee voted to end funding for the Selective
Service _ the system that requires 18-year-olds to register in case
the draft is ever revived.
</P>
<P>
   Because they don't expect _ or necessarily want _ a return to
the draft, military planners have struggled to understand their
recruiting woes. Begines, the Pentagon spokesman, explained that
the economy isn't the only factor. Rather, the bullish civilian job
market seems to have tipped the scales on a good-news, bad-news
scenario that has been sneaking up on recruiters ever since the
collapse of the Berlin Wall in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for recruiters has been that since the end of the
Cold War, the armed forces have shrunk from 2.1 million in 1989 to
1.36 million today.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, has reduced recruiting needs, Begines said. A
decade ago, the armed forces had to sign up 300,000 youngsters a
year to fill their ranks. A smaller military means recruiters need
only 200,000 warm bodies this year.
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, the shrinking military also has hurt recruitment
by reducing the pool of veterans in civilian life. Research
indicates that more than 70 percent of new enlistees have a family
member with prior military service. Half have a parent who served.
With fewer role models around to encourage prospects, recruiters
have had a tougher time getting young people to consider military
service, Begines said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has done polls to measure the willingness of young
men _ and more recently young women _ to consider military service.
Willingness to serve has dropped since 1989. A decade ago, 26
percent of white men and 54 percent of black men professed a
willingness to serve. The latest polls show just 20 percent of
whites and 30 percent of blacks are ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Polls that break out Hispanic men, going back to the mid-'90s,
show they have the highest propensity to serve _ about 44 percent
in the 1998 survey.
</P>
<P>
   In regard to women, a 1998 survey reveals that 7 percent of
white women, 23 percent of black women and 26 percent of Hispanics
said they would consider enlistment in one of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The makeup of the armed forces during the past 20 years has
changed correspondingly, with greater numbers of minorities and
women in uniform. In 1976, whites constituted 76 percent of those
in uniform, blacks 16.6 percent, Hispanics 4.6 percent and Asian
Americans 2.8 percent. By 1997, whites had shrunk to 65 percent of
those in uniform, with blacks and Hispanics increasing to 22.1
percent and 7.5 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, women have increased their presence in the military,
rising from 4.6 percent of all military personnel in 1976 to 13.7
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Within these economic and societal trends, recruiters hustle to
meet their annual quotas. Ironically, despite its booming economy
and liberal reputation, Northern California produces close to its
share of enlistments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relative to our size, we are one of the strongest recruiting
areas in the nation for the Marine Corps,'' said Maj. Paul Kennedy,
whose Alameda command hit its goal last year, enlisting 1,065 good
men _ and 75 good women.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the Corps so far has been immune to the recruiting
woes facing the other services.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're familiar with marketing strategies, the Marines have
a well-identified brand,'' he said. ``Our pitch is: `Do you have
what it takes to be one of us.' That's different from the other
services, which stress what's in it for the recruit.''
</P>
<P>
   A sample of this approach occurred during the recent X-Games, a
sporting event held this year in San Francisco _ and one the
Marines has sponsored for the past three years. At this year's
event, the Marines set up a booth that challenged people to do
chin-ups. Over nine days, 7,000 men and women tried to do the 20
pull-ups needed to pass a Marine fitness test.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Hogue, a spokesman for the Army's Northern California
recruiting command in Sacramento, stressed incentives in explaining
how local Army recruiters hope to meet their goal of 5,200
enlistees _ when they're only at 60 percent of quota with less than
two months to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got a message: There's a $4,000 bonus for people who
enlist between now and September 30,'' Hogue said.
</P>
<P>
   Such bonuses are one-time rewards that get added to the normal
lures when services seem shy of reaching their quotas. By far the
most popular regular inducement to military service is the ability
to earn money to go to college. Recruits can earn up to $30,000 for
a two-year hitch, or $50,000 for a four-year commitment. The money
is paid out by the Veterans Administration after the person leaves
the service and enrolls in college. The top payment of $1,388 a
month can be used to pay for tuition, books and living expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have offered a few more incentives'' to lure recruits in
the strong economy, said Navy Cmdr. Nancy Sanders, who has sent
2,119 Northern Californians to ``boot camp'' this year, just
slightly ahead of her goal of 2,078. The Air Force's Northern
California enlistments also are just above target, with 1,386
prospects headed for basic, 10 more than quota.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, with the exception of the Army, which has raised its
local quota in the past three years, the flow of recruits from
Northern California is so strong that it undermines the argument
that the economic boom is causing the nation's enlistment
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some of us who believe the real problem is a lack of
leadership and poor morale in the armed forces,'' said Chuck
Spinney, a civilian analyst in the Pentagon. Spinney is part of a
small, unofficial group of civilian and military analysts who think
the military's real problem is that skilled military are not
re-enlisting in sufficient numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many soldiers and airmen believe their leaders are
politically correct careerists more interested in their own
promotions than taking care of the troops,'' Spinney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I totally and vehemently disagree,'' said Gen. Lloyd Newton,
commander of all recruiting and training for the Air Force. Newton,
who flew 269 combat missions in Vietnam also was the first African
American pilot to join the Thunderbird precision-flying unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can spell the word `computer,' much less operate one,
you have a job these days,'' Newton argued. ``We just didn't have
these recruiting problems before.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
