<SLUG> BC-QUANTUM-QUANTUM </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Quantum Plans to Lay Off 800  
 By Henry Norr 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Hard hit by fierce competition and shifting markets, Quantum
Corp.'s Hard Disk Drive Group plans to lay off 750 to 800 employees
and restructure its business to focus on drives for sub-$700 PCs.
</P>
<P>
   About 600 of the layoffs, which will take place over the next
year, will affect workers at the company's Milpitas headquarters,
warehouse and configuration center, according to a Quantum
spokeswoman. The others will come from company facilities in
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth of the low-cost PC market has become a challenge
for virtually every company in the PC supply chain, and Quantum is
no exception,'' said John Gannon, president of the drive group, in
a press release announcing the moves.
</P>
<P>
   Quantum is the volume leader in the PC hard-drive market. In the
three months ended June 27, its disk drive group suffered a net
loss of $43.2 million (52 cents per share). The loss ate up most of
the $51.5 million earned by the company's tape and storage systems
group, which makes higher-priced products for the corporate market.
</P>
<P>
   For the current quarter, analysts surveyed by First Call
predicted a loss of 56 cents per share for the hard-disk group.
Since last month, the two Quantum groups have been listed
separately as tracking stocks on the New York Stock Exchange,
replacing the company's previous stock.
</P>
<P>
   Quantum will take a special charge of $50 million in the current
quarter to cover the restructuring. Once complete, the changes will
generate savings of $100 million per year, the company estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Other makers of disk drives, including Seagate Technologies and
Western Digital, have also been suffering as the PC market shifts
toward lower-cost models. Quantum CEO Michael Brown has previously
attacked competitors for compounding the problem by seeking to
expand their market share by reducing prices.
</P>
<P>
   In yesterday's statement, he said, ``Quantum will continue to
speak out strongly against the destructive pricing practices that
are plaguing our industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown also said, though, that the newly announced restructuring
moves won't immediately alleviate the competitive price pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Katzive, vice president of Disk/ Trend, a research company
in Mountain View, said no single drive company is responsible for
the price wars. ``They're all in the soup together, and they all
blame each other.''
</P>
<P>
   He did say, though, that a new low-cost Seagate drive called the
U4 has put significant price pressure on all PC drivemakers.
</P>
<P>
   While Quantum will concentrate on low-cost drives and
consolidate some unannounced product-development programs, the
company said it will continue to compete in the high-performance
segment of the drive market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
