u f BC-WANG-FRAUD-400&AMP;ADD-NY     08-19 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANG-FRAUD-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BROKER PLEADS QUILTY IN STATE AND FEDERAL COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Victor Wang, the former chairman of Duke &AMP; Co., a
defunct New York brokerage firm, shuttled Thursday between
Manhattan and Brooklyn, pleading guilty to three crimes in two
courts.
</P>
<P>
   In New York Supreme Court Thursday morning, Wang pleaded guilty
to charges of enterprise corruption brought by Robert Morgenthau,
the Manhattan district attorney. In the afternoon, he pleaded
guilty to federal charges of securities fraud and money laundering
presented by Loretta E. Lynch, the U.S. attorney for the eastern
district of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's guilty plea in state court is part of a 109-count
indictment brought against Duke and its principals last May. He is
the 11th defendant to plead guilty to felony charges in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment accused Duke, Wang and 17 other employees of the
firm of defrauding investors by manipulating the prices of six
stocks that had been underwritten by the firm. Assisting Duke in
the manipulations, according to prosecutors, were two small
brokerage firms, Bishop Allen Inc. and the First Cambridge
Securities Corp. Both are defunct.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's plea to federal charges stems from a plan he designed
with two officers of Stratton Oakmont, a defunct Long Island
brokerage firm that was the subject of numerous regulatory run-ins
before it closed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to prosecutors, between 1991 and 1993, Wang bought
stocks underwritten by Stratton Oakmont in a phony account set up
to benefit the Stratton officers, whom prosecutors did not
identify. When the stocks were sold at a profit, Wang paid the
Stratton officers two-thirds of the after-tax profits from the
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's links to Stratton were strong. He started Duke in 1993
after he had been an executive at Stratton. He also served as chief
executive of Judicate Inc., a firm specializing in alternative
dispute resolution that was taken public by Stratton.
</P>
<P>
   Duke had two offices, one in midtown Manhattan, another in Long
Island. About 35,000 customers invested $171 million with Duke. The
firm was the subject of 26 regulatory actions before it closed in
March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant plea from a significant offender,'' said
James M. Kindler, chief assistant district attorney in Manhattan.
Kindler would not comment on what information Wang might be able to
provide his office on other investigations active there.
</P>
<P>
   Wang, 34, faces a maximum sentence of 50 years in prison under
both courts' charges. Federal prosecutors are also seeking $650,000
in illegal proceeds made by Wang. He will probably be sentenced in
the fall. A telephone call to his lawyer Thursday was not
returned. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thursday's pleadings indicate that the turf battle over Wang
that erupted between federal and state prosecutors in May has been
resolved. At that time, federal prosecutors removed Wang from a
cell in Rikers Island, where he was being held after his indictment
by a New York State grand jury, without notifying the district
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   It was feared that Wang would agree to plead guilty to federal
charges as a way to avoid state liability. Under New York's double
jeopardy law, someone pleading guilty to a federal crime cannot be
prosecuted for a similar crime by the state.
</P>
<P>
   But with Wang pleading guilty in both state and federal court
Thursday, it is clear that the prosecutors have made peace.
</P>
<P>
   Wang was also the subject Thursday of a complaint brought by the
Securities and Exchange Commission. The SEC accused Wang and three
Duke brokers of orchestrating a huge market manipulation intended
to bolster the stock price of Paravant Computer Systems, now known
as Paravant Inc., which Duke had taken public in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg A. Thaler, Charles T. Bennett and Jeffrey S. Honigman,
former principals and brokers at Duke, participated in the
manipulation, which generated more than $10 million in illegal
profits, the SEC said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
