<HEADER>
A3484 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BESTBUY-BESTBUY_SFCHR     08-19 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTBUY-BEST </SLUG>
 BUY _ SF CHRON  
 Best Buy Ready for Opening Of 5 Stores
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Carol Emert &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Consumers will have more shopping choices _ and electronics
retailers will have more competition _ today (friday)  &LR; when Best
Buy opens five megastores in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The grand opening will leave Best Buy, the largest electronics
chain in the country, with seven stores in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   The stores opening today are in Dublin, Milpitas, Pinole,
Pleasant Hill and San Carlos. Best Buy opened a Marin City store
earlier this year and one in Santa Rosa in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   By next fall, Best Buy, which is based in Eden Prairie, Minn.,
intends to open an additional nine superstores, including three in
San Francisco, bringing its total to 16 in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming in and they intend to win,'' said Mary Tolan,
global managing partner for retail with Anderson Consulting.
</P>
<P>
   After operating in the red as recently as two years ago, Best
Buy has staged a remarkable turnaround and is now considered the
most aggressive company in its sector.
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy chief executive Richard Schulze, who founded his
company as a single store called Sound of Music in 1966,
demonstrated a touch of that aggressiveness yesterday morning while
reviewing the new Best Buy store in San Carlos.
</P>
<P>
   Schulze squinted at a sign towering over Highway 101 in which
Best Buy's name is displayed below that of Breuner's, an adjacent
furniture store. ``Check the lease and try to get our name on
top,'' Schulze directed one of his lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy is now going head-to-head with Circuit City, which is
headquartered in Richmond, Va., and operates 19 stores in this
area; Burlingame's Good Guys, which runs 15; and smaller merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Good Guys is considered vulnerable. The company has been racking
up losses for three years and is undergoing a painful
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The company's founder, Ron Unkefer, returned to lead Good Guys
last month, taking over from former chief executive Robert Gunst.
He has closed three departments, suspended plans to remodel and
open stores, and has discontinued sales of computers and home
office equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Gordon, an analyst with Banc of America Securities in
San Francisco, estimates that Good Guys stores located near Best
Buys will lose at least 10 percent of their sales, ``which is a lot
for a retailer that's struggling anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it is difficult to track sales shifting between
retailers, Schulze said he believes most of the dollars Best Buy
has attracted from other retailers in the Los Angeles area have
come from Good Guys.
</P>
<P>
   But Unkefer said smaller dealers are the ones who suffer most.
``Our sales volumes for our Southern California stores and our
margins are very similar to the margins and sales volumes of our
Northern California stores,'' which have not had to compete with
Best Buy, Unkefer said. ``So I don't see the impact of Best Buy on
our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy tends to become the dominant retailer in its markets,
with about 20 percent of the market share in its categories, said
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Computers and accessories make up about 35 percent of Best Buy's
sales, televisions and stereos make up 28 percent and software and
CDs account for 23 percent. The remaining 9 percent is in sales of
large appliances such as ranges and refrigerators, warranties and
services.
</P>
<P>
   Best Buy's sales totaled $10 billion last year, compared to $9.3
billion for Circuit City and $928.5 million for Good Guys, which
sells consumer electronics almost exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Unkefer said Good Guys stores offer twice the selection of
consumer electronics merchandise as Best Buy, including several
high-end brands, such as Mitsubishi, that aren't carried by mass
merchants like Best Buy and Circuit City.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 25 percent of Good Guys merchandise can be found at
Best Buy, ``and our prices on the items where we overlap are very
competitive,'' Unkefer said.
</P>
<P>
   Schulze said the biggest difference between Best Buy and its
rivals is that Best Buy sales associates are not as pushy because
they do not work on commission.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Good Guys, Best Buy is trying to push higher-margin,
high-tech products like high-definition TVs and digital camcorders.
Its stores feature demonstration counters where consumers can try
the latest equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The new Best Buy stores are shiny and attractive, but still have
a mass-merchant, warehouse feel, with towering ceilings and
linoleum floors. Cardboard boxes holding refrigerators and other
appliances line the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Newer Good Guys stores are far more upscale, with comfortable
living room areas where shoppers can sit on sofas and try a variety
of televisions and stereo systems. The stores also showcase sexy
new technologies like thin-screen TVs, adding an element of
entertainment that Best Buy stores do not enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an underserved market for the top half of the line,''
said Unkefer. ``When it's done correctly, (high-end companies like
Good Guys) can thrive and prosper ... by offering the next level up
in quality of customer service and amenities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL;
</P>
