A3486 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ESCRIP-ESCRIP_SFCHRON     08-19 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCRIP-ESCRIP </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Safeway Signs On With Net Scrip Firm
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Stein &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Electronic Scrip Inc., which has devised an Internet fund-raising
scheme for schools and nonprofits, is about to get a big boost from
grocery-store giant Safeway, which said it is signing up to
participate in the company's plan.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Scrip's product is called eScrip. It's an online
version of scrip _ gift-certificates that schools and nonprofits
buy from businesses, such as grocery stores and restaurants, at a
discount and then resell at face value to their supporters,
pocketing the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Paper-based scrip programs have been around for 10 years, but
the organizations that use them to raise funds say they can be a
hassle. Schools have to raise the money to buy the certificates
upfront. Also, they must rustle up volunteers to sell scrip and
protect the certificate from loss or theft.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Lambert, a Safeway spokeswoman, said the grocery chain
plans to phase out its participation in all paper-based scrip
programs in the near future and focus solely on eScrip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be on the cutting edge of technology,'' she said.
``And frankly, schools and parents are tired of dealing with paper.
EScrip is just much more convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   With the eScrip system, parents or other members register their
credit card and ATM numbers with San Mateo's Electronic Scrip.
Every time they use the cards to make a purchase from a
participating merchant, a portion of the sale is donated
automatically to the preselected organization of their choice.
Unlike paper scrip, which is free to participating parents, eScrip
costs $10 a year for each person who registers credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Scrip, which just launched in January, also is
responsible for recruiting merchants to participate. So far, it has
signed on smaller grocery stores such as Draegers and Andronico's,
and a host of other businesses, including Crate &AMP; Barrel and Budget
Rent a Car. But Safeway is its biggest coup to date.
</P>
<P>
   That's because about 80 percent of all funds raised through
scrip come from grocery stores. Also, having a marquee name on its
roster will help Electronic Scrip attract more people and
organizations to its program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect our membership to grow from about a thousand people
currently to hundreds of thousands of people in California alone
within the next 18 months,'' said Ian Diery, CEO of Electronic
Scrip.
</P>
<P>
   Designated schools or charities will receive 2 to 4 percent of
their supporters' Safeway eScrip purchases, depending on how much
they spend a month.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Carr, a parent who is active in the Portola Valley
Schools Foundation, which participates in eScrip, said the program
has a big influence on where parents shop. ``This will give Safeway
a real advantage over Lucky,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Scrip agreed to an exclusive relationship with
Safeway, meaning that eScrip will not be available at other major
grocery chains, such as Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  There are 190 Lucky stores in Northern California, compared
with 215 stores for Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Enochson, a spokeswoman for the Lucky chain, said loyal
shoppers should not despair. She said the company plans to roll out
its own fund-raising program called Community Partners Card that it
will manage itself.
</P>
<P>
   Program members will receive a separate card that can be used at
any Lucky store. The amount of their purchases will be recored
automatically, and a percentage of the sale will be transferred via
check to the appropriate organization. Enochson did not say when
the program would go into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Esber, a parent in the Palo Alto Unified School District,
which also participates in eScrip, admitted that the program might
force some parents to change their shopping habits from Lucky to
Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents have raised that issue with us,'' Esber said. ``We are
certainly not in this to promote any particular vendor. We just
want to raise money for our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
