<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3495 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-MUSTANG-AR     08-19 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-MUSTANG-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADDLING MUSTANGS FOR A BIRTHDAY RIDE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 22) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My first Mustang, a used 1968 hardtop with a 289 V8, came with
the basic Mustang handling upgrade: two sandbags in the trunk. For
better grip in snow _ as well as a car that didn't try to change
direction each time it hit a bump in hard cornering _ a little
ballast helped.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 35 years after the Mustang's introduction, it is time to
dump the sand for something more sophisticated: an independent rear
suspension. Alas, this is available only on the 8,095 SVT Mustang
Cobras built this year, at a $4,000 premium over similarly equipped
GTs. Other Mustangs, including the GT, keep the old live axle.
</P>
<P>
   The new suspension is a Mustang watershed, giving the car
newfound sureness and putting it within range of European sport
coupes _ in road manners, if not in overall sophistication. Is it
worth the premium? After comparing the models, I will say this: The
Cobra is as different from the GT as two cars sharing the same
basic body, transmission and frame (and, to Ford's chagrin, maybe
even the same power output) can be.
</P>
<P>
   After the first couple of fast corners in the Cobra, your fear
of sewer-grate apexes disappears. The car goes where you point it
on turn-in, and it doesn't change its mind when the first bump
comes along. A normal slight penchant for understeer (a tendency to
move ahead on a turn) can be pushed into oversteer (turning too
sharply) whenever the driver, and not not the car, decides.
</P>
<P>
   And the slightly heavier independent rear suspension _ a modular
unit that bolts onto the same mounting points as the live axle _
and slightly lighter V8 improve the Cobra's weight distribution to
about 55/45 front-rear. (The GT is about 57/43.)
</P>
<P>
   The Cobra's ride is also significantly more comfortable. Road
joints are far less jarring, and the noise level is improved to
where the Cobra is almost tolerable for a long trip _ although that
may change when Ford replaces its exhaust system to help correct a
horsepower shortage.
</P>
<P>
   In the GT, I had to blast the optional Mach 460 sound system to
appreciate its virtues. (Tip: Keep the engine revving high enough
to mask the whine from the GT's drivetrain.) In the Cobra _ which
has the same sound system as standard equipment _ classical music
is within the realm of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Cobra also has standard all-speed traction control, a nice
addition on wet surfaces. That is now an option on all other
Mustangs, and although the system engages heavy-handedly, it's
worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Cobra's engine _ a 4.6-liter aluminum-block V8
with double overhead cams and 32 valves _ was supposed to get a
15-horsepower boost to 320 with redesigned intake ports and
combustion chambers, giving it 60 more horsepower than the
single-overhead-cam, 16-valve engine in the Mustang GT. So after a
week in the jackrabbit GT, imagine getting even more power _ with a
20th-century rear suspension, too.
</P>
<P>
   Well, don't tax your imagination. At first, I thought that the
Cobra _ meant to be more like a European GT car _ had been tuned to
be more mannerly. But I, like a number of Cobra buyers, was left
with the feeling that some of those 320 horses had been rustled.
Gear ratios in the five-speed manuals are the same, and the
manufacturer's power and torque curves showed little clear
difference.
</P>
<P>
   The Cobra had fewer than 400 miles on the odometer, so the
clutch shouldn't have been slipping. Maybe my memory of the GT was?
As it turned out, my mind had not failed me _ this time, anyway;
Ford is preparing new intake manifolds and exhaust systems to bring
the cars up to the advertised power level.
</P>
<P>
   As it now stands, my right foot preferred the GT. If you just
want to flex your muscle car, whatever mischief you could wreak
with the Cobra you could do as easily with the GT. And if the GT's
engine roar gets tiresome, you can putter around in the 2,000-rpm
range without the car's bogging down. Beyond 2,000 rpm the GT and
the Cobra have lots of passing power.
</P>
<P>
   This may all change to the Cobra's benefit once the new parts
are added, but if you are thinking of buying an SVT Cobra, consider
a comparison test drive with a GT, to be sure you're getting both
the better handling and the extra horsepower you're paying for.
</P>
<P>
   The GT convertible's handling wasn't exactly terrible, thanks to
some suspension improvements, and anyone who hasn't driven the new
Cobra should find the new GT an improvement over the old one. But
over bumps, the twitchy back end reappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect the GT's ride to be smooth. The optional
P245/45 tires on 17-inch aluminum rims transmitted road joints and
uneven pavement with little dampening and lots of noise. The
optional leather buckets with power adjustments for the driver
(standard on Cobra) were comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Both cars came with power four-wheel antilock disk brakes, and
they performed surely and evenly, with good feel. Steering was the
same in both _ power rack and pinion _ but felt heavier in the GT.
The system features numerous improvements, although the GT's
steering effort _ along with the bodybuilding clutch in both cars _
puts muscle on the drivers of these muscle cars.
</P>
<P>
   Interior trim on each car is little changed from the previous
Mustang's straightforward, plasticy and just good enough to keep
the car's price down without looking shoddy. When I took the GT
through a car wash, there were dribbles down the door windows. Both
cars had gearshift mechanisms that did not go from second to third
without some deliberate placement _ and into fourth without
whacking the fold-out cup holder.
</P>
<P>
   The Cobra and GT convertibles had some body flex over bumps, but
if my wife's '94 Mustang is an indicator, the hardtops probably
won't be rattlers. And the GT's boomy engine keeps you from
realizing how much exterior sound filters in with the top up.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hall, a spokesman for SVT _ Special Vehicle Team, Ford's
performance operation _ said there had been no discussions about
offering the Cobra's suspension on other versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``As always with the Cobra, it's the technology hotbed for the
Mustang,'' he said, but Ford likes to keep the Cobra distinct from
the GT, which is meant for muscle-car fans who pay relatively less.
</P>
<P>
   So for most Mustang buyers, there is no cure yet, but there is
hope.
</P>
<P>
   And sandbags.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: The Cobra beats the GT in the turns (as it
should); the GT holds its own on the straights (as it shouldn't).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3496 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-TONY-AYALA20-COX     08-19 1353
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TONY-AYALA20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ayala returns to ring after 16 years
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The opportunity to see if Tony Ayala Jr. was
indeed a changed man after 16 years in prison came even before the
first fight in his improbable comeback.
</P>
<P>
   At a pre-fight interview, his opponent, Manuel Esparza,
sauntered to the mike. Esparza, 21, was only 4 years old when Ayala
last fought in San Antonio. Back then, Ayala unleashed all the
savage fury he had in and outside of the ring, battering a helpless
Robbie Epps even after the referee had declared Ayala a winner in a
first-round technical knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Esparza, who will fight Ayala in a 10-round middleweight bout
tonight in San Antonio, was still shy of his third birthday in 1981
when Ayala pounded Jose Baltazar into submission in two rounds and
then spit on him to avenge a pre-fight insult to the boxer known as
Torito.
</P>
<P>
   Like a wine-sodden tourist in Pamplona, Esparza couldn't resist
running in front of a bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to ask you a quick question,'' he said, turning to
Ayala. ``Do you like mayonnaise or mustard? Because I'm going to be
feeding you some fist sandwiches all night, brother. Hopefully, a
lot of people will come out to see the fight to see what happens to
the ex-champ and the new champ.''
</P>
<P>
   If that weren't enough to get him gored, Esparza added, ``I told
him if I win, you buy me a beer. If he wins, I'll buy him a box of
Rogaine. If he's lucky, I'll buy him a case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my, that's worse than Robbie Epps in 1982,'' said emcee
Lester Bedford.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala stopped fiddling with his sunglasses and the wristband of
his watch. He got up to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been much for words, I've always let my fists talk
for me,'' Ayala said. ``He (Epps) crossed a boundary. As far as I
was concerned it got personal, it affected my family. This time
around the topic seems to be my hairline.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience, liberally sprinkled with Ayala friends and camp
members, laughed. But Ayala continued, ``You know what? I've never
considered myself a pretty boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come Friday I'll be in there every single minute of every
single round. Win, lose or draw I will leave my heart there. That
is a promise. I wish you good luck. I hope your bite is as tough as
your bark. I don't think it is. All through my career I've met guys
like you, guys who talk a lot of (garbage).''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' Esparza tried to fire back.
</P>
<P>
   A little later Ayala promised to again be the warrior of old in
the ring. ``My heart has not changed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A rising star falls
</P>
<P>
   In some ways Torito II, as Ayala is billed, is the same as the
original incarnation. He's short on political correctness, temper
and tact, long on machismo. It was, after all, Ayala's rage in the
ring _ and a left hand that could stun an elephant _ that set him
apart as a fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Former manager Lou Duva once said, ``Forget Leonard, forget
Hagler and yeah, forget Mike Tyson. Rocky Marciano and Tony Ayala
were the guys. Not even Muhammad Ali, great as he was, had it quite
like those two.''
</P>
<P>
   Until New Year's Day 1983, it looked like Ayala would get a
chance to rumble with the likes of Sugar Ray Leonard, Marvin Hagler
and Thomas Hearns, and earn the huge paydays such fights would
bring. He had a $750,000 title shot against Davey Moore on the
horizon. He was just 19, was 22-0 with 19 knockouts and was the
most feared force in boxing, walking through other boxers' best
shots like he was some kind of Terminator.
</P>
<P>
   But Ayala was feared outside of the ring as well. He was
involved with booze, drugs and violence.
</P>
<P>
   After a New Year's Eve party, Ayala, armed with a knife, broke
into the New Jersey apartment of a 30-year-old woman and raped her.
He was later found guilty of six charges, including aggravated
sexual assault, and sentenced to 15 to 30 years, 15 of which were
mandatory. When he first became eligible for release, he was turned
down. Finally, in April, after 16 years behind bars, Ayala was set
free.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have said Tony Ayala Sr. was part of his son's problems,
that his whole boxing clan of four sons had been raised like pit
bulls. Yet Ayala Sr. tears up when he relates, ``The fact that I
have my family together means a lot to me. Christmas, holidays,
birthdays _ we'd set a place for him at the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Jr. also said there's more than boxing this time around,
that friends and families have become more important to him. Yet
boxing was always what he did best.
</P>
<P>
   There were doubts, however, about whether he could pull off the
most remarkable comeback in boxing's history.
</P>
<P>
   Getting back up to speed
</P>
<P>
   Imagine eating prison food for 16 years, getting released to a
world where you can finally have anything your tastebuds desire,
and then having to lose almost 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'd have to be a sick puppy to enjoy training,''
Ayala said. ``It's boxing, bed. Boxing, bed. That's about all you
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ayala has run on the track and up and down hills at dawn under
his father's critical eye. He's worked and sparred in his father's
bandbox, iron bar-laced Zarzamora Street Gym on San Antonio's west
side. The gym is gradually getting a bright, fresh coat of green
and yellow paint, but it's still dark, stark and breathtakingly
hot. It's 90 degrees, and that's before the boxers start working
out and the curious drift in and sit on discarded bowling alleys
pews to watch Ayala. Then, the body heat pushes the gym's
temperature near the century mark.
</P>
<P>
   There, on a street lined with such businesses as Chino's Cantina
and a bail bondsman, Ayala has been getting work against quality
fighters, including local junior middleweight James ``Cowboy''
Coker, who is 19-1 and will fight Lalo Gutierrez on tonight's card.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Ayala was sporting a small shiner, courtesy of Coker.
``My dad runs the toughest boxing gym in the world. I hurt him. He
hurts me,'' Ayala explained.
</P>
<P>
   Coker said, ``He's 100 percent improved, or 75 percent from when
he started. It's a bunch. When you come in there and you haven't
sparred any, day after day you finally get back in the swing of
things. He knows how to box. He knows the punches to throw, he's
just got to get 'em going again. He likes to move in with his hands
up, cover up and then once he gets inside let a barrage go. That's
the way he still fights. Lead in a little with a pumping jab and
then once he gets to you, swarm you. He's a master at cutting off
the ring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing to me is a dangerous sport, and I know exactly what I'm
doing,'' Ayala warned. ``There are no time-outs. There are no
substitutes. You're in there, fighting with 8-ounce gloves, and
punches hurt. I haven't met an opponent yet who can stand up after
10 rounds of taking my shots. Nineteen of my fights ended in
knockouts. I was young then. I'm 36 now. But I have the confidence
that I can go as hard as I need to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubts about Ayala's condition and fear over backlash about his
criminal past have kept the sport's biggest promoters playing a
watch and wait game _ at least for the moment. Torito's career,
after all, stopped just before he became household-name famous. He
was known to boxing fans, many Hispanics, and San Antonioans, but
not to the public at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I remembered the name Tony Ayala, but
that was about it. He hasn't been in my mind since he was gone. But
the people in San Antonio, he never left their minds. It was an
ongoing saga those 16 years,'' said promoter Nick Huzella.
</P>
<P>
   So Ayala's return comes not in some glitzy Las Vegas casino but
the Freeman Coliseum. It's not the most glamorous of settings, but
it is Ayala's home town.
</P>
<P>
   Said Brian Raditz, director of psychology at Trenton State
Prison and Ayala's manager/adviser, ``I've known Tony for 16 years
now and this Friday night will be a very emotional night for all of
us. It's something that we've pictured and dreamed about for a
number of years. ... Tony's desire and passion are back.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
