<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DOWNERS-GROVE-ART-$ADV22-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SUBURB SEES THE FUTURE IN ITS OLD DOWNTOWN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 22) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By JOEL KOTKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOWNERS GROVE, Ill. _ Ellen K. Dean has seen the future of this
middle-class Chicago suburb, and it lies in its past.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, commercial development in Downers Grove and
hundreds of similar towns across the country meant accommodating
strip malls and ``big box'' chain retailers. But Ms. Dean, Downers
Grove's economic development director, says that model is played
out. If her city wants a vibrant retail future, she believes, it
will find it on its old Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of cities are getting into the idea that the big box is
the future, but I think they are becoming commodities, and their
product can be gotten on the Internet,'' Ms. Dean said, stepping
carefully through the reconstruction work the city has undertaken
to brighten its downtown streetscape, including installing new
sewer pipes and new pavement on Main Street. ``We think specialty
retailers like the ones here are the future, and so is downtown.
The future is more interactive and people-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   The ambitious effort to revitalize downtown Downers Grove, where
many of the brick buildings date from around the turn of the last
century, reflects a broader trend seen in other smaller towns
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from successful projects in big cities like
Chicago, suburban communities that for years seemed content to
allow malls to proliferate while old downtowns deteriorated have
begun to reverse course and rediscover the potential in their
historic cores.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is epitomized in Downers Grove, Evanston and Highland
Park around Chicago, and Santa Monica and Pasadena near Los
Angeles, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Communities have tried to re-inject life into their downtowns
before. One wave of such projects crested about two decades ago, as
cities and towns in many regions tried to combat the burgeoning
strength of new edge-of-town shopping centers by sprucing up Main
Streets, turning busy shopping blocks into pedestrian malls and
erecting parking ramps downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Some projects succeeded in forestalling shoppers' flight to the
malls for a time, but many proved as futile as they were expensive,
as vacant storefronts continued to proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, urban commercial neighborhoods have turned to
organizing business improvement districts, which use money from
parking fees or local tax surcharges to pay for cosmetic
improvements and stepped-up services like street cleaning _ but
again with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   But one important factor is different this time around. The new
wave of Main Street projects is a response not to the strength of
shopping centers but to their perceived new weakness, prompted in
part by the explosion in Internet retailing.
</P>
<P>
   For the same reasons that new shopping centers once emptied old
downtowns _ convenience and lower prices _ the Internet has now
begun to siphon off a significant share of sales from shopping
centers' big tenants. And just as important to city officials like
Ms. Dean, it has cut into sales tax revenue in mainstay categories
like airline tickets, books, records, clothing and, especially,
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when one of our car dealers told me that 25
percent of his sales now go on the Internet,'' she recalled.
``That's the kind of thing that makes me shake in my boots.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, many communities are still trying to attract as many
new big-box retailers, strip centers and malls as possible. Towns
and small suburban cities like Downers Grove still depend on them
for a huge share of the sales and property taxes that finance their
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there are clear signs, even in a healthy commercial market
like metropolitan Chicago, that this style of retail development
has passed the saturation point.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Knitter, president of Great American Realty in Oak Park,
another Chicago suburb, estimates that there are already roughly
200 giant, empty store buildings surrounded by acres of parking in
the region, representing 10 million square feet, with an additional
5 million square feet due to become available in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Knitter said a number of factors are contributing to the
oversupply, with revenue losses to Internet commerce fairly low on
the list. He cited intense competition among national chains that
has flattened many second-tier local competitors, as well as many
retailers' unwillingness to occupy space deserted by failed stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it is superstition about going into a failed
location,'' said Knitter, a retail real estate consultant whose
firm specializes in the Midwest market. ``But people often want to
build their own building with their own footprint, rather than go
into someone else's. A Walgreen's is always a certain number of
square feet _ they don't want to change the configuration; they
want them to look the same and be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The casualties are scattered liberally between downtown Chicago
and its western suburban ring. Some have been razed and
redeveloped, occasionally by other retailers, while others have
been converted into educational or medical centers. The rest remain
vacant, awaiting new uses, which Knitter thinks could eventually
include housing, recreational facilities or even pet cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   In Downers Grove, the trend is manifested in a big store on
Ogden Avenue that has been vacant for five years and in the city's
failure to attract new retail development on several
shopping-center-size parcels.
</P>
<P>
   So the city has decided to concentrate instead on restoring Main
Street to what it once was: an attractive strolling, shopping and
dining destination for the surrounding region and a convenient and
desirable place for singles and ``empty nesters'' to live.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dean points to the many essential services found downtown _
city hall, the library and the post office are there _ and its
intimate, pedestrian-friendly atmosphere, rare in newer suburbs.
The 300 retail businesses operating downtown differ markedly from
typical mall fare and include independent bakeries and restaurants;
the city's one brew pub, the Founder's Hill Brewing Co.; a
consignment store; a locally owned five and dime, and a movie
theater, the Tivoli, that dates from 1928. An adjacent park
features a band shell for outdoor concerts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downtown provides something unique _ the entertainment,
meet-and-greet venue,'' Ms. Dean said over a soft drink at
Founder's Hill. ``This can't be duplicated on the Internet at all.
Virtual reality is not reality. This is.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joel Kotkin is a senior fellow at the Pepperdine Institute for
Public Policy. His column on the Main Street economy appears the
fourth Sunday of each month. E-mail: grassrts(AT)nytimes.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
