<HEADLINE>
STOCKS CLOSE LOWER FOR 2ND STRAIGHT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An unexpected worsening of the nation's trade deficit
sent stocks into a skid Thursday, and despite a partial recovery,
prices closed lower for the second straight session.
</P>
<P>
   The market has been pressured recently by various signs of
economic pickup in Japan and Europe, where currencies tend to
strengthen against the dollar as investors buy relatively more
appealing foreign shares. The government's report of a $3.4 billion
jump, instead of a small decline, in the trade deficit pushed the
dollar down further and set off speculation about how the Federal
Reserve would view this trend, a fresh source of upward pressure on
prices, at its policy meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The global economy is recovering,'' said Lorraine Wang, an
equity strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``Where we're
concerned is the U.S. dollar, which is bad for inflation.'' The Fed
is widely expected to increase the overnight lending rate a
quarter-point next week, and Ms. Wang predicted the rise would not
be its last.
</P>
<P>
   Although other analysts disagreed, investors found little reason
to buy on Thursday, especially ahead of Friday's expiration of
stock options and index options; these expirations often lead to
big price swings.
</P>
<P>
   With most Internet and other high-tech issues in retreat, the
NASDAQ market slumped 36.3 points, or 1.37 percent, to 2,621.43,
the biggest loss among the main gauges.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, which was down by as much as
118 points in the morning, ended with a loss of 27.54 points, or
two-tenths of a percent, to 10,963.84. Eighteen of its 30
components fell, although none by more than Alcoa's decline of 1
11/16, to 65 3/16. Reynolds Metals, which accepted a sweetened
takeover offer from Alcoa, fell 2 11/16 to 65 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market's expensive,'' said Neil Eigen, a managing director
at J.&AMP;W. Seligman. ``It's very difficult to make the case that
stocks go a lot higher.'' Some bank stocks stood out among the
day's losers, with Chase Manhattan down 2 9/16 to 82 7/16 after
being downgraded by a leading analyst who said the high-flying
shares, still up nearly 18 percent this year, may have little room
left to grow. Bank of New York fell 1 5/8 to 37 after a report that
Russian criminals may have used it to launder money, and Citigroup
fell 1 5/32 to 45 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index declined 9.25 points, or
seven-tenths of a percent, to 1,323.59, as 277 of its components
fell while 202 rose and 21 were unchanged. Microsoft accounted for
the most damage, slipping 1 3/16 to 83 13/16, while Royal Dutch, up
1 1/16 to 64 11/16, was the biggest plus.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more optimistic strategists was James Paulsen, chief
investment officer at Wells Capital Management. He said the economy
was clearly slowing down and that interest rates were likely to
ease soon, clearing the way for a resumption of the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think stocks will probably take off again and go on to new
highs,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   At least two companies made successful market debuts. Wink
Communications, engaged in interactive TV, sold 4.75 million shares
at 16, and they spurted to close at 35 11/16. Netro Corp., which
provides broadband wireless access, sold 5 million shares at 8, and
they nearly tripled, closing at 23 1/2 on turnover of 18.8 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange was a moderate 673.7
million, slightly less than on Wednesday. Declining issues
outnumbered advancing ones by 1,643 to 1,382, while 93 made new
52-week lows, and 44 made new highs.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell in major European markets but gained in Brazil and
rose more than 3 percent in Hong Kong. Japan's Nikkei 225, up 31
percent so far this year, was slightly lower.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
