<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-PALMER-BOS &LR;      08-19 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-PALMER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMER'S PRESENCE PROVES POWERFUL AT NASHAWTUC CC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ His third shot to the par-5 18th was an
indifferent wedge that was pulled slightly, coming to rest on the
fringe some 35 feet from the pin. When his putt came up 6 feet
short, Arnold Palmer winced, gave that vintage forehead-wrinkled
disgusted look skyward, and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   A casual pro-am Thursday at Nashawtuc Country Club, a prelude to
the start of the BankBoston Classic, would end with a three-putt
bogey, but in the settling dusk it mattered little to the people
who truly count in Palmer's world _ the fans. They have provided
the stage, paid the bills, and given him the life he has been
blessed with.
</P>
<P>
   And though it was not quite an Army, it certainly was a loyal
following. It also was a rewarded following for Palmer was, well,
Palmer. Which is as good as it gets if you prefer your heroes to be
gracious. Palmer shook hands, greeted old friends, and didn't miss
a request for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   For parts of five decades he has graced the American sports
stage and as he nears his 70th birthday, Palmer remains more
important than ever. In a world of people who wear their hats
backward, he is a constant reminder that manners and discipline
count for something, an old-fashioned person who doesn't think it's
a particularly bad thing to be called that.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, he remains the conscience of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Palmer was the one Ben Crenshaw telephoned last
week, the guiding force needed to help the Ryder Cup captain get
through a difficult PGA Championship week. The pay-for-play
controversy crushed Palmer as well as Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely disappointed in our people. They don't seem to
understand what this competition is all about. The money and the
lifestyle the game has afforded them . . . '' Palmer said, shaking
his head. ``I'm a little sorry the controversy came up.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer will be the main attraction the next three days at
Nashawtuc, his first competitive appearance in the area since 1988.
The excitement has nothing to do with how he now plays; it has
everything to do with what he stands for. Lee Trevino once said,
``People would rather watch Arnold take the clubs out of his trunk
than watch us play.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? The stories explain the legend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gary Player recalls a visit to a gold mine in South Africa.
``Gold bars were everywhere and the man says, `Anyone who can pick
one up can have it.' So Arnold tells me he'd like to try and I
asked the man, `Can my American friend here give it a try?'
</P>
<P>
   ``So Arnold goes over and picks one up. There was such a look of
fright in the man's face. He tells Arnold, `Sir, I just work here.'
Arnold looks at him and says, `You did work here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some 30 years later, Player smiles at the memory. ``Such a look
of fright on the poor man's face,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was the GTE Northwest Classic in Seattle and Palmer turned to
his caddie, Greg Aune, prior to teeing off in the third and final
round. ``I'm going to do something special today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-5 closing hole, Palmer needed a birdie to shoot his
age, 66. ``Everyone knew what was going on,'' said Aune and the
challenge had Palmer focused as if he were stalking a Masters title
in his prime. He killed a drive, said Aune, and had 215 to the
green. ``He had a 5-wood. I couldn't have put a better club in his
hand.'' And? ``And he hit it fat, left it 40 yards short of the
green. I said, `Oh no,' and covered my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Aune couldn't bear to watch the third shot, which Palmer knocked
to 2 1/2 feet. Nor could he witness the putt, which Palmer knocked
dead center. Aune did see the smile, though, a grin that comes with
only the greatest of triumphs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ask those who know Palmer best if he's as good as his press
clippings and they will tell you no, emphatically. ``He's better,''
said Richard Connolly, a close friend of Palmer's for 20 years.
``He walks with kings and queens, but eats hamburgers and hot
dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   What he has never understood is why others can't feel the same.
</P>
<P>
   Like one of the first Shark Shootouts at Sherwood CC in Thousand
Oaks, Calif., after which the players talked of a quiet restaurant
up in the hills, away from the crowd. ``What's wrong with that
place,'' asked Palmer, pointing to a local pub, and he was told it
was too crowded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then that's where we're going,'' said Palmer, and off he went
to have a cheeseburger and a beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no phony baloney with him,'' said Aune. ``He is every
bit as good in person as he is in private.''
</P>
<P>
   It reminds one of what a fellow pro once said of Palmer: ``He
doesn't realize he's Arnold Palmer.''
</P>
<P>
   Which helps explain why, after winning the 1985 Ford Senior
Players Championship by 11 shots at Canterbury Golf Club in
Cleveland, Palmer found himself talking casually to a writer. Said
writer was rushing to a high school reunion and Palmer thought it
sounded like a good idea. So there went Palmer, as a guest, to the
writer's high school reunion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He is always asked how much longer he'll play, but everybody
knows Palmer is, above all, a competitor. The passion for the game,
for the challenge, will always be with him.
</P>
<P>
   Like the day he saw a sportswriter he knew playing a round.
Palmer, whose house was on the course, left his garage and offered
the writer some new clubs. The writer declined, pointing to a new
set of Jack Nicklaus irons. Palmer winced, then left as play
continued.
</P>
<P>
   A few holes later, Palmer appeared on the tee. There would be a
match, he announced. The writer objected, thinking the price was
too high.
</P>
<P>
   It was to no avail. ``Let's see how good those Nicklaus clubs
are now,'' said Palmer, a sly grin on his face, a twinkle in his
eye, and a challenge in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, he'll bring that same passion to Nashawtuc CC.
Regardless of what he shoots, the game wins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
