<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PERROT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIM PERROT, LEADER OF WNBA CHAMPIONS, DIES OF CANCER AT 32  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La., Texas, Sweden, Germany, Israel, France)   By MAUREEN BALLEZA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Kim Perrot, the tiny floor leader of the Houston
Comets team that has won the first two Women's National Basketball
Association championships, died here Thursday. She was 32.
</P>
<P>
   She died at the University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center
after a public battle against lung cancer. She recently had been
seeking alternative treatment in Mexico after undergoing surgery on
Feb. 24 to remove tumors in her brain, where the cancer had spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thought Kim Perrot would be a two-time WNBA
champion?'' she said when she accepted her second championship ring
during a Comets home game on June 22. ``When no one else believed
in me, my teammates and the fans stuck with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, who was 5 feet 5 inches and 130 pounds, was indeed an
unlikely professional champion despite a record-setting career in
college. She held 26 school records at the University of
Southwestern Louisiana, where she remains the career scoring leader
with 2,157 points. In her senior season, she led the nation in
scoring at 30.1 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, she did what other American female basketball
players had to do at the time: she went abroad to play
professionally, spending one year each in Sweden, Germany, Israel
and France.
</P>
<P>
   But the success of college women's basketball, coupled with the
high-profile Olympic championship team at the 1996 Atlanta Games,
put women's basketball on the American sports map. Perrot returned
to the United States and attended an open tryout with the Houston
Comets, who signed her as a developmental player. Her work ethic
impressed her coaches, and by the end of the WNBA's first season,
Perrot was in charge of league's best team. In her two-year career
she averaged 4 assists, 7.2 points, 2.6 steals and 2.9 rebounds a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot is survived by her mother, three brothers and two
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
