<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEVY OFFERS INSIGHT WITHOUT EGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marv Levy really didn't need this.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, a television network known for its
``attitude'' called the 74-year-old former NFL coach, who stepped
away from the game two years ago because he didn't want to deal
anymore with the grind.
</P>
<P>
   They had an offer: Come to L.A. on the weekends and be part of a
new Sunday-morning NFL pregame show. Oh, and if it works out, stick
around for the weekend to work the telestrator for the nightly news
show as an analyst.
</P>
<P>
   This is someone who not so long ago had to take time off from
coaching to beat prostate cancer, which made losing four straight
Super Bowls with the Buffalo Bills seem almost incidental. He
retired after 47 years of coaching in 1997 after his team lost six
of its last seven games and turned a 6-10 season into no fun at
all.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality of it, Levy really DID need this job from Fox.
He practically asked for it.
</P>
<P>
   Fox Sports Net introduces Levy and the newest of Sunday-morning
grid-gab genre with its ``NFL This Morning'' show that'll debut on
Sept. 12 at 8 a.m., leading into the network's NFL better-known
pregame studio show. On the set at the Fox compound in Century City
with Chris Myers and former Rams great Jackie Slater, Levy will
expound on what might be his most passionate diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Levy is content with renovating an apartment in Chicago with his
wife. He's doing OK with motivational speaking, happy to talk about
how the cancer is out of his system. A concerned wife might contact
him and ask if he'll make a personal call to her husband, to make
him go to the doctor to get the blood test that detects prostate
cancer before it becomes a fatal inconvenience. And he's happy to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   But the NFL . . . there's something to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have too high regard for the game to just want this to have
something to do,'' said Levy, who maintains a regimen of running
three miles a day as well as working out in the weight room. ``My
health is excellent. The cancer has been gone for four years and
I'm so excited to get back close to football. There's no slowing
down.''
</P>
<P>
   But putting your mug on TV at a place like Fox? Levy has some TV
experience doing NFL games for NBC and the USFL for ESPN, and when
he left coaching made it known in TV circles he'd like to try
broadcasting again. But how does someone who looks more like Buster
Keaton fit in with a network dedicated to a bunch of ex-NFL party
boys who seem to be on their own career ego agenda?
</P>
<P>
   By playing it straight with some deadpan humor that even someone
like Keaton would have appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   Levy can spot a phony on TV and he doesn't appreciate it. This
is, after all, a guy with a master's degree in English from
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be a still-laced Calvin Coolidge, but I don't
want humor to distract,'' said Levy, who was one of the coaches NFL
Films liked to hook up with a microphone during one of its
productions. ``TV makes the NFL very entertaining for fans, but
I've seen too many shows where they think the fans want to see one
guy rib the other guy. I don't want this to be an exercise in
buffoonery. It demeans the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real success of the game depends on the three participants
_ the players, the fans and the media. I don't want to make any of
those adversarial. I want to make this show to appeal to the
spectrum of men and women, young and old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can bring enthusiasm and inject a bit of humor when
it works. That's the only way to approach this. I used to say to my
teams right before the games in the locker room: `Where else would
you rather be than right here, right now?' That's how I feel about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The only game in town: For one year _ 1970 _ Levy worked for
the Los Angeles Rams, a special-teams assistant coach under George
Allen. He remembers the Coliseum filled with NFL fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real event, those Rams games on Sunday, and the fans
were rabid,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   And because the magic stadium sits empty for the fourth NFL
season in a row, Levy is saddened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was an analyst doing games in the USFL, we went to the
Coliseum (for a game against the Express) and I interviewed the
team owner before the game,'' said Levy. ``He said attendance had
not been very good, but the weather hadn't been good either that
spring. But the day of the game, the newspapers said: `Beautiful
weather expected for the weekend, 1 million expected at the
beaches.' And that's Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe today they're not the same fans you see in Cleveland or
Buffalo or Green Bay because there are so many other things to turn
your attention. But in my opinion, a team belongs there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems almost any place the NFL goes, it's going to ask for
public financing. But I never knew all the machinations to what
goes into financing a team. I had a tough enough time trying to
figure out what Bruce Smith is saying.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES
</P>
<P>
   __ Promo this week by KABC Channel 7's Bill Weir: ``Dodgers and
Angels highlights at 11 . . . please watch anyway.'' &QL; 
__ We aren't bowled over by KXTA-AM (1150) luring Terry Bradshaw to
do an hour show each weekday at noon starting Monday, but at least
it does remove a chunk of the time left for the guys who follow. &QL; 
__ John Elway's number-retirement ceremony at halftime of the Sept.
13 Denver-Miami game will be shown instead of the usual highlight
package on the season-opener of ABC's ``Monday Night Football.''
But be warned: Starting with the second week, it'll be Chris Berman
live from the ESPN Zone restaurant in New York's Times Square. Can
the ball drop early this year? &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES
</P>
<P>
   __ OK, so KFI-AM's Tom Leykus needs to fill in an hour of
programming Tuesday, but did it have to be a full-on assault on
KTLA-Channel 5's Claudia Trejos? &QL; 
__ It's going to cost someone at least $3 billion to televise the
NCAA men's basketball tournament past 2002. CBS has first crack
since it holds the current rights and has been negotiating. If CBS
doesn't reach a deal by next week, the network could lose the
rights, with ABC/ESPN, Fox and ISL U.S._ a company that has the
rights to the men's and women's soccer World Cups _ said to be
ready to jump into the bidding. CBS paid $1 billion in 1991 for a
seven- year deal, extended it to 2002 with an extension in 1995
worth $1.73 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
