u a BC-SCI-PIG-TRANSPLANTS-7     08-19 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PIG-TRANSPLANTS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY BOLSTERS CASE FOR PIG-DONOR TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For some time, scientists exploring the use of pigs
as organ donors have faced intense criticism over fears that
cross-species transplants could unleash a dangerous animal virus in
humans. Now British researchers say they have encouraging evidence
that pigs' organs are safe enough to begin testing in people.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest study yet of people treated with pig tissue,
though not whole pig organs, researchers at Imutran PLC of
Cambridge, England, a biotechnology company that is breeding
genetically modified pigs for their hearts, livers and kidneys,
examined the blood of 160 such patients from around the world,
looking for evidence of a particular pig virus.
</P>
<P>
   None of the patients showed conclusive evidence of infection by
that virus, although the blood of four contained pig antibodies, a
finding that Imutran attributed to some other virus, whose identity
and source, the company said, were unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Independent experts, however, said the presence of the
antibodies could mean that these four patients had been infected
with the particular pig virus in question at some point after
treatment with the tissue.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the results showing no evidence of widespread
infection were not especially surprising. But there was one
startling discovery: among those patients whose treatment had
consisted of having their blood filtered through pig spleens, pig
cells were still circulating in the bloodstream eights years after
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this study is an important milestone in the
development of this potentially lifesaving technology,'' Dr.
Corinne Savill, Imutran's chief operating officer, said in an
interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Savill described as ``good news'' the finding that ``people
are walking around with pig cells in their circulation for up to
eight years and still we cannot detect any infection.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Jonathan S. Allan, a virologist at the Southwest
Foundation for Medical Research in San Antonio, had a different
interpretation. ``If pig cells are still there,'' Allan said,
``there is still a potential that a pig virus could be expressed
and infect the patient at some later time.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 62,000 Americans are waiting for human-organ
transplants. And with demand for organs far outstripping supply,
scientists at Imutran, a subsidiary of the Swiss pharmaceutical
giant Novartis International AG, and other biotechnology companies
have spent a decade investigating the use of pigs bred with human
genes as an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Already some tests are under way using gene-altered pig cells _
as opposed to cells from ordinary farm pigs, as was done with the
patients in the Imutran study _ as therapy for Parkinson's disease
and other disorders.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the Food and Drug Administration, as well as
British regulatory authorities, have said they want better evidence
that pig tissue is safe before allowing tests of ``whole organ''
cross-species transplants to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The results of the Imutran study, being reported in Friday's
issue of the journal Science, do not necessarily mean that testing
of cross-species transplants, called xenotransplants, will now be
permitted, said Dr. Philip Noguchi, who supervises xenotransplant
research for the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and officials at the federal Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention, which participated in the study by doing its own
laboratory analysis, said the outcome did not completely allay
their safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Noguchi noted, for instance, that most of the subjects of the
Imutran study had been exposed to pig tissue for only days or
months, not years as an organ recipient would be.
</P>
<P>
   The worries over the use of pigs has focused on a single virus,
called porcine endogenous retrovirus, or PERV. Most viruses can be
bred out of pigs, but PERV cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago a British virologist, Robin A. Weiss, proved that
PERV could infect human cells in the test tube. That raised the
question whether the virus, which does not make pigs sick, could
infect people, and, if so, what harm it could do.
</P>
<P>
   Because PERV is a retrovirus, it integrates its own genetic
material into the cells it infects, in the same manner as HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS. Experts say that like HIV, PERV could be
latent for years before causing any symptoms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The 160 patients in the Imutran study were treated with pig
tissue over a period of 12 years, for various durations and for a
variety of conditions. Over the last 18 months, at Imutran's
request, their doctors took blood samples for the company to
analyze.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the patients, 100, who came from a hospital in St.
Petersburg, Russia, had their blood filtered through pig spleens.
Fifteen burn patients from Germany had pig skin grafts. Still
others received injections of pig pancreas cells for diabetes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
