<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATS ARE QUIET, BUT FANS AREN'T AS YANKS LOSE TO ROYALS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The foreign sound of the New York Yankees being booed
at Yankee Stadium erupted in several sections Thursday once Jason
Grimsley stumbled to a 3-0 count on Jermaine Dye in the 11th
inning. The Kansas City Royals had loaded the bases, in part
because Derek Jeter had committed another error, and the score was
tied. It was an inopportune time for Grimsley to be suddenly
searching for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The noise escalated even more after Grimsley's fourth pitch
dropped out of the strike zone to force in the go-ahead run in a
game the Royals eventually won, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   From Jeter's miscue to Grimsley's misfiring to a wild throw by
Ricky Ledee and an awkward attempted catch by Jorge Posada, the
Yankees climaxed a sluggish homestand with an inning that would
have made the Toms River East Little Leaguers blush.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone's seven gritty innings were wasted because the
Yankees scored only once off a starter named Blake Stein and five
relievers. Bernie Williams, who again did not start because of a
stomach virus, narrowly missed a chance to win the game as a
pinch-hitter when he lined out to third with two on in the 10th.
Then the emotional pendulum swung dramatically, and the Yankees
imploded in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an ugly way to lose a game,'' Cone said. ``After an
exciting game, to have that happen was a real downer.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-place Yankees should not panic. They still have a
comfortable lead in the American League East and are almost assured
of barreling into the post-season. But the Yankees went 3-4 against
the vastly inferior Royals and Twins in the past week, and they
have scored only eight runs in their last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Why has the offense disappeared? Especially against Stein, who
won for the first time in the major leagues since Aug. 19, 1998,
and Dan Reichert, who won, 3-0, on Wednesday after entering the
game with a 12.08 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a little funk,'' Jeter said.
</P>
<P>
   The funk was defensive in a sloppy 11th. After Johnny Damon's
single, a sacrifice bunt and an intentional walk to Carlos Beltran,
Mike Sweeney slapped a grounder into the shortstop hole. Jeter
glided to his right to corral it, but he picked up his head to peer
at third, and that prevented him from fielding the ball cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight game in which Jeter made a
devastating error that helped the Royals rally. His throwing error
on Wednesday resulted in the Royals' first run in the Yankees' 3-0
loss. Jeter has 13 errors, but three in his last five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I caught it, I was going to third,'' Jeter said. ``It
bounced up and hit the heel of my glove.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimsley's matchup with Dye was quick and painful for the
Yankees. It went sinker for ball one, sinker for ball two, fastball
for ball three, the beginning of the boos and then another fastball
for ball four. Damon trotted home with the Royals' second run, and
Grimsley heard the taunts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid to see good baseball,'' Grimsley said. ``We played
well up until that last inning. I didn't do my job and we end up
losing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Randa followed with a fly ball to medium center field. It
would have taken a powerful and accurate throw for Ledee, playing
center in place of Williams, to even dream about nailing Beltran.
As Ledee stood under the ball, he realized that he needed to
retreat another step, so he did not get any momentum going forward.
Instead, he stepped back and unleashed a high, wild throw that
landed about 30 feet to the left of the plate. Posada scampered up
the line to smother the ball, but it ricocheted off his foot and
into the Royals' dugout. The throw was hideous. The attempted catch
was unsightly. Two runs scored _ one on the sacrifice fly and one
on the error _ and the Royals led, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I threw it, I knew something bad was going to happen,''
Ledee said. ``It was an ugly way to lose the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees lost it before then by going 0 for 8 with runners in
scoring position. In addition to Williams not starting the last
three games, the Yanks have a bevy of players who are struggling.
Scott Brosius was 0 for 28 before he singled in the 10th, Posada is
7 for 37, Jeter is 3 for 16, Chili Davis is 0 for 14 and Chuck
Knoblauch is 1 for 10.
</P>
<P>
   After stranding seven men in the first three innings, the
Yankees did not have another runner in scoring position until Jeter
sacrificed Brosius to second in the 10th. After Paul O'Neill was
intentionally walked, Al Morman whiffed Tino Martinez. Williams was
the pinch-hitter against Brad Rigby and some fans leaped when he
lashed a bullet toward third, but Randa dived to his left and made
a nifty leaping catch. The play stopped the Yankees and made the
ugly 11th, and the booing, possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans were spoiled all day because everything was so
tight,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``All of a sudden, we let it get
away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
