<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT APPOINTS HIS NEW COUNSEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday named Beth Nolan, a
deputy in the Justice Department, as his new counsel, succeeding
Charles F.C. Ruff. Ruff left the White House two weeks ago to
return to private practice.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Nolan, 47, a native of Irvington, N.Y., has served as a
deputy assistant attorney general in the Office of Legal Counsel at
the Justice Department since 1996. Before that, she taught law at
George Washington University, taking a leave from 1993 to 1995 to
serve as associate counsel to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had asked Cheryl D. Mills, Ruff's deputy, to become
chief counsel, but she declined.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Clinton said of Ms. Nolan: ``While
Chuck Ruff is a tough act to follow, I know of no one better than
Beth to succeed him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
