<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH IMPLIES HE HAS USED NO DRUGS IN LAST 25 YEARS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan.)   By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROANOKE, Va. _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, who has vowed not
to answer questions about whether he has ever used illegal drugs,
answered a few Thursday morning and suggested he had not used drugs
in the last 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief, informal news conference as he campaigned in
southwestern Virginia, Bush fielded questions for the second
straight day about drug use, and explained why he chose to answer a
question from The Dallas Morning News on the subject Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had been asked ``what I thought was a relevant
question:'' whether as president he would insist that his
appointees undergo full FBI background checks, which include
questions about past drug use. He would, he replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could I pass the challenge of a background check?'' Bush said
he was then asked. ``My answer is `absolutely.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he could swear that he had not used drugs within the
period required by the Clinton administration of potential
employees _ the previous seven years. Then he went further, saying,
``Not only could I pass the background check and the standards
applied to today's White House, but I could have passed the
background check and the standards applied on the most stringent
conditions when my dad was president of the United States _ a
15-year period.''
</P>
<P>
   That would appear to mean that Bush has not used drugs since
1974, or 15 years before his father's administration, which ran
from 1989 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   C. Boyden Gray, President Bush's former White House counsel,
confirmed the 15-year standard, which he said was later relaxed to
10 years. White House spokesman Barry Toiv said that prospective
Clinton administration employees were asked to disclose illegal
drug use for the last seven years, or since age 18, whichever was
less. Some high-level political appointees are asked whether they
have ever used illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, at a second campaign event later Thursday in Columbus,
Ohio, declined to answer whether he could deny using illegal drugs
since he was 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told the American people all I'm going to tell them''
on the subject, he said. ``I hope the people appreciate a candidate
who comes along and says, enough is enough. Enough is enough
digging into people's background years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   At his appearance here, Bush said, without giving specifics,
that ``over 20 years ago,'' he did ``some things'' that he now
considered wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told the people of this country that over two decades
ago I made some mistakes, when I was younger. I have learned from
those mistakes.'' It was not clear whether he was referring to drug
use or to drinking to excess, which he has acknowledged, or
something else. Bush gave up drinking some years ago and now sticks
to alcohol-free beer.
</P>
<P>
   All the presidential candidates were asked on Wednesday by The
Associated Press whether they had ever used drugs. Spokesmen for
all of Bush's rivals for the Republican presidential nomination
said no. Aides to the Democratic candidates, Vice President Al Gore
and former Sen. Bill Bradley, admitted that the candidates had used
marijuana in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Bush refused to reply, and he said in an interview Thursday
night during a flight here that he was determined to end what he
called ``the politics of personal vilification'' and ``give my best
shot at cleansing and re-invigorating the system.''
</P>
<P>
   But to his evident irritation, the governor was peppered at
every stop with questions about drugs _ not from voters, several of
whom said they supported his position, but from reporters. Only one
of several hundred people with whom Bush spoke at a farmer's market
here pressed him to make a fuller statement about drug use. That
was a man in modish sunglasses who refused to give his name, but
said he was a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had answered the Dallas paper's query about FBI
background checks, while refusing to answer most others touching on
the subject of drugs, because it was ``a relevant question about
how I would conduct my presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people need to know if there will be
security checks administered on White House personnel. It is a very
good question.''
</P>
<P>
   If the American people ``don't like my position,'' Bush said
here, ``they can go out and find someone else to vote for. That's
the great thing about the American system.''
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance in New Orleans earlier this week, Bush was
asked whether Texas would follow Kansas' lead and de-emphasize the
teaching of evolution in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that he thought such decisions were best left to local
school boards and that he believed children should be taught about
evolution. But he said he saw nothing wrong if teachers wanted to
reflect other views.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe children ought to be exposed to different theories
about how the world started,'' Bush said, adding he would not
mandate such teaching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
