<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOTHER COURAGE AND HER CHILDREN:' THE EVER-CHANGING SCENERY OF
WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) (DW) 
 By ANITA GATES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``We're all in God's hands,'' says the chaplain. The
old woman beside him answers, ``I don't think it has gotten that
bad yet.'' At another point she observes, ``I have learned that
nothing comes when you think it will, not even the season.'' At one
point a major pays one of the woman's sons, whose name is Elvis,
the highest compliment: ``You have the makings of a young Marcos.''
The woman describes her only daughter as ``half-GI.'' She will
eventually lose all her children to war.
</P>
<P>
   This is ``Mother Courage and Her Children,'' but in the Ma-Yi
Theater Company's admirable if sometimes stiff production, numerous
changes have been made. Bertolt Brecht's original Mutter Courage's
name has been translated to Nanay Isog, and the setting has been
changed, from the 30 Years' War to the Philippine conflict between
1971 and 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The play's original setting ``may have less impact for a nation
that has continued to suffer from its colonial past,'' Rodolfo
Carlos Vera, who wrote the adaptation, has said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why we felt compelled to pull Mother Courage's cart
through the villages of Jolo, Zamboanga and the Maguindanao
regions,'' he continues. ``We realized that what happened in
Mindanao in the 1970s resembled the three decades of war in
17th-century Europe, differentiated mainly by magnitude and
geography.'' The resulting message seems to be that all wars are
bad in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're peace-loving people,'' says Nanay (Ching Valdes-Aran),
holding a knife to the neck of a soldier who wants her son to sign
up and fight. Ms. Valdes-Aran's portrayal of the matriarch who
makes her living by war (she sells wares from a traveling cart to
soldiers) has both strengths and weaknesses. Her bearing, that of a
woman beaten down and exhausted but not defeated, is convincing,
and she is a competent actress, but her singing voice lacks both
power and discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily most of the rest of the cast has strong voices, so the
production's several musical numbers are largely effective. (Fabian
Obispo is the composer; Vadim Feichtner and Nicky Paraiso are the
musical directors.) Apparently this is not the case with Tess Lina,
who plays Ynez, the loose woman who marries a warlord. She recites
some of her lyrics, in the style of Rex Harrison in ``My Fair
Lady,'' while another actress, several feet behind her, sings them.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Eastman's set _ gray corrugated tin walls and a yellow
stage floor with a pattern that looks like dirty footprints _ is
just right. Doing the battle scenes by strobe light, however, is a
painfully cliched choice, and it doesn't fit the overall tempo of
Tazewell Thompson's direction.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MOTHER COURAGE AND HER CHILDREN'
</P>
<P>
   By Bertolt Brecht; translation by Ralph Mannheim and John
Willett; adapted by Rodolfo Carlos Vera; directed by Tazewell
Thompson; original music/sound by Fabian Obispo; sets by Donald
Eastman; lighting by Robert Wierzel; costumes by Jeff Fender;
dramaturge, Vera; musical director, Vadim Feichtner and Nicky
Paraiso; production stage manager, Cristina Sison. Presented by
Ma-Yi Theater Company at the Connelly Theater. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Ching Valdes-Aran (Mother Courage/Nanay Isog), Maurice
Villa-Lobos (Elvis Laoyan), Rich Ceraulo (Kesong Puti), Kim Awon
(Christine Brown), Jojo Gonzalez (Cook), Art Acuna (Chaplain and
Young Peasant) and Tess Lina, Ynez.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
