<SLUG> BC-FURROW-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. INDICTS SUPREMACIST IN MAILMAN'S KILLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A federal grand jury Thursday indicted the white
supremacist Buford O. Furrow Jr. on three felony counts in the
murder here last week of a Filipino-American letter carrier, as the
government focused its prosecution on charges that could result in
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow, 37, has been held without bail since he turned himself
in and confessed to the killing and to the shooting of five people
at a Jewish community center last week.
</P>
<P>
   He was charged with the murder of a federal employee, Joseph
Santos Ileto; with the use of a firearm in the murder, and with the
illegal possession of a firearm by a felon. Furrow has a previous
felony assault conviction in his native Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   The murder charge and the charge that he used a firearm in the
killing of Ileto, 39, both carry a possible death penalty. Furrow
is scheduled to be arraigned on Aug. 30, when he will enter his
plea. His court-appointed lawyer, Sean Kennedy, did not return
calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment was a clear indication that the prosecutors
wanted to pursue the case without delay and obtain the harshest
possible sentence for Furrow. It also answered any lingering
questions about whether the federal or state prosecutors in the
district attorney's office would proceed first with charges against
Furrow.
</P>
<P>
   The two offices filed separate criminal charges last week, but
sought to stress their cooperation Thursday. U.S. Attorney
Alejandro N. Mayorkas said that one or perhaps two prosecutors from
the district attorney's office would be appointed special assistant
U.S. attorneys to assist in the federal case, an effort to present
a united front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Garcetti and I decided together that at this juncture this
is the best course of action,'' Mayorkas said, referring to
District Attorney Gil Garcetti.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings began in the morning of Aug. 10 at the North
Valley Jewish Community Center in the neighborhood of Granada
Hills. Furrow admitted he fired more than 70 bullets from an Uzi
submachine gun, hitting five people, including three children. All
survived the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow said he carjacked a Toyota a few miles away, and then
spotted Ileto on a quiet street, where he was delivering mail.
Furrow said he decided to kill Ileto, shooting him nine times at
close range, because he was not white and was a ``target of
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Furrow, for years a member of the Aryan Nations, a hate group
based in Idaho, turned himself in to the FBI in Las Vegas the next
morning. He had slipped through a massive police dragnet after the
shootings and told police he had wandered around the streets of
Hollywood, reportedly getting a haircut, shopping for a baseball
cap and drinking a few beers before taking an $800 taxi ride across
the desert and spending the night in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   He was casual enough after the shootings that he made his way
about 20 miles to Hollywood and then went to Scorecard, a sporting
goods store, and tried on Cleveland Indians and Atlanta Braves
baseball caps.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Sanders, the store's manager, said that Furrow wandered
in alone around 2 p.m. Aug. 10, and that the only notable part of
the visit came as Furrow responded angrily when a salesperson joked
about Furrow's thick neck and offered to get him an extra large
cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't take it well,'' Sanders said, adding that Furrow
bought nothing and just walked away.
</P>
<P>
   Questions remain about how Furrow assembled his arsenal,
including an assault rifle, hand grenades and more than 5,000
rounds of ammunition; whether he had any assistance in locating
targets in a city he apparently did not know well, and how he
managed to slip past the police.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said that Furrow may face further firearms
charges for the attack on the community center, and civil rights
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether anyone else would be charged and whether the
number of charges might be increased, Mayorkas would say only,
``The investigation is continuing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
