<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves make up for lost time
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The past three days at Coors Field sucked plenty of
life out of the Braves' offense and left John Rocker with a
terrible case of altitude sickness.
</P>
<P>
   But it ended well for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   In a game lasting more innings than any they had played this
year, they came away with a 9-7 victory in 14 innings Thursday to
pull within a half-game of the first-place Mets in the National
League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so numb to the fact that somebody was going to win the
game,'' said Chipper Jones, whose three-run home run gave the
Braves a 4-2 lead back in the eighth. ``Nothing mattered when it
was after about the 12th. I was saying if you're going to do it, do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Andruw Jones, who doubled to left field with two out in
the top of the 14th. Randall Simon followed by sending the first
pitch from left-handed reliever Roberto Ramirez into right field to
score Jones for the go-ahead run. After an intentional walk to Jose
Hernandez, Eddie Perez provided some insurance with a single that,
aided by a Lenny Harris error, allowed two more runs to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all tired,'' Simon said. ``Everybody wanted to go
home. He started me with a curveball, so I thought he'd come back
with a curveball or a slider. I just tried to stay back and use my
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' three runs in the 14th equaled their production off
Rockies pitching in the previous two games, both losses. Bruce Chen
got his first career relief win after pitching a scoreless 13th,
but he needed help in the 14th from Terry Mulholland, the starting
pitcher two days earlier. It was Mulholland's first save as a
Brave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more hungry than anything else,'' said Mulholland, who
said he could have gone another inning.
</P>
<P>
   After two uncharacteristically low-scoring games and a 2-1
Colorado lead after seven innings in this one, Coors Field made up
for lost time in the eighth and ninth innings. The Braves and
Rockies scored nine times and traded the lead twice before a Bret
Boone run-scoring single with two outs in the ninth set it up for
extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   Coors Field made up for lost time in the eighth and ninth
innings. The Braves and Rockies scored nine times and traded the
lead twice before a Bret Boone run-scoring single with two outs in
the ninth set it up for extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most innings played in a game at Coors Field since
the first played in the stadium on April 26, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker blew a save opportunity for the second consecutive day.
On Wednesday, a three-run home run by Larry Walker in the ninth
inning saddled him with his first loss since June 29.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, a bases-loaded walk to Angel Echevarria followed by a
bases-loaded double by Jeff Barry in the eighth turned a 4-2 lead
into a 6-4 deficit. A two-out, two-run rally by the Braves off
Rockies closer Dave Veres in the ninth saved Rocker from another
loss.
</P>
<P>
   In three appearances here this season, Rocker allowed seven runs
while recording only two outs for a 94.45 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   As bad as the day was for the closers, it was another good one
for the starters.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz, who was pitching with a sore elbow and sore groin,
and who has now gone a career-high nine games without a win, gave
another very winnable performance. He held the Rockies to two runs
on five hits with no walks and eight strikeouts, the most
strikeouts he's had since his nine on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, it feels like two years,'' Smoltz said of his
winless streak. ``I just keep plugging along and doing what I set
out to do and try to give the team a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Kile, the Rockies' free-agent flop, looked like anything
but against the Braves for the first seven innings, limiting them
to one run on four hits while striking out five. But he let the
Braves break out of their offensive trance and take a 4-2 lead in
the eighth by giving up a walk to Gerald Williams, a single to
Boone and Chipper Jones' 32nd home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had scored only four runs in their previous 25
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
