<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sore-handed Jordan rests most of game
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Brian Jordan did not start Thursday to rest his injured
right hand. He continues to be bothered by a bad bruise from being
hit by a pitch June 22.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who has played 18 games in a row (he entered in the
eighth inning), might have a CT scan done when the Braves return
home this weekend to determine if he's hurt more than doctors
originally thought. The pain and swelling has spread to other parts
of his hand, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're hurt, you're hurt,'' Jordan said. ``You want to
play here (in Coors Field), but it doesn't matter. I am (upset). I
hate watching baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams replaced Jordan in right field. Ryan Klesko hit
cleanup and played left field for the first time since Aug. 6, when
he switched from first base at mid-game against the Giants. His
last start in left field was Aug. 4 against the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took fly balls the day before yesterday,'' said Klesko, who
has started 46 games in left field and 44 games at first base this
season. ``The ball carries differently here. You really have to
concentrate to get under fly balls here. No matter how long you've
been coming here, you really have to concentrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall Simon started at first base for the first time since
Aug. 4 in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies rested Larry Walker and Dante Bichette, though both
pinch hit.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker: `Mental breakdown'
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker was more angry about two walks in a row than
Wednesday's winning homer to Walker. Rocker walked Neifi Perez and
Terry Shumpert before Walker's ninth-inning blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't mentally into it,'' said Rocker, who ended a streak
of 14 consecutive scoreless outings in 15 2/3 innings. ``I don't
know (why). There are just some days you have more trouble
concentrating than others. It's just a mental breakdown. There's no
reason to go out there and not have better command.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker had thrown Walker two good sliders _ one for a ball, one
for a called strike _ before hanging the fateful 1-2 slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what messes you up here,'' said Rocker, who has allowed
six runs in one-third of an inning in two outings at Coors Field.
``In Atlanta, that pitch probably would have been a high strike.
Here, it doesn't move. (Kevin) Millwood showed you can throw good
breaking balls here ... (but) if you have the slightest lapse in
concentration, an average pitch turns into a real bad pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker's homer was the first Rocker has given up to a
left-handed hitter this season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
