r s BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN     08-19 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
 
McNOWN AMONG McUNKNOWNS? 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Four years ago this month, a freckled freshman
named Cade McNown arrived in Westwood to begin a record-setting
career.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, he was UCLA's fourth-string quarterback, stuck
behind unproven veterans Ryan Fien, Rob Walker and Steve Buck. But
it did not take long for depth-chart tectonics to shift.
</P>
<P>
   Buck broke his thumb early in training camp and never recovered
the lost ground. Walker was ineffective and Fien, the starter,
suffered concussions in the first two games. By late September,
McNown had emerged from the morass to claim the starting job and he
never let it go.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks before the 1999 season opener, UCLA's quarterback
quagmire has come full circle. Once again, there are four
candidates, myriad questions and no easy answers. Is there another
McNown in the group or are they simply a bunch of young Bucks?
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Bruins coach Bob Toledo and offensive coordinator
Al Borges will select two candidates to compete for the starting
job. Based on practice performance, it appears junior Drew Bennett
and redshirt freshman Cory Paus have surged ahead of sophomore
Scott McEwan and redshirt freshman Ryan McCann.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to formulate some ideas,'' Toledo said. ``We've
seen what they've done and what they haven't done. We've charted
them, but we're going to wait for (a scrimmage) Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus, a 6-2, 220-pounder from New Lenox, Ill., has been the most
consistent and the most accurate. He doesn't have a great arm
(neither did McNown), but he throws a tight spiral that's pillow
soft. He's an instinctive leader, tough and confident, with a knack
for big plays. Tuesday, he threw the pass of the preseason _ a
majestic 40-yard strike over receiver Jon Dubravac's outside
shoulder, inches beyond three defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cory has been really consistent,'' McEwan said. ``He's
throwing the ball well.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bennett and McEwan constantly evaluate the competition _
``I even check how everyone else is doing in the weight room,''
McEwan said _ Paus keeps his gaze internal and his plan practical.
His goal wasn't to win the job in spring practice, for instance,
but to stay within range of Bennett, whose experience gave him a
huge early advantage. This week, Paus has been focused on surviving
the first cut and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to keep myself in the top two and stay in the
race,'' he said. ``If I can keep it like that, I'll probably play
in the first game. All I want to do is get to that game.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Paus wins the job outright or splits time with Bennett _
Toledo is considering a two-man platoon for the opener _ depends on
how quickly he learns the offense. There are dozens of passing
plays, a plethora of patterns within each play and several options
for each pattern. McNown needed 18 months to absorb it. Bennett has
had three years, and Paus, 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a good grasp of all the plays and reads,
and what plays are good with what defenses,'' Bennett said. ``I
know where the (third and fourth) receivers are on all the
routes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bennett's head has outperformed his arm. He worked on
mechanics all summer _ refining his footwork and balance, honing
his release point _ yet his passes often flutter. His immense
athleticism and grasp of the offense might be enough to beat Boise
State and Fresno State, but Pac-10 defenses will feast on his
floaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Drew has a downside, he needs to be a more consistent
thrower,'' Borges said. ``But he's ironing that out.''
</P>
<P>
   McEwan, a Thousand Oaks native, also has thrown better in recent
days and might have gained ground. He has the strongest arm of the
group and trails only Bennett in experience. But is there enough
time for McEwan to overcome a skittish start, which he attributed
to flawed mechanics? Toledo has shown no sign of wavering on the
weekend deadline. There's barely enough time to prepare two
quarterbacks for game conditions, much less three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing my whole future ahead of me in one week,'' said
McEwan, who has used his redshirt year. ``There's a lot of
pressure, but quarterbacks have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann, out of Agoura High, doesn't appear bothered by pressure
or mechanical flaws. He has a prototype delivery and good pace on
his passes. But McCann is not as experienced as Bennett and not as
accurate as Paus _ at least not yet. By next week, who knows? An
injury here, a slump there, and the quarterback shuffle could begin
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a tough situation,'' Borges said. ``It's the
epitome of paralysis by analysis. The guys are trying to absorb so
much stuff, and there's so little time, and they're trying to
impress the coaches and they're trying to make plays. It's not
easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
