<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-TRACK-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 MARION JONES WANTS TO GO WHERE NO WOMAN HAS GONE BEFORE: FOUR GOLD
MEDALS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ Marion Jones has been asked to address the same
topics for months, and Thursday, as she sat next to Michael Johnson
and Maurice Greene on a makeshift stage with a microphone in her
hand and a lazy stretch of the Guadalquivir River in the
background, she was asked again by a much larger audience than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   Was she ready to peak at the world track and field championships
here? Were her long-jumping difficulties no longer difficulties?
Which relay would she run and why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get this meet started now,'' Jones said with
only 48 more hours of prologue to endure and the just-barely
finished 60,000-seat stadium in Seville in clear view in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has done this to herself, stamping out subplots with her
surpassing talent and willfully, cheerfully, convincingly,
generating the highest expectations by proclaiming well in advance
what she wants to achieve. Four gold medals in Seville and five
next year at the Olympics in Sydney, Australia, are what she wants,
although it is not what she predicts. Therein lies the difference,
and part of Jones' appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Muhammad Ali braggadocio,'' said Craig Masback, the
chief executive of USA Track and Field, who has watched Jones both
sprint and field questions with style.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some awkward questions to handle lately in the
wake of the positive drug tests that have led to the suspension of
the American sprinter Dennis Mitchell and cast a shadow over the
Olympic gold medalists Javier Sotomayor and Linford Christie. On
Wednesday night, Jones discovered that another familiar name had
been added to that list: Merlene Ottey, the Jamaican who was
running remarkably fast before the 23-year-old Jones was born and
who withdrew from these championships after the banned steroid
nandrolone was detected in a test administered last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody could have thought this was going to
happen,'' Jones said. ``Obviously in the past couple of weeks our
beautiful and lovely sport has been marred by all of this. I think
the athletes wish we could have come here to Seville and put all of
that in the past and start on a positive note. Once again, we've
started on a negative note, but we can only hope that our wonderful
performances in a couple of days will overshadow everything that
has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones won two gold medals in her first world championships in
Athens, Greece, two summers ago, in the 100 meters and in the 4 x
100-meter relay. This year, her goal is to win the 100 and 200, the
long jump and then either the 4 x 100 or 4 x 400 relay.
</P>
<P>
   Women have won four medals at the same world championships, but
no woman has won four gold medals. After an opening ceremony on
Friday night, Jones will begin her quest with a burst of activity
on Saturday. The qualifying round for the women's long jump begins
at 10:30 a.m. Fifteen minutes later, the first round of the 100
begins. The second round of the 100 is on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to go out there and hopefully on my first jump
qualify and be able to concentrate on the 100 after that,'' Jones
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Jones makes it look easy, track and field experts know
the truth. ``Any time you try to knock off even three events, it's
a huge tussle,'' said Lance Harter, the coach of the American
women's team in Seville. ``But to be considered a relay candidate,
too, with the number of rounds she has to go through, is
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   John Smith, who coaches Greene and Inger Miller, an American who
could pose a slight threat to Jones in the 200, said: ``She's going
to stand on that podium four or five times. It's just a matter of
which color she's going to stand there with. But I'm going to be
watching very intently to see it happen. There is going to be some
history being made, and I think the sport needs that. And,
actually, she needs challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is nearing her peak and will have plenty of chances to
show off with three world championships and two Olympics in the
next six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marion Jones is arguably the best athlete in the world right
now and what I call the first female athlete who will have a chance
to transcend sports as Pele and Ali and Michael Jordan did on a
worldwide basis,'' said Masback, who, in light of track and field's
minor status in the United States, has a major stake in that
prediction coming true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, what is the universe of female sports stars?''
Masback asked. ``Tennis stars basically, who traditionally are
hermetically sealed and grew up on country clubs and, at least
historically, are not people of color. With all due respect to the
women's soccer World Cup, how many countries are serious about
soccer for women? But track and field, there are 150 or 160
countries of the 210 here who have serious women's programs. And so
when Marion is the world champion, it means something, and the
world will come to know her.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' biggest challenge in Seville should be the long jump, in
which she finished 10th in Athens. Though her times and margins of
victory have not been as awesome this season, she has not lost a
sprint since 1997, but she has been beaten three times in the long
jump in that span: in last year's Grand Prix final by Heike
Drechsler, in this year's U.S. championships by Dawn Burrell and by
Drechsler at a meet in Linz, Austria, on July 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had problems the last couple of competitions with my
rhythm on the runway,'' she said. ``But since Linz, we've gone back
to the drawing board, and I'm ready and excited to get out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The long jump final is on Monday night; the first two rounds of
the 200 on Tuesday; the semifinals on Wednesday and the final on
Friday. Then, she said, she will choose between the 4 x 400 and 4 x
100 relays.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the decision likely will unfold this way: ``Trevor
Graham, my coach, has told me that after my three individual events
are done and hopefully I'm happy with three wins there, he said
he's going to look into my eyes and tell if I'm ready to run a 400
meters or not.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jones already has three golds by then, Graham will probably
see a lot more than that in his pupil's eyes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
