<HEADLINE>
3 JAPANESE BANKS DISCUSSING $1.3 TRILLION COMBINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Three major Japanese banks confirmed Thursday that they
were in discussions about a possible merger that would create the
world's largest financial institution, with $1.3 trillion in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   An alliance of the Industrial Bank of Japan, Fuji Bank and
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, if completed, would be the biggest step taken
by individual Japanese banks to overcome the effects of the
nation's protracted recession, which has left the banking industry
hobbled by bad debts. It also could help the three Japanese banks
adapt to the government's deregulation of the financial markets,
which is creating new competition in the banking and securities
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the banks said in a brief statement that they were
working toward forming a joint holding company. Their statement
followed a report in Japan's leading business daily, Nihon Keizai
Shimbun, that they had been negotiating an alliance aimed at
bringing about an integration of their activities within a year.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's report led to speculation that more such mergers
would be coming in Japanese banking, and this contributed to a
rally in bank stocks. Dai-Ichi Kangyo shares rose 11 percent,
Industrial Bank of Japan shares gained nearly 9 percent and Fuji
shares gained 1 percent before the Tokyo Stock Exchange halted
trading in them shortly before the banks confirmed that they were
in talks.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, it is unclear whether such a combination would
succeed, partly because of the sheer magnitude of the three-way
merger. Their combined assets would surpass the $899 billion in
assets of Deutsche Bank (with Bankers Trust), making such a
combination potentially the world's biggest bank.
</P>
<P>
   It would also surpass what would have become the world's biggest
bank if Banque Nationale de Paris had succeeded in acquiring
Paribas and Societe Generale. The assets in that three-way deal
would have totaled around $1 trillion. Banque Nationale won
shareholder approval only from Paribas.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether a Japanese bank deal comes to fruition,
analysts said there would probably be more consolidations in an
industry that remains bloated and inefficient. Many banks are still
struggling under the weight of hundreds of billions of dollars in
loans that soured when the Japanese real estate market collapsed in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   And though interest rates here have fallen to record lows, which
should stimulate more lending and help bank profits, the balance
sheets of many institutions remain weak.
</P>
<P>
   The 3 banks are among 15 that were beneficiaries of an enormous
government-financed rescue package in March. Although they are all
saddled with large bad debts, the banks concentrate in different
businesses that could complement each other, were they to merge
into one huge force.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial Bank of Japan, for example, is the only domestic bank
that still specializes in long-term loans to Japanese companies.
Its two competitors, the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan and Nippon
Credit Bank, were seized by the government after they became
insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   Fuji Bank would regain its presence in the securities business
through IBJ Securities, a subsidiary of the Industrial Bank of
Japan that is one of the most profitable securities operations in
the country. Fuji lost its securities business link nearly two
years ago when an affiliate, Yamaichi Securities, collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Dai-Ichi Kangyo, one of Japan's biggest lenders, would benefit
by gaining the customers of the two others.
</P>
<P>
   The three banks combined have 41,000 employees in 772 branches
in Japan and abroad. But any merger of this size would probably
lead to cost-cutting and layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Nihon Keizai Shimbun, quoting unidentified banking officials,
said the three institutions would divide their operations in
retail, corporate and investment banking, hoping to realize large
economies of scale.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
