</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-PERROT-OBIT-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERROT, INSPIRATIONAL LEADER OF HOUSTON COMETS, DIES OF CANCER AT
32 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By W.H. STICKNEY JR. 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Houston Comets guard Kim Perrot, whose fighting spirit and
tender heart inspired cheers in times of triumph and prayers as she
struggled for her life, died Thursday afternoon, ending her
six-month battle with brain and lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   She was 32.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot came to Houston in 1997, a shy woman who at 5 feet 5
inches tall was given little chance of making the Houston Comets'
10-player roster during the inaugural season of the Women's
National Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did she endure, she led the Comets to two WNBA
championships as the team's emotional leader. After she was
diagnosed with cancer earlier this year, the on-court firebrand
became a cheery, tireless spokeswoman for construction of Kim's
Place, a residential facility for children suffering from
life-threatening illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family promise that dream will endure in the wake of
Perrot's death shortly before 3 p.m. CDT Thursday at M.D. Anderson
Cancer Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim was an inspiration to each of us, and she touched all of
our lives in so many ways,'' the Perrot family said in a statement
released by the Comets. ``We will always love her and cherish her
in our heart, and we know that each of you will, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those at the bedside was Perrot's closest friend on the
Comets, Cynthia Cooper. The rest of the team received word of her
death after arriving in Los Angeles, where the Comets will play the
Los Angeles Sparks on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Comets coach Van Chancellor said he has lost his best friend, a
woman who was as close to him as a daughter and a player who, when
the coach's words failed, could move her teammates to greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things went bad, Kim was the person who held this team
together,'' Chancellor said. ``She leaves a void in my life that
can never be filled. How do you lose someone you loved so much?''
</P>
<P>
   WNBA President Val Ackerman said, ``The entire WNBA family is
devastated by this tragic loss. We will always remember Kim as a
woman of great heart and indomitable courage who refused to be
daunted by any challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot had spent much of the past month in Tijuana, Mexico,
receiving alternative treatment for lung cancer that had spread to
her brain. But her condition worsened, and she was flown back to
Houston early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot received word of the cancer diagnosis Feb. 19. It was a
bolt from the blue for Perrot, a nonsmoker and the most physically
fit member of the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, during an emotional news conference at the
Comets' Westside Tennis Club practice center, Perrot clutched at
the hand of Chancellor, her friend, father figure and coach, and
fought back tears as she disclosed her condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a fighter all my life,'' she said. ``This is just
another fight, and I'm going to win this one, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later at M.D. Anderson, Perrot underwent surgery to
remove a golf-ball-sized tumor from her brain. Four smaller tumors
also were found in her brain.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot also had advanced alveolar adenocarcinoma, which accounts
for only 2 percent to 4 percent of lung cancer cases but is the
most common form of lung cancer in nonsmokers.
</P>
<P>
   In cases such as Perrot's, when tumors spread to the brain, the
cancer is ``virtually incurable,'' said Garrett Lynch, acting chief
of oncology at Baylor College of Medicine. Average survival is
three to six months, and only 15 percent of patients survive one
year.
</P>
<P>
   Though chemotherapy was offered as an option, Perrot chose
instead to travel to Tijuana for alternative treatment. The family
has declined to discuss details of the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch said patients sometimes seek alternative therapies in
Mexico such as shark cartilage, laetrile (an extract from apricot
pits purported to cause regression of cancer), vitamins and herbs.
Lynch said laetrile was not shown to be effective in a National
Cancer Institute study. Studies evaluating the effectiveness of
shark cartilage are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her illness, Perrot once again became a familiar face at
Comets practices and games early this season. On June 18 at Compaq
Center, she received her 1998 WNBA championship ring from
Chancellor and Rockets executive Carroll Dawson. She felt strong
enough six days later to travel with the team on a two-game trip to
Detroit and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But after a day and a half in Detroit, Perrot flew back to
Houston because of ``job-related business,'' she said. Over the
next month, her visits to the Comets became far less frequent and
of shorter duration.
</P>
<P>
   But Perrot was at Compaq Center on July 11 when the Comets
hosted the Sacramento Monarchs. The Comets built a 23-point
first-half lead, then began to wither in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``During one timeout,'' said Chancellor, ``she came into the
huddle behind me, and I didn't even see her, didn't know she was
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said to me, `Coach, you know I love you.'''
</P>
<P>
   While the Comets held on for a five-point victory, the lingering
memory for Chancellor was not the win, but Perrot's words. He burst
into tears while recounting them earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Perrot returned to Tijuana. Cooper said she planned
to return to Houston in mid-August to begin chemotherapy. During
the first week of August, however, Cooper was summoned to Tijuana.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's OK,'' Cooper said, ``but she's finding the fight a
little tougher than she expected.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 12, the Comets were told Perrot had taken a turn for the
worse. Team owner Leslie Alexander arranged for her to be flown to
Houston and for her family to join her.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Southwestern Louisiana in Lafayette, Perrot was a
member of the U.S. national team in 1989 and 1990. She scored 58
points in a game against Southeastern Louisiana, the second-highest
single-game total in NCAA history, and she led the nation in
scoring her senior year with an average of 30.1 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   After playing professional basketball for six seasons in Sweden,
Germany, Israel and France, she was invited to try out for the
newly formed WNBA in 1997. Chancellor fondly recalls her as being
``the 58th player on a 55-player roster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She had no chance of making our team,'' Chancellor said.
``None. But she proved everybody wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of person Kim Perrot is. She was the most
lovable person you'd ever want to meet, but put a challenge in
front of her, and she'd fight you tooth and nail.''
</P>
<P>
   The nuts and bolts of Perrot's career _ 7.2 points per game, 230
assists and 153 steals _ were overshadowed by her leadership and
her impact on those she met in hundreds of public appearances
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got up every day having to prove herself being 5-5, and
she overcame more things. It made her tough,'' said the Rockets'
Dawson. ``I believed in everything she said she was going to do.
She was an extraordinary person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably talk to as many people a day in my job as anybody.
It's always before business starts: `How's Kim doing?' She touched
a lot of people. The world's not as good as it was before 3
o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Plans for funeral services and a memorial service are pending. The
family has designated Kim's Place for memorials. Contributions
should be made payable to the Clutch City Foundation and sent to 2
Greenway Plaza, Suite 400, Houston 77046. For information, call
713-996-7359.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporters Leigh Hopper and Jonathan Feigen contributed to
this story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
