<HEADLINE>
TENNANT, BLUTE TELL CONFLICTING TALES ON CRUISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS AND MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Breaking his silence over the scandalous harbor cruise
that that has rocked the state's political establishment,
Republican operative Alexander Tennant Thursday fingered ousted
Massport director Peter Blute as the event's organizer.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant also said he had, at Blute's invitation, joined a
similar cruise last August with about 15 people, including Massport
officials, at which there was heavy drinking and socializing. He
said Blute had also organized that trip and the agency paid the
$575 tab for the boat's rental.
</P>
<P>
   Blute denied Tennant's account and said the 1998 summer outing
was ordered by Massport board member George Cashman to view harbor
facilities and was not for pleasure. Cashman was not available for
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is careening out of control,'' said Blute when told of
Tennant's statements.
</P>
<P>
   Massport officials say private boats are hired from time to time
for official cruises, especially for out-of-town VIPs. Usually
alcohol is served aboard the cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Massport would not provide details Thursday of the cruises or
how much they cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bring board members out there all the time,'' Blute said in
an interview with the Globe. ``It was not like the one that
happened the other day.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the previous trips involved the Nauticus, the cabin
cruiser the agency rented for Tuesday's now infamous voyage.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant's first public comments since Tuesday about the cruise
revealed a rift between him and Blute, his friend of 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess all around,'' said one top Cellucci insider.
</P>
<P>
   The two men caused the first major scandal of the Cellucci
administration after they were photographed by The Boston Herald
drinking beer and champagne with women dressed in beachwear. One of
the women, identified by sources as Gidget Churchill, a part-time
actress and stunt double, bared her breasts for the Herald
photographer.
</P>
<P>
   Blute was forced to resign by Governor Paul Cellucci, who was
reportedly furious at Blute's behavior and the embarrassing photos.
Cellucci, who is on vacation in Florida this week, and Lieutenant
Governor Jane Swift have severed all ties with Tennant, who has
used his connections to Cellucci to boost his lobbying business.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant said Blute set up the cruise in July, and invited
Tennant to come along.
</P>
<P>
   But Blute Thursday insisted his account that Tennant had
requested he set up Tuesday's party cruise is correct. He pointed
out that he had boarded the boat alone, while the others aboard
were Tennant's guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the one who brought the people,'' Blute said. ``There
was nobody from Massport except myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Blute has admitted arranging through Massport for the boat's
rental, but said it was always assumed ``private parties'' would
reimburse the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Tennant also revealed details of the cover story he
and Blute came up with late in the afternoon, after realizing they
had been spotted by the media drinking and socializing with the
women aboard the Nauticus.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant said he, Blute and Maureen Stemberg _ a well-known
Boston socialite who joined the cruise on its final leg _ decided
together they would tell the media that Stemberg, ex-wife of
Staples chief Tom Stemberg, would pay for the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   As the story blew up Wednesday, more questions were asked, and
Stemberg balked, Blute reimbursed the agency $834 for the boat
rental.
</P>
<P>
   Blute said he went along with the initial story, a decision he
admits was a serious mistake. But he insisted that the story had
been created by Tennant to cover up the fact that the Massport was
paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   Blute expressed frustration at his friends continuing the debate
over his behavior, which he said showed a serious error in
judgment. TV news reporters were stationed outside his Shrewsbury
home Thursday and he was granting interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Another Massport official expressed frustration with Tennant, a
lobbyist who has made inquiries recently at Massport for his
client, Arthur Winn, who wants to build luxury housing on the East
Boston waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandy has been harrassing the hell out of us for Arthur
Winn,'' said one Massport insider. The source said Tennant had
wanted Blute and others to restrict the bidding so that Winn's
competition would be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant said Thursday he could not discuss his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Angry at media coverage, Tennant also fiercely defended his
right to carry on a lifestyle that includes socializing at Boston
night spots and political circles with one or several young women.
He said he and his wife had agreed to separate nearly three years
ago and that he is free to conduct his private life as he wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I do with my time is nobody's business but my own,''
Tennant said. ``If someone has a problem with my lifestyle they
should deal with me and stop harrassing my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennant said the media Thursday descended on his family home and
frightened his wife and children. He said he and his wife had
wanted to keep their separation private to protect their children.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant also said he deeply regretted the embarrassment he had
created for Cellucci. ``I feel very badly if I caused him any
embarrassment,'' Tennant said. ``It certainly was not my
intention.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he understood why Cellucci had to cut his ties with him.
``Paul had to do what was in his best political interest,'' Tennant
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, interim Massport executive director Scott L. Kafker
said the agency was trying to move beyond the shock of Blute's
resignation and concentrate on business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direction to everyone is to stop spending time worrying
about this stuff and get back to work,'' Kafker said.
</P>
<P>
   Kafker also forcefully reminded senior Massport staff of the
agency's ethical rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday's events are obviously extraordinary and very
disturbing,'' Kafker said. ``There are rules that prevent the use
of public moneys for non-public purposes. We are trying to make
sure nothing slips through the cracks here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kafker, who is not considered a candidate to permanently replace
Blute, would not speculate about how long he might serve as acting
executive director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
