<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3638 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     08-19 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHAT makes athletes special also makes them vulnerable. Sometimes
they are too strong, too tough and too headstrong for their own
good. They drink too much or drive too fast or they do both at once
because they think they can, because they wrongheadedly believe
they are immortal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show me a hero, and I will write you a tragedy,'' F. Scott
Fitzgerald once said. But Kim Perrot was a different kind of hero,
and a different kind of tragedy. Once, her story was as uplifting
as any I have ever covered. Today, honestly, it's the saddest.
</P>
<P>
   See, Kim didn't do anything wrong. You kidding? She did
everything right. She worked twice as hard as the next player, she
believed in herself when almost no one else wanted to, and she
politely refused to accept no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   Van Chancellor, the Comets' coach, admits he wrote her off the
first day of practice, ranking her as the longest shot among dozens
trying to stick. Yet nobody, except perhaps two-time WNBA MVP
Cynthia Cooper, came to value her more than Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   A spindly, unheralded 5-foot-5 woman making a living, albeit it
a humble one relative to that of her hulking male counterparts, as
a professional basketball player? Ridiculous. And miraculous. If
anybody, anybody, could have defeated the kind of cancer that was
destroying her lungs and attacking her brain, it was going to be
Perrot.
</P>
<P>
   No one could have, of course. This was bad, bad stuff. The worst
imaginable. Medical people who heard what her illness was when we
were told of it at a tear-stained February news conference _ Kim
bravely opted to break the news herself _ shook their heads. They
understood. They couldn't say it, but she never stood a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes miracles aren't an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``In incidents like this,'' Rockets/Comets executive Carroll
Dawson said, ``when you're so close to someone, you tend to think
more with your heart than you do with your head. She had overcome
everything. I believe she thought she was going to beat this, and I
did, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But Kim probably realized from the start the magnitude
of what she was confronting. It wasn't something simple like making
a basketball team or gaining a starting job or contributing hugely
to two championship runs. Guts, heart and desire, all of which she
possessed in such abundance, making her a front-and-center Comet
despite many obvious physical shortcomings, wouldn't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot's relentlessly positive outlook and sunny disposition
might have prolonged her life a little _ and touched a great many
other lives in the process _ but they wouldn't save her. We weren't
in a movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   She died Thursday afternoon, six months after the awful clock
started ticking. Everything that could have been done was done,
down to the obligatory last-ditch, futile pilgrimage to Mexico for
``experimental'' treatment. You only hope she went comfortably,
without pain or fear, having made peace with her god.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, meanwhile, were already in Los Angeles, where they
must play the most seemingly empty and unimportant of basketball
games tonight. But, honestly, it's a game they must win because
that's the one truly appropriate way to honor the memory of someone
as determined and courageous as Perrot was.
</P>
<P>
   As pros, you suck up, you give your all and you win. Then you
grieve. Then you win again Saturday and you grieve some more. Then
you keep on winning until you have your arms around another WNBA
title.
</P>
<P>
   For Kim, this one.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances, it won't be easy. That's the way you
want it, though, because nothing came easy for Perrot. Had she not
achieved a measure of celebrity for her basketball achievements,
very few of us would have paid notice to her passing. Lots of folks
died Thursday without newspaper stories and columns being written
about them.
</P>
<P>
   Kim willed herself to be special. Kim made herself be noticed _
the right way. Her path never detoured across a police blotter or
through a detox center. But while you loathe the screaming
injustice of a unique athlete and a good person dying young, in her
prime, you find a modicum of solace in your memories of her.
</P>
<P>
   The way she ran Van Chancellor's offense, at once reading,
interpreting and creating. The way she flustered, irritated and
occasionally embarrassed larger, more celebrated opponents with her
scrappy defense. The way she and Cynthia Cooper came to be of the
same mind, instinctively reacting to what the other would do _
before she did it.
</P>
<P>
   We had already come to miss that, and accepted how it could
never be again. Just the same, the finality of the news of Kim's
death cut a hole in us anyway. You realize there's no answer, but
you can't help it. Over and over, you still ask why.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-99 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990819.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3640 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-AIKMAN-TE     08-19 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-AIKMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN EXPECTING COWBOYS' REVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ Jogging the memory can be a painful
experience, even if you have three Super Bowl rings.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to take you through the period we just came out
of ... \Rwhere\S we did nothing on the football field to indicate
we were doing anything right,'' Aikman said of the Cowboys' 6-10
season two years ago and one playoff victory since their last Super
Bowl victory in January 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I'm not surprised that people have their doubts. But
slowly, in my opinion, we're regaining some respectability.`
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys might be 25-1 Super Bowl long shots in Las Vegas.
They might be panned as a team in decline and criticized for having
had only one draft choice since the '93 draft _ Larry Allen _ make
the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Aikman isn't afraid to look ahead. And, for the
first time in a while, it has become easier than looking behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to get some young players in here who are
really going to help this team,'' Aikman said. ``But for the
longest time, we were losing great players and doing nothing to
replace them. We weren't bringing in any youth that would sustain
us.''
</P>
<P>
   More and more, that has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Ebenezer Ekuban. Peppi Zellner. Dat Nguyen. Wane McGarity.
Solomon Page. Of the Cowboys' eight draft choices, these five, and
maybe a sixth, barring injury, should make this team and should
make significant contributions as rookies in '99.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Ellis. Flozell Adams. From the '98 draft come two '99
starters, at least.
</P>
<P>
   David LaFleur. From the '97 draft comes this key player to the
'99 offense, according to no less an authority on the Cowboys'
offense than its quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be the offense that we hope to be, then
\RLaFleur\S is going to be a very integral part of it,'' Aikman
said. ``He is extremely important to us in the running game. He's
also important to us in the passing game. In a two-back offense, if
you don't have a tight end who can win in passing situations,
you're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-7, 280-pound LaFleur only recently has returned to
practice after suffering a broken right ankle in workouts on May
11. A week later, he underwent back surgery to repair a herniated
disk.
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur is scheduled to make his preseason debut tomorrow night
at New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely playing,'' LaFleur said yesterday. ``I don't
feel totally back to where I was \Rbefore breaking the ankle\S ...
but then I wasn't the fastest tight end in the first place. I'm
struggling with \Rthe ankle\S, but I'm getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur welcomes the pressure put on him by Aikman, saying,
``Everybody wants to be involved as much as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   The '98 Cowboys offense was disappointing in four of its last
five games. Not coincidentally, LaFleur missed 3 1/2 of those five
games with a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur doesn't have to be the reincarnate of Jay Novacek for
this offense to prosper. LaFleur simply needs to block like an
offensive tackle and beat mostly linebackers on short to
intermediate routes. But he has to be able to do it consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the tight end in this offense isn't going to be
like the tight end with Novacek in it a few years ago,'' LaFleur
said. ``But coach Gailey and the offensive staff are taking it upon
themselves to involve the tight end more. I hope I can step up and
fill the role.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, as Aikman, Emmitt Smith and Michael Irvin try to
recapture their lost youth and magic, there is the arrival of this
young talent, looking to sustain the Cowboys in a way that drafts
earlier this decade could not do.
</P>
<P>
   And if this doesn't translate into a movement by the so-called
experts to pick the Cowboys to repeat as NFC East champs and make a
strong run in the playoffs, well, Aikman isn't surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if anybody has anything good to say about any
team in the NFL,'' said the six-time Pro Bowl quarterback, who is
starting his 11th season. ``I could say the same thing: `This team
or that team is not going to win the Super Bowl. This team or that
team doesn't have a chance,' and you know what? I'm going to be
right 30 out of 31 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to win a Super Bowl. Minnesota had a great year,
but who cares? Denver won the Super Bowl. Was Minnesota's season
better than ours season last year? Statistically, it was. But I
don't know if they feel any better about their season than we feel
about ours. This game is about winning the Super Bowl. If you don't
do that, it doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk how the \RCowboys\S struggled over four of the
last five games and how Minnesota piled up 50 points a game. Who
cares?'' Aikman concluded. ``Minnesota lost in the NFC Championship
Game and had a great statistical year. Five years from now, nobody
is going to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, no one remembers.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
