r s BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     08-19 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS COACH'S TRIP TO CHINA NOT A BIG JOKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, it seemed like a logical request.
</P>
<P>
   In China, the People's Liberation Army contains an estimated 2.5
million soldiers. Surely, they could have spared one tall, skinny
private.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, however, though he and the boss flew all the way
to Beijing for one Chinese take-out order, Don Nelson will be
returning empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Chinese team's manager, it is ``not the right
time'' for 7-foot-1 Wang Zhizhi to abandon his homeland for a
career with the NBA's Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   (Supply own joke here).
</P>
<P>
   Qian Limin, who runs the Army team, the Bayi Rockets, did say it
was ``a nice thing'' that Wang was selected by the Mavs in the June
NBA draft. Speaking in Mandarin, Qian also politely left out all
mention of the Jason Kidd trade.
</P>
<P>
   The item made ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' and the daily notes
section of sports pages across the United States. A good chuckle
probably was had by all.
</P>
<P>
   But let's be realistic here. Did Nelson and owner Ross Perot Jr.
really expect young Wang to be waiting in his barracks, duffel bag
packed, eager to elope with basketball's global Welcome Wagon, the
Mavericks?
</P>
<P>
   No. The idea was simply to secure Wang's draft rights by
tendering him a contract offer. Under China's Military Service Law
of 1984, all men _ and women _ between the ages of 18 and 22 are
liable for at least three years of compulsory military service.
Eventually, therefore, his military commitment will be satisfied.
And if Wang ever plays anywhere where the Chinese flag isn't flown,
Nelson wanted to make sure that it is Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Second-round draft picks are not odds-on choices to
log prompt NBA playing time, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Allow me to defend this latest Tour de Nellie for a second. The
trip builds goodwill. There was also no guarantee, given the
vagaries of the international mails, that the contract offer would
have ever reached Wang's company mail call.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Nelson likely finally got to see Wang work out first hand.
</P>
<P>
   The trip reminds me of a personal quest that I undertook at the
1976 Montreal Olympics, during the days when the media was still
allowed to roam the hallways of the Athletes Village. The team from
back home, the then-New Orleans Jazz, had caused a mild stir that
spring by drafting the NBA rights to Soviet Union center Alexander
Belov. The Jazz had no clue of what to do after that.
</P>
<P>
   Yours truly volunteered to test the negotiating waters. I was
escorted through the winding halls of the delegation village by Jim
``Hoss'' Brock, the great former Cotton Bowl impresario, who was
assisting the U.S. Olympic Committee's public-relations contingent.
</P>
<P>
   Brock, it must be noted, never met a stranger and has the
defining habit of referring to everyone he speaks to as ``Hoss.''
</P>
<P>
   With Brock leading the way, we finally found the temporary
quarters of the Soviet Olympic Committee. A floor-to-ceiling
hammer-and-sickle flag hung behind the main desk. A giant framed
portrait of Lenin stared back from the near wall. The bald
gentleman behind the desk had two rows of military medals draped
over his left breast.
</P>
<P>
   I took a deep breath and began to explain why I wanted to talk
to Belov, the future center of the New Orleanigrad Jazzkis. The man
nodded. I rambled. The man nodded. I think I said something about
good restaurants to find Chicken Kiev.
</P>
<P>
   Brock intervened. ``Well, what about it, Hoss? Think you can
help my man?'' he asked the Soviet Olympic comrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not possible,'' I remember the man saying. ``Mr. Belov
plays for us. It is not possible for him, therefore, to play in the
United States. Have a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   I slithered out of the room. I'll bet they don't get rid of
Nellie that easily.
</P>
<P>
   Since that day, of course, the NBA's policy of global warming
has been refined and all Hosses identified.
</P>
<P>
   It drives most Mavericks fans crazy. They don't understand why
Nellie has to fly all the way to Beijing or Melbourne to find
prospects when there are perfectly good players in New York or
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, there are 1.24 billion people in China. They
come in all shapes and sizes. Wang is not a giant among dwarfs.
</P>
<P>
   He is, perhaps, the Mavericks' future, as is Dirk Nowitzki,
Michael Finley and maybe even Bruno Sundov. Nelson can boldly think
of the future because, thanks to Perot, he has a contract that
guarantees him either the owner's patience or his money, whatever
runs out first.
</P>
<P>
   As Wang's Chinese team manager said, this isn't ``the right
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He can say that again.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
