<HEADLINE>
NEWELL HEAPS PRAISE ON MAVS' 18-YEAR-OLD ROOKIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever problems Mavericks rookie Leon Smith had during the
early days in minicamp, they have been nonexistent at Pete Newell's
Big Man camp.
</P>
<P>
   The camp, held this week in Honolulu, is a showcase for post
players aspiring to develop their skills. Newell has been impressed
with the work turned in by the 18-year old Smith, who is 6-foot-11
and weighs 235 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got loads of talent, he's quick and he can jump,'' Newell
said. ``He has the body of a person who can play at a high level
while weighing between 270-275 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a big jump from the high school to the NBA. But
he's playing with NBA players here, and he's doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   During the first day of the Mavericks' minicamp last month,
Smith walked out of camp after assistant coach Donnie Nelson told
him to run wind sprints. But Newell has detected no rebellious acts
from Smith, who graduated from Chicago's Martin Luther King High
School last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He listens very well, and I'm very happy about his
receptiveness,'' Newell said. ``What I had heard he did in the
Mavericks' camp, I've seen none of that down here, and all of my
NBA coaches have seen none of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, they all say he's very coachable, he has a good
attitude, and he works real hard. There's nothing that he's done
here that indicates that he can't be coached or taught.''
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks center Shawn Bradley is also attending Newell's camp
for the first time since he entered the NBA in 1993. Newell said he
had always wanted to work with Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley's been fine, although he had a little trouble with his
back the first day, and we had to keep him out of the contact part
of the scrimmages,'' Newell said. ``But he's very athletic, and he
has good agility for a man his size.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had always shied away from Newell's camp, saying the
summer was the time he dedicates to spending more time with his
family. Newell is happy the six-year veteran finally had a change
of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley's footwork is so good that he's good enough to go out
and guard a lot of guys away from the basketball,'' Newell said.
``So, there's no reason why he can't be a dominant player in the
NBA if he dedicates himself.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
