<HEADER>
A3647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-MILLIONAIRE-GOOF-N     08-19 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MILLIONAIRE-GOOF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.) 
HIT QUIZ SHOW MISSES ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ABC wanted its new summer series ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?'' to bring back the days when game shows were among
the biggest hits in all of television.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing it wanted was a return to the days when some of
the answers on those shows were open to question. But in an odd _
and by all accounts unscandalous _ confluence of events this week,
both things seemed to come to pass, as ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?'' which began its broadcasts on Monday, rocketed to
ratings as the breakout hit of the summer, and then wound up
embarrassed by a mistake that eliminated the show's best contestant
so far, even though he gave the right answer.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the twists of television fate, the unjustly
dispatched contestant was going for the $64,000 question.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody at the show or at ABC was being accused Thursday of
anything more than sloppy research, however, and the contestant is
already invited back to continue his quest for $1 million on Aug.
29, the last day of the show's scheduled two-week run.
</P>
<P>
   It is nothing like the days of programs like ``Twenty-One'' and
``The $64,000 Question,'' when contestants became national folk
heroes by succeeding week after week, displaying mental acuity
that, in the case of ``Twenty-One,'' was mainly the product of
being given the answers beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' has consciously aimed to
re-create the excitement of the old prime-time quiz shows, taking
contestants to a New York studio with stark lighting and camera
shots that emphasize sweaty tension over testy questions. But
nobody was doing the contestant, David Honea, any favors.
</P>
<P>
   In the show that was taped on Wednesday and broadcast last night
at 8:30, Honea, a doctoral student in computer engineering from
Raleigh, N.C., washed out on a question about which of four Great
Lakes (not including Lake Superior) has the largest area. He said
Lake Huron (right); the show said Lake Michigan (wrong).
</P>
<P>
   That decision cost Honea $32,000. He had won that much in the
game's complicated format, in which a player advances to different
dollar levels after answering multiple-choice questions. Had he
been fairly judged on the $64,000 question, he would have been only
four questions away from the ultimate total of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   After being told by the show's host, Regis Philbin, that he had
lost, Honea accepted his fate gracefully _ along with a check for
$32,000. He mentioned his doubts to the show's executive producer,
Michael Davies, only after he was off the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he kept picturing a list, and he could see Huron
ahead of Michigan,'' Davies said. The producer then consulted an
almanac. ``It said he was right,'' Davies said. ``I felt awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Calls were made to the show's researchers. More almanacs were
consulted. Lake Huron won in every case. Davies explained that one
of the show's researchers, ``a really excellent researcher,'' he
said, though he declined to name her, had essentially tried to do
too much in putting the question together.
</P>
<P>
   Davies said she had made a note that Philbin might use on the
air saying that if a contestant guessed Lake Michigan, Philbin
could say that was wrong, though Lake Michigan is bigger in volume,
not area. Somehow the issue of which lake was larger in volume
became confused with which was bigger in area and Lake Michigan
made its way onto the card that listed the right answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game show makes mistakes,'' Davies said. ``It happens on
`Jeopardy' every so often, but they're not in prime time. We have
been doing so well. That's why I think a mistake like this is
getting more attention. Because we're in prime time, we do have a
higher profile.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Who Wants to Be A Millionaire?'' is already something
of a phenomenon, having grown substantially in viewers each of the
three nights it has been on. It had 11.5 million viewers Wednesday
night, the biggest audience of any show on television that night.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure the audience knew that Honea would be back, Davies
made the unusual request of ABC that he be allowed to add a full
minute to the tape of the show last night to explain what happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
