<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-19 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PENSION-CASH-BALANCE-     08-19 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENSION-CASH-BALANCE-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEES OUTRAGED BY SWITCH TO NEW TYPE OF PENSION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINOOSKI, Vt. _ Corporate activism did not come easily to Bill
Syverson. But like a lot of his strait-laced colleagues at IBM, the
49-year-old engineer found his cause this year after realizing that
his employer planned to slash his pension by what he estimates to
be 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is nothing less than corporate-sanctioned greed,'' Syverson
told 700 employees of IBM Corp., most of them other middle-aged
men, at a meeting here Tuesday night called by the local
congressman. Cheering and applauding wildly, the employees quickly
drafted Syverson, a captain in the Naval Reserves and a natural
leader among those who work at IBM's plant in nearby Essex
Junction, in northwestern Vermont, to form a committee to fight the
pension changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I refuse?'' said Syverson, who figures he will have
to work 10 additional years to make up what IBM has taken away. No
agitator himself _ he emphasizes that he wants no part of
union-organizing efforts under way at Big Blue _ he is eager to
take on this fight. ``I've been hammered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In what critics say is the biggest threat to the pensions of
many Americans since corporate raiders and leveraged-buyout artists
plundered pension plans in the 1980s, IBM and hundreds of other
companies are changing from old-fashioned pension plans to a new
type of pension: the so-called cash-balance plan.
</P>
<P>
   For many middle-aged employees who have spent their careers at
one company, the change means that the value of their pensions will
drop by one-third to one-half, they say, delaying retirements and
in some cases making college tuition payments harder to come by.
``It scares the hell out of me,'' said Michael Mock, 43, an IBM
technician for a decade who attended the meeting on Tuesday.
``People are so afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the backlash has prompted scrutiny from lawmakers and
government agencies. Just last week, the IRS took the position in
filing in a lawsuit that a pension plan at Onan Corp., a subsidiary
of Cummins Engine, should be stripped of its tax-exempt status
because of the way it converted to a type of cash balance plan.
</P>
<P>
   The realization of what is happening has been slow and painful
for many workers. Instead of disclosing plainly that pensions were
being changed in a way that meant benefit reductions for certain
workers, some companies told workers the changes were not that
important, or were even good for them.
</P>
<P>
   But as employees sat down and worked out the numbers, and traded
information at coffee breaks and over the Internet, many found
instead that hopes for a comfortable retirement were dashed. People
walked the halls ``like zombies'' after they began to comprehend
the changes at IBM, said Tim Barritt, who also spoke at the Vermont
meeting. They asked each other, ``Are you as bashed as I am?''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional pensions, which rewarded long tenure, are being
eliminated at many companies. In these plans, retirees were
typically paid using a calculation that factored their length of
service and the amount of their annual paycheck in the few years
before retiring. Thus, most of the value of their pension accrued
late in their career.
</P>
<P>
   But the new pension plans turn that math upside down. Under
these, corporations contribute a percentage of each employee's pay
to a cash-balance account every year, and then guarantee that money
will grow at a certain interest rate, such as the yield on a
Treasury bond. At retirement, that account is their pension.
</P>
<P>
   The switch cuts costs sharply at many companies. IBM, for
instance, estimates it will save $200 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies also say the change is necessary to attract
younger workers who are not as likely to spend their entire careers
at one place, and thus prefer the faster early accruals of
cash-balance plans to old-fashioned pensions. Indeed, even harsh
critics of cash-balance conversions say that younger workers,
particularly job-hoppers, are better served with these plans.
</P>
<P>
   The IBM plan allows the roughly 30,000 employees who have either
25 years at the company, or are 50 years old with a decade of
service, to stick with the old plan.
</P>
<P>
   But for the 45,000 thousand workers with between 15 and 24 years
of service who are not 50 years old, IBM officials acknowledge that
on average the value of their pensions have dropped 20 percent,
assuming they take early retirement when they qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the protests across the country, plus the threat of
various legal challenges, IBM says it has no plans to change the
program, which went into effect July 1. But officials say many
details are misunderstood by workers and that estimates of benefit
reductions are often too high. ``We're finding in general that
calculations they're doing on their own are not correct,'' said
Jana Weatherbee, an IBM spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   For many middle-aged workers, the switch comes at exactly the
wrong moment: Just as they reach the age when the value of their
old-fashioned pension starts to soar, they discover they have been
transferred into a plan in which they accrue benefits at the same
pace as co-workers two decades younger. Worse, some conversions to
cash-balance plans include a transition, or ``wear-away,'' period
under which older employees effectively stop accruing pension
benefits for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Such plans were rare a decade ago but have boomed recently, as
consultants have touted the conversions as a way to save big money.
According to Watson Wyatt Worldwide, a human resources consulting
firm in Bethesda, Md., at least 16 of the nation's 100 largest
companies now have such plans. And a recent survey by Plan Sponsor,
a trade publication, of 109 companies with employee pension assets
of at least $50 million found that 37 percent had switched to
cash-balance plans, or are considering doing so.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But it is IBM's conversion that has set off the harshest and
most publicized reaction from its employees. Since the company,
based in Armonk, N.Y., disclosed the change this spring, the
backlash has turned into a social movement of sorts, with fuming
employees conspiring via e-mail to protest and pressure their
company to rescind the conversion.
</P>
<P>
   When the chief executive, Louis Gerstner Jr., visited the
company's Austin, Texas, plant last month, a plane circled above
dragging a banner that read, ``Hey Lou, Thou Shalt Not Steal,''
according to The Austin American-Statesman. Employees at plants
around the country have called meetings to discuss efforts to
unionize. And in Vermont this week, Rep. Bernard Sanders, I-Vt.,
organized the meeting in Winooski.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said that many hurt by the switch ``came to IBM and
stayed at IBM precisely because of the pension program that the
company offered.'' He continued: ``These are employees who,
throughout their careers, rejected job offers from other companies
because of their loyalty to IBM. And these are the same employees
who woke up one day, not so long ago, to discover that all of the
promises that IBM made to them were not worth the paper that they
had been written on.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders elicited hoots and boos at the expense of Gerstner. He
noted that Gerstner had total compensation last year of nearly $14
million and is sitting on stock options worth nearly $500 million.
``I'm sorry to say that he rejected my request to be here
tonight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weatherbee, the IBM spokeswoman, giving specifics of the
company's side, said many older employees would receive additional
annual contributions to their cash balance accounts of up to 4
percent of their pay. And for employees who choose to convert their
account to an annuity when they retire, the company will increase
the annuity's value by up to 30 percent or so, depending on age and
tenure. She added that the company had plowed money saved by the
conversion into higher salaries and other compensation, and that a
number of IBM's competitors did not even have pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weatherbee said she could not explain why the protests have
been so severe at IBM, but she said she believed part of the reason
was that the company maintained a strong benefits package even as
it suffered huge losses in the early 1990s. ``What we're hearing
is, `Why now? Why are you doing this now when things are good?'''
she said. The reason, she added, is that ``we learned a lesson''
from the company's prior tough times, and IBM officials want to
become more competitive now, while the company is enjoying good
times.
</P>
<P>
   Though the backlash has been especially harsh at IBM, these
conversions have angered workers at many other companies, and
lawmakers have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Both consumer advocates and industry lobbyists say they expect
federal legislation to pass that would require companies to make
better disclosure of how much employees stand to lose from a
cash-balance conversion.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals favored by business groups would require that
employees be given sufficient information to understand how a
conversion affects them. Other plans would require fuller
disclosure, including a proposal backed by the Clinton
administration requiring employers to provide specific examples of
how the change would affect different groups of workers, as well as
whether a conversion includes a ``wear-away'' period during which
older workers stop accruing benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have also sought federal investigations to
determine whether the plans comply with age-discrimination, labor
and tax laws. The plans are ``a focus of a lot of attention'' at
the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, said Reginald Welch,
the agency's communications director. While it is too early to say
whether the agency feels the conversions may violate
age-discrimination laws, the chairwoman, Ida Castro, is ``extremely
interested'' in the issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits are also pending that contend that some conversions
violate age-discrimination statutes and federal laws against
reducing pension benefits already accrued.
</P>
<P>
   In the Onan Corp. case, the IRS position came in a lawsuit in
U.S. Tax Court brought by two Onan employees, who complained that
the Onan pension plan was changed to reduce future benefits in a
way that violated federal law. The plan provides employees with the
highest level of benefits from three different formulas, including
a cash-balance plan.
</P>
<P>
   An IRS spokesman, Don Roberts, declined to comment Thursday,
citing laws prohibiting disclosure of taxpayer matters. Marya Rose,
a Cummins spokeswoman, said she had not heard of the IRS filing and
could not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Much more could ultimately be at stake in this fight, say
advocates for employees. If cash-balance conversions are allowed to
continue, they say, corporate lobbyists will be emboldened to push
for greater pension changes that are detrimental to workers. One
possibility might be eliminating the 50 percent excise tax that
companies must pay if they take money from an overfunded pension.
</P>
<P>
   Pension raids were commonplace in the 1980s, as raiders would
acquire a company and siphon off the pension surplus, or use it to
pay off debt from the takeover. Congress effectively ended this
practice a decade ago by imposing the 50 percent tax on such
withdrawals. But with many large companies enjoying huge pension
surpluses _ a byproduct of the soaring stock and bond markets _
``they will try once again to get at that surplus,'' predicted
Karen Ferguson, director of the Pension Rights Center in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most recent in a series of practices by large
employers to really cut back on benefits that workers and retirees
have reasonably been led to expect,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
