<SLUG> BC-FEMALE-MUTILATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN FEARING MUTILATION SAVORS FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By WINNIE HU    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Adelaide Abankwah fled the threat of genital
cutting in her native Ghana, she thought she would find a better
life in the United States. But instead, that life _ as for many
other illegal immigrants _ unfolded in a detention center.
</P>
<P>
   For the next two years and three months, Ms. Abankwah was caught
between a world she didn't want and one that didn't seem to want
her. After arriving at Kennedy International Airport in March 1997
with false identification papers, she was arrested and taken to the
Wackenhut Detention Center in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I thought I would die in there,'' she said Thursday
in her first public appearance since being released from the center
last month. ``Nobody ever got in there, and sometimes I can't eat
and can't sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abankwah, 29, flanked by Gloria Steinem and other
supporters, spoke haltingly at a news conference at Marie Claire
magazine on West Broadway. Since her plight was detailed in the
magazine's May 1998 issue, it has attracted the attention of scores
of women's rights organizations, politicians and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Ms. Abankwah received final word that her ordeal
had ended. The Board of Immigration Appeals granted her petition
for political asylum on the grounds that she feared being subjected
to genital cutting if she returned to Ghana. She is one of only a
few women to be granted asylum in the United States for that
reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so happy to be free,'' she said Thursday. ``I don't have
to worry about being deported or dying in jail. Today, I am
surrounded by my friends and supporters, who have all helped me
attain my freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked by a reporter to describe the genital cutting process
that she might have faced in her homeland, Ms. Abankwah paused and
her eyes filled with tears. Her lawyer, Dennis LaRochelle,
intervened to say she would not answer.
</P>
<P>
   Russell A. Bergeron, a spokesman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Washington, said that Ms. Abankwah's
lengthy detention was unusual. He said the average waiting time in
a detention center is 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Abankwah, whose initial request for asylum was denied by
an immigration court, pursued her appeal through higher courts, all
the way to the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   While many INS detainees are released while awaiting immigration
decisions, Bergeron said Ms. Abankwah was considered a flight risk
because her request for asylum had been denied.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abankwah's release followed months of telephone and letter
campaigns to Attorney General Janet Reno, Congress and the White
House by her supporters, including Ms. Steinem and the actresses
Julia Roberts and Vanessa Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Abankwah, the long, hard fight to stay in the United
States has brought her many new friends and opportunities where she
once had none. She plans to take classes for a high school
equivalency degree at Marymount Manhattan College and to work part
time. She said she would also be a volunteer for Equality Now, a
group that is campaigning against genital cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving the detention center, Ms. Abankwah has lived in
the Bronx with Victoria Otumfuor-Neequaye, a Pentecostal minister
who left Ghana 22 years ago. The two met after Ms. Abankwah called
her in desperation from the detention center.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw her, we cried together because she was in
that deplorable situation,'' said Ms. Otumfuor-Neequaye, who
accompanied Ms. Abankwah on Thursday. ``God has seen us through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
