<SLUG> BC-NESTLE-HAAGEN-DAZS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NESTLE AND HAAGEN-DAZS TO OPERATE JOINT ICE CREAM VENTURE IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DANA CANEDY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two leading producers of ice cream, Nestle SA and Haagen-Dazs,
are joining forces to better compete in the large but fragmented
U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   Nestle USA, the American subsidiary of the Swiss foods giant,
and the Pillsbury Co., the unit of Diageo PLC of Britain that
controls Haagen-Dazs, said Thursday that their joint venture would
benefit from shared technology and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement unites Nestle's novelty ice cream products with
Haagen-Dazs' premium desserts. The companies hope to keep pace with
the market leader, Unilever NV, the maker of Breyers ice cream and
Klondike bars.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that short of an outright acquisition by one of
the partners, the agreement was a good strategic fit. ``Both
companies have been trying to grow on their own but not very
easily,'' said Naomi Ghez of Goldman, Sachs. Combining forces
``opens new growth opportunities for both companies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The joint venture, which the companies are calling Ice Cream
Partners USA, will unite Haagen-Dazs' powerful brand name with
Nestle's technology skills and broad distribution channel. It will
also expand the Haagen-Dazs line by adding Nestle's chocolate and
other confectioneries to new, premium products.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of cannibalizing either brand is small, however,
because the companies' products appeal to different consumers in
the $11 billion market, analysts said. Haagen-Dazs' premium-priced
pints of ice cream are popular with adults, while many Nestle
products, such as Itzakadoozie flavored ice pops, are primarily
eaten by children.
</P>
<P>
   The two brands will remain separate, but the combined entity
will be overseen by a nine-member board.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement brings together two complementary businesses
with strengths in two distinct segments, super-premium packaged ice
cream and novelties,'' said Joe Weller, chairman and chief
executive of Nestle USA.
</P>
<P>
   Paul S. Walsh, chairman and chief executive of the Pillsbury
Co., said the partnership would ``enable Haagen-Dazs to continue to
accelerate incremental growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Nestle and Haagen-Dazs each have U.S. revenue around $300
million and control about 5 percent of the domestic market. With a
combined market share of nearly 10 percent, the new partners will
still trail Unilever, which has 16 to 20 percent of the market. The
two companies are counting on their venture to advance product
innovation and further close the gap.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will be based in Northern California at an
undetermined location to take advantage of two manufacturing plants
in Tulare and Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
