<HEADLINE>
GRAZIANO SAYS DODGERS CAN EAT ALL THEY WANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ If the Los Angeles Dodgers need to eat a few
million dollars to trade Eric Young, they can do it.
</P>
<P>
   If they have to do the same for Devon White or Raul Mondesi or
whomever else, they can do so.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes time to make offseason changes, Dodgers president
and CEO Bob Graziano said neither he nor general manager Kevin
Malone will have to get permission from the Fox Group, the Dodgers'
parent company.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Graziano said the Dodgers, if they so choose, will have
no problem eating contracts _ as long as they remain within the
team budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't eat payroll and then blow our payroll budget,''
Graziano said. ``It's not like we have to eat personnel to eat
payroll in a trade. We don't have to go out and get approval on a
particular trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The ability to absorb contracts might be the biggest key to the
Dodgers climbing out of their current underachieving place in the
NL West and building, or rebuilding, a competitive, playoff team
for next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' familiar targets of trade talk are all overpriced,
and the length of their deals makes it nearly impossible to
maneuver. Eating contracts might be the only way the Dodgers can
create roster flexibility, both financially and on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Young, the 32-year-old second baseman, is without question the
top trade priority for the Dodgers. He is guaranteed $9 million
over the next two seasons. White, the 36-year-old center fielder,
has also been mentioned as a possible trade target, but he's in the
first year of a three-year, $12 million contract. Many baseball
personnel believe the Dodgers will have to absorb a few million
dollars if they are to trade either White or Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we're going to have to discuss when the
season is over,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also Mondesi, the estranged right fielder who a week ago
ripped into Dodgers management and manager Davey Johnson and
demanded a trade. Mondesi is guaranteed $20.5 million over the next
two seasons, and if the Dodgers try to trade him, again, they might
have to take on some of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remain within our budget,'' Graziano said. ``When
we signed Kevin Brown (to a seven-year, $105 million contract), we
knew that signing was going to put us over budget on player payroll
and it was a commitment and a significant contract to the club. I
wouldn't do that type of contract without getting approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as what we spend on payroll, it's really Kevin's job to
define where he wants to spend the dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers absorbed nearly $4 million of reliever Mel Rojas'
contract during an early-season trade with the Tigers that also
included Dave Mlicki. When Malone did that, all he needed was the
go-ahead from Graziano. The Fox Group was told about it, but not
until after the deal happened.
</P>
<P>
   That deal was done because the Fox Group wanted the Dodgers to
decrease payroll from $84 million to its current spot at $80
million, which puts it third behind the Yankees and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers moved Bobby Bonilla to the Mets for Rojas last
offseason, they took on $1 million of Bonilla's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Fox Group personnel said they expect to lose money
on the Dodgers this season, team officials said they believe the
payroll will be near $80 million next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be a substantial decrease, if we decrease it,''
Graziano said. ``We're looking at how to better spend our payroll
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last winter, when Brown, Randy Johnson and Mo Vaughn were
available, this year's free-agent group is not star-studded. With
that in mind, Malone said the Dodgers have to be savvy this winter
so they can improve and create more flexibility for next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
