<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-AFTERHOURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO EXCHANGE SETS AN AFTER-HOUR PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Chicago Stock Exchange, the nation's third-largest
stock market, said Thursday that its board had approved a plan to
offer after-hours trading to both institutional and individual
investors starting in October _ the first exchange to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The move creates yet another forum for investors eager to trade
after the 4 p.m. close at the major stock exchanges and holds out
the eventual prospect of around-the-clock trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that investing has become a national pastime, it has
become clear that after-hours trading is here for good,'' said
Richard K. Strauss, an analyst at Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. ``So
everyone's scrambling to be a first mover.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, ETrade Group, the big online broker, said it was
joining Instinet, the Reuters Group unit that is one of the largest
electronic trading networks, to offer after-hours trading to
smaller investors between 4 p.m. and 6:30 p.m. And earlier this
month, the Datek Online Holdings Corporation began offering its
online investors after-hours trading via a unit called Island ECN _
for electronic communications network _ between 4 p.m. and 5:15
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say a movement is clearly afoot to create a global
24-hour stock-trading network using the Internet and the kind of
low-cost electronic trading networks that are shaking up Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the leading markets have been moving cautiously. The
New York Stock Exchange, the world's largest stock market, and the
Nasdaq market, home to many popular technology issues, are also
considering offering after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   While they study the move, which is also being monitored by
regulators, new rivals say they will fill the vacuum to offer
trading in Big Board and Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this is a subject that has legs, and it's our
responsibility to be responsive to our customers,'' said Robert H.
Forney, the chief executive of the Chicago Stock Exchange. ``We
think this will promote competition and give investors the benefit
of that competition.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the New York Stock Exchange reiterated Thursday
that the Big Board is studying the issue of after-hours trading
under the supervision of the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Securities Dealers, which operates
Nasdaq, has considered closing the market at its regular time, 4
p.m., then reopening at 5 p.m. for an evening session. That plan
may have to be rethought if competing electronic networks trade
during that hour. A Nasdaq spokesman declined comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to its plan, the Chicago Stock Exchange _ which
operates a highly automated auction-style forum _ will offer its
more than 150 member brokerage firms after-hours trading in some of
the nation's best-known Big Board and Nasdaq stocks between 4 p.m.
and 6:30 p.m. Eastern standard time.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Chicago exchange said that their electronic
trading system would let almost any brokerage firm or online broker
tap into its after-hours market to trade, by limit order only, in
the stocks that make up the Standard &AMP; Poor's 100-stock index, the
Nasdaq 100-stock index and other very active stocks, including such
big names as McDonald's, AT&AMP;T, Microsoft and Intel. A limit order
is at a specific price, instead of an open order to buy or sell at
the current market price.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago exchange now offers a half-hour of trading after the
closing bell but mainly for institutional investors. The new system
will greatly expand the hours and try to tap the lucrative retail
market that fast-growing online brokerage firms are poised to
dominate.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago exchange is going head-to-head with Island and
Instinet as well as trying to get a jump on other exchanges, which
face the same competition. Lisa Cervenka, a spokeswoman for the
Chicago exchange _ which trades about 50 million shares a day _
said it had a low-cost electronic trading system that executes
trades automatically. The system, she added, is expected to be
accessible over the Internet to hundreds of brokerage firms by
October.
</P>
<P>
   What all the after-hours trading systems seek is liquidity _
enough order flow to make profits and create active and efficient
marketplaces.
</P>
<P>
   Island, for example, depends on Datek clients and other brokers
with access to the Island system for trading in Nasdaq stocks.
Instinet will bring together more than a million ETrade customers
with institutional orders for mostly Nasdaq issues and some Big
Board ones. And Chicago officials say they will have a mix of Big
Board and Nasdaq orders at prices competitive with the electronic
communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
