<HEADER>
A3671 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-SHOOTING-FURROW-LADN     08-19 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-FURROW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS WILL TRY FURROW IN FEDERAL COURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Federal and state authorities have agreed to
prosecute Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr. in U.S. District Court in the
murder of mail carrier Joseph Ileto an hour after, according to
allegations, he wounded five people at the North Valley Jewish
Community Center.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to pursue federal charges first was based on the
belief that they are more likely to bring a quick sentence and have
a chance of invoking the death penalty. Prosecuting Furrow in state
court on charges of shooting three small boys and two staff members
at the day camp facility in the Los Angeles suburb of Granada Hills
would take place later.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Gil Garcetti and U.S. Attorney Alejandro
Mayorkas made the decision jointly but refused to discuss it,
saying that would reveal trial strategy.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury indicted the 37-year-old white supremacist
in the killing of Ileto, a Filipino immigrant delivering mail, and
for using a 9mm handgun in a violent crime that resulted in death.
The indictment also charges Furrow as a felon in possession of a
firearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a decision in conjunction with the District Attorney's
Office to proceed first in federal court. Everybody brings
something to the table,'' said Thomas Mrozek, the U.S. Attorney's
spokesman. ``You can rest assured we took into account the
efficiency and expediency in achieving justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Attorney's Office might seek other charges against
Furrow for wounding three boys, a teen-age counselor and a
receptionist at the Jewish community center last week, setting off
a rampage that included a carjacking nearby, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The move to seek a murder conviction in federal court first
would prevent the Los Angeles County District Attorney's Office
from prosecuting Furrow for the same offense, given a state
constitutional protection against facing trial twice for the same
crime.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors still plan to seek convictions on five
attempted murder charges, carjacking and weapons and other related
charges, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If convicted on those charges alone, he could receive several
life terms,'' said Sandi Gibbons, the District Attorney's
spokeswoman. ``Both sets of prosecutors are interested in _ if not
getting the death penalty _ ensuring he stays in prison for the
rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said the move is not surprising and Garcetti took
what he could get.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Attorney has all the cards, since they have him in
(federal) custody and they will probably get to trial faster,''
said David Conn, former head of the District Attorney's Major
Crimes Unit.
</P>
<P>
   A federal trial could proceed faster, given procedural rules and
judges known for conducting more speedy trials compared with state
courts, legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   By joining forces, the prosecutors combine expertise. Legal
analysts say state prosecutors are far more experienced in death
penalty cases while federal prosecutors have more experience with
weapons violations and civil rights violations, and the FBI lab
provides vast resources for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think another factor is the public perception that the
federal government should get involved in stopping these sorts of
hate crimes,'' said Laurie Levenson, a Loyola Law School professor
and former federal prosecutor. ``From the president to the attorney
general and down through the ranks, I think the federal government
has decided it wanted to make its mark.''
</P>
<P>
   Furrow surrendered to the FBI in Las Vegas the morning after the
Aug. 10 rampage and subsequently confessed in an FBI interview to
carrying out the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Furrow is scheduled to appear in U.S. District Court on Aug. 30
for an arraignment. He is expected to enter a plea and a trial date
should be set.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires the trial to begin no later than 70 days
after the indictment, but the defense could waive that speedy trial
standard to gain more time to prepare its case, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Pretrial hearings are likely on such issues as change of venue,
use of Furrow's confession and whether the death penalty will be
sought.
</P>
<P>
   If the trial is held in Los Angeles, the jury would be drawn
from the nation's largest federal court district, spanning seven
counties with 17million residents.
</P>
<P>
   The confession will be a prime defense target. If it holds, the
prosecution should have a strong case, legal experts say.
</P>
<P>
   If a mental defense is sought, hearings could significantly
delay the trial. Legal experts said that is a critical issue in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his lawyers will pitch that he is not as culpable as
someone who does not have these mental problems and committed these
same crimes,'' Levenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state prosecutors are accustomed to working together
in U.S. District Court, notably on drug cases. Deputy district
attorneys are designated as Special Assistant U.S. Attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on seeking the death penalty, however, will be made
following a lengthy review process by the U.S. Attorney's Office
and the U.S. Attorney General's Office in Washington, D.C. That
decision must be made within a reasonable period before trial. &UR;  &QL; 
!dlim!!end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
