u f BC-LATINO-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-19 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISA'S LATIN-TINGED MAINSTREAM SPOT MAY ANTICIPATE A TREND 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Major American corporations regularly broadcast
Spanish-language advertising to reach the nation's fast-growing
Hispanic population.
</P>
<P>
   But now a big advertiser, Visa USA, is going mainstream with a
Latin-culture commercial, specifically intending to reach people in
the 18-to-34-year-old range. And the agency that created it, BBDO
New York, a unit of Omnicom Group , is confident the commercial is
on the cusp of a trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Latin culture used to be for Latins, but not
anymore,'' said Jimmy Siegel, BBDO New York senior creative
director. ``Latin culture has become hip, and it's sort of on the
edge of becoming more popular in the mainstream. I would expect
more commercials with some sort of Latin influence.''
</P>
<P>
   The spot, which is part of Visa's 14-year-old ``It's everywhere
you want to be'' campaign, opens showing a young Hispanic woman in
jeans and halter-top swaying to a Latin beat. It then quickly cuts
to others dancing to salsa music as a narrator says that you can
get lessons at Salsa Lovers Dance Studio in Miami, but _ as always
in the ``everywhere'' campaign _ bring your Visa card because they
don't take American Express.
</P>
<P>
   The Visa team at BBDO was researching trends in popular culture
for a spot aimed at the so-called Generation X and Generation Y
markets when it decided to zone in on Latin culture, Siegel said.
The team members noticed the crossover appeal of Latin music and
dance, especially in cities like New York where several Latin clubs
draw big multicultural crowds. They also recognized the broad
success of Latin celebrities like Ricky Martin and Jennifer Lopez,
and decided that _ like hip-hop culture before it _ Latin culture
is on the edge of mainstream popularity.
</P>
<P>
   When an advertiser the size of Visa USA taps into a trend, it
usually does signal that lots of interest and acceptance exist
among the audience it is aiming at, said Jack Trout, a marketing
consultant in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agencies are usually good at capturing a hot trend that is
slowly moving into the mainstream,'' Trout said, ``This is probably
an early effort, and Visa smells a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   While there has been some recent use of Latin music in
mainstream commercials, they have not had an overall Latin feel.
Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. ran a fashion spot earlier this year
advertising its spring skirt collection set to Latin-type music.
And a new ad for Loanworks.com, an online mortgage lending company,
is set to Cuban music.
</P>
<P>
   The Loanworks.com spot _ showing a little boy in snow clothes
who is trying to get to the bathroom _ is aimed at young people,
who are more likely to apply for a mortgage on line, according to
Virginia Morse, group account director at DGWB, an agency based in
Irvine, Calif., that produced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a dot-com company that is cutting-edge, and we thought
the music was upbeat, fun and also cutting-edge,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Davis, a music producer at Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi Advertising in
New York, said that Cuban music was popular, citing the strong
crossover sales for ``Buena Vista Social Club,'' a Cuban music CD
with singers from the Fifties and Sixties.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Davis said, rock'n'roll, and most recently electronic
music, seem to dominate music in commercials, which have little
Latin music.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of recognition in mainstream advertising is a
welcome development to Latinos, many of whom have complained that
the general American media virtually ignore Hispanic culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Hispanic portion of the population is roughly 13 percent and
they have about $400 billion in spending power, but those facts are
not reflected in the general media, said Marta Garcia, a founder of
the Hispanic Media Coalition. She said that the coalition is asking
Latin viewers to avoid programs on the four big networks on Sept.
12 to express outrage at the lack of Hispanic actors in their fall
television lineup.
</P>
<P>
   While advertising is not part of the so-called brown-out, Ms.
Garcia said, so far mainstream advertising has not really picked up
on the popularity of Latin culture, nor are Hispanic characters
often seen in nonethnic advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some progress, but not enough vis-a-vis our
population growth,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Spanish-language advertising is booming,
especially in New York where it supports many actors, agencies and
production houses, said Manny Alfaro, executive director of the
Hispanic Organization of Latin Actors in New York. Still, he said,
Latin actors are paid less for those spots because the ads reach a
smaller audience than mainstream ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Progress is when we become part of the fabric of American life
as seen on TV,'' Alfaro said.
</P>
<P>
   BBDO researched several trends among young people, and Liz
Silver, Visa's vice president of advertising, liked the salsa
dancing spot immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agency always has its antenna out for the latest trend and
what's going on in pop culture,'' she said.``And, of course, then
there were all the possibilities for this idea, in terms of the
visuals, the music and the wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger generation is an important audience for Visa, she
said. ``Generally these are people just starting a serious
financial relationship, and you tend to be loyal to who you start
out with,'' Ms. Silver said. ``Also, these are good, responsible
users who understand and grew up with plastic, and who are at a
point in their lives where they want to buy a lot of things, and
that will only continue as they get married, furnish a house,
etc.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on consumer reaction, Ms. Silver said, the spot is a
success. And it may end up serving a dual purpose. Some banks that
serve large Hispanic populations are looking to leverage the salsa
spot with Visa promotions of their own or local media plans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
