u s BC-PACKERS-FREEMAN-NYT &LR;      08-19 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACKERS-FREEMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREEMAN IS FOCUSED ON BEING THE GREATEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antonio Freeman joined the Green Bay Packers in 1995 as a
third-round draft pick, as a ``project,'' as a kick returner rather
than as a receiver. He was full of impatience and exhibited a
spirited edge that appeared ruffian-like. His contract was for
three years and included a $370,000 signing bonus as part of an
$850,000 deal.
</P>
<P>
   Four seasons later, Antonio Freeman is an All-Pro receiver who
along with Minnesota's Cris Carter has caught more touchdown passes
(36) in the last four years than any other National Football League
receiver. Freeman holds or shares 13 Packers playoff records, owns
a Super Bowl ring, caught the longest touchdown pass (81 yards) in
Super Bowl history and has turned that testy side of him into
unmistakable production, patience, maturity and leadership. This
week, he signed a new contract: seven years and a $10 million
signing bonus as part of a $42 million deal. He is now pro
football's highest-paid receiver.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Freeman is from Baltimore, from Virginia Tech, and he is
only 27. That old football line about planning your work and
working your plan has been around longer than Freeman, but he might
as well have created it. That is because of his focus toward
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very happy and I'm very blessed,'' Freeman said.
``Everything that has happened to me goes back to my determination
to be one of the best receivers ever in the game. My final goal is
the Hall of Fame. I'm not going to stop until I get there. When I
walk off the field, I want to be known as one of the greatest
players to ever play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to be regarded as the greatest receiver ever. The
greatest player ever.
</P>
<P>
   It is a mighty quest. He did not quite say it, but everything
about him shouts that his ultimate goal is that kind of supreme
greatness.
</P>
<P>
   A traipse through the history of pro football's marquee
receivers includes Don Hutson and Lance Alworth and Lionel Taylor
and Steve Largent. The 49ers' Jerry Rice tops them all in stature
and in achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks (Joe Montana?), running backs (Jim Brown?) and
linebackers (Dick Butkus?) are traditionally the positions to begin
with when attempting to name the greatest player. Can Freeman
change that?
</P>
<P>
   Similar to Rice, if there is a way to start, he has found it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came to Green Bay, I was behind five receivers,
including Robert Brooks and Mark Ingram, and Keith Jackson was here
at tight end, too,'' Freeman said. ``My vibe was the franchise
thought of me as a project. I returned kicks my first year and that
allowed me to watch those guys and learn patience, route running
and how to watch film and understand and learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman took his 6-foot-1-inch, 198-pound body and threw it into
the wild world of punt and kickoff returns. In 1995, he returned 37
punts and was the best kickoff returner on the team, returning 24
an average of 23.2 yards. As a returner, he displayed the
attributes that would make him a showcase receiver: soft hands,
fearlessness, tricky speed and the ability to whisk through
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   In his second pro season, he returned no punts and only one
kickoff. The Green Bay coaches saw his intensity and impact in
games and said, hey, this kid can start at receiver for us. And so
in 1996, he did.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the numbers. Eight catches in his rookie season. Then
56. Then 81. Last year, 84. The receiving yardage went from 106 to
933 to 1,243 to 1,424. Touchdowns, too _ from one to nine to 12 to
14.
</P>
<P>
   This is very hard to do in pro football. This is when a coach
knows he has a special player, when his production always moves
forward.
</P>
<P>
   But Freeman's move to starter in '96 was not without setback. He
fractured his left forearm a month into the season and missed all
of November. But he came back in December with his breakout, career
month and with his signature game.
</P>
<P>
   That month, he caught 25 passes for 452 yards and four
touchdowns and was named the National Football Conference offensive
player of the month. On Dec. 1 that year at Chicago, he caught a
Hail Mary pass for a touchdown and then grabbed another in the end
zone, twisting and turning his body in a spectacular, diving catch.
For the game: 10 receptions, 156 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was coming off my first 100-yard game, and that game made it
back-to-back 100-yard games for the first time in my career,''
Freeman said. ``That game was my coming-out party.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued building a relationship with Brett Favre, the Green
Bay quarterback, the kind of communication between receiver and
quarterback that is required for greatness. Entering last season,
Freeman's contract had expired. Green Bay offered $17 million over
five years. Freeman balked and took a one-year deal for $1.153
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that new TV money would be coming into effect this
season and if I had signed that contract last year that I would be
in the middle of the pack of receivers,'' Freeman said. ``I saw a
bigger picture. My family and friends wondered what I was doing and
it is true that I had never been offered or seen that kind of money
in my life. But I saw a lot bigger picture.''
</P>
<P>
   A $42 million dollar picture.
</P>
<P>
   NFL contracts will continue to escalate as the game grows and
revenues grow. New receiver deals will be made that will pass
Freeman's.
</P>
<P>
   But can he stay a step ahead of other receivers on the field?
Can he continue to match his big-game, big-play production? Will he
continue to draw prime-time attention? Can he become the greatest
receiver of all time? Sure he can.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest player ever? Unlikely. But never say never with
Antonio Freeman. Look how far he has already come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I wasn't signed and though I didn't practice, I
came to our minicamps in the off season, anyway,'' Freeman said.
``Because the team named me franchise player in the off season,
that kept me from shopping myself as a free agent and hitting that
circuit. I might have gotten an even more lucrative deal, but this
is where I wanted to be. We've still got No.4, Brett Favre, and
he's gotten us to two Super Bowls. We've got a power running game
and a passing attack. We've got Desmond Howard back returning
kicks. Our defense is solid. Every team has weaknesses, but the key
is relying on your strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Lord blesses me with health, I have no limits. Winning
championships puts you at center stage. I'm pushing, real hard.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
