<SLUG> BC-YALE-CLUB-CASUAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE CLUB GOES CASUAL ON FRIDAYS, BUT THE HARVARD CLUB HOLDS THE
LINE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass., Pa., N.H.)   By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the Yale Club in Manhattan, in the once-exclusive
domain of the jacket and necktie, there are now short-sleeve
tattersalls. There are tieless button-downs. There are yellow polo
shirts. There are Top-Siders, not to mention Nike Airs. Khakis have
been observed in the exclusive Roof Dining Room. There are jeans
and last Friday, egad, there was a purple Izod.
</P>
<P>
   As if that were not enough, one woman actually won admission to
the once-sacrosanct Tap Room in jeans, sandals and a white T-shirt.
``I suppose T-shirts are OK now, as long as they aren't wet,'' said
David Weild III, Yale '52, dressed in a dark blue suit and
observing this spectacle with some amusement.
</P>
<P>
   In case all these pret-a-porter ensembles have not given it
away: the Yale Club has gone casual on Fridays, the first of
Manhattan's exclusive Ivy League bastions to do so. No jacket. No
tie. Its 21-member board unveiled the new dress code last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to engage the interest of more and more younger
members, professional people who are not just lawyers and
accountants but also architects and people who work on the Web,''
said William D. Weber, Yale '60, a business consultant in
Ridgefield, Conn., who is the club's president. ``We lose business
when such people feel inhibited about coming to our club.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber declined to disclose the revenues of the privately held
club, which has occupied the neoclassical limestone and brick
building at 50 Vanderbilt Avenue since 1915.
</P>
<P>
   But do not imagine for one second that such goings-on have been
unnoticed over at the Harvard Club on West 44th Street, where
jacket-and-tie formality is still de rigueur in the main dining
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even in the late 1990s there should be a few havens for proper
attire and decorum,'' said John D. Sicher, a member of the Harvard
Club for 32 years. ``I wouldn't expect the rowdies from New Haven
to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midtown Ivy enclave to the west of Grand Central Station,
where the clubs huddle in splendid mutuality, the other Ivy League
clubs are making their last stand for manners. Still holding the
line along with Harvard is the Princeton Club on West 43rd Street,
which requires jacket and tie in its Woodrow Wilson dining room.
United in solidarity are alumni of Columbia University, who are
compelled to be united, sharing the Princeton Club as they do.
</P>
<P>
   Also fighting the casual tide are the stalwarts of the
University of Pennsylvania Club on West 44th Street (the library is
off-limits to the tieless and jacketless) and the University Club
on East 54th Street, where formality is required at all times,
according to the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Wavering at the balance of modernity is the 6,850-member Cornell
Club-New York on East 44th Street. A jacket _ but not a tie _ is
required on Fridays in the dining room on the second floor.
Acquiescing to this equivocation are some 70 members of the Brown
University Club, who share the Cornell clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   But dragged right into the whole dress-down-Friday boola-boola
has been the Dartmouth Club of New York, which has shared the Yale
clubhouse since 1974. ``We take the lead from them,'' said Barry
Weeks, the Dartmouth Club's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   The casual-Friday rule at the Yale Club is in effect only from
Memorial Day to Labor Day. ``T-shirts, cutoffs, torn jeans, shorts
and provocative or revealing clothing are not permitted,'' Weber
has informed the membership. Obviously, those rules apply to women
as well.
</P>
<P>
   (As for the woman in the white T-shirt, members speculated that
she had come from the 140-bedroom members' residences upstairs,
where no dress code is enforced and where members pay $105 to $215
a night.)
</P>
<P>
   Weber contended that the club is ``solvent,'' adding that a
booming economy meant that ``these are happy times at the Yale
Club'' for its 9,500 members. They pay a yearly maximum dues of
$1,124 plus tax; members for less than eight years (and those who
are suburbanites or out-of-towners) pay less.
</P>
<P>
   Do members feel, taking their cue from the legendary New Haven
song lyrics, that the gentlemen songsters are off on a spree? Will
they be damned from here to eternity?
</P>
<P>
   Most of the reaction ``has been positive,'' Weber said, ``and
there have been no resignations over this as far as I know.''
</P>
<P>
   But some diehard Bulldogs feel strongly that ``the club made an
error,'' said A. Peter Barbaresi, class of '45, a 77-year-old
lawyer in Rye, N.Y. ``There are certain manners that should prevail
in a club. I am sorry to see good taste go out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Dress-down Friday ``doesn't shock me,'' Barbaresi added, ``but
it disappoints me. Americans in general are not at their best when
they are casually dressed. So much is failing us. Even our language
is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the Old Blue cynosures for whom the club's dress
code is not an issue. William F. Buckley Jr., class of '50, author
of the 1951 polemic ``God and Man at Yale,'' said he ``never uses
the Yale Club in New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
