<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TIMES ARE TOUGH, YOSHII PROVES TOUGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Time after time, Masato Yoshii has pitched his best
with his job in jeopardy. And not just this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really precisely put my finger on it,'' Yoshii said
Wednesday night through his interpreter, Kota Ishijima. ``But in
the past, there have been numerous times that I've been on the edge
_ of being released, of going to the bullpen, of being sent to the
minor leagues. And when something like that happens, I always come
back strong. Consciously or unconsciously, I don't know why that
is. But it has been a pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pavlovian pattern, if you will, of direct response to a
stimulus, and it continued Wednesday night in Yoshii's start
against the San Diego Padres. At the beginning of this month,
Yoshii was banished to the bullpen after a series of poor outings.
But since he was restored to the Mets' rotation on Aug. 13 in place
of the injured Rick Reed, Yoshii has pitched two of his best games
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday's outing may have been his best in his two years
with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by home runs from Robin Ventura and Mike Piazza, who each
drove in three runs, Yoshii allowed one run and six hits while
pitching a complete game in a 9-1 victory over the Padres. It was
only the Mets' second complete game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing a first-inning run, Yoshii (8-8) retired 16
batters in a row at one point to enable the Mets to head home in
first place in the National League East. The Atlanta Braves beat
the Colorado Rockies, 9-7, Thursday to cut the Mets' lead to a
half-game.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, who would have thought that Yoshii would be
playing an integral part in the Mets' post-season run? Nobody but
Manager Bobby Valentine, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one thing that people have heard me say so many times
that they discount it, and it is that Yoshii is a true
professional,'' Valentine said Wednesday night of the 34-year-old
right-hander. ``There is no doubt in my mind that he understands
competition as well as anyone in that clubhouse. He understands his
job and what he has to do. He had a good forkball his last time out
and a super forkball tonight. We talked about how he needed it, and
he found it. That said, we'll see what happens. But there's no
doubt he's made a major contribution to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii could find himself back in the bullpen after Reed or
Bobby Jones comes off the disabled list, but there is little doubt
that he will start again next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I have nobody else to pitch that game,'' Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   If Yoshii has been anything this season, it has been
inconsistent. But, Valentine said, that has been the problem with
most of the Mets' starters.
</P>
<P>
   What Yoshii has done better than some of the other starting
pitchers is put together a run of four or five strong starts at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   After opening the season 1-3 with a 7.52 earned run average,
Yoshii was on the verge of being demoted to the minors. He
responded by allowing just six runs in 312/3 innings over his next
five starts, a 1.71 ERA, to save his job. Yoshii allowed 13 runs in
just six and two-thirds innings his next two starts before
finishing June on a roll: a 2.30 ERA in 271/3 innings over four
starts.
</P>
<P>
   July was a complete disaster for him, however. Yoshii made five
starts and allowed 25 runs in 22 innings. One week after the Mets
traded for Kenny Rogers, Yoshii allowed seven runs in one and
one-third innings in Chicago. A couple of days later, he learned he
was the odd man out on the starting staff.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii made two relief appearances: one strong, one a mess. But
Reed suffered a strained tendon in his right middle finger, and
Valentine had only Yoshii to turn to.
</P>
<P>
   In his first start back, Yoshii allowed three runs and four hits
in six innings of a 3-2 loss in San Francisco. Over his last two
starts, he has given up three earned runs in 15 innings. Valentine
called the starts as good as the team has had back to back.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, whose ERA for the season is 5.39 (the team's is 4.44),
credits his latest resurgence to his forkball. Hideo Nomo taught
him the pitch three years ago and helped him refine it in Milwaukee
early this month when the Mets played there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past I didn't have any confidence in it, and, of
course, Mike didn't either,'' said Yoshii, referring to Piazza, the
catcher. ``Now, he's calling more forkballs than ever. But I still
don't know why all of a sudden it's doing so well.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everything went well for Yoshii on Wednesday night. He
grounded into a double play in each of his last three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``All throughout my career, when I do something great, I always
do something dorky to mess it up,'' Yoshii said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Every complete game has its price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
