<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABDUL-MALIK CONFIDENT ABOUT MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's defense seems a likely candidate for a shaky
start, with so many players either inexperienced or changing
positions.
</P>
<P>
   But Sultan Abdul-Malik is already taking the offensive to any
potential criticism over his move from defensive end to outside
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Malik was a second-team All-Pacific-10 Conference
performer last season but requested the move to linebacker because
he didn't feel he was big enough to play defensive end in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has seen me play linebacker since high school. But
they'll find out at Hawaii,'' said Abdul-Malik. ``I've got
linebacker skills. I'm truly a linebacker. I was a fast, undersized
defensive end the past two seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense's changing face could also see true freshman Bernard
Riley as a fixture at tackle. Following Thursday's practice, USC
coach Paul Hackett said Riley had an ``excellent chance'' to be in
the three-man rotation with Ennis Davis and Aaron Williams.
</P>
<P>
   During a 35-play controlled scrimmage that worked on various
game scenarios Thursday, Hackett cited freshmen Troy Polamalu (free
safety), Aaron Graham (middle linebacker) and Omar Nazel (outside
linebacker) as players that stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at our (recruiting) class as a whole, I could
not be happier,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Scrimmage notes: During Thursday's scrimmage, the most
noticeable difference probably took place at kicker. Junior David
Bell easily made 40- and 50-yard attempts and appeared well ahead
of sophomore David Newbury, a junior college transfer who missed
his 50-yard attempt and had an extra point blocked by Riley.
</P>
<P>
   __ Soward improves: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward held a meeting
with Hackett on Thursday morning to discuss his perceived slump
during the first five days of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't feel he was performing, but I told him, `Put it
behind you and start over,' '' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   The talk apparently worked. Although Soward suffered a sprained
right ankle in the morning practice, he returned and had his best
outing of training camp in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``His energy level was up. He ran good routes. He caught the
ball today,'' Hackett said. ``That's how he makes his living.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Steele arrives: After much delay, linebacker Markus Steele
was scheduled to arrive Thursday night and be eligible to practice
today. The Long Beach City College graduate has been waiting for
USC to receive his transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   After consulting the NCAA, USC determined Steele does not need
to practice his first three days in shorts and can practice in
pads. However, Hackett said he will probably have Steele spend at
least two days in shorts for conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coming back slowly: Offensive tackle Matt Welch is recovering
from shoulder surgery in the winter. He might return to practice
today but hasn't progressed as fast as the coaching staff
anticipated at the outset of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disappointment is clearly (the recovery of) Matt Welch; he
should have bounced back but hasn't,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tired legs: USC is beginning to wear down physically as
training camp nears the end of week one. Several players complained
about fatigue between practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our legs are tired,'' Hackett said. ``We're tired, but
we fought through it today.''
</P>
<P>
   USC will probably only hold an afternoon practice today, to
allow players with minor aches and pains some extra rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
