<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DANDRIDGE' HAS FEW TRIUMPHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
Two moments grip you in Introducing Dorothy Dandridge, HBO's
worthy-but-flawed chronicle of the first Black woman to receive an
Oscar nomination for Best Actress.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first occurs at a Hollywood party, where manager Earl Mills
has been lured to hear a promising singer. He finds three women
laughing under neath the piano: Ava Gardner, Mari lyn Monroe and
Dandridge. And it's Dandridge he's drawn to.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, a medical examiner pauses over Dandridge's nude
body while searching for clues in her still-mysterious death at 42.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dorothy Dandridge,'' he says to a colleague. ``Wasn't she some
kind of colored singer?''
</P>
<P>
   Those two scenes capture the es sence of Dandridge, at least as
she's presented here. All the talent, fire and beauty in the world
couldn't overcome the obstacles _ both in ternal and external _ she
faced. Gardner and Monroe are legends. Dandridge, the true pioneer,
is merely a footnote.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes movies can correct that kind of shortcoming. This one
won't. Although it's obviously a labor of love for Halle Berry, who
is not only mag nificent in the title role but the execu tive
producer of the movie, it falls short in too many places to change
history's perception of Dandridge.
</P>
<P>
   Given network television's current lily-white atmosphere, you
really want to love this movie. It's always watchable and, at
times, quite mov ing. We're left with an interesting look at one of
Hollywood's most in triguing stars. We're also left wanting more.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is told through an all-night telephone call Dandridge
makes to a friend. She begins by remembering picking up a
dry-cleaned dress at a hotel where she once stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your lady must have already paid,'' the clerk says,
dismissively checking the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Dandridge goes upstairs, puts on the dress and walks down to the
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   `` `My lady' is going out for the evening,'' Dandridge says
icily, toss ing a cover of Life magazine down in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Her picture is on the cover. She's on her way to the Academy
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the few truly satisfying res olutions of such a
situation in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of an actress, Dan dridge performed as part of the
sing ing Dandridge Sisters at the famed Cotton Club in Harlem.
That's where she met her future husband, Harold Nicholas, one of
the tap-dancing Nicholas Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Dandridge gives birth to a mentally retarded daughter, and her
shaky marriage falters. Her mother urges Dandridge to concentrate
on her burgeoning career, which, though promising, is fraught with
problems compounded by racism. She tells Mills, for instance, that
she isn't in terested in being a singer; she's a se rious actress.
</P>
<P>
   The next scene finds her on a movie set, her face darkened by
makeup, tied to a stake while waiting to be rescued by Tarzan.
</P>
<P>
   She takes Mills' advice and hits the supper-club circuit. Again,
racism is painted in broad strokes. With a sin gle song, Dandridge
wins over the racist city fathers in Miami Beach who have held up
completion of a club where she's performing. The easy victory seems
artificial, con trived.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Dandridge's reputation (and Mills' persistence) win
her a reading with Otto Preminger, who is casting an all-Black
version of Car men, called Carmen Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just realized this is the moment I've always dreamed of,''
Dandridge tells Mills (well-played by Brent Spi ner of Star Trek:
The Next Genera tion).
</P>
<P>
   ``A reading with Preminger?'' he asks. Dandridge shakes her head
no.
</P>
<P>
   ``A chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Well. Let's put on a show, kids. Pab lum like that keeps popping
up, and keeps Introducing Dorothy Dan dridge from rising to the
heights it might have reached.
</P>
<P>
   Dandridge wins the role, of course, and begins an affair with
Preminger. She is nominated for an Academy Award but doesn't win, a
result chill ingly predicted by her sister, who screams in a
drunken rage, ``You're not going to win an Oscar, Dottie! They
already gave us one!'' (Hattie McDaniel won a Best Supporting Ac
tress Oscar in 1939 for Gone With the Wind, the first Black actress
to win one.)
</P>
<P>
   The nomination doesn't lead to bet ter roles. Dandridge
continues to fight racism (when she defiantly dips her toe into a
Las Vegas swimming pool, the hotel drains the water and scrubs the
pool). But she spirals downward, firing Mills and falling into
another unhappy marriage, bank ruptcy and addiction to prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   She reunites with Mills for a come back, but just before leaving
for New York, he finds her dead of an over dose of a prescription
anti-depres sant. The cause of death _ suicide or accident _ was
never deter mined.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tragically unsatisfying way to end a life. And it's a
fittingly unsatis fying way to end the movie. Again, Berry is
excellent as Dandridge (she's also an accomplished lip-syncher;
Wendy Williams does the actual singing), and Klaus Maria Brandauer
brings brilliant life to Preminger.
</P>
<P>
   But Introducing Dorothy Dandridge does just that _ introduces us
to her. It would have been far more sat isfying to get to know her
even bet ter. &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at (602) 444-8974, or at bill.goody
koontz &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
